<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7707 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPS-HNS &LR;      08-06 1792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
FOR two decades, Richie Phillips led major-league umpires down a
path to power, privilege and riches. Through strikes and threatened
work stoppages, the umpires' union leader raised their salaries
tenfold, to $200,000 and more, while lengthening in-season vacation
time from zero to five weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But this summer, the Philadelphia lawyer embarked on a course
that might cost the jobs of one-third of his union _ and his own as
well. Fearful the commissioner's office would change their working
conditions when a collective-bargaining agreement expires Dec. 31,
the umpires, whose labor contract has a no-strike clause, resigned
en masse, effective Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   When 12 union members in the American League refused to walk out
and 25 Class AAA minor-league umps were hired by the major leagues,
the union position crumbled. All resignations were rescinded within
two weeks of their issue, but Major League Baseball chose not to
rehire 22 umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig got what he wanted _ the right to hire
and fire umpires. No more Eric Gregg. No more Ken Kaiser.
</P>
<P>
   But players dispute the popular notion that umps are
interchangeable and unimportant and that the departing ones are no
better than the newly hired minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These umpires are the best in the United States at what they
do,'' said the Astros' Jeff Bagwell. ``You take me out of a game
and put in a minor-leaguer, and it makes a difference. You take out
a major-league umpire and put in a minor-league umpire, and that
makes a difference, too. The calls on pitches, plays at certain
bases _ those determine the outcomes of ballgames. You want the
best possible umpires to make those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpires' union is in civil war, and that's not necessarily
good for baseball. As it stands, the national pastime will enter
its September stretch run with 25 minor-league umpires on full-time
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the veteran umpires who were retained are suspect.
Privately, baseball officials admit politics got priority over
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the keepers: 14, led by Joe Brinkman and John Hirschbeck,
who issued a statement denouncing union leadership for ``a flawed
strategy that was doomed to fail from the beginning. The advice to
quit jobs in order to keep them made no sense at all.''
</P>
<P>
   AL president Gene Budig informed nine umpires their resignations
would stand: Kaiser, Drew Coble, Jim Evans, Dale Ford, Rich Garcia,
Ed Hickox, Mark Johnson, Greg Kosc and Larry McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   NL president Leonard Coleman notified 13 umpires that they won't
be needed after Sept. 2: Gregg, Joe West, Tom Hallion, Terry Tata,
Bob Davidson, Bill Hohn, Frank Pulli, Larry Poncino, Gary Darling,
Bruce Dreckman, Larry Vanover, Paul Nauert and Sam Holbrook.
</P>
<P>
   There were injustices. In an offseason poll by the players'
union, Garcia was ranked as the AL's third-best umpire and Coble
ranked sixth. In the National League, Pulli, 64, is one of the most
respected of arbiters. So is Darling, 41 and a 12-year veteran of
the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the league rehired Charlie Williams, rated by the
players as the NL's worst.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   So how did it all come to this?
</P>
<P>
   By threatening a walkout, Phillips hoped to draw Sandy Alderson,
Major League Baseball's vice president of operations, to the
negotiating table while the umpires had some leverage _ the
lucrative postseason looming. There were many issues to be
negotiated, but the key one is job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude in the past has been that even the umpires who
aren't that great are still better than anybody we could replace
them with,'' Phillips said. ``The attitude has never been to
improve umpiring by firing umpires. But that's the new mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   The union had reason to be confident in its negotiating
strategy. In two previous umpires strikes and a lockout, the
amateur replacements were so distractingly inept that the baseball
owners caved in to Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Phillips, 58, failed for several reasons.
Foremost, he overestimated support from his union members.
</P>
<P>
   National League umpire Randy Marsh said the resignation plan
``didn't turn out to be the right move, because we had our
defectors. Our association fell apart when the American League guys
went the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   With his own union split, Phillips had no chance of organizing
the minor leagues. So Alderson could offer full-time jobs and snare
Class AAA umpires who had big-league experience as summer fill-ins
for vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Hooper, a Houston labor lawyer, said Phillips also was
hampered by the mixed reviews players gave his umpires. Ballplayers
are among the world's most ardent union supporters _ as long as
it's their own union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately after the resignations,'' Hooper said, ``I heard
David Cone (All-Star pitcher for the Yankees) say, `Maybe we'll get
somebody up here who can actually call the strike zone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The public statements of players have not been supportive of
the umpires, and that's surprising. They gave the impression
they're not going to bad-mouth the replacement umpires and thereby
jeopardize the validity of the games they'd be playing with
replacement umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players are staying out of the umpires' squabble because
they don't want to expand the war. And some of the stars resent the
way umpires beseech them for autographed bats and balls, claiming
they are for charity causes. Even so, the players generally prefer
the devil they know to the newcomers they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to each umpire; you get to know them and how they
call a game,'' the Astros' Billy Wagner said. ``With new guys, you
just don't know. I think after a couple of years it would be fine.
But I think it will take a couple of years. That's the way it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say it's a tight situation and it's me facing Mark McGwire and
I throw him some good pitches. A new umpire, being in awe of
McGwire, may give him calls. Whereas if you have a veteran umpire
back there calling them straight up, you know you don't have to
groove the ball down the middle to get a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Phillips isn't giving up the fight. But his former ally,
baseball labor icon Marvin Miller, doubts he can prevail in court.
Miller said the umpires ``put themselves in a very difficult
position because they gave the owners so many options and so many
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts criticized Phillips for filing suit in
Philadelphia, in the court of U.S. District Judge Edmund Ludwig,
who last week refused to force Major League Baseball to hire back
all his umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going to Ludwig, Phillips could have sought
protection from the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, in a case where a union alleges unfair labor
practices, the National Labor Relations Board has original
exclusive jurisdiction,'' Hooper said. ``So he wouldn't have been
able to prosecute that assertion in the courts prior to going
through the National Labor Relations Board.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all his tactical blunders, Phillips has failed because
he succeeded so well in the past. He negotiated the lengthy
vacations that allowed replacement umps to gain the big-league
experience that made Alderson's strategy feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the job security Phillips acquired for his union
members, the minor-league umps saw little hope for advancement.
They jumped at the opportunity to join The Show, even if it meant
undermining Phillips and his union.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen who represents the umpires in future labor
negotiations. Phillips' foes tried to replace him with Baltimore
player agent Ron Shapiro during a union meeting in Phoenix in
March. Phillips emerged with a five-year contract, but the 14 who
voted against him are haunting him.
</P>
<P>
   American League umpire Dave Phillips, one of the insurgents,
said: ``I want the image of umpires to change. We act like we are
gangsters all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who denies wanting to head the umpires' union, is much
less bellicose and abrasive than Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that confrontational bargaining is the worst
thing you can do,'' Shapiro has said. ``My philosophy of
negotiation is that to get what you want, you have to strategize
about how to help the other side get some of what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Along with behind-the-scenes maneuvering by the warring factions
of umpires comes iciness on the field. Hohn said he felt betrayed
by fellow umpires who rescinded their resignations ahead of the
Phillips supporters. Marcia Montague, wife of NL ump Ed Montague,
wrote a letter to Hirschbeck's wife, Denise, calling her husband
``Judas.''
</P>
<P>
   The league presidents, Coleman and Budig, then sent memos
threatening umpires with disciplinary action for ``illegal threats,
intimidation or harassment of other umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential directive, hardly conciliatory, referred to
``the illegal mass resignation plan'' of Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper said the mass resignations probably were legal, but they
``violated their no-strike agreement. So the individuals who
participate in that action are not protected by the National Labor
Relations Act, which generally protects people engaging in
concerted activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps belatedly, Phillips this week asked the NLRB to file
suit against Major League Baseball for unfair labor practices that
he said ``were designed to break the umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   He has charged that umpires were offered up to $2 million in
future gains if they joined the anti-Phillips faction. He also
claimed the umpires' labor contract was violated when they were not
offered assignments to games between the Baltimore Orioles and the
Cuban national team.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has accused Major League Baseball of illegal
retaliatory action with its ``arbitrary and capricious'' dismissal
of umpires. The NLRB will review the complaint but is unlikely to
respond by Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   So the war goes on, and the players are caught in the crossfire.
Games will be decided by inexperienced umps and by veterans who are
bitter about losing their livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have too much pride to go out there and try to do a bad
job,'' Darling said. ``We're going to be second-guessed a bit more,
because people will wonder if our concentration might not be there.
But I know we'll all focus hard, as always.''
</P>
<P>
   The microscope will be on these lame ducks for three more weeks.
And then, unless the NLRB and federal courts rescue them or the
owners show mercy, they will vanish from the major-league stage.
</P>
<P>
   At the most critical juncture of the season, the game will be
jangled by shaky officiating. The umpires' union is in disarray,
but has the sport gained? That's not an easy call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
