<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPSIDER-HNS &LR;      08-06 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPSIDER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Gary Darling is not the stereotypical umpire who baseball wants to
excise. He's not fat. He's 6-3, 208 pounds and athletic. He's an
avid golfer and basketball player who played college baseball. He's
not confrontational, so you don't see him on highlight films.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He does his job quietly and competently, seldom drawing
criticism. When players list the best umpires in the National
League, Darling invariably is mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the fastest risers in his profession _ in the big
leagues at 30. Now he's 41, married, a father of two _ and possibly
about to be unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   He's not a rabble-rousing union leader, just a loyal follower.
He's a model employee you would think the league would want to
keep. But he's one of 13 NL umpires to be discharged, effective
Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never told why I was one of the 13,'' Darling said,
standing outside the umpires' dressing room in the Astrodome.
``There's a wide variety of guys _ middle-of-the-road guys, young
guys. One was hired this year, so he couldn't be doing that bad. I
don't know what the criteria was.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is mum, other than to say it didn't want
to decrease the percentage of minority umpires.
</P>
<P>
   To deflect charges of illegal retaliation in a labor dispute,
the league retained union president Jerry Crawford, who was rated
the No. 1 NL ump in an offseason poll of the players' union. Also
rehired was union activist Bruce Froemming, who ranked near the
bottom in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   A major shock was the banishment of Frank Pulli, a 28-year
veteran and one of the most consistent of umpires. But this season
he incurred the wrath of the baseball lords when he violated rules
by viewing a television replay before making a call on whether a
ball was a home run or a double.
</P>
<P>
   Also dismissed was the much-respected Tom Hallion, but that was
attributed to one notorious misstep: He bumped Colorado catcher
Jerry Reed and was suspended for three games in July.
</P>
<P>
   That suspension, by league president Len Coleman, was one of a
series of incidents that incited umpires to vote July 14 to resign
en masse. When they withdrew their resignations, 22 major-league
umps were not hired back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was fair the way they treated us the whole
time,'' Darling said, ``starting with last November when they tried
to force things down our throat with (standardizing) the strike
zone and centralizing us, without going through the proper
channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball wants umpires from both leagues to be
supervised by Sandy Alderson of the commissioner's office. With
interleague play, it makes sense to have centralized umpiring and a
standardized strike zone, and the umpires are not necessarily
opposed to those concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be more than willing to listen,'' Darling said. ``But
they're unilaterally trying to take over, trying to break the
collective-bargaining agreement and trying to break our union.''
</P>
<P>
   Union chief Richie Phillips is making those claims in asking the
National Labor Relations Board to sue Major League Baseball for
unfair labor practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys don't agree with the things Richie is doing for
us,'' Darling said. ``But we've got 44 guys sticking together, and
we need the solidarity. I've talked with guys on the other side,
and hopefully we can all pull back together.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is trying to gain the support of the 25 minor-league
umpires hired by Alderson as full-time replacements for the
departing veterans. Darling said Hunter Wendelstedt, a replacement
umpire on his crew who is the son of longtime NL umpire Harry
Wendelstedt, has promised to honor a work stoppage if Phillips
calls for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter and all the other new National League guys have said
they're not going to work if we go out,'' Darling said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not sure about the American League, which has 11
veteran umpires seeking to remove Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American League guys (replacements) say they don't look at
it as being scabs if they do work,'' Darling said.
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea why National Leaguers are more union-loyal, but
it might be because the union is headquartered in Philadelphia, a
National League city. NL umps have more contact with Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Darling admitted the replacements, from Class AAA, are more
capable than the amateurs hired in the past to break strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a fine job when they have the veteran umpires around
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is they won't do so well if 13 NL veterans
depart.
</P>
<P>
   If Darling loses his job, he's due more than $300,000 in
severance. But umpires with less than 10 years' tenure will draw no
golden parachutes. They face the prospect of earning $12,500, tops,
as minor-league umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an emotional roller coaster for me and my family,''
said Darling, who lives in Phoenix. ``My wife is supporting me, and
sometimes I'm having to support her, because we don't know what
will happen. Even if the legal system works in our favor like I
think it will, the way baseball is going, they might have different
umpires next year _ if they get what they want and can fire guys
easily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
