<HEADER>
A7709 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-HN     08-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Shane Reynolds played the guessing game with the Los Angeles
Dodgers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dodgers lost.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds pitched a five-hitter for his seventh career shutout
Thursday as the Astros completed a three-game homestand with a 7-0
victory over the Dodgers before a crowd of 38,018 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won for the 10th time in 13 games and extended their
lead in the National League Central to 2{ games over Cincinnati,
which lost 2-1 to the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (14-7) struck out six and walked none in his third
complete game and second shutout of the season. Rarely behind in
the count, Reynolds retired 16 of the final 17 Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was keeping them off balance,'' catcher Paul Bako said. ``I
don't think they knew what he was going to start off with or finish
them with. He was throwing all four of his pitches for strikes.
When you get a guy taking a fastball for a third strike, that means
you've got them guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismael Valdes matched Reynolds for six innings before the Astros
finally solved the Dodgers righthander.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Russ Johnson had three hits, including a home run that
snapped a scoreless tie and ignited a six-run seventh inning.
Johnson added a double and a single, getting within a triple of
becoming the first Astro to hit for the cycle since Andujar Cedeno
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score for a long while, but when Russ hit the home
run I figured the way Shane was pitching, that would have been
enough,'' said Bako, who had two singles.
</P>
<P>
   Since struggling in mid-June, Reynolds has won seven of his last
eight decisions, including three in a row. Reynolds has allowed no
more than five hits in any of his last three starts, giving up only
one earned run (0.38 ERA) in 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had runners at second and third in the first inning,
but Reynolds worked out of the jam with a strikeout of Todd
Hollandsworth. The Dodgers' only other substantial scoring
opportunity was blocked in the fourth when center fielder Richard
Hidalgo gunned down Gary Sheffield at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a few mistakes early, but after that I got into a
rhythm,'' said Reynolds, who has not issued a walk in his last 16
innings. ``I was in the dugout thinking, `One run may win this game
on either side.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros didn't test the theory, opening the floodgates for
six runs off Valdes and relievers Alan Mills and Pedro Borbon in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Johnson connected for his fourth home run of the
season _ a bases-empty shot to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (8-10) walked Jeff Bagwell, one of a season-high six free
passes he gave up, and Mills came in and walked Derek Bell. Lance
Berkman followed with an RBI double, and Hidalgo walked to load the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Then Matt Mieske just missed his second grand slam of the season
with a deep foul fly to left. But he was effective nonetheless,
with a two-run pinch double off Borbon to put the Astros ahead 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bogar got a run home with an RBI single, and Reynolds bunted
home the final run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Barker drove in the seventh run with a single in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell had a double and walked three times.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the late run support, the talk in the Astros'
clubhouse dealt with Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today wasn't so good,'' manager Larry Dierker joked. ``I can't
say enough about the starting pitching. You sometimes win fans with
home runs and big scores, but you win games with pitching and
defense. You win championships with pitching and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Dierker didn't think twice about letting
Reynolds go for the complete game. After the long seventh inning,
pitching coach Vern Ruhle noticed some stiffness in Reynolds'
warm-up pitches in the eighth. And Reynolds was approaching 100
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But like he has done all season, Dierker left Reynolds in the
game, the pitch count stopping at 123.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I told Vern), `If we get to 100 pitches, we'll start counting
backward,''' Dierker said. ``So he ended up with 85 pitches, which
was well within his limit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
