<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STEWART-HNS &LR;      08-06 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Some boys dream about hitting a home run in the
World Series. Others imagine making a diving catch in the end zone
to win the Super Bowl, and some stand on their driveway and pretend
they just sank the winning 3-point shot in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other boys across America, Tony Stewart also grew
up with a dream of becoming a sports hero. But Stewart's dream
wasn't about hitting a ball, making a catch or sinking a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's childhood fantasy was to someday win a race at the
historic speedway that is only 50 miles north of his boyhood home
in Columbus, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to race in the Indianapolis 500, a goal he
accomplished in 1996 at age 25. Stewart has made four starts in the
Memorial Day weekend event, but his dream of taking the checkered
flag at Indy has eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old driver will get another shot to win at Indy on
Saturday, and many racing fans believe it's his best chance. But
this time, Stewart will be competing at the Brickyard in a car with
fenders and bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who grew up watching the Indy 500 will be one of the top
contenders in the Brickyard 400, hoping to guide his Home Depot
Pontiac to a victory on his personal field of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can win in front of the hometown crowd, it would be
great,'' said Stewart, who will start on the inside of row 6 after
qualifying Thursday at 178.348 mph. ``I could see them all cheering
for me today in the grandstands. You never know what can happen,
but really, I'd like to make any racetrack my first win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody asks about Indy like I've got a choice in it.
Brother, if I can win a race, I'm going to win a race. I don't care
where it is. I'll sure take it this week if I can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of winning a race is something most Winston Cup
rookies can't imagine. It usually takes a few years before a driver
can learn all the things he needs to know to win at NASCAR's
highest level. But Stewart's rookie season has been one of the best
in Winston Cup history. Even Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt as
rookies can't compare to what Stewart has done this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has put the No. 20 Grand Prix in the top 10 at 11
events, including five times in the top five. He is fifth in the
points standings (one spot ahead of Gordon) and is likely to become
the first rookie to finish in the top 10 since Jody Ridley in 1980.
Stewart is on pace to become the first rookie in history to finish
in the top five in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Stewart is a great driver,'' said TV analyst Buddy Baker,
a former Winston Cup driver. ``He can drive anywhere, on any
surface. It doesn't matter if it's dirt, pavement, a road course,
whatever. He's also the bravest racer I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Stewart hasn't done so far this season is win,
but it appears likely he will see Victory Lane soon. No rookie has
won a Winston Cup race since 1987, when Davey Allison did it twice.
Allison became a top driver, but he died in a helicopter crash in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey had his time, and we all enjoyed it,'' said his father,
Bobby Allison. ``Now it's Tony Stewart's time, and the guy is
really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart came painfully close to his first win last month at New
Hampshire. He had a 17-second lead with two laps to go when he ran
out of fuel. After the race, a bitterly disappointed Stewart
received some rare bad publicity when he refused to meet with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get that close to a major goal and something happens
that's beyond your control, it's disappointing,'' he said. ``I was
so consumed with the emotion about what happened. Unless you're a
race-car driver, it's hard to understand how much emotion is
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hadn't run out of there. I just didn't do the right
thing. I've taken some grief over it, and I deserved it. I know I
have to deal with the good days and the bad, but I just hope people
will see the big picture. Sometimes you do or say things in the
heat of battle that you wish you could take back.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing fans have seen Stewart's emotional outbursts in the past,
especially at Indianapolis when a blown engine or another
mechanical problem kept him from having a chance to win the Indy
500.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart managed to win the Indy Racing League championship in
1997, but he already had decided to make his future in NASCAR. He
felt he wasn't getting the opportunity to make the most of his
talent, and his frustrations showed at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three years (in the IRL), I wasn't a very happy
person,'' Stewart said. ``And I didn't appear to be a very nice
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart opted to take the same route that Gordon took when he
left the short tracks of Indiana after racing against Stewart when
both drivers were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people compare us (as Winston Cup rookies), I correct
them quickly,'' said Gordon, the top rookie of 1993 and a
three-time Winston Cup champion. ``I tore up a whole lot more race
cars than he has. I wasn't as smooth or as patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gibbs hired Stewart to drive a Busch Grand National car in
1998 (while Stewart raced a full IRL schedule) before moving
Stewart up to Winston Cup this season. Gibbs admits he never
expected so much so fast from Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would make a ton of mistakes,'' Gibbs said. ``We
thought we would have a lot of cars to fix because we thought he
would have some wrecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most surprising thing about Stewart's season is that
he has managed to finish every race and stay away from accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a meeting, and I told Joe that for every car I don't
crash, he can just pay me an extra bonus,'' Stewart said with a
grin. ``That's when the meeting ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart wants to keep his car in one piece Saturday and give
himself a chance to earn his first victory. But he said he won't be
overly aggressive to try to win at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't happen, I don't think it will be a great
disappointment to us,'' Stewart said. ``Actually, I'm amazed at
where we are as a team. The main thing is we're in contention all
the time, so the wins will come. When the year began, I would have
considered 20th in the points to be a successful season. I still
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it, not for a guy as competitive as Stewart. Racing
is more than a career for Stewart; it's his life.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first driver to win the United States Auto Club
triple crown in the same year (1995) by winning titles in midgets,
sprints and Silver Crown cars. Earlier this year, he became only
the second driver in history _ joining John Andretti _ to compete
in the Indy 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   After his disappointment at New Hampshire, Stewart healed his
sadness the next day by racing on a dirt track in Knoxville, Iowa.
After he finished sixth in the Pepsi 400 on July 3 at Daytona, he
came home to Indiana the next day and won a late-model stock-car
race in Terre Haute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was a kid in a candy store,'' Stewart said. ``I
was so excited. I hadn't won a race since last year. Winning is
winning. It doesn't matter where it is or what kind of car it's in,
the feeling is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said by the time he was 12, when he won his first
national go-cart championship, he knew what he wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put all my eggs in one basket,'' he said. ``I didn't go to
college, because I wanted to pursue a racing career. Everything in
my life has been focused for this. I don't know what I would have
done if it hadn't worked out. I'd probably be picking up aluminum
cans.''
</P>
<P>
   With $1.2 million in earnings this year, Stewart won't be
looking for added income any time soon. It's likely the best is yet
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are variables that are important in your career, like
being in the right place at the right time with the right people
and the right equipment,'' Stewart said. ``If you take one of those
variables out, you won't be as successful. Those variables are all
in place for me now. That's all you can ask for as a driver. If you
do your best each week, the victories will happen. Maybe even at
Indy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
