<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros won for the 66th time Thursday, which left them tied for
the major-league lead and happens to be more victories than they
ever have accumulated after 109 games.
</P>
<P>
   Were they the team they were supposed to be in spring training _
never mind the team they might have been had Randy Johnson stayed
on or Roger Clemens deigned to come home _ this information would
startle no one. But under the circumstances, it's borderline
miraculous. Even preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just keep pinching ourselves,'' Craig Biggio said, ``and
hope we can keep it going. Eventually, we'll get everybody back.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Bidge, who needs everybody? Your Astros routed the fat-cat,
dog-like Dodgers 7-0 behind Shane Reynolds and the New Orleans
Zephyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Reynolds, whose masterful five-hitter was at least
somewhat in line with the expectations for a staff ace on a
twice-defending division champion, Houston's heroes were the Killer
B-team _ Paul Bako, Lance Berkman, Tim Bogar and Glen Barker _ plus
fellow bit players Russ Johnson and Matt Mieske.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' Biggio said, resisting the temptation to pinch
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, only Bogar, a career .230 hitter, surfaced in
Kissimmee last February with a better than 50-50 chance of breaking
camp on the Astros' roster.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some real irony for you. In the Astros' six-run seventh
heaven of a seventh inning, the superstar second baseman Biggio
grounded out and flied out in his two plate appearances. Johnson
homered to start the onslaught. Berkman, who is headed back to New
Orleans today to make room for Carl Everett, and Seattle discard
Mieske contributed run-scoring doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, with a squeeze bunt, and Bogar added the other RBIs.
Bogar at shortstop also thwarted a likely first-inning Dodgers run
by spearing Mark Grudzielanek's screaming liner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting contributions from the entire roster,'' Biggio
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone we've called upon,'' manager Larry Dierker said,
``has found a way to do something to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros went a franchise-record 102-60 last season ``by
beating everyone's brains out,'' Biggio said. ``We were a lot
better team last year than we are this year. It became a very
special season. But this season is starting to get pretty special,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-charts special, it would appear. Playing what Biggio
calls ``little ball'' _ ball that features superb pitching, tight
defense, sound fundamental strategy and timely contributions at the
plate _ the Astros keep coming up big. Win No. 66 might have been
the Astros' most typical to date.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's game was exactly, to a T, what the '99 Astros are all
about. Apparently, their opportunism knows no bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo, scuffling along at the plate with a .226
batting average, prevented two Dodgers runs with his sharp play in
center field, cheating Eric Karros out of a first-inning RBI with
extra-effort hustle on Karros' double, then cutting down Gary
Sheffield at the plate with a perfect strike following Raul
Mondesi's fly ball in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane obviously pitched extremely well,'' Dierker said. ``He
made it look easy, and it's not easy to get a complete game, much
less a shutout, the way baseball is played today. But he needed a
lot of help to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Little of which was forthcoming from the usual suspects to
provide it. Biggio led off with a single but was nailed at second
trying to stretch it into his 47th double, then went hitless the
rest of the way. The Dodgers took the bat out of Jeff Bagwell's
hands by walking him thrice. Cleanup man Derek Bell was 0-for-4
with three K's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Moises Alou and Ken Caminiti, those eternal
rehabbers, occupied their normal seats in the dugout, as did
Everett. At least Everett will be back for today's doubleheader in
Chicago, which is why Berkman's two-base hit would be his last
National League hurrah until an anticipated September call-up.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, somebody else gets hurt before then. And the
way things have gone, somebody probably will, although the Astros
don't figure to miss a step or break a sweat. Where there's a will,
there will be a way. How do you explain Barker, a .245 hitter in
the minors with most of his experience at the Class AA level or
lower, batting .316 as a part-time NLer? You don't. You simply
applaud it and celebrate it.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio was asked which kind of winning was more satisfying _ the
conventional biff-bash style of a year ago or the
all-hands-on-deck, chewing-gum-and-spit approach of late. He
decided not to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning, is winning,'' he said. ``I'm always happy when we
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But surely this way provides an extra tingle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
