<SLUG> BC-CANYON06-KWALTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFS DECISION TO AFFECT TOURISTS AND CANYON WORK ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ The National Forest Service will announce a decision
today that could dramatically alter northern Arizona tourist
patterns as well as give Grand Canyon park workers a decent place
to live.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, officials have wrangled over the fate of Tusayan,
the Canyon's gateway community, which has been little more than a
pit stop for overpriced hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, regional forester Eleanor Towns will either
approve Scottsdale developer Tom De Paolo's plan to build the large
scale Canyon Forest Village, or a smaller, Tusayan landowner-backed
project called FaeX.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the decision, it will be a day of anguish for the
hospitality industry in Flagstaff and Williams, which relies on
Grand Canyon tourism for its livelihood. Flagstaff is 75 miles and
Williams 50 miles from Tusayan, which is only a few miles away from
the Canyon's South Rim.
</P>
<P>
   If the Canyon Forest Village alternative is approved, an
additional 1,220 hotel rooms could be added just outside the
Canyon's gate.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, workers at Grand Canyon, most of whom have
been relegated to living in substandard shacks inside the park,
will have an alternative. Both plans call for construction of
residential housing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 1,220 hotel rooms, the Canyon Forest Village
proposal calls for the development of 270,000 square feet of retail
space and 1,100 housing units for local employees only.
</P>
<P>
   The CFV project also will include 20,000 square feet of retail
space for Native American merchants and 29 acres dedicated to
Flagstaff's Museum of Northern Arizona for a visitor-orientation
center about the history of the Colorado Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   De Paolo said he and his inves tors would exchange 2,200 acres
of land they own in the area for 282 acres of Forest Service land
between Tusayan and the park boundary, where the development would
be built.
</P>
<P>
   The FaeX plan calls for the construction of 400 new hotel rooms
and 250,000 square feet of retail space along with an undetermined
number of housing units.
</P>
<P>
   All of the state's major environmental groups have backed the
project, except the Sierra Club, which has concerns about
groundwater depletion in the Canyon area. The Havasupai and Hopi
tribes have also blessed the CVP project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice coalition of diverse groups, which we hope will
shape the future up there,'' De Paolo said. ``We've waited eight
years for this, but this last day is the toughest.''
</P>
<P>
   De Paolo said that CFV has a contract with the Central Arizona
Project to bring in 61 million gallons of water a year from the
Colorado River at the community of Topock. The water would be moved
by rail from Topock to Williams and then sent by pipeline to
Tusayan.
</P>
<P>
   The Coconino County Planning and Zoning Commission and Board of
Supervisors are required to approve the development after the
Forest Service's decision before any building can begin.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Roush, a consultant for CFV, said it would take four years
to complete the project after the county's approval.
</P>
<P>
   But Tusayan and Williams business owners hope that never
happens. Tusayan hopes its plan will win out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of competition,'' said Chris Thurston, who owns
the Red Feather Lodge in Tusayan.
</P>
<P>
   But Thurston said that the Forest Service would ``give away
valuable land'' if it approves CFV and make it ``so we're no longer
on the same playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   The CFV effort is nothing but a land grab, Williams Mayor Jim
Hoffman said. Hoffman's wife owns a large portion of private land
in Tusayan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cow pasture they're getting for that is worth (much
less),'' Hoffman said, referring to the land proposed for exchange
by the CFV investors. And Williams could lose half a million
dollars a year in tourism if De Paolo gets his way, Hoffman added.
</P>
<P>
   If the Forest Service endorses Canyon Forest Village, Thurston
and Hoffman said they will fight it in court. &UR;  &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
