<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSE-SEX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMISSED NURSES EXPANDING X-RATED BUSINESS ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE CRISSEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A husband-wife nurse team fired Thursday by a Scottsdale
hospital for running an X-rated Web site aren't giving up their
business, they're expanding.
</P>
<P>
   George Miller says he's posted suggestive pictures of his wife,
Tracy, in her role as ``the very touchable Dakota Rae'' on 250 free
X-rated Web sites every day since the couple were suspended July 1
by Scottsdale Healthcare Osborn.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures contain a link to the Millers' Web site, where
surfers are invited to become members who may view explicit sex for
$14.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Hits on the site reached 48,000 on July 29, the day the Millers
appeared on the Howard Stern radio show in &UR; New York City, one of a
half-dozen media outlets that have aired the couple's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I can say about this is that one door has opened
another door, and so on,'' George Miller said. ``I never thought
this would be this big.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 33, of northeast Phoenix, said hospital officials told
the couple they were being dismissed because they tried to recruit
fellow employees to appear on the Web site. The couple denied it.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital termination notices say the Millers, who worked as
on-call intensive care nurses, were being fired for violating
hospital policy by harassing other staff members and ``creating a
hostile or offensive working environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset; this is all lies,'' said Tracy Miller, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, who had worked at the hospital for three &UR; years, and
George, who had worked there for two, say they earned $92,000 at
the hospital last year, and that the Web site is now their sole
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Sperduti, a hospital spokes woman, declined Thursday to talk
about the Millers' case because hospital policy forbids &UR; public dis
cussions of a specific personnel issue. She said the Millers' case
was the first of its kind in her 13 years at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers have three days to appeal the hospital's action and
said they plan to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made a huge mis take,'' George said. ``This battle
has just started.''
</P>
<P>
   A Winter Park, Fla., lawyer whose firm specializes in defending
the owners of adult Internet sites said Thursday that he will be
representing the Millers without charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is this: It was an inappropriate, illegal
termina tion,'' attorney Lawrence Walters said. ``The hospital
fired them because they didn't like the Web site. It had nothing to
do with their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Stern show, the couple have appeared in the past
month on TV and radio shows, including CBS' Morning News, Court TV,
Extra and Inside Edition.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers will appear in an Aug. 24 Fox TV network show and
have been approached by the TV news show 48 Hours, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple tout their publicity on the Web site, telling surfers
that they have ``seen her on TV and read about her in the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Millers have even used their dismissal from the hospital to
lure more members to their Web site. The opening page now says,
``X-rated porno nurse fired.''
</P>
<P>
   The site also has a special e-mail link for reporters to contact
the couple.
</P>
<P>
   George Miller said 150 hospital employees have become members of
the site in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Web site can see photos of ``Dakota Rae'' in
nurse's garb, sitting at a computer bare chested, and lounging by
the swim ming pool. More explicit pictures are shown only to
members. George Miller, known on the site as ``Da kota Rae's''
husband, ``Jack,'' ap pears in the members' section of the site
engaged in sexual activity with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the number of paying members has hovered around
2,200 for the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers could make more than $100,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They say they started the Web site three months ago to make
money for their children's college educations. They have an
11-year-old son and a 5-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he and his wife explained the Web site and their job
situation to their son, who took it in stride. &QL; 
Mike Crissey can be reached at (602) 444-7474. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
