r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     08-06 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT MAN FOR LAKERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ From the long-anticipated to the unexpected,
the Lakers continued their roster building Thursday by re-signing
their own free agent, Rick Fox, while contemplating pursuit of
another L.A. free agent, the Clippers' Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, as expected, signed a six-year deal worth about $24
million, leaving the Lakers with one open slot on the 12-man roster
and a gaping hole at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley is the man most coveted for that role, but the
Lakers are less than confident he'll sign here, which brings them
to Plan B _ luring Wright away from their arena roommates, the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's agent, Robert Fayne, contacted Lakers executive vice
president Jerry West and told him Wright would play for the $2
million middle-class exception. That led to an erroneous ESPN
report that had Wright accepting an offer that technically has not
yet been tendered by the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Fayne and West are scheduled to meet today.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who can play forward and center, has turned down the
Clippers' six-year, $30 million offer and has tried to force a
sign-and-trade deal. Those efforts have failed so far, leaving
Wright with few options, and none as lucrative as the Clippers'.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would prefer Oakley, but he is taking his time making
a decision and there are signs his flirtation with the Lakers might
simply be a ploy to get Toronto to increase its offer. The Raptors
have offered $5.5 million per year, far short of the $8 million
Oakley is seeking but far more than the Lakers can offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think realistically, the odds are stacked against us,''
Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak admitted. ``We're just hopeful
that he would make a decision not solely based on economics.''
</P>
<P>
   If Oakley takes too long or turns down the Lakers, ``we have
options,'' Kupchak said. He wouldn't say that Wright was one of
those options.
</P>
<P>
   The re-signing of Fox comes two days after guard Derek Fisher
re-upped with the Lakers for seven years and gives the Lakers a
pair of complementary players known for self-sacrifice and
teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick will do anything for the team,'' Kupchak said, ``and I
think now that he has some long-term security, it'll just magnify
(that attitude) of `whatever you guys want me to do, I'll do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, primarily a backup at small forward and shooting guard,
should flourish in new coach Phil Jackson's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good passer, a good shooter, he liked to rebound and is
fundamentally sound. Those things work well in the triangle,''
Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick is versatile,'' he added. ``I can envision him bringing
the ball up the floor, playing a ball-handling guard, playing small
forward, and as you recall during the San Antonio (playoff) series,
he even guarded Tim Duncan. It's unusual to have a player who can
play four positions. . . but he has done it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
