<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-06 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FIELD OR OFF, GWYNN MAKES CONTACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn stroked his 2,999th hit on Thursday. That's a lot of
contact for a slender piece of wood but a pittance for its stout
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Is San Diego's Gwynn the best there ever was at making contact?
We should think so, considering all the lives he gets ahold of that
go unrecorded by the Elias Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, 39, connects with rawhide and regular people with
awe-inspiring consistency. It's what makes him a shoo-in for
Cooperstown and kingdom come.
</P>
<P>
   There are 106 major-league players who earn more money than
Gwynn but arguably no one who leads as rich a life.
</P>
<P>
   The ``selfish'' player journeyman catcher Jim Leyritz described
last weekend after being traded to New York (we trust the door
didn't hit him on his way out) is a family man who opens his home
to nieces and nephews and anyone who needs a stroke of luck or just
plain stroking.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn and his wife Alicia are rearing three nieces and nephews
in addition to their own children, Anthony, 16, and Anisha, 13.
Three other children are living with them right now, kids they
rescued from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we see where Leyritz was coming from. Gwynn, he's a
regular Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn doesn't go out of his way to publicize it, but he and his
wife have put more than a dozen students through college.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn sprays money like he does hits: He goes to all fields.
</P>
<P>
   On the diamond, he is especially fond of the gap between second
and third. Off it, he is partial to kids who fall through society's
cracks: the abused, the abandoned and the emotionally troubled.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing purer than Gwynn's swing is his sense of purpose.
Michael Brunker, who has known the 18-year veteran since his
playing days at San Diego State, said, ``Tony's got his life in
order, which allows him to be committed to service over self.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's life wasn't always so neatly prioritized. He struggled
in his early years in the big leagues to strike a balance between
family and baseball. He fixed it the same way he did his early
throwing and fielding deficiencies _ he made a conscious effort
every day to be better.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn can remember as vividly as his 1,000th hit (a single off
Nolan Ryan on an 0-and-2 fastball) when he knew he had some
catching up to do as a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a green costume in my daughter's room and I had no
idea what it was for,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Padres traveled up the I-5 to play the Dodgers in
June, Gwynn didn't take the team bus. He drove himself so he could
attend Anisha's eighth-grade graduation in the afternoon. Then he
lead-footed it back to Dodger Stadium to be on hand for a game he
wouldn't play in because of a calf injury.
</P>
<P>
   If that made him a prima donna in Leyritz's eyes, well, Gwynn
can live with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six years ago, there's no way I would have driven home
for my daughter's graduation,'' Gwynn said. ``In the old days, if
there was a choice to be made between baseball and something else,
I always chose baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter's radiant expression when her name rang out and she
heard her dad holler for her in that distinctively squeaky voice of
his is a memory Gwynn wouldn't trade for his 4,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you miss a moment like that,'' Gwynn said, ``you never get
it back.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd never know it from the way he holds court before or after
a game, but Gwynn is not naturally gregarious. Like hitting to
right field, talking to reporters is an acquired skill for the Long
Beach native.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure you take an extra five minutes with people, it'll pay
off down the road,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's good-gabber policy was tested in New York last year,
after Game 1 of the World Series. Gwynn went 3 for 4 with a home
run, but the Padres lost 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   In the visiting clubhouse, a reporter stuck a microphone in
Gwynn's face and said it had to be the greatest night of Gwynne's
life, hitting a home run in the house that Ruth built, yada, yada,
yada.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's cheeks reddened.
</P>
<P>
   Chicks, as Gwynn learned long ago, aren't the only ones who dig
the long ball. Seems he's always getting asked about losing weight
or hitting more for power.
</P>
<P>
   When he met Ted Williams for the first time, the superlative
contact hitter of yore managed to push both hot-button issues with
one comment. Williams took one look at Gwynns 5-foot-11, 225-pound
frame and said dryly, ``Big as you are, you should be hitting the
ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Gwynn takes great pride in swinging for the gaps
and not the fences. He decided the man behind the microphone should
have known that. A good reporter, Gwynn scolded him, does his
homework before the game, not after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed him a side of Tony Gwynn nobody else has seen,'' the
outfielder said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months later, that exchange continues to gnaw at Gwynn. He
can't believe that poor, misguided reporter and how he snapped at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking afterward that I came on a little too strong,''
Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we've heard that Albert Belle frets over that sort of
stuff, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's supposed to be no cheering in the press box. It's hard,
however, not to root for a player who showed up at the All-Star
Game this year even though he was injured, so he could pay homage
to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Gwynn came prepared. He bought a book on the history
of the place. Whether he's hitting in a park or simply admiring it,
Gwynn always does his homework first.
</P>
<P>
   It's Gwynn's fastidiousness, on the diamond and in his
day-to-day dealings with people, that set him apart.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm, cloudless June afternoon at Dodger Stadium, Gwynn
mused about the machinations of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you do the off-the-wall things that draw people's
attention,'' he said, ``people just kind of forget about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Not always. Once in a long while someone comes along and quietly
connects with so many balls and so many people he has a whole
nation standing to give him his due. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0037EDT &QL; 
