<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUESTION OF GOVERNMENT VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone in the federal bureaucracy charged with helping
America's small businesses apparently has a lot more dollars than
sense.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Sen. Kit Bond, chairman of the Senate's Small
Business Committee, is irked at the Small Business Administration
for what he sees as questionable use of its resources. He wants
some answers, pronto.
</P>
<P>
   The flap involves what the Missouri Republican says is a
violation of the congressional intent of 1997's SBA authorization
legislation, which mandated increased financing for the Service
Corps of Retired Executives. As it turns out, however, the SBA
apparently has cut administrative support for the organization
commonly known by its acronym, SCORE.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to SBA Administrator Aida Alvarez, Bond and ranking
Small Business Committee Democrat Sen. John Kerry expressed concern
about the matter and requested a ``prompt reply'' concerning what
can be done ``to rectify the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation, according to Bond's letter, is a seeming decision
by somebody in the SBA to divert money intended to reimburse
expenses incurred by SCORE volunteers to pay instead for
administrative outlays such as office space and telephone and
postal services.
</P>
<P>
   If someone did make such a decision, it's foolishness, because
dollar for dollar, Uncle Sam probably gets more bang for his buck
from SCORE than any other activity you'd care to name.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent any time whatsoever with SCORE volunteers
has no trouble understanding the significant contributions made by
this dedicated group.
</P>
<P>
   SCORE is exactly what its name says. Some 14,000 retired
executives and business managers throughout America spend a
considerable chunk of their spare time sharing their knowledge and
expertise with existing and aspiring small-business operators.
Kansas City is fortunate to have a particularly effective SCORE
organization, which during its years of working cooperatively with
local SBA officials has contributed substantially to the area's
economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   The only recompense these volunteers receive is for expenses
incurred while helping others. It's one of the few areas in which
the federal government probably gets more value than its pays for.
As Bond puts it, these are really ``volunteers,'' in the truest
sense of the word, because they get no stipend whatsoever for their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the compelling question is, why would anyone try to save
money by shortchanging those who do so much public service for so
little in return? Chalk it up to Oscar Wilde's line about a cynic
being somebody who knows the cost of everything and the value of
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's letter states the obvious when it points out that the SBA
should hardly be trying to reduce support for SCORE volunteers at
the very time Congress is considering even higher funding for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, anyone in Washington who thinks SCORE isn't pulling
its weight should spend some time observing how these retired
business types contribute to the good of their communities and U.S.
economic health.
</P>
<P>
   Shortchanging SCORE would be an example of ill-advised
government policy at its worst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
