<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-REVITALIZE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER &AMP; LIGHT DEVELOPERS ASK FOR BIGGER, MORE EXPENSIVE DISTRICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Plans for the Power &AMP; Light District are
getting bigger and more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of the entertainment district are asking for changes
in the voter-approved downtown revitalization plan that would boost
the total cost to $628 million from $454 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes would double the amount of office space, triple
the amount of apartment space, cut 10 movie screens from the
centerpiece megaplex and spare the President Hotel from the
wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very bold initiative,'' said Nick Bashkiroff,
managing director of Power &AMP; Light District LLC, an AMC
Entertainment Inc. subsidiary that is leading the project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also asks the city to accelerate, but not increase,
$176 million in taxpayer-assisted financing approved by voters in
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of what I call pot-stirring _ increasing
component size and adding more apartments,'' Bashkiroff said. ``We
feel very good that we are going to get this done and we are going
to get this done sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes are included in a book of numbers the developers
expect to submit to the Kansas City Tax Increment Financing
Commission today. The developers have been sharing the numbers
privately with TIF staff and other city leaders in the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers are staggering in their complexity, profoundly
important and massive in their implications, but ultimately may be
in the best interests of the city,'' said Donald Zuchelli,
president and chief executive of ZHA Inc., the TIF Commission's
financial consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Smith, lawyer for the TIF Commission, said the changes in
the development plan will be discussed at a public hearing on Sept.
15.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the changes need the approval of the TIF Commission.
The Kansas City Council will review the changes, but Smith said the
changes aren't significant enough to require council approval.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Franco, lawyer for some landowners who don't want to move
for the project, said the changes might require council approval
because they substantially change the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts will have to decide that,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes do not alter the boundaries of the 12-block
district on the south end of downtown, roughly bounded by 13th
Street on the north, McGee Street on the east, Wyandotte Street on
the west and Truman Road on the south.
</P>
<P>
   And the proposal continues to call for movie and live theaters,
offices, apartments, hotels, restaurants, stores and parking
garages.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major changes:
</P>
<P>
   - Greatly increasing the amount of office and housing space in
an effort to attract people to live and work in the district,
increasing traffic for retail and entertainment components.
</P>
<P>
   - Restoring the Power &AMP; Light Building as a 198-unit apartment
structure that could be converted into condominiums. Apartments on
five of the floors would include terraced balconies.
</P>
<P>
   - Cutting 10 screens from the planned 30-screen AMC megaplex
movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   - Saving the President Hotel as a 185-suite hotel instead of
razing the vacant building.
</P>
<P>
   - Constructing more of the district in the initial phase.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased size of the project, the proposal only
adds 89 parking spaces. Backers said that would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The approved plan calls for the construction of three blocks of
entertainment and retail in the first phase of the plan. In the
amended plan, developers plan to tackle nine blocks, including
offices and apartments, at the beginning of the project, completing
as much as 70 percent of the total project.
</P>
<P>
   By completing more of the project quickly, more city money would
be spent sooner. The existing plan calls for the city to spend $108
million in the first phase of construction. According to the
amended plan, the city would spend $161 million in the initial
construction period.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes are the result of advice from co-developers
on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's foot traffic, critical mass, a 24-hour city,'' said S.
Reid Freeman, vice president of Regent Partners, one of two
Atlanta-based co-developers approved in April. ``You've got to have
people. We felt it was important to take and accelerate the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman declined to name prospective tenants, but said, ``We're
in deep negotiations with a number of potential anchor tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the project can proceed quickly, and that the
city is committed to the project, Power &AMP; Light District lawyer
Aaron March said the developers are asking the city to issue TIF
bonds and put as much as $50 million in escrow to help pay for land
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   By having the $50 million in escrow, the developers can acquire
land and move quickly into construction. March said the bonds would
not be issued until the developers met conditions in the existing
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions require the developers to have financing
commitments from private lenders and leases on at least 40 percent
of the space in the entertainment district, excluding the AMC
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kay Barnes said the provision of money in escrow shouldn't
affect the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate that it will be a major issue as long as we
have the assurance that all the requirements will be met before any
of the city's money is in their hands,'' Barnes said. ``That hasn't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bashkiroff, of Power &AMP; Light District LLC, said the developers
had let contracts to buy many of the properties in the district
lapse because the developers didn't have a certain starting date
for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Bashkiroff said the developers expect to start acquiring land in
December and hope to break ground before April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Franco, the lawyer for the landowners, said the request that
the city put money in escrow suggests the co-developers don't have
the financial strength to support the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just shows they signed up a group that doesn't have the
financial breadth for the project or the financial strength to sign
on the dotted line,'' Franco said. ``Obviously that's
disconcerting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
