<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUELAS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO (MANY) RUELAS FIGHTS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Ruelas brothers are giving themselves another
chance this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel and Rafael Ruelas, whose careers were thought by many to
be over last year, fight Saturday and Sunday against journeyman
opponents. Each brother has an eye on one more opportunity to fight
for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Ruelas, who faces Jose Rodriguez of Nicaragua in a
10-round lightweight bout Saturday in Miami on Telemundo, hasn't
fought since John Brown took him out in eight rounds in October of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Ruelas, who takes on Hicklet Lau of Miami in a 10-round
junior welterweight bout Sunday on Fox Sports Net, last fought when
he was stopped by Kostya Tszyu in nine rounds last August.
</P>
<P>
   Both insist the one-sided losses were anomalies and both expect
to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people tend to judge a fighter on his last fight,''
said Rafael Ruelas (52-4, with 42 knockouts). ``. . . I'm doing
this for myself. I enjoy proving myself right and in the process
proving others wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't necessarily believe in me, but I certainly
believe in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Ruelas, who has relied more on tremendous heart than
natural ability, hasn't fought for a championship since he lost his
IBF lightweight title to Oscar De La Hoya in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe his skills have eroded as he has taken more and
more punches. Some even fear for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas' reaction? A look that says, ``Thanks for sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   He's only 28. As always, he's in tremendous physical condition.
He's trained for three solid months. And he has the wisdom gleaned
from 56 fights working in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   It also should be pointed out that money isn't his prime
motivation. He has invested his earnings well and is attending
school to become a financial adviser. With or without boxing, he
has a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to give it one more shot,'' he said. ``. . . If
you look at the record, I've only had a few losses and I don't
believe I've taken devastating punishment in any fight. The only
one where people can make a case is the Tszyu fight. That just
wasn't my day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. I'm optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that Gabriel Ruelas (45-5, 24 KOs) has more left
than his brother because he hasn't taken as many punches.
</P>
<P>
   However, he hasn't been the same since delivering the blows that
killed Jimmy Garcia on the same card in which De La Hoya beat
Rafael Ruelas. With the exception of a thrilling knockout loss to
Arturo Gatti in 1997, he has lost the fire of his early career and
three of his past seven fights.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after nine-plus months off, he insists he has it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss it,'' he said. ``. . . I thought maybe by just going to
the gym I'd fill that emptiness, but then I started thinking. I'm
only 28. I started thinking of all the fighters older than me who
are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give myself a chance. I haven't been hungry for
years. I feel that way now, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous by his absence will be Joe Goossen, who trained both
fighters since they were children.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen has declined to comment in detail about the separation,
but it's obvious that he doesn't approve of the fighters' decision
to resume their careers.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as obvious that the fighters picked up on it, which is
one reason they moved on. Gabriel Ruelas works with Raymond Acquaye
of Ghana, Rafael Ruelas with Mexican Chato Robles.
</P>
<P>
   Both said it will be strange without Goossen in their corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been different,'' said Rafael Ruelas, who
trains at the L.A. Boxing Gym downtown. ``It IS sad when you think
about it. He's the only trainer we've had.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put that behind you, though. You have to focus on
the future, focus on progressing with a new trainer. That's what
I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
