<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7743 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOUGLAS-AZR &LR;      08-06 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGLAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR BLAMES EMPLOYERS FOR IMMIGRANT WOES  
</HEADLINE>
   (resending to correct slug, dateline) 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. The mayor of this border city is fed up.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Borane is sick of illegal immigrants dying in the desert as
they try to sneak past the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   He's sick of his city's notoriety as the place where ranchers
with rifles stand ready to shoot migrants off their property.
</P>
<P>
   He's sick of the tension, the trash and the tragedy accompanying
the never-ending flow of people through his small city.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of blaming the undocumented, he's lashing out at
those who entice them to come: employers and pampered Americans who
he says are exploiting desperate Mexican job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our community can no longer cope,'' he says in letters
recently fired off to newspapers around the country. ``You are
ultimately to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   In Douglas, a city of 15,000, the residents are outnumbered
every month by the illegal immigrants passing through city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents at the Douglas station stopped 16,900
illegal entrants in July. And that wasn't even the peak month. The
numbers have been higher every month this year, except for May when
there was an unexplained drop to 15,477. March saw a record 27,225
apprehensions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night alone, agents intercepted a group of 240
stealthy crossers hiding in the brush northwest of the city. It was
the third time in just one week that a group of more than 200 had
been caught after cutting past Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, 240 illegal entrants, including three from
Guatemala, were apprehended by agents northwest of Double Adobe, a
small community about 15 miles northwest of Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Border Patrol agents detained 198 illegal entrants
east of Douglas. They were part of a group of about 600 people, the
largest mass crossing ever confronted by Arizona agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an invasion,'' says Borane, a retired state education
official. ``I blame the magnet of people pulling them here to
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was just as direct in the missive he sent to more than
a dozen papers in cities that attract large numbers of migrant
workers including the ``Las Vegas Sun,'' the ``Chicago Tribune,''
the ``Washington Post'' and ``The Arizona Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hire illegal immigrants because you have forgotten,
or never knew how to make your own beds, mow your own lawns or cook
your own meals, as we do ours daily, it causes our fields to be
littered with thousands of plastic jugs and pieces of clothing,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The terrain at the border between Douglas and Agua Prieta,
Sonora, is undeveloped desert where plastic water bottles and
grocery bags discarded by migrants who cross in the night clutter
the harsh landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Borane understands the frustration of the ranchers who complain
that their cattle die after eating the plastic trash or wander off
when their barbed wire fences are cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor, whose maternal grandmother was from Sonora, also
feels sympathy for the migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Borane was born and reared in Douglas. He speaks Spanish
fluently and easily slips into friendly slang when he calls his
counterpart in Agua Prieta. He wants those who hire illegal
immigrants to consider the crossers' sacrifice and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial writer for the ``Aspen Daily News'' thought
Borane's tough talk was right on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a haven for wealth and privilege, this entire region must
accept responsibility for the social and cultural upheaval it
perpetuates,'' Paul Andersen wrote. ``Construction and maintenance
of luxury homes and resort amenities are made profitable for
developers, investors and owners because of cheap labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have chafed at the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not stand all high and mighty, saying, `See, all these rich
people are the problem,' '' angry Aspen area resident Leslie
Stevens wrote about Borane. ``They have to go through you first in
order to get here no matter what route they take. . . . Take care
of your own policies before you start trying to make ours. We are
not the problem, sir, our government policies are.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Henzo, an artist who has lived in Douglas 10 years, says
there is some truth to what Borane says, ``but in terms of hysteria
created by (the illegal immigration), it's more of a nuisance, if
anything, to the ranchers and farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see a great horde invading the community, raping and
pillaging,'' he said while playing dominoes with a group of other
retired men at the Hotel Gadsen. ``They do leave behind trash,
plastic bottles and bags. . . . Most people in Douglas really
aren't affected by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the feedback, Borane is glad that his campaign is
drawing attention to his city's plight. But what he really wants is
a response from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, he went for broke, sending an angry letter to
President Clinton. In it, he accused Clinton of failing to address
the problem of uncontrolled illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write to tell you the border is bleeding,'' Borane's July 29
letter said. ``I simply cannot comprehend your inability to even
publicly recognize or acknowledge this invasion _ intrusion into
our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our isolation, we feel disgusted, frustrated and
abandoned, wandering in the darkness without any expectation of
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, since Douglas became the focal point for
illegal crossings, the federal government has stepped up
enforcement. About 300 agents are now stationed in Douglas &UR; with an
additional 50 on temporary assignment.
</P>
<P>
   In May, ranch patrols were also organized by the Border Patrol
in response to complaints from ranchers and other rural residents.
</P>
<P>
   But Borane says enforcement alone will never stop the flow of
undocumented immigrants. The disparity between the poverty in
Mexico and the ``insatiable demand'' for cheap Mexican labor in the
United States, he says, fuel the flow.
</P>
<P>
   Borane's point is borne out across the line in Agua Prieta. It
is afternoon, and young men and women are milling about on the
sidewalks outside the dozens of cheap hostels that have popped up
to serve the growing numbers of border crossers.
</P>
<P>
   Storm clouds are churning overhead, but no one is deterred from
his or her plan to cross at nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   ````Hay mucho trabajo'' _ there's a lot of work waiting,'' said
Ramiro Reyes, a married father of two who's successfully crossed
illegally several times to work in California fields picking
grapes, melons, kiwis and watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   Borane's argument gets support from Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employers have jobs, but they don't have people to fill
them, so they have to hire Mexicans,'' he said. ``If it wasn't for
the Mexicans, who would do this work?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0110EDT &QL; 
