<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-SALES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANY BECOMING INTERNATIONAL PLAYER WITH SOFTWARE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 4-year-old Kansas City-area Internet
company and the world's largest computer products wholesaler have
cut a deal that is likely to change the way millions of consumers
buy computer games and other software.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an agreement expected to be announced today, NetSales
of Overland Park, Kan., will distribute software over the Internet
for Ingram Micro Inc. Using NetSales, Ingram Micro will offer
thousands of retailers an opportunity to let consumers buy and
download software online.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Micro is a $23.6 billion-a-year wholesaler that supplies
computer products to more than 140,000 retailers ranging from Best
Buy and CompUSA to small storefront computer shops.
</P>
<P>
   Its entrance into electronic software delivery is expected to
rev up an online market that is predicted to grow from $200 million
in 1997 to $5.9 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales could get a big boost, in revenue and industry
visibility, as it collects a percentage of each Ingram Micro sale.
NetSales is one of the area's fastest-growing companies and could
go public soon in what would be the area's first big Internet stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales will provide software electronically for Ingram Micro's
retailers to sell online. Consumers shopping on the Web from those
retailers will be connected invisibly to NetSales, where they'll be
able to download 75,000 or more software products from the Overland
Park company.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with NetSales will allow California-based Ingram
Micro to expand into a new market, said Guy Abramo, senior vice
president of marketing worldwide. NetSales' extensive online
experience makes the company ``an ideal partner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fraser, NetSales founder and CEO, said the agreement was
a ``quantum leap'' for software retailing that would ``rock the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is big step for NetSales, a company that had 15
employees about 18 months ago, employs more than 120 now and has
set up a task force to handle the Ingram Micro project and hire 80
more workers by Jan. 1. The company is expected to grow to 400 or
more by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably double again to 800,'' Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   Even hitting the 400-job mark would make it larger than some
recent new employers that have moved into the area, including the
Harley-Davidson assembly plant in suburban Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership with Ingram Micro is the latest in a series of
high-profile deals for NetSales, which specializes in building
electronic commerce sites for small and medium-size companies.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales is operating more than 1,600 online storefronts and
adds about 40 client retailers or software companies a week. Among
those are deals to set up online stores for the Weather Channel,
Daytimers, Xerox, the Christian Broadcasting Network and the
American Jazz Museum in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to announce an initial public stock
offering later this month. Analysts predict the company will try to
raise $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This outfit has objective business prospects at least as good
as some of the recent smash success IPOs,'' said William F.
Zachmann, an industry analyst and president of Canopus Research.
``That doesn't mean it will happen, but the prospect is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to comment specifically on the
possibility of a public offering.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fraser said NetSales had lost some contracts because it
wasn't a publicly traded company. ``A lot of the bigger clients
want to deal with a bigger company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's start-up financing was raised privately, including
$1.6 million from Kansas City Equity Partners and $6.8 million from
Boston-based HarbourVest Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Zachmann, who met recently with Fraser to discuss NetSales, said
he was ``blown away'' by the company's ``brilliant business
model.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about what they were doing, I thought to myself,
`How come somebody else hasn't been doing that?' '' Zachmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies generally have three options in the rush to enter the
Internet e-commerce consumer market, which is expected to reach $54
billion a year within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Large hardware companies like IBM have established big
e-commerce programs, offering retailers and manufacturers hardware,
software and setup. It comes with a price _ usually in the millions
_ and the process can take up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have turned to outside consultants, who use
off-the-shelf software to set up sites in a process that also can
cost millions and take months.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales and a few other online commerce companies, most notably
Digital River Inc. of Minnesota, offer turnkey e-commerce
alternatives. Instead of charging the companies a large setup fee,
they charge as little as $250 for setup and take a 15 percent cut
of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser thinks the partnership with Ingram Micro will give the
company a boost over the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means our sales are going to go through the roof,'' Fraser
said. ``Tons of new customers are going to come to us. It's going
to get a lot of attention in the marketplace. It also is a huge win
for ESD,'' or electronic software delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said downloadable software is the next high-growth area
in Internet e-commerce. Although computer professionals have been
buying specialty software online for several years, consumers
haven't been as willing to follow that trend as they have been to
buy books, CDs and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think downloadable software is hampered by slow
download speeds and consumers who want to see their software
delivered in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   He said the problem was that no company of any size was offering
enough software online to make the market viable.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser conceded that consumers ``generally feel more comfortable
having a CD-ROM with the software on it.'' In some cases, online
sellers follow up by sending out a hard copy of the software, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Being the ``plumbing,'' as Fraser calls it, of electronic
commerce wasn't always in the plans at www.netsales.net.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser started the company in 1995, working with three employees
out of cramped offices on 87th Street. The business plan then was
to sell advertising to software companies from a Web site at
www.benchin.com where consumers can write their own reviews of
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the Benchin days, e-commerce didn't seem like a big
deal,'' Fraser said. ``It looked like the Internet would bring
information to the desktop, but there was nothing about commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising exploded across the Internet, making Benchin a minor
player among thousands of sites offering advertising opportunities.
However, the company's business relationship with software
companies led to a new business plan _ selling downloadable
software online.
</P>
<P>
   Using database and security software developed by Fraser,
NetSales developed a secure online storefront. The company made its
first software sale on Oct. 31, 1996. ``It was $199. We made 20
bucks. I was like, `Yeah!' ''
</P>
<P>
   NetSales is expected to gross about $7 million this year and
jump to $14 million by the end of next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
