<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY HAS UN-FUNNY VALENTINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Todd Hundley will stay at his Long Island home instead
of the Dodgers' team hotel, will chat with old friends and
reminisce about the good old New York days when the Dodgers begin a
four-game series with the Mets today.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant memories, Hundley calls his days as a Met, although he
can't say the same about his dealings with Mets manager Bobby
Valentine. When it comes to Valentine, Hundley has no desire to
speak to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a no-brainer,'' Hundley said. ``It's really a given. I
don't have anything I need to talk to him about.''
</P>
<P>
   Time hasn't soothed the ill feelings between the two. Hundley
made history with the Mets when he hit a major-league-record 41
homers as a catcher in 1996, but his time in New York ended in
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine made comments about Hundley's New York's night life
negatively impacting his play, then said he got along better with
Mike Piazza because they were both Italian and Hundley is not. An
unnamed Mets employee also accused Hundley of having a drinking
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Hundley responded by saying Valentine's problem with
him stemmed from the fact Hundley was the most popular of the Mets.
Hundley said that didn't sit well with his former manager.
</P>
<P>
   While the words were flying, Hundley was sitting because of
reconstructive elbow surgery. When he returned from his rehab,
Hundley flopped in an experiment in left field and then was traded
in the offseason with minor-leaguer Arnold Gooch for Roger Cedeno
and Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to go in there with a better record than we have,
but you have to put (the turmoil) to rest,'' said Hundley, who
spent parts of nine seasons with the Mets. ``It'd be easy to go
back if we were higher up in the standings, but that's not the
situation. That's where I grew up as a baseball player. I have a
lot of friends there so it's going to be fun. I'll see the guys,
the old teammates, or at least the ones that are left.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mulling Mills: After pitching well for three months, Dodgers
set-up man Alan Mills has been awful the last month. He went 0-3
with a 4.20 ERA in July and is now having control problems.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Thursday's game in Houston with the Dodgers trailing
1-0, walked two batters and allowed an RBI double. All three
batters he faced scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan, that's the worst I've seen of him,'' said Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson, who also had Mills in Baltimore. ``It's not
close. He's not just missing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Arnold hearing delayed: Jamie Arnold's appeal hearing for his
five-game suspension was changed from today until Monday, which
means the right-hander will start Saturday's game against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hoping to have Arnold's suspension reduced, and
team officials believe it can get chopped to three games despite
the video footage of Arnold repeatedly punching Seattle's Damaso
Marte during a July 11 brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad when it's over,'' Arnold said. ``I haven't
thought about (the significance of the start) one bit. Any
opportunity I get to go out and pitch, especially start, it's an
opportunity for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Eric Karros tied his career high with
his 30th double in the first inning. He also had 30 doubles in
1992. . . . Paul LoDuca, recalled from Triple-A before the road
trip, started behind the plate and went 0 for 3. He's now 2 for 39
(0.51) this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
