<HEADLINE>
TWA CANNOT RECOVER FUNDS FROM INSURERS, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A St. Louis judge has ruled that Trans World
Airlines cannot recover from its insurers more than $30 million in
environmental compliance costs at its Kansas City overhaul base.
</P>
<P>
   TWA sued Associated Aviation Underwriters and London Market
Insurers in 1994, seeking to have the insurers indemnify the
airline for polluting four sites at the maintenance base with
hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   The case referred to TWA's consent agreement with the
Environmental Protection Agency in the late 1980s. The EPA also
fined TWA $100,000, but the airline is expected to spend more than
$30 million to comply with the consent agreement, which involves
cleanup, monitoring of soil samples, studies and audits.
</P>
<P>
   But in Missouri Circuit Court in St. Louis, Judge Robert H.
Dierker Jr. ruled Monday that ``pollution exclusion'' provisions
contained in TWA's insurance policies since 1970 meant that its
insurers were not liable for the claims.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said there was no evidence that contamination of
groundwater discovered in the late 1980s occurred before 1970, when
TWA's insurance policies did not have the pollution exclusion
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total victory for us,'' said Joe B. Whisler, attorney
for Cooling &AMP; Herbers of Kansas City. Cooling &AMP; Herbers represented
London Market Insurers on the case, along with the lead law firm,
Lord Bissell &AMP; Bank of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   TWA declined to comment, saying its counsel was studying the
ruling. Whisler, however, said he fully expected TWA to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The lag between the EPA's action 10 years ago and TWA's seeking
of insurance coverage was a factor in Dierker's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since TWA did not invoke coverage until 1994, long after the
1989 consent order, it is plain that AAU (Associated Aviation
Underwriters) had no duty to defend,'' Dierker wrote.
</P>
<P>
   TWA operates and leases the maintenance base, which is owned by
Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
