<HEADLINE>
FISET DEFEATS KINGS IN SALARY RULING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ One month before the start of training camp,
goalie Stephane Fiset recorded his first victory of the season on
Thursday, defeating the Los Angeles Kings in salary arbitration and
winning a one-year contract worth $2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings did not immediately accept the ruling but were
expected to do so, and they must do so by Sunday or exercise their
``walk-away rights'' as spelled out in the NHL's
collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings follow the unlikely path of using their ``walk-away
rights,'' Fiset, 29, would become an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   If Fiset then signed with another team for less than 80 percent
of the $2.1 million ($1.68 million), the Kings would have the right
to match the offer and keep their No. 1 goalie. Fiset also would
have the right to accept the qualifying offer (just over $1.2
million) the Kings made to retain the goalie's rights before the
free-agent signing period began July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, however, the Kings will accept the arbitrator's
ruling. It is not known what offer the Kings made to Fiset before
the arbitrator, except that it was worth more than the qualifying
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Plagued last season by persistent groin injuries, Fiset appeared
in 42 games, posting an 18-21-1 record with three shutouts and a
career-best 2.60 goals-against average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
