<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7755 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CEDENO2-LADN-(SLA     08-06 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CEDENO2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEDENO HAUNTS DODGERS (CORRECTS BYLINE)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ One lap around the New York Mets clubhouse and
it's eerie how often you run into the ghosts of Dodgers past.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner is Mike Piazza, the one-time cornerstone with big
numbers and the big contract. In another is Orel Hershiser, still
pitching more than a decade after winning a Cy Young Award and a
World Series ring. Across the way is Bobby Bonilla, a grim reminder
of last year's transition from Peter O'Malley to Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in manager Bobby Valentine and pitching coach Dave Wallace
and it's the Dodgers the way they were supposed to be, in first
place with the best record in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the starkest connection to the past is quietly
sitting at his locker, lost in the sound of Latin music under a set
of head phones.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno gives a big smile and a wave, but it is still
scary. He is the ghost of Dodgers future.
</P>
<P>
   For years they pictured him doing what he's doing this year for
the Mets, batting .314, stealing 52 bases and securing a place as
one of the league's most exciting players.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno clearly is not the player who made every fly ball an
adventure, every dash from first to third a dance through land
mines. He is the one who pulled hamstrings and misplayed fly balls,
suffered broken toes and broken dreams.
</P>
<P>
   This year he nearly made the All-Star team and leads the league
in stolen bases heading into tonight's series opener against the
Dodgers at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a place that believed in me,'' Cedeno said. ``I'm on a
team where I'm not always looking over my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be simple to check off Cedeno as another Dodgers
disaster, another Pedro Martinez who was buried under a language
barrier and crushing expectations. But Valentine, who came up in
the Dodgers organization in the late 1960s, says it's more
complicated than that. For the first time, Cedeno excelled because
no one was waiting for miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen very often that a player comes to New York
with less pressure on him than the place he came from,'' Valentine
said. ``But that definitely was the case with Roger. When we traded
for him last winter, we saw him as a fourth outfielder at best. We
didn't see him as a savior. He came into spring training knowing
that there was no pressure. He just took off from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who turns 25 later this month, was acquired in a
three-team trade with the Dodgers and Baltimore on Dec. 1. When
veteran free-agent Rickey Henderson started slowly, Cedeno became
the offensive catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I never saw in Los Angeles was his speed,'' said
Bonilla, who played just over a half-season with the Dodgers after
coming over from Florida in the Piazza trade. ``He just has a
confidence here that wasn't there before. But I don't blame the
Dodgers. Where was he going to play with (Raul Mondesi) in right,
(Devon White) in center and (Gary Sheffield) left? Sometimes you
have to let a guy move on and hope it doesn't come back to haunt
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno played parts of four seasons with the Dodgers. In 1996,
he took over in center when Brett Butler underwent surgery and
treatment for throat cancer. He played 86 games, batting an
unspectacular .246 and stealing just five bases.
</P>
<P>
   He also was tentative defensively and injury prone. He missed
the final 30 games of the 1997 season with a fractured left big toe
and was sidelined all of spring training and the first 20 games of
1998 with a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think back to him in those days, that is what you
remember,'' Piazza said. ``He was getting an opportunity, but
things always got in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of it all, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone says he
was reluctant to trade a switch hitter with speed regardless of his
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My scouts said he couldn't play center field,'' Malone said.
``There was no other place to put him in our outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem goes back even farther than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have an unofficial rule that any player signed out
of Latin America must spend at least two years playing for the
club's rookie-league team in the Dominican Republic. The move is
designed to give the players a chance to mature and develop before
arriving in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, a Venezuelan, played only 58 games for Santo Domingo
before heading to Great Falls, Mont., and the Dodgers minor-league
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything I would do over, it would be keeping him
in the Dominican the full two years,'' said Dodgers chief Latin
scout Ralph Avila. ``He was just such a complete player, we forgot
how much he still had to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno and Valentine credit former Mets center fielder Mookie
Wilson, now a coach with the team, with the turnaround. Wilson took
over the project with only one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there to restore his confidence,'' Wilson said. ``We
talked a lot about what happened with the Dodgers, but we didn't
dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Cedeno's rebirth with the Mets, Valentine says Malone's
scouting report was accurate. Although Cedeno often is dazzling
defensively in right, he is shaky in center. Valentine hopes to put
Cedeno there some day, but when he traded starter Brian McRae at
the July 31 deadline, he got center fielder Darryl Hamilton in
return.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno got three hits Wednesday in Milwaukee after going through
his first extended slump with the Mets. Since July 17, he had gone
11 for 56 (.196) with 17 strikeouts, dropping his average from
.336.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine stayed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't criticize the Dodgers and we certainly didn't have all
the answers,'' he said. ``We had some coaches who would have rolled
their eyes when Roger would make a mistake. But one thing we did
during the instruction was get him to answer us when we asked him a
question. A lot of times, a Latin player will just nod because he
doesn't understand the questions. We tried to communicate more and
I guess it got through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
