<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NY     08-06 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT MARINERS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There will be the peripheral issues for Manager Joe
Torre in these last two months of the Yankees' regular season, the
Darryl Strawberry sideshow and Andy Pettitte's crisis of confidence
and the overpowering intensity of Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The project that will consume the Yankees, however, is the
mystery of Roger Clemens, a puzzle that must be solved before the
post-season. Clemens floundered early again on Thursday night but
survived, lasting seven innings in a 7-4 victory against Seattle in
the Yankees' first game in the newly opened Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez slammed his 200th and 201st career home runs, ending a
string of 79 at-bats without a homer. Torre had called Martinez
into his office before the game for one of those chats Torre likes
to have with slumping players. Martinez batted seventh in the
lineup for the Yankees, the lowest position in the batting order he
has occupied in his four seasons since being acquired from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had five extra-base hits against Jamie Moyer (10-6),
Bernie Williams' first-inning two-run triple among them, and if
Clemens were pitching as the Yankees expected him to when they
traded three players for him in February, they would have glided to
their 65th victory. But again Clemens was wildly inconsistent at
the outset, inning to inning, batter to batter, pitch to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He missed his aim with a fastball to Alex Rodriguez in the first
inning _ catcher Jorge Posada set up inside and Clemens's fastball
went outside _ and Rodriguez crushed a two-run homer. The Yankees
(65-42) assumed a 3-2 advantage in the second, on the first of
Martinez's home runs, before Clemens struggled badly in the third,
repeatedly failing to finish off hitters once he reached a
favorable ball-strike count.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Clemens threw to the three batters who preceded Ken
Griffey Jr. and Rodriguez in the third inning:
</P>
<P>
   _ Russ Davis, the No. 9 batter, fell behind by no balls and two
strikes and stroked a single.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian Hunter walked on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Bell fell behind, no balls and two strikes, and drew a
walk.
</P>
<P>
   Bases loaded, nobody out, Griffey and Rodriguez due to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fired a fastball through Griffey's swing for strike one,
tossed another for strike two _ no balls and two strikes again _
before Griffey laced an outside fastball to left field, driving
home a run. Griffey hit the ball so hard that Hunter had to stop at
third, even with his sprinter's speed. Clemens got ahead of
Rodriguez no balls and two strikes, the same pattern, and Rodriguez
managed to loft a fly ball to right field, deep enough for Hunter
to score. The Yankees trailed, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coaches who have worked with Clemens in the past say he
adjusts adeptly. If there is a mechanical flaw, he will fix it. If
he falls into a pitch pattern that needs correcting, he will
change. Clemens could not have compiled 243 victories without
adapting.
</P>
<P>
   So the solution for Clemens does not appear to be simple,
reflected in the possible theories considered by the Yankees. Once
he recovers from a strained hamstring and regains his leg strength,
they thought, then the Rocket would take off; he has not. Once
Clemens went back to relying on his fastball, they thought, then
Clemens would rebound; he has not.
</P>
<P>
   A hitter for another team that faced Clemens recently said the
talk among his teammates is how much less Clemens commands the
outside part of the plate. ``He doesn't seem as intent on
intimidating you as he used to be,'' the player said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another theory, too. Clemens is not Clemens yet, but
on Thursday night, he was good enough to win. Imperfect though he
was, _ he required 95 pitches to get through the first five innings
_ he battled and competed enough and had enough run support to pick
up his 10th victory.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees down a run in the sixth, Martinez lofted his
second home run of the game, a two-run shot that propelled his team
into the lead. Clemens shut out the Mariners (53-55) in the fourth,
fifth and sixth innings, and the Yankees added a run in the top of
the seventh, moving ahead, 6-4. They closed out their scoring with
a run in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell was the last hitter Clemens faced, with two outs in
the bottom of the seventh, and after Williams ran down Bell's long
drive at the base of the wall in right-center field, Clemens waited
for Williams in front of the dugout and patted him on the head,
affectionately pushing his hat from side to side. His teammates
helped Clemens get through Thursday night, and they are hoping for
_ expecting _ the greater side of Clemens to appear before
October's trials. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
