<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, WHITE HOUSE SCRAMBLING TO SAVE HUGE PLANE DEAL WITH CHINA
AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and Washington politicians are
scrambling to salvage The Boeing Co.'s plan to sell $1.5 billion
worth of airplanes to China Airlines after the carrier indicated it
was walking away from the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Taiwan and its largest carrier, China Airlines,
have told Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., they won't proceed with plans
to buy as many as 12 Boeing 777 airplanes. Instead, they are opting
to order A340 airplanes from Boeing's rival, Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   The indication has set off a flurry of activity in Washington,
D.C., with senators pressing Taiwan to reconsider and senior
Clinton administration officials contacting their Taiwanese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the press will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   China Airlines could complete its agreement with Airbus within
days, according to congressional aides. Still, Boeing has a chance
to land the order _ or a portion of it _ thanks to the last-minute
flurry of visits, according to an aide familiar with the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can work something out here,'' said Washington
Democratic Rep. Norm Dicks. ``I am very encouraged'' by the Clinton
administration's response, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential order appears to be a victim of the Taiwan
government's anger over President Clinton's China policy and its
claims that Boeing has treated it poorly, according to lawmakers
and congressional aides.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton will make a final effort to appease those concerns by
flying Friday to Taiwan. He plans to meet with senior officials
from both the government and China Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   While China Airlines appears ready to craft a deal with Airbus,
the carrier could also decide to grant Boeing a portion of the
original 777 order, according to a congressional aide familiar with
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing should hope, at least, to save half of it,'' the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   If that effort fails, China Airlines would strip Boeing of a
lucrative contract and reward its competitor, Airbus, in the
critical Asian market. China Airlines never officially agreed to
buy the 777s. Rather, in 1995 it signed a letter of intent, which
isn't a binding contract.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the airline denied that politics would influence
the company's decision. The contract will be announced next week,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   While China Airlines may place its $1.5 billion 777 order in
Airbus' hands, Boeing is still expected to land a separate order
with the carrier for up to 13 Boeing 747-400s, worth an estimated
$2.5 billion, next week.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan pushed the carrier toward Airbus on the 777 contract,
initially because officials were angered by Clinton's refusal to
alter the U.S. position on China, according to Dicks.
</P>
<P>
   President Lee Teng-hui recently said Taiwan and China should
conduct talks as two equal states.
</P>
<P>
   The move angered China, and in the wake of the comments, Clinton
reaffirmed U.S. support for the ``one China'' policy that has been
a backbone of U.S. policy toward China and Taiwan. However, Clinton
added that he ``would take very seriously'' any attempt by Beijing
to resolve its differences with Taiwan by force.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks said Taiwan should consider how much it relies on U.S.
support as it looks to the European-based Airbus for the new order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Taiwanese should recognize if there ever is a
crucial moment in the future it is going to be the United States of
America upon which their security rests,'' Dicks said. ``I would
not think I would want to go out and offend that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan, however, has also laid the blame at the feet of Boeing,
saying the aerospace giant has failed to treat it like a top-flight
customer that has purchased billions of dollars worth of airplanes
in the last four years, according to Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Murray met Thursday with Stephen Chen, a Taiwan representative
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said before the meeting that it was unlikely the Boeing
order could be saved. But ``they did not say ... the door is
shut,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and the United States don't have formal ties.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Commerce
Secretary Bill Daley have also joined the fray and have written
letters to Taiwan officials.
</P>
<P>
   We ``have relayed to them that any purchase should be made on
commercial and technical merit,'' said Helaine Klasky, a
spokeswoman for Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co., which is the largest U.S. exporter, and Taiwan
also play large roles in Washington's economy, spurring Gov. Gary
Locke to offer his assistance Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been enlisted, but have thought on my own that I
would be more than willing to help in any way I can, to talk with
Taiwanese officials, to the government of Taiwan, to help Boeing,''
Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Boeing nor its rival Airbus would say much about the
$1.5 billion potential order as it entered a critical stage of
international diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the marketplace has spoken,'' said Marta Newhart, a
spokeswoman for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only flag carrier in Asia that hasn't chosen it (the 777)
is China Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials declined to discuss the situation, except to
say the consortium of European companies would welcome an order as
the market for wide-body airplanes softens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wide-body order would be particularly nice to have at this
point in time,'' said David Venz, an Airbus spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace rivals should know the winner in a matter of days,
according to Murray.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Boeing officials have their work cut out for them as
they make their last-minute pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have progressed (to the point) that they are close to
signing a deal with Airbus,'' said Cynthia Bergman, a spokeswoman
for Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
