<SLUG> BC-BOX-BRIGGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGGS CAN'T AFFORD TO WASTE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. _ Growing up in the rough Brownsville
section of Brooklyn, N.Y., Shannon Briggs spent four of his
formative years on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was a heroin addict, whose habit caused her to lose
everything, including a place to live. But Briggs survived.
</P>
<P>
   As a heavyweight boxer, Briggs has battled asthma, a supposed
lack of heart and the stigma that he is not as serious as he should
be about his profession. But today, Briggs labels himself a
determined, more mature fighter.
</P>
<P>
   He gets a chance to prove that against Francois Botha (39-2, 24
KOs), who will fight the new Shannon Briggs on a pay-per-view card
Saturday in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am 27 years old now,'' said Briggs, ranked No.7 by the WBC.
``I have matured, physically and mentally, and I am enjoying boxing
a lot more now.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, or the career of one of the more talented
heavyweights to come along recently could have been a waste.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of change for Briggs came when he hired trainer
Emanuel Steward, who trained Lennox Lewis when Lewis knocked out
Briggs in the fifth round March 28, 1998. It was his second loss,
the other was to Darroll Wilson, who knocked Briggs out in the
third round on March 15, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Briggs, now 31-2, is a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was a heroin addict for 15 years, so we eventually
fell,'' said Briggs, whose mother died Dec. 4, 1997, on his 25th
birthday. ``And I lived on the streets. But it was a learning
experience for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back and regret any of it. I feel like that is
how I got into boxing. I know I wouldn't have been able to go
through the toughness of boxing unless I went through that
hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suffered a lot. But before my mom died, she got to see her
son become successful as a boxer. That was very important. She
didn't feel like her life was wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, her son is working to avoid wasting what could become a
fine boxing career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
