<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY IS FINE IN ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The season has been as baffling to Chuck
Finley as it has been disappointing, but for one night the Anaheim
Angels pitcher showed why he was a sought-after commodity before
the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing one of his best games of the season, Finley shut out
the Boston Red Sox on four hits in seven innings as the Angels won
8-0 Thursday night before 26,175 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Finley won his first game in five starts; his last win was on
July 9 vs. Colorado. He struck out seven, giving him 2,075 in his
career and moving him into 46th place on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Finley has endured what he called the worst slump of his career.
And coincidentally or not, it started after he suggested he might
accept a trade to a contender if the Angels fell out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In his eight previous starts going into Thursday's game, Finley
won one game and had an ERA of 9.29.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Angels' second in a row, the first time
they've won back-to-back games since beating the Rockies July 9 and
10.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus hit a three-run homer, Jim Edmonds had four hits,
Garret Anderson had three and Orlando Palmeiro and Ben Molina added
two apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus broke a scoreless tie in the fourth inning after singles
by Edmonds and Darin Erstad put runners on first and third with
none out.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus hit a towering fly ball down the left-field line on a 1-0
pitch, but it hooked foul. On the very next pitch, Glaus hit
another towering fly ball, but that one stayed fair and gave the
Angels a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was Glaus' 18th home run of the season, tying him with Mo
Vaughn for the team lead. Glaus' 50 RBI rank second on the team
behind Vaughn's 64.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox threatened to rally in the sixth, putting runners on
first and second with one out. Finley fell behind in the count to
Butch Huskey, 3-1, but got him to hit into a force play for the
second out.
</P>
<P>
   Finley then fell behind to Troy O'Leary, 3-0, but threw three
consecutive strikes to get out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added to their lead in the bottom of the sixth after
Glaus opened the inning with a walk. Jeff Huson's hit-and-run
single drove Glaus to third, and Ben Molina scored Glaus with a
single to right.
</P>
<P>
   After ex-Dodger pitcher Mark Guthrie replaced Bryce Florie,
Orlando Palmeiro's sacrifice fly to the short fence in right field
scored Huson. One out later, Garret Anderson drove in Molina from
second with a bloop single to center for a 6-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, it looked as though the game would be just
another with missed opportunities. The Angels loaded the bases on
three walks with none out in the second inning, but Huson grounded
into a 1-2-3 double play and Molina lined out to center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
