<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7766 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-CANCER-SPI &LR;      08-06 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-CANCER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS WORRY THAT STUDY ON SUNBURN, SKIN CANCER WILL BE
MISINTERPRETED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists in Texas have found that sunburn may actually stop
the beginnings of skin cancer by ridding the skin of genetically
damaged cells.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in
Houston cautioned sun lovers that the finding is not at all an
endorsement of serious tanning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean a sunburn is a good thing,'' said Dr.
Honnavara Ananthaswamy, chairman of immunology at the University of
Texas' M.D. Anderson center and a co-author of the study, published
Friday in the journal, Science.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the study's findings, Dr. Daniel Berg, director of
dermatologic surgery at the University of Washington in Seattle,
said it's the sunburn that causes the damage in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believing sunburns will protect you against skin cancer is
like arguing that slashing somebody with a knife stimulates their
body's wound healing system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas team's research, based on mice, showed that skin
burned by excessive exposure to the ultraviolet portion of sunlight
triggers a genetically programmed ``cell suicide'' mechanism that
kills off heavily irradiated skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   But Ananthaswamy emphasized that the same sunburn also causes
moderate damage in cells that don't get eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might kill off those cells with excessive damage, but
cells with less damage will persist, and may later develop into
cancer,'' he said. ``This (study) isn't a license to go out and get
a sunburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Skin cancer is the most common form of cancer. In the United
States, about 1 million cases are diagnosed annually.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious form, melanoma, accounts for about 44,200 cases
each year. Although skin cancer can be treated if detected early,
it kills about 9,200 Americans each year.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston cancer center team, led by Drs. Laurie Hill and
Laurie Owen-Schaub, identified the role of a particular gene
product, a protein known as FasL, that plays a key role in
responding to sunburn and leading to the ``cell suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   The mouse is considered a good model for human skin cancer
studies.
</P>
<P>
   One potential implication of the study could be that humans
defective in the FasL protein may be at greater risk for developing
skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Owen-Schaub said it appears FasL helps protect the body from
over-exposure to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get DNA damage almost every time you go out,'' she said.
``If you can get rid of the cells containing the DNA damage, you
get rid of the cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important known players in ridding the body of
mutated cells is a gene known as p53, which so far appears to be
implicated in half of all cancers.
</P>
<P>
   When p53 fails to do its job, cancer can occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know about p53 and how to protect their p53s,''
said Christopher Kemp, a cancer biologist at the Fred Hutchinson
Cancer Research Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding sun exposure, tobacco and charred meat are ways people
can protect their p53 genes, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas study is interesting, he said, because
the research team found that FasL appears to work together with p53
in ridding the skin of pre-cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sheds light, no pun intended, on the mechanism of how cells
get damaged by a toxic substance such as sunlight and respond to
that damage,'' said the UW's Berg.
</P>
<P>
   This could lead to tests that might help identify those people
at higher risk for skin cancer, Berg said. It could also lead to
better treatment and prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, doctors said they were concerned the study would be
misinterpreted. That fear, they said, stems from the public's
misunderstanding of the value of sunscreen lotions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Owen-Schaub and Berg agreed that the proper use of
sunscreens likely protects against skin cancer, they said no one
knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   That unanswered question, Berg said, is complicated by a number
of studies that found people who frequently use sunscreen have a
higher rate of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Some have interpreted this to mean that sunscreens somehow cause
the cancer, he said, when it may mean that people who use lotions
spend more time in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a false sense of security ... and they over-expose
themselves,'' said Ananthaswamy.
</P>
<P>
   He and the other cancer experts said the use of sunscreen
together with limited exposure to sunlight is still the most
prudent method for preventing the risk of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas study was based on a comparison of mice
which had normal protein FasL activity against mice that were bred
to be deficient in this protein.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups of mice were then exposed to UV radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the normal mice, 5 percent had genetically damaged, or
mutated, skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   Among the FasL-deficient mice, 70 percent had mutated cells.
</P>
<P>
   That indicates that the lack of FasL allowed more DNA damaged
cells to persist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
