<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7769 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUD-GRANT-SPI &LR;      08-06 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-GRANT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S RAINIER VALLEY GETS FED HELP FOR REDEVELOPMENT PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Southeast Seattle's Rainier Valley scored a major
redevelopment windfall Thursday when the city received $17.2
million in federal support for a $45 million commercial and housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainier Court Shopping Center would bring retail shops, an
8- to 10-screen movie theater and apartments to a run-down,
eight-acre tract at 3700 Rainier Ave. S.
</P>
<P>
   The project, with 156,000 square feet of commercial space, will
create 250 jobs and add up to 180 affordable housing units,
developers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This part of Seattle has been ignored for too long,'' U.S.
Rep. Jim McDermott said at a news conference. ``While other areas
of the city were benefiting from redevelopment in a thriving local
economy, parts of Rainier Valley have been left out.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hoped that a project of this magnitude, offering both
commercial and housing, will serve as an economic jumpstart for one
of the city's poorest areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating a civic center that makes you want to get out
of your car and do things,'' said Earl Richardson, executive
director of SouthEast Effective Development (SEED), a non-profit
community development corporation, which will be the developing
agency.
</P>
<P>
   SEED plans to build 201 apartments and 43 townhouses, with 140
to 180 of the units pegged for low-income tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment rents would go for about $500 to $700 a month, and
residents would range from working-class people to those earning
about $60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said his group has talked with Magic Johnson Theaters
about building the multiscreen movie complex.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball legend Johnson is known to build multiscreen theaters
in inner-city locations in cities such as Los Angeles and Miami,
filling a void.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was praising what was being billed as one of
Seattle's biggest such redevelopments.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents worried that the gentrification of the area _
which is near the upscale Mount Baker neighborhood _ and escalating
property taxes will drive minorities, working-class people and
longtime residents out of Rainier Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making it too expensive for us to live here,'' said
hair designer Andrena Harris, shampooing a client's hair Thursday
at Unique Hair Design, a block from the development.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the site last night, 20-year resident Penny Graham
hoped developers will keep in mind the needs of local residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to broaden the survey of what people here really
need,'' Graham said. Keep it affordable, she said, so people who
have lived here a long time won't be driven out.
</P>
<P>
   But at Continental Sales and Music Center, owner Marshall Jones
welcomed the development as a step toward getting rid of blight and
crime, instilling community pride and bringing jobs to the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``We need something out here that we can
call our own rather than going out to Southcenter Mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Starbucks boss Howard Schultz opened a joint-venture
Starbucks Coffee shop in Columbia City this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the community here deserves this,'' Johnson said at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But critics cautioned those who celebrated the HUD financial
backing, saying the development is another step toward yuppifying
Seattle and displacing poor, minority residents to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to the Columbia City Starbucks as an example of
unwanted gentrification.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a project that's friendly to this area. SEED has
turned its back on the community,'' said George Curtis, a Rainier
Valley resident and member of Save Our Valley. The group this week
requested a federal investigation of what it sees as racially
driven inequities in Sound Transit's proposed light rail line
through Rainier Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Peter Steinbrueck welcomed the news of the federal
money, but cautioned that redevelopment should not mean pushing out
poor, working-class people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should preserve communities and not cause displacement,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainier Valley ranks high on Mayor Paul Schell's list of
neighborhoods that should receive public resources.
</P>
<P>
   But even as politicians promise to not force anyone out of
subsidized housing, fears persist among some wary South End
residents that when there's talk about redevelopment, it means
being pushed aside by a new upscaled community.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case when the city this year requested a hefty
federal grant to double Rainier Vista's 481 housing units and build
new homes to replace the World War II-era housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Schell and others point to positive changes at the east Beacon
Hill housing project of Holly Park, undergoing a transformation
from low-income to mixed-income.
</P>
<P>
   And the manager of a Safeway store across the street from the
proposed Rainier Court Shopping Center said the neighborhood needs
the commercial growth and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're pouring dollars into the community. It can't help but
help,'' said the manager who declined to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's $17.2 million in HUD backing consists of $15.5
million in loan guarantees, which the city will pass on to SEED.
</P>
<P>
   The city also drew a $1.7 million Brownsfield Economic
Development Initiative grant.
</P>
<P>
   SEED will borrow $27.8 million more from private sources. The
developer hopes to break ground in 2000 and finish construction in
July 2002.
</P>
<P>
   SEED hopes the anchor stores, offices and retail shops will
capture a portion of the estimated $250 million in local consumer
money currently spent outside the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to partner with the private firm of Gramor Development
Washington to build Rainier Court.
</P>
<P>
   The first job is to spend $7 million to buy parts of the site
SEED does not already own, then $800,000 to $1 million for
environmental cleanup of petroleum products and chemicals left from
past businesses. The site was once home to a welding shop, auto
distributor, tool company and dump truck service.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said residents around the site are concerned about
traffic and parking.
</P>
<P>
   The project will include parking for 1,009 cars, including 289
underground spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on balance, they want to see something happen,'' he said.
``It's a pretty much rundown site and that doesn't help property
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Phuong Le contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
