<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSTV-LADN-(SLA     08-06 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSTV-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA PACK HEAVY FOR GWYNN, MCCGWIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It is a fact of life in sports that once an athlete
rises above the pack, he comes to dislike another pack altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the media pack, a species with hundreds of legs,
thousands of dollars of electronic equipment, interchangeable faces
and questions that range from the obtuse to the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing personal. Tony Gwynn and Mark McGwire actually like
many of the media people who intersect their lives, and they and
other superstars certainly understand it's a part of the process.
Gwynn is glib, and McGwire is guarded in dealing with reporters,
but they essentially handle it well.
</P>
<P>
   But times like now are very wearing. The media attention at
milestone moments like this McGwire hit his 500th and 501st career
home runs and Gwynn collected his 2,999th career hit Thursday can
be suffocating, frustrating and even damaging.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers double their usual number of reporters. National
magazines dispatch reporters and photographers. The number of radio
microphones, usually seeking nothing more than a crisp 15-second
quote, can triple. Each TV crew can include as many as four people
sportscaster, producer, cameraman and sound man and every one wants
the ultimate one-on-one interview.
</P>
<P>
   And each and every interview session has the same dynamic,
because the questions all focus on ``The Moment.'' How will you
feel? Are you pressing? Nervous? What have your teammates said? Is
this the greatest moment in your life?
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers are bigger than both of us,'' said Gwynn. ``We
try to handle it like professionals. The thing is, we know what
people are going to ask, and sometimes, there's no answer. Or the
answer is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get a hit, people will want to know why. And
sometimes the answer is that I happened to suck that night.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went through this past year during his chase and
escalation of the home run record. He came to deplore the `how will
you feel' question, because there's no way to predict exactly what
someone will feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one more (home run),'' McGwire said Wednesday, ``and then
I can answer all the questions you've wanted to ask.''
</P>
<P>
   The better reporters often look for deeper, more meaningful
questions. But those require much more time than either the
reporter or athlete have available. That can then lead to obtuse
questions, like the one thrown out Wednesday at McGwire: ``When's
the last time you were asked a good question?''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire pursed his lips and shrugged. ``Last spring?'' he said.
``It's the same stuff all the time. I go to the archives. I give
the same answers to the same questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn and McGwire talked about the crush during Wednesday's
game, after a Gwynn single led to a pitching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he doesn't have to explain why he didn't get a hit
every time,'' said McGwire. ``Tony's been through things like the
World Series, but this is the first time he's had to deal with
everything personally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tougher for me,'' Gwynn said. ``I've never had to deal
with it like this. Basically, I'm talked out. There's no way I can
preview this any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The media crush has other angles beyond what someone says and
the size of the pack. On Wednesday, a reporter asked McGwire if he
is still taking andro, the hormone supplement which caused a bit of
a firestorm last summer.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said no, that he had stopped taking andro before the
season because he was concerned his use was an influence on kids.
He was uncomfortable that teens might think he's endorsing the
product. Since the andro story broke a year ago, the product has
enjoyed a sales boom, and a significant percentage of new users are
teenage boys.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he waited until August and the eve of his 500th
home run to announce this, he said ``no one asked.'' The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch takes issue with that. Its reporters say they asked
him about it during spring training. They believe he waited until
the timing was right 42 homers in early August and andro-free for
four months to guard against critics saying his 70-homer season was
a hormonal fluke.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it is easy for the media pack to feel a bit used
and abused. Is it any wonder why so many of us are cynical.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the teammate issue, which becomes a question of
media spillover. The impression last year during McGwire's run was
that he was well-liked by his teammates and they were tolerant of
the situation. But soon after being traded, Brian Jordan said last
year ``was all about one guy'' and that many teammates resented the
attention McGwire received.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn felt this brush last weekend, when Jim Leyritz, after
being traded, said Gwynn wasn't a leader and inferred he was
selfish. Two other Padres, quoted anonymously, said Leyritz was out
of line, but they also said there was a little truth to what
Leyritz said.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was angry for a few days, then let it go. He's the first
to admit the crush of coverage of his milestone takes away from his
teammates and can warp the usual list of priorities. The Padres
have won one game in their last 12, so it isn't a happy, fun-loving
clubhouse right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get it done just so things can get back to
normal,'' he said. ``This takes away from the 24 other guys. The
focus shifts from the games to what you do, and that I really don't
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is winning and losing. When you have
success and the team doesn't win, it's difficult to sit there and
talk about yourself with a smile. Your teammates have every right
to (feel a bit strange). Right now, I want to get these two hits
and get back to being just one of 25 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
