<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN-(SLANG     08-06 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND A PROFIT WAS MADE BY ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall on ABC's ``Show Me The Money'' Monday prime-time:
</P>
<P>
   Join the hijinks on the links with Tiger Woods and one of his
PGA pals in the new drama/comedy/tragedy series ``Two Guys, A
Gallery and a Fairway with Floodlights and a Big Rock in the
Middle,'' coming up right after ``Monday Night Football'' on most
of these network stations.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   The next made-for-Tiger ``Showdown at (Fill In the Name of the
Elite Country Club)'' match-play event will likely happen, but
exhibitions like last Monday night's crowd-pleaser at Thousand
Oaks' Sherwood Country Club will depend on much more than Nielsen's
backing, according to those involved in such programming decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour gods must allow it. There have to be sponsors. It
has to show a profit. And the headline players have to be
available. If there's a charity available to kick back some of the
dough to, so as not look too obscene, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, TV might not even require two golfers to be present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matchup has to make sense on a number of different
levels,'' said John Filippelli, ABC's new senior vice president of
programming. ``If Tiger Woods takes on Justin Leonard, would that
capture the same interest? This was a unique situation with the
Nos. 1 and 2 golfers available and a prime-time slot available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say we had the top two NASCAR or Grand Prix drivers available
_ could you do a show around two cars going around a track for an
hour and a half? I don't know. But we'd consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   A regularly televised golf-tour event might appear to have
minuscule ratings/ share numbers, such as the 3.0/7 for the PGA's
Greater Hartford Open on CBS last weekend. But that's deceiving
because it's like comparing a pound of angel food cake to a sliver
of cheesecake _ the smaller piece is much richer. The male
demographics bear that out.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's respectable 7.4/12 ratings/share for the
overnights in major markets, adjusted to a 6.9/12 once everyone
else was accounted for, definitely showed that even casual fans
took notice. On Monday nights in July and August, ABC typically
airs a stale movie that even Blockbuster has taken off the rental
shelves, which usually delivers a 6.3 rating.
</P>
<P>
   By ABC research, more than 20 million viewers watched some or
all of Monday's Tiger 'n Dave show. Even though overall it was only
the fourth-most-watched show that night behind CBS' ``48 Hours,''
``Becker,'' and ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' one of the most
important numbers to the sponsors was that ABC grabbed the
highest-rated share of men ages 18-49 and men ages 25-54 for the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, to counter the $1.5 million that the network paid the PGA
for the rights to the event, it reportedly sold more than $2
million in advertising spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever criteria you use to measure success, we met and
exceeded it,'' said Filippelli.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Gerber, the executive vice president of ESPN Regional
Television, might be the single busiest golf producer on TV today.
He oversees 48 televised events each year, and for the last 10
years has been involved in the Skins Games, which many golf
elitists consider to be the beginning of the made-for-TV events
that have cheapened the game.
</P>
<P>
   On July 26-27 of last week, he conducted a similar event _ the
DLJ direct Par 3 Shootout with Jack Nicklaus, Ray Floyd, Phil
Mickelsen and Lee Janzen that was shown tape-delayed in prime time
over two nights on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Gerber, like Filippelli, doubts there'll be a sudden surge of
these events, especially on a weekly basis, but ``you'll probably
see another excursion or two in prime time as long as it has a
unique format and the cooperation of the PGA Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerber notes that since the PGA won't sign off on members to
play on TV elsewhere when there's a tour event going on, the only
TV windows generally open during the season are Mondays and/or
Tuesdays. After the tour season ends, the so-called ``Silly
Season'' that includes the Shark Shootout are played during the
fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of Woods and Duval was exposing the game to the
non-golf viewer,'' Gerber said. ``I'd think the tour would welcome
anything that increases popularity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Events like this or the Skins Games bring out the
personalities, so to be successful, you need someone with a strong
public following. But there's only a handful of guys who have the
ability to bring a ratings spike.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Woods has done for TV is impressive. Prior to him, the
regular tour was a ratings doldrum. Tiger can probably generate a
ratings point or two all by himself if he's on the leaderboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerber agrees that these ratings will spark future events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, anytime you can go to a course and watch Tiger and David
play and bump into Wayne Gretzky, it can't be all that bad,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics who call these events an insult to the game don't
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absurd,'' said Filippelli. ``. . . This was a chance to
do something for the game of golf, something that could be hugely
important to its future by exposing it on larger stage. On its own
terms, it had merit. Anyone who says it was a sham, I'd suggest
they get more of a life.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
__ NFL. On TV. It's (brace yourself) back. The warmup is the
2{-hour Hall of Fame induction ceremonies from Canton, Ohio, shown
Saturday on ESPN2 at 10 a.m. that'll include Eric Dickerson's time
to shine. Later that day at 6 p.m., Fox delivers the American Bowl
between the Ryan Leaf-less San Diego Chargers and John Elway-less
Denver Broncos from Rupert Murdoch's backyard in Sydney, Australia.
Pat Summerall does the call with Matt Millen because no one could
figure how to get the Maddencruiser to drive on water. Monday, it's
the unofficial opener to the 30th season of ``Monday Night
Football'' with the Hall of Fame Game in Canton between Cleveland
and Dallas at 5 p.m. (don't worry, regular ``MNF'' goes back to 6
p.m. when the season starts). This could be the first time many
people actually turn on the audio portion of the telecast, since
the team of Al Michaels and Boomer ``Mr. America'' Esiason will be
free from the syntax shackles of Dan Dierdorf. &QL; 
__ Veteran sports radio guys Fred Wallin and Peter Vent have worked
a deal to take their show to KRLA-AM (1110) for a Saturday 7-10
p.m. slot. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
__ This messy ending to the relationship of former USC broadcasters
Larry Kahn and Mike Lamb with the university. Suits and
countersuits in L.A. Superior Court, claims of defamation and
breach of contracts forcing the two to come up with nearly three
quarters of a million dollars. Kahn and Lamb, who might have got in
over their heads financially but were always professional as
broadcasters, busted their tails for the school and are left busted
by broken promises. &QL; 
__ Jimmy Roberts' health plan. Next time you're on the golf course
trying to do an interview, try a little power-walking with a
protein-boost shake at Ballys before going step-for-step with Tiger
Woods, as was attempted during his match play against David Duval.
Roberts, who must now cover golf as he would a triathlon, might try
to use the Casey Martin exemption and ride a cart alongside next
time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
