</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MILESTN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN WITHIN ONE HIT OF 3,000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ST. LOUIS  &UR; _  &LR; The final tally after Thursday's baseball game at
Busch Stadium was 501 home runs for Mark McGwire, 2,999 hits for
Tony Gwynn, a 10-3 Padre win, and ten standing ovations from a
crowd of 45,106.
</P>
<P>
   For Gwynn. Not for Mark, the big redhead in the Cardinal jersey
who crushed two more baseballs and made some more baseball history,
but for the right fielder in the visiting gray uniform.
</P>
<P>
   There were standing ovations before the game, for each of
Gwynn's five at-bats, an enormous cheer after his two-run double in
the ninth inning, a cheer as he ran out to right field for the
bottom of the ninth, another rousing ovation when the scoreboard
flashed a thanks-and-good-luck message, and one last cheer as he
walked into the dugout after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the loud boos when Gwynn was walked in the second
inning and the assorted individual hosannas, and you have about two
dozen physical displays of affection.
</P>
<P>
   One can't imagine what the reaction would have been if he had
actually gotten his 3,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Gwynn was virtually speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say? It is absolutely amazing for a visiting
player to be treated the way I've been treated the last four
nighst,'' he said. ``The fans here treated me and my family like
royalty. I can't thank the people here enough.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did what people in St. Louis have come to expect. He
crushed two belt-high pitches from Andy Ashby, a 451-footer to
center field in the third inning for the 500th of his career, and
No. 501 in the seventh off the left field scoreboard. He now holds
the record for being the fastest man to 500 home runs. It took Babe
Ruth 5,801 at-bats to get to 500, and McGwire just 5,487.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's hit came off of Manny Aybar, a two-run line drive double
to right field in the ninth inning. He hit the ball well all night,
in fact, but two well-hit drives were caught by Cardinals
center-fielder J.D. Drew. He grounded out and walked in his other
two plate-appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The fans booed pitcher Larry Leubbers after each ball of the
walk, which came in a two-on, two-out, first-base-open situation in
the second. During his other at-bats, you could hear fans chanting
his name and rhythmically clapping for a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn certainly would have liked to get his 3,000th hit in front
of so many true baseball fans, not to mention three other players
with 3,000 hits, Stan Musial, Lou Brock and Paul Molitor. But there
was also a sense that McGwire deserved the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his stadium, his ballpark,'' said Gwynn. ``How many times
does this guy deliver? I had a feeling he would do it tonight, and
I'm glad the Cardinal fans got a chance to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gwynn, it's now (ital) c'est la vie (end ital) and on to
Montreal. He admittedly was restless after Wednesday's game, where
he got three hits. He didn't get to sleep until about 5:30 Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Between the clash of history, royal treatment and number of
family members on the trip, Gwynn was pretty exhausted. Montreal
won't provide much in the way of ambiance, but that may be what
Gwynn needs most.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have drawn fewer fans in 1999 than any other team in
major league baseball -- 507,681 in 55 home games, a robust average
of 9,230 per game. They trail the team ranked 29th in attendance,
Minnesota, by a mere 303,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sagging attendance, ownership arguments and the lack of public
financing and interest in a new stadium has the franchise poised to
move, perhaps to suburban Virginia as soon as next season. The
Expos' M.O. in the '90s has been to discover and develop quality
talent and then watch it leave via free agency or
financially-motivated trades.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some richness to Montreal's past. It is where
Jackie Robinson broke into professional baseball with the
International League's Royals in 1946. Rusty Staub, Le Grande
Orange, became sort of a folk hero in Montreal, Gary Carter had his
most productive years as an Expo, and Rick Monday broke Montreal's
heart in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be easier now,'' he said. ``One is a lot easier than
two. I think I can get one hit, so I don't think I'll be as hyped.
At this point, whether I play before 5,000 or 50,00, I just want a
hit. Bloop, chinker, bunt, line drive, I don't care what it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
