r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SOWARD-LADN-(SLAN     08-06 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOWARD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WITHOUT R. JAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.1999 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ R. &UR;  &LR; Jay Soward was in full uniform, from his
gleaming cardinal helmet to his gold No. 18 jersey to his white
leather gloves.
</P>
<P>
   He had just come in from a lengthy photo session with ESPN The
Magazine, which might put the game-breaking receiver on its cover
in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There was irony in Soward's full-pads appearance at USC last
week because his teammates were running laps in the mid-afternoon
heat while the senior out of Fontana High School was on campus just
to pose for a magazine shoot.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Trojans have been working without R. &UR;  &LR; Jay all
summer. By his count, he's made only three of the non-mandatory
workouts in three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' coach Paul Hackett said of Soward's summer
attendance. ``I'm very disappointed. You'd think his attitude would
be, `Let's prepare to have a great senior year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Said USC tailback Chad Morton: ``At first, everybody was kind of
mad at him. But eventually the team said, `That's R.Jay.' He's kind
of like Dennis Rodman; you gotta let him do what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward, a free spirit by all accounts, knows he might not be the
most popular member of the USC football team just now. But it's
hard to stay angry at such a bright, likable guy _ and such a
talented one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Hackett is very demanding,'' Soward said. ``He wants to
see me a lot and be around the team. Honestly, I haven't been
around the team all summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's apologizing. Soward came close to making himself
available for the NFL draft last April, and he sees his senior
season at USC as his last chance to kick back and relax before he
gets a high-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time getting out of bed,'' he said. ``I'm lazy.
I'd like to sleep all day if I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get to the NFL, that's a real job. I can't be late to
meetings because I'll get fined. Here, I'm being asked to sacrifice
my body for $700 (in stipends) a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be at school right now. It may (tick) Coach
Hackett off. He may show some animosity. So be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Morton: ``As long as he's not getting into trouble, that's
his choice. What he's doing now, you don't want to do in the pros _
just not show up. He can be a kid for another year, just be wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward concedes his attitude might be influenced by the
$7.6-million contract former teammate Chris Claiborne got. And by
the fact that former USC teammates Billy Miller and Mike
Bastianelli are now playing for pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gotten, like, $3 million,'' he said. ``Then I
wouldn't be eating fast food every day and trying to live on the
$60 a month my dad sends me.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward was so close to declaring for the draft that he told some
friends he would. ``I think the coaches thought I was gone,'' he
said. ``I told some of my friends I was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he had a conversation with Marvin Demoff, a well-known
agent, who advised Soward that he would go no higher than No.10 in
the draft _ and perhaps as late as the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Soward changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' he said, shaking his head. ``Not even. That's not
me. I'm always top-10. If I'm not No.1, I want to be close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Heritage Hall. ``I apologized in front of the
team,'' he said. ``I didn't think it was necessary, but Coach
Hackett felt I should do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his erratic attendance at team functions has cost
him any organized publicity campaign on his behalf by the
university. Morton, a competent but undersized tailback, is on the
cover of the media guide.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, a player with 21 40-yards-or-more gains to his credit, a
guy who scores a touchdown every 6.9 times he touches the ball, a
preseason all-American in several publications, is relegated to the
inside of the foldout cover, sharing a page with workaday fullback
David Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Soward said being a Heisman Trophy candidate would be nice, but
his real goal is to be No.1 in the NFL draft next year. He figures
he can do that by gaining 3,000 all-purpose yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ever been done,'' he said. ``If I can do
that, I can see myself being the No.1 pick.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have a chance at 3,000. Hackett plans to have Soward
return all kickoffs and punts, and he remains the home-run threat
at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, however, wants the ball more often than he's been
getting it. He had 44 catches last year, but is thinking in terms
of 100 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they have to do is throw me the ball three times a
quarter,'' he said. ``Till now, my career has been, `R.Jay, go
long, and the quarterback's gonna throw it as far as he can and you
see if you can catch it.' I mean, that's the lowest-percentage pass
there is. Then I come back to the huddle and they give the ball to
Chad or throw to Billy Miller on the `out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, throw me a hitch, coach! Let me take a step, look at the
quarterback and turn and run!''
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't feel comfortable with Hackett, who last
season replaced John Robinson, a man Soward felt comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Hackett is so hard to talk to,'' Soward said. ``I don't
feel I can be open with him. When I'm in his office it's really
tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward has spent much of his summer working on his music, he
said. He has a pre-production studio in his Los Angeles apartment,
and he has recorded some rap songs, including one cut entitled
``It's a Struggle,'' and also managed his cousin, a San
Bernardino-based rythym and blues artist named Lawrence Dotson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of fun, getting out to the clubs, meeting some
people,'' Soward said. ``I've always loved music, and if I had to
walk away from football I'd make a demo tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward, Hackett and Morton agree on one thing: They expect No.18
to be ready to play when camp opens later this month at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotta perform,'' Hackett said. ``He's gotta return punts,
he's gotta return kicks, he's gotta catch passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Morton: ``When he gets in the pads, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Soward: ``I know I have to come into camp and be in shape
and blah, blah, blah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
