<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC SHARES CLIMB 23 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wall Street gave a strong endorsement Thursday to
recent changes at telecommunications equipment specialist Tekelec,
driving up shares by 23 percent in the wake of better-than-expected
financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   The stock jumped $2.125 to $11.625 with 4.06 million shares
changing hands, four times the 30-day average. Analyst Nikos
Theodosopoulos at Warburg Dillon Read Inc. began coverage with a
``buy'' rating and a 12-month target of $17; Timothy Savageaux at
Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co. lifted his rating to ``buy'' from
``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Savageaux also said he believes Tekelec, which sells switching
equipment and diagnostic tools for improving network performance,
is turning around its performance.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which saw shares bottom out at $6.75 four months
ago, surprised Wall Street late Wednesday with second-quarter
profits of $4.7 million, or 8 cents a share, excluding one-time
acquisition charges. Not only did that beat forecasts by a penny,
but the report also showed a 57 percent gain in back orders to a
record $66.3 million. Sales rose 20 percent to $51.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with analysts, Cruttenden Roth's Glenn
Powers declared, ``It looks like things are turning around.''
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec, which has about 450 employees, also acknowledged
Wednesday its profitability had been impacted by its commitment to
maintain spending on research and development and infrastructure
despite a lower-than-expected revenue base. ``Tekelec views this
investment in its future as critical toward maximizing its
long-term potential,'' it noted.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street also shrugged off the announcement that Chief
Financial Officer Gilles Godin will leave in October to spend more
time with his family and pursue personal interests. Tekelec said it
has started to search for a successor. Doug Moxley, who has been
controller since 1993, will assume Godin's duties while the search
is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec shares had hit $25 last year on optimism stemming from
sales of switching equipment to major telecom entities such as
Sprint. But the stock was hammered in February and March after a
disappointing earnings report that included failure to close sales
on time and a bleak outlook.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
