<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IPO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTION MILD TO REALTY NET SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Despite having premier backers, HomeStore.com
made a modest Wall Street debut on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com shares rose by $2.75 to close at $22.75, up by 14
percent on volume of 10.2 million shares. The double-digit gain by
the Thousand Oaks-based parent of real estate Web sites may sound
impressive, but not in relation to investor expectations of
previous Internet highfliers with blue-blood backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is not very receptive right now to IPOs. It's very
selective,'' said Tom Taulli, an IPO analyst and author of
Investing in IPOs. ``It's not necessarily a bad company. It's bad
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Internet Capital Group went public Thursday as
well, and it rose by 103 percent to $24.4375. It is a venture
capitalist firm that invests in Internet companies. Part of the
appeal may be its business model. Indeed, Taulli said the company
is nicknamed ``CMGI Jr.,'' after the popular Internet venture
capitalist firm.
</P>
<P>
   Some other IPOs on Thursday came from Mission Critical Software,
which saw a 59 percent increase to $25.4375 a share; Interactive
Pictures Corp., whose stock rose by 6 percent to $19 a share; and
Pivotal Corp., which rose 2.6 percent a share to $12.3125.
</P>
<P>
   But the market didn't treat the initial public offering this
week from 1-800-Flowers.com too well. The stock was priced at $21
and closed at $16 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com sold 7 million shares for its IPO. Initially
priced from $8 to $10 a share, the company debuted at $20 and
garnered about $121.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the offering, total outstanding shares stood at 67
million. The lead underwriter is Morgan Stanley. The company's
backers include the National Association of Realtors, GE Capital
and Kleiner Perkins, a well-known venture capitalist firm that has
backed Netscape, Excite and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com operates these Web sites: Realtor.com, which lists
1.4 million homes out of 1.5 million available nationally;
HomeBuilder.com, which lists more than 100,000 new homes;
SpringStreet.com, which lists 45,000 rental properties in more than
6,000 cities; and CommercialSource.com, which provides links to
commercial property listings.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com traces its roots to July 1993. Back then, the
company was known as InfoTouch and developed kiosks with computer
screens for home-listings searches, according to Securities and
Exchange Commission filings.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, RealSelect was formed to operate the
Realtor.com real estate Web site. RealSelect initially was owned by
the National Association of Realtors and NetSelect LLC. In turn,
NetSelect LLC was owned by InfoTouch and a holding company called
NetSelect Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, NetSelect Inc., NetSelect LLC and InfoTouch
merged into the entity now called HomeStore.com.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the company reported revenues of $19 million but lost
$69 million. For the first six months of 1999, HomeStore.com lost
$50 million on revenues of $21.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com also is being sued by Cendant Corp., which alleges
that it reneged on a deal that gives it access to real estate
listings in exchange for part ownership in the Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore officials declined to comment on the pending
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
