A7820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS     08-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GO NOWHERE IN TRIP OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With Mo Vaughn in no position to help or
hinder his former team Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, the Red Sox opened a
seven-game trip here against an Angels team that has been dangerous
only to itself for much of this season.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Vaughn absent because of a staph infection that
likely will cause him to miss the entire weekend, the Angels were
anything but an E ticket ride at Disneyland for the Sox, whose
wild-card aspirations are sandwiched between the Blue Jays and A's
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox managed just four singles, advancing just one runner
to third base in falling, 8-0, to the Angels before 26,175 in
Edison International Field. The Blue Jays, who were idle, now lead
the Sox by a game, while the A's moved within a game of Boston by
beating the White Sox in extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who have lost three of their last four games, are 13-18
since July 1. Of those 18 losses, this was the seventh time they
have lost by five runs or more. Nomar Garciaparra's 13-game hitting
streak also came to an end, as he went 0 for 4, with left fielder
Orlando Palmeiro robbing him of a hit with a diving catch in the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Brian Rose was unable to pitch past the fifth inning for
the seventh time in his last eight starts, leaving with a 3-0
deficit in the fourth, when Troy Glaus followed singles by Jim
Edmonds and Darin Erstad with a three-run home run. Rose gave up
six hits and walked three before he departed.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, now 6-4, has walked three or more batters only three times
in 15 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had an answer for that,'' Rose said when asked about
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's control problems, ``because then I would have
fixed it out there. I used to be able to find out what was wrong
and correct it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I don't throw strikes, this is what usually happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus's home run was the first three-run homer struck by an
Angels player since Vaughn went deep June 24 against the Mariners,
37 games ago. Any questions why the Angels are in last place in the
American League West, 19 games behind division-leading Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Rose retired the next two batters after the home run, but Jimy
Williams retrieved him following Palmeiro's two-out single. By
then, Rose already had thrown 78 pitches, and Williams had surmised
that Rose's capacity for escaping trouble of his own making had
expired. The rookie righthander had base runners in every inning,
including the second, when he walked the first three batters but
survived when Jeff Huson tapped into a pitcher-to-home-to-first
double play and rookie Ben Molina lined to center.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Bryce Florie spelled Rose after Palmeiro's hit, retired
Gary DiSarcina to end the fourth, and worked a scoreless fifth
before the Angels pounced on him in the sixth, when Glaus walked
and Huson and Molina followed with singles to make it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Williams went to lefty Mark Guthrie, last seen making out his
last will and testament after giving up a game-winning home run to
David Justice Monday night. There's no telling what Guthrie would
have done Thursday &UR;  &LR; night if Palmeiro, who flied out to the track
in right to bring home a fifth run, had lofted his ball a couple of
feet farther.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Guthrie let both of his inherited runners score, as
Garret Anderson blooped a two-out single to center to make it 6-0.
Guthrie gave up the last two Angels runs as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, meanwhile, were being mesmerized by Chuck Finley,
the lefthander who has spun some beauties against them in the past
but has been mostly awful this season, entering the game with a
Woolworth's record (five and dime) and a 5.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox actually looked like they might get to Finley early,
until Mike Stanley ran them out of a potential rally in the first.
Jose Offerman walked and two outs later Stanley drew another pass.
Butch Huskey then shot a single through the left side, but the
combination of a newly conservative Wendell Kim, the third base
coach, and the overzealous Stanley, sabotaged the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kim threw up the brakes to the speedy Offerman, holding him at
third as Stanley chugged around second, head down, unaware that
Palmeiro's throw was cut off by third baseman Glaus. The Angels
trapped him in a rundown, before second baseman Huson whirled and
threw to the plate to retire Offerman, bolting for home on a
suicide mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-out situation, we had a chance maybe to do some things
early,'' Williams said. ``Leadoff hitter on second base, two outs,
two strikes on the hitter, but the ball was hit really hard, right
at him (Palmeiro), he came at the ball hard and came up with it
clean. It would have been a really close play.''
</P>
<P>
   A play you force the Angels to make?
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said before, you normally send him,'' Williams said.
``But not being in the (coaching) box, that's a different position.
You see where the runner is, the ball is, you've got to make a
decision quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go with the decision. That's what I believe. The decision
was made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox didn't stir again until the sixth, when singles by John
Valentin and Stanley put runners on the corners with one out. But
Finley retired Huskey on a tapper to third and Troy O'Leary
whiffed, Finley's seventh strikeout of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality pitcher,'' Valentin said. ``They've been saying
he's not pitching as well. You hope that he'd fall behind us and
we'd hit him, but today he pitched well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
