<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINO MARTINEZ HOMERS TWICE TO BEAT MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ During batting practice, especially before the first
game of a series, Mariners manager Lou Piniella often floats around
the batting cage, like the host at a party, greeting guests with a
smile and small talk.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, as he prepared to take his turn in the cage, New
York Yankees first baseman Tino Martinez came by and hugged
Piniella, his former boss with the Mariners. Then he showed
complete disregard for etiquette by spoiling the party.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez hit two home runs, including the 200th of his career,
as the Yankees beat the Mariners, 7-4, before a sold-out Safeco
Field. Teammate Bernie Williams added four hits and three runs
batted in as the Mariners fell to a season-high 12{ games behind
the Texas Rangers in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, part of the 1995 team that generated the momentum to
build Safeco, worked with coaches before the game on shortening his
stride. The adjustments helped snap a 4-for-35 skid for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Derek) Jeter said to Tino, `You waited until you got home,'''
said Yankees manager Joe Torre. ``He likes it here in the new
ballpark. He broke it in right.''
</P>
<P>
   If 45,190 fans were expecting a pitchers' duel, they didn't get
it. The Yankees' Roger Clemens threw 126 pitches over seven
innings, the Mariners' Jamie Moyer 117 over six.
</P>
<P>
   Selectivity at the plate was a hallmark of the Yankees' 1998
championship season. Moyer was facing New York for the first time
in more than a year, and noticed a significant difference between
the Yankees and the Baltimore Orioles, whom he beat in his last
start while throwing only 29 fewer pitches in two more innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very disciplined hitters,'' Moyer said of the Yankees.
``You look at that club and put Baltimore on the same field, and
Baltimore swung at a lot of my first pitches. (The Yankees) were
more selective. It would be interesting to see how many first-pitch
strikes I threw; probably not a whole lot. That made a big
difference tonight. But it wasn't just their patience. It was a
combination of their patience and my inconsistency.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the game was Martinez, who had not homered in
more than three weeks. He broke a 2-2 tie with a solo shot in the
second, then hit a two-run blast to overcome a 4-3 deficit in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed five earned runs on seven hits and two walks over
six innings. He was touched in the first inning by a familiar foe _
Williams, who now has 23 hits in 46 career at-bats off the
left-hander. With two on and one out in the first, Williams drilled
a triple to right-center, giving New York an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners erased the Yankees' lead in their half against
Clemens, whose 18 wins against the M's are the most of any active
pitcher. Only Dave Stewart, with 20, has beaten Seattle more times.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clemens of '99 has been different from the pitcher who
has dominated the American League since the mid-'80s. He missed
three weeks with tightness in his left hamstring early in the year,
then won six of his next eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   But over six July starts, he was 1-2 with a 5.30 earned-run
average, and has had trouble this year starting games strong. His
ERA has consistently been twice as high the first two innings as it
has the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern continued last night. Brian Hunter was nearly
buzzed by Clemens' second pitch of the game; he then sliced a
single to right. With two outs and a runner on first, Clemens tried
to bust Alex Rodriguez inside. But he missed over the plate, and
Rodriguez crunched a two-run homer over the wall in right-center,
tying the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rodriguez's 26th home run of the year, and sixth at
Safeco Field. The left-field power alley is 388 feet from the
plate, but Rodriguez has improvised: four of those six homers have
gone the opposite way.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens encountered trouble again in the third. Russ Davis led
off with a single, then Hunter and David Bell fought Clemens off to
draw walks. Ken Griffey Jr. drove in Davis on a single to left, and
Rodriguez brought home Hunter on a sacrifice fly to right. That
gave the M's a 4-3 lead, and by the time Edgar Martinez grounded
into an inning-ending double play, Clemens had induced only four
swings that missed over three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first,'' Torre said, ``it looked like he was trying to
throw the ball to Mount Rainier.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the game was a vintage effort. Jay Buhner swung
and missed at all three strikes for Clemens' first whiff in the
fourth. Clemens hustled to the bag for the throw on John Mabry's
grounder to the second base hole, then fanned Davis to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens went 1-2-3 through the fifth, put two runners on but
struck out Mabry to end the sixth and finished with a 1-2-3 seventh
highlighted by Williams' racing catch of a long fly by Bell to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
