<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN WATSON HAPPY BACK IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Allen Watson never asked the Mariners for his release
_ verbally, at least.
</P>
<P>
   In every other way, he let them know he wasn't happy. Watson's
body was in a Mariners uniform for nine days in June, but his mind
was far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be here,'' said Watson, in town with the New
York Yankees. ``I had some pretty good reasons why I didn't want to
be here. I guess they kind of figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending three years with West Coast teams, Watson signed
with his hometown New York Mets last winter. Other teams showed
interest, he said, and he could have signed for more money. But he
wanted to play in New York, because his only sibling, a sister,
needed help raising her son.
</P>
<P>
   Used infrequently by the Mets, Watson came to Seattle in
mid-June for pitcher Mac Suzuki. It was a disaster from the first
hitter Watson faced, in Cleveland on June 19 in a game he now calls
the worst of his career.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Watson allowed a leadoff homer, and two more homers to
the next eight batters. He pitched three games for the M's,
allowing first-batter home runs each time. In all, he got nine outs
and allowed five long balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love baseball, it's what I live for, play hard for and
dedicate myself to,'' Watson said. ``But just at that point, I
wasn't there. It wasn't fair to Seattle. No excuses _ I just
pitched bad.''
</P>
<P>
   With his mind elsewhere, Watson wasn't himself with the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were great, Lou (Piniella) was great,'' Watson said.
``I just didn't pitch well and I wasn't mentally here. That's a bad
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson was released on June 28, and signed with the Yankees. In
five games before Thursday night, he had allowed one earned run in
72/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Being close to his family, he said, has made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball players go through the same things in life as anybody
else does,'' Watson said. ``Everybody thinks we're different
because we play baseball. But whatever happens in their lives
happens to us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEE BALL, HIT BALL: John Mabry grinned as he hustled down the
ramp from the Mariners clubhouse to the batting tunnel Thursday
night. He'd already taken batting practice, but Mabry was going for
another round of a new technique that's gaining popularity with M's
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything to get an edge,'' Mabry said.
</P>
<P>
   The first baseman is one of eight Mariners participating in a
new kind of eye-hand coordination drill. Conditioned Ocular
Enhancement, a Chicago-based company that works extensively with
the Milwaukee Brewers, has been training Mariners hitters using
tennis balls traveling as fast as 160 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davidson, a ``visual trainer'' for the company, inks a
number on each of the four sides of the ball. Hitters try to read
the number as the ball flashes by, with Mabry's 1-in-4 success rate
among the best.
</P>
<P>
   Using a patented machine, Davidson gradually increases the speed
of the tennis balls from 70 to 160 mph. The goal is to make better
contact hitters and reduce strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the guys are seeing the ball hit the bat now,''
Davidson said. ``Did you ever ask players if they see the ball hit
the bat? Nine out of 10 say no. And here, we're training guys to
see the ball hit the bat, and at that split second, they actually
see the ball stop. Once they see it, they're all over it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BABY TALK: It's been an uneventful season on the field for
Carlos Guillen, who has been down since early April with a torn
anterior cruciate ligament. He's been working out 4-5 hours a day,
and said he might start hitting next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple of months, I have to get ready for winter ball,''
Guillen said. ``I think I might be ready in November.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he's enjoying fatherhood. Guillen's wife gave
birth to their first child, Alfonso Jose, on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Another Mariner is preparing for the role _ outfielder Shane
Monahan has ``MM'' written on the back of his cap for daughter
Madison Monahan, who is due in three months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Yankees pitcher David Cone was honored before
the game as the 1999 Hutch Award winner. Cone received the award,
which honors competitive spirit, at the Post-Intelligencer's Sports
Star of the Year banquet in February. ... Even with his error
Wednesday, Russ Davis entered Thursday night's game third among
American League third basemen in fielding percentage, at .956. ...
The Mariners tied their three-year-old club record of 25 pitchers
in a season when Tom Davey made his first appearance Wednesday. The
M's are four shy of the all-time mark, set by the 1996 Angels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
