<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     08-06 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CHRISTEN SAFECO FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At last, the real opening of Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees came to town Thursday night. Tino Martinez, the
matinee idol. Pesky little Chuck Kno-blauch. Smooth Derek Jeter,
and the glowering Paulie O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   You better watch out for flying Gatorade dispensers. O'Neill can
go off, which is why Mariner fans booed O'Neill with delight
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fun of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks to the night that Seattle dawned (or is that
dusked?) a new era of outdoor baseball, the Mariners got the one
opponent worthy of stepping first onto the green grass of their new
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that the Padres, Diamondbacks, Twins, Royals, A's,
Orioles and Devil Rays all dipped their toes in Safeco's grass
already.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finally made it here for Opening Night, Part II.
</P>
<P>
   The defending World Series champion Yankees helped make us feel
the kind of heady rush that the presence of a true baseball rival
can induce in a baseball town, which Seattle still is, right?
</P>
<P>
   If you were watching Thursday night, did you catch the blinding
glare of all those camera flashbulbs when in the first inning, Ken
Griffey Jr. stood in against Roger Clemens?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was an All-Star matchup; a Hall of Fame moment. But it
was enhanced by the fact that Clemens is a Yankee now and Griffey,
a lifelong Mariner (so far) and the little kid former Yankees
manager Billy Martin chased from the Yankees clubhouse, was at the
plate to defend his new, natural home turf.
</P>
<P>
   The night had some pop.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was Alex Rodriguez and not Griffey who took Rocket
Roger deep in the first inning to waken the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, that was Tino Martinez who did A-Rod one better.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was once the ultimate Mariner but when his free-agent
price tag grew too big because of all he accomplished with the M's
through the magical season of '95, Mariner manager Lou Piniella
took Martinez aside and asked the fellow Tampa native where he
wanted to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Yankees are the Yankees, Martinez told his skipper
to ship him to the Bronx _ a place with so many World Series
banners and so much history, they play amongst stone monuments
erected for baseball ghosts who never quite die.
</P>
<P>
   Since Martinez has been a Yankee, he has indeed won two World
Series, making it easier to forget all the emotional moments in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But word out of New York earlier this week is that Martinez was
asking about the new park. How does it play? Is it true what they
say about the fences being too far back? Is Safeco as grand as
everyone has reported?
</P>
<P>
   He must have taken notes. Martinez came to town and etched his
mark on Safeco.
</P>
<P>
   During his first at-bat at the park he helped build, the other
half of the Two-Martinez Launch cranked a homer to right field _
the 200th of his career. And in the sixth, Martinez belted his
second of the night, one that pushed the Yankees to a 5-4 lead that
would grow to a 7-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you gotta love that guy.
</P>
<P>
   And say what you want about the Yankees, you gotta love them,
too _ or at least acknowledge their place in Seattle baseball lore,
if not Seattle's baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Yankees had some problems here in the past,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said Thursday night, although it was not
Torre's ship that sunk those three electric October nights when the
Mariners committed the most improbable, franchise-saving comeback
in the history of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is the start of a new era,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   What Torre meant was, maybe this first Safeco Field series
between the Mariners and Yankees is the start of the new era in
which the Yankees will no longer be made to look like chumps, as
they were in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better. That dome _ there is something about a dome.
When you play, you want to have a little touch of the outside about
the ballpark,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the misery the Mariners dished to the Yankees back
in '95, the Yankees remain every bit as much the reason Safeco
Field exists. As much as the M's and their September to remember.
As much as the swooning Angels.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, without question, the Yankees should have been the
Mariners' first visitor at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule-makers had it completely wrong, bringing us the
Padres to kick off this rekindling love affair with the game. The
curse of inter-league baseball struck us at completely the worst
time, diminishing Safeco's original grand opening with a
novelty-type matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the wrong idea. There have been a healthy smattering
of Safeco Moments so far in the ballpark's infant existence.
</P>
<P>
   There was the return of Randy Johnson. There is the shrinking
Mariner pitching staff ERA. There was the first homer (Russ Davis)
and the first steal of home plate (Dan Wilson) and the first fan to
get hit by a foul ball (the writer of this column).
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks to the night of Safeco's first opening night,
the M's got their true rival to stop by the new yard for the start
of what we hope is a sizzling weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   For these Yankees, they should have brought back the Seattle
Symphony. They should have hung the bunting back up.
</P>
<P>
   More than simply the grand ceremonial feel of Safeco's inaugural
game, the arrival of the Yankees has marked Safeco's real opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
