<HEADLINE>
SENSE AND NON-SCENTS: HALIFAX RAISES A STINK ABOUT ODORS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This droll 575-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 7 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, NOVA SCOTIA _ First passive smoking, now passive
smelling.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be tolerated, the people of Halifax, the capital of
Nova Scotia, are being told. Though the air in this Canadian port
may sometimes carry the fragrance of fish, the citizens themselves
should not indulge in the immoderate use of scent, after-shave,
hair spray or strong-smelling deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   No edict yet has the force of law, but many businesses and
public offices now tell staff, and ask visitors, not to use balms
that could offend their colleagues. Those who transgress in
scent-free zones may be asked to wash.
</P>
<P>
   And about time, too, it should be said. To stand downwind of
another's perfume may send more than the nostrils aquiver, while
the mix of dozens of cheap scents can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly, the public-spirited employers of Halifax have taken
responsibility for their staff. It is about time someone put a foot
down. But why stop with smells? Among offenses against the senses,
scents are not the only ones to incense.
</P>
<P>
   Noise is especially irksome. Overlook, for present purposes, the
ubiquitous ghetto-blaster, the supposedly silent but
impossible-to-ignore Walkman, the chirping mobile phone and the
inane conversation of those who take such delight in using it.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrate instead on chatter, and in particular the
chatterer's charter, the so-called right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are impudent enough to talk in public at all _ in the
street, on buses and in trains _ only do it to annoy. And in Nova
Scotia they even do it in a funny old Scottish accent.
</P>
<P>
   A total ban is long overdue. Then there is the matter of
appearance. Applaud the good burghers of Halifax for forbidding the
use of hair spray. Improvements to the air quality aside, that will
do much to rid television screens of images of bouffon-haired
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But whose retina has not also been scorched by a particularly
vile checked shirt, shoulder pads so huge that they would become an
American football-player, or a pair of trousers that would have
looked out of place even on the backside of a Soviet booldozeristka
_ female tractor-driver _ of yore?
</P>
<P>
   Let's confine these clothes to private clubs.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem indelicate to mention more personal shortcomings,
but medical science now has solutions to many of the sights that so
often cause public dismay _ bad teeth, for example, and big noses.
Some people really are too plump; that can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Others need to remember that hair is frequently a needless cause
of unsightliness. Those who have too little will find that
transplants, never mind toupees, are nowadays quite inexpensive.
Those who have too much should just cut it. This applies
particularly to the facial fuzz beloved by all those awful bearded
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Redheads, incidentally, need not be embarrassed to dye their
hair some less offensive color.
</P>
<P>
   In Halifax, it is the task of the personnel manager and the
buildings superintendent to enforce the no-fragrance rules. That is
sensible too _ though really these people should be given their
proper titles, the human-resources director and the facilities
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Every company needs them, just as it needs appropriate rules to
govern the thoughtlessness and intolerance of those who insist upon
being fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   Let the wives of litigious husbands take note. And, by the by,
let's have no flowers in public gardens: a rose is a rose is a
rose, not a machine for making sweet smells. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this quirky 575-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
