<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZING-TOMMY-THOMPSON-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO SHOULD BE KING: GOP'S TOMMY THOMPSON  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wisconsin Editors)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 7 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wisconsin governor's office is closed for renovations, which
means that Governor Tommy Thompson has to meet your Economist
correspondent, Lexington, in a small conference room, the sort of
place any minor businessman might use.
</P>
<P>
   The governor does not have the usual politician's polish. He
looks more like a small-town bank president who enjoys hunting
ducks with his customers at the weekend but is perfectly capable on
Monday morning of bullying those who have fallen behind on their
payments.
</P>
<P>
   He brims with confidence, and yet pauses periodically to ask his
visitor personal questions that would seem odd anywhere outside the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has dominated Wisconsin's politics for 13 years. He has
led the Republican Party along the road to its present position on
subjects like welfare reform and school choice.
</P>
<P>
   He is far more sure-footed than the acerbic fellows who make up
most of the Republican ranks in Congress in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If presidential nominations were based on accomplishment alone,
it is Tommy G., not George W., who would now have the Republican
presidential nomination all but locked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I initiated welfare reform in this country,'' Thompson says
with no hint of modesty; and he is right.
</P>
<P>
   The W-2 program (Wisconsin Works) was the first to insist that
able-bodied welfare recipients either find work or lose the dole.
It combined the stick of time-limits with large dollops of money
for training, transport, health care and child care.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has raised state subsidies for child care from $12
million to over $150 million. As a result, the number of Wisconsin
families on welfare has fallen spectacularly, from 100,000 to a
mere 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   He also created one of the country's first school-choice
programs for poor students. Pupils can select the school they want
to go to from a range of options that includes state schools,
private religious schools, vocational schools, and charter schools
operated by bodies such as the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   And Thompson should get at least some of the credit for bringing
Wisconsin's flabby economy back into shape.
</P>
<P>
   When he was first elected governor, in 1986, he cut or
eliminated a number of taxes, made the training of workers
tax-deductible, and vigorously lured businesses into the state.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment has fallen from 7 percent when he took office to
under 3 percent now. True, times have been good from coast to
coast, but Wisconsin's unemployment has now been lower than the
national rate for 144 consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few states where manufacturing jobs are sharply
on the rise, and the combination of a healthy economy and dwindling
welfare rolls has put a record 69 percent of the state's
working-age population into wage or salary jobs, up from 54 percent
when Thompson became governor.
</P>
<P>
   How has he got these things done in a state that voted for Bill
Clinton in both 1992 and 1996, and whose legislature has been
controlled by Democrats for half of the governor's time in office?
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is, says Bill Kristol, the editor of the conservative
Weekly Standard, ``a strong and bullheaded guy who is also a very
good politician.''
</P>
<P>
   He is personable, but he is also just rough enough around the
edges to make opponents cock a wary eye at him. Above all, he is a
serious realist.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of his governorship, says Donald Kettl, a professor
of political science at the University of Wisconsin, has been his
ability to work out and then to sell common-sense solutions to
familiar problems.
</P>
<P>
   He manages to present these solutions, even pretty conservative
ones, in a non-ideological way.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare reform means finding poor people jobs, says the
governor. If he had just gone out there ``and said I'm going to
kick everybody off welfare, I would have never got anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   At key moments, he invites his Democratic opponents to the
discussion table rather than leaving them to throw stones from a
distance.
</P>
<P>
   In his first term, he put a senior Democrat in charge of the
state's health and family services, and then gave him
responsibility for getting the first of his welfare reforms through
the legislature. The committee that hammered out the details of the
final bill had more Democrats than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Should Washington's Republicans, who have a knack of snatching
defeat from the jaws of victory, pay more attention to Thompson? He
reckons they have something to learn.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Republicans in Congress is that ``they make
these outlandish statements. That scares people.'' The Republicans'
rhetoric can be so shrill, he says, that even their talk of vast
tax cuts makes people wary.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are Republicans in Washington who give
Thompson his due for fighting lonely battles and winning most of
them. But, they add, it is easier to do these things from the
executive branch of government.
</P>
<P>
   While governors fix the bridges on roads already built, the
Republican majority in Congress has the harder task of drawing the
map for the roads of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there may be lessons for the map-drawers in Thompson's
success. The Republican right may sneer at ``compassionate
conservatism,'' but the voters seem to find it an attractive pair
of words.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet time for Thompson to declare victory and go home.
He has recently unveiled a new program which will expand Medicaid
coverage to children and adults in working families earning less
than 185 percent of the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   He will almost certainly have to modify his welfare-reform
program when the economy starts to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if that were not enough, Congress has made Thompson the
chairman of Amtrak, with the task of making America's
passenger-train system self-sufficient within four years.
</P>
<P>
   This year Amtrak high-speed trains will link up Washington, New
York and Boston. There are plans for a profitable high-speed rail
corridor in California, and a nine-state network in the Midwest
with Chicago at its hub.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has endorsed George W. Bush for the Republican
nomination. Down the road, there may be a vice-presidential
candidacy, or a job in a Bush cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But why, Lexington asks, is Thompson, who has much the more
impressive record, not himself the nominee?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four reasons,'' he answers without pause. ``One, my name's not
Bush. Two, I don't come from Texas. Three, I don't have $40
million. Four, he's better-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a realist. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
