<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECOGNIZE-SOMALILAND?     08-06 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECOGNIZE-SOMALILAND?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A LAND OF NOMADS _ AND 10,442,443 GOATS _ A COUNTRY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 7 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARGEISA _ This is a country of about 3 million people, five
telephone companies, seven airlines and, according to the
government's improbable statistics, 10,442,443 goats.
</P>
<P>
   These facts about Somaliland are not unrelated. Over half its
population are nomads, walking every year with their herds of
goats, sheep (5,571,565) and camels (5,454,590), from the grazing
lands of northeast Ethiopia to the ports from which their livestock
are exported to Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   This nomadic life, carried on through many generations, has
formed them into family clans that stick together with fierce
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   It has also made them natural travellers, so that, when Somalia
fell apart as a state in 1991, they scattered all over the world
but kept in close touch with relations still at home. Hence the
telephone companies and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Remittances from the exiles (not in the statistics, but
estimated at up to $500 million a year) and revenue from livestock
are the country's only sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But is it a country? Somaliland has a flag, a president, a
parliament, a currency, a central bank, a university, an army and a
planning department that produces these oddly precise statistics.
But nobody recognizes it.
</P>
<P>
   A former British colony that willingly merged with the former
Italian Somalia at independence in 1960, Somaliland was badly
neglected under the dictatorship of Siad Barre.
</P>
<P>
   A rebellion in 1988 resulted in a three-year battle for the
capital, Hargeisa, in which the town was destroyed and the
population fled to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion spread and Barre was overthrown, but the rest of
Somalia descended into fearsome clan warfare.
</P>
<P>
   With at least the semblance of a government, Somaliland declared
independence in May 1991. Two years later it had its own clan war.
</P>
<P>
   But the clan system that had divided the country so bitterly
also provided the mechanism for putting it together again. At a
series of conferences, some of them lasting for months, groups of
elders worked out peace treaties.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, the clans would have sought women and camels as
compensation for killing and as tokens of peace. Now they agreed to
share power.
</P>
<P>
   War, many of them had come to realize, was impoverishing
everyone. Some of the more intransigent clans were simply bought
off.
</P>
<P>
   Poets, highly influential in Somali society and traditionally
glorifiers of war, began to sing of the stupidity of so much
fighting and killing.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Somaliland has enjoyed remarkable stability and
security. In one street in Hargeisa, women sit in a row trading in
gold. There is not a gun in sight. Almost half of the capital's
buildings now have roofs, and some parts of the city have
electricity. With the help of aid agencies, the water supply has
been restored.
</P>
<P>
   The country has an administration that is certainly no worse
than that of many African countries.
</P>
<P>
   So is it time for the world to accept Somaliland as an
independent state?
</P>
<P>
   Lack of recognition has meant that the country, if such it is,
is being rebuilt without much help from western donors. It cannot
issue passports, so its ministers and businessmen cannot travel
easily.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-month ban on the import of its livestock by Saudi Arabia,
its chief market, resulted in a collapse in government revenues
from $45 million to $27 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The ban, now lifted, was ostensibly imposed because Somaliland's
veterinary certificates, giving the animals a clean bill of health,
were not internationally recognized.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason why the world will not accept Somaliland's
independence is that the rest of Somalia does not want it, and its
other neighbors are wary.
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammed Haji Ibrahim Egal is now suggesting some sort
of halfway house that would give Somaliland international status
but leave the door open to reunification with Somalia at some
point.
</P>
<P>
   That should at least give Somaliland access to money to rebuild
its infrastructure. But recognition would not solve its deeper
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The elders may have been able to bring the clan wars to an end,
but they cannot run a state. They chose the president and members
of parliament, but Egal was, at least until recently, able to
manipulate the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament has now begun to exert more independence and to curb
the president's autocratic tendencies. A parliamentary commission
has drafted a constitution that proposes a mix of multi-party
democracy and traditional representation. Egal, who depends upon
the traditionalists, does not like it.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is that livestock farming, the backbone of
the economy, is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The nomads, who look after the animals, are the poorest people
in the country and there is no government assistance for them or
their flocks. Their lands are overgrazed, and trees, essential for
regular rainfall, are being cut down.
</P>
<P>
   Free enterprise, the government's philosophy, is encouraging
people to enclose huge areas of common grazing land. Somaliland's
tough nomads, survivors of drought, pestilence and wars, have never
faced more difficult times. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 03:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRO     08-06 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH FIRMS' PLEA FOR WORK VISAS DRAWS CRITICISM  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key immigration critic in the House charged
Thursday that the INS cannot keep track of how many foreign work
visas have been issued and said the program should not be expanded
until the agency sorts out the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The comments from Rep. Lamar Smith, the Texas Republican who
chairs the House Judiciary Committee's immigration panel, came as
lawmakers from both parties responded to the clamor from high-tech
companies to let them hire more temporary workers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after a prolonged battle, Congress raised the ceiling
for the so-called H-1B visas from 65,000 to 115,000. But the INS
reported on June 15 that the increased supply of visas had already
been exhausted for the fiscal year that ends in September.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., introduced a bill this week to lift
all limits on foreign workers who hold a bachelor's degree or
higher in science, mathematics or engineering from a U.S.
university and have an offer for a job paying at least $60,000 a
year. Lofgren's bill would allow workers to stay in the country for
five years, rather than the three allowed under the H-1B program,
and it would not affect the overall ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you touch immigration issues you make somebody mad,''
Lofgren said. ``But if we could at least agree on where we agree,
that it is not in America's best interest to force away the top 20
percent of real smart scientists and engineers who can pull down
big salaries ... that would be a useful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Smith's opposition, the push for visa expansion has
strong GOP backing. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott has teamed
with Texas Sen. Phil Gramm to expand the number of visas to 200,000
and exempt all foreigners with a master's degree or higher who were
paid at least $60,000 a year. Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., Thursday
introduced a companion measure in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Smith called Thursday's hearing to try to slam on the brakes. He
suggested that visa fraud at a consulate in India, along with a
huge backlog of applications from previous years may explain why a
new visa shortage has cropped up so soon after the program was
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the INS approved a backlog of almost 20,000 H-1B visa
petitions before the new ceiling went into effect last October.
``So an argument can be made that even before fiscal year 1999 even
started, the 115,000 quota approved by Congress for this year had
in effect already been reduced to 95,569.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin Fragomen, chairman of the American Council on
International Personnel, whose members include large multinational
corporations, agreed that INS record keeping was atrocious. But he
also argued that the shortage of high-tech workers is real. He and
Crystal Neiswonger, an immigration specialist at TRW Inc.,
estimated that the demand for workers will exceed the new cap by at
least 40,000 workers this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the American Electronics Association released a study that
found wages _ a market indicator of demand and supply of workers _
in the high-tech industry have risen nearly 20 percent since 1990.
At the same time, unemployment for engineers, computer scientists
and programmers and mathematicians ranged from 1.2 percent to 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of U.S. graduates in science, math
and engineering is falling, AEA found, with the number of
bachelor's degrees in electrical engineering alone falling 33
percent between 1990 and 1996. Foreign nationals, by contrast, are
now receiving from one third to nearly two thirds of doctoral and
masters degrees in those fields. Foreigners received 64 percent of
the U.S. doctoral degrees granted in engineering technology in
1996, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study said visas provide at best a temporary remedy. It
argued that poor U.S. science and math education in grades K-12,
which leaves U.S. students ill-prepared to go on to advanced
degrees, is at the root of the problem. Lofgren said her proposal,
which does not lift overall H-1B visa caps but removes the
restrictions for extremely skilled workers, offers a way to ``chase
the best'' without arguing about whether or not shortages exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the best and the brightest,'' Lofgren said. ``In my
judgment, you can never have too many geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The current system, she said, ``is not very good at assessing
shortages, but I think the marketplace does help establish'' what
is actually happening in the real world. ``If you're paying people
a whole bunch of money the day they walk out of college, that says
something about whether they're a hotshot or not _ probably more
than Congress knows about how to evaluate'' skills.
</P>
<P>
   She said her bill limits the number of new visas ``by the very
terms of who's eligible. It would only be people who have graduated
from American universities, with a degree in the hard sciences,
math or engineering, who are offered at least $60,000. That's a
limited pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is opposed to expanding the visa
program, saying last year's increase was adequate and companies
should focus on retraining U.S. workers. A spokesman for Smith said
the prospects for a visa increase remain uncertain, but a measure
could pass given the broad and enthusiastic support in Congress for
the high-tech industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
