<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-MARY-POPPINS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY LOUIS GATES: A MARY POPPINS PHILOSOPHER OF BLACK EXPERIENCE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 7 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates is a phenomenon in America, but virtually
unknown in Britain. That may be about to change, thanks to a
six-part television series, ``Into Africa,'' broadcast over the
past month on BBC2 and, from October, on PBS in America.
</P>
<P>
   Part travelogue and part ancient history, it is the story of a
singular African-American confronting his roots from Zanzibar to
Timbuktu.
</P>
<P>
   The W.E.B. Dubois Professor of the Humanities and chairman of
the African-American studies department at Harvard University is
known as ``Skip,'' but under his fuller name Gates has become the
chief interpreter of the black experience for the white
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   He has built up his department into the country's most important
black-studies faculty; has been the co-author of 15 books and has
written five of his own as well as numerous magazine articles; is a
consultant to the Dreamworks film studio, and the creator, with
Microsoft, of the first pan-African CD-ROM encyclopedia, which will
make him a very rich man.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he is only 48.
</P>
<P>
   A natural ``academostar,'' Gates is a silver-tongued
intellectual imp. Nearly everyone (Louis Farrakhan, head of the
radical Nation of Islam is a rare exception) who meets him loves
him, including the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in his gold wire-rimmed glasses and Harvard T-shirt,
Gates is as much a character in the television films as the
characters he discusses: King Solomon or Don Francisco de Souza,
Ivory Coast's most notorious slave trader.
</P>
<P>
   As such, he is both commentator and comic relief. But his
willingness to play the buffoon has led critics to accuse Gates of
creating an ``easy listening'' version of the black experience.
</P>
<P>
   It might be more accurate to say that his is the Mary Poppins
philosophy of social and cultural instruction: a spoonful of sugar
helps the agenda go down.
</P>
<P>
   In the television series, Gates wants to rebut the deeply-rooted
conviction of whites from Hume to Hegel that black Africans had no
culture, that they couldn't read or write and thus couldn't have
created the astonishing civilization unearthed on their continent.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to pin down ``the part of black history that was
lost or stolen,'' both metaphorically and, on occasion, literally.
(He has set up a base at Harvard to catalogue and translate 4,500
medieval books that were written by Africans and are housed in the
library at Timbuktu.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether the program draws as big an audience in Britain as it
will in America is not yet clear. Gates is, he says, a ``citizen of
the black Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   While he admits you cannot extrapolate from America to Britain _
``in America the primary signifier is race,'' he says; ``in
Britain, it's class'' _ he believes that the personal struggle to
reconcile the past and the present is universal. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
