<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A DIRTY RING AROUND CITY HALL  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It seems like everything is falling down and
wearing out, as I was saying just this morning to my fanny-tuck
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the woman in the bathtub who fell off her
roof and suffered career-ending injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1969, a mannequin woman has been taking a luxurious bath
in an antique claw-foot tub on the roof of Caldwell's Factory
Outlet on Bayshore Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how dismal the weather, the world political situation,
the national economy or the performance of Muni, that woman bathed
away. Her tranquility was unshakable. She was a spiritual
touchstone and a symbol of life's fine small moments.
</P>
<P>
   But the wood supporting the tub rotted away, and two weeks ago,
crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, we just found her on the ground,'' says Oscar
Salinas, a Caldwell's employee. ``The tub wasn't damaged at all,
but the woman, she got  &UR; all &LR;   &LR; broken up. Everyone's been calling,
`What happened to good old Betty?'''
</P>
<P>
   Several people have inquired about buying the tub. It would be
worth about $250, but this is San Fransentimental, so offers have
topped $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Caldwell says he won't sell it,'' says Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Bless Mr. Caldwell's heart. I don't want to turn this into a
popularity contest, but if I had to save either Caldwell's bather
or the Doggie Diner's doggie, I'd vote bath woman.
</P>
<P>
   The tub probably will go back up on the roof soon, with a new
bather.
</P>
<P>
   Then maybe Mr. Caldwell, who seems to have a feel for tradition
and timely repair, can fix up the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Like ... oh ... City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The building itself is fine, but the infrastructure seems to
need attention.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is shutting down and rummaging through the files of at
least two city agencies. The feds have been swarming for weeks, and
the mayor says, ``I don't know who they are investigating. I have
no concern and no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm no expert on mayoral duties and on where the buck stops, but
in this case, shouldn't Willie Brown have both concern  &UR; and &LR; 
comment?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's only the Housing Authority and the Human Rights
Commission. Wake Willie when the G-men start snooping around
something important.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI seems to suspect that there has been a significant
victimization of poor people and minorities by people in city
agencies. Why should that be a mayor's concern?
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Walker is at least part of the focus of the FBI probe.
Walker throws a huge party for Willie every year, a fund-raiser for
Walker's ``nonprofit'' agency.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Brown says Walker is not a Brown associate. Yet there is
the annual party, and Walker was a key figure in the campaign for
passage of the 49ers' stadium/mall, a campaign upon which Mayor
Brown lavished more time, energy and passion than on any other
single project during his term in office.
</P>
<P>
   In the current FBI investigation, Walker has not been charged.
But his nonprofit agency, which has had some big-money dealings
with City Hall, has never been registered as a nonprofit agency.
</P>
<P>
   That is a detail that someone in the mayor's administration
should have noticed, especially since Walker served three years in
prison for abusing minority contracting programs in this very San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   You would think the mayor would at least like to explain how
Charlie Walker got past the B.S. detector without setting off
buzzers, bells and foghorns.
</P>
<P>
   However, with a mayoral race under way, it's important that we
all realize, as Brown's re-election campaign press secretary said,
``This is not a campaign issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is a town where the major issue of the last
mayoral campaign was a candidate's shower with two radio DJs.
</P>
<P>
   I'm eagerly awaiting the official list of suitable, Brown-OK'd
campaign issues. I hope there are some spicy items on the list.
Otherwise, it could be a dreary race.
</P>
<P>
   Party pooper Angela Alioto dropped out of the mayor derby
because she's busy with her law practice. She probably wouldn't
have showered with DJs, but she would have been a spirited sparring
partner for Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Reilly can't seem to pick up steam in the polls, despite
the fact he offers specific, written solutions to major problems
and has enough of his own money that he doesn't have to sell his
soul to campaign backers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Reilly, coming off a long career as a political
consultant, is considered by some to be too political.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jordan needs to show a little more flair and visibility.
He could volunteer to replace the woman in the tub on Caldwell's
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, barring any messy discoveries by the FBI, it's
looking like another four years of Mayor Brown.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to ask Willie about the campaign, but first I'll have
to see if the campaign is a campaign issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
