<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-BUGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, WARNER BROS. TEAMING UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Can the Batmobile be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. and General Motors Corp., a pair of venerable
American business icons, staged a corporate love-in Thursday to
launch a four-year marketing alliance. The first product of their
union: a minivan bearing Bugs Bunny and WB logos.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that GM and Warner Bros. have an assured
date for the prom,'' said Michael Schau, editor of the
Entertainment Marketing Newsletter. ``You want that ready-made
friendship because it's really about GM being able to use
whatever's going on at Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   The van, with a $29,575 price tag, is by far the most expensive
studio tie-in product ever let loose on the mass market, Schau
noted.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on the Warner lot attended by Time Warner
chief Gerald Levin and new studio chief Barry Meyer, GM announced
it will build 20,000 Chevy Venture Warner Bros. vans _ 20percent of
the van's production run _ during the next year as a first element
of the partnership, which gives it ``first look'' at promotions for
all studio operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes creative marketing to another level,'' said Dan
Romanelli, the studio's consumer products chief. ``The
possibilities are limitless.''
</P>
<P>
   GM, which has previously worked with Warner on product placement
in movies, would not give specifics on the 15 other partnerships it
has formed with the studio. But Phil Guarascio, vice president for
advertising and corporate marketing, hinted the automaker is
working on more Warner-themed vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not borrowing assets,'' Guarascio said. ``We're trying
to integrate customers where we have the same customer, so it feels
natural, not forced. We're putting money on the table because we
want Warner to know we're serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives would not comment on how much money GM has committed,
although reports have emerged of a $30million ``floor'' for royalty
payments.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan, produced at GM's Doraville, Ga., plant, will hit
showrooms next month. The vehicle is aimed at mid-upscale parents
with young children and includes features such as a
console-mounted, flip-down screen for passengers in the back to
watch videos or play games with the VCR controlled from the front
seat.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a built-in child-safety seat and a sound system that
allows passengers to listen to three different audio sources.
``We've got the ultimate family road trip machine,'' proclaimed Dan
Keller, brand manager for Venture.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers will become part of ``VentureTainment,'' which includes
free videos and compact discs, discounts at Warner Studio stores,
early access to Six Flags parks and passes to movie sneak previews.
</P>
<P>
   Executives refused to comment on reports GM had first approached
Warner's rival and neighbor, The Walt Disney Co., about a similar
alliance. Other significant Hollywood partnerships include
Universal's deals with Dodge and Coca-Cola and Disney alliances
with McDonald's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 0625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 06:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7873 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-LA-2Takes-LAD     08-06 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LA-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. NFL BID IMPERILED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Staff Writers Joshua Lowe and Rick Orlov contributed to this
story.)  
BY STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Prospects for the NFL returning to the Coliseum
took a pair of damaging blows Thursday when Gov. Gray Davis
withdrew the state as a dealmaker, and the NFL responded by saying
it would now focus on other stadium sites in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in position by the NFL over the Coliseum impasse could
either open the expansion door back to the city of Carson or to
Hollywood Park, or signal the league is now prepared to give its
32nd franchise to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the negotiations quoted an NFL source as
saying, ``This is their way out. They are ready to go to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest flurry of developments in the saga over who would get
the league's 32nd franchise opened up several possible scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment giant Michael Ovitz originally proposed a new $370
million NFL stadium and shopping mall in Carson, before the league
selected the Coliseum as its area site and he designed plans for
Exposition Park with competing billionaire Eli Broad. He now could
revive his Carson plan, although local officials said the politics
of the deal had shifted.
</P>
<P>
   Oil billionaire Marvin Davis has an option on the Hollywood Park
property Raiders owner Al Davis planned to relocate his team to
five years ago before moving his franchise back to Oakland. Davis
now could step in with an offer, much as race track officials
anticipated when the Coliseum deal began the prime focus last year.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has given Los Angeles a Sept. 15 deadline to complete an
acceptable expansion package, or the league said the next franchise
will be awarded to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum deal started falling apart last week in Chicago
when the agreement Gov. Gray Davis' designated representative, Bill
Chadwick, thought he had brokered with the NFL was rejected by
owners. Instead of signing the nonbinding agreement, league
commissioner Paul Tagliabue demanded more public funding for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials were united in rejecting the demand for
public funding, and Davis refused additional support Thursday,
asking the league to work out the deal with the potential owners.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league would now focus on other possible
sites in the area.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the negotiations said Chadwick failed to
consult either prospective ownership group, Eli Broad-Ed Roski Jr.
or Ovitz-Ron Burkle, over his plans to partially repay the
$150million in bonds for new parking garages through a
$5million-per-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chadwick's plan effectively pulled the leg out from under the
deal, taking $40million away from the team's owners,'' the source
said, noting previous discussions had focused on $1million-a-year
Coliseum rent.
</P>
<P>
   Roski, who has been championing the Coliseum for the past three
years, said despite the NFL's new stance, he did not believe the
Coliseum deal was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' Roski said. ``We just need to continue
our dialogue with them. We're definitely not going to cease our
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they decide to go to Houston we would continue on,
because I really think it's important to the city and the fans of
Los Angeles to have an NFL team. We will continue to pursue it, and
continue to pursue it at the Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Davis, Tagliabue said the league chose the
Coliseum as the site advocated by Los Angeles leaders, but more
public funding was needed. &QL; 
``We have concluded that our effort to reach agreements for the
operation of an NFL team in Los Angeles can no longer be limited to
the Coliseum and Exposition Park and will in the weeks remaining
before September 15 focus on other potential stadium sites in the
Los Angeles area.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leaders scoffed at the suggestion that another site
could suddenly satisfy the NFL's demands within the next 40 days.
</P>
<P>
   Coliseum Commission President Sheldon Sloan said he believes it
will be almost impossible for any other group to come up with
detailed plans and still meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the site is in the city of Los Angeles, it will not get any
local political support, and if they expect anything from the
state, they can forget it,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Hernandez, who represents the area around Dodger
Stadium, had threatened action to block plans by then-owner Peter
O'Malley to build a football stadium in Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said the cost elsewhere of a new stadium and
infrastructure will be far more than rebuilding the Coliseum, where
all existing facilities are in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate the NFL is rejecting the proposal developed
by Bill Chadwick and that it was not considered substantial enough
for them,'' he said. ``I think they're also overlooking the fact
that building at the Coliseum requires only the approval of the
state architect. Anywhere else they go will require numerous
permits and potentially delay things for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz was far along in his plans for Carson but abandoned the
city when the NFL tabbed the Coliseum without naming Broad-Ovitz as
the ownership group or approving their stadium and site plans. The
league gave approval to the site plans essentially designed for the
Coliseum by Ovitz at its meetings last week.
</P>
<P>
   Carson Mayor Peter Fajardo said he was eager to get his city
back in the NFL expansion picture, but warned many at City Hall
were left with ill feelings over Ovitz's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are interested and would like to have a new team
and stadium,'' Fajardo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do come back, it will be a whole different ballgame
after these people walked out and left us cold.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Carson originally committed $180million to the stadium and mall
plans. Fajardo said although the city could still generate the
funds, there might not be as much open-ended support for the
financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be tremendous economic benefits, jobs and so on,''
he said. ``But the political complexion may have changed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ovitz comes back to us, he will be very surprised by our
attitude and what we will want from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's new position leaves Ovitz in an awkward position. If
he quickly returns to Carson, he would likely be viewed as
flip-flopping. His representative, Mark Fabiani, said Ovitz had yet
to read Tagliabue's letter to Davis and would not comment until he
had.
</P>
<P>
   A quick deal might be more easily put together at Hollywood
Park. R.D. Hubbard's company is in escrow with Churchill Downs over
the race track, but will still own the casino and land _ including
the 100-acre site across from the Forum where the football stadium
had been proposed. Hubbard could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Any stadium effort other than the Coliseum, however, could be at
risk of running up against political opposition from Los Angeles.
When Al Davis wanted to build a new stadium in Irwindale,
opposition and legal action tied up and eventually killed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Like Roski, Broad said in a statement he would continue to
support the Coliseum as the NFL site and had sent a letter to
Tagliabue on Tuesday outlining a new financing scheme for
Exposition Park, ``Which can be accomplished at no net cost to
taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter he made another bid to be selected the franchise
owner, offering $2 million for a nonrefundable 60-day option to
complete a deal that included a $150 million public investment to
be repaid from sales, property and income tax; public
responsibility for costs outside the Coliseum, including demolition
and site work, and maintaining the stadium; rent of $1 million per
year for 55 years; the franchise receiving all revenues from
parking, stadium rentals and concessions; and guaranteed sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   Broad's plan calls for a franchise fee of $550 million, a
stadium renovation of $400 million, and includes a $150 million
loan from the NFL. Broad offered to put up $275 million in cash
without expectation of a return on his investment for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan praised the
plan and threw his full weight behind the Broad plan, saying it was
the only one that could bring the city's business community fully
behind the team and ensure the sale of costly luxury boxes needed
to make the finances work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Eli Broad's proposal is sound and responsible,''
Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
