<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-COMPLIANCE-$     08-06 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-COMPLIANCE-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS EASES INTO COMPLIANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a hugely popular move, Republicans in 1995
required Congress to abide by the laws it enacts for the rest of
the country. It was the first plank of the GOP ``Contract With
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the lawmakers have begun to live under many of
the provisions of 11 health, safety, labor and anti-discrimination
laws. But Capitol Hill has not quite put itself quite into a
straitjacket of regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were significant exceptions that Congress gave itself,''
said Ricky Silberman, executive director of the little-known
congressional Office of Compliance, set up to administer the laws.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, her small office, not a huge federal bureaucracy,
is the overseer. And there are other differences:
</P>
<P>
   _ Trade groups can now unionize and bargain for pay and
conditions. But unlike private-sector workers, they are forbidden
to strike. Staff workers for Congress members and committees are
forbidden to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   _ Congressional employees can now seek compensation for job
discrimination or sexual harassment under a mediation system that
is often completed within a mere 60 days, much faster than under
civil rights actions in the private world.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most worker complaint cases are kept strictly confidential,
protecting lawmakers from embarrassing publicity that might hurt
re-election campaigns. In 27 cases since 1996, congressional
employees have been awarded a total of $204,959, the compliance
office reported this week. No details of the cases are given out
unless the plaintiff decides to take the case to court.
</P>
<P>
   When an award is paid to an employee, it does not come from the
pocket of the supervisor or member involved or even from a member's
office, but from a separate taxpayer fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fire and safety hazards have abounded at the Capitol's power
plant, paint shop and other work areas controlled by the architect
of the Capitol, whose employees have the highest rate of accidents
and injury of any federal agency. Yet an Office of Compliance
citation issued last month was only a symbolic action in response
to infractions discovered after a fire in a Library of Congress
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the private sector, the secretary of labor sets the fine,''
said Gary Green, general counsel for the compliance office. ``It
would have been a big bill, in the high five figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said that he is conducting a complete review of Capitol
Hill buildings. He said he was ``satisfied'' that the hazards
listed in the citation have been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Congress has ``done a pretty good job'' with
installing wheelchair ramps and other changes required in the
Americans With Disability Act.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for many no-smoking signs in the areas where
lawmakers work. Unlike many other workers today who must leave the
building for a cigarette, members of Congress can light up in their
work areas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
