<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN07-CO     08-06 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: Cool and breezy is forecast for
Prague
 &HT;    (Eds: Fifth in a series. Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
reported from Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago, just
before the fall of the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to
write about the changes that have led three former Eastern Bloc
countries _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland _ to become the
newest members of NATO. At the end of the series, CoxNet will
compile these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for running
as a Perspective-type page or op-ed feature. These pages are
available for sale to New York Times News Service clients at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE _ Prague is a city intoxicated on freedom, and that's not
all.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual to meet someone along the street smoking a
joint.
</P>
<P>
   One of the finest restaurants in Prague is just a block from an
open drug market.
</P>
<P>
   You may be sitting in a restaurant and, instead of a waiter,
it's a drug dealer who comes to your table to ask what he can bring
you.
</P>
<P>
   It takes some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   But then, so does the weather girl on TV, who appears totally
nude and then begins to dress herself accordingly for the next
day's weather. On occasion, it's an equally naked weather boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has so much history, and now so much freedom,'' a
Prague friend explained. ``The people are almost like spoiled
children. Everything's allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a selection of snapshot impressions made during a
three-day visit:
</P>
<P>
   _ You see police everywhere, but they're there primarily to make
sure things don't get out of hand. Otherwise, they leave you alone.
As for possession of narcotics, police are allowed a wide degree of
discretion in enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prostitution is prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Walk into a store and the employees are sitting around and
talking among themselves. You may have to interrupt them in order
to be waited on, and then you're likely to be treated as if you're
an intruder. Such is the legacy of communism.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eating out is cheap, if you go outside the tourist center of
the city. Two can dine for as little as $20, including drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prague has ``non-stop bars,'' open 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't dare criticize Czech beer. As the ancestral home of
Budweiser, beer is one of the few things sacred in this ancient
city _ that and the ice hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most Americans didn't take much notice, but the Czech Republic
won the European championship in ice hockey this past year, and the
ensuing celebration in Prague was like unto New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's no sense of the American health craze here. You'll see
children as young as 12 smoking in public. Men drink lots of beer
and it shows. Women, however, are expected to keep their figure and
dress provocatively _ and drink only dark beer, which, it is
believed, increases their bust size.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mini-skirts and low-cut blouses are much in fashion. Sexist
remarks are considered compliments, especially from a boss. Women,
even if they have jobs outside the home, are expected to do all the
household chores and have a hot meal on the table for their
husbands at dinnertime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visitors are warned to watch out for pickpockets. Worst places
in the city are the two train stations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Czechs hate everything Russian. An upscale Russian restaurant
finally gave up trying to maintain its storefront, such was the
graffiti. Under communism, Russian was a required language course.
Now, Czechs refuse to speak it, and won't even acknowledge they can
speak it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Czechs love everything American, especially our music and
fashion, but they consider us arrogant and, worse, ignorant of
Czech culture. Don't ever say, ``In America, that's not the way
things are done.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Example of Czech culture that Americans are ignorant of: At
Christmas, fish peddlers sell live carp on the street. The large
fish is brought home and kept in the bathtub for several days. On
Christmas Eve, as the women prepare the holiday feast, the
tradition is for the man of the house to whack off its head with a
butcher knife. It's a Czech thing _ you wouldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. His address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
