<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING PC ONLINE BRINGS IT FULL CIRCLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's fitting that one of the most popular items people use their
computers to buy over the Internet is ... other computers. There's
something wonderfully circular about updating your wheezing
compu-clunker with a few clicks of its mouse, and having a shiny
new replacement show up on your doorstep a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   Web sales of PCs are accounting for more and more machine sales.
And why not? Besides the convenience, there's the ability to
customize a machine to fit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   Here are examples of three PCs you can buy online. One's a
low-budget system, the other high-end, and the last is just plain
cool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dimension L500c, $1,361, Dell Computer Corp.: This is at the
high end of the low-price category for PCs, but it's worth it. This
machine has only one flaw _ its graphics system _ and it's a
significant one. But overall, it's one of the best low-cost
desktops I've seen this year.
</P>
<P>
   The L500c comes with Intel's new 500-megahertz Celeron chip, 64
megabytes of fast memory, a 6.4-gigabyte hard drive, a 40X CD-ROM
drive, a 56K fax modem, Harman Kardon speakers and a 17-inch
monitor. I added an Intel 10/100 Ethernet card to this base
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   As you'd expect, there are no performance complaints with this
system _ it took everything I threw at it. Although it's not quite
as fast as a 500-MHz Pentium III system, it's more than
respectable.
</P>
<P>
   The system is well designed. The case opens simply by pushing
back on a tab, and the side falls away. There are no old-style ISA
slots, just three open PCI slots.
</P>
<P>
   The computer comes with its Intel-based AGP graphics adapter
built into the motherboard, and there's no separate AGP slot if you
want to upgrade to a faster video card. The adapter also uses the
system's RAM for its own memory, but in a unique way. Rather than
having a fixed amount _ say, 2 MB _ it will take what it needs. One
minute you may have 63 MB of system memory available for programs,
and the next minute only 60 MB.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics also are limited to 24-bit color displays. It won't
do 32-bit displays, which means you shouldn't plan on using this
machine if you do high-end graphics work, or if you want 32-bit
color for state-of-the-art games that support it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aspire 6160, $1,719, Acer America: Acer has made an aggressive
push to sell its home PCs online. There are a variety of models at
different prices, but unfortunately, you can't customize them. Take
'em or leave 'em _ though Acer says the ability to configure your
own is on its way.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried was the 6150, which has since been replaced by
the 6160. My system had a 500-MHz Pentium III chip, 128 MB of
memory, an eight-GB hard drive, a 4X DVD-ROM drive, a 56K modem and
a 4-MB ATI Rage Pro graphics adapter.
</P>
<P>
   The 6160 improves on this with a 550-MHz Pentium III chip and a
13-GB hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   (The price listed above does not include a monitor. I used a
Dell 1500FP flat panel display, at $949, which has a 15-inch
active-matrix screen. It has an excellent look _ sharp and bright _
and several people here in the office mistook it for a traditional
CRT monitor until they realized how thin it was.)
</P>
<P>
   The Aspire line is aimed at home users, and is one of the few
systems that still has a simplified shell that sits on top of
Windows, allowing fast access to the programs on the computer. The
ACE Desktop is indeed handy, and those who are confused by the
Windows Start button and Explorer may benefit from this.
</P>
<P>
   This computer also makes extensive use of the Universal Serial
Bus. Both the mouse and the keyboard connect via USB ports, and
there are two more open USB ports for other devices.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very fast machine, though the ATI graphics card is a bit
underpowered. Since it sits in an AGP slot, rather than being
soldered to the motherboard, it's easy to upgrade to something more
muscular.
</P>
<P>
   _ Profile, $2,299, Gateway: This is one of several new designs
that are both eye-catching and space-saving, and rely largely on
notebook-PC technology. Indeed, the Profile looks like a notebook
computer perched on a display stand _ and performs like it, too.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a 400-MHz Advanced Micro Devices K6-2 chip, 64 MB
of memory, a 6.4-GB hard drive, a 2X DVD-ROM drive, a four-MB ATI
Rage LT Pro graphics adapter, a 56K modem, a built-in 10/100
Ethernet adapter and a 15-inch active-matrix flat-panel screen.
Simple speakers are built into the PC's base.
</P>
<P>
   This is an incredibly easy PC to set up. Pull it out of the box,
set it on your desk, plug in the mouse and keyboard and you're good
to go. A snap-off panel in the back masks ports for the modem and
Ethernet connections.
</P>
<P>
   The Profile has a nice, bright display that benefits from the
fact that it doesn't run on batteries. The screen also has a decent
field of view _ you can still see the display even if you are
standing off to the side.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that similarly configured desktop systems sell
for less than half the cost of this, you're paying a premium for
space savings and the coolness factor. You're certainly not paying
for friskiness, because this is no speed demon.
</P>
<P>
   Most notebook computers are not as fast as desktops, even if
their specifications are comparable. There are numerous bottlenecks
in a notebook, ranging from the system bus to the hard drive, that
can cause this. It's the price you pay for portability.
</P>
<P>
   And you also pay the price here, for the sake of a neat design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
