<HEADLINE>
BANK LENDS A HAND WITH CHILD CARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M.SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It typically happens when the baby sitter calls in
sick or the kids wake up sick.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there's a big scramble to find someone or someplace to
take care of the kids and still get to work on time.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, that'll be one problem Chase Bank of Texas employees won't
have to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The bank plans to open a backup, on-site child care center to
serve its 3,500 employees in downtown Houston and another backup
center in west Houston for the 2,000 employees who work in nearby
call centers.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is also building a child care center in Arlington,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Employees can use the centers free 20 days a year for each
child. Chase is also giving its parents of newborns eight weeks of
free care to help them adjust to the expense and hassles of child
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep the employees we have and keep them happy,''
said Dee Dee Guzman, vice president of human resources product
development. ``Time and time again, employees say they feel more
committed and more loyal'' when the bank helps with something that
can be so stressful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase is spending more than $4 million to build the three
centers in Texas and expects to spend each year between $600,000
and $700,000 to operate the downtown site and $400,000 to $500,000
to run the west Houston site.
</P>
<P>
   Chase surveyed its employees last year and found that while they
liked their regular child care arrangements, they're in a quandary
when their day care center closes for a religious holiday, or there
are floods and schools are closed.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a completely new endeavor for New York-based Chase
Manhattan Corp. It built its first backup child care center in 1992
to help employees who had been transferred to the bank's offices in
Brooklyn. It was so popular that the bank is expanding the concept,
and by 2001, there will be 11 backup child care centers around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LESS PRESSURE ON EMPLOYEE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Valle Wilson, a senior credit lender at Chase's consumer loan
center in west Houston, said she is thrilled with the plans for the
new child center that is scheduled to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   The church-affiliated day care center that her son, 14-month-old
Zachary, attends is closed on some religious holidays that the bank
doesn't observe. On those days, Wilson's husband has taken the day
off, but that will be more difficult to do now because he has been
traveling quite a bit lately. Other times, Wilson has asked
relatives to step in, but that's hard because they work too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a lot of pressure off me,'' said Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The new program will also take pressure off managers who have
production quotas to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of parents who wake up in the morning and Johnny
has spots,'' said Kevin O'Brien, executive vice president of cash
management, an intensive 24-hour, seven-day-a-week operation.
Employees then scramble to find alternative care and come in late,
or take leave to stay at home, all of which slows down the
processing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, parents have brought their children to work with
them, but that causes great disruption, O'Brien said, because
everyone wants to stop for a 10-minute conversation about the
child's school progress and plans for summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SERVICE FILLS A NEED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston has a handful of corporate on-site day care centers as
well as places to take sick children. But child care advocacy
experts say they don't know of any local corporate-sponsored child
care that is strictly designed for backup care.
</P>
<P>
   It's a real need, said Suzanne Hinds, director of Initiatives
for Children. The child care referral service gets about 5 percent
of its calls each month from parents looking for backup care.
Another 5 percent comes from parents looking for care for their
sick child.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Horizons Family Solutions, which manages child care
centers and will manage Chase's new centers in Texas, has a couple
of other employers who have set up backup care. But they don't
offer it free of charge, said Missy Martines, communication project
manager for Cambridge, Mass.-based Bright Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   More clients are interested in providing the service because it
greatly reduces employee absenteeism and it's a great recruiting
incentive, Martines said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
