<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEVENTEEN-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON IN TOP 10 AS TEEN HAVEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's official. Houston is the place to be if you're a
mall-hangin', shopaholic teen.
</P>
<P>
   Or a Comet-gazing teen.
</P>
<P>
   Or a thrill-seeking teen.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is one of 10 cities named as teen havens in the
September issue of Seventeen magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The others are Ann Arbor, Mich.; Billings, Mont.; Boston;
Boulder, Colo.; Honolulu; Montclair, N.J.; New York; San Francisco
and Seattle. San Francisco was singled out as the top town for
teens, but the other nine weren't ranked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping, anyone? If you love to indulge in retail madness,
Houston is the place for you,'' according to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   You'll get no quibble on that from Lauren Young, a 14-year-old
freshman at Cypress Falls Senior High School. She's lived in
Houston all her life, and she says it's a good place for teens.
``It's big, and there are lots of places to go shopping,'' she said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite? The Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   For its first-ever survey of teen livability, Seventeen looked
at 120 cities across the country, checking out five major
categories: fun stuff to do, shopping, crime rate, schools and
quality of life. The magazine defined ``quality of life'' as
involving climate, mass transit, free festivals, curfew laws, how
cool downtown is for kids, access to reproductive health care,
divorce rates, quality of the library system, and suicide and
depression rates.
</P>
<P>
   It crunched the numbers and came up with the winners. The losers
in the magazine's rankings weren't identified.
</P>
<P>
   The results are good news for Houston, said Jim Kollaer,
president of the Greater Houston Partnership and father of a
15-year-old son. That's because it points up the city's appeal to
younger workers. ``We're getting a lot more growth in this area,''
Kollaer said. ``It means we'll have a more educated, younger work
force.''
</P>
<P>
   No other Texas cities made the Top 10, although San Antonio and
Dallas were both cited for their shopping opportunities, and San
Antonio made the list of best places for a cheap date _ just $19.93
for a pizza and two movie tickets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its wealth of shopping destinations _
Westheimer's eclectic mix of shops and coffeehouses were mentioned,
along with the Galleria _ the magazine listed the WNBA championship
team, the Comets, and the city's amusement parks as being of
special appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And for kids who don't already live here, Seventeen thoughtfully
provided a list of the city's universities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
