<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-GAMES-2TAKES     08-06 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-GAMES-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING ROOT IN DALLAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  A childlike love of games is turning a handful of companies in
North Texas into heavyweights as they churn out blockbuster titles
in an atmosphere of healthy competition and communal pride 
 
By TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Two major deadlines are pressing down on game developer
Terminal Reality.
</P>
<P>
   The company's next game, a flight simulator called Fly!, must be
ready to ship to stores in a few weeks. A second game, Nocturne,
needs a playable demo finished soon so it can be included in a game
magazine's October issue.
</P>
<P>
   President and Lead Programmer Mark Randel is feeling the heat.
He and his team of programmers have been punching in programming
code for hours, day and night.
</P>
<P>
   The art teams continue to smooth out the look of each game, and
level designers work frantically to make everything fit together.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the strain in Randel's face. He's losing sleep and
it shows in his eyes. Every day, there's another fire for him or
Brett Combs, Terminal's vice president, to douse.
</P>
<P>
   This is life in the computer and video game industry. But this
isn't San Francisco, Los Angeles, Seattle or Austin.
</P>
<P>
   It's Dallas. And in the past few years, this city of 1.1 million
people has been a contender for the title of America's game
developing capital.
</P>
<P>
   In the thick of things are about 10 &UR;  &LR; independent Dallas
development houses. No less than half have each had a blockbuster
hit of 500,000 or more units sold in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The city's game companies form a web of friends, semi-rivals and
pseudo-families. And their lifestyles are driven by an ardor that
is rarely seen in other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working in this industry is addictive,'' said Robert Atkins,
art director for Ritual Entertainment. ``It will take over your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a game developer means living a life of high stress,
grueling ly long hours and a ``complete lack of a personal life,''
Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear of caffeine headaches and a sensitivity to sunlight
hasn't stopped what he and other game makers have accomplished so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Hit games have been developed by Terminal Reality (Monster Truck
Madness I and II), id Software (Doom and Quake series), Apogee
Software Ltd./3D Realms Entertainment (Duke Nukem series) and
Ensemble Studios (Age of Empires series).
</P>
<P>
   Several more developers have ``sure things'' due for release
later this year, or early next. Among them, Ritual Entertainment
(Heavy Metal: FAKK2), Third Law Interactive (KISS Psycho Circus _
The Nightmare Child), Edge of Reality (Monster Truck Madness N64)
and Ion Storm (Anachronox).
</P>
<P>
   Propelling these young companies is a video gaming industry that
is in its third consecutive year of double-digit growth, according
to the Interactive Digital Software Association.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of PC games rose between 10 and 15 percent last year, and
console games for machines like Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64
grew between 15 and 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At about $6.3 billion, the game industry took in more money in
1998 than the movie industry did at the box office in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a kind of child-like fascination with
(games), or it would be just another job for you,'' said Sverre
Kvernmo, Third Law's lead designer. ``It was what I always did in
my free time anyway, and now it's how I make my living. That's true
of a lot of the other guys here.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Milken Institute, a California think tank
that studies world economic growth, placed the city second only to
the Silicon Valley based on the concentration and economic output
it in high-technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Institute, Dallas has a diversified high-tech
base _ seven technology industries out of a possible 14 were more
concentrated in the area than elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is also home to six of the nation's 20 largest
telecommunication service companies, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain, in part, why Dallas has attracted so many game
developers.
</P>
<P>
   But many claim the success of id's Wolfenstein 3-D, a project
proposed, funded and originally published as shareware by Apogee in
1992, played the greatest role.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfenstein and then the phenomenal success of id's follow-up,
first-person shooter Doom helped attract some of computer gaming's
most visionary and renowned artists, designers and programmers to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us have released at least one big hit, and, having
tasted that success, it's high motivation to taste it again,'' said
Scott Miller, founder of Apogee and a partner in 3D Realms.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors, too, made it easy for Detroit native Randel to
move his company to nearby Lewisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a more relaxed and laid-back attitude here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't hurt to know a strong-selling game can yield a
developer $1.5 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in the ``Dallas gaming mafia,'' as the group's been
dubbed, have ``always been independently owned and therefore we've
always been able to play by our own rules,'' Scott Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mike Wilson and Harry Miller took that burgeoning
attitude and persuaded four local companies and two outside of
Texas to form Gathering of Developers, a computer and video game
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The Gathering wants to change the publishing side of the
industry, and it's done so by breaking a few steadfast rules. Its
developers receive higher royalties and creative space to create
games and get the majority of the recognition for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the founding companies has a seat on the board and a say
in all business decisions. The partners include Ritual
Entertainment, Terminal Reality, Epic Megagames, Edge of Reality,
Apogee/3D Realms and Poptop Software.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Miller, Gathering's president, said the game publisher has
made some inroads already.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were misunderstood for a long time, but that's changed,''
he said. ``Other publishers are looking to work with us, whereas
before they were not. They understand why we are here.''
</P>
<P>
   The developers had no doubts about the Gathering's purpose.
After working with Microsoft to publish Terminal Velocity: Fury 3
and other games, the team at Terminal Reality joined the Gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Fly! _ a general aviation flight simulator that uses real
satellite terrain imagery and has realistic cockpit controls _ is
Terminal's first title published by the Gathering.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Terminal's second title, Nocturne, that will mark its
entry into the non-simulation market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional publishers like to typecast. They expect a
developer to do one type of genre game for their entire
existence,'' Combs said. ``What's been cool about the Gathering is
they've allowed us to go outside our typecast of being a simulation
company in creating Nocturne.''
</P>
<P>
   Nocturne, a horror/action adventure, debuts on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on Nocturne, my baby, for three years
now,'' Randel said.
</P>
<P>
   Randel wanted to create a new interactive experience with
Nocturne, which required the development team to go beyond what
other character games had done before.
</P>
<P>
   The early results: realistic proportions, realistic physics and
early praise in the gaming press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can do it in real life, then you can do it in the
game,'' Randel said. ``You can run, jump and climb, but you can't
scale walls and do a standing back-flip from a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't do it, why make a character jump, turn twists and
stand like a superhuman? Now the monsters, on the other hand ...,''
he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious force driving these twenty- and thirty-somethings
has less to do with becoming rich overnight and more with gaining
respect for their creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misconception about the game industry is people
don't realize how big and serious of an industry it is,'' said Rob
Cohen, president of Edge of Reality. ``The premier games are
technological and artistic masterpieces. Eventually (they're) going
to be recognized as an art form.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also evident is, unlike their California peers,
Dallas-based developers aren't afraid to express their excitement
over another developer's work, nor do the companies discourage
employees from mixing with those of a rival firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gaming community here is younger. There's no paranoia
about having employees mixing,'' said Tony Goodman, president and
CEO of Ensemble Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Ensemble Studios threw a grand opening bash to show
off its new headquarters and upcoming game, Age of Empires II. The
guest list was a gumbo of the Dallas gaming elite.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Wolford, managing partner at Third Law Interactive, said the
companies actually ``root for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Development teams have a family element to them, and people
move around so much that most of us have been friends or worked
together at some point in time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The success and experience found in Dallas have inspired two of
the city's newest game makers _ Third Law and Edge of Reality.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, along with Vice President Mike Panoff, started Edge of
Reality last year. The company's seven employees work out of an
apartment in a Dallas suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Their first game, Monster Truck Madness 64, is now in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wolford and the entire Third Law team jumped ship last year from
Ion Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons for our leaving varied from person to person,''
said Kvernmo, a native of Tromsdalen, Norway, near the Arctic
Circle. ``What we did have in common was the notion we had
potential as a team, and that wasn't being realized (at Ion).''
</P>
<P>
   The Gathering will publish Third Law's first game, The Nightmare
Child. It should hit stores next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Both Edge of Reality and Third Law said there's tremendous
pressure to be part of the successful history of developers in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's there. This is the title that will break or make us,''
Kvernmo said.
</P>
<P>
   Handling Third Law's daily operations keeps Wolford busy enough.
But as the only woman in a company of 11 young men, she's also
taken on the unofficial position of ``Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Her office would make her popular among teenagers. Comic books
and action figures from Kiss Psycho Circus line her bookshelves and
any free space on her floor. The Psycho Circus was created by Todd
McFarlane, the mastermind behind the best-selling Spawn comic books
and merchandise line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'd rather the team think they've got a brilliant,
attractive woman running the ship rather than a motherly figure,''
Wolford, a tall, 37-year-old blond, said, laughing. ``But the `mom'
persona works much better for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   At id Software, Katherine Anna Kang and administrative assistant
Donna Jackson consider themselves and their 13 male colleagues one
big family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Donna thinks of the guys as her kids, and I think of them
as my bratty brothers,'' said Kang, id's director of business
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are not embarrassed to run around with Nerf toys,
shooting each other. You can be a kid and that's still OK. It's a
relaxed, youthful environment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear the overall atmosphere is a balance of competition,
respect and success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing laid-back about Dallas business, and you are
only as good as your last work,'' said Wilson, chief executive of
the Gathering. ``It's a great environment for keeping one focused
on work and productivity, and having others around you driven to
excel is great.''
</P>
<P>
   And as in any relationship, there are feuds. But they come and
go as the developers seek success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you hear of spats and stuff, but then it dies,''
said Ritual's Richard ``Levelord'' Gray. ``We're all so busy.
There's no time to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
