<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALES-TAX-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-06 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALES-TAX-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES-TAX HOLIDAY COULD BE BONANZA _ OR BUST _ FOR TEXAS RETAILERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG HASSELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As Texas retailers gear up for the state's first sales
tax holiday, which started Friday morning and continues through
midnight Sunday, one big question remains to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Will shoppers embrace the event and stampede the stores like
they do on the days after Thanksgiving and Christmas? Or will they
dismiss it as a political gimmick that offers little relief for
their pocketbook?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure what the impact will be, because we've never
had anything like this before,'' said John Pew, general manager of
Baybrook Mall in Houston. ``To be on the safe side, we are going to
assume that it will be very, very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't panic. It's unlikely the crowds will rival those that
jam stores during the peak days of the Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This holiday only affects some of the stores _ those that sell
clothing. We have a lot of stores that don't sell apparel, and they
will not feel much of an impact,'' Pew said.
</P>
<P>
   The sales-tax holiday of 1999 will give Texans 72 hours of
tax-free shopping, as long as they are buying clothing and shoes
costing less than $100 per item.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing and equipment used exclusively for athletic purposes _
things such as golf shoes or football pants _ will not be
tax-exempt. Likewise, the law does not exempt accessories such as
jewelry, handbags and wallets.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday is timed to coincide with back-to-school shopping,
and the list of tax-exempt merchandise is tailored to try to give
the biggest break to families needing to outfit their children for
the coming school year. State officials estimate Texas shoppers
will save about $69 million during the three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay so much tax. So even though this isn't a huge tax
break, it feels really good not to pay tax on something,'' said
Shannon Mathias, who planned to do some shopping for her two
children Friday morning at The Woodlands Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to beat the rush and get back home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Erin McLeod plans to cash in on the tax savings, but she has a
slightly different strategy for avoiding the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my daughter's birthday this weekend, and we are going to
go shopping late Friday night,'' said McLeod, who has her sights
set on hitting First Colony Mall, which planned to stay open until
midnight Friday and Saturday. ``I think the crowds will be ungodly,
so we are going to shop late.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond setting their shopping hours, the mother acknowledges
she'll be able to control little about their upcoming shopping
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haley is turning 11, so she has to pick out everything she
wears herself. I'll tell her what she can't have _ that's why I am
going along,'' McLeod said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Ball likes the idea of a tax holiday, but she isn't
putting shopping on her to-do list this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great idea, but I won't be there,'' she said. ``I've
got family in from out of town, and they aren't coming here to
shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to gauge public interest in the sales-tax holiday is a
key business decision for merchants. Most are spending big bucks to
pay for extra staffing and extra merchandise. Many are cutting
prices to motivate customers with more than simply the tax break of
8.25 percent, which includes regional and local sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Foley's retail store is offering its big ``Red
Apple'' sale this weekend. Other merchants, such as Macy's and
Palais Royal, are offering steep discounts on selected items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to rip and roar,'' said Oshman's Sporting Goods
President Alvin Lubetkin.
</P>
<P>
   But Lubetkin is concerned the public may be too uninformed or
apathetic to make this a big sales bonanza. As he sat in a barber's
chair Thursday, Lubetkin was keenly interested when the
conversation swirling around him turned to the upcoming sales tax
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman in the barber's shop spoke up and said she had just
heard about this thing called the sales-tax holiday. She acted like
she had never heard of it before,'' he lamented. ``I don't get the
sense that a lot of people are real excited about this. I hope I am
wrong. We are hoping for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the best-case scenario for merchants, could this weekend
conceivably rival the weekend after Thanksgiving?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Lubetkin said. ``I just don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may not be a runaway train, the weekend will give a
sales boost to some retailers, including some who aren't normally
thought of as mainstream clothing merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Raisbeck, co-owner of Charlotte's Saddlery, didn't think
his merchandise would be covered by the tax holiday until he read a
newspaper article that specifically listed ``riding pants'' as
being tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, that surprises me,'' Raisbeck said. ``I didn't expect it,
but I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirts, pants and some boots sold at Charlotte's will be
tax-free, he said. Kroger supermarkets will get a piece of the
action because it sells diapers, pantyhose and socks, all of which
are tax-exempt items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stocked up on diapers and will run a special on large
packs of Huggies,'' said Kroger spokesman Gary Huddleston. ``Kroger
is excited to participate in the sales-tax holiday. ... It's real
tax relief for real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so enthused about the tax holiday, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the lottery. There is an illusion present
that could end up costing some people a lot of money,'' said Reggie
James, director of the Consumers Union Southwest Regional Office.
``Low-income (people) don't have a lot of disposable income.
Because of easy credit, there will be a temptation to spend a lot
of money they don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an appreciable savings,'' James added. ``On $100, you
save about $8.''
</P>
<P>
   But if shoppers hunt for the best discounts being offered and
don't blow their budgets sky-high, the holiday will be a benefit,
James conceded.
</P>
<P>
   A more typical line of complaint concerns the list of items that
are tax-exempt. For instance, lingerie is not your normal
back-to-school staple, but it's tax-exempt. But pencils and a paper
tablets are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are so concerned with school kids, why aren't school
supplies exempt?'' McLeod asked. ``I'll spend $100 easy on school
supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Another head-scratcher is that fur coats are exempt, but
backpacks are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't they include backpacks? Every kid who goes to
school wears a backpack of some kind,'' Lubetkin said.
</P>
