<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CROWN (Undated) _ Whenever she can, insurance
investigator Catherine Banning (Rene Russo) refers to Thomas Crown
(Pierce Brosnan), her billionaire playboy prey, as ``Tommy.'' The
boyish nickname is part tool of reductive seduction, part nominal
territory-marking, part Banning's way of informing Crown that she
doesn't take his smooth-operator comportment seriously. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FRASIER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ It has been one of television's
better teases, the pining of the lovelorn Dr. Niles Crane for the
oblivious Daphne Moon. But it's been six years now. Something has
to give with those kids from ``Frasier.'' Otherwise, David Hyde
Pierce (who plays Niles) says, ``It starts being unbelievable.'' By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SENSE (Undated) _ ``The Sixth Sense'' sneaks up on
you _ slowly, on tip-toe, slinking up the cellar stairs until it's
hovering right behind you, hissing down your neck. The film is a
cunning paranormal thriller about a boy who sees dead people and
the child psychiatrist who tries to help him. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LIFE (Undated) _ Sometimes an out-of-touch
kids-find-sex movie can be quaint in its need to pretend that
yesterday is better than now _ or that yesterday is a lot like now.
But ``My Life So Far'' is neither a reminiscent throwback nor mild
allegory, it's a willfully turgid demonstration that if a filmmaker
puts his mind to it he can tell a tale about a boy sexually coming
of age as if the birds, bees and educated fleas were the only one's
doing it. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LUMINATA (Undated) _ Imagined as a love song to his
wife about the strength of their marriage, John Turturro's ``Il
luminata'' uses the theater to craft a Chekhovian-flimsy
Shakespeare version of ``The Ballad of John and Yoko.'' But for
better or worse, the wife, Kathryn Borowitz, is no Ono. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MYSTERY (Undated) _ Champion City could be one
post-millennial metropolis over from Tim Burton's Gotham City and
two towns away from any Terry Gilliam municipal zoo. Basically,
it's a circus of emancipated superhero carnival freaks who want to
time warp again, and ``Mystery Men'' is their bacchanal. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
