<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Most cities have a disaster
contigency plan if a hurricane hits or if key employees go on
strike. But most households don't have the resources to turn on a
dime when one of the most personal of disasters strike: normal
child care arrangements fall through. It happens when the nanny
calls in sick or the kids wake up sick. Suddenly, it's a big
scramble to find someone or someplace to take care of the kids and
still get to work on time. By L.M. SIXEL
