<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL ADVENTURE REQUIRES CAREFUL PLANNING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Moved in ''f`` and ''l`` categories.) 
 
By JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Think you'll just dash out and grab some
back-to-school stuff for the kids this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   Think again. The experts say you need a plan.
</P>
<P>
   High on the list is deciding when and where to shop.
</P>
<P>
   First thing in the morning and late afternoon-to-early evening
are generally quiet times, although many retailers expect bedlam
this weekend as people take advantage of the three-day sales tax
holiday, which began at 12:01 a.m. Friday. It continues until
midnight Sunday, giving Texas families a break on shoes, clothing
and a variety of other items.
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax exemption amounts to 8.25 percent at stores inside
the Houston city limits, and many stores are offering further
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   So prepare for crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost have to go with the same attitude you would have at
Christmas,'' said David Gusewelle, special events manager for J.C.
Penney Co. ``Parking will probably be something. You'll have to
wait for everything. If you have to go to the bathroom, you'll
probably have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding what you want before leaving home could speed things
up.
</P>
<P>
   Priscilla Thorne, a spokeswoman for Foley's retail store,
suggests going through your kids' closets and determining what they
need to complement what they already have. She recommends sticking
with the basics _ jeans, khakis, polo shirts _ and allowing for one
or two special items.
</P>
<P>
   School uniforms simplify the choices, but kids will need a few
other things, depending upon their ages and interests. A
skateboarding 11-year-old has different wardrobe requirements than
a 16-year-old with a part-time job and a busy social life.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to older kids about what they need and want _ not always
the same thing, of course _ can help determine your destination. If
only one brand name will do, figure out ahead of time which stores
carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the shopping plan is figuring out how much you
can spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of families are on budgets, so come prepared with the
amount of money you're able to spend,'' advised Christina Kerford,
a Macy's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of how much money is at hand. You can
usually find the available limit on your credit cards with a quick
telephone call, avoiding embarrassing and time-consuming delays in
the checkout line.
</P>
<P>
   Thorne suggests giving older kids a budget and some guidelines _
including a firm thumbs down on anything you'll definitely hate _
and letting them make their own choices. Teens may be happy with
fewer things in exchange for one thing they really want, whether
it's an outrageous pair of sneakers or an expensive pair of
designer jeans. If they love it, they'll wear it constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, if kids of any age tell you they don't like something,
believe them. They won't wear it.
</P>
<P>
   Some die-hard shoppers swear by the piecemeal approach: blue
jeans in the morning, followed by a break for lunch. Shoes in the
late afternoon, then call it a day. Make a couple of equally
well-defined forays the following day, and repeat until the job is
done or you're broke, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't work for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Gallegos ought to have back-to-school shopping down to
a science _ she has 10-year-old triplets.
</P>
<P>
   Rayanne, Taylor and Tyler will start fifth grade at Memorial
Parkway Elementary School in nearby Katy next week, so Gallegos is
girding for a one-day shopping spree this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all go as a family,'' she said. ``It's quite an event.''
</P>
<P>
   With no older siblings to pass along hand-me-downs, the family
starts new every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need everything,'' Gallegos said. ``Socks, underwear,
shirts, shorts, jeans ... We like to buy it all at once. I know
that sounds crazy, but we do. We don't like to keep going back and
forth (to the mall), so we try to make a big haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Thorne said, people with several kids should shop for
one child at a time, ``especially if they're younger.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you'll be shopping en masse this weekend or later in the
month, make it as easy as you can:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scour the ads for sales before leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trying on new clothes will be less of a hassle if the kids
wear easy-on, easy-off shoes and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   _ You should wear comfortable clothes, too, and, most important,
comfortable shoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure the kids have had a good night's sleep and a good
breakfast. ``Bathe them, feed them, give them lots to drink and
take them to the bathroom,'' advises one store employee bracing for
the busy weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ To sustain yourselves, drink plenty of water before and
throughout the shopping trip. Take a water bottle for convenience.
If you've got small kids, a tote bag of toys, snacks and drinks is
handy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget to take an occasional break.
</P>
<P>
   _ And remember that kids grow. Buy some things in larger sizes
or wait until the after-Christmas sales to buy things for the
second half of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Take into consideration your children's taste,'' Kerford
said. ``Compromise. Let kids pick out a few things they like.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask if you're getting the absolute best price _ some stores
have coupons or other special deals you may not know about. Ask
about the return policy, just in case. Some clothing can't be
returned if the tags have been removed.
</P>
<P>
   And try to have a good time. The Gallegos family will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good little shoppers,'' Gallegos said. ``We love the
mall, and our kids actually like going. My daughter is like, `Oh,
Mom, let's shop 'til we drop.' And the boys are like, `We'll go if
we get something.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
