r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN07-COX     08-06 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arguments: Husbands know when it's time to quit talking and find
a cot
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Discovering you're no longer welcome in
your own home is a sad experience. The best I can say for my wife
is that she tried to break the news diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad you finally decided to clean out your shop,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I replied. ``I need a place to paint the tractor. After
30 years I thought it needed a face lift, and now that I'm getting
a little long in the tooth myself, maybe a tractor that looks new
will help my image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had another use in mind for the shop,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?'' I asked. I thought she might be planning to clean
out her closets and start a nearly-new boutique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of putting in a bathroom,'' she said. ``And a
washer and dryer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have more bathrooms than we had in the south half
of Fayette County when I was growing up,'' I said. ``Why in the
world do we need another one in my shop?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever totaled up the real cost of your garden?'' she
asked. ``Now that we don't have children in college your garden is
our biggest expense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's preposterous,'' I replied. ``With this heat wave, our
electric bill is more than house payments used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And why do you think that is?'' she asked. ``What do you think
runs the pump that runs all night so you can water your garden? If
you didn't insist on having a garden, we could cut our electric
bill in half.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this got to do with a bathroom in the shop?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can shower out there after working in your garden instead
of messing up the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know we can't afford to build a bathroom in the shop just
so I can shower before coming in from the garden,'' I argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only can we afford a bathroom,'' she said. ``We can afford
a sink and a washer and dryer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a washer and dryer in the basement,'' I pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're both about worn out,'' she said, ``from washing
your garden clothes twice a day.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to concede I do have a lot of garden clothes to be washed
and dried. The older you get, the more you sweat, a phenomenon
complicated by repressive house rules. I'm not allowed to sit on a
sofa or in a dining room chair when my clothes are wet with sweat.
Because of those restrictions, and especially in this hot weather,
I have to change clothes twice a day, at noon, and again at
suppertime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think a little extra washing justifies
installing a bathroom and a laundry operation in the shop,'' I
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does when you consider the cost of carpet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do carpets have to do with it?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't track mud from the garden in the house, we
wouldn't have to replace the carpet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're saying,'' I concluded, ``is that you really don't
want me in the house anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all the time,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit I brought part of this on myself. When my garden
was thriving last month I did some bragging, even going so far as
inviting Dr. George Patton, the north Fayette master gardener, down
to view the fruits of my labors.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the Bible it says that the Lord will smite a
braggart and bring the boastful low. If the Bible doesn't say that,
it must have been an oversight, because it surely is the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The very day I bragged about my superior corn patch, the Lord
sent a driving rainstorm and high winds. Half my corn patch was
flattened. With ears on the ground and subject to raiding raccoons,
the Silver Queen had to be harvested immediately. Then it rained
for eight days and eight nights, causing the tomatoes to wilt. They
had to be picked before they rotted on the dying vines. The wet
weather prompted squash and cucumbers to record production.
</P>
<P>
   All of this merged with a bumper crop of figs made more
unmanageable than usual when two extra bushes I'd put out for
insurance kicked in. I'll admit the kitchen and the washing machine
got vigorous workouts, and maybe some mud was inadvertently tracked
on the carpet during the eight days and nights of monsoons. But
with people starving all over the world, it would have been sinful
to let anything go to waste.
</P>
<P>
   I guess all of that put together pushed my wife over the edge.
Nevertheless, it isn't a good feeling to realize you're about to be
kicked out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll get a little cot and sleep in the shop, too,'' I
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good idea for the rainy season,'' she responded, with
more enthusiasm than I thought appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone knows where I can find an old Army cot and mattress,
please let me know. I could also use a small stove to heat soup and
keep me warm on cold winter nights.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
