<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN-07COX     08-06 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN-07COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Psuedoscientific hooey the scare tactic of choice nowadays
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ People know that politics, philosophy and theology
are based on personal beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Science, however, is considered based on knowledge obtained from
comprehensive testing and objective research.
</P>
<P>
   That perception opens the door for deception.
</P>
<P>
   America apparently is chockablock with anti-business,
anti-industry Luddites willing to support any flimsy excuse to
malign politically incorrect technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientific studies show such and such'' is more persuasive
than ``I believe such and such.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, whose careers depend on persuasion, know this. Any
trial where enough money is involved likely will have dueling
scientific experts.
</P>
<P>
   After the contradicting experts are finished, the jurors, who
have been carefully screened for their lack of knowledge on the
points in dispute, are often left to mold a decison out of
conflicting emotional arguments and contridictory
scientific-sounding testimony.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson would be on death row had his fate rested in the
hands of a panel of genuine scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Junk science caused Dow Chemical Company to file for bankruptcy
and put thousands of workers out of jobs due to claims that the
company's silicone breast implants caused cancer, lupus and other
chronic disorders.
</P>
<P>
   When all the payments are completed, it is estimated that Dow
Corning will have paid out $3.2 billion to lawyers representing
176,000 women for diseases caused by silicone breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   The billions of dollars, the anxiety of a national scare and the
loss of jobs were all based on anecdotal claims of scientific
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The science was junk and the claims were bogus, according to an
actual long-term scientific study of the evidence by respected
scientists who made up a committee named by the Institute of
Medicine, the medical division of the nonprofit National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   After a thorough examination of all available evidence, the
committee found that women with silicone breast implants are no
more likely to develop chronic disease than women without the
implants.
</P>
<P>
   There are risks inherent in any invasive surgery, especially
when a foreign object is placed in the body, but the scientists
said there is ``no evidence to suggest that the silicones used in
the transplants are toxic to humans.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no accounting to show how many millions or
billions of dollars have been wasted to accommodate faulty science
that supposedly showed that electromagnetic fields, or EMF, from
high-tension lines caused cancer or childhood leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it turns out that a scientist at the Lawrence
Berkeley Laboratory faked the evidence to help him win $3.3 million
in federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-industry scares based on junk science often can be spotted
simply because they appear out of nowhere and quickly sweep across
the nation. Real science is slow and time-consuming. It is based on
tests on top of tests that are open to peer review.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Alar on apples and global warming, other popular scares
have been the report that houses and buildings with high radon
counts cause cancer and that the tiny amounts of electromagnetic
energy (more good ol' EMF) from cell phones cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The alar scare was eventually found to be spurious.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead scientists promoting global warming for the
Clinton administration previously promoted a global ice-age scare.
</P>
<P>
   The only long-term measurements of the planet's temperature come
from NASA satellite data that consistently show a slight global
temperature drop, not an increase.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it's better to be safe than sorry, right up to the
point that we are repetitively foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
