<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, August 7
and Sunday, August 8, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TV-BERNADETTE _ A review of ``Bernadette Peters in Concert,''
her one-woman taped last year at Royal Albert Hall in London. It's
much like the concert she did here at the Rialto in September, with
a few notable additions. (Janich, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
13. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-EXPO _ ATLANTA _ Big expo for black women at the Congress
Center. Top-name musicians will appear. With photo from last year's
event, and if-you-go info. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
12. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ The Taunton Press is once again
demonstrating one of its most remarkable aptitudes, that of
creative literary recycling. ``The Basics of Craftsmanship'' can
serve as a useful augmentation to the first volume of Tage Frid's
trilogy, ``Tage Frid Teaches Woodworking: Joinery _ Tools and
Techniques,'' but it won't replace it. I doubt anything ever will.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LEFTBEHIND _ Jerry Jenkins and his ``Left Behind'' series
of Christian novels based on the book of Revelation has left behind
all other religious books in sales. The original has sold nearly 2
million and is averaging 100,000 sales per months. The five sequels
are each averaging 70,000 a month. And, the newest one, released
Thursday, had advance sales of 800,000. We talk to Jenkins about
the appeal and about how his life has changed with this
best-selling series. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MARIANIST _ To commemorate the sesquicentennial of the
Marianist Ministries in America, the Marianists, a religious order
of brothers and priests, commissioned historian Christopher J.
Kauffman of the Catholic University of America to write a
comprehensive ministry. The result is a book of more than 300 pages
titled Education and Transformation: Marianist Ministries in
America since 1848 (Crossroad Publishing, $29.95). (Dayton Daily
News). 14. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   PRAY-TEENS _ Christina Hurr knows that kids reach a certain age
when there's only so much you can do for them. She has three kids
at that age now: a 16-year-old son and 14-year-old twins. And,
although she knows they are bound to do things she won't agree
with, there's one thing she can always do about it: ``I can always
pray.'' That's why she has started Pray 4 Teens Ministry, where
parents, friends or the teens themselves can call or e-mail to
request prayer support. (Dayton Daily News). 16. WITH PHOTO. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: This is the CoxNet SciHealth page for the week. The
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0803 -- A relatively new program is looking for
ways to use the unique capabilities of such creatures as
cockroaches, honeybees, moths, lobsters and lizards to perform
military tasks. (Nesmith, Cox Washington Bureau) Art includes
3-column color photo of beekeeper handling bees, an 18-pica color
photo of a researcher next to a moth case and a 18-pica color photo
of a drawing showing how bees might carry electronic gear.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DEPRESSION WALK -- Almost every day for the past three
months, someone has stopped Stuart Perry on the road, wanting to
talk about depression. Since May, Perry has walked on back roads
from Georgia to Chicago talking about depression to anyone who
would listen. He began his trek to educate people about the
devastating illness and to give hope about treatment. (Miller,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ANTIOXIDENTS GAIN RESPECT -- An increasing number of
people believe that antioxidants _ certain vitamins, minerals and
plant-based chemicals _ are the key to maintaining health if you
live in a city with high levels of air pollution and other toxic
chemicals. (Kennedy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MANATEE _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Manatees aren't too slow or stupid
to get out of the way of boats; they just can't hear them, says a
Florida Atlantic University scientist whose research into sea cow
acoustics is getting international attention. Edmund Gerstein's
research shows that manatees evolved to hear only high-pitched
sounds, not the low rumble of boat propellers. His solution: he's
developed an ultra-high pitched warning beacon that boaters could
stick to their hulls. He recently published his research in an
international acoustics journal. The British magazine New Scientist
just ran a blurb on it, causing his phone to ring off the hook.
(King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-FUTURE _ The key to making the works of America's best
playwrights economcally viable is a strong National Endowment for
the Arts says Robert Brustein, a critic of The New Republic
Magazine and artistic director of American Repertory Theatre in
Cambridge, Mass. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   THEATRE-CENTURY _ A CENTURY IN THE ARTS: THEATER: The changing
nature and mission of American theater in the 20th century is tied
to the places that it serves. To put it bluntly, the what and why
of theater is intimately connected to the where. Up until the
1950s, the where was New York and the why was for-profit. Beginning
with ``Oklahoma!'' in 1943, and extending through ``A Streetcar
Named Desire'' and ``Death of a Salesman'' at the end of the
decade, theatrical talent converged and peaked in the Broadway
district. By the ``60s, the regional theater movement had started.
It continues to flourish today. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 90. WITH COLOR PHOTO ILLUSTRATION. FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
