   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: This is the CoxNet SciHealth page for the week. The
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0803 -- A relatively new program is looking for
ways to use the unique capabilities of such creatures as
cockroaches, honeybees, moths, lobsters and lizards to perform
military tasks. (Nesmith, Cox Washington Bureau) Art includes
3-column color photo of beekeeper handling bees, an 18-pica color
photo of a researcher next to a moth case and a 18-pica color photo
of a drawing showing how bees might carry electronic gear.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DEPRESSION WALK -- Almost every day for the past three
months, someone has stopped Stuart Perry on the road, wanting to
talk about depression. Since May, Perry has walked on back roads
from Georgia to Chicago talking about depression to anyone who
would listen. He began his trek to educate people about the
devastating illness and to give hope about treatment. (Miller,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ANTIOXIDENTS GAIN RESPECT -- An increasing number of
people believe that antioxidants _ certain vitamins, minerals and
plant-based chemicals _ are the key to maintaining health if you
live in a city with high levels of air pollution and other toxic
chemicals. (Kennedy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MANATEE _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Manatees aren't too slow or stupid
to get out of the way of boats; they just can't hear them, says a
Florida Atlantic University scientist whose research into sea cow
acoustics is getting international attention. Edmund Gerstein's
research shows that manatees evolved to hear only high-pitched
sounds, not the low rumble of boat propellers. His solution: he's
developed an ultra-high pitched warning beacon that boaters could
stick to their hulls. He recently published his research in an
international acoustics journal. The British magazine New Scientist
just ran a blurb on it, causing his phone to ring off the hook.
(King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
