<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD07-COX     08-06 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New woodworking book is basic, but not best
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Taunton Press is once again demonstrating one of
its most remarkable aptitudes, that of creative literary recycling.
</P>
<P>
   The publishers of Fine Woodworking magazine let very few
articles go unreprinted; they have put out several series of
softcover books, gathering under specific headings a number of
compatible and complementary articles published over a period of
years.
</P>
<P>
   I've just received the first two in what I assume will be
another lengthy series with the overall designation of Essentials
of Woodworking.
</P>
<P>
   These are ``The Basics of Craftsmanship'' and ``Ingenious Jigs
and Shop Accessories.'' Taunton is reinventing the wheel, so to
speak, with both of these; it already has at least one book on shop
jigs and several on basic woodworking. Nonetheless, at least the
first of these books will be of interest to many less experienced
woodworkers and they are reasonably priced at $17.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basics of Craftsmanship'' is broken into six parts _ setting
up a shop, materials, tools, techniques, projects and finishing.
</P>
<P>
   The section on setting up a shop will be of particular interest
to the beginner, although the ``How to Buy Used Hand Tools''
article is somewhat questionable. Used hand tools, in my
experience, are either woefully abused or antiques or both.
</P>
<P>
   An article on buying hardwood lumber will answer a lot of the
newcomers' questions, and so will one on sandpaper. The tools
section is useful, although it does not cover the entire range of
tools; the techniques section is good as far as it goes but it
doesn't cover that most basic of all woodworking joints, the
mortise and tenon.
</P>
<P>
   What the beginner really wants to buy first is another Taunton
Press book, the one that established it as a pioneer in the field _
the first volume of Tage Frid's trilogy. It's called ``Tage Frid
Teaches Woodworking: Joinery _ Tools and Techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the best book on woodworking ever published. It is
eminently readable; I really have never been sure whether Tage Frid
made the book or the book made Tage Frid. I got to know this truly
great man after the book was published, and I can assure you that
reading the book is exactly like listening to him talk.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't go so far as to say it's the only book on woodworking
you'll ever want or need, but I will assure you that if you read it
carefully and keep it by your bench, you will be able to build just
about any piece of furniture you desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Basics of Craftsmanship'' can serve as a useful
augmentation to Frid's work, but it won't replace it. I doubt
anything ever will.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ingenious Jigs'' book is not another one of those tiresome
books for people who would rather spend their shoptime making shop
knicknacks than furniture. It deals primarily with major jigs such
as sliding crosscut sleds for the table saw, router tables and the
like. It's certainly worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
