<HEADER>
A8029 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-LEFTBEHIND06-CO     08-06 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LEFTBEHIND06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jenkins inspires with stories of `the Rapture'
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a counselor at a Christian camp, Jerry Jenkins
relished opportunities to entertain and inspire his young minions
with stories of ``the Rapture,'' the time, many Christians believe,
when the faithful will be called into heaven leaving those on Earth
to deal with the end-times.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jenkins, 49, is co-author of a series of novels that has
enthralled the reading public with that same story, embellished and
updated.
</P>
<P>
   The series started in 1995 with ``Left Behind,'' which opened
with Capt. Rayford Steele flying a 747 across the Atlantic when
more than 100 of his passengers disappeared _ as, he learned later,
did his wife and son. In fact, millions of people all over the
globe vanished. Steele, his daughter and Buck Williams, a senior
writer for a newsmagazine, are Left Behind.
</P>
<P>
   This week, book six in the series, ``Assassins,'' hit bookstores
with an advance printing of 850,000 copies. ``Left Behind'' sales
are nearing 2 million, and ``Tribulation Force'' (1996) and
``Nicolae'' (1997) have each topped 1 million in sales. ``Soul
Harvest'' (1998) is a few sales shy of a million; ``Apollyon''
(1999) has sold more than 850,000. There are also ``Left Behind''
books for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apollyon'' hit both The New York Times and the Publishers
Weekly list of best sellers for the general market. ``That's
unprecedented for a Christian novel,'' said Lynn Garrett, religion
editor of Publishers Weekly, a book industry trade magazine.
Garrett attributes the accomplishment to the success of the
previous books and to savvy marketing by publisher Tyndale House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the books have had appeal beyond the usual
audience,'' said Garrett. ``They're being read by people who aren't
evangelical Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins will be in metro Atlanta today and Saturday for signings
at two bookstores, one Christian, one secular.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Brown, a community relations manager for Barnes &AMP; Noble in
Morrow, said the store invited the author because ``these are
enormously popular books. We're excited about his coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown read ``Left Behind'' in preparation for Jenkins' visit and
said she will probably read more. ``You get hooked on the series,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Store manager Emily Gulledge, 46, got hooked and read them all.
``Even if they didn't have the religious content, they would be
interesting books,'' said Gulledge, who says she was raised
Southern Baptist and has attended several different kinds of
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my wife fight over who's going to read them first,''
said aircraft mechanic Bob Brown, 41, who lives in Milner and
attends Fairview Baptist Church in Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   For Jenkins, successful books are nothing new. He's written more
than 130 volumes, including co-authoring memoirs for Billy Graham,
Nolan Ryan and Orel Hershiser. His ``'Twas the Night Before,'' a
secular Christmas novel from Viking, has been sold to CBS for a
movie next year and he has a new Christian novel, ``Though None Go
With Me,'' due out from Zondervan in January. For readers who want
to keep up with it all, he also has a website:
www.jerryjenkins.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Left Behind'' books are the result of a match made by a
literary agent, Rick Christian of Alive Communications. Co-author
Tim LaHaye, a Bible prophecy expert, author of several non-fiction
Christian books, and part of a power evangelical partnership with
wife Beverly, founder of Concerned Women For America, had an idea:
a modern-day account of the events of the book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that appealed to me about the project is that Tim
didn't want to ... help write it,'' said Jenkins. ``He provides the
prophetic chart and sequence of events. He serves as the expert on
prophecy. And he's proven to be a great cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who was born and raised in a Christian home in
Kalamazoo, Mich., and spent his teenage years in Chicago, said he
``had always believed the way LaHaye did, although I wouldn't have
been able to justify it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said he felt good about the first ``Left Behind'' book
and thought it might sell as many as 200,000 copies. ``I didn't
tell too many people that,'' he said. ``It doesn't sound good to
predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the phenomenal sales of ``Left Behind'' and its sequels,
Jenkins says, ``It's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to what he attributes the success, Jenkins answers, ``The
great writing,'' but quickly adds, ``no, I'm just kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dr. LaHaye has it right,'' Jenkins said. ``Revelation
is so difficult to understand that by fictionalizing it, people are
fascinated. I think that's part of it. I think there's also a
general hunger for spiritual things in the market place. Look at
'Celestine Prophecy' and other New Age-type things. People seem to
be drawn to those. We feel like we get a chance to throw our answer
into the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he and LaHaye are splitting millions in royalities,
``my life really hasn't changed much materially,'' said Jenkins,
who lives in Colorado Springs. ``I was raised in a tradition where
you're not comfortable with great amounts of income. We look for
places to use it for good because the Bible sort of teaches that
wealth can be a dangerous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is a bit uncomfortable with the financial riches the books
have brought, he thoroughly enjoys the visibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen people read my books on airplanes before,'' he
said. And as for book signings and public appearances, ``I really
love that part of it,'' he said. ``Writing is such a solitary
profession, I think it's good to get out and meet people. I've had
my share of those autograph parties where three people show up and
two of them are relatives. I kind of enjoy the crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOK SIGNINGS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Noon-2 p.m. today, Berean Christian Store, 441 Cleveland Ave.,
Atlanta. 404-767-7514
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1-2 p.m. Saturday, Barnes &AMP; Noble Booksellers, 1939 Mount Zion
Road, Morrow, Ga. 770-471-8483
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
