<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RECESS (Washington) _ With its tax cut behind it,
Congress left for its August recess today setting the stage for a
high stakes autumn confrontation with President Clinton over what
should be the nation's fiscal policies in an era of budget
surpluses. That battle is the most far-reaching of many
ideologically charged policy disputes to come in the fall, also
setting the stage for a high stakes election battle. Other issues
on the agenda for the fall are health care, gun control, campaign
finance reform and the question now is whether there will be a
season of compromise or continued partisan strife. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   NEV-NUKE-WASTE (Washington) _ The Energy Department releases a
draft Environmental Impact Statement that says that Yucca Mountain,
100 miles from Las Vegas, would be fine for nuclear waste storage
for the next 10,000 years. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ARK (Little Rock) _ President Clinton's day, including
comments on the drought. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-WIFE-DRUGS (New York) _ The wife of an Army colonel
involved in U.S. counternarcotics operations in Colombia is facing
federal charges of shipping large amounts of cocaine to the United
States earlier this year. The woman, Laurie Hiett, is the wife of
Army Col. James Hiett, who at the time was in charge of all U.S.
military activities in Colombia, including counterdrug operations.
By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Feature one year after the
embassy bombings. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CHRISTIANS (New Delhi) _ Indian Government issues summary
of report on killing in January of Australian missionary and his
children. Government says report absolves the governing Hindu
nationalist party of inciting the anti-Christian violence. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   IRA-GUNS (Dublin) _ The IRA denies involvement in a recent
gun-running plot and punishment killing. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FRANKEL-DEALS (Undated) _ A feature on the complex dealings of
Martin R. Frankel, the fugitive Connecticut money manager, accused
of stealing $350 million in insurance company money. By Joseph Kahn
and Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The United States economy generated
many more new jobs in July than economists and Wall Street had
expected, in a report likely to fan worries of higher interest
rates. The Labor Department said that non-farm payrolls rose
310,000 in July, leaving the unemployment rate unchanged at 4.3
percent. The report also showed that wages rose 6 cents, or 0.5
percent _ the biggest increase in average hourly earnings in seven
months. Stock and bonds fell sharply at the opening but recovered
in early trading. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-FRAUD-ASSESS (New York) _ A news analysis of the Bear
Stearns case. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-ONE2ONE (London) _ Deutsche Telekom buys British
cellular company One 2 One for $11 billion, in its first major
expansion outside of Germany. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   FED-APPOINT (Undated) _ President Clinton nominates Roger W.
Ferguson Jr. as vice chairman of the Federal Reserve, and will send
the nomination to Congress today.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-BRITAIN (London) _ IBM confirms reports that British tax
authorities are investigating its accounts, amid allegations that
the company avoided paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO-SCANIA (London) _ Volvo has offered to buy Swedish rival
Scania AB for $7.4 billion, strengthening Volvo's truck business in
Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   GM-DAEWOO (Tokyo) _ General Motors signs an agreement to
intensify discussions aimed at forming an alliance with the Daewoo
Motor Co., the core of South Korea's struggling Daewoo Group. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANK (Singapore) _ Indonesia's Government is
investigating allegations that an official at the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency, the agency in charge of an estimated $35
billion bailout of Indonesia's banks, helped engineer millions of
dollars in payments to a businessman with connections to the
country's ruling elite. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ The ruling Liberal Democratic Party says
it will not pressure the Bank of Japan to buy Japanese Government
bonds that are likely to be issued to finance further fiscal
stimulus programs. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
