</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARBAGE-$ADV08-COX     08-06 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATES FEAR FLOOD OF NEW YORK GARBAGE
 &HT;    1150&AMP;add. With GARBAGE-OHIO. For release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The effect of New York City's decision to close its
Fresh Kills landfill, a 50-year-old, 3,000-acre mound of garbage on
Staten Island, is spreading through neighboring states like a bad
smell.
</P>
<P>
   Without Fresh Kills, which is scheduled to close Dec. 31, 2001,
the only way the city can get rid of the 13,000 tons of residential
garbage it generates every day is by shipping it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki search for
fresh fields for garbage now going to Fresh Kills _ the largest
active landfill on Earth _ state officials as far south as North
Carolina and as far west as Ohio and Indiana wait nervously.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing convoys of big trucks loaded with what rots and stinks
from New York, state legislatures are passing laws to ban or
restrict out-of-state garbage _ and bills have been introduced in
Congress to overturn a Supreme Court decision declaring such state
laws unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate bill, introduced by a first-term Republican, George
Voinovich of Ohio, has been assigned to the Environment and Natural
Resources Committee, whose chairman has expressed strong
reservations about the bill. Voinovich says he still hopes the
panel will approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the pending collision between a garbage stream that
cannot be turned off and an adamant ``not here'' reaction to it is
forcing new dialogues about the way America looks at waste, and may
be providing a preview of future garbage wars.
</P>
<P>
   Various interests swirl around garbage like the seagulls, crows,
starlings and pigeons that hang out at Fresh Kills. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Private garbage haulers and landfill operators, including two
of the largest companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Environmentalists, who think they perceive in the crisis
circumstances that could decisively favor one of their movement's
fondest dreams, recycling.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York officials like Giuliani, who inherited the problem in
a city that has a history of responding to garbage problems with ad
hoc solutions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Neighborhood officials, such as Staten Island Borough
President Guy Molinari, who is adamant that Fresh Kills, which
opened in 1948 as a ``temporary'' solution to an earlier solid
waste crisis, be closed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Federal environmental officials, equally determined that the
city keep its 2001 commitment to close the landfill, which lacks a
lining to contain liquid runoff.
</P>
<P>
   _ State officials, such as the Republican governors of New
Jersey, Pennsylvania and Virginia, all of whom have engaged in
angry exchanges with New York's Republican mayor over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Local officials, such as those in Charles City County, Va.,
which has enjoyed an infusion of revenue in the form of ``host
fees'' from a 934-acre landfill owned by America's largest trash
hauler, Waste Management Inc. of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Chandler, county administrator of Charles City County, said
the modern, federally approved, lined landfill is a welcome
addition to his county, primarily because of the revenue it
produces.
</P>
<P>
   The landfill is the largest business in the county of 7,000
people, Chandler said. Since it opened in 1990, it has provided a
stream of revenue that allowed the predominantly black county to
build a state-of-the-art school complex, with elementary, middle
and high schools, while cutting property taxes 44 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of where we are today was seen as a very
good thing in the '80s,'' Chandler said. ``Regulated landfills were
actually promoted by the state back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the garbage that has subsequently come to Charles City
County originated in New York, where Waste Management and other
haulers collect a daily load of commercial waste roughly equal to
the 13,000 daily tons of residential garbage that goes to Fresh
Kills. The commercial garbage is already trucked out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Charles City County landfill is one of seven ``megafills''
in Virginia, all of them owned either by Waste Management or the
country's second largest garbage company, the yet unnamed entity
that would result from the pending merger of Browning Ferris
Industries of Houston and Allied Waste Industries of Scottsdale,
Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating new business from the Fresh Kills closing, Waste
Management has received county permission to build special garbage
barge docks at Port Tobacco on the James River.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gov. James Gilmore, who like other state officials
supported the waste industry in the early 1990s when the seven
large landfills were built and who has received significant
campaign support from the industry, ordered the state attorney
general to oppose construction of the port in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   So far, courts have ruled that the state's opposition to the
port is an effort to ban or restrict the flow of out-of-state
garbage. In a 1993 ruling, the Supreme Court declared that garbage
shipments were protected from state interference by the
Constitution's interstate commerce clause, which reserves to
Congress the authority to regulate commerce between states.
</P>
<P>
   Bills introduced in the House and Senate would delegate this
authority to states, as far as garbage is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The measures resemble bills that have been introduced in each of
the past several years. Ironically, the chief obstacle to passage
has been Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House Commerce
Committee and a close friend and ally of Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a pretty good chance of it this time,''
Voinovich said. ``The environment has changed significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich said that when he became governor of Ohio eight years
ago, that state was importing around 3.7 million tons of garbage a
year, most of it from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the largest garbage importer is Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   For collecting and hauling off commercial refuse, New York
already pays about $57 a ton, and although contracts for handling
the residential waste haven't been signed, most expectations are
that the cost will easily exceed $60 a ton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, environmentalists say the net cost of recycling
materials like metal, glass and plastic _ a process that brings in
less revenue than it costs _ is going down in New York. The city
already sells more than 130,000 tons of waste paper a year to a
newly opened paper recycling mill on Staten Island, and another
paper plant is planned in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the next five years or so, it's likely that despite the
inevitable start-up costs, recycling and landfilling will be on a
cost par with one another, and that's not environmental
poppycock,'' said Eric Goldstein, an attorney in the New York
office of the National Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge for the 21st century will not be whose
landfills get filled up first, but how to accelerate the shift to
recycling, reusing and recovering that will benefit the nation as a
whole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein and others think the dilemma closing in on Guiliani
may force New York to lead the way in making that shift.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the method, Staten Island wants Fresh Kills closed.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1948 as a temporary way to deal with garbage that was
spilling out of small, waterfront dumps, the landfill became so
large that the Statue of Liberty could be buried upright in it with
25 feet of garbage on top of her upreaching arm.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nicholas Dmytryszyn(cq), environmental engineer and
consultant to borough president Molinari, by the seventh day of
every calendar year the landfill generates enough air pollution to
be in violation of the federal Clean Air Act for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous flow of methane gas is collected and flared, and
eventually it will be added to natural gas used by New York's gas
utility, Brooklyn Union Gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dmytryszyn said he was skeptical about the prospects for
recycling to significantly reduce the New York waste stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are great differences between our understanding of
reality and that of the environmental groups,'' he said. ``They
tend to take the position that if you recycle, businesses will come
in and set up technologies to use the materials.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it is done, he said, Staten Island wants Fresh Kills
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This landfill has been operating too long illegally and we
want it shut down,'' he said. ``It is a quality-of-life debacle on
this island.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Young, an assistant New York santitation commissioner, said
the city will close Fresh Kills on time, and that will mean
exporting thousands of tons of garbage a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York City Department of Sanitation, before entering
into a contract to export garbage, checks that our garbage is
delivered to a licensed and permitted facility that also has a host
community agreement,'' she said. ``That's wherever our garbage
goes. And anyone who is exporting our garbage knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recycling? I wish we could recycle everything we throw away,''
she said. ``However, I can drink a soda in a plastic bottle and
throw it in the recycling bin, but if there's not a company that is
willing to to pick it up, there's not going to be any recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ultimate solution, she said, one principle will
endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garbage will always win,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARBAGE-OHIO-$ADV08-C     08-06 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-OHIO-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOINOVICH SEES 'PRETTY GOOD CHANCE' OF LIMITING GARBAGE
SHIPMENTS
 &HT;    With GARBAGE. For release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, spoke with Jeff
Nesmith of the Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau about the politics
of garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you became governor, the state (of Ohio) was already
receiving a lot of waste.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it was as high as 3.7 million tons. (It was coming from)
New Jersey and New York, but primarily New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did it decrease while you were governor?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think one of the reasons is that some of the waste outfits
tried to be responsive to our requests and we kind of encouraged
them to not take out-of-state waste. Maybe it became easier to send
it someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the June hearing of the Senate Environment and Natural
Resources Committee on your bill, Sen. John Chafee, (R-R.I.,
chairman of the committee) expressed pretty strong reservations
about any bill that would impose these kind of restrictions on
interstate commerce. What are the chances you'll even get it out of
his committee?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think we have a pretty good chance, actually. Now
that John Warner (R-Va.) is interested in it, that enhances our
opportunity. He's putting a whole lot of pressure on John Chafee to
get a bill out.
</P>
<P>
   My staff is working with Warner's to come up with kind of a
compromise piece of legislation that we can agree on and use that
as the basis for a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some of the areas you expect to be compromising on?
</P>
<P>
   A: The staff has been working on it, and I don't know. Our bill
goes farther than Warner's.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the House, Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-Va., chairman of the
House Commerce Committee) has traditionally opposed this kind of
legislation. Is there any reason to think that will change?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the environment has changed significantly. For
example, we had a real difficult time convincing Tom Bliley when I
was governor. I don't think he was interested in at that stage
because they weren't getting so much in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   I think that he's a lot more interested in it now, because there
are a lot of people raising hell about this thing in his state. I
think he realizes that something's got to be done. He understands
as well as we do that when Fresh Kills closes, there's going to be
something like 13,200 tons of garbage each day that are going to be
diverted to other facilities. I think he realizes his state of
Virginia is going to be on the list of places to take it.
</P>
<P>
   You are talking about an additional 4 million tons a year going
someplace, and that has gotten the attention of a lot of people
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much are you concerned about the solid waste industry
lobby?
</P>
<P>
   A: I hope that they realize that there's a problem out there and
what we're suggesting is reasonable. It gives a lot of options to
states. It doesn't close the door unless a state wants to. They
have good relations with state legislatures. States can't ban new
facilities (under the bill), but they can require than no more than
20 percent comes in from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   This is not some kind of draconian piece of legislation that
will shut them out. What it will do is bring some reason to this
and, frankly, it may force New York state to come to grips with the
fact that they haven't done a very good job of dealing with their
own problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of providing more landfills?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. In Ohio, we realized that we had a problem and we
started to close down the ones that weren't environmentally sound
and they started to build other ones that really are about the best
you can get. For some reason, the political leadership in New York
just hasn't had the fortitude to understand that they have a
responsibility to take care of the good part of their own waste.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
