<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CROWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING THE `GQ' LIFE IN THE `THOMAS CROWN AFFAIR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever she can, insurance investigator Catherine Banning (Rene
Russo) refers to Thomas Crown (Pierce Brosnan), her billionaire
playboy prey, as ``Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   The boyish nickname is part tool of reductive seduction, part
nominal territory-marking, part Banning's way of informing Crown
that she doesn't take his smooth-operator comportment seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But in the context of John McTiernan's designer makeover of
Norman Jewison's 1968 ``Thomas Crown Affair,'' the only person I
really could think of is that other Tommy _ the one who makes
several lines of clothes Thomas Crown likely would deem too urban
for his more uptown and, yes, urbane taste. But it's a tacit,
coincidental fashion allusion in a film stylized to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   While purporting to be about a fortysomething corporate
money-bags who gets off on nabbing his favorite paintings, and the
woman trying to nab him, ``TC '99'' is a GQ-W magazine team-up, a
fashion-spread sex story _ not at all disguised as a heist caper _
about a clothes-horse and his mare. Against all odds, the cat falls
for the mouse and jet-setting ensues. Of course, McTiernan (``Die
Hard'') imagines the whole affair to be a sexy way of persuading a
pair of chic yuppies to get over themselves.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Eyes Wide Shut'' and the upcoming adaptation of Chuck
Palahniuk's ``Fight Club,'' about apathetic young metropolitan
suits who turn to refereed death matches to ``feel something,'' the
upper crust is in crisis, afflicted with restlessness and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Cruise visits an orgiastic secret society on Long Island,
Tommy Crown stuffs a Metropolitan Museum of Art Monet in a hi-tech
briefcase that you should expect Coach to offer in the fall. The
boy can't help it.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Thomas Crown'' finds a less pretentious way of sating
hedonistic desire _ namely by doing away with that inane fauxrotic
chess-playing business between Steve McQueen and Faye Dunaway in
the original and going directly for the horizontal gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Crown and Banning have movie sex on every surface in his
Manhattan brownstone, from the marble staircase to a mahogany desk
from which all the dog-eared books and mags are wiped to the floor.
The film wants you to believe that these are a couple of
have-it-alls charged by the multifold meanings of mergers and
acquisitions. But what starts coming into McTiernan's film that was
irrelevant in Jewison's is a sense that Crown and Banning find
compatibility in their middle-aged miseries.
</P>
<P>
   McTiernan's film mines what substance it has from its two stars,
but is admittedly about keeping up its own appearances. ``Thomas
Crown's'' dizzying, cool finale multiplies the guy with the bowler
hat from a Magritte painting into a sea of Savile Row extras
through which Crown attempts to replace his booty. Composer Tom
Conti's hand claps and toe taps intertwine with Nina Simone's
gospel-soul arrangement of ``Sinnerman,'' and the film reaches its
cumulative watershed _ a clever, sexy, mildly inane engrossment.
Like Bruce Wayne et al., Crown, who made it to Oxford on a boxing
scholarship, lives alone (read: single, with suspiciously
omniscient butler), and his mid-40s bachelor status makes him
eccentric (read: a sociopath who wants to be caught).
</P>
<P>
   He owns a Magritte and babysits Monets, selecting ``San Giorgio
Maggiore Soleil'' for his booty. (And, in a Madison Avenue revision
of McTiernan's ``Die Hard'' and ``Hunt for Red October''
sensibilities, Crown steals the piece amid a clan of Romanians
pulling their own Metropolitan heist. It's another romanticization
of '80s-style movie theft, with these art-nappers treated with the
menace usually reserved for terrorists.)
</P>
<P>
   Crown also visits a shrink, played by Dunaway, to discuss his
intimacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Brosnan merely could have have glided along on the oily panache
he oozes as James Bond or used to secrete as Remington Steele, but
Crown's arrogance is a front for his chronic discontent, which
Brosnan inhabits with a flaneur's aimless lassitude.
</P>
<P>
   It takes Russo about 20 minutes to appear, but it's as if the
film can smell her coming and hardly can wait for her to get there.
Tom Priestly's photography catches the vapors trying to capture
her, melting in and out around her as if the whole enterprise were
about to go weak in the knees. Russo's decked out in freshly
tousled burnt-umber bedhead and adult contemporary couture (ranging
from scintillating to sinful), as though she couldn't decide who
she most adored _ Ann-Margret, Angie Dickinson or Tina Louise.
</P>
<P>
   She's a feline hybrid of the three, infusing the experiment in
cosmetic amalgamation with enough sophisticated stardust to make it
clear that she's busting loose from her arm-candy status.
</P>
<P>
   Banning gets to be jealous of the Euro toy (supermodelicious
Esther Canadas, with an expletitive-laced evil eye) Crown is
spotted with. And there's also enough girlish glee in Russo to
rescue her from being the preening vamp Banning could have been.
</P>
<P>
   Russo also saves herself from some of the more unintentionally
farcical things she's made to wear. An oversized alabaster parka
and one XL turtleneck come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Even Denis Leary _ at his most irascible, brittle and
susceptible to emotion as the jealous NYPD detective working with
Banning _ has a tough time resisting a smirk. Though his character
has a Today's Man air about him that, under these circumstances,
makes him a fashion emergency with a badge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
