<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MYSTERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOT MILK? NO, IT'S `MYSTERY MEN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' is an opulent farce teeming with idiosyncratic
nonsense and directed by Kinka Usher as though all the scrapbooks
of commercials he's done entitled him to come up with something
this visionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' doesn't aspire to the heights the Wachowski
brothers were trying to climb with ``The Matrix,'' but then it's
not saddled with the marketing hurdle that once was Keanu, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's too preoccupied with maintaining the self-respect of its
participants, but exactly the embarrassing hipper-than-thou pop
traffic-jam the trailers and television spots make it out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassment is something the film seems programmed to avoid.
``Mystery Men'' thinks it's cool _ Usher lets the ad-libs and
improvs fly. But Usher wants it to be (slightly) more than a
collection of Gen-X trading cards of Ben Stiller, Janeane Garofalo,
William H. Macy, Kel Mitchell, Hank Azaria and Paul Reubens.
</P>
<P>
   This spin-off from Bob Burden's ``Flaming Carrot'' comics didn't
need these people to grace it with their coffeehouse-street-cred
verve, but that's part of the film's
``hey-let's-make-a-Hollywood-movie'' self-consciousness. Usher and
Co. aren't peddling cynicism so much as they're looking for
sardonic ways of saying ``I like myself'' without committing to
anything real enough to get them called sellouts and evicted from
The Garden of Indie.
</P>
<P>
   The film, written with a perpetual smirk by Neil Cuthbert,
revolves around a band of struggling blue-collar superheroes
looking for their big break into superstardom like their arrogant
idol, Captain Amazing (Greg Kinnear). He's the Batman of Champion
City, and like the products endorsed _ Ray-O-Vac batteries, for
instance _ on his NASCAR-biker costume (courtesy of designer
Marilyn Vance's inspired Goodwill-hunting), his services have
gotten old. But that's because he's either destroyed or
incarcerated every foe in town, and, in an inspired whiff of
jokiness, he's reduced himself to taking out assembly-line villains
who attack nursing homes as though they were bum-rushing a Gotham
City debutante ball.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate sponsors want to drop him, so, disguised as his
alter ego, Lance Hunt _ whom no one recognizes behind his
horn-rimmed glasses _ Amazing shows up at the 17th parole hearing
of his archest enemy, Casanova Frankenstein (Geoffrey Rush, doing
Klaus Kinski gone Studio 54), and gets him released, only to try to
lock him up again. Amazing's plan backfires and Frankenstein holds
him hostage, allowing Frank and his disco henchmen to ransack the
city.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of depressed pals _ whose powers range from the ability
to get uselessly angry (Stiller) to the gifts of wielding a shovel
(Macy) and kitchen utensils (Azaria) _ seize Amazing's kidnapping
as the occasion for their coming out. They wind up reluctantly
enlisting a guy called the Spleen (Reubens), whose power is his
silent-but-deadly gas, and a black teen called Invisible Boy
(Mitchell), who, in an inversion of Ralph Ellison's assertion,
believes that if no one's looking at him, he can't be seen.
</P>
<P>
   This downtrodden justice league's big score comes in the form of
a head case called The Bowler (Garofalo), whose bowling ball is
possessed by her father, whose skull is encased there.
</P>
<P>
   By the time The Sphinx (Wes Studi) gets the gang to attend his
Yoda-esque ``Iron John''-for-self-esteemless-superheroes woodland
getaway, Usher's mocked the fact that these guys can't do anything
right. But he admires their scrappy determination, rewarding the
cast, particularly Garofalo, by keeping the one-liners bouncing off
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   The film obviously hates the blond, blue-eyed Amazing and how
his corporate-sponsored lifestyle has warped Champion City as much
as protected it: Why would anyone ever want to emulate Amazing,
when instead he could be part of their own multicultural
crime-fighting force that can stop selling out in a single leap and
bound?
</P>
<P>
   That's a bemusing paradox from the television visionary who made
``Got Milk?'' ads and that Nissan spot with Barbie, Ken and Van
Halen's ``You Really Got Me.'' One of ``Mystery Men's'' most
hilarious qualities is the way it turns its nose up at success and
unmitigated contentment as if a sneer were preferable to a smile
and having your best fringe buddies around you were enough to keep
the hounds of lost integrity at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if crimes of crass commercialism are what the Mystery Men
are after _ I can see them going after villains like Star Buck or
the Tower Recorder or the Golden Arch in a sequel _ the gang would
be advised to first recruit David Arquette as Quirk, Parker Posey
as The JAP and Ben Affleck as The Ex-boyfriend, then head West to
fight cell phones and criminally overpriced espressos at Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
