<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ILLUMINATA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL TRICKS AND LITTLE MAGIC IN `ILLUMINATA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagined as a love song to his wife about the strength of their
marriage, John Turturro's ``Illuminata'' uses the theater to craft
a flimsy version of ``The Ballad of John and Yoko.''
</P>
<P>
   But for better or worse, the wife, Kathryn Borowitz, is no Ono,
and the ensemble piece _ about the serious/screwball antics
revolving around a playwright's (Turturro) unfinished work _ that
she's nestled into is robbed of the vitality, wryness, wit, depth
and passion it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1900s New York, ``Illuminata'' was co-written and
directed by Turturro, and neither ideology nor plot nor his wife,
for that matter, seems to be what's inspiring Turturro to work,
here _ it's directing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film takes place on a boundless stage _ conceived
and designed by Robin Standefer, Donna Zakowska and Roman Paska _
that looks as if it's in the process of being both constructed and
razed.
</P>
<P>
   And between several scene transitions and during the opening
credits, a puppet sequence designed and performed by Paska is more
alluring and achingly sensual than most of the interactions between
humans.
</P>
<P>
   Music video cinematographer Harris Savides frames shots with
painterly diligence. He also supplies the film with so much of the
blue that most of the action looks as though it's unfolding in
Atlantis _ with Christopher Walken, Susan Sarandon and Ben Gazzara
splashing around in it.
</P>
<P>
   Borowitz, as an actress, doesn't seem enchanted with the beauty
undulating around her. She's pensive, churning and too focused on
the bad dialogue and frissons of profundity, as if she's trying to
make sense of the artificiality of her surroundings. She, as well
as the rest of the cast, would've benefited by having drunk more of
whatever was in the mermaidenly Georgina Cates' water.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro tricks you into thinking there's magic realism
streaming through this ode to art and committed love _ despite
there being little magic and not a trace of reality to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
