<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING OF AGE IN `MY LIFE SO FAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes an out-of-touch kids-find-sex movie can be quaint in
its need to pretend that yesterday is better than now _ or that
yesterday is a lot like now. For instance, those little girls
learning that their Miss Jean Brodie was a prime specimen of lust
was precious.
</P>
<P>
   But ``My Life So Far,'' by ``Chariots of Fire'' director Hugh
Hudson, is neither a reminiscent throwback nor mild allegory, it's
a willfully turgid demonstration that if a filmmaker puts his mind
to it he can tell a tale about a boy sexually coming of age as if
the birds, bees and educated fleas were the only one's doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the childhood memoirs of British television
mogul Dennis Forman, but produced by the occasionally
thrill-seeking David Puttnam (``Midnight Express,'' ``Cal''). Did
he think was making the United Kingdom answer to last year's
``Permanent Midnight,'' the Ben Stiller vehicle about heroin-fiend
TV writer Jerry Stahl. The more innocent ``My Life So Far'' is one
of those indulgent little U.K. adventures in which the kid knows
more about the nasty than the grownups who feign belief in storks
and immaculate conceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged as a toddler by his father (Colin Firth) to
communicate in ``dog'' and surrounded by a bunch of uptight
geriatrics like matronly Gamma (Rosemary Harris), Fraser was raised
in the '20s in a manner Wilson and screenwriter Simon Donald would
have you believe is eccentric. It's an era when impure thoughts are
detectable and _ psst! _ ``incorrigible.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Fraser's philandering inventor father (played by a
squandered-again Firth) and his attempt to seduce his French
sister-in-law (Irene Jacob) without alienating his wife (Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio) would have been vaguely more watchable were
they seen through Hudson's eyes and not Fraser's. Though the value
of what they both would witness would have been interchangeably
dull.
</P>
<P>
   But Hudson gets more than a piffling performance from Norman,
who spends the film looking like he's entered its prudish Scottish
environs through the Phantom Tollboth and would probably rather be
getting to know Gamma's apple pie than Gamma herself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
