<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-SENSE-HNS     08-06 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUNNING, FEAR UNITE IN `THE SIXTH SENSE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' sneaks up on you _ slowly, on tip-toe,
slinking up the cellar stairs until it's hovering right behind you,
hissing down your neck. Then it pounces. And when it pounces,
you'll find yourself reeling from the craftiest, most tub-thumping
jerk of a plot twist since Jaye Davison got personal in ``The
Crying Game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all we'll say about it. That's all anyone ought to say
about ``The Sixth Sense,'' a cunning paranormal thriller about a
boy who sees dead people and the child psychiatrist who tries to
help him.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that its premise is an unoriginal rehash of every
spooky-kid movie since ``The Shining'' _ and the fact that yet
another spooky-kid movie, the smartly acted ``Stir of Echoes,'' is
due for release next month _ only adds to the surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a movie about a child with supernatural powers can indeed
be an intelligent, chilling, trim and nuanced film. It can also be
the vehicle for a terrifyingly apt performance by 11-year-old Haley
Joel Osment, who played Forrest Gump Jr. and here delivers the most
precocious (and prodigious) thespian feat of the summer. That it
pops up in a film of minimal hype by a virtually unknown
writer-director (M. Night Shyamalan, who made the equally mystical
but far inferior ``Wide Awake,'' released last year) gives one
faith in the caprice of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis is Malcolm Crowe, a prosperous Philadelphia shrink
with a palatial home and a wife (Olivia Williams) on the verge of
feeling ignored. One night, while the pair are kvelling over a
shiny new award, a lathering ex-patient named Vincent Gray (Donnie
Wahlberg, freakish and unrecognizable) bursts into their bedroom
and starts howling about futile psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know so many things!'' he yells. ``Do you know why
you're afraid when you're alone? I do. I do.'' Then, after accusing
Malcolm of failure, he shoots the doctor in the gut and kills
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jump ahead to the next fall. Malcolm is outside the home of Cole
Sear (seer _ get it?), a worried, jitter-riddled boy who scoots
down the street as if he's being chased. Dutifully, the doctor
reads from his notes: 9 years old, divorced parents, anxiety
problems, possible mood disorder. Malcolm follows Cole into a
church, where the boy plays with toy soldiers in the sanctuary of a
pew. There they begin the psychological pas de deux that marks
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, seeing in Cole a chance to redeem his failure with
Vincent, tries to nudge him into confessing his secrets. He plays
games, does goofy magic tricks, intuits truths about the boy's
parents. But the boy keeps his ghosts to himself, allowing the film
to focus not on Cole's spectral visitors _ which aren't seen until
the second hour _ but on the terror they bring to his face.
</P>
<P>
   In this the movie is similar to the paranoiac ``Blair Witch
Project,'' which emphasizes the fruits of fear rather than its
cause. Unlike that film, ``The Sixth Sense'' does deliver the
ghouls, and they're damned scary when they appear. But scarier
still is the ravaged vigilance in Cole's sad face, his eyes as wise
and worn as a tired old man's.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of the movie's scenes are one-on-ones between
doctor and patient, thoughtfully scripted sequences that emphasize
the humanity, and the pain, on both sides: It isn't long before
Cole is counseling Malcolm on how to communicate with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Willis, as those who loathed ``Moonlighting'' will be relieved
to learn, has permanently deep-sixed his squint. His face has
become gaunt and block-like with age, and more honest; his acting
is as clear and uncluttered as it once was tic-ish. Toni Collette
drums up compassion in her small role as Cole's struggling mom,
adding believable pathos to Cole's battered home life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' has its weak points (there are plot holes
that loom ever larger on reflection), but none is serious enough to
collapse the framework. Because Shyamalan's script is so narrow in
its focus (boy, shrink, mom, wife, ghosts), he gets away without
the busybody bosses and nattering sidekicks that normally clutter
movies about patients and shrinks. It's a film about fear _ Cole's
_ and regret _ Malcolm's. The cadaverous ghosts are secondary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
