<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSEDGE-LANG-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANG ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The sixth game of the 1996 World Series was one of the high
points of Ilene Lang's career _ literally. That was the year of the
AltaVista blimp, a great airship that hung above Yankee Stadium,
silhouetted against the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Lang ran AltaVista, the Internet software business
unit of the old Digital Equipment Corp. She and her colleagues had
decided to lease a blimp to raise the profile of the AltaVista
Internet search service, but they'd never expected quite so high a
profile.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodyear blimp had been damaged in a storm, and the Fox
Network, which televised the game, was desperate for an aerial
camera platform. Out went the call for a blimp. Lang was happy to
oblige, and 20 million baseball fans were introduced to the
AltaVista brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was so new,'' she recalls. ``We started getting press,
and it brought more traffic to the site than you could have
imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it was pretty much downhill from there. Digital reneged on
its plan to turn AltaVista into a separate subsidiary, a retreat
that led to Lang's departure from the company. ``I was extremely
disappointed,'' she says now, but adds, with a shrug in her voice,
``Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Lang, 55, is once again trying to build an Internet
business under the aegis of a larger parent company. This time it's
NewsEdge Corp., a 400-person Burlington, Mass. firm that uses
computers and humans to serve up electronic news reports to
corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   Lang's job is to deliver some of the same services to anybody
with an Internet browser. She's the president and chief executive
of NewsPage.com Inc., a NewsEdge subsidiary that lets visitors
create a personalized news portal on line.
</P>
<P>
   Lang is one of the leading women in the Massachusetts high-tech
community, a curious fate for someone who majored in history and
literature at Radcliffe. After graduating in 1965, she landed her
first job as a technical writer, cranking out contracts for MIT. It
turned out that her knowledge of Chaucer came in handy. Unlike many
technically trained people, ``I knew what English was,'' she says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   By 1971, her employer was staggering toward collapse, and
Harvard Business School was finally accepting women. Lang spent the
next two years there, then after graduating spent the next decade
in the retail picture-framing business. Only in 1982 did she get
back into technology, as an executive at artificial-intelligence
pioneer Symbolics Inc., where she spent five years. Several other
high-tech assignments followed.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1993, Lang went to Lotus Development Corp., where she
took over worldwide responsibility for the company's SmartSuite
office software line. It was a thankless task; SmartSuite was being
hammered by Microsoft Corp.'s Office software, and Lotus was
pouring most of its resources into an up-and-coming new product
called Notes. Three months after IBM Corp. acquired Lotus, Lang
made the move to Digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't an AltaVista when I went there`` in November
1995, she says. At least, there was no business unit of that name.
Instead, AltaVista was the code name for a powerful Internet search
service. It was one of about 25 networking products that Digital
wanted to combine into a separate business unit under Lang's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at all the products on the first day,'' she recalls,
``and I basically said the only ones here that are worth trying to
build a business around are these new Internet products.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the theory, anyway. By 1997, Digital had changed its
mind about spinning off AltaVista through a public stock offering,
and Lang changed her mind about working for Digital. Digital was
acquired last year by Compaq Computer Corp., while Lang, after a
brief stint as chief executive of Internet utility company
Etility.com, came to NewsPage.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Internet services, NewsPage is free; the service hopes
to make its profits by persuading big-name companies to buy ads on
the site. Once a user signs up, he or she can ask to receive a
daily news briefing covering 1,400 topics, from politics to
technology. NewsPage's electronic and human editors scour 52 media
outlets, from wire services to trade magazines, to find stories
related to the subscriber's interests. The system sends a short
e-mail news summary each morning, as well as a link to the NewsPage
Web site, where the subscriber can read each story in full.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? NewsPage was born in 1995 at Individual Inc.,
another Burlington firm that was in the forefront of the old fad
for Internet ``push'' services. Back then, companies vied to make
software that would automatically dump large amounts of Internet
data onto people's desktops. But push systems swamped both
individual users and corporate data networks with useless
information. Soon people turned their backs on the concept, and
push pioneers fell on hard times. Indeed, NewsEdge was born last
year when its predecessor company, Desktop Data, acquired a
moribund Individual for $83 million.
</P>
<P>
   There's no surprise that Lang says, ``We don't like to use the
word `push,' because of the concept there. It's a very intrusive
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she says, NewsPage is a friendlier service. Users don't
have reams of data pushed onto their hard drives. Instead, they
visit their own customized NewsPage, read the stories that interest
them, and ignore the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Making it all go is the same information-processing
infrastructure that parent company NewsEdge uses. Former Pentagon
data analyst Donald McLagen started Desktop Data in 1988. McLagen
and his colleagues have devised sophisticated algorithms that can
enable computers to sort 10,000 documents a day, cross-linking each
of them to the likely interest of various readers. For instance, a
story about the Microsoft antitrust case would probably be of
interest to antitrust attorneys, but not criminal attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   News-analysis software is all very well, says McLagen, but ``at
the end of the day, it gets you about 40 percent of the way
there.'' So NewsEdge also has a couple of dozen people who skim
through the day's news stories to sharpen up the process. For
instance, several news services will cover the same event; the
editors will choose the best-written account and discard the rest.
``People do that real fast,'' McLagen said.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting newsfeed is sent to about 1,400 clients, including
some of the world's largest businesses. KPMG LLC, the accounting
and consulting firm, recently made NewsEdge part of its KWorld
internal data network. The KWorld intranet currently links 15,000
KPMG employees; eventually all 100,000 employees worldwide will be
linked. And NewsEdge will provide a customized package of news on
such matters as tax law and corporate finance issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Avishai, KPMG's director of intellectual capital, says
NewsEdge helps the company's workers make the most efficient use of
their time. ``They can be one click away from the five or 10 most
relevant stories,'' instead of wasting time on fruitless Internet
searches, Avishai says.
</P>
<P>
   Lang's NewsPage site offers a subset of the NewsEdge service.
While NewsEdge corporate subscribers can choose from 2,000 data
sources, NewsPage uses only 52. David Curle, a senior analyst for
Outsell Inc., a California-based market research firm, says that's
why the free NewsPage service probably won't cannibalize NewsEdge
customers. ``There's a lot of premium content that a service like
NewsEdge provides,'' Curle says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NewsPage's Lang will focus on attracting a large
audience of readers for the more limited offerings on her service.
So far, NewsPage has nearly a million registered users, with about
half that number being regular visitors to the site. With top
portal sites such as Yahoo getting more than 30 million visitors a
month, NewsPage has a lot of growing to do before it can attract a
profitable share of Internet ad revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Lang is confident she can do it, even though NewsEdge lacks the
vast resources that Digital could command. Indeed, she thinks that
Digital was too large and unwieldy to make a good corporate parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital can't really be faulted, in some sense, because no
other big company has been able to do this kind of thing
particularly well,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsEdge is a nice-sized company, but it's still small,'' Lang
adds. ``It's very entrepreneurial, and it hasn't forgotten its
roots. . . . It's a perfect kind of situation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost. There's no blimp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
