<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES BELIEVES HE HAS HIS POSITION COVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Sophomore jinx or sophomore hijinks?
</P>
<P>
   To hear the Patriots tell it, Tebucky Jones has a better chance
for boisterous fun than a second-season letdown.
</P>
<P>
   Already splitting time with veteran Steve Israel on the first
team, Jones is beginning to act more like the cornerback the
Patriots had envisioned when they drafted him in the first round as
a strong safety out of Syracuse a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jones (6 feet 2 inches, 215 pounds) started out as a running
back at Syracuse and was moved to strong safety two years ago,
playing one year on defense at college before the Patriots
braintrust saw his athleticism and decided to turn him into a
bump-and-run corner.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Patriots tried to push the process along last
season, it never clicked well enough for the coaches to trust Jones
against big receivers such as Keyshawn Johnson and Marvin Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems Jones is starting to figure it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's night and day from a year ago,'' said Patriots defensive
backs coach Ron Lynn. ``And understandably so. Last year he had
never lined up at that position. He understands the calls better,
understands the technique better. He has caught a million balls
from this angle now that he'd never seen before. He's so much
better. You used to think he was in a total body spasm when the
ball came down and he was nowhere near the ball. Now he's right on
it. He knows how to turn for the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Tebucky Jones won't be unveiled until the first of four
exhibition games, Aug. 13 against the Washington Redskins. He's
been guaranteed at least two starts and he'll have plenty of
opportunity to prove he's ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have way more confidence now than I did last year,'' said
Jones. ``It all started in the offseason. I started working out
again in January and I felt I had the edge on everybody else
because of it. Then the minicamps started and at that first one we
had, I started to cover guys and I was finding that I was staying
with them. That feeling started to build itself up and up and I
haven't come down from it yet. When I'm out there on the field, I
think I can cover anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots want someone who can get their hands in the face of
bigger receivers and get physical with them at the line of
scrimmage. Jones is big and tough enough to handle those tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for Jones may come in staying with his man off the
line while not being flagged for holding or interference. At times
last season, he hung on receivers too much, which is something Lynn
has worked on with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he's the baddest guy in the world and he doesn't
have to be that way all the time,'' Lynn said. ``He's tried to get
too physical with those guys and what we're telling him is that
he'll get his chances to be physical, but he also knows when he has
to be able to get off a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn considers Ty Law, Israel, and Jones all starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it's going to shake down as to who steps on
the field for the first play, but he's going to play a ton,'' said
Lynn. ``He'll be fine. He could step in and hold his own.
Eventually, I think he's going to be a dominant player if the
officials let guys play bump and run. I don't mean holding and
grabbing or anything illegal past the 5-yard area, but Tebucky is
going to be a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones may be the best athlete in the backfield. Law is an
All-Pro, but Jones can do a lot of things. Law says he'd like to
play on both sides of the ball, but Jones has actually done it in a
big-time college setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me the ball,'' said Jones. ``I'd love to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says he's focused on learning to be a corner. The
Patriots have never even hinted Jones might move to safety, even
with the release of free safety Willie Clay. Safety would seem to
make sense for Jones as he could use his ability to hit people from
a strong safety spot and he wouldn't have the cover
responsibilities he'll have at the right corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a corner,'' said Jones. ``I haven't even thought
about safety since I played it in college. I can play corner and
now I have to go out and show it to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll has never wavered on the topic. He's wanted Jones
to play corner from the moment he saw him at a Syracuse workout
before last year's draft. And Carroll thought he was worth the
gamble of a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference now is I know what I'm doing,'' said Jones. ``I
learned a lot of things about playing the position last year. I've
taken those things and just gotten better at them because I
understand them better.''
</P>
<P>
   Receivers don't like to go up against because they can figure on
getting hammered at some point. Terry Glenn said, ``He's very
physical. I'm not going to go up against someone that physical in
the regular season. He gives everyone a good test at the line of
scrimmage. If you can get away from him, you're doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jones doesn't cut it as the opening day right corner, he said
he won't be disappointed. But he expects to take advantage of every
opportunity and give the Patriots something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll give me the chance and the rest is up to me,''
said Jones. ``I have to continue to be a good special teams player
and contribute to this team as best I can in all areas. If I play
in the nickel, then I have to do the job there, too. I have all
season to show them that I can be a starter and a good player in
the regular defense. I feel I've reached that point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
