<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLINS STEPS FROM ROCK TO A HARDER PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Henry Rollins talks about ``more adrenalin and more
testosterone,'' you wake up and listen. Here's a guy who has made a
career of these things, yet he's upping the ante even more. The
former leader of the seminal punk band Black Flag is not going
quietly into the night.
</P>
<P>
   These days are peak times for hard rock _ look at the success of
Limp Bizkit and Korn. And now comes the return of Rollins, who has
a new version of the Rollins Band and a new determination to
pulverize every audience in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last tour, there was just a certain level of adrenalin
and testosterone that I was missing,'' says Rollins. ``And I felt I
wasn't going to get it done with the guys I had. It's just not
where we were headed. I wanted to rock out _ and a straight 4/4
thing is really not what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins, 38, has a new unit that is ``ready to kick out the
jams'' every night.
</P>
<P>
   Members of his last band have caught on elsewhere _ drummer Sim
Cain joined the J. Geils Band reunion tour and guitarist Chris
Haskett is doing studio work for David Bowie. Meanwhile, Rollins
found a bunch of hard-rock devotees in Mother Superior, a
pre-existing band that backs him on this club tour and on a new
album, ``Get Some Go Again,'' due out in January to greet the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll come into the millennium with a definite roar, that's
for sure,'' says Rollins. ``My manager said, `Hey, there's never
been a better time for you to make a hard-rock album.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his new sound, Rollins notes, ``It's not like
we're doing heavy metal. And it's not some speed-metal thing. It's
kind of like older rock 'n' roll. It sounds like Thin Lizzy and
Black Sabbath and John Lee Hooker or Lightnin' Hopkins on a lot of
hormone shots. It's like the MC5. It's not rocket science. It feels
good and it rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The album includes a Thin Lizzy cover song, ``Are You Ready,''
done as a present to Lizzy singer Phil Lynott's mother. ``I sent it
to her and she loved it,'' says Rollins. ``She sent us a nice
letter back, saying `God bless you boys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins will finish these band dates, then embark on a
spoken-word tour, before reuniting the group for a winter tour once
the album is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aerosmith's Joe Perry on Woodstock: An exhausted Aerosmith
arrived back home in Boston last week, ready to begin a month-long
vacation after 2 1/2 years of touring. But fatigue didn't stop
guitarist Joe Perry from mustering anger at the small group of
youths that ran amok at the end of Woodstock '99 and torched 12
tractor trailers, leaving a sad legacy after most other attendees
had a great time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those kids have everything and they still want more,''
says Perry. ``They came to party and hang out, but they still had
to burn things. We've just been abroad and you see how much tougher
some of the kids have it over there, even in the civilized
countries. And then you see kids over here, torching the place
where they're partying. It made me disgusted. These kids have it
too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aerosmith was initially booked at Woodstock '99 (after enjoying
great success at Woodstock '94), but dropped out a few weeks before
the event. Some observers suggest that Aerosmith was smart to do
so, but Perry says, ``No, we don't feel that way. We don't have any
crystal ball about how things are going to turn out. We just wanted
more control over the production, which we wouldn't have had.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted us to sign over all our rights on the
pay-per-view, and on the concert album,'' Perry adds. ``Plus, they
wanted us to go out there with no soundcheck and no (stage) lights
of our own. . . . Some of that stuff wasn't brought up to us until
later. And then when we got a contract about it coming out of our
fax machine, we said the hell with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Perry remains a fan of the Woodstock concept of mass
social gatherings. ``I hope they can keep it together and have
future festivals. Europe has festivals like this all the time _ we
just played 10 of them. Some went for one night, some for three or
four nights. Every country has one or two of them, it seems. It's
no big deal over there. They have them every year. It's not like,
`Gee, I wonder if this will be as big as the one in 1994 or 1969?'
Who cares? Let's just have a festival and get some music
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Aerosmith dropped out of Woodstock, Perry was still
rumored to be a possible participant in a Jimi Hendrix tribute
conceived as Woodstock's finale, but which ended up just being a
video tribute. ``I was never contacted,'' Perry says.
</P>
<P>
   He did recently head down to Florida, though, for the unveiling
of a new roller coaster ride at Disney World entitled ``the Rock
'n' Roller Coaster Starring Aerosmith.'' Each car on the coaster
has its own stereo that booms Aerosmith songs. ``We took the kids
and had a great time. It was a blast,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New album releases: Look for new albums within the next few
months from AC/DC, Alice In Chains (a boxed set), Michael Bolton,
Nine Inch Nails, Sting, 'N Sync, Creed, Melissa Etheridge, David
Bowie, Tony Bennett, Tori Amos, Method Man, Redman, Primus, Kenny
Wayne Shepherd, Toni Braxton, Mariah Carey, Eric Clapton, Celine
Dion (a hits collection), Ice Cube, Paul McCartney, Metallica, Nas,
Puff Daddy, Rage Against the Machine, LeAnn Rimes, Stone Temple
Pilots, and Barbra Streisand. And, according to Billboard, look for
new Christmas discs by the Backstreet Boys, Paula Cole, George
Strait, Amy Grant, Jewel, Garth Brooks, Reba McEntire, and, whoa,
Ringo Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
