<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-06 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY CHECK: FUNDAMENTALS DO MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is reality check time for Internet stocks. The results aren't
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet stocks rallied Thursday after dropping sharply in
the morning. But most have fallen dramatically this week and are
now trading at prices 50 to 60 percent below the highs they reached
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest explanation for the selloff: a growing realization
by investors that the old-fashioned rules of economics apply to the
Internet sector, too.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are starting to appreciate that growth rates matter,
that companies need strategies that eventually will lead to
profitability, and that fierce competition will produce winners and
losers. Even something as dull as rising interest rates can have an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks can only detach from the fundamentals for so long,''
warns Nick Moore, a money manager with Jurika &AMP; Voyles in Oakland,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, some drops of rain have fallen on the
Internet parade.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Amazon.com, the on-line bookstore, reported that its
second quarter sales were 7 percent higher than its sales in the
first quarter. For most companies, that would be good news. But for
a company that is supposed to be growing at light speed, the
numbers were disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not as explosive as we have seen in the past,'' says
Eileen Leary, an analyst with State Street Research, a Boston
investment firm. It didn't help matters that Amazon once again said
it would not be profitable in the foreseeable future while it makes
investments in staff and a distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, an influential Wall Street analyst threw cold
water on another set of high fliers, the on-line brokerage firms.
Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Bill Burnham said the volume of
electronic stock trading in the third quarter might not be any
greater than it was in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The news immediately drove down the share prices of companies
like ETrade and Ameritrade, two of the pioneers in electronic
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Competition also reared its ugly head this week, reminding
investors that gluts can develop even in brand-new fields. Tuesday,
four different Internet companies all launched initial public
offerings, the latest in a long line of dot-com companies to sell
stock this year. All four ended the day at prices below their
offering price, a sign that the appetite for Internet stocks is not
unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the latest round in the battle between
Microsoft and America Online, in which Microsoft hinted that it was
planning to offer Internet access service like AOL's at prices far
below the $21.95 that AOL charges per month.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you sell Internet access or tractors, a price war
inevitably leads to lower profits. ``The stock market can do the
math,'' says money manager Nick Moore. AOL's stock fell 4 3/16
Thursday to close at 83 1/4, about half the value it had in April.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we go from here?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, opinions vary widely. Alan Loewenstein,
manager of John Hancock's Global Technology Fund, predicts that a
divide is coming. He thinks investors will begin to sort Internet
stocks into two categories: winners that have a business model that
can produce profits and losers that can't differentiate themselves
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, two Internet companies, Internet Capital Group and
HomeStore.com, both had successful IPOs. Internet Capital debuted
at 12 and closed at 24 7/16, while HomeStore, opening at 20,
finished up at 22 3/4. Such results suggest that Wall Street hasn't
given up on the whole field.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Leary thinks investors will wait for more information.
She thinks the upcoming Christmas season will be crucial for
retailers like Amazon, who must prove they can get back on the fast
growth track.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Moore doesn't have to wait for more information. He has
made up his mind. ``The selloff isn't over by a mile,'' he says.
``Phase one may be over, but even the highest-quality companies in
this group are still three times as expensive as they should be.
We've had a correction, but the bubble isn't pierced yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore predicts it will take another round of disappointing
numbers to trigger the kind of rout he envisions.
</P>
<P>
   Who's right here? We aren't smart enough to know. But one thing
is clear: Keeping track of the Internet stocks isn't going to be
boring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
