<HEADLINE>
TOUR MAY BE OVER, BUT SEASON GOES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you think cyclists do when they finish _ even win _ the
Tour de France? Here's a hint: They don't grin at the camera and
announce they're going to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   No, they just keep riding.
</P>
<P>
   In football, baseball, hockey, the Super Bowl, World Series or
Stanley Cup playoffs signal the end of the season. Not so with
cycling. After the Tour, there are stage races in Europe and the
national criterium championship in America until the season finally
wraps up with the World Championships in Italy in October.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the US Postal Service team has dispersed, most of
the Tour riders are still competing.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Vaughters was the first to pack up and leave Europe
when he was part of the massive pileup on the Tour's second day of
racing. He was out of the Tour, but not out of racing. Vaughters
came back to the States and immediately entered the Red Zinger
Classic, a small stage race in Colorado. And his brush with the
Tour must have boosted his confidence; he won the Red Zinger.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton, of Brookline, Mass., went back to his home in
Girona, Spain, after finishing 13th in the Tour. He and other
teammates will be riding in races in Spain, Denmark, and Germany,
with a visit to the USPRO Criterium championships in Chicago on
Aug. 22. Hamilton also plans to be in New England on Aug. 21 to
defend his title in the Mt. Washington race. He made it up the
mountain in 51:56 two years ago, and the record still stands. Some
of the team also will go to the stage race in Killington, Vt., over
Labor Day (won by Postal rider George Hincapie last year), before
going back to Europe for the worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Tour winner Lance Armstrong has by far the busiest schedule. The
day after finishing first in Paris, Armstrong was off to Belgium
and Holland to ride in some traditional post-Tour criterium races.
Then he jetted to New York, where he was feted by Mayor Rudy
Guiliani and interviewed on talk shows for two days until he was on
his way back to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He's returning stateside next week, where his hometown of
Austin, Texas, will welcome him with a ticker-tape parade Monday.
The next day he'll go to the White House to meet with President
Clinton, then head West, where he'll tour the Nike campus (They're
one of his sponsors) in Oregon and do the Los Angeles talk-show
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   After some moutain bike races, including one in Mt. Snow, Vt.,
on Aug. 20, Armstrong likely will put away his cleats for the
racing season and think about his first offseason job _ fatherhood.
His wife, Kristin, is due to give birth to their first child in
late October.
</P>
<P>
   The team is busy, too, fielding calls from new potential
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely a hot commodity now, and it's exciting,''
said director of operations Dan Osipow from the Postal Service
team's headquarters in Sausalito, Calif. ``But there's only so many
names you can fit on a jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the US Postal Service logo emblazoned on the
front of the jersey, half a dozen other sponsors own some real
estate on the shirt, including Visa, Trek, Volkswagen, Yahoo!, and
Shimano.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's show time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The third annual Bicycle Show and Swap will be held next Sunday,
Aug. 15, at the Larz Anderson Museum of Transportation in
Brookline, Mass. The day will feature displays of classic bicycles,
a swap meet, clinics, and a centennial tribute to Massachusetts
native Major Taylor, who was the 1899 world champion. Admission is
$5 for adults, $3 for children . . . The folks at Mt. Snow, Vt.,
will be host for more than 2,000 mountain bike racers in the
National Off Road Bicycling Association series finals Aug. 19-22.
An NBC crew will be there, too, taping a program to air Sept. 11.
But they are cautious about saying Tour winner Armstrong will be
there. Armstrong said in France that he'd be at the race, though,
and his agent, Bill Stapleton, repeated it this week: ``Lance and I
will be there,'' he said. . . . US cyclists cleaned up at the Pan
American Games that finished earlier this week in Winnipeg,
Manitoba, as 20 of the 21 Americans won a medal. Karen Dunne, of
Colorado Springs, Colo., was the last winner with a victory in
Wednesday's women's 51-mile road race. It was the 11th gold medal
for the US team. Earlier in the week, both Alison Dunlap of
Colorado Springs and Steve Larsen of Bend, Ore., won golds in their
cross-country mountain bike races, and Elizabeth Emery of
Albuquerque , won the women's time trial. Sean Petty, director of
athlete performance at USA Cycling, attributed the US victories to
America's success in the Tour de France. ``Everyone had momentum
after Lance's win,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
