<HEADLINE>
HEAT ON CARROLL, PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN/SI launches its NFL Preview show Aug. 15, and its analysts
wasted little time picking on the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Trev Alberts, a former All-American linebacker and first-round
draft pick of the Indianapolis Colts in 1994, told reporters that
the Patriots would have a disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill Parcells left that team, there was a definite drop
in discipline on players, there was a definite difference in the
physical nature of the makeup,'' Alberts said. ``That's why I think
the Willie Clay thing was so interesting. I don't think this team
makes the playoffs, and I think the pressure will build throughout
the entire season on Coach (Pete) Carroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots coach Ron Meyer is another analyst on the
hour-long show. He was also puzzled by the handling of Clay. ``I
was shocked,'' Meyer said. ``I looked at the numbers, and I thought
they could have juggled elsewhere and resolved that situation. I
don't know if it's a personality conflict nor do I know defensively
what they're thinking. . . I think Clay is a pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was more optimistic about the Patriots' chances this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are going to get in and probably lose in the
opening round of the playoffs, simply because of Bledsoe and I like
their defensive attack as a whole,'' Meyer said. ``However, I think
its going to be a tough year for Pete. Bob Kraft wants more, so do
those fans up there. You saw a little indication of this last year
in the offseason when he changed up his coaches. That's always a
bad sign when you're the remaining coach on that staff. In other
words, it's who do we throw to the sharks first?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second sister
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2 has 65 million subscribers, making it the second-most
watched cable network behind its sister network, ESPN. ESPN2 airs
two hours of NFL Hall of Fame coverage Saturday, starting at 1 p.m.
Mike Tirico and Tom Jackson will host. The 1999 inductees are Ozzie
Newsome, Tom Mack, Billy Shaw, Eric Dickerson, and Lawrence Taylor
. . . Chris Berman will host a two-hour program on the greatest
coaches of the century Aug. 10 at 7:30 p.m. The show is part of
ESPN's SportsCentury project and focuses on ``the magnificent
seven'' legendary coaches of the last 100 years. They are John
Wooden, Dean Smith, John McGraw, Vince Lombardi, George Halas, Bear
Bryant, and Red Auerbach. The show concludes with the 48-member,
SportsCentury panel's choice for the best coach . . . ESPN Classic
airs a 24-hour marathon on Barry Sanders, as well as a replay of
the Marvin Hagler-Sugar Ray Leonard fight at 5 p.m. . . . ESPN's
23d Greatest Athlete of the Century is Jackie Joyner-Kersee. The
profile airs at 10:30 p.m. Joyner-Kersee is the third track and
field star (Edwin Moses was No. 47 and Wilma Rudolph No. 41) and
the third woman in the top 50 (Rudolph and Chris Evert at No. 50).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Extra cornbread
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEEI-AM in Boston gave Cedric ``Cornbread'' Maxwell a two-year
extension as Celtics' radio analyst . . . FX airs the Toughman
World Championship Friday night at 10 p.m. The weekly slugfest
debuted July 23. Butch Stearns replaces Fox sports anchor Jeff
Cawley on a temporary basis, starting Saturday night on the
station's 10 p.m. newscast. Stearns will work as a reporter and an
anchor . . . Fox was all over the Celtics' trade with the Denver
Nuggets. It was able to talk with both Ron Mercer and Paul Pierce.
Pierce said he was pleased with the trade that sent guard Mercer to
Denver and brought rebounder Danny Fortson here. Mercer had more
interesting things to say. ``I would do anything to stay in
Boston,'' Mercer said Tuesday night. ``But I want what's fair.
(Rick) Pitino has his value. No one said anything when he signed
with the Celtics as head coach and he got his money _ what was fair
for him. You think Pitino would have went to the Celtics for $30
million instead of $50 million? That's the question you have to
ask.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
