<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-RAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY FLIERS MAKING SKIES LESS FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was 3:34 p.m. Wednesday, 11 minutes before his
flight was scheduled to leave Logan Airport, and the 30-something
man in the business suit had received bad news at the United
Airlines gate. Because of a computer glitch, his first class seat
had been given away; he would have to travel coach. Nothing to be
done about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a huff, the man headed toward a bathroom, but the gate
attendants waved him back. More bad news: the flight was leaving
now, so he would have to use the restroom on the plane. That's
when, to put it nicely, the passenger lost his cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people are out to screw us!'' he shouted, according to
gate agents and passengers who watched him, mouths agape.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the man departed for good, airline workers
lamented the new state of affairs: Air travel is not so civil
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   These travelers aren't just venting inside cramped airplane
cabins, but at crowded ticket counters, airline gates, and baggage
carousels. Airport workers say it can make for tense and unpleasant
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting tough these days, there's no doubt about it,''
said gate agent Lorna McKibben. ``It seems like they're getting
uglier and uglier.''
</P>
<P>
   Among airline workers, they are known as ``irates,'' these
passengers, battered by airport snafus, who release their
frustrations on the nearest employees. ``I've already had two
irates come in today,'' one baggage clerk said on a routine, sunny
Wednesday. And that, he said, was a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since airlines were deregulated in the late 1970s, the
number of air travelers has skyrocketed, from 275 million in 1978
to 614 million in 1998. The sharp increase in passengers, fueled by
cheaper fares, has meant more flights, more planes, more
overcrowding, more delays, and the phenomenon known as ``air
rage.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some dramatic examples of late. On a stormy
night in July, a Continental Airlines passenger, enraged over a
boarding pass dispute, pushed a Newark gate agent to the floor. As
such anecdotes pile up, some airlines are taking action, seeking
ways to train employees in handling angry fliers and pledging
vigilant prosecution of people who threaten their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, acts of airport violence are rare. About 26 million
passengers flew out of Logan Airport last year, Massachusetts Port
Authority officials said. That year, State Police were called about
a dozen times to remove unruly passengers from airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Far more common, employees say, are the small, unreported
examples of tempers flaring. There's a sizable dent in the wall of
Logan's Delta Airlines baggage claim office where a furious
customer recently laid a punch. One baggage clerk said passengers
have hurled cups of coffee at the wall behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Another said a minister recently launched into a screaming fit
when his bag didn't arrive. Some clerks say they call for a police
officer, as a deterrent, several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Some frustration, of course, is understandable. Air travel is
full of annoyances big and small, from the ride to the airport to
the trek through the parking lot, from the risk of delay to the
chance that the baggage simply won't arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Jorgenson, a 26-year-old engineer from Albuquerque, stood
slumped against an airline counter Wednesday, looking defeated. Her
car rental company had given her the wrong directions to her hotel
_ twice. The travel agent had messed up her reservations _ twice.
The hotel sent her wakeup call to the room next door.
</P>
<P>
   And when she finally arrived at the airport, thankful to be
headed home, she discovered that her flight was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what road rage feels like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Stuart Kauffman, a noted chaos theorist who waited behind
Jorgenson in line, said there's little that compares to the chaos
of air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be in the clutches of a given airline from before noon
to 9 or 10 at night without being given anything more than a tiny
bag of pretzels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while frustration is inevitable, said Reg Brown, a
supervisor for United Airlines' Logan operations, a tantrum should
still rank as unacceptable behavior. There's something about air
travel that makes people lose their self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``People only act like that at the airport,'' Brown said.
``Where else do you see people behave that way?''
</P>
<P>
   At United, spokesman Joe Hopkins said, a task force is studying
ways to train employees to handle customer rage. The airline has a
``zero tolerance'' policy, promising to arrest menacing passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But many airline employees said they have learned on their own
how to defuse a passenger's rage. The trick, they say, is a veneer
of calm and a bit of peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, I'll just sit there and look at him like that,''
said Business Express flight attendant Carol Coleman, raising her
eyebrows and throwing a give-me-a-break kind of glare. At that
point, she said, other passengers often chime in to help, saying,
``It's not her fault'' or ``leave her alone.''
</P>
<P>
   A little information helps, too, Brown said. When Denver airport
workers recently neglected to put two carts of luggage on a flight
to Boston, clerks kept the updates flowing, and the crowd of 108
potential irates remained calm.
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure _ about delays, fares, and schedules _ is a
major theme of the ``passengers' bill of rights,'' a list of
initiatives the airline industry has proposed in the wake of
consumer and government pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overtures, though, many passengers aren't appeased.
</P>
<P>
   And some are using the law to voice their frustration. The
passenger who attacked the Newark gate agent last month has sued
Continental, contending that his outburst was caused by poorly
trained employees and bad airport conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many airline employees say air rage more often stems from
factors beyond an airport worker's control: increased air traffic,
poor weather, and flowing alcohol. Airline workers, they say, want
everything to go smoothly for their charges.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what gate agents said they told the fuming
businessman who was angry at being called back from the airport
lavatory Wednesday: ``If we were out to screw you, we wouldn't have
told you, and you would have missed your flight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXCUT-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      08-06 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXCUT-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWASH IN SPENDING IDEAS, PARTIES PUT THEIR FAITH IN THE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL AND AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They can't help themselves; it's the nature of the
beast. Whether it's Republicans pushing for a big tax cut or
Democrats trying to cover the cost of prescription drugs through
Medicare, politicians here are drooling over a projected
multitrillion-dollar budget surplus and vying over ways to spend
it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the GOP's turn Thursday, as the House and Senate passed a
historic $792 billion 10-year tax cut. President Clinton, with his
own plans for the money, promised a veto.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrat or Republican, only a few have paused in their
reveries to ask: What if the number crunchers are wrong?
</P>
<P>
   It is no casual question, for if recent experience is a guide,
the 10- and 15-year budget projections on which elected officials
are relying could be elusive and ephemeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``These future budget surpluses are . . . based on `pie in the
sky' projections,'' said Senator Robert Byrd, a Democrat from West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think `pie in the sky' is right,'' Byrd said, upon
reflection. ``The projections are so far out into the stratosphere
_ more than a decade away _ that we would need the Hubble Telescope
to track them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson. Jimmy Carter. Ronald Reagan. George Bush. That's
just a partial roster of US presidents whose optimistic economic
projections ultimately failed to materialize, and so gave them
considerable political pain. And none of them ever had the temerity
to claim they could see 15 years into the economic future, which
Clinton has done. Because of the difficulty of making long-term
projections, the House traditionally forecasts spending and tax
revenues for no more than five years, the Senate for 10.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the anticipated huge budget surpluses _
$5.9 trillion over the next 15 years by one administration measure
_ is the failure of congressional and White House analysts to
predict the feverish growth of the economy when compiling the
federal budgets over the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Office of Management and Budget and the Congressional
Budget Office have been wrong _ horrendously wrong,'' said Stephen
Moore, an analyst with the Cato Institute. ``Three years ago they
were predicting $100- to $200 billion deficits, instead we got
$100- to $200 billion surpluses.''
</P>
<P>
   The OMB at the White House and the CBO on Capitol Hill are the
two agencies that most of official Washington relies upon when it
comes to predicting budget deficits and surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the CBO predicted that the nation would face a $400
billion budget deficit in 2005. Within three years, as the economy
continued to exceed expectations, the CBO changed that prediction
to a $100 billion surplus: a swing of a half-trillion dollars. A
key reason was that the economy grew faster than most economists
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The list of variables that could eat up a projected surplus is
long and multifarious: A recession. A slump in the dollar. A leap
in health care costs. A drag in productivity gains. A failure by
Congress to respect its current caps on discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   The current projections are under suspicion for some reasons
that are beyond the forecasters' control. No one can claim to know
how fast the economy, or the work force, or the cost of living will
grow. Moreover, government forecasters must assume that the
spending caps will remain in law.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is fiddling with the numbers,'' said Henry Aaron, an
economist with the Brookings Institution who studies government
spending policy. CBO and OMB ``are using the methods they've used
all along.'' The agencies have never built a deep recession into
their forecasts and today's economy gives few reasons to do so,
Aaron said. And CBO and OMB ``are duty-bound'' to assume that the
existing laws on spending will hold, even if many people believe
Congress will change them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, under the guise of emergency spending, the discretionary
budget caps are already eroding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the other day the House of Representatives determined
that the money to pay for the decennial census in the year 2000
required an emergency appropriaton outside of those limits,'' said
Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat from New York. ``All of
a sudden, we have made it into an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, ``because we have these big surplus
projections, people are saying now we can go on another spending
spree,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Yet economic ``expansions don't always last forever. Governments
tend to go through boom and bust cycles,'' said Moore. ``When there
is a boom cycle, like where we are now. . . . The politicians say,
`This is going to last forever and we can spend and spend and
spend.' And then when the expansion ends we go from 7 percent to 2
percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make the case these surpluses are a curse because they
have been an excuse to break down all semblance of fiscal
discipline,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a libertarian, sides with the House and Senate
Republicans who Thursday gave final passage to the sweeping $792
billion tax cut. The GOP plan would be the largest tax cut since
1981, trimming the bottom 15 percent income tax rate to 14 percent
in 2003 and reducing the other rates by 1 percentage point in 2005.
It would also give two-income couples relief from the ``marriage
penalty,'' gradually repeal the federal estate tax and trim the
capital gains tax rate for most investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrd and others think that the inherently risky business of
making economic projections is a reason to forestall such a large
tax cut. The Clinton administration, which has opposed the size of
the tax cut, is exploring the idea of using the surpluses to buy
back Treasury securities and thus reduce the $5.5 trillion national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate on the tax bill last week, Moynihan charged
that the secret strategy of tax-cutting Republicans since the
Reagan years has been to use robust budget projections as an excuse
to cut taxes _ and thus starve the federal government when the
projected revenues don't materialize.
</P>
<P>
   A series of ``rosy scenarios,'' issued by OMB during the Reagan
administration, resulted in annual deficits of $150 to $200 billion
in the late 1980s and early 1990s, Moynihan noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deficits _ that had presumably been the horror of conservative
financial thought _ now became something attractive because they
could be used to reduce the size of government itself,'' said
Moynihan. ``The secret solution was to let the federal budget
deficits rise, thus leaving Congress no alternative but to cut
domestic programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is at it again, said Moynihan: ``We are proposing to
spend a surplus, sir, that does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax-cutting Republicans and Democrats, however, argue that their
tax cut is but a meager 25 percent of the expected surplus _
leaving plenty of room for error. And Moore and others point out
that the projections could just as well be too pessimistic as
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert Kerrey, a Democrat from Nebraska, defended the
CBO projections when explaining his support for the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressional budget office, though they obviously will
from time to time make mistakes, forecasts that there will be $3
trillion more coming in over the next 10 years than we have in
obligated expenditures,'' said Kerrey. ``I think one would have to
imagine some pretty unusual economic circumstances to imagine a
downturn in the economy that would eliminate a $3 trillion
forecast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1332EDT &QL; 
