<HEADLINE>
COMING SOON: AN UPDIKE MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who'd a thunk it? Cameron Mackintosh's next big musical
extravaganza will be John Updike's ``The Witches of Eastwick.''
</P>
<P>
   The London-based Mackintosh, producer of such hits as ``Miss
Saigon,'' ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' and ``Les Miserables,''
says he submitted a list of ideas for potential musicals to two
young American writers he likes, John Dempsey and Dana Rowe. The
team picked the Updike story, best known to the public via the Jack
Nicholson/Cher/Michelle Pfeiffer movie, filmed in Cohasset 13 years
ago. Mackintosh then bought rights from Updike's West Coast agent,
Dan Sherman. ``Updike is very pleased that he's becoming a
musical,'' the producer says. ``But, as with the movie, he doesn't
want to have anything to do with the creation itself.'' No comment
from the sage of Beverly Farms.
</P>
<P>
   The British press has been pumping star names like Catherine
Zeta-Jones and Nicholson-esque dirty old man Michael Douglas for
the London premiere, but Mackintosh says casting hasn't been
finalized. ``These roles will have to be played with terrific
panache,'' he says. ``Famous film stars aren't used to doing eight
shows a week for a year.'' Although he hasn't booked any American
dates for the show, he describes ``Witches'' as a ``contemporary,
traditional American musical comedy,'' written and staffed by
Yanks. Apart from the writers, Mackintosh says he has recruited the
``cream of Connecticut'' _ the late Michael Bennett's
choreographer, Bob Avian, production designer Bob Crowley, and
director Eric Schaeffer _ to work on ``Witches.''
</P>
<P>
   The show starts rehearsing in March, and should open in late May
or early June at the Theatre Royal Drury Lane. Mackintosh thinks
his writing team has produced at least two show-stopping tunes,
``Dance With the Devil'' and the finale, ``You're the Man.'' ``It's
very funny and at the same time it will have Updike's special
twists on life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bookwatch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Improper Bostonian recently asked local notables about
their summer reading plans, the self-effacing Alan Dershowitz felt
compelled to mention his own forthcoming novel, ``Just Revenge.'' A
reviewer for Publishers Weekly also spent time with the book, and
rendered this opinion: ``Subtlety is not Dershowitz's strong suit,
nor is literary finesse, but he makes up for these shortcomings
with the dramatic and tragic events that frame the plot, and the
intensity of his moral argument.'' . . . Damage control time
(again) at the Christian Science Church, as Caroline Fraser's
``God's Perfect Child: Living and Dying in the Christian Science
Church'' finds its way into bookstores. Fraser, a former Scientist
and a careful (if prolix) writer, has been working on this tome for
several years, and, put gently, its publication will not win any
new converts to Mary Baker Eddy-dom. Former Scientist Spalding Gray
gives it this blurb: ``For me, `God's Perfect Child' acted like an
excellent deprogramming map, freeing me from that demented, magical
world I thought I'd left behind.'' I can't mention this book
without putting in a plug for my friend Thomas Simmons's excellent
``The Unseen Shore: Memories of a Christian Science Childhood,''
which you can get at a library or through bibliofind.com. . . .
Friends? Plugs? That would lead me directly to John Spooner's new
book, ``Do You Want to Make Money or Would You Rather Fool
Around?'' which is excerpted in this month's Playboy. If you buy
the magazine, you get not only Spooner but also, um, a Joyce Carol
Oates short story! What a deal!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Erratum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Harrington, who edits the ``Insider's Guide'' series that
failed to capture my imagination a few weeks ago, notes that his
Cape Cod guide does mention Provincetown's delightful Portuguese
bakery, in a sidebar that escaped my attention. My mistake.
Faithful reader Amy Whorf McGuiggan, who spent her childhood
summers in P-town, points out that the cognoscenti call the
bakery's fried-dough patties that I enjoyed ``flippers.'' A detail
not to be found in the ``insider's'' guide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
