<HEADLINE>
POSTS ARE A GOOD SUB FOR CONCRETE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 8, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am building a 10- by 24-foot addition to the house. The
contractor suggested using Lally columns set in concrete for
supports instead of a foundation. I realize this is within code,
but I am concerned about plumbing freezing in that open crawl
space. Is this OK?
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN ROE, Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Lally columns are steel posts filled with concrete; they are
OK, and a lot less expensive than a foundation of any kind. As for
the open crawl space under the addition, water lines could freeze
in winter. To prevent this, make sure the lines are between the
joists under the floor, then insulate between the joists with
6-inch fiberglass insulation, with the paper backing up, touching
the floor boards above.
</P>
<P>
   As for the open crawl space, you can have a skirt board
installed, which will make the addition look better, help insulate
the crawl space, and keep out vermin. Your contractor will know
exactly what that means, and could put one in. Make sure the crawl
space is well ventilated from spring through autumn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Benjamin Chernoff of Brookline, Mass. asked if a rotted
rail on the bottom of his paneled wood garage door could be fixed,
the handyman must have seen the forest and not the trees, or seen
the trees and not the forest, because he did not give enough
information.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman said the bottom rail can be cut off and replaced,
which is true enough, but three readers said there is a better way.
</P>
<P>
   And that is to replace the entire bottom panel, replacement
parts of which are available at overhead door companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stevens of Framingham, Mass. said he bought a replacement
panel at Door Systems Inc. of Framingham (508-875-3508; a Boston
number is 617-237-0404). The section cost $130, said Stevens. He
undid the hinges, threw away the rotted panel, rehinged the
replacement, tacked on a new gasket, and was done.
</P>
<P>
   John Barrett of Reading, Mass. said he got his door panel from
Overhead Door in Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And, wrote Michael Boyle of Reading, Mass.: ``Atlantic Overhead
Door of Winthrop will replace the bottom section of a garage door
for a reasonable price . . . I found Atlantic Overhead door in the
Yellow Pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, gentlemen, the handyman stands corrected. But it
won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have discovered lead in my water. I can get a filter to
remove it but, in the meantime, can I shower with this leaded
water?
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNED
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can shower, even bathe in your leaded water, because
lead does not enter the body through the skin, according to the
National Safety Council's Regional Lead Information Center. Most
city and well water does not contain lead, but if it does there are
filters you can buy to remove it. You may be getting lead in the
water because your plumbing lines and solder on copper lines
contain lead. Water is picking up the lead as it passes through the
pipes, more so if it sits in the pipes for a time. Sometimes
letting the water run for a few minutes before using will purge the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. After replacing the sill in a window (circa 1974), I find it
difficult to open and close; it really takes effort. Did I do
something wrong? I did put in new jambs a while ago.
</P>
<P>
   PERPLEXED
</P>
<P>
   A. I am only guessing, but I believe you reduced the distance
between jambs at the bottom of the window, making the sash tighter
in the jambs. Measure the distance between jambs at the top of the
window, then at the bottom. If the measurements are just an eighth
inch or so different, then try spreading the bottom part of the
jambs just a bit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had new paper put in the bathroom. In two weeks, the paper
above the shower stall started to tear, and some seams came loose.
I used Seam Sealer, a super sort of wallpaper paste, which helped a
little, but some of it still is coming up. What's wrong?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY McGANNON, Hanover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The fix is easy and inexpensive, and within your realm. You
can continue with Seam Sealer or PolySeamSeal, an adhesive caulk. I
like the idea of the PolySeamSeal because it comes in a caulking
cartridge with a nozzle for inserting small beads of caulking.
These pastes and the PolySeamSeal can be applied thinly, but may
take a while to grab. You have to hold down the paper until it
sticks permanently. Don't make the caulking too thick; you will end
up with a lump in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There is some cheap plywood paneling in the seasonal cottage
I am buying in Maine. I'd like to put vertical boards over this
paneling. Can I nail the boards into the paneling?
</P>
<P>
   LINDA ROEMER, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No; the plwyood is too thin to hold a nail for long.Easiest
and fastest is to nail 1 x 2 or 1 x 3 horizontal furring strips,
driving nails through the plywood and into the studs. Then nail the
vertical boards to the strips, which should be placed 16 24 inches
apart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
