<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MY-LIFE-BOS &LR;      08-06 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MY-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY LIFE' ROAMS AN INNER LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MY LIFE SO FAR 
Directed by: Hugh Hudson 
Screnplay by: Simon Donald (based on Denis Forman's memoir) 
Starring: Colin Firth, Rosemary Harris, Irene Jacob, Tcheky Karyo,
Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, Malcolm McDowell, Kelly McDonald,
Robert Norman 
Running time: 93 minutes 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The producing-directing team of David Puttnam and Hugh Hudson
has, artistically speaking, led a charmed life on Scottish soil,
first with ``Chariots of Fire,'' then with ``Greystoke'' and now,
again, with ``My Life So Far.'' The new film is based on the
between-the-wars boyhood of Sir Denis Forman, a British TV and
opera impresario, who came of age in the Scottish Highlands near
Argyll, almost magically coccooned in a great stone nest known as
Kiloran House. Puttnam and Hudson made atmosphere count in
``Chariots of Fire,'' and it counts for even more in this luminous
family chronicle bathed in mists and teeming with the energetic
members of a loving, eccentric family.
</P>
<P>
   As far as 10-year-old Forman surrogate Fraser Pettigrew, played
by Robert Norman, is concerned, everything that takes place there
is instantly mythologized. But if he's wide-eyed, he's also
clear-eyed. He begins by worshipping his exuberant and romantic
crackpot father, Edward, played by Colin Firth with a kind of fizzy
stiffness. Edward's passions include Beethoven, the Bible, sphagnum
moss and, in a lapse that cracks the family's united front, a
charming French cellist. She's been brought to Kiloran as the bride
of Fraser's uncle and Edward's brother-in-law and rival, the rich
Morris, whose love of jazz is matched by Edward's hatred of it, and
whose love for Irene Jacob's sparkling Heloise is unfortunately
shared. Which means that in the space of a year the hitherto
adoring son must ask himself if he can understand and forgive his
reduced-in-stature father.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown built around this jolting instance of sexual
waywardness in the otherwise puritanical family never altogether
obscures the golden benevolence of life at Kiloran. Although Morris
and Edward are rivals for the eventual control of Kiloran, the
ascension is not an immediately looming thing, thanks to the silken
strength of the family matriarch, Rosemary Harris's Gamma. Although
she doesn't have much screen time, the reliably flawless Harris
sees to it that there's no doubt that her presence shapes the tenor
of life in the great stone pile. Her ironclad rule seems to result
less in a feeling of control than in a reassuring climate of
harmony. But then the film is too generous-hearted not to draw all
its characters richly. It's an enchanted story of childhood
idealizations that beguile and move us.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm McDowell's Uncle Morris, stern and pushy as he may be on
the outside, obviously has a loving heart. And Edward's idea of
harvesting and selling the copious quantities of moss on the estate
is hardly divorced from practicality, given the World War I
battlefield discovery that moss, used when bandages ran out, not
only has absorbent qualities, but anti-bacterial ones. The children
are managed and disciplined, but never in ways that crush their
spirits. Although we don't realize it until we feel the force
behind one of the film's payoffs, Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio's
Moira is more than the children's passive mother and Edward's
indulgent wife. When the crunch comes, she reveals convincing
degrees of strength that mark her as her mother's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that a film gives us a family that feels like a
family, but this one does, and at no cost to their distinctive
personalities and individual traits. Young Norman does all that can
be asked in the role of the boy who learns a lot between his 10th
and 11th birthdays. Without ever descending to cuteness, the film
convinces us as well that the adults must manage a bit of growing
up, too, and do. The detailing is beautiful and loving, not just
the period authenticity and visual handsomeness, but the emotional
detailing. ``My Life So Far'' is one of those rare films that gives
us a life, several lives in fact. It deepens steadily, not just in
nostalgia, but like a novel whose characters stay with you. And yet
its most magical moments _ as when a French aviator lands in a
field on the estate and romances one of Fraser's teenage sisters _
seem just as natural a part of the rituals of life at that sweet
little latter-day Camelot called Kiloran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
