<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MYSTERY-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYSTERY MEN' UNRAVELS COMIC HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MYSTERY MEN 
Directed by: Kinka Usher 
Screenplay by: Neil Cuthbert &AMP; Brent Forrester (based on Bob
Buirden's comic book) 
Starring: Hank Azaria, Claire Forlani, Janeane Garofalo, Eddie
izzard, Greg Kinnear, Jenifer Lewis, William H. Macy, Kel Mitchell,
Lena Olin, Pras, Paul Reubens, Geoffrey Rush, Ben Stiller, Wes
Studi, Tom Waits 
Running time: 120 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (comic action violence and crude humor) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' begins terrifically, then dwindles away to
overextended ordinariness in its action sequences. Maybe it's
because its comic-book anti-heroes don't really specialize in
action, but in aspiration. The fact that they don't even have much
in the way of powers, let alone superpowers, is the gimmick in this
film drawn from the popular Dark Horse comic book. ``Mystery Men''
goofs with ironic verve on the whole idea of comic strip heroes.
There's something desperate, and desperately funny, in the idea of
a team of losers trying to parlay their miniscule gifts into heroic
displays of crime-fighting prowess.
</P>
<P>
   In an apocryphal Champion City, stylistically in the dark comic
book gothic mainstream with its looming, nocturnal,
half-futuristic, half-retro look, three would-be gangbusters begin
by falling on their faces while a gang of thugs is routed by the
city's official hero, Greg Kinnear's Captain Amazing. So The Blue
Raja, The Shoveler and Mr. Furious decide to beef up their team. To
their amazement, Hank Azaria's Blue Raja (who wears a turban,
affects a British accent and throws forks and spoons at the enemy),
William H. Macy's hard-hatted digger called The Shoveler and Ben
Stiller's Mr. Furious, whose temple veins bulge when he gets angry
though nothing else happens, find that most of the applicants don't
even measure up to their miserable level.
</P>
<P>
   Still, from beneath this commentary on the type of person who
needs a heroic alter ego, there emerge four more team members. The
best of them is Paul Reubens' flatulence-spewing character known as
The Spleen and Janeane Garofalo's Bowler, who routs bad guys by
aiming at them a supernatural bowling ball in which is encased her
murdered father's presumably vengeful skull. Amusingly, the story
has Captain Amazing trip himself up on his own hubris. Because he
has run out of villains to look heroic against, the muscular but
dim Captain suggests that arch-criminal Casanova Frankenstein,
played by Geoffrey Rush, be paroled. He is, and the first thing he
does is take out Captain Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   So re-enter The Mystery Men and Garofalo's Mystery Woman. It's
at this point that the film begins to slide and eventually plummet
downhill. Rush is a wonderful actor, but there's nothing scary
about this Frankenstein, which means that he's left with little
more than empty posturing to work with in Frankenstein's disco
castle. In his maroon velvet, he suggests an ``Austin Powers''
refugee. Unlike the sardonic dialogue in the film's first half, the
material in the second half is remarkably punchless. Macy, Stiller
and Garofalo, whose character should have been called The Martini
because she's that dry, give it what diminished pizazz it has,
although Claire Forlani's tough waif of a waitress and Tom Waits'
junkyard genius are plusses, too. ``Mystery Men'' certainly is more
fizzy and original than most of what's come down the pike this
summer, although that's not saying much. Too bad its second half
doesn't live up to its first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ABBADO-BOS &LR;      08-06 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ABBADO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAUDIO ABBADO'S FULL CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ Forty-one summers ago a 25-year-old Italian
musician arrived in Boston, where a customs inspector read his
visa. ``Conductor,'' it read on the line for ``profession.'' ``Do
you mean you drive a bus?'' the inspector asked Claudio Abbado.
</P>
<P>
   Abbado was en route to Tanglewood, where he planned to spend the
summer as a student at the Berkshire Music Center (now the
Tanglewood Music Center). He didn't know anyone, and he didn't
speak much English. But a young couple befriended him and offered
him a ride to Lenox in their car. They wished him good luck and
told him they were sure he would excel, and he did; they were in
the audience when it was announced that he had won the Koussevitzky
Prize as the most promising and accomplished conductor of the
summer _ which took some doing, because one of his classmates was
Zubin Mehta.
</P>
<P>
   Abbado has spent the last three decades at the summit of his
profession. He has held some of the world's most prestigious
musical posts, including artistic director of La Scala in Milan,
music director of the Vienna State Opera (a post in which he will
be succeeded by Seiji Ozawa), and music director of the Berlin
Philharmonic. Today he holds the post of artistic director of the
Salzburg Easter Festival, and serves as artistic director of the
Chamber Orchestra of Europe and the Gustav Mahler Youth Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The youth orchestra is currently in residence at Tanglewood,
where Abbado will conduct it Saturday night in a performance of
Mahler's Seventh Symphony, Abbado's first appearance in the
Berkshires since his student days.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday noon he joined his manager, assistant conductor, and
members of the Tanglewood Music Center Orchestra and the youth
orchestra for lunch in a tent set up next to Seiji Ozawa Hall; a
special guest at the table was violinist Robert di Pasquale, whose
brother, Joseph di Pasquale, was formerly principal violist of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra, and one of the first musicians to greet
Abbado in 1958. The conductor is interview-shy, having been
scorched by the press in Italy and Austria, but agreed to let this
reporter sit in.
</P>
<P>
   The maestro, looking trim and at least two decades younger than
his 66 years, spoke with great affection of his earlier time at
Tanglewood, and of the opportunity to hear such great conductors as
Charles Munch and Pierre Monteux. ``What did I conduct myself?
Well, I remember Schubert's `Unfinished' Symphony, the First Violin
Concerto of Prokofiev, with the concertmaster as soloist,
Tchaikovsky's `Romeo and Juliet,' and a piece by Anton von Webern.
That summer Eleazar de Carvahlo did most of the teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbado is the founder of the youth orchestra, and his eyes light
up when he talks about it. ``It all goes back to 1978 when I helped
start the European Community Youth Orchestra. When we played
concerts in Salzburg and in Lucerne, young musicians came to see me
because they were unhappy that they could not play in the orchestra
_ Austria and Switzerland were not members of the European
Community. They didn't think it was right that they couldn't play,
and I agreed with them . . . But it just couldn't work for legal
and bureaucratic reasons, so when I went to Vienna in 1986, I
decided to form the Mahler Youth Orchestra so that we could include
young players from Austria, from Prague, from Bratislava, and other
places. It was not so easy at the beginning. I remember when we
were supposed to perform Schoenberg's `Gurrelieder' in Berlin, I
was told that the young players from East Berlin would not be
allowed to play. I told them that if that were the case, I would
not be allowed to conduct, so visas and permissions were granted
for the young players from Leipzig, Dresden, and East Berlin. That
was a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Later the youth orchestra played in Moscow, with young Evgeny
Kissin as soloist. Mikhail Gorbachev attended the concert and
afterward talked to Abbado. ``This was always my dream,'' Gorbachev
said, ``to have all Europe working together.'' Today there are
musicians from Russia, Kazakhstan, and all of the Baltic republics
in the orchestra. Abbado is proud that musicians led the way. ``Of
course, everything is easier with musicians than it is with
politicians!''
</P>
<P>
   Over the 13 years of its existence, the orchestra has produced
many alumni who are playing in the major orchestras of Europe _
there are 11 alumni in the Vienna Philharmonic, for example, and
eight in Dresden's Staatskapelle.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra rehearses, performs, and tours at Eastertime and
in the summer. Over the years Abbado has conducted many of the
symphonies of Mahler with the orchestra. He chose it to play for
performances of Mozart's ``Don Giovanni'' in a staging by the
legendary Peter Brook at Aix-en-Provence in France. The orchestra's
guest conductors have included Bernard Haitink, Pierre Boulez,
Daniele Gatti, and Kent Nagano; Seiji Ozawa will lead the orchestra
in concerts in Salzburg next season. At Abbado's urging, the
orchestra has also created an Akademie for advanced musical study
in Bolzano, Italy; it will meet in the winter, and all the students
will be supported by scholarships. Five European cities, in
rotation, host the orchestra for rehearsals. ``This is a joy and an
honor for us,'' Abbado says, ``and it is good for the cultural life
of the town.''
</P>
<P>
   The two weeks in Tanglewood lead off a tour that will take the
orchestra to Venezuela and Cuba. ``There used to be fantastic
orchestras in Cuba,'' Abbado says. ``Erich Kleiber was a music
director there. They asked us if we could please do something; they
are in danger of losing a great musical culture. They lack many
basic things today, so all of our players are bringing along things
like good strings. Now the Tanglewood musicians have joined them in
making gifts, which is a very nice gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the tour, Abbado is conducting Mahler's Seventh
Symphony; at the close of the tour it goes to Berlin to play the
work in a Mahler festival that will encompass the composer's
complete works. The Seventh Symphony is probably the least-often
played of his cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for this,'' Abbado says, ``is that it is one of the
most difficult. Mahler was a genius who wrote way over the limits
of his time. Even today the Scherzo sounds crazy. For me, the
second movement is the most beautiful. In it you can hear a direct
connection to Schubert.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbado's homes are in Engadin, Switzerland, and on the northwest
coast of Sardinia; he is looking forward to spending more time
there. ``The fantastic thing about music,'' he says, ``is that
there are not limits. You can always find something new in a great
score, no matter how often you have studied and conducted it. I
learned a very great lesson from Peter Brook when we were working
on `Don Giovanni.' We took all the time we needed _ and `Don
Giovanni' is an opera I have already conducted many times. We
auditioned more than 100 singers for the roles, and then we took
months to rehearse it. The young British conductor Daniel Harding
was my assistant, and he conducted one of the performances; he did
it so well that I told him he could take over the production the
next summer. It was wonderful to be able to take all the time I
wanted to, all the time the work needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have commitments through 2002, but after that I plan to
spend more time for myself, studying more. There is so much more to
discover in a work like Wagner's `Tristan und Isolde.' I did it
this season in a semi-staged performance with the Berlin
Philharmonic, and next summer I will do it again in Salzburg. But
`Tristan' is not something you can prepare in two weeks or two
months. I ask myself why there are all these limits set by the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the late 1970s and early 1980s, Abbado conducted some of
the finest Boston Symphony Orchestra concerts of the period,
including a Mahler ``Resurrection'' Symphony that no one who heard
it will ever forget. Naturally BSO management figures have been
anxiously scrutinizing Abbado's face for signs of renewed interest
in the orchestra and in Tanglewood, particularly now that Ozawa has
announced his resignation _ ``You need to be careful,'' was
Abbado's advice to his successor in Vienna. ``You should do only
what you like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a direct question about whether he is having a
good time at Tanglewood, Abbado smiles and says yes, he is. He was
in the audience Sunday afternoon for Ozawa's concert with the
combined Mahler Youth Orchestra and the TMC Orchestra. It was
``fantastic,'' he says. ``Afterwards, Seiji made a speech and said
how it was his dream that young musicians from all over the world
could come together like this to play. He's right _ this is a very
big dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
