<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-BOS &LR;      08-06 1779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAD TIMES FOR THE MEN IN BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a small anteroom up the stairway adjacent to the
home clubhouse at Fenway Park, the entire unwieldy morass was
condensed into a tidy, if awkward, microcosm.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garcia, Mike Reilly, Laz Diaz, and Brian O'Nora had just
worked last Friday night's Red Sox-Yankees game seamlessly,
unobtrusively, in complete cooperation, the ideal of all umpires.
Now the crew members were preparing to go their ways. Their
separate ways, which wouldn't have been the case a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   This group, headed by Garcia, represented the ideological
spectrum in the imbroglio that has resulted in the dismissal of 22
of the 66 major league umpires, effective Sept. 2. It also has
created a gulf of dissension within the union ranks, turning
longtime friends against one another on some issues and in other
cases making enemies of people who invariably describe their select
fraternity as ``like a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, a 25-year American League veteran, will be out of work
next month. Reilly, who has been in the big leagues for 22 years,
the last 14 on Garcia's crew, will be retained. Diaz and O'Nora,
both young minor league officials who are sporadically called up to
fill in for vacationing or injured major leaguers, will become
full-time, full-fledged AL umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, vice president of the Major League Baseball Umpires
Association, was among the 57 members who convened in a
Philadelphia airport hotel meeting room July 14 and, at the urging
of counsel Richie Phillips, submitted their resignations en masse,
effective Sept. 1, as a method of expediting negotiations on a
collective bargaining agreement for next year. Within days, several
umpires solicited private counsel, were advised that the
resignations, rather than being a bargaining spur, left them
vulnerable to dismissal at the discretion of the American and
National Leagues, and rescinded their letters.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that this sundering of solidarity severely compromised
their position, the remaining umpires who had signed resignation
forms rescinded them July 27. But by then, the leagues already had
hired 25 replacements _ mostly Triple A International and Pacific
Coast Leaguers who had some major league exposure as fill-ins. As a
result, there wasn't room for all the would-be returnees, and only
some of the rescisions were accepted. Garcia's was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   So on this night at Fenway, he was sitting in a corner of the
umpires' room, sipping a soda during a lengthy rant to reporters
about the injustice he perceived. He called Major League Baseball
officials ``cowards,'' criticized those umpires who had rescinded
their resignations before July 27 as ``making things easier for
Major League Baseball to do what it wants to do _ kick the umpires'
ass, teach us renegades a lesson'' _ and vowed to fight ``all the
way to the Supreme Court if I have to; I want my job back.''
</P>
<P>
   While Garcia harangued, there was only silence among his
partners. Reilly, one of the group that withdrew their resignations
before July 27, finished shaving and dressed, declining to comment
about his action ``because I've said everything I had to say about
it and I don't want to keep going into it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Nora and Diaz nervously ate their postgame meals, with
Garcia's oratory as background, and refused to discuss their good
fortune, which will result in a salary boost from $12,000 to the
major league minimum of $75,000 annually. It's not that they were
left speechless by this chance of a lifetime; rather, they could
see no benefit in injecting themselves further into such a
sensitive situation. ``It's my personal preference not to say
anything,'' said O'Nora.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down at the floor, Diaz said, ``I'm not going to comment
on anything.'' Asked if the crew members were staying at the same
hotel, he said, ``I'm not going to comment on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As Garcia's colleagues left the room _ Reilly with his son, Diaz
and O'Nora in tandem _ they looked almost sheepishly his way,
waving goodbye. Garcia interrupted his denunciations and called out
enthusiastically, ``Hey, see you guys later.''
</P>
<P>
   Clad only in a towel, he proceeded to address the conflict for
another hour, emphasizing that, as his farewells had indicated, he
was trying not to take this personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like what these guys did but I respect them
professionally,'' he said. ``When we're on the field, it's
forgotten. They work their (expletive) asses off. Anyone who
doesn't work his (expletive) ass off, I don't want him on my
crew.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, these crew members are welcome to Garcia. And
they do indeed stay in the same hotel. But he won't deny that the
union chasm has created palpable tension, if not open hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Reilly told me what he was going to do and said, `I don't
want it to ruin our friendship,' '' recounted Garcia. ``I said, `I
hope it doesn't ruin our friendship.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And these kids, I taught most of them, worked with them in
spring training and on off days, not because I had to but because I
wanted to. I've had them all over to my house (in Clearwater, Fla.)
for dinner. My wife has cooked for them. Brian O'Nora has been like
a son to me. I can't say what I'd do if I were one of those kids
because I've never been in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the defectors, ``these are grown men with families,''
said Garcia. ``Everyone is entitled to their own opinions. I just
wish they'd expressed their opinions at the meeting or in the
conference calls we had about every other day afterward. Nobody
ever did, but then we'd start hearing, `This guy's rescinded; that
guy's rescinded.' If they'd let us know that beforehand, we
wouldn't have taken the action we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hostility on my part, but I've told them all how
disappointed I am. I'm hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The declarations of independence _ or suicide notes, as some
umpires consider them _ were ready and waiting when the union
members were summoned to Philadelphia for a mandatory meeting the
day after the All-Star Game in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did they think when nine umpires didn't show?'' wondered
Dave Phillips, a 29-year AL veteran who was at the meeting but soon
rescinded his resignation. ``Did they figure all these guys had
flight connection problems or were going to Disney World? They were
rebelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension and speculation were at a full broil on this scalding
July day. Many umpires were under the impression that they would be
taking action on a proposed one-day wildcat strike, even though
their current collective bargaining agreement contains a no-strike
clause.
</P>
<P>
   There had been an air of suspicion ever since last November when
commissioner Bud Selig named former Oakland Athletics general
manager Sandy Alderson as executive vice president for baseball
operations. One of his mandates was to evaluate the umpiring with
an eye toward centralizing the operation rather than giving each
league jurisdiction over its own crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took action because of what was coming out of Major League
Baseball,'' said Garcia. ``They were going to straighten us out,
weed out the lower-rated umpires, fire people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a matter of interpretation. Hoping to get a jump on
negotiations before the current collective bargaining agreement
expires Dec. 31, Alderson and special assistant to the commissioner
for baseball operations Ralph Nelson met with union president Jerry
Crawford, an NL umpire for 23 years, at Phoenix in late May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it has been portrayed was that we had a list of 20
umpires we wanted terminated,'' said Alderson. ``I don't know where
that came from. There's never been a list of 20 umpires; there's
never been a list of one.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, added Alderson, who flew in for the Phoenix meeting on
his son's birthday because he considered it vital, he reassured
Crawford that MLB had no intention of firing any umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent was and is to set up standards for the umpires to
meet,'' said Alderson, whose house in California's Marin County was
barraged by marbles recently, an incident that is under
investigation. ``Most would meet them right away. There was never
any intent to dismiss those who didn't; that wouldn't be fair.
Rather, we'd give them time and support in the form of training and
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has a similar recollection. ``I distinctly remember Sandy
saying, `I don't want to make a blanket statement that we're not
going to fire an umpire if there's cause,' '' he said, `` `but it
is not our intention to fire anyone for what they do on the field.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's response, according to Nelson: ``I don't trust you,''
meaning management.
</P>
<P>
   The union president recalls an entirely different message from
the meeting: ``My impression was that there were going to be
firings. My feeling all along from my discussion with Sandy was
that his intent was to make things easier for firing. He wanted us
to grease the skids.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Alderson and Nelson departed believing they had
made significant headway and told Crawford that they hoped to have
a proposal ready for the union's consideration by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Nelson began devoting 12-hour days to
formulating a centralized umpiring system, which would include
five-man crews so that minor leaguers wouldn't have to be brought
in as vacation replacements; a considerable reduction in travel
schedules; and substantial cost reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson calculated that each umpire's travel would be decreased
by 12,000-15,000 miles annually, a savings of $250,000 in that
department alone. ``And what we contemplated,'' said Alderson,
``was giving that money back to the umpires in the form of
increased per diem'' from the current $240.
</P>
<P>
   Centralization long had been a point of contention, especially
in the NL, ``but we were going to grandfather it,'' said Nelson,
``so that umpires who wanted to stay in one league could choose
that schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   But because they spent so much time on the logistics of
centralization, Alderson and Nelson realized they couldn't meet the
July 1 deadline for presenting a comprehensive contract proposal.
In late June, they advised Crawford that they now would aim for an
August proposal but would like to conduct exploratory meetings with
him in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that would be fine,'' said Crawford. ``From that
time, I didn't hear anything from them for two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
