<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-IRON-GIANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IRON GIANT': A CHARMING, OUTSIZED BUDDY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE IRON GIANT 
Directed by: Brad Bird 
Screenplay by: Tim McCanlies (based on Ted Hughes' book) 
With the voices of: Jennifer Aniston, Harry Connick, Jr., Vin
Diesel, James Gammon, Cloris Leachman, Christopher McDonald, John
Mahgoney, Eli Marienthal, M. Emmet Walsh 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' is a solid, not to say ironclad, winner in
the less than overcrowded family animation arena. Set in 1957, at
the height of atomic and Red Scare paranoia, it justifies its
period look and avoids the deadening pall of political correctness
lurking in its antiweaponry allegory. In transferring the story
from Ted Hughes's famous children's book, ``The Iron Man,'' and
Americanizing this British classic, director Brad Bird had a lot of
little decisions to make and one big one. He gets the big one
resoundingly right by putting the friendship between a 9-year-old
boy and a giant robot at the film's center and keeping it there.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the huge robot emerges mysteriously from the sea.
In this new animated version, it drops from space, landing in the
ocean off the coast of Maine, just in time to rescue a storm-tossed
fisherman before disappearing into the woods. The charm of the
robot lies in the fact that while it's big, it's also an innocent.
Like a big baby animal, its appetite is as huge as it is. It meets
the spunky kid named Hogarth Hughes by creeping out of the pine
forest one night and scarfing down Hogarth's TV antenna. Hogarth,
at home alone because his mother, Annie, must work late as a
waitress, follows the metal-eating robot into the woods and saves
its life by shutting off the juice when the robot starts chomping
on a power station.
</P>
<P>
   The boy and the robot reverse parent-child roles and become
friends. When the pragmatic kid realizes he's got to hide his big
friend because the nearby town with the tongue-in-cheek name of
Rockwell can't handle the reality of the robot, he cleverly
persuades the neighborhood hippie, a beatnik sculptor, to hide the
robot in his junkyard, which also solves the food supply problem.
The goatteed hippie named Dean, slyly designed to invoke early
Brando, and voiced with an engaging drawl by Harry Connick Jr., is
a plus. So is Hogarth's spirited and loving single mom, voiced by
Jennifer Aniston. The film's need for a heavy is filled by a nasty
fed played with sneering duplicitous lowness by Christopher
McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   But it's in the chemistry between the boy and the robot that the
payoff is to be found. The drawing and construction of ``The Iron
Giant'' are more sophisticated than its deceptively simple style
might lead you to believe. The film actually succeeds in making you
believe that the big hunk of iron not only has feelings, but
feelings of childlike purity that are shaken when he sees a deer
shot by hunters and Hogarth explains what to the robot are the
hitherto alien concepts of killing and dying. The film makes a
laudable distinction between dying, which it presents as part of
the natural cycle of death and rebirth, and killing, which is
aggressively different.
</P>
<P>
   This distinction is brought to a dramatic climax when Hogarth
discovers that the robot is a formidable weapon that goes into the
attack mode, but only in self-defense. When the hysterical fed
calls down the wrath of the armed forces upon the robot, the
question becomes who and what, if anything, will be left standing.
There's more than one moral to be taken from this allegorical fable
with its engaging central characters. Fittingly enough, given its
'50s atmosphere and references to Cold War politics and period
sci-fi, ``The Iron Giant'' is a plea for arms control that must
have been reassuring in the nuclear world of Hughes's own two
children, for whom he wrote the story in 1968, after the death of
their mother, the poet Sylvia Plath. When the robot unleashes a
death beam and the boy stops it from doing more by rebukingly
saying, ``Guns kill,'' it may have made kids feel a little less
helpless in a world filled with terrifying forces. There's a lot to
like in this film that only the NRA could hate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
