<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SIXTH-BOS &LR;      08-06 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SIXTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIXTH SENSE' SUFFERS FROM A REFINED SENSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SIXTH SENSE 
Written and directed by: M. Night Shyamalan 
Starring: Bruce Willis, Haley Joel Osment, Toni Collette, Olivia
Williams, Trevor Morgan, Donnie Wahlberg, Mischa Barton, Glenn
Fitzgerald, Bruce Norris 
Running time: 115 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (intense thematic material and violent images) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' is the kind of flawed movie that's worth
sticking with. It's got an eerie flavor all its own. Also, a lot of
things that appear not to add up eventually do make sense in light
of the film's surprise ending. Getting to that ending is sometimes
a chore, but the grave clarity with which the story is filmed helps
knit together what seem its disjointed parts. At times, ``The Sixth
Sense'' seems unanchored, floaty, like a dream. It's somber and
heavy, but justifiably so, since its protagonist is an
eight-year-old Philadelphia boy who sees ghosts. Young Haley Joel
Osment's face looks strained and pained, again understandably so,
since the ghosts are of people who died unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   It is this legion of troubled spirits that get the boy down. His
face, too pinched for one so young, is also wise with the knowledge
that the ghosts, some of whom died horrific deaths, mean him no
personal harm. It's just that he's stuck with their unrest because
he happens to be sensitive to them. And he knows they wish to use
him to get even. Enter Bruce Willis, as a children's therapist, in
a performance as subdued as any he's ever given, in keeping with
the mournful tone of the film. Essentially, the doc sets himself
the job of becoming the boy's exorcist, following a traumatic
experience that he himself recently underwent when a troubled
patient (Donnie Wahlberg, who makes you feel the character's
torment) invades the doc's home, excoriates him for failing to
help, then shoots the doc and turns the gun on himself, fatally.
</P>
<P>
   Willis's doc, slow to recover, finds his confidence shaken and
would prefer not to add to his stress levels by facing up to the
fact that his marriage is drifing into trouble, much of which stems
from the fact that he has grown distant to his wife (Olivia
Williams), an antiques dealer. Writer-director M. Night Shyamalan
has no trouble steeping the film in disquieting atmosphere. Adding
to the overall uneasiness is the boy's loving but bewildered single
mom, played by Toni Collette. She shuttles between protective
instincts and frustration at her inability to make sense of the
things her son tells her, things she can only regard as troubling
fantasies. Willis's soft-spoken doc believes the boy, though, and
is resolved to lift him out of the trough of despond into which he
has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely to the psychologist that there's more than
divorce trauma working on the eight-year-old boy, who has evolved
rituals involving toy soldiers and religious figures in an
improvised safety zone where he hides when it all becomes too much
for him. As the film progresses, so do the boy's terrifying visions
of people who died violent deaths. Not that Shyamalan is
exploitative in terms of splashing gore across the screen. Just the
reverse. There's a dolorous integrity about ``The Sixth Sense''
that unfortunately translates into ponderousness much of the time.
``The Sixth Sense'' is the only horror film this year that
underplays its horrors. But it's also the kind of film you respect
more than you're grabbed by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
