<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BEAUTIFUL-MAN-BO     08-06 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BEAUTIFUL-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTIFUL MAN' SHOWS EXCESSES OF ANOTHER ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MOST BEAUTIFUL MAN IN EXISTENCE 
The Scandalous Life of Alexander Lesassier 
By Lisa Rosner 
University of Pennsylvania Press, 202 pp., $29.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a novelist of little merit, a faithless husband, and a
physician who faked his thesis. He was by turns vain, charming and
seductive, and lazy and entitled and, ultimately, hobbled by
scandal. In fact, Alexander Lesassier is a rogue more likely to pop
up as a character in a Restoration comedy than anywhere else. But
in historian Lisa Rosner's hands, the trunk full of journals he
left behind provide fresh insights into the development of the
medical profession and English society in the early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   For a modern reader, ``The Most Beautiful Man in Existence'' is
also an oddly reassuring reminder that no single era has a corner
on sexual license, lying, family feuds, and overextended credit.
</P>
<P>
   Rosner, professor of history at Richard Stockton College in New
Jersey, could have made Lesassier a buffoon. Instead, she sees him
as a rather hapless figure in a pivotal time for medicine. Medicine
was turning into a science, and although antibiotics, germ theory,
and a full understanding of anatomy were still in the future,
Rosner documents their stirrings in London, Edinburgh, and the
British military. With Lesassier as her foil, she is able to do so
with humanity and humor. She is aided by Lesassier's penchant for
self-creation and for recording every small triumph, slight insult,
and steamy sexual liaison in the pages of his diary.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in genteel poverty by an irascible father, Lesassier
began his journal in 1803, when he was 16, with a teen-age lament:
``This day through the ill usage of my Father I resolved on leaving
him: but am not yet certain what part of the world to move to.''
</P>
<P>
   Resources were scarce in the family, and Lesassier had to
scramble to try to realize his daydreams of independence and
leisure. Without the money for a formal medical education, he
served an apprenticeship with an apothecary and audited courses at
the Royal College of Physicians in Edinburgh, finally winning a job
as hospital mate in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The life of a soldier not to mention the splendid uniform and
cocked hat appealed to Lesassier. ``The fifteen months that
Lesassier spent with the 42nd Regiment in England were probably the
happiest of his life,'' Rosner writes. He took long walks, read
romantic potboilers and plied the social circuit. ``He lived, in
fact, as much like an independent gentleman as he would ever
manage, drawing his pay with very little work, since there were
very few calls on his medical or surgical skills.''
</P>
<P>
   And he womanized. ``As the historian Anthony Fletcher has noted,
beneath the facade of sophistication of Georgian society was a
`deeply selfish set of sexual mores and an unabashed male
hedonism.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lusty subplots run throughout Lesassier's journals. Although he
marries, hoping for an inheritance, he energetically pursues
affairs with single women, married women, maids, and contessas. He
begins an obstetrical practice and has sex with scores of patients.
Short of cash, he writes ``Edward Neville,'' a novel based on his
fantasy of family and redemption, but it sells poorly. If only he
had applied the same energy to medicine; his blunders there were
``legion,'' Rosner writes. Crisis seems inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scandal, to borrow his earlier phrase, was poised to attack
him openmouthed, and in the fall of 1822 he set a consecutive chain
of events in motion that linked his name with scandal for years to
come.'' His affair with Lady Louisa Kintore became the talk of
Edinburgh after a letter was intercepted by her husband. His wife,
Catherine, divorced him, and his creditors sued.
</P>
<P>
   As he approached middle age, his roistering behavior began to
pall. As a plaintive journal entry on his 40th birthday in
September 1827 puts it: ``I am shocked to say I am forty!! .. I
blush to think how very old I am, &AMP; how little good I have done
either for others or myself.'' Ever the escape artist, he rejoined
the military and died in 1839 during the First Afghan War.
</P>
<P>
   Lesassier's personal papers, used as evidence in his divorce,
languished in a trunk at the medical college in Edinburgh until
1987, when they were put in order by an archivist. He is a fluid,
vivid writer, Rosner notes, and is never boring. His journals were
``his most trusted friend. He imparted every thought to them,
confided every misfortune, sought consolation, commanded their
secrecy. Whether in the end they served faithfully, or betrayed
him, I leave to you, Dear Reader, to decide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-THOMAS-BOS &LR;      08-06 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THOMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `CROWN AFFAIR' TO REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE THOMAS CROWN AFFAIR 
Directed by: John McTiernan 
Screenplay by: Leslie Dixon &AMP; Kurt Wimmer (based on Alan R.
Trustman's script for the original) 
Starring: Pierce Brosnan, Rene Russo, Denis Leary, Ben Gazzara,
Frankie Faison, Faye Dunaway, James Saito 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: R (some sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' with Pierce Brosnan and Rene Russo
playing the roles Steve McQueen and Faye Dunaway originated in
1968, is a little more than just your average remake. It switches
the locale from Boston to New York City and goes a few other places
the original didn't go. The first time around, the jaded
thrill-seeking zillionaire engineered a bank heist. This time it's
an art heist, a Monet from the Met. Art thefts are inherently more
interesting than bank robberies, especially when the rich thief
actually steals the painting with his own hands, as he does here,
instead of just masterminding the caper from afar, which was the
case the first time out.
</P>
<P>
   But the real motor of ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' then and now,
as the double entendre in its title proclaims, is the sexual chess
between Crown and the insurance investigator who goes after him
frontally, telling him she's convinced he's the thief and that
she's going to get him, figuring that he'll be unable to resist the
sexual challenge, since challenge is all that turns him on at this
stage in his life. Neither character is deficient in the hubris
department, which adds to the fun. It feeds the feeling that we're
watching two jungle cats stalking one another, trying not to lick
their lips.
</P>
<P>
   The original version peaked in one of film's great sex scenes _
an actual chess game between McQueen and Dunaway in Crown's Beacon
Hill mansion. The only nakedness involved was the nakedness of the
sexual power struggle between two characters so heavily armored and
self-protective that it was hard to like either of them. Then
McQueen literally blinked first, becoming the first one to show
vulnerability, leaving himself open to checkmate. In the new film,
Russo's ex-bounty-hunter turned insurance investigator is the more
vulnerable of the two. She's the one who falls for Crown, yet seems
the stronger for being able to gamble on jettisoning a bit of the
control that has served her so well.
</P>
<P>
   Russo has it all. She's glamorous, tough, full-blooded. Brosnan
isn't bad, but he seems to have brought with him from his James
Bond films a little more suavity than the film needs. When McQueen
played the role, he brought to it a restlessness that made him seem
about to jump out of his skin. We could believe in his need to push
the envelope by speeding, gliding, making high-stakes bets on the
golf course and aimlessly tearing up Cape Cod's beaches by racing
his dune buggy up and down them. In these environmentally conscious
days, dune buggy sequences would be unthinkable. Instead, Brosnan's
Bond pushes the envelope with a catamaran. He's OK, especially in a
wittily choreographed climax, but at times seems imprisoned in
elegance in a way that McQueen, who spoke a louder body language,
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   This new ``Thomas Crown Affair'' is more elaborate and inventive
than the first, from a Trojan horse beginning to a bravura
Magritte-flavored closing caper. But while Russo fills the screen
with tempestuousness, this slicker but more hollow new version
misses the primal predatoriness of the original. It tries harder to
humanize the characters, coax them out from behind their defenses,
have them talk more about trust and feelings. This new earnestness
is not always a plus. The original had more fun with the shallow
mercenariness of its characters. But Denis Leary's working-class
police detective, always expressing more than he's saying, unsure
of whose side Russo is on, represents one of this film's undisputed
advances over the original. And there's a bonus. Dunaway, written
in as Crown's therapist, appears in a series of punctuating
vignettes that are actually pretty funny. Instead of holding his
hand, she laughs at his Peter Pan immaturity and his fearful
concealments during his sessions with her. Dunaway dished out tough
love the first time around and she dishes it out here, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
