<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-SPIEGELMAN-BOS &LR;      08-06 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-SPIEGELMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIEGELMAN TAKES HIS PROVOCATIVE CAARTOONING INTO OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IAN SHAPIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Art Spiegelman loves to provoke, firing unpredictably
and with vitriol.The Queens, N.Y.native is as famous (or infamous)
for his 1992 Pulitzer Prize-winning Holocaust cartoon book,
``Maus'', as he is for his New Yorker covers alluding to sensitive
news stories, such as portraying a Hasidic Jew smooching with an
African-American woman in 1993, and, in March, a New York beat cop
aiming a gun at miniature human targets in a shooting gallery. (The
illustration sparked a protest by members of the New York Police
Department.)
</P>
<P>
   Now Spiegelman, 51, is experimenting, interested less in
triggering controversial issues and more with amplifying his
medium. But into what? Try opera. For the past few years,
Spiegelman has been testing his hand at writing a libretto,
attempting to mix the seemingly opposite art forms into a
cartoon-musical theater. These ``comic operas,'' as he prefers,
involve musical theater amid projected cartoons. At the American
Repertory Theatre, he is presenting ``Drawn to Death,'' a
work-in-progress that serves as the penultimate program this summer
of the Institute of the Arts &AMP; Civic Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of the Institute's programs, ``Drawn to Death''
harnesses its artistic energies to contemplate social issues. In
four scenes, the comic opera explores the tumultuous career and
characters of the comic book industry near the middle of the
century. In between those scenes, Spiegelman will insert his own
short comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see `Drawn to Death' as a kind of requiem to comics, that
it's about the rise and fall of the American comic, a medium that
was born and flourished in the 1930s and has now become
overshadowed and supplanted by television and movies,'' Spiegelman
explained in his Cambridge hotel room, smoking his eighth cigarette
in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The four scenes delve into the industry's more audacious _ not
to mention deranged _ comics pioneers, such as Bob Wood, author of
the popular 1940s comic book ``Crime Does Not Pay,'' who later went
on to bludgeon his wife; and Jack Cole, the creator of Plastic Man
and famed Playboy cartoonist, who ended up committing suicide in
1958.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``Drawn to Death'' is also very much about the
demise of the comics book industry. Led by music director Richard
Gordon and composer Van Dyke Parks, the four vocalists _ including
two from the Boston Lyric Opera Company _ perform parts of the 1954
U.S. Senate Hearings on Comic Books and Juvenile Delinquency; in
the final scene, they sing the actual Comics Code, laws that
hamstrung the artists' penchant for lurid violence and sexual
imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were even comic book burnings,'' Spiegelman said. ``We
all know there was a lot of censorship in that period, but
burnings?''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Drawn to Death,'' Spiegelman's cartoons aren't the only
things that dramatize comics' run-in with the First Amendment.Sure
enough, it's his libretto, together with Parks's score, that helps
symbolize the industry's raging but short-lived economic success in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The songs have a very Kurt Weill feel to them,'' Gordon said.
``There's a Germanic, ominous tone but Van Dyke has managed to
bring a pop/rock feel as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this performance depends on plenty of opera basics _
singing, spoken dialogue, and instrumental accompaniment _ ``Drawn
to Death'' relies unabashedly on technology. First, Spiegelman
draws his comics with computer programs such as Illustrator and
Photoshop. Then, those images are linked up via Apple G3 computers
to two projectors that splash the images onto a 40-by-25-foot scrim
divided into three panels.
</P>
<P>
   The show depends heavily on the digital projector in the back of
the theater. Looking like a boat's motor, it taps its power from
three microchips ``the size of postage stamps,'' explained
projectionist Paul Warner. Each of these chips contains some 80,000
hinged mirrors off which 8,000 lumens of light bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the lumens are reflecting -- instead of going through a
piece of film or panel _ they maintain more of their inherent
light, not getting diffused by passing through any medium,'' Warner
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Spiegelman, seeing his comic strips magnified to the nth
degree can be satisfying, but stretching the medium's capabilities
presents even more of a challenge _ if only because comics do not
necessarily depend on the passage of time, whereas theater does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting to see how a comic strip would move if
it was onstage, because comics are a way of murdering time and
turning it into space,'' Spiegelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics allow you to go back in time by shifting your eyes
left,'' he said. ``It's a mistake to think of (one) as a storyboard
for a film; comics have properties of their own: directness,
intimacy _ the fact that you're able to hold a temporal even in
your head by seeing it. . . . Now I'm trying to see what happens
when the elements of theater and comics collide.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of reverence for his craft _ and a willingness to
remain versatile in an age of increased specialization _ that makes
Art Spiegelman one ofthe world's most acclaimed and most vilified
arts figures.
</P>
<P>
   His New Yorker covers, especially, have made his work more
accessible and has given the publication's strait-laced image a
jolt. ``When I was putting together an early draft of the Institute
on the Arts and Civic Dialogue back in 1993, I thought about those
New Yorker covers because every special issue was a big chat,''
said Institute director Anna Deavere Smith. ``So I met up with Tina
Brown and she said, `You have to talk to Art Spiegelman.' '' The
cartoonist, however, is under contract with The New Yorker
(Spiegelman's wife, Francoise Mouly, is the art director) and will
not be working with Brown's Talk magazine anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Smith likes to think of Spiegelman as a provocateur: ``His
characters capture visually (the) problems, challenges, and
anxieties we all have. He's a trickster.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all have warmed to his work. In fact the Aug. 3 Village
Voice cover story by syndicated cartoonist and columnist Ted Rall
skewered Spiegelman, attacking his New Yorker covers _
``embarrassing vestiges'' in Rall's opinion _ as more of a
``softball pitch than kick in the privates.'' He also wrote that
Spiegelman's ``Maus'' was ``facile'' and ``one-dimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiegelman would not go on the record about Rall's story, but
was certainly miffed.
</P>
<P>
   But for most people in the art world, Spiegelman is up to a lot
of good _ and welcome good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful artist who uses the medium of cartooning _
and not just political cartoons, these are comic strips _ to make
powerful art,'' said ART artistic director Robert Brustein. ``Only
a few artists emerge out of that kind of field: Charlie Chaplin
being one of them, Art Spiegelman being another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
