<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES MOVE TO PROVIDE BENEFITS TO DOMESTIC PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ American Airlines will follow in the steps of
competitor United Airlines and offer a full package of benefits to
employees who have unmarried partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time was right, for our employees and our company,''
American Airlines spokesman Tim Kincaid said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by American, a unit of the AMR Corp. of Fort
Worth, Texas, came less than a week after United became the first
passenger air carrier in the country to provide benefits to
same-sex and opposite-sex domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   The two carriers join a growing number of companies,
universities and government agencies that do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The offers generally require employees to have a joint residence
and financial interdependence with an unmarried partner.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the two airlines is particularly
significant, however. They are part of an industry-supported
lawsuit challenging San Francisco's 2-year-old Equal Benefits
Ordinance. The law requires companies doing business with the city
to provide the same benefits to workers with unmarried partners as
they give to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines, in a lawsuit brought by the Air Transport
Association, contend that local jurisdictions have no authority
enacting mandates on the federally regulated industry.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has ruled that airlines do not have to provide
equal health and pension benefits to domestic partners, but must
provide other perks, such as flight discounts and bereavement
leave. The airlines are required to offer the limited package of
benefits even as they appeal that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chicago-based United, a division of the UAL Corp.,
and American have decided to go beyond the court order.
</P>
<P>
   They will extend medical and dental coverage, pension and life
insurance to employees worldwide who have domestic partners. United
has 97,000 employees around the globe; American has 110,000.
Neither company would speculate on how many workers would benefit
from the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Aftergut, chief assistant city attorney who has taken the
lead in defending San Francisco's law, welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``These airlines are recognizing that they were on the wrong
side of history and they're moving to the right side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid downplayed the role the San Francisco law had in the
company's decision, saying American already had been weighing
whether to offer the benefits. And, he noted, American and the
other airlines involved in the litigation, including United, are
pressing forward with their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This always was about principle. This never had anything to do
with discrimination against gays and lesbians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's ordinance becomes effective only when companies
enter into new contracts with the city or extend old ones. So far,
United and Federal Express are the only airlines flying into and
out of San Francisco International Airport that must adhere to the
ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express, based in Memphis, Tenn., has yet to say whether
it will offer domestic partners benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
