<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-06 1724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... for two weeks.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the umpiring union hierarchy, two possible strategies were
evolving. One was to strike, despite the contract stipulation to
the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board had authorized me to call the meeting to discuss a
strike,'' said Crawford. ``We felt there were unfair labor
practices going on and we had the right to strike. They had changed
the working conditions in the sense that Major League Baseball was
controlling things where the leagues in fact had done so before.''
</P>
<P>
   The other ploy, mass resignations, also was in the works, though
it was news to the nine-man board. ``It was never discussed in the
conference call preceding the meeting,'' said Dale Scott, who
resigned from the board in protest within a week of the
Philadelphia conclave, rescinded his resignation soon after, and is
being retained by the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Should the board have been consulted?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absoutely,'' said Scott. ``Richie maybe talked to one or two
people.''
</P>
<P>
   One, in fact. ``Richie had discussed the resignation plan with
me,'' said Crawford, who rescinded his resignation with the
majority of the group July 27 and will keep his job. ``The reason
we didn't discuss it with anyone else was that we didn't want it to
get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the 57 umpires gathered, the strike talk was quickly
dismissed. Then came the alternative proposal from Phillips, who
has been the union counsel since 1978 and whose confrontational
style has made him a lightning rod for criticism but also has
earned his constituency raises from less than $20,000 to a salary
range of $75,000-$225,000, plus an extra $20,000 per man from the
playoff pool, vacation time during the season, and greatly enhanced
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the case,'' said Crawford. ``I stood up and said, `It's
a very seriuous thing. I want legitimate questions, no rah-rah.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Questions were raised, according to some participants, but no
opposition was voiced. ``Dave Phillips gave a great speech,'' said
union supporter Terry Tata, who is being fired after 27 years in
the NL. ``Then he jumped ship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lie,'' said Phillips. ``This was a scam meeting.
(Richie Phillips) already had the resignation letters to be signed.
It was portrayed as being no big deal. They were to be used as a
negotiating tool. They were not necessarily going to be sent in. I
got up and said, `This may be the best idea you've had since 1979'
'' _ when the umpires staged the watershed strike that brought them
far better working conditions _ ``because he had intimated the
letters never were going to be sent out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, according to others in the room. ``We were under the
impression that he was going to send in the letters,'' said NL
umpire Dana DeMuth, a union supporter who will be retained.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the letters were distributed to the rank-and-file.
``One man created this fiasco, point blank _ Richie Phillips,''
said Dave Phillips, who not surprisingly is no relation. ``This was
going to be mass suicide, like Jim Jones in Guyana.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite as massive as the union figured. ``We passed out
the letters and the guys passed them back,'' said Garcia. ``We
didn't check them one by one. It turns out some guys hadn't signed
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the fallout was almost immediate. Dave Phillips
arrived home in Lake St. Louis, Mo., that night to discover four
reporters waiting to ask him about the resignations, which Richie
Phillips _ who did not return several calls from the Globe seeking
comment _ had announced on TV. Dave Phillips, who is on disability
leave because of back problems and had expressed concern outside
the meeting room to one of Richie Phillips's associates, Pat
Campbell, about the possible impact on his health benefits,
maintains that Campbell had reassured him, ``Don't worry, Dave.
We'll tear yours up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Phillips called the union office the next day and asked,
``Who's going to tear my letter up now, G. Gordon Liddy?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the letters were faxed to the leagues that day, July
15, while opponents of the strategy went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys got home,'' said Joe Brinkman, ``they talked to
their wives or whatever and thought, `What the hell did we just
do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   AL veterans Brinkman and John Hirschbeck, both of whom skipped
the Philadelphia meeting in protest, did more. They sought advice
about the situation from veteran sports agent/attorney Ron Shapiro,
who told them the action was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the prevailing opinion among labor and legal
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite many disputes and quite a few strikes,'' said
legendary former players' union executive director Marvin Miller,
``there was never one day of a (player) strike during the pendency
of a collective bargaining agreement. It was always months after a
collective bargaining agreement had expired. It's an important
principle: Not only did (the mass resignations) not honor the
contract, it put the members at a tremendous disadvantage. It was
(an illegal) concerted action. It's so appalling to have given
management so many options or weapons to use. I can't imagine what
was going through the minds of Phillips and the umpires. They gave
Major League Baseball carte blanche to break the union completely
or, as they have chosen to do, to select which ones they want to
keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Abrams, dean of the Northeastern University Law School who
teaches a course in sports law, doesn't consider the strategy
folly, just extremely risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a lot of pieces to fall into place,'' he said.
``What happens if you call a mass quit and nobody comes? They
really made some faulty predictions on what people would do.
Getting the minor leaguers to agree not to come up (which they
refused to do) was a tough one. If they'd pulled it off, it
would've been really interesting to see what would've happened,
though my guess is that (MLB) would have found someone on the
street to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't necessary. Brinkman and Hirschbeck retained private
counsel and started calling their fellow umpires urging them to do
likewise. Now the exodus was on. And even staunch union supporters
felt compelled to join the rescision parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either all or none,'' said DeMuth. ``That's the only way
you have a union.''
</P>
<P>
   With their umpiring ranks now overflowing, the leagues last week
announced the casualties among the veterans. The union countered
this week by filing an unfair labor practices charge with the
National Labor Relations Board in New York. While umpires hope
their position will be upheld, Abrams, for one, is dubious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere deep in baseball's central offices is a memo that
explains why they are keeping some and not others,'' he said.
``It's been drawn up by their skillful lawyers to protect them from
any action.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, men who have worked, traveled, and socialized with
one another for years are left to battle it out among themselves,
Garcia's claims of a tenuous peace to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Tata, who as a minor league umpire in 1970 rejected an offer to
serve as a fill-in during a proposed playoff strike by his major
league counterparts, branded this year's new hires ``scabs'' and
said of the veteran defectors, ``If there's a small fire on the
ship, you put it out. You don't jump overboard into the waters with
the sharks. I can tell you I'll be saving some postage this
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Scott, ``It's put a lot of guys at odds. Some who have been
friends for years aren't even speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness has filtered to the families. NL umpire Ed
Montague's wife, Marcia, sent a letter to Hirschbeck's wife,
Denise, July 28 in which she called Hirschbeck a ``Judas'' and
added, ``He shamed us all.'' Carbon copies were sent to every
umpire's spouse, prompting Major League Baseball to announce it
wouldn't tolerate harassment and exposing Ed Montague to possible
NL sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine why it would,'' said Marcia Montague. ``It was
definitely my words. I came up with it on my own. I hope people
appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Hirschbeck said, ``I really don't have any comment on the
letter because I'd like to put it behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question her husband is hurt by the reaction to
his activities. Garcia, ``who is like my flesh and blood,'' said
Hirschbeck, accused him and Brinkman of unwittingly helping Major
League Baseball break the union. This particularly wounds
Hirschbeck, for Garcia was among several umpires who served as
pallbearers when Hirschbeck's 8-year-old son John died of
adrenoleuko dystrophy in 1993. ``When people talk about us being
like a family,'' said Hirschbeck, ``nobody knows that better than
the Hirschbecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck and several of his colleagues insist that the dispute
will not dissolve relationships because ``you don't stop being
friends with someone who's like family.''
</P>
<P>
   But also to be considered is the impact on baseball. While
Garcia maintained that resentment doesn't spill onto the field, he
added a cautionary note. ``What Major League Baseball wants is
going to hurt the integrity of the game,'' he said. ``If a young
umpire goes out there and knows he can be fired because of a
major-market team's clout if he makes a mistake, it will hurt the
integrity of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the veterans are immune. Montague worked the plate in
Miami Wednesday night, ``and the pitcher looked in at me and I
jumped him. Then I jumped the bench. Normally, I'm pretty
easygoing. But this is with us constantly. The tension is so high,
it's with you every inning.''
</P>
<P>
   It reaches all the way down to the minors. Marvin Hudson, who
will become a full-time NL umpire in September after his
apprenticeship as a vacation fill-in, was working one of his final
IL games in Pawtucket, R.I., last week. He didn't want to talk
about his situation. He's 35, has a wife and two children, has
worked his way up from the godforsaken Appalachian League in the
past eight years, and now is headed for the main stage. When he got
the call informing him of his promotion, ``I was excited,'' he
said. ``You'd be crazy not to be excited.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said this, his voice was a monotone, his face
expressionless, his eyes dead. He may have been excited about his
big break, but he sure didn't seem to be enjoying it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
