<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
August 7. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   PARTY _ In 1992, Ross Perot led an impassioned following of
angry, disaffected voters that caused fits for the campaigns of
President Bush and then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton. His independent
candidacy won almost 20 percent of the vote, the best showing for
an independent or third party presidential candidate in more than
half a century. And it sparked a debate that continues today about
whether he might have sealed Bush's defeat, even though exit polls
show that he probably drew almost equally from Democrats and
Republicans. Flash forward to 2000. Could a third-party candidate
wield that kind of political clout again? 36. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG: Two men who helped send reputed Kansas City crime boss
Anthony Civella to prison in 1993 stand accused of the exactly the
same charges. Wilbur Swift and Louie Ferro Jr. are accused of
diverting $10 million worth of pharmaceuticals from doctors,
dealers and others to drug stores on the West Coast. Civella,
a.k.a. Tony the Ripe, was convicted of running a $1 million drug
diversion scam. Mark Morris. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   COOK: Steven Cook had been dead so long that his body had begun
to stink. His body was discovered July 21 in his sweltering midtown
Kansas City apartment. Another heat victim, authorities said. But
it was a needless death, say officials with the local Mental Health
Association, Legal Aid and a patient advocate group. They're
outraged because Cook was only 40, and no one had checked on him at
the Campbell Street group home where he lived, even though he was
taking a drug for schizophrenia that made him heat sensitive.
Officials are concerned because many mental patients live in
low-rent midtown apartments with no air-conditioning and are on
similar medications. Apparently, there's no procedure in place for
checking on these people when temperatures soar. Photo. Alan
Bavley. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   ID: The Kansas City Police Department's South Patrol has started
a program called Cops as Clerks, with officers posing as liquor
store employees to nab teens trying to buy booze, usually with
phony IDs. The fake IDs are often made by computer, and, while
there is not yet an epidemic of them, it seems that some kids are
trying to take advantage of advanced technology to get liquor.
Malcolm Garcia. 15 inches. Photo
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO: Missouri retailers' unwillingness to stop selling
tobacco to teen-agers could cost the state nearly $10 million in
federal alcohol- and drug-treatment grants. The money represents
more than 13 percent of the state's entire budget for
substance-abuse treatment programs, state officials said. Kit
Wagar. 23. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   ARMA. World War II was very personal for this tiny southeast
Kansas mining town. Its veterans' memorial displays a plaque with
the names of 629 young men who went off to war. For the Varsolona,
Kmetz and Kovacic families, the contribution was extraordinary.
Each of the families sent five sons to the Pacific or Europe.
Miraculously, all 15 men returned safely. Twenty-six young men from
Arma weren't so lucky, and they are being remembered this weekend,
during what Arma residents believe is the nation's oldest annual
celebration of V-J Day. John Petterson. 27. Photo. Map
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   SPORT _ Kansas City area leaders kick around ideas for improving
Kauffman and Arrowhead stadiums, including a rolling roof. But
where would the money come from? crumpley, rice
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Y2K as cultural icon. All the entertainment detritus this
much-hyped event has spawned. With screen grabs from Web site for
Y2K movie that will never get made. Finn Bullars, Dave Hayes
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   POSNANSKI. Joe Posnanski column on the 20 greatest athletes of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   WHITLOCK: Jason Whitlock column from the Chiefs training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS: Royals vs. Minnesota Twins, 7:05 p.m. Bob Dutton.
</P>
