A8211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-SWITCHES-HNS &LR;      08-06 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SWITCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETECTIVES SNOOP FOR FRAUD AT RACETRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ One of the most notorious switcheroos
in horse racing happened in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   South American stakes winner Cinzano entered the United States
and the New York racing circuit falsely identified as a claimer
horse named Lebon.
</P>
<P>
   The ruse resulted in a jail sentence for a Long Island
veterinarian, after he collected unearned winnings at Belmont.
``Nowadays the only switches we discover are accidents, when horses
are put in the wrong vans,'' said James Zito, chief horse
identifier charged with protecting bettors and breeders from fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes are usually caught before a horse reaches the paddock,
he said, and no substitutes _ either inadvertent or orchestrated _
have appeared at Saratoga Race Course this season.
</P>
<P>
   At Saratoga, Zito and his team of five ``detectives'' review
coat markings and paperwork of 14 to 20 horses each day. The
thoroughbreds travel from around the world to make their debuts
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We photograph 2,000 to 3,000 horses a year at all three (New
York Racing Association) tracks,'' said Zito, a former agent with
the Thoroughbred Racing Protective Bureau who is no relation to
trainer Nick Zito. ``NYRA is the only one in the country to use the
photo system, and we have for about 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, assistant identifier Carol Delgado and
photographer Janet Reid set out for Barn 51, stall 7 on the
backstretch. They followed in the footsteps of equine tattooist
Frank Rossi, who inscribes a unique set of numerals on the inside
upper lip of horses that were not branded prior to arriving at
Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo matches the numerals on the Jockey Club foal
registration certificate, but is not always legible, so Delgado
relies on other identifying characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   River Emperor is a bay gelding who belongs to Dakar Stables. He
allowed photographer Diane Connor to flip his lip so she could read
off the inscription to Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   Groom Mike Webster pulled River Emperor into the light for
Delgado to compare the horse's markings to what his certificate
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says he has neck cowlicks, beneath the right falling mane,
and an irregular diamond star with a cowlick, which he has,''
Delgado said, stroking beneath the gelding's forelock after she has
confirmed all the whorls of fur.
</P>
<P>
   Any stockings or socks _ lighter hair around a horse's fetlocks
_ would be noted if River Emperor had them.
</P>
<P>
   Zito said cowlicks appear in every foal and are permanent, and
that another set of markings called chestnuts _ markings on the
back of a horse's four knees _ are comparable to human
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory is that the legs rest against each other in the
womb,'' Zito said. ``The markings mirror each other. There is also
an Indian term for them, night eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The women have been a team for five years and work quickly. They
speak to each other in short hand as Connor moves about River
Emperor's hooves to first photograph the chestnuts, then the body
while Delgado and Webster lead the thoroughbred about the walking
circle: ``More daylight (between the legs); (move the) front leg;
(give me his) full face.''
</P>
<P>
   A facial portrait, full-body profile and shot of the derriere,
with tail raised in an undignified fashion to capture fetlock
markings are taken. They go into a black binder compiled for each
race by the women.
</P>
<P>
   When owners, jockeys and racehorses gather in the paddock to
parade before each race, Zito is there with the black book to make
a visual inspection of each contestant.
</P>
<P>
   Zito said the entrance requirements for foreign horses are
stricter now, and that a repeat of the Cinzano incident was
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be burned again,'' Zito said. ``Once was
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado and Connor said they never had a trainer try to pass off
one horse for another. And that includes using shoe polish to
disguise a thoroughbred's markings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone asks us that,'' said Delgado, laughing. ``But we
never know what we'll discover in the morning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
