A8213 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-BAD-FOR-KNEES-(NE     08-06 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-BAD-FOR-KNEES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS SEX IS BAD FOR THE KNEES  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., AUG. 9, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ANDY COGHLAN  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a sobering message for footballers launching themselves
into a new soccer season: an overactive sex life could give you a
career-threatening injury. A study obtained by New Scientist
suggests that players are especially prone to arthritic knee
injuries triggered by sexually transmitted bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The study, a masters dissertation completed by Paul Oyudo when
he was a student at Queen Mary and Westfield College in London,
analyzes the cases of 10 sportsmen with persistent knee injuries.
Of the 10, six were football players and five of these played in
the Premiership, England's top soccer league.
</P>
<P>
   The study was made available by John King, a consultant
orthopedic surgeon at the London Independent Hospital. King, who is
president of the British Sports Doctors Association, hopes to make
football players aware of the risk to their careers posed by
frequent unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   While most football players' injuries are sustained on the field
of play, the cases studied by Oyudo involved sexually acquired
reactive arthritis, or SARA. It is triggered by the same bacteria
that cause nonspecific urethritis, an inflammation of the urethra.
In eight of the 10 cases reviewed by Oyudo, the sportsmen clearly
had nonspecific urethritis. Three had cloudy discharges in their
urine and two tested positive for Chlamydia trachomatis, a
bacterium implicated as a cause of SARA.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the sportsmen revealed the full extent of their sexual
activities to their doctors is unclear, but five of them admitted
having had more than 11 sexual partners in their lifetime. Only
about one in four British men in their mid-20s reports having had
this many partners. ''The level of promiscuity among these
sportsmen calls for concern,'' Oyudo wrote. ''Footballers appear to
be the greatest culprits.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies have shown that SARA is most prevalent among
men between the ages of 18 and 34. Frequent travelers and
entertainers are most at risk. ''Sportsmen fall well within this
group,'' Oyodo wrote, adding that football players have more sexual
opportunities than most: ''They are very rich and have lots of
spare time.''
</P>
<P>
   On average, each of the five Premiership football players had
spent eight months struggling with their knee injury before being
diagnosed with SARA.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is difficult to diagnose. Sufferers usually have eye
and urethral irritations, as well as tender, swollen joints. A test
that measures the speed at which red blood cells settle out of a
blood sample helps doctors to make a diagnosis. This occurs faster
in infected individuals.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Football Association says that young players
are routinely given ''general sex education,'' including advice on
avoiding sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
