<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV08-COX     08-06 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL TO REACH KEY MILESTONE
 &HT;    800&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Soon after the financial markets close Tuesday,
rival attorneys from the Justice Department and Microsoft Corp.
will descend on the federal courthouse, each bearing thick legal
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the epic struggle recognize that U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is all but certain to lay aside their
proposed verdicts in the Microsoft antitrust case and issue his
own. Nevertheless, the voluminous briefing books, with
diametrically different story lines, were being meticulously edited
late last week in a bid to sway not only the judge, but also the
media and legal scholars.
</P>
<P>
   As the Microsoft case approaches another milestone, that outside
``jury,'' which also includes financial analysts, appears largely
persuaded that Jackson will find that the company has failed to
obey the antitrust laws. At the same time, some informed observers
doubt the judge will be swayed by recent government feelers to
investment bankers on how best to break up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In forming his own conclusions, the judge will place a lot of
weight on the credibility of the courtroom witnesses,'' said Daniel
Reznek, a retired partner in the law firm of Arnold &AMP; Porter, who
has followed the case closely and who has known Jackson for many
years. ``That's what he needs to do to dampen the chances of being
reversed on appeal,'' Reznek added.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments from the bench during the non-jury trial,
Jackson often seemed favorably disposed to the searing
cross-examination of Microsoft witnesses waged by David Boies, the
lead prosecutor. ``But that predisposition doesn't mean that he'll
buy wholesale into any government-written remedy package,'' Reznek
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers privately see the revived breakup talk as a
harassing tactic aimed at gaining bargaining leverage in renewed
settlement talks, which could follow any preliminary indication
from Jackson that the world's largest software company remains in
legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Such a signal could come shortly after closing oral arguments
are heard in mid-September. In the interim, the legal combatants,
in addition to filing their rival opinions, formally known as
``findings of fact,'' will also prepare rebuttal briefs, also due
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the prosecutors contend that it is normal
procedure, as the landmark trial moves toward a climax, for them to
explore potential remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The proscutors asked Wall Street investment bankers to estimate
Microsoft's future worth if it were broken up _ either to compete
against itself as several ``Baby Bills'' or else by spinning
Windows off from such applications as Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   But the bankers were reluctant to do so, pointing out that a
company that chiefly sells intellectual property represents a
different model than the ``Baby Bells'' that were successfully spun
off from AT&AMP;T to meet antitrust issues in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking at possible remedies, but it's premature,''
said Justice Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona. ``The judge
hasn't even ruled on whether Microsoft is liable. We've said all
along we would talk to experts, asking for a wide variety of
options. But we haven't even made a decision on what kind of
remedies we may or may not ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the 71-day trial, the Justice Department and 19
state attorneys general built a methodical case against the
software giant. It is based on both direct testimony from 13
prosecutorial witnesses and e-mails from Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates and his top lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that Microsoft broke the law by bullying
rivals in the computer industry in an effort to protect its
lucrative Windows monopoly and to dominate the market for Internet
browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's rivals dismiss the rapid changes that have occurred
in the high-tech sector since the case was filed some 15 months
ago, asserting that they have not altered Microsoft monopoly power
over the market for personal computer operating systems. It is a
monopoly, they argue, that if left unchecked would enable Microsoft
to unfairly dominate Internet commerce and squash its weaker
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the arguments likely to be advanced in the dueling
briefs, a deal that would short-circuit the trial and avoid a
lengthy appeals process remains a viable option. Earlier sporadic
settlement talks proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the judge accepts some limited portion of the government's
clims, a renewed settlement effort would make a good deal of
sense,'' said Michael Lacovara, a key member of Microsoft legal
defense team. ``As I see it,'' he added, ``the trial has been a
distraction (for Microsoft) and it would be good to move on _ if a
fair and sensible way could be found to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite his openness to the idea of a striking a bargain,
Lacovara, a partner in the New York law firm of Sullivan &AMP;
Cromwell, said his client is dealing from a position of strength.
</P>
<P>
   Lacovara noted that the government case has been specifically
aimed at Windows 98, an operating system shipped by Microsoft a few
weeks after the suit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 includes a built-in browser known as Internet
Explorer. Even as large computer makers widely pre-loaded that
system on their Intel-based machines, the government argued in
court that their customers should regain the freedom to buy an
unbundled version. It is a ``freedom,'' Microsoft says, that users
have never sought and that is technologically impossible to
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Around the time Jackson is due to rule, most likely before the
year's end, Windows is due to be supplanted by Windows 2000, a
heftier operating system based on another file structure. A
consumer-oriented version of Windows 2000, code named Millennium,
is likely to be released early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be our firm position that, whatever else might
happen, the government, if it chose to do so, would have to build
an entirely new case with respect to Windows 2000, which has never
been part of this case,'' Lacovara said during an interview in the
conference room of his law firm's Washington offices, which
features spectacular views of the White House complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the broader sense,'' he said, ``the development and
forthcoming release of Windows 2000 underscores the truly dynamic
structure of this industry, a reality that the government has
adamantly refused to acknowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1,000 or so pages that Microsoft's lawyers will present to
the judge boil down to this: The company did nothing to harm
consumers while adding features such as browsers simply to meet
their needs. Its overall behavior has, in fact, fostered
competition. It lacks monopoly power because of the continual
competitive threats it faces. Low Windows' pricing patterns reflect
such real world restraints.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the issues in the trial have hardly moved since
Attorney General Janet Reno announced the broad attack against
Microsoft. ``Government intervention into a healthy, competitive
and innovative industry will adversely impact consumers and a U.S.
company's ability to improve its products,'' the company claimed on
the day the suit was filed. It has never wavered from that view.
</P>
<P>
   But, on another level, the issues are also as immediate as the
day's technology headlines. Thus, as Microsoft attempts to loosen
America Online Inc.'s grip on millions of instant-messaging
customers, it is also reflects the ongoing legal struggle between
the nation's top software maker and its leading online service.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the trial, AOL absorbed Netscape Communications
Corp. at a cost of $10 billion. In suing Microsoft, the government
had held that the company had illegally sought to destroy
Netscape's business in order to extend its monopoly power to
Internet commerce. Its complaint cites Netscape 130 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But market dynamics do matter,'' Lacovara contended. ``In the
course of discovery, we were able to see what the parties were
saying to each other. And those exchanges greatly bolster our
case.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
