<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-FUNDING-$ADV08-CO     08-06 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-FUNDING-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS HMO'S DROP ELDERLY, ALL SIDES SEEK TO ASSIGN BLAME
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after Congress expanded managed care
choices for Medicare, nearly 200 HMOs have dropped coverage for
roughly three-quarters of a million elderly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Of those dropped by their health maintenance organizations, more
than 50,000 this year and nearly 80,000 next year will be forced
back into traditional fee-for-service Medicare because there
weren't any other managed care plans locally available.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers are blaming the federal Health Care Financing
Administration for the HMO withdrawal, claiming HCFA misinterpreted
what Congress intended when it passed the Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Two congressmen, Reps. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., and Peter
Deutsch, D-Fla., have introduced legislation to block HCFA from
slashing managed care reimbursement rates by $11.2 billion over
five years. Bilirakis is chairman of the House Commerce
subcommittee on health which has partial jurisdiction over
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing before the panel last week, the managed care
industry argued that the implementation of the ``Medicare+Choice''
program had created a ``fairness gap'' between payments to HMOs and
the fee-for-service system. But HCFA officials argued there was
little evidence that low payment rates were behind the decisions to
drop Medicare participation.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare+Choice program was designed to expand the choice of
health plans available to the elderly by allowing a variety of
managed care-type plans in addition to HMOs, which restrict
enrollees to using only their medical providers.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, just before Medicare+Choice took effect, 346 health
plans participated in Medicare covering 6.2 million people, about
17 percent of all Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   When the program took effect in January, 99 plans had dropped
out or reduced their geographic coverage area _ 45 withdrawals and
54 reductions _ affecting 407,000 people, of whom 51,000 were
unable to rejoin a plan because none was available.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, another 99 plans announced plans to drop out or
curtail coverage effective Jan. 1, 2000. This time, 41 plans
withdrew and 58 reduced territory, affecting 327,000 people. Of
those, 79,000 don't have another plan in their area.
</P>
<P>
   Offsetting the withdrawals, 41 plans have expanded or joined the
program and another 22 are awaiting approval.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president and chief executive officer of the
American Association of Health Plans, warned Bilirakis's panel that
the Medicare+Choice program was facing a crisis and its survival
was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beneficiaries stand to lose a great deal,'' Ignagni said. ``If
you don't act this year, we look forward to far more beneficiaries
being affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and their supporters testified that the
turbulence in the Medicare+Choice program has not reduced total
Medicare HMO enrollments and has forced relatively few into the
fee-for-service system.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Berenson, HCFA's director for health plans and
providers, said there are now nearly 6.5 million Medicare
beneficiaries enrolled in managed care, slightly more than when
plans began dropping out last year. He noted that 95 percent of
Medicare managed care beneficiaries have not been affected by the
cutbacks and less than 2 percent will be forced back into
fee-for-service.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Moon, a senior fellow at the Urban Institute, said the
``withdrawal of plans from certain markets is a natural by-product
of choice and competition. They should not only be expected, they
are a necessary part of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignagni claims that a major reason so many plans are dropping
coverage for next year is a new HCFA formula which adjusts payments
to the expected risk each enrollee brings to the health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, HMOs have received 95 percent of the average cost of
treating local Medicare fee-for-service patients. But studies have
indicated that an average tied to fee-for-service payments has
grossly overpaid managed care plans which historically have
enrolled younger, healthier beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA's new risk adjustment formula is projected to trim $11.2
billion over five years from HMO payments. That's on top of more
than $22 billion in payment cuts over five years imposed through
other provisions of the Balance Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Ignagni said the cuts imposed by the risk adjustment formula
treat HMOs unfairly and are not what Congress intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of this risk-adjustment methodology will be to
restrict new market entrants and leave beneficiaries with fewer
options, reduced benefits and higher out-of-pocket costs,'' Ignagni
said. ``Overpaid health plans do not leave a market. Overpaid
health plans do not reduce benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson argued that the fight over the risk adjustment formula
is designed to hide the fact that some managed care plans have been
unable to find a market in certain areas, particularly rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inadequate reimbursement to plans does not explain plan
decisions to trim participation in the program,'' he said.
``Payment is rising in all counties this coming year by an average
of 5 percent and will rise by as much as 18 percent in some
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
