<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF PACHYSANDRA AND IVY DON'T COVER THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At times it seems as if I were the only member of the ``anything
but pachysandra'' group. Pachysandra, the ubiquitous and _ yes, I
admit it _ highly useful evergreen ground cover, smothers
landscapes throughout my central New Jersey community and many
other parts of the country as well.
</P>
<P>
   So deep is my aversion to pachysandra's boring, reliable
greenness, that I accepted plugs of ivy from a neighbor 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm thinking of starting an ``anything but pachysandra or
ivy'' club.
</P>
<P>
   A reasonable response to such an assertion is: ``Well, what else
is low maintenance, grows no higher than eight inches and provides
a welcome touch of green in dreary winter months?'' After much
research and years of experimentation, I have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least three evergreen ground covers that fill the
bill, all little-known native Americans. I treasure them for their
resistance to disease and pests as well as for their elegant
beauty. And all three provide a bonus: colorful spring flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The first to bloom, Waldsteinia fragariodes, has a most
unfortunate common name: barren strawberry. It conjures up images
of the horrible wild strawberries that streak through my organic
lawn. If not for the recommendation of an expert gardener, I never
would have tried this plant.
</P>
<P>
   Waldsteinia has leaves three to four inches wide, glossy green
and three lobed. Over time, it forms dense, spreading mats, with
new leaves appearing on top of those from the previous year and
concealing them. Though the foliage resembles that on cultivated
strawberries, there is no noticeable fruit.
</P>
<P>
   In spring, golden yellow flowers open on slim, seven-inch stems
and look like fairy stars sparkling above a rich green floor. This
year, the flowers bloomed for five weeks, starting in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Waldsteinia truly comes into its glory in winter, when repeated
blasts of cold weather infuse the leaves with a purple flush. The
two tones, dark green and purple, are especially lovely when
emerging from a sparkling blanket of snow.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my garden books say the common name derives from the
plant's preference for barren areas or flat open spaces. Others
declare it is a woodland plant. I compromised and placed it as an
underskirt in a border filled with dwarf deciduous shrubs. There,
its colorful foliage is exposed throughout winter.
</P>
<P>
   In spring, Waldsteinia's flowers shine among the emerging leaves
and flowers on the shrubs. Hidden beneath the shrubs through summer
and fall, Waldsteinia serves as a protective mulch that conserves
water and inhibits weed growth.
</P>
<P>
   While the leaves of golden ragwort (Senecio aureus) are about
the size of Waldsteinia's, they are rounded, rather than lobed, and
have minute notches as an edging. April breezes seem to induce a
color reaction in the rich, dark green foliage: the undersides turn
a lovely purple.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, golden, asterlike flowers open for almost three
weeks on top of two-foot stems. The flowers then metamorphose into
rounded white seed heads, which look like fluffy buttons as they
bob above the dark green foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Though I have yet to find any seedlings sprouting, the
rhizomatous roots started to take off after a year or two. Golden
ragwort spreads easily, and is thus ideal for large spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Since I do not have large spaces, I have begun to pass clumps on
to friends. That's how I learned how adaptable this plant is.
Conventional wisdom decrees that one should place it in lightly
shaded, moist garden soil, as I did.
</P>
<P>
   One friend placed it on a dry wooded slope resting on a shale
outcropping. It flourishes there and is also completely avoided by
the groundhogs that feast on most other vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Foamflowers (Tiarella) are a woodland genus, interbreeding at
will. Four of its five members hail from North America.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1990s, gardeners could choose only between an
aggressive spreader (T. cordifolia) and a more restrained clumper
(T. wherryi). The spreader has white flowers, which bloom for two
to three weeks in April, and the clumper has pink flowers, which
open for six to seven weeks in mid- to late spring and often
repeat-bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Plant breeders have changed all this, creating many lovely
hybrids that combine features of both species, plus two others from
the Pacific Northwest, T. trifoliata and T. unifoliata. Leaves are
now described as heart shaped, maplelike and oaklike; many have
veins etched in maroon.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried hybrids over the years, most notably Tiger Stripe
and Elizabeth Oliver. On my grounds, they have produced their own
little hybrids, so that I now have many different leaf forms,
though all the plants bear spiky, pink-tinged flowers, none of
those taller than 12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Each is charming in the shade garden throughout the growing
season. Elizabeth Oliver takes center stage in winter. Its foliage
mat, a luscious maroon in the cold, provides a welcome touch of
elegance in a season of bare earth.
</P>
<P>
   It may be lonely here in the ``anything but pachysandra'' group,
but it certainly has its rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Waldsteinia is available from Bluestone Perennials, 7211 Middle
Ridge Rd., Madison, Ohio 44057, (800) 852-5243; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Golden ragwort and some Tiarellas are sold by Crownsville
Nursery, P.O. Box 797, Crownsville, Md. 21032, (410) 849-3143; free
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Many Tiarellas, including those mentioned here, are available
from the Primrose Path, R.D. 2, Box 110, Scottdale, Pa. 15683,
(724) 887-6756; catalog, $2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
