A8312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-BUSINESS-CAMP-AR     08-06 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-BUSINESS-CAMP-ART-800&AMP;add-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAMP WHERE BUSINESS IS USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 8) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MARCIA BIEDERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While other teen-agers stuffed Frisbees and flippers into duffel
bags last month, Michael Granat packed long pants and collared
shirts for a camp where things don't get much looser than a casual
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 14, of New City, N.Y., was headed for his second summer
of business camp, where there are treks to the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York, hikes through a Ferrari dealership and lessons on
tying knots on acquisition targets. At mealtime, there is
instruction in business etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   One recent tip: Eat before lunching with the boss to avoid that
wolfish look.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it will be years before Michael and his fellow
campers, ages 13 to 16, have an actual boss, some seem as if they
can't wait to be 40. At the Julian Krinsky Summer Camps at
Haverford College, they don't have to. They get a leg up on future
rivals for Wall Street partnerships, or for financing their
E-commerce start-ups, by learning corporate skills in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   For Michael, who left home with a case of sodas to sell at a
profit to other campers, ``business has always been a passion,''
said his father, Steven Granat. Granat, a self-employed middleman
in the footwear industry, said his son has been reading the stock
tables since elementary school, when he bought Disney. (Well, a
share or two.)
</P>
<P>
   If, in the age of Bill Gates, Michael Eisner and 26-year-old
dot-com moguls, business is cool, the message hasn't quite reached
Michael's teen-age friends back home in Rockland County. ``Kids
think, why don't you just go skateboarding?'' his father said.
``That's why he loves the camp. He can meet kids with the same
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   There are campers like Adam Wynn, 15, of Scarsdale, N.Y., who
plans to start a company called LABA Associates with six friends.
The name means nothing, Adam said _ but then again, neither does
Haagen-Dazs. ``Business should be something society will benefit
from,'' Adam said, and proving he'd paid attention in class, he
added, ``and you should also have brand equity so everyone will
know your name.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-week camp, which attracted about three dozen youngsters
in two sessions this summer (ending August 13), is one more sign
that business leaders have become pop figures, serving as role
models to impressionable minds, and that many families think it's
never too early to get on track for a corner office.
</P>
<P>
   The business camp, which costs $3,400, is an outgrowth of golf
and tennis camps on the Haverford campus run by Krinsky, a South
African-born former tennis star who played at Wimbledon, and a
partner, Adrian Castelli. In the morning, the 200 campers pursue
special interests, which besides business include drama and
cooking; in the afternoon, sports and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing teen-agers for business and the corporate world, an
idea Krinsky conceived five years ago, seemed like a good fit with
the existing camp because, he said, ``We truly are teaching
business persons' sports _ tennis, golf and squash.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, the campers were given a tour of the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business by the
coordinator of its undergraduate division, Sharon Mulholland. The
tour ended in a lecture hall, where Mrs. Mulholland urged campers
to apply to Wharton's bachelor's program, rather than end up as
``poets'' _ the school nickname for MBA candidates who did not
study business as undergraduates. She ticked off admissions
requirements, offered tips for writing the application essay (``use
Spellcheck'') and urged them to check on applications themselves
(``a mother drove us crazy'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Does everyone have a resume?'' she asked, and was answered
with nods. Writing one is a camp activity.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was a meeting with Michael G. Rubin, 27, the chairman
of Global Sports Inc. in nearby King of Prussia, Pa. On the way
over, Felipe Valdez, 16, and Nadia Schwartz, 14, exchanged
reminiscences about Trunk Bay in the U.S. Virgin Islands like two
attorneys comparing vacations. But the next minute, they were
giggling about the camp's Crazy Olympics, which included an event
involving pantyhose and a tennis ball, proving they are still
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   As on all field trips, campers adhered to a dress code fit for
cubicle life: slacks and shirts with collars for boys, skirts for
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia, poised and post-feminist in a gray stretch miniskirt and
``hoodie'' (a hooded vest) and electric-blue nail polish, looked
older than her years. Until she recalled a recent lesson on futures
trading. ``I finally got it,'' she smiled, flashing braces.
</P>
<P>
   A number of campers mentioned the futures-trading course as a
high point. ``I guess it's about the only thing they don't teach in
school,'' said Nicholas J. Cirillo, the instructor and a former
floor trader at the New York Mercantile Exchange. ``They don't
teach you how to make money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the offices of Global Sports, the campers were ushered in to
meet Rubin, who had ``role model'' written all over him. By age 14,
he had opened his first sporting-goods store. At 22, he was dubbed
a mogul by The Wall Street Journal. Now, his company is shifting
focus to the Internet. He asked the campers what Web site they
associated with CD's.
</P>
<P>
   ``CDnow,'' they chorused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys?''
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the ex-children dared answer.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Oyarzun, 16, a camper from a French suburb of Geneva, asked
about Rubin's past ownership of bars, which Krinsky had mentioned.
``That was one of my big mistakes,'' Rubin said. ``A nightclub is a
very difficult business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick was undeterred. Traveling back to camp, he told about his
dream of running a club someday. After all, what did Americans know
about serving food and drink? Nick, on his first visit to the
United States, was pleased with the camp but revolted by American
food. ``It's just junk food,'' he said. He was particularly
horrified by the sight of scrambled eggs at breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   This day's lunch was not likely to improve his opinion. Campers
brought trays of pizza and steak hoagies into a room where Krinsky
taught a lesson in etiquette, substituting for the usual lecturer,
a newspaper columnist who writes under the name Miss Demeanor. He
asked if anyone knew the proper way to dip a spoon into soup.
Felipe demonstrated. His father, Abelardo Valdez, had been chief of
protocol at the White House during the Carter Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The young people listened as Krinsky, 49, discussed the
intricacies of napkin and fork use. Nick wanted to know if
Americans actually used toothpicks in public.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the campers were showing signs of boardroom fatigue. They
were itching for the afternoon activities, when they would mix with
the general camp population. Nick had signed up for tennis.
Michael's name was on a list for a facial and a manicure.
</P>
<P>
   Krinsky has found the market for summer business instruction for
teen-agers to be steady, but not a growth business. Two other
business camps, one run by Babson College in Wellesley, Mass., and
the other by the Breakers resort in Palm Beach, Fla., failed in
recent years for lack of campers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the National Foundation for Teaching
Entrepreneurship, a nonprofit group, operated about 15 ``Biz
Camps'' this summer for low-income youngsters, all of whom attended
on scholarships underwritten by corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariotti, the founder of the camps, said his mission is to
teach business skills to poor youth, because ``it's one of the best
strategies to get them out of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful for people if they're not competent with money
and don't understand ownership and markets,'' he said. ``The sooner
that children can learn this, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, he hopes to revive the Babson College program with
a mix of low- and upper-income campers. ``I want a camp where kids
from the South Bronx and Watts would mix with kids from
Greenwich,'' he said. ``It's healthy for both groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Krinsky agreed, but said his camp can offer only an occasional
scholarship. He said camp is a great opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's always the other opportunity. ``Next year,''
Nadia said, ``my parents want me to get a job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
