<HEADLINE>
REFORMER PAT AND SEN. SPRINGER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: OK. Why did the first lady talk about her
beloved husband being ``scarred by abuse'' in the context of his
chronic philandering if she wasn't trying to palm off Bill
Clinton's allegedly troubled childhood as an excuse for his
revolting personal behavior as an adult?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary made the comments in a magazine interview and then
reacted to the ensuing uproar by insisting that her remarks were
not intended to let hubby off the hook. The president seconded her
... uh ... clarification.
</P>
<P>
   So. What are we supposed to believe? As is always the case with
this pair of dissembling manipulators, we can believe whatever we
want to. If they ever tell the truth about anything, it's because
they were caught off guard and couldn't think of a lie to tell.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: The president says that he plans to veto the
Republican tax cut because it's fiscally irresponsible. Well,
Clinton might have his reasons for opposing the tax cut _ maybe
even a good one or two _ but the American people can count on this:
Whatever reason he states in public is not the real reason.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is constitutionally incapable of telling the truth
_ even when the truth makes a better story than a lie. On this
particular issue, of course, the lie makes a better story because
the truth is that Clinton wants to keep all that tax money flowing
into government coffers so that he can do what liberal Democrats
always do with money that flows into government coffers: spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton doesn't care about paying off the national debt. He
doesn't care about saving Social Security and Medicare. He doesn't
care about fiscal responsibility. Most of all, he doesn't care
about all those just plain taxpayers who keep forking over their
hard-earned bucks to pay for an endless parade of government
programs that most Americans don't want or need.
</P>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN: Rumors persist that the
columnist/commentator-turned-perennial presidential candidate will
quit the Republican Party and sign on with the Reform Party.
Buchanan denies the rumors, but it makes sense that he might be
tired of waging no-hope campaigns for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party, disenchanted with founder Ross Perot and
apparently unable to lure wrestler-turned-politician Jesse Ventura
into the presidential race, might be thrilled to hook up with a
political karate expert such as Buchanan. Besides, Buchanan really
parted ways with the Republicans when he helped torpedo the GOP's
White House hopes in 1992 and 1996 by conducting disruptive primary
campaigns against eventual nominees George Bush and Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Why not make it official? Maybe Buchanan could talk Ventura into
being his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY SPRINGER: The much-maligned TV talk-show host is said to
be considering a run for the U.S. Senate from Ohio, where he once
served as mayor of Cincinnati. This does not sit well with
occupants of the world's greatest deliberative body _ or at least
not with Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, Daschle considers Springer a ``joke''
and wants no part of him _ even though Springer's election would
add a Democratic seat to Daschle's Senate minority.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle is entitled to his opinion, needless to say. But why
wouldn't he welcome a joke like Springer to a place that's
populated by more clowns per capita than a traveling circus?
</P>
<P>
   MARK McGWIRE: The St. Louis Cardinals' slugger took lots of heat
last season for using the dietary supplement androstenedione _ even
though the substance is perfectly legal in major-league baseball.
Some dolts in the media went so far to suggest that the supplement
was the reason that McGwire hit 70 home runs _ even though there's
not a shred of evidence to support such a theory.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, McGwire has stopped using androstenedione because
he didn't want to be perceived as encouraging kids to use it. Once
again, Big Mac proves that he's not just a great ballplayer _ he's
a great role model.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
