<SLUG> BC-MCCAFFREY-MCGWIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DRUG CZAR APPLAUDS MCGWIRE'S DECISION TO DROP ANDRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after joining the elite 500-home-run club,
Mark McGwire won the praise of White House drug policy director
Barry McCaffrey Friday for saying no to the dietary supplement
androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message Mark McGwire sends to our young people by walking
away from this substance is a powerful one,'' McCaffrey said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McGwire's home-run exploits have made him a hero to
thousands of young people across the nation ... However, doctors
and scientists have raised serious issues concerning the safety of
androstenedione use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who is only the 16th player to reach the 500-homer
mark, disclosed late Wednesday that he had stopped using the
controversial supplement, also known as andro, because he was
worried about the possible influence that his continued use of it
could have on children.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said he still did not believe there was anything
wrong with the legal supplement and that adults should be allowed
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire acknowledged taking andro last summer. Later the St.
Louis Cardinals' first baseman set a major-league record of 70 home
runs in one season. On Thursday night, before hitting career homers
No. 500 and 501, he was asked about his Wednesday comments and said
he has not taken the supplement for the last four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I need to prove anything, but this (message) is
for young children who think they need it,'' he said. McGwire
didn't explain why he waited four months to say he had dropped
andro.
</P>
<P>
   Since it became known that McGwire was using it, sales of the
supplement surged from $10 million to more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Andro is sold legally over the counter and on the Internet in
the United States even though some medical experts say it is
essentially an anabolic steroid. The supplement is banned by the
National Football League, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association and the International Olympic Committee because
organization officials say it enhances one's performance and could
be a potentially harmful drug. But baseball authorities have not
banned it and have refused to condone or condemn it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, McCaffrey said his office has asked the
federal Drug Enforcement Agency to test andro to determine if it
has steroid characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who care about the vitality and beauty of sport need
to take seriously the threat of drug use and doping to the
legitimacy of athletic competition,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
