<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A DRAGONFLY SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the hot-dogging ace pilots of the bug world. Often
decked out in iridescent colors of green and blue and red, they are
agile aerialists. In fact, if Igor Sikorsky and Tinker Bell had had
a baby, it would have been a dragonfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extraordinary powers of flight and sight, unequaled among
animals,'' boasts Philip S. Corbet in the definitive and scholarly
``Dragonflies: Behavior and Ecology of Odonata'' (Cornell
University Press).
</P>
<P>
   Dragonflies are everywhere this summer, with various species
emerging in waves throughout the season into fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial arena, they are embroidered on pillow cases
and pajamas. They festoon dresses and dangle as earrings.
</P>
<P>
   In the natural world, the insects with four wings and six legs
ply their trade mostly near ponds and moist meadows, zigzagging
around us as we walk or garden. They capture our imaginations as
deftly as they do flying pests, including mosquitoes, gnats, and
black flies.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Carpenter, of the Nature Conservancy in Rhode Island,
and author of ``Dragonflies of Cape Cod'' (now out of print) has
long been intrigued by these creatures. ``They are top predators
and just spectacular to observe,'' she explains by phone. ``Also,
there are still so many mysteries left in insect studies.''
</P>
<P>
   The lifestyles of dragonflies turn out to be as intriguing as
their looks.
</P>
<P>
   They start out as ``nymphs'' _ water-dwelling larvae that are as
lethal in babyhood as they will be as adults. According to the
``Insects'' volume of the Peterson Field Guides (Houghton Mifflin),
dragonfly nymphs snag prey with ``peculiarly modified labium,'' a
prehensile organ that juts out at lightning speed.
</P>
<P>
   This nymph stage can last for years in some species. But
eventually, the skin splits and the dragonfly appears. After
casting off the exuvia, and a few hours of recovering from the
exhausting process of emergence, the dragonfly is ready for its
maiden flight to hunt and mate.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Carpenter says, when so many leave their nymph
days behind, ``they emerge explosively from the water,'' ready to
launch into life.
</P>
<P>
   These great flyers do (itals)everything(unitals) while airborne.
They can grab and gobble a mosquito in flight. And many also wing
it when it comes to sex. They may fly in tandem, and then,
employing something like a space-age docking system, they lock into
place with a series of grooves and notches. This act is sometimes
accomplished with ``an audible click,'' according to field reports.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger is the fact that the parts that need to line up
force these creatures into strange contortions. During this
Flying-Wallendas-meet-Dr.-Ruth maneuver, the male's abdomen can
become ``dented.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth has it that dragonflies sew up the lips and ears of
unsuspecting humans, and interestingly, some members of the family
are in fact called darners. And even though they don't sting, they
may bite when handled, according to the Peterson guide.
</P>
<P>
   But Carpenter says it is perfectly fine to handle them. You can
catch them with a net, she says, without fear of hurting them, if
you're careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dragonflies are really sturdy _ they've been around for 250
million years,'' she says. ``And insects' skeletons are on the
outside. You can net them and be able to look them right in the eye
and then release them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 190 species of dragonfly in New England. A couple of
species to look out for now, Carpenter advises, would be the green
darner (at 3 inches long, Carpenter says, they will ``jump out and
grab you'') and the lady skimmer, a large bluish-black active
specimen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
