<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Aug. 8, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOWELL-ANTIQUES (New York) _ The movie star, Malcolm McDowell,
recently spent an afternoon indulging his other passions: antique
watches, painted Shaker furniture and 19th-century flywheel toys.
McDowell, 56, collects with the same wild-eyed intensity that makes
him such a distinctive, often disturbing actor. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-BUSINESS-CAMP (New York) _ While other teen-agers stuffed
Frisbees and flippers into duffel bags last month, Michael Granat
packed long pants and collared shirts for a camp where things don't
get much looser than a casual Friday. Michael, 14, of New City,
N.Y., was headed for his second summer of business camp, where
there are treks to the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, hikes
through a Ferrari dealership and lessons on tying knots on
acquisition targets. At mealtime, there is instruction in business
etiquette. By Marcia Biederman. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-CLIPS (New York) _ Recently, I've noticed more and more
men doing away with the conventional wallet, replacing it with a
money clip and a slim-line credit-card case. A few months back, I
spotted my friend Adam Wiener, an executive producer at CBS New
Media, pulling out a brown leather credit-card holder, made by
Fossil, with a brass clip attached to the front. ``My old wallet
just took up too much space,'' he said. By Douglas Century.
</P>
<P>
   MUSTACHE-MODEL (New York) _ The burning question at last month's
menswear shows was not about the masculine merits of clamdiggers or
the demise of the backpack in favor of an over-the-shoulder bag
with a strap as wide as a Miss Universe sash. The query on
everyone's lips was, ``Who's the guy with the mustache?'' The man
causing the flurry of interest in an otherwise uneventful three
days of shows in New York for Spring 2000 was Eugene Hutz, a model
who also is a member of a Ukrainian punk rock band called Gogol
Bordello. Hutz, 25, appeared in only two fashion shows _ for the
designers Marc Jacobs and Nigel Curtiss _ but he garnered the
lion's share of notice. By Frank DeCaro. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-TAILORS (New York) _ Taking a cue from professional
clothes hangers and social swans like Blaine Trump, who have
quietly frequented tailors for years, many insist that a $500
custom suit or dress made in the style of a Gucci or a Dior is just
as chic and often more deftly constructed than the $2,000 original.
(To avoid any legal questions about copying the designs of others,
the tailors say they make minor modifications in the fabric, shape
and details.) But savings isn't the major draw for tailoring's
newest devotees. Young professionals who can well afford
high-fashion beading or Savile Row draping forgo such luxuries for
the thrill of outfoxing the system and playing designer themselves.
By Ruth La Ferla. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Three evergreen ground covers that are
treasured for their resistance to disease and pests as well as for
their elegant beauty. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
