<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOWELL-ANTIQUES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE SHOPPING WITH MALCOLM MCDOWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 8)  
(mk) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's something else to do, away from the damn movies,''
Malcolm McDowell said, throwing himself into an afternoon of
indulging his other passions: antique watches, painted Shaker
furniture and 19th-century flywheel toys. ``And it's a lot of
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, 56, collects with the same wild-eyed intensity that
makes him such a distinctive, often disturbing actor. In New York
last week to promote his latest movie, ``My Life So Far,'' McDowell
invited his dealer along for the excursion. Steven Weiss, of Gemini
Antiques, has supplied much of the early Americana that fills
McDowell's home _ a barn outside Santa Barbara, Calif., where he
lives with his third wife, Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   As the car inched across the Upper East Side, Weiss made the
mistake of likening McDowell's new film, a tony period piece, to a
Merchant Ivory production.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know what he's talking about!'' an appalled
McDowell bellowed from the back seat. ``I associate Merchant Ivory
with sentimental stuff.'' Not exactly McDowell's genre.
</P>
<P>
   First stop, Evergreen Antiques, on Third Avenue at 72nd Street.
McDowell strode into the shop with the cocky, bowlegged gait of the
psychotic thug he played in ``A Clockwork Orange'' and started
poking around, without breaking anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' he said, spotting an 18th-century cabinet priced at
$38,000. It passed the McDowell test by looking great from three
feet, 15 feet and 45 feet away. ``It should have impact from all
those distances.'' The same might be said of McDowell, whose
twisted verve was now being benignly channeled into a collector's
boyish enthusiasm. He settled on two tramp-art boxes ($65 and $85)
before bidding the politely starstruck owners farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Time for Time Will Tell, a small vintage-watch store on Madison
Avenue at 76th Street. The owner was out. McDowell greeted the
saleswoman behind the counter with ``What have you got, darling?''
and zeroed in on a 1927 Patek Philippe: 18-karat gold, porcelain
dial with italicized Roman numerals, $7,200. Peering through a
jeweler's loupe, he marveled, ``The finest movement ever made!''
Then, ``This isn't a reconditioned dial or anything, is it?'' His
mercurial actor's face shifted to momentary disgust at the thought
that anyone might have tampered with such an exquisite timepiece.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing around chronophile lingo like ``bubbleback'' and
``California dial,'' he picked up a Rolex Prince from the '30s.
``You know who used to collect these?'' he asked. ``You couldn't
get one while he was alive. Andy Warhol. He had 150 Princes!''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell's watch collection is more modest. About 60, of
different makes, he said. Today, he wore a 1916 Longines, its clear
white face as large as a pocket watch. Telling the saleswoman he
would call the owner to wrangle for a better price on the Patek, he
made his exit from the little shop, sucking much of the air out
with him.
</P>
<P>
   In the back seat again, he stressed that there is a limit to
what he can spend on such trinkets: ``I'm not a millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   At Weiss' apartment cum showroom on West End Avenue, McDowell
pressed this point on his dealer, who was showing off two
portraits, of a little boy and girl, by Joseph Whiting Stock, in
the American-primitive style. Weiss valued the pair, painted circa
1845, at $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dreaming!'' McDowell said. He squinted at the better of
the two pictures, the girl. ``What are you asking for it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, 30,000,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to me, darling. What'll you sell it to me for?''
</P>
<P>
   They moved on. After an hour's haggling and an impromptu
performance from a gangster film he had just finished shooting,
McDowell bought a wooden milliner's head for $850. On the way out,
he took off his 1916 Longines and gave it to Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for you,'' he said. ``You've always wanted a good
watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
