<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx14;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGNER-TAILORS-ART-     08-06 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-TAILORS-ART-$ADV08-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT, HAUTE AND TAILORED, WITHOUT THE FANCY LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release Sun., August 8)  
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mark Heithoff decided to abandon his signature
orange trousers and velour Korean flight jacket for something a
little more subtle, he ventured into Seize sur Vingt, a custom
clothier to the downtown set, on Elizabeth Street.
</P>
<P>
   James Jurney, the store's denim-clad tailor and part owner,
fitted Heithoff for a dapper but casual cotton shirt that perfectly
suited his tastes. ``I'm tired of being a billboard for somebody
else's style,'' said Heithoff, who wanted a businesslike but hip
alternative to the ``stuffed shirt looks'' he usually finds on the
racks.
</P>
<P>
   Farther uptown, about a three-minute walk from Bloomingdale's,
Joanne Weill stood rail-backed under the chandelier at Eva
Devecsery's custom atelier, careful not to dislodge the pins
securing the seam of her green velvet gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband picked out the fabric in Paris,'' she murmured.
``Yes,'' chimed in Mrs. Devecsery, a diminutive Hungarian-born
woman with a tape measure slung around her neck like a rope of
pearls. ``It's his contribution to the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Heitfhoff, 30, a portrait photographer, and Mrs. Weill, the
impeccably coiffed 50-ish wife of the financier Sanford I. Weill,
have joined the expanding circle of New Yorkers deserting designer
labels now and then for the personalized services of a custom
tailor or dressmaker. Working in downtown lofts with peeling walls
and muslin-curtained fitting rooms or in Old World-style salons
appointed with pretend Louis furnishings, such establishments have
lately become magnets to shrewd bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from professional clothes hangers and social swans
like Blaine Trump, who have quietly frequented tailors for years,
many insist that a $500 custom suit or dress made in the style of a
Gucci or a Dior is just as chic and often more deftly constructed
than the $2,000 original. (To avoid any legal questions about
copying the designs of others, the tailors say they make minor
modifications in the fabric, shape and details.)
</P>
<P>
   But savings isn't the major draw for tailoring's newest
devotees. Young professionals who can well afford high-fashion
beading or Savile Row draping forgo such luxuries for the thrill of
outfoxing the system and playing designer themselves. Visiting a
tailor is the ``perfect pursuit for the creatively challenged,''
said Lisa Gabor, 35, an editor working on a start-up magazine for
Time Inc. ``They're the kinds of people who know what they want but
would sew their fingers together if they went near a needle and
thread.'' Heithoff likens the process to a think-tank exchange in
which the client retains creative control _ the sartorial
equivalent of a director's cut.
</P>
<P>
   One need not be style-struck to take part, but it helps. Just
ask Ms. Gabor, whose closet teems with Armani and Gucci look-alikes
whipped up by Joseph Ting of Dynasty Custom Tailor in midtown
Manhattan. Or Michael A. Schub, a New York lawyer, who said, ``At a
tailor you can indulge your fantasy and create any sort of
variation on a style that comes to mind.'' He recently persuaded
Ned Mateosian of Ned on lower Fifth Avenue to fit him for a
double-breasted suit with a notch collar, creating a stylistic
hybrid that, Schub said, ``you don't easily find off the peg.'' Or
check with Sharon Scott, who works in a New York accounting firm.
Ms. Scott had her heart set on a Versace dress to wear to a recent
gala, persuading Joan Weston, her dressmaker in the Bronx, to run
up a line-for-line copy. The price of her new blue and white
one-shoulder silk evening dress: $350, a trifle compared with the
$5,000-plus for the made-in-Milan original.
</P>
<P>
   Until the advent of designer ready-to-wear in the late 1960's,
dressmakers' salons were mainly the province of fashionable matrons
ordering copies of the Paris haute couture. But that has changed.
``There is clearly an element of remarkably young, very successful
people going to tailors without fail,'' said Suzanne Kilgore, the
executive director of the 300-member Custom Tailors and Designers
Association in Washington. Her observations are anecdotal, since
there is no official client profile or tally of American tailors,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Running mostly small, independent businesses, tailors generally
drum up trade through word of mouth _ no easy feat, given that
clients tend to guard their clothiers' identities jealously.
Marjorie Gubelmann, 30, a private venture capitalist, said she is
thrilled that her dressmaker shares her taste for vintage Balmain
and dresses photographed on contemporary royalty, which run her
$1,500 to $3,000 _ a fraction of the cost of a Paris original.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't tell you his name,'' she said. ``If he became
commercial, he'd be too busy, and probably too expensive. And I
would no longer have the best little secret in New York.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Others _ including more than a few fashion stylists and
socialites _ have another secret they'd prefer not get out: they
buy garments off the rack, engage a tailor to knock them off, then
return the originals to the stores. They are content to reproduce
the current runway hits. More daring customers may invent a look
outright, their creativity hemmed in only by the size of their
wallets and their imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our clients _ he never carries a briefcase _ asked to
have 50 secret pockets stitched inside the lining of his suit
coat,'' said Luna Song, Dynasty's design adviser. Few requests are
too esoteric or challenging for Ms. Song, who adapts or interprets
even the most eccentric ideas with a little judicious tweaking.
``One lady asked us for a wedding dress modeled on a crinoline gown
that that she'd seen in `Gone with the Wind,''' she recalled. ``But
we cut down the skirt so the client could actually move in it.''
</P>
<P>
   When clients come in clutching ``swipe'' _ magazine tear sheets
or film stills they want copied _ she is encouraging, sometimes
going so far as to send them to museums, libraries or movies for
inspiration. ``Designers do it all the time,'' said Ms. Song, whose
workroom runs up samples for J.Crew and Gene Meyer, a men's wear
specialist. ``Why shouldn't ordinary people?''
</P>
<P>
   On his first visit to Ned, where a custom jacket with a
hand-stitched canvas runs about $750, Frank Perich implored the
tailor to interpret one of his long-cherished fantasies. ``I asked
for a three-piece version of the black suit Cary Grant wore in
`North by Northwest,''' said Perich, an actor who appears in
``Summer of Sam.'' Two fittings later, Perich was so happy with his
purchase that he proceeded to order a ringer for Grant's trademark
black topcoat, followed by duplicates of his blue blazer and gray
flannels. Perich finds the process addictive. ``I don't smoke, I
don't drink, I don't buy sex,'' he said, laughing darkly. ``This is
my obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's impatience that sends people to a custom
workroom. ``I do a lot of weddings,'' said Bill Bull, whose
clients, mostly fashion insiders, have access to pri-cey bridal and
evening-wear salons but lack the forbearance to put up with lengthy
fittings or delayed deliveries. ``They want something simple, but
they don't want to wait nine months for a Vera Wang,'' Bull said.
</P>
<P>
   More commonly, clients ask him to duplicate a favorite pair of
Daryl K trousers or Audrey Hepburn's little black dress from
``Breakfast at Tiffany's.'' And then there are people who ask for
the moon. He declines to identify the well-known model who showed
him a badly battered Victorian lace dress, begging, ``Make me be
able to wear this.'' Part couturier, part textile conservationist,
Bull obliged, reconstructing the flea market frock, tier by tier
and bead by bead, and supplying an underskirt in the bargain. At
$1,200, such services are beyond most people's reach, but to his
client, he maintained, they are worth every penny. ``Her closet is
full of Pradas,'' he said with a shrug, ``but she wants to wear
vintage lace.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people need look no farther than their closets for
salvageable relics. Elaine Hershcopf, the wife of a Manhattan real
estate lawyer and a confessed couture pack rat, hangs onto the
Chanel suits and Dior evening dresses she bought in Europe in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very beautiful, expensive things I can't discard,'' she
said, ``so sometimes I'll change a detail or raise the shoulders.''
The latter, a labor-intensive procedure, may run her $100. ``But it
pays,'' she said. ``When I wear my old couture dresses I get more
compliments than when they were brand-new.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Hershcopf's best ideas start with an old dress, Ms.
Gabor's frequently originate with a piece of fabric. Not long ago
she traveled to Bangkok, carrying along her tailor's yardage
requirements for a shirt. She returned with a length of fuchsia
silk, which Ting promptly transformed into a replica of that
season's rage, a close-fitting long-collar Gucci top. The price:
About $160, fabric not included. The fit: Perfect. ``I might have
bought that shirt off the rack,'' Ms. Gabor acknowledged. ``But
let's face it, some of us aren't born with the contours to wear
whatever happens to be going on this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasional extreme request doesn't faze Ned Mateosian, whose
clients include the basketball star Charles Oakley, for whom he
constructed a chrome yellow suit, one of about 100 similar styles
he cut for Oakley in every hue of the spectrum. ``He likes bright
colors,'' Mateosian said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Some tailors, however, insist on saving clients from themselves.
When a buxom celebrity asks for a dress better suited to Gwyneth
Paltrow's lithe frame, ``my job is to talk her out of it,'' Ms.
Song said. The same for the recalcitrant 12-year-old dragged into
the shop by her exasperated mom. ``The girl wants a tube top,''
said Ms. Song, who is quick to suggest a more demure alternative.
Why, she wondered, does she have to look like a Spice Girl?
</P>
<P>
   Most tailors defuse such potentially explosive encounters with a
bluntness tempered by infinite tact. ``Your shoulders slope,''
Jurney of Seize sur Vingt told Heithoff, but seeing his client's
look of alarm, was quick to put in, ``Of course, that's common with
people who work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gabor reported that visits to Ting are usually balm for the
ego. ``You know the best thing about Joseph?'' she said. ``When you
walk in, he always asks, `Have you lost weight?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
