<HEADER>
A8420 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-FUTURE08-COX     08-06 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-FUTURE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong NEA a key to future, critic says
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even a demanding observer of the American theater _ Robert
Brustein, critic of The New Republic magazine and artistic director
of American Repertory Theatre in Cambridge, Mass. _ has hope for
the art form's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sea change,'' he says. ``Plays are making a comeback
on Broadway. I don't see a diminishment of writing talent. David
Mamet is in his prime. We have Paula Vogel, Anna Deavere Smith,
Suzanne Lori-Parks, Tony Kushner.''
</P>
<P>
   Top playwrights also include August Wilson, David Henry Hwang,
John Guare, Jon Robin Baitz, Wendy Wasserstein, Richard Greenberg.
Few are prolific, yet they can't be expected to spend all their
time on $10,000 play commissions when television and movies offer
up to $1 million for scripts.
</P>
<P>
   The key to making their challenging plays economically viable,
Brustein says, is support beyond the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must beef up the National Endowment for the Arts,'' he
declares, ``and return to making grants for excellence instead of
sociology. Without public funds, theaters are forced toward
commercial work or pleasing the tastes of private benefactors. The
deficit then becomes artistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a revolution in arts education,'' the critic-director
added, ``because children are taught that art is just
self-expression and are not being exposed to the best that's been
created.''
</P>
<P>
   If the language-centered playwright is uncertain of his
audiences, the image-centered theater artist will be in sync with
future tastes. ``The Who's Tommy'' (1993), a triumph in elegant,
computerized slide projections, appealed to graying baby boomers
and teenagers. The technological savvy and deconstructed language
of avant-garde auteurs _ Robert Wilson, Peter Sellars, Elizabeth
LeCompte and their younger followers _ speak the visual language of
a generation raised on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet as tool for ticket sales and theatrical information
is tapping new audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But there is justifiable worry over ``corporatization'' on
Broadway and on the road. Replacing the colorful, David
Merrick-style independent producers of yore are diversified
entertainment giants and theater owners such as Disney (the
forthcoming ``Hunchback of Notre Dame''); SFX, owner of Pace
Theatrical Group (the forthcoming ``Seussical''); and the
financially troubled Livent (``Ragtime''). Disney's ``Beauty and
the Beast'' and Pace's ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' show the sterile, plastic
quality of corporate products.
</P>
<P>
   ``With costs running from $8 million to $10 million for musicals
_ and some of us believe `Lion King' cost twice that _ the smaller
player has trouble,'' said Miles Wilkins, chairman of Pace, whose
many national tour packages include the Atlanta Broadway Series.
``The advantage of (corporate producers) is having resources to
meet rising expectations of the public, to keep projects in lengthy
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was talk of the `death of the mega-musical,''' Wilkins
added, ``but I don't buy it. Folks want it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, theater's best hope may be an intangible, timeless
factor that transcends economics or technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only times theater has died, civilization died with it,''
says Zelda Fichandler, who ran the Arena Stage of Washington for 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's seen `Iceman Cometh' (on Broadway with Kevin
Spacey) knows there's nothing like being drenched in the same
emotions that characters are feeling in the instant. Theater won't
die. We all yearn to breathe the same air as the person telling the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8421 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATRE-CENTURY2NDTAK     08-06 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATRE-CENTURY2NDTAKE08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: and the Seattle Repertory Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The `marriage' crumbles
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as people moved to the suburbs and fell in love with
their TVs in the 1960s and '70s, serious plays were increasingly
shunned on Broadway, unless _ like Edward Albee's ``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?,'' a ferocious little cocktail hour gone wrong _
they could offer titillation. Only Neil Simon in his early sitcom
phase thrived as a nonmusical playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Off- and off-off Broadway were the creative caldrons from the
late '60s through the late '70s. The Negro Ensemble Company
flourished under Douglas Turner Ward; playwrights Amiri Baraka and
James Baldwin distilled black rage into cool eloquence. Charles
Ludlam raised gay camp to literate art in his Ridiculous Theatrical
Company. The Living Theater amazed (and annoyed) patrons with such
demands as ``Give me all your money!'' Sam Shepard waited tables at
the Village Gate and captured the heady, hallucinogenic moment in
the Beat spirit of Jack Kerouac, usually _ but not always _ waiting
for the drugs to wear off before writing. When a boyish Sam
Waterston, in 1967's ``La Turista,'' ran through the wall of the
set and left a body-shaped hole, a new genius left his mark.
Shepard was blasting through the old walls of the American theater.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-'80s and his second, movie-acting career, Shepard
was the most prolific, original playwright in America _ his subject
was America, embodied in self-invented rock stars, cowboys, con
men. The most damning fact about Broadway is that no producer dared
to produce Shepard there in all those years.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of art and commerce was on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   A loss of joy
</P>
<P>
   These were hard transitional years for the musical, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Dolly!'' with Carol Channing and ``Fiddler on the
Roof'' with Zero Mostel, in the mid-'60s, marked the end of its
golden age. Bob Fosse (``Sweet Charity'') and Michael Bennett (``A
Chorus Line'') maintained excitement through the '70s with sensual
dances, but each died before his time. Stephen Sondheim learned at
Hammerstein's knee, but his lyrics had more biting wit, his tunes
less hummability. His ``Company'' and ``Follies'' _ John Updikian
dissections of marriages _ brought refreshing reality to the art
form but weren't about to blanket the nation in high school and
amateur productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Hair' (1969), it got to be that you never see musicals
on contemporary subjects _ with a rare exception like `Rent' _ and
that's a problem,'' Uhry says. ``What's lacking in musicals _ and I
include my own work _ is joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-Vietnam and Watergate, the theater reflected a nation with
less to be joyful about. Although David Mamet's exposes of
capitalism's jungle law (1977's ``American Buffalo,'' 1984's
``Glengarry Glen Ross'') were 10 times funnier than Miller's, they
were so savage that they ran a fraction as long on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, the monologist (Spalding Gray, Eric Bogosian, Karen
Finley) rekindled the primal fascination of the lone storyteller.
Playwrights saw AIDS as a national emergency (Larry Kramer's ``The
Normal Heart''), likewise persecution of gays. But many mainstream
theatergoers felt too distantly affected by either issue to connect
with the plays, unless _ like Tony Kushner's masterwork, ``Angels
in America'' _ they addressed a range of issues with a compelling
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   By 1991, most of Broadway's income came from British
blockbusters (``Cats,'' ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' ``Miss
Saigon'') catering to the one-show-a-year tourists. Plays of
thought and substance became like old photo albums and broken
musical instruments, pushed into attics and garages. The new
magazine Entertainment Weekly only mentioned a play if a young
movie star happened to be in it.
</P>
<P>
   Art and commerce got a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   To diversity, to the Bard
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, regional theaters, typically covering their bets with
a mixture of art (classics, new dramas) and commerce (musicals,
comedies) gathered strength. A breakthrough was the 1977 launch of
the Humana Festival of New American Plays at Jon Jory's Actors
Theatre of Louisville, where Beth Henley's ``Crimes of the Heart''
debuted. Regionals began premiering and exporting _ not just
importing _ new plays.
</P>
<P>
   The theater scenes blossomed in turn: Chicago and San Francisco
and Minneapolis in the '70s, San Diego and Seattle in the '80s,
Atlanta in the '90s. In this last decade, artistic directorships
diversified swiftly, with the appointment of blacks (Kenny Leon at
the Alliance, George C. Wolfe at the New York Shakespeare Festival)
and women (Molly Smith at the Arena, Carey Perloff at A.C.T),
though the new multicultural plays they promoted were rarely hits.
Buffered from the vicissitudes of contemporary playwriting,
companies specializing in Shakespeare _ in Washington; Ashland,
Oregon; Montgomery _ gained in luster. By 1999, there were 189
professional theaters running nationwide, playing to an annual
audience of 14.5 million _ 3 million more than Broadway's record
mark of that season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nonprofits are financially insecure, as dependent on
politically sensitive grants as the bouncing box office. Sometimes
it seemed audiences were never fully satisfied with anything but
``A Christmas Carol.'' Again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This worries me,'' says Robert
</P>
<P>
   Brustein, critic for The New Republic and artistic director of
American Repertory Theatre in Cambridge, Mass. ``The nonprofits
were set up as an alternative to the commercial sector, and many
end up imitating it, getting less adventurous over the years. ...
The Alliance Theatre's collaboration with Disney is something I
worry about, too, though I can see the need for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Alliance's cumulative deficit increased to $800,000
last season even with the record-setting ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agenda
</P>
<P>
   The families of O'Neill's and Williams' plays, so startling for
their time, look like the folks next door compared to the
super-dysfunctional denizens of end-of-the-century plays.
</P>
<P>
   Consider characters in the recent Pulitzer Prize winners: the
idiot father who mocks his daughter's breasts in Paula Vogel's
``How I Learned to Drive''; the idiot doctor who calls a
50-year-old professor a ``girl'' in Margaret Edson's ``Wit.''
Although they're minor characters in otherwise strong plays, these
unreal men seem to serve as hollow vessels for their authors'
contempt. It's as if anger is being rushed onstage in raw chunks,
without undergoing the full transformative magic of the artistic
process.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, anger is the engine that drives the plays of Odets,
Miller, Mamet, Ntozake Shange (``For Colored Girls ...''). Even if
it means that theater becomes less visible in the culture, more
like a specialized cable channel than a broadcast network, anger
must have a place. The stage by its nature favors change.
</P>
<P>
   One who felt his world change in a theater was the late Frank
McMullen, a Yale drama professor. He told students that after
seeing the first act of ``Salesman'' in 1949, he fled to the
bathroom to weep. He was so shaken that it took several minutes to
notice that the people in the stalls on either side were wearing
high heels.
</P>
<P>
   Uhry recently saw the revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers, old men, all kinds of people were sobbing,'' he
says. ``Now tell me that play doesn't still speak to America
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
