<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATRE-CENTURY1STTAK     08-06 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATRE-CENTURY1STTAKE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How America became stage-struck
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1944, Horton Foote, a Texas-bred playwright
struggling to make it in New York, received a letter from his
equally penniless Southern friend Tennessee Williams, who was
peddling screenplays in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so discouraged,'' recalls the 83-year-old Foote, who
won the 1995 Pulitzer Prize for ``The Young Man From Atlanta.''
``He wrote, `I've got a pretty good play, but it has no commercial
possibilities.' Tennessee was so hungry, he had to have a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He had it. ``The Glass Menagerie,'' on March 3, 1945, began a
fabled Broadway run of 560 performances. Its success, both in
critical response and at the box office, came from Williams'
refusal to follow formulas that prevailed in the movie industry
(MGM had rejected an earlier draft, ``The Gentleman Caller.'')
Williams wrote fearlessly from his heart, spinning from the
strange, claustrophobic specifics of his sister Rose, mother Edwina
and himself a poetic drama of universal reach. He had no way of
knowing that Eugene O'Neill had already written ``Long Day's
Journey Into Night'' and locked it in a safe until after his death,
so nakedly did it expose his loved ones. The playwrights had
crystallized the defining form of American play in the 20th
century: the realistic family drama.
</P>
<P>
   Television was still little known, so ``Menagerie'' _ an event
seen by fewer than 1,000 people a night, ballyhooed on radio and
newspaper wire services _ could still capture the nation's
undistracted consciousness. It captured Foote's. As the
gate-crasher stood at the rear of Broadway's Playhouse Theater
(Williams smuggled him in through the stage door), Foote was struck
by ``how Laurette Taylor (as Amanda) and the rest of the actors
gave the words a complete life you missed on the page. Jo
Mielziner's set, too, was part of the magic. That night taught me
that this art form is so collaborative, so ephemeral.''
</P>
<P>
   When theater was king
</P>
<P>
   ``Menagerie'' was a magical marriage of two estranged traditions
in American theater _ commerce and art _ a union so improbable that
even the author could not see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   And how could he? With few exceptions until then, American
theater _ like America itself _ was about commerce. Before movies
learned to speak, theater and its raffish brother, vaudeville, were
among the leading sources of mass entertainment. Between 1900 and
1927, the number of New York theaters quadrupled, from 20 to 80,
and even smallish cities (Macon and Columbus, for instance) had
their classy venues for tours.
</P>
<P>
   Theater was more like the movies in that the writer was
secondary to the producer and star _ combined, for example, in the
person of George M. Cohan. Leftists and egghead writers such as
George Bernard Shaw were for tired, old, cloudy Europe; the sunny
triumphal conservatism of the Yankee Doodle Dandy was unchallenged.
It was the Age of Personality. One went to a show not for the title
or author but the sheer energizing presence of Al Jolson, Ed Wynn,
the Barrymores (John, Ethel, Lionel).
</P>
<P>
   Innocent young lovers warbled Victor Herbert's ``Ah, Sweet
Mystery of Life.'' ``The Wizard of Oz,'' ``Babes in Toyland'' and
``Peter Pan'' all debuted before World War I.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the madness of that war revolutionized other arts
(Stravinsky, Joyce, the dadaists), it sent subtler tremors under
the boards of Gotham. Mae West was thrown in jail for 10 days for
writing and playing a hooker in 1926's ``Sex'' (it was a smash,
even though the papers wouldn't print the ads). The explicitness,
not the subject matter, was new. Broadway had long leered over
titillating melodramas about cheating spouses.
</P>
<P>
   The staginess of melodrama hung on under O'Neill, even in bold
experiments such as the spoken thoughts or ``interior monologues''
of his seven-hour ``Strange Interlude.'' Robert Benchley of The
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker called it ``an interesting stunt carried about four
acts too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of O'Neill was new. As was said of Milton, he wrote a
mighty line, as seen in the updated Greek myth of ``Mourning
Becomes Electra.'' With O'Neill, American plays became not just
entertainment, but literature.
</P>
<P>
   There were even more experimental playwrights in the '20s and
'30s: Sophie Treadwell, whose ``Machinal'' showed life as a
male-run machine; Elmer Rice and Clifford Odets, whose America was
a capitalist-run machine. But with their limited audiences they
could have been on a different planet from the solidly crafted,
happy-making star vehicles: Helen Hayes in Maxwell Anderson's
costume dramas; Tallulah Bankhead in Lillian Hellman's ``The Little
Foxes''; Ethel Merman in Cole Porter's ``Anything Goes'' and the
Gershwin brothers' ``Girl Crazy''; and the Lunts in just about
everything else, it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show music was in sync with popular taste,'' says Alfred Uhry,
who studied under Frank Loesser (``Guys and Dolls'') on the way to
a 1999 Tony Award for best book of a musical (``Parade''). ``You'd
hear the hit song on the radio and go see the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the innovations of Jerome Kern and Oscar
Hammerstein II's 1927 ``Show Boat'' _ songs to advance dramatic
story, a black actor opening with the stupendous ``Old Man River''
_ but the producer was the same Florenz Ziegfeld who was packing
'em in for his leggy, gaudy ``Follies.'' Even ``Show Boat'' was
commerce first, with art far down the list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Five golden years
</P>
<P>
   ``The Glass Menagerie'' brought the two elements into balance.
Thus began a five-year roll of works that entertained with no
compromise in excellence: Rodgers' and Hammerstein's ``Carousel''
(darker, deeper than ``Oklahoma!'') and ``South Pacific'';
O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh''; Williams' ``A Streetcar Named
Desire''; and Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman.'' In the last
two productions, director Elia Kazan perfected a poetic, gutsy,
uniquely American realism to rival the more abstract styles in
continental Europe and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   No American burg could be mentioned in the same breath as New
York. If, in 1949, a fortuneteller predicted that ``Salesman''
would triumphantly return in a remount of a Chicago production (the
current Goodman Theatre staging with Brian Dennehy), she would have
been laughed out of her Times Square parlor.
</P>
<P>
   If she'd prophesied a Walt Disney version of ``Aida'' in little
ol' Atlanta, she'd be buckled into a straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   What happened after 1950 _ Act 2 of the century _ to bring these
startling changes?
</P>
<P>
   Women on the `frontier'
</P>
<P>
   Talent was already ``out there'' _ west of the Hudson River, in
a few scattered semiprofessional outposts such as the Goodman of
Chicago and the Old Globe of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Now a wave of regional talent arose, led by women. Margo Jones'
Theatre '47 was a few steps from the livestock pavilions at the
Texas State Fair grounds in Dallas, but her first season premiered
the Williams play that evolved into ``Summer and Smoke.'' Zelda
Fichandler started the Arena Stage in Washington in 1950, not on
the model of a Broadway house (a place that producers rent on a
per-project basis) but rather a European repertory house, a
nonprofit troupe offering a full season of artists in residence.
</P>
<P>
   The local actors and designers were shaky at first, but the
programming was sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called a visionary, but I honestly couldn't see past
getting the toilets cleaned at first,'' says Fichandler, who
retired from the Arena in 1990 and now teaches at New York
University. ``Our modest mission was to bring theater, like
libraries and museums, to where people live. To let artists, whose
job is to interpret the life of the community, live there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chekhov and Moliere with local actors did not catch on
immediately in cities that had known only star tours, so the
National Endowment for the Arts (founded in 1965) was
indispensable. The next 15 years saw the founding of the Mark Taper
Forum in Los Angeles, the American Conservatory Theatre in San
Francisco, the Alliance Theatre in Atlanta, the Denver Center
Theatre and the Seattle Repertory Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
