<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8424 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BERNADETTE07-COX     08-06 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BERNADETTE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peters shines through bevy of Broadway tunes
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is drama queen, imp, big bad wolf and girl next door. And
when she is good, as she is in most of this PBS pledge-drive
special, she doesn't just sing songs, she inhabits them.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Peters, one of Broadway's reigning divas, delivers 22
tunes in this 85-minute concert from London's Royal Festival Hall.
And, after a slow start _ ``You're in the Money'' in English and
pig Latin(!?) and her saucy, overexposed ``Broadway Baby'' _ she
hits the bull's-eye.
</P>
<P>
   This concert is similar to the one Peters did last October in
Atlanta but she mixes in just enough new songs to keep things
interesting. Metro fans didn't get the tender, tongue-in-check
``Raining in My Heart'' from ``Dames at Sea,'' for example, or the
exquisite ``Later'' from ``A Little Night Music.'' The latter is
one tough number, requiring operatic highs, deep and resonant lows,
and a heck of a lot of breath control. It's not done often, let
alone this well, and we're lucky Peters has added it to her
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, Peters is patter perfect, from the
tongue-twisting lyrics of ``You Could Drive a Person Crazy'' to the
rapid-fire ruminations of ``Some People.'' You can tell the songs
she especially connects with. It's in her eyes, and often in her
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include ``Unexpected Song'' from Andrew Lloyd
Webber's ``Song and Dance,'' and ``Moving On'' from Stephen
Sondheim's ``Sunday in the Park With George.'' In fact the entire
second act is devoted to her buddy Steve with numbers from
``Sweeney Todd,'' ``Into the Woods,'' ``Anyone Can Whistle'' and
``Merrily We Roll Along.''
</P>
<P>
   While this all makes for a very good night, it could be better.
Compared with other one-woman shows (Patti LuPone's 1995 Broadway
gig, for example), there are too few spontaneous moments. And we
don't always know what song Peters is singing or where it came from
(titles superimposed on the screen would help). Still, that's like
quibbling over the kind of olive in the best martini you've ever
sipped.
</P>
<P>
   Peters _ with her serious talent, china-doll skin, baby-doll
pout and crown of reddish curls _ is as superlative as that
cocktail can be. And just as intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernadette Peters in Concert''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on WGTV and 8 p.m. Thursday on WPBA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Janich writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
