<P>
   AOL-MINDSPRING _ America Online signs up MindSpring to offer
instant message software on the mindspring homepage. This deal was
in the works long before the IM wars started with Microsoft and is
part of MindSpring's long term plan to put more ``sticky products
on its homepage.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-COX _ATLANTA _The FCC ruling that media companies can own
more than one station in a market will cause Cox Enterprises to
reevaluate its position. Perhaps this will ultimately rearrange
ownership of stations in Atlanta, a lucrative market in which Cox
owns the largest station. Other markets? Other media companies?
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-PIRACY _ The owners of Microseconds, one of the
companies charged by Microsoft with selling pirate software,
responds to the accusations. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-JOBS _ The U.S. economy churned out far more jobs in
July than Wall Street expected, causing the biggest increase in
average hourly earnings in seven months and increasing the odds the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates soon. The Labor
Department said Friday that non-farm payrolls rose 310,000 in July
as wages climbed six cents, or 0.5%, to $13.29. Both numbers
exceeded Wall Street expectations and caused a slump in bond prices
which is expected to carry over to the stock market. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
