<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEY-CLIPS-ART-$ADV0     08-06 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-CLIPS-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING EMPTIES A FAT WALLET FASTER THAN A MONEY CLIP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You carry a money clip?'' my friend asked, staring
at me as we split the check after a recent dinner. ``Who do you
think you are _ Damon Runyon?''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, I tossed my wallet into the trash and began
carrying my cash in an old-fashioned money clip. I was glad to get
rid of the wallet, since it had long stopped functioning as a
billfold and become a repository for bank deposit slips, bent
business cards, Post-it notes and other things too important to
throw out but not important enough to deal with promptly.
</P>
<P>
   It had become so fat and heavy, in fact, that when jammed into
my back pocket, I could no longer sit down without listing to the
left.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't any space inside for cash, and I'd taken to shoving
my bills haphazardly into various pants pockets. My wife, annoyed
to catch me leaving crumpled bills behind in taxicabs, bought me a
money clip as a birthday gift.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never really paid attention to money clips before, but now I
can't imagine the disordered state of affairs without one. Mine is
gold-plated, hinged, with a little snapping-turtle action, and
engraved with my initials. For my ID and credit cards, I bought
myself the necessary companion, a slim gray leather card holder,
anchored with a single screw, which allows me to fan my plastic out
like playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   These days, virtually every man I know shares the common
complaint of a bloated and unwieldy wallet. Many are carrying more
gold and platinum plastic than necessary, or comfortable. And
without the luxury of those bottomless-pit handbags beloved by
women, most guys are forced to turn their wallets into traveling
file cabinets, stuffed with phone numbers, dry-cleaning receipts
and other clutter.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, I've noticed more and more men doing away with the
conventional wallet, replacing it with a money clip and a slim-line
credit-card case. A few months back, I spotted my friend Adam
Wiener, an executive producer at CBS New Media, pulling out a brown
leather credit-card holder, made by Fossil, with a brass clip
attached to the front. ``My old wallet just took up too much
space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This model, which retails for $18 to $20 at Lord &AMP; Taylor,
Stern's and Macy's, is marketed as a Front Pocket Wallet, and
according to Jim Cullen, an account representative at Fossil Inc.,
a maker of hip sunglasses, watches, belts and other accessories, it
is by far the company's hottest selling item this year, now
accounting for 25 percent of Fossil's total sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started as a golfer's wallet, because it's lightweight and
fits in their front pocket,'' Cullen said. ``Golfers wanted a money
clip attached to a gusseted credit-card case with room for just two
or three cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharper Image advertises a similar design, a slim card
holder with a Velcro money clip attached, in grained leather
($39.95) or mock crocodile ($44.95). ``Instead of loading down your
back pocket with an overstuffed wallet _ tempting thieves,'' the
catalog copy reads, lighten up with our innovative Deep Pocket
Safety Wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   These all-in-one styles are gaining favor, but most
traditionalists insist on separating the clip and credit cards in
different pockets. The latest trend in money clips is the
leather-covered magnetic models by Coach ($30), Tumi ($18) and
Fossil ($15).
</P>
<P>
   They're a bit high-concept for my taste. I prefer the more
classic designs. Macy's Estate Collection of antique jewelry
features a sterling silver owl and a simple rectangular clip
engraved with a dollar sign.
</P>
<P>
   Nat Sherman, the cigar store, sells a cigar-decorated clip, and
Peter Stonehill, a salesman, said that sterling clips with the
logos of Cadillac, Mercedes-Benz and BMW have been selling briskly.
</P>
<P>
   At Barneys New York, Gabriella Vassallo, men's accessory buyer,
said, ``We're seeing a great business in customers using a flat
credit-card case and a money clip for their bills.'' The store
carries traditional rectangular money clips, in sterling, ranging
from $55 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   These models are more like the old money clips that were carried
to do away with pocket detritus and to make a style statement as
well. Cecil B. DeMille carried his cash in a clip bearing the
figure of an Oscar. The notoriously parsimonious Jack Benny gave a
gold money clip to his pal George Burns, featuring caricatures of
them both.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy's money clip was a first-anniversary gift from
his wife: it bore an image of St. Christopher, and he had it in his
pocket when he was killed in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra, ``went nowhere without his money clip,'' said
Bill Zehme, the author of ``The Way You Wear Your Hat: Frank
Sinatra and the Lost Art of Livin''' (HarperCollins, 1997). Sinatra
favored a gold triangular paper-clip design from Tiffany's and no
card holder. ``He never carried a credit card in his life,'' Zehme
said. ``He loathed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan King, in his memoir, ``Name-Dropping'' (Scribner, 1996),
recounts buying a gold money clip engraved with an image of the
Torah, from Swifty Morgan, a Runyonesque figure whom King describes
as carrying tissue-wrapped jewelry in every pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In King's account, the money clip had belonged to Rabbi Stephen
S. Wise, who had parted with it on his deathbed. King treasured the
clip for its rabbinical provenance until he spotted Sinatra in
Beverly Hills pulling out a wad of cash from an identical Torah
money clip. ``Oh, it's a great story,'' Sinatra told King. ``On his
deathbed, Rabbi Wise gave it to Swifty Morgan.''
</P>
<P>
   Money clips gradually fell out of favor when they became less
associated with swells than with old fogies _ like carrying a
fountain pen or a cigarette case _ and with mobsters, at least in
popular imagination, though not all gangsters seem to have actually
carried them.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Donnie Brasco,'' Al Pacino's character, Lefty Two Guns,
instructs Johnny Depp that a real wise guy always carries his cash
in a roll, with a $100 bill on the outside for flash.
</P>
<P>
   But Sidney Zion, the Daily News columnist who knew mobsters like
Meyer Lansky and Longy Zwillman, told me that the big shots, the
bosses, often didn't carry any cash. ``Their bodyguards carried
it,'' Zion said. ``There'd always be somebody around to throw down
the Benjamins when the time came.''
</P>
<P>
   Zion was surprised to hear that money clips were in vogue again:
``They're back? Like cigars and martinis?''
</P>
<P>
   In this digital age, with the easy swipe of debit cards and
online payments as quick as a mouse click, money clips may soon be
rendered obsolete again. But for now at least, I relish the crisp
sensation of folding my bills and snapping them tenderly inside my
money clip.
</P>
<P>
   As Zehme said, ``You want something cold and metallic to keep
that lettuce chilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
