<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-TOWER-HNS &LR;      08-06 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-TOWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LANDMARK WITH GRIM PAST TO REOPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As an architecture student in the 1970s at the
University of Texas, Stanley Lars gazed up at the tall limestone
structure, often wishing he could get a closer look but rarely
thinking about the tragedies that prevented him from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Austin architect gets a first-hand look at that same
building every day as he oversees renovations that will allow
university officials to reopen the legendary tower next month after
a 24-year shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tower is kind of a mysterious thing, but opening it will
help people experience it and see how wonderful the view is,''
Stanley said Friday during a tour of the observation deck for
reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It connects you to the city in a unique way,'' he said. ``I
think it definitely will erase some of the stigma. Instead of the
mystery and foreboding, it'll be exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``stigma'' is the slaughter that occurred on the grounds
below the tower 33 years ago when Charles Whitman toted sandwiches,
toilet paper and a rifle up to the deck and started shooting at
random.
</P>
<P>
   Within 96 minutes, he killed 14 people and wounded 32 others. He
was stopped when officers stormed onto the deck, killing him in a
hail of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bullet-hole scars in the limestone walls are carefully
concealed.
</P>
<P>
   An arched, stainless steel lattice designed by Stanley is being
erected around the deck, a safeguard against would-be jumpers. The
tower was temporarily closed to visitors after the Whitman
shootings and permanently closed in 1975 after several suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at the urging of some students, the UT System Board
of Regents finally voted to reopen the tower after certain safety
renovations were completed.
</P>
<P>
   The observation deck, 231 feet high, provides an unobstructed,
awesome view of the surrounding campus, the city of Austin and the
picturesque Texas Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   While visitors Friday seemed captivated by the panoramic scene,
they also were compelled to look down on the peaceful-looking mall
where terror reigned on another hot August day 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The orange tower lights are turned on to celebrate a football
victory or some sports triumph, the building itself often serves as
a reminder of Whitman's horrific attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when I'm walking through that open area, I'll think
about it,'' said Erin Shubel, a 23-year-old research assistant who
graduated from the University of Texas last spring. ``I'll think
how people were just walking through there too when someone opened
fire on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surreal, I can't imagine it. It's insane,'' she said.
``People must have just had targets on their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she supports reopening the tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to have something like that not accessible,'' she
said. ``By isolating it, it makes it that `evil place,' when really
it was just an evil person.''
</P>
<P>
   The tower is scheduled to be open to the public on Sept. 16,
though there will be a ceremonial opening the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The renovations will cost about $600,000. University officials
hope to offset some of the costs by charging visitors $3 each.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who studied under UT sculptor Charles Moore in the
1970s, designed the lattice to fit into the architectural and
historical context of the tower and adjoining building. It is made
of stainless steel for strength and because it blends well with the
limestone walls.
</P>
<P>
   An elevator also is being installed. Visitors will have to pass
through a metal detector before getting on it, and there will be an
armed guard patrolling the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he's honored to help reopen the Texas landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole state of Texas knows about this tower,'' he said.
``When people come here, it's one of the things they want to see.
It should be accessible to people. That's why it exists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
