<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSTACHE-MODEL-ART-$A     08-06 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSTACHE-MODEL-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSTACHE CREATES BZZ AT MENSWEAR SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 8.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscibers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK DECARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The burning question at last month's menswear shows
was not about the masculine merits of clamdiggers or the demise of
the backpack in favor of an over-the-shoulder bag with a strap as
wide as a Miss Universe sash. The query on everyone's lips was,
``Who's the guy with the mustache?''
</P>
<P>
   The man causing the flurry of interest in an otherwise
uneventful three days of shows in New York for Spring 2000 was
Eugene Hutz, a model who also is a member of a Ukrainian punk rock
band called Gogol Bordello. Hutz, 25, appeared in only two fashion
shows _ for the designers Marc Jacobs and Nigel Curtiss _ but he
garnered the lion's share of notice.
</P>
<P>
   It's not every day you see Snidely Whiplash on a runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walked into casting, I said I have to have this guy in
my show,'' said Curtiss, an alumnus of Comme Des Garcons, who
showed his collection for the first time in New York on July 27.
``In his mustache, in his sideburns and in his eyes, he had such a
strong attitude,'' the designer recalled last week from his London
home. Hutz's mustache, he said, ``was so fresh and unexpected that
it captured everybody's attention.'' That, it did. No one else on
any runway was sporting anything close to the underbrush beneath
the model's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there was a little chin scruff here and there,
particularly in Jacobs' show, but no mustaches. Hutz's handlebar
managed to be what tattoos and body piercings no longer can be _
genuinely shocking.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this state of affairs exists purely on and around the
runway. Policemen, firemen, cowboys and the occasional macho
newspaperman like Phil Bronstein of San Francisco (Sharon Stone)
have never stopped wearing mustaches. But in fashion circles, the
look hasn't been popular in 20 years. As Curtiss said, ``You don't
see anyone at the right parties or the right places who has one.''
Even Mark Spitz, the Olympic star who wore his mustache as proudly
as his gold medals in the 1970s, was cleanshaven in a recent
television advertisement for a videogame. Although goatees and Van
Dykes have come and gone in the last five years _ and in many cases
come and stayed _ the mustache has shown little signs of a revival,
despite the enduring upper lips of mustachioed icons like Tom
Selleck and John Waters. In fact, it is one of the few vestiges of
the '70s that has not yet made a comeback, although some have
tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a fashion story a couple of years ago for Paper magazine
about Burt Reynolds, and the response was incredible,'' recalls
Stefan Campbell, a freelance fashion stylist, who also styled
Curtiss' show last month. The magazine story, which coincided with
the 1997 release of ``Boogie Nights'' and re-created Reynolds'
famous Cosmo centerfold, was about the return of machismo and
featured a rugged young model with a mustache. The article followed
a 1996 runway show by John Bartlett that was a hirsute ode to the
mustachioed he-men featured in After Dark magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But the look didn't take off, except as camp. Mustaches sprouted
on cross-dressing women known as drag kings, in a Beastie Boys
video spoofing '70s cop shows and most recently, in a print ad for
Altoids mints. ``It's slowly taking its time to get here,''
Campbell noted wryly.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutz could speed things up a bit. ``I felt Eugene would be a
bit of a trendsetter,'' said Karen Long, director of the men's
division of DNA Models in New York, who signed Hutz to her agency
three months ago. ``He had a face that I thought would be appealing
to men because he's not your typical pretty boy.'' Because of his
mustache, Hutz is not boyish-looking at all, which is one reason
that some observers say mustaches have not come back. ``Everyone
wants youth and young and baby faces and a cleanshaven face and a
big buff body, but a mustache says maturity,'' Campbell explained.
In a youth-obsessed culture, most people figure why look any older
than you have to?
</P>
<P>
   A column in the current issue of Time Out New York magazine
suggests that because ``pop culture has clearly turned against
sub-nasal carpeting,'' mustaches have become an act of revolution
and should be embraced by the truly alternative among us. But there
are better reasons to embrace them. Now that the funny but
terminally uncool jokemeister Weird Al Yankovic has shaved off his
mustache _ he appears in his latest video, a ``Star Wars'' spoof
called ``The Saga Begins,'' free of facial hair and dressed as a
Jedi knight _ it's safe to grow one. As Curtiss said last week,
``It's a completely new look again.'' And unlike a tattoo, when you
get tired of it a few months later, you can remove it.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutz himself has the best reason for growing a mustache. ``A
goatee makes my face look like a skateboard. It's too long,'' he
said. ``This evens it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
