<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brisk jet stream winds flowing near the boundary between chilly
air over eastern Canada and hot air over the southern states will
promote fast weather changes from the northern Plains to the New
England. The vigorous high-level winds will energize potent
thunderstorms which will move from the northern Mississippi Valley
on Saturday to the Northeast on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will be unrelenting from the southern Plains to the
interior Southeast. Plentiful sunshine will cover most areas,
although a few afternoon thunderstorms will develop, especially
near the Gulf Coast and over the hills of western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The hot, humid air will be drawn northern through the
Mississippi Valley by the circulation around low pressure moving
east from Minnesota. Converging winds near the low pressure zone
will lift the moist air, resulting in clouds and showers from the
eastern Dakotas to the western Great Lakes. Broken bands of strong
thunderstorms will develop in the heat of the day from Missouri to
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Northeast will have ample sun, seasonable
temperatures and comfortable humidity as weak high pressure moves
into New England. Clouds will increase from west to east Saturday
afternoon and into the night as the disturbance approaches from the
Midwest. Thundershowers will sweep from the Ohio Valley to the
interior Northeast overnight.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, clouds and showers will be common as
slow-moving low pressure swirls over the region. A few potent
thunderstorms will form over the interior in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SNOW RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Just as football referees confer when deciding the outcome of a
controversial play, The National Climate Extremes Committee met
this week to decide whether this past winter's snowfall of 1,140
inches at Mount Baker set a national record. Measuring snowfall
breeds controversy because snow compacts, melts or is blown away by
the wind. But proper procedures were followed _ measurements were
taken once a day on a ``snow board,'' a flat surface made of
material such as tile that limits melting. The committee ruled that
Mount Baker's snowfall was a national record. It also broke the
world mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
