<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV08-B     08-06 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV08-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKESIDE GURU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 08, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guru is a Hindi word for personal spiritual adviser or teacher.
It has come into common usage in English during the past 30 years
or so to mean any charismatic leader highly regarded by a group of
followers. I don't know much about gurus, but I know one when I see
one.
</P>
<P>
   One such is a long-time Boston money manager named Dean LeBaron.
LeBaron is 66, and no longer active as a fund manager. But the
trajectory of his career may have something to say about
semi-retirement in the epoch of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Harvard College and, in 1960, the Harvard
Business School, LeBaron rose quickly in Boston's staid money
management community to become director of research at F.S.
Moseley, then at Keystone Investment Management Corp. In 1969 he
left to found Batterymarch Financial Management Corp., at a time
when even a growth fund was something of an innovation.
</P>
<P>
   He was a man in the right place at the right time, and rapidly
became one of the prophets of quantitative investing. He favored
computers for the sifting of massive data sets, economic models for
systematic analysis, and, when judgment was required to help choose
out-of-favor stocks, esoteric techniques of detachment gleaned from
Zen buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, he was a pioneer in the creation of index funds
designed to mimic the behavior of the market as a whole, on the
theory, that no investor, however shrewd, was likely to outsmart
the market consistently over time. Then, dramatically, he abandoned
the strategy in favor of active management based on various
intriguing new results from finance theory. In later years he would
self-deprecatingly quote performance arbiter Rex Sinquefield's
dictum that ``There are three classes of people who don't think
markets work: the Cubans, the North Koreans, and active managers.''
</P>
<P>
   His was one of those names that everybody knew, like Hayne
Leland and Barr Rosenberg and Fischer Black, before the community
itself grew so large and various as to come to be known
collectively simply as ``quants'' and ``rocket scientists.'' By the
early '80s, Batterymarch was managing as much as $18 billion and
training a new generation of quantitative investors.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble arrived in the late 1980s, in the form of a couple of
employee breakaways and a series of bad bets. In 1994 LeBaron sold
Batterymarch to the Baltimore brokerage firm of Legg Mason Inc. for
$60 million, with another $60 million contingent on its performance
over three years.
</P>
<P>
   So now LeBaron spends his time going back and forth between the
Santa Fe Institute (where he is a trustee) and the annual World
Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, where he is a favored guest.
His latest project is a books on other gurus _ 30 or 40 little
profiles of fellow gurus, with little reading lists, Web addresses,
etc. _ the guru himself turned economic journalist.
</P>
<P>
   The volume begins with an e-mail exchange between LeBaron and
his friends and fellow gurus Robert Monks and Chrisopher Meyer
(head of the Center for Business Innovation for Ernst and Young.)
``At times we may seem glib and cavalier,'' writes LeBaron with his
coauthor, Romesh Vaitilingam. ``It is merely in our attempt to be
concise about things that defy precision.''
</P>
<P>
   The real locus of LeBaron's activities is his Web page,
www.deanlebaron.com. ``Welcome,'' he says, ``to this new, very
public, very global sandbox. I have grown up in the investment
world and witnessed continuous change in markets and technology,
but never with the rapidity as that occurring right now. We have
instantaneous access to people and resources. We have the tools.
Everything here is subject to change. The essence of the Web is
freshness and mental freshness is what we are trying to promote.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's there? Well, plenty of brief pensees on this and that
in the ``snippets notepad'' under ``Futurebytes.'' A daily video
commentary _ the guru as Walter Cronkite (except when his
3-year-old granddaughter fills in with some reflections on the New
Hampshire presidential primary). Some old speeches. An unpublished
book on his experiences in Russian markets called ``Climbing
Falling Walls.'' And a ``completely personal album of family
history pictures,`` which ``might amuse some of you and bemuse
others as a departure from my usual serious commentaries.''
</P>
<P>
   There are the remarkable family and friends. The beautiful
houses. (The one at the end of of Sagamore Road on Standish Shore
in South Duxbury, Mass. is ``right on the beach with a big front
lawn,'' he notes.) The Cessna Skymaster. And then there is ``Two
Lakes,'' a pair of web cameras transmitting pictures taken every
half hour from the front lawns of LeBaron houses on Lake Sunapee in
New Hampshire and the Wallensee in Switzerland. The lakes are
``similar in many respects, different in others,'' says LeBaron.
The Sunapee camera is out of service for the moment, having been
hit by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Like most personal Web ages, therefore, LeBaron's is part
bulletin board, part scrapbook, part storeroom for old items whose
copyright no longer matters. In fact, the really interesting thing
on offer on LeBaron's Web site is neither the guru book nor the Web
page but something called ``The Ultimate Book of Investment
Quotations.'' It is what used to be called a commonplace book, 300
pages of quotations about the business of international investing
that have attracted LeBaron's attention over the years.
Unfortunately it doesn't seem to be available in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, LeBaron notes that in the 1950s, he was the
world's greatest expert on the shares of makers of fiberglass
boats: Glaspar, Glasstron, American Molded Fiberglass, and so on.
The concept was great: high fixed costs and low variable costs. The
builder would pay $300,000 for a mold, $50 for the material he put
in it, and would stamp out as many boats as he liked. Rather like
the Internet stocks, LeBaron notes. ``And who remembers the
fiberglass boat stocks now, 40 years later?''
</P>
<P>
   An equally striking parallel is to the boats themselves. Like
the fiberglass boat business, the guru industry reliably produces a
few big winners a year, year after year. But just as heavy hulls
whose designs sold only a few copies still litter many a beach, the
World Wide Web now assures that there will be an awful lot of gurus
attentively tending roadside, mountainside, and lakeside stands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
