<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV08     08-06 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV08-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOT OF FUND POSITIONS? CHECK MID- AND SMALL-CAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 08, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I, aged 74 and 76 respectively, are in a dilemma
about rebalancing our portfolio, and about where to invest
additional funds. We find ourselves in a very fortunate position,
primarily because we began building mutual fund positions 20 years
ago and we have been buy-and-hold investors since. As a result, we
have significant, though unrealized, capital gains on most of our
holdings, although some are modest in size. Since we are not
dependent upon income from our investments, and since we now have
some additional funds to invest because of a home sale, we need
some advice. According to the ``experts,'' we have too many funds.
We hold eight Fidelity funds totaling $586,000, with more than
$200,000 each in Magellan and Contrafund, $82,000 in four
miscellaneous funds in other families, $33,000 in three TIAA/CREF
funds, and $30,000 in four Vanguard funds. We also have $150,000
available for investment. We have followed your advice in the
paper, and accordingly we have small amounts in Vanguard GNMA and
Vanguard Health Care, and are adding $250 a month to those, as well
as to some of the miscellaneous funds. We would prefer to invest a
large chunk of the house proceeds rather than let them languish in
a money market fund. Should we therefore raise our fund investments
to more substantial levels, or should we invest in other funds? We
are both mindful of the asset allocation principal and the
too-many-funds syndrome, so you can understand our puzzlement. What
do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   W.R., Barnard, Vt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Pooh on those ``experts.'' Sure, you have a lot of funds, but
you also are working toward a fairly nice diversification, aside
from the skew toward those large-cap blend funds that would
generate such big tax bills if you were to sell them. It seems to
me that there are only two disadvantages to holding a large number
of funds.
</P>
<P>
   One is that reviewing fund performance is more cumbersome than
if you limit yourself to a half dozen or so. But many people don't
find that chore onerous, and my guess, based on the fact that you
put this portfolio together to begin with, is that you are one of
them. The other disadvantage is that portfolios made up of many
funds often tend to get bunched up in one category, such as the
nine large-cap funds that probably make up about 75 percent of the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to look carefully at the tax consequences
of selling some of the large-cap holdings where gains have been
modest; if you find that you can sell one or two without horrible
tax consequences, you make the sales and increase your positions in
the mid- and small-cap sectors, and perhaps even increasing the
Vanguard Health Care position.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the large-cap dominance, it seems to me that the
major problem of this portfolio is its very small participation on
the fixed-income side. Since you don't supply exact amounts of your
investments in Vanguard GNMA and the TIAA/CREF Bond Plus accounts,
I'm going to guess, and my guess is that the level is a good deal
less than 5 percent of the total portfolio; in any event it
couldn't be more than 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you don't need an income stream from this portfolio,
my suggestion, made for the sake of safety and proper asset
allocation, is to devote all of that $150,000 from the real estate
side to the fixed-income side. I'd even add one more fund, the
Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond fund. My idea would be
ultimately to divide the $150,000 between that fund and Vanguard
GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   But I am also aware that the bond market is pretty choppy right
now, so I would adopt a dollar cost averaging program, putting most
of the money in Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund and moving
$3,000 a month to each of the two target funds; if you achieve
average 5 percent returns from the money market fund, this would
spread the investment period out over the course of about 27 1/2
months.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in order to keep the dominance of the large-cap funds
from growing, I suggest you take all the distributions from these
funds in cash, reinvesting the proceeds in the small- and mid-cap
and health care sector holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last summer we sold our house and cleared $200,000, of which
we put $150,000 in Fidelity Spartan GNMA. We invested in the GNMA
fund to provide a monthly income of about $750. Since then,
although we are still getting close to the original monthly check,
the principal amount has fallen to $145,000. How safe are GNMA
funds, and what's in the future?
</P>
<P>
   R.K., North Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With Ginnie Mae funds, you have to take a long-term view.
Although the federal government guarantees the principal and
interest payments on the mortgages that underlie GNMA securities,
they remain subject to changes in interest rates, with the
principal falling as interest rates rise (or as people worry that
they might) and with principal rising as interest rates fall (or
when lower rates are anticipated). But the important thing is that
over the long haul _ that's to say over a period of a decade or so
_ the better GNMA funds tend to go nowhere, with all the gains and
losses crossing one another out. In the interim, what you get is a
yield in the neighborhood of 1 1/2 percentage points better than
you would get from a money market fund or a CD. Your fund, now
merged into Fidelity GNMA, is a solid offering in the category, and
my advice is to ride out the bumps. The fund will do precisely what
you expected it to _ deliver a solid monthly check that you can
rely on in good markets and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Projecting what interest rates will do in the future is a good
way to get poor quickly, and it's not a practice I follow.
Certainly, there's a lot of talk about higher interest rates right
now, and I wouldn't be surprised if you saw further short-term
price erosion. But you also have to remember that we are in one of
the longest economic expansions in our modern history, and
eventually it's going to end. And when the economic worm turns, the
normal approach of government officials is to cut interest rates to
spur the economy _ and that's when you'll see your principal
account begin to gain.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with the fund; it's a solid offering and it should meet
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
