<HEADLINE>
AUTO BUSINESS IN THE U.S. BOOMS ON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. _ A true multinational corporation with 104
factories in 34 countries, the Honda Motor Co. constantly assesses
economies and vehicle demand around the world _ and the company's
leaders think they know where the strongest market will be over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``North America is the only place an investor would want to put
their money,'' said Hiroyuki Yoshino, Honda's chief executive and
president.
</P>
<P>
   Few industries play as large or as cyclical a role in the
American economy as automobile manufacturing. Last week, at the
University of Michigan's annual automotive conference here in
northwestern Michigan, Yoshino and a parade of other top executives
predicted that auto sales and the American economy would stay
strong through the rest of this year and into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1990s, the auto industry never managed more than two
consecutive years of high, steady sales. But automobile sales have
been about 15 million every year since 1993. And just as industry
executives were worrying earlier this year that American garages
might finally be full, business became even better.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in July, reported by all the big auto makers last Tuesday,
showed the industry on course for its best year ever, roughly 17
million vehicles. That would exceed the record of 16.03 million,
set in 1986, when people rushed to take out car loans before the
end of tax deductions for the interest.
</P>
<P>
   Rising household incomes this year, along with fairly low
interest rates and gasoline prices, have fed demand. Yet prices of
new cars, after rebates and other discounts, have stayed flat,
helping hold down overall inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce competition has led companies to pass on to consumers
much of the recent savings from simpler designs. Gary Valade, an
executive vice president of DaimlerChrysler, predicted here that
discounting would remain high through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year national labor contracts of General Motors, Ford
Motor and DaimlerChrysler all expire on Sept. 14. A generation ago,
the expiration of labor contracts in a time of such prosperity
would have prompted the United Automobile Workers union to demand
higher wages and benefits, giving rise to worries at the White
House and on Wall Street about an inflationary spiral.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the UAW is more worried about job security. The
union's top priority is to stop auto makers from asking nonunion
suppliers to build large chunks of vehicles, instead of just
shipping parts to be bolted together at unionized assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the union holds the line, auto makers' costs would not
rise. They might not fall quickly either, but in any case the
effect is unlikely to be inflationary.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to some extent the economy is doing well now because
the auto industry is prospering, rather than the other way around.
For all the attention that the growth of high-technology companies
has received, GM still produces 1.5 percent of the nation's output,
and Ford adds about 1 percent, the two largest roles played by any
companies in the American economy, according to the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Even with GM's spinoff in May of Delphi Automotive Systems, an
auto parts company larger than the Intel Corp., GM remains eight
times the size of Microsoft. When a strike hurt GM in June and July
of last year, knocked 0.6 percent off the growth rate of the entire
American economy in both the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   So brisk is demand now that auto factories across North America
are straining to meet it. Toyota's assembly plant in Cambridge,
Ontario, has increased the speed of its assembly line five times in
the last seven months and slowed it only once, in a constant effort
to meet demand for its Corolla and Solara cars, said Ray Tanguay,
Toyota's vice president for Canadian engineering, production
controls and information systems.
</P>
<P>
   To manage the extra speed, Toyota has had to figure out how to
pare further the mere 90 seconds that a Corolla, for example,
spends passing through each work area on the assembly line as
different parts are attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to say to the team leaders, O.K., now we have to take
two seconds out,'' Tanguay said. To help match production with
demand, Toyota hopes to start filling custom orders for specific
paint and options combinations on the Solara within five days.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody here was even talking about the possibility of a
recession. But the next downturn could be particularly severe if
Americans decide that their garages are full of vehicles that don't
need replacing because they are still running well after years of
use.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of American cars fell during previous economic
expansions as older cars were traded in, but cars have become so
dependable that their average age is climbing now by almost two
months each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worried about that for a long time,'' said Thomas Davis,
a GM group vice president, ``because they've been getting more
reliable for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
