<P>
   ATLANTA SHOOTINGS
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTINGS-BARTON _ ATLANTA _ By the time Mark Barton wrote his
chillingly elegant confession, the demons that had haunted him
since childhood had finally consumed him. As a shy teenager, he
broke into a drug store and made his own hallucinogens. In
business, he undermined his own success, sabotaging a colleague's
work and referring to his first wife by the nickname ``Stupid.'' In
his final months, he killed his daughter's kitten, then helped her
search for it. Why Barton became Georgia's worst mass murderer may
never be known. But clues emerge from several critical points in
his life: his teenage years in South Carolina, his business success
and downfall in Texas, his response to his first wife's murder, and
his final months of rage and madness. ``He had no compassion,'' his
former secretary said, ``no compassion for anything or anybody -
except himself.'' (Judd,/Schneider/ Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/SHOOTINGS-GREENLEY _ATLANTA _Interview with Anne Greenley, who
was accosted by Mark Barton at a mall. She was the last person on
earth he spoke to. He was the last person on earth she wanted to
meet. (Gilpin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA SHOOTINGS
</P>
<P>
   ALA-SHOOT _ COLUMBIANA, Ala. _ A man accused of shooting three
people to death at two companies where he had worked told one of
his victims, ``I'm tired of your rumors about me,'' a prosecutor
said today. At a court hearing today, District Attorney Robert
Owens Jr. said Alan Eugene Miller made the comment when he shot
Terry Jarvis to death at Post Airgas Co. on Thursday. (Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ABA-HUBBELL _ Former Deputy U.S. Attorney General, Clinton
confidant and federal convict Webster Hubbell discusses his ``life
as a target'' to the ABA convention. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   w/ABA-NOTES _ Highlights of the day's events at American Bar
Association Annual Meeting. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
12.
</P>
<P>
   METEOR-SHOWER _ Perseid Meteor Shower is peaking. Guide to
viewing. (Kennedy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT _ GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The current drought is the worst
ever recorded for agriculture in four Northeastern states, and it
threatens to cripple businesses and communities that depend on
devastated farm economies. ``Throughout much of this country, we
have seen the worst drought since the Dust Bowl days,'' President
Clinton said today before leaving the White House for a weekend
trip to Arkansas and Missouri. The drought is the worst ever for
farmers in Maryland, Delaware, New Jersey and Rhode Island. The
Senate approved $7.4 billion in emergency farm aid on Wednesday.
The House will consider an emergency aid package after the recess.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DOGS _ MEXICO CITY _ This city has long ago gone to the
dogs _ and their excrement, say health officials in Mexico City.
Mexico City has legions of lean, mean and scruffy street dogs that
deposit their waste about this metropolis, causing many a health
hazard. Pampered pets, too, contribute to Mexico City's foul air.
Pet owners routinely fail to pick up dog poop, which dries and
flies into the air, mixing in with all the other contaminants that
make this city's air one of the world's worst. At least one
burrough of the city is pledging a crackdown. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move on Wed., Aug. 4, in both International and
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
