A8499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      08-06 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CAMP TO `FOCUS ON ISSUES' DESPITE GOP MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ A spokesman for Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Friday dismissed moves by Gov. George Pataki to unify the
Republican Party to counter the first lady's potential Senate
campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wrapped up her latest ``listening tour'' in the state as
Pataki said he would urge Rep. Rick Lazio to abandon plans to
challenge New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the Republican
nomination for Senate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans do or don't do is up to them,'' said
Harold Wolfson, the spokesman for Clinton's exploratory campaign.
``Mrs. Clinton is going to continue focusing on issues and
listening to New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who has had strained relations with the mayor in the
past, said Giuliani had ``earned the right'' to be the Republican
Party's candidate for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win, the Republican Party must be unified behind
one strong candidate,'' Pataki said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are intent on winning the seat held by Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring, after losing
the state's other Senate seat last year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show Clinton and Giuliani in a statistical dead
heat, while Clinton would swamp Lazio, a Pataki ally from Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has in the past threatened to run as a Conservative Party
candidate if he fails to win the GOP nomination, which could
benefit Clinton by pulling Republican votes from Giuliani, were he
to win the party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, finishing a three-day swing through western New York,
vowed to continue her exploration of a Senate race for months to
come, and she voiced fond childhood memories of a late
step-grandfather who was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time during her exploratory campaign, she talked
about Max Rosenberg, a Russian-born Jew who married Clinton's
divorced maternal grandmother, Della, in 1933, seven years after
her split from Clinton's maternal grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's tabloid newspapers splashed the revelation in
editions published Friday. Jews are an active Democratic political
constituency in New York, representing about 12 percent of the vote
in the 1998 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very fond childhood memories of my grandfather,''
Clinton recalled. ``He was not my biological grandfather; he was, I
guess you'd say, my step-grandfather. But I used to delight in
going to a place called Kiddieland with him, which was one of our
favorite outings together as a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Methodist who grew up in Oak Park, Ill., said in the
wake of publication of her family ties to a Jew _ first reported in
the Jewish newspaper The Forward _ ``It has been wonderful to
rethink all of those good memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In her would-be Senate campaign, Clinton continued to avoid
partisan clashes with state Republicans or specifics on a variety
of touchy issues in the state, including the impact of the North
American Free Trade Agreement, the launch of independent public
charter schools and the revival of college programs in state
prisons that were suspended by Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding questions from reporters at the conclusion of her
fourth campaign-style tour across New York, Clinton declined to
criticize Republican direct-mail efforts that use her candidacy as
a goad for contributions. She skirted an invitation by a reporter
to go after Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm not in a campaign yet,'' Clinton declared at
Rochester's School of the Arts, where she discussed the benefits of
Rochester's partnership between city schools and businesses to
prepare students for work. Clinton added: ``There'll be plenty of
time to talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said what will be important in ``this Senate race is who
has the best ideas and who can best implement ideas that would be
effective to help improve the lives of most New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady insisted that she has not reached any decision on
a Senate candidacy, saying that she would continue crisscrossing
the state for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more time I spend doing this, the more enthusiastic and
encouraged I am,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   She is scheduled to return to New York on Monday and Tuesday to
plunge for the first time into inner-city neighborhoods, including
the southeast Queens congressional district once represented by
retired Rep. Floyd Flake, D-N.Y., a prominent leader in the
African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday:
</P>
<P>
   _ When asked about the North American Free Trade Agreement, the
5-year-old trade pact between Canada, Mexico and the United States,
Clinton said she was generally in ``favor of what is called free
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know more about what would be effective ways to
promote trade and promote exports but not to the disadvantage of
our farmers or our manufacturers or our small business people or
our workers who depend upon those jobs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the deal hurts American workers by sending
jobs to Mexico, where labor costs are substantially lower, and to
Canada, where the strong American dollar has more purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton said she was ``going to wait and watch very
carefully'' how the law is implemented that allows local
jurisdictions in New York to establish independent public schools.
``I'm very hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked about in-prison education programs in some state
correctional institutions, Clinton said the resumption of college
courses for inmates ``is something we ought to consider trying to
support.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
