<SLUG> BC-WINE-IMMUNE-SYSTEM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CONCLUDES RED WINE DOES NOT HURT IMMUNE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill.)   (bl)  
 By KAREN VOYLES   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIEFLAND, Fla. _ Susan Percival already has people lining up to
take the place of the mice in her experiments. The experiments
involving red wine. The ones that require drinking as much as two
to three glasses of wine a day.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a chance to sip the ``fruit of the vine,'' Percival's
experiments have yielded an interesting finding: Red wine, in
moderation, does not suppress immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe the number of people who want to `help'
me,'' Percival said with a laugh. Percival, a food science and
human nutrition researcher at the University of Florida, started
off by getting her laboratory mice established as moderate
drinkers, consuming the equivalent of two to three glasses of an
alcoholic beverage a day.
</P>
<P>
   What Percival found out was that red wine did not suppress the
immune systems in laboratory mice, making it different from many
other alcoholic beverages that can lower immunity.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, study after study has shown that red
wine helps prevent coronary heart disease and some cancers, but
Percival could find no studies on how it affected disease-fighting
functions.
</P>
<P>
   That's why she spent eight weeks studying her four groups of
mice: teetotalers who drank only water, ethanol drinkers, muscadine
wine drinkers and cabernet sauvignon wine drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   After the mice had become moderate drinkers, they were given a
chemical that made them slightly ill for a couple of days with
cold-like symptoms to challenge their immune systems. Those that
drank the ethanol suffered a weakened immune system, while the mice
that drank wine had normal immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is that there is something in the wine that
prevents suppression of the immune system,'' Percival said. ``But
remember, while there were no harmful effects on the immune system,
too much wine can have other harmful effects, like on the liver.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next for Percival is a closer look at how the liver
processed muscadine wine compared with how it processed the
cabernet sauvignon while detoxifying the alcohol. Her theory is
that because muscadine grapes have a greater concentration of
antioxidants, it may offer humans more protection.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research on wine includes a University of Illinois study
that found the skin of grapes works to block carcinogens, a Swiss
study that found that drinking wine with a high-fat meal may
minimize artery damage, and French research that suggests it also
may cut the risk of Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Voyles writes for the The Gainesville Sun (Gainesville,
Fla.), which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times News
Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
