</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD HOPING ITS EXCURSION WILL SUPPLANT SUBURBAN AS NATIONAL CAR OF
TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the Suburban-buster.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Ford wants Texans and other fans of the venerable
General Motors full-size sport-utility vehicle to think about the
new 2000 Ford Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   At 7.2 inches longer, 3.3 inches wider and 4.3 to 5.8 inches
taller than the Chevrolet/GMC Suburban, the Excursion is the first
sport-utility vehicle that fits into the Suburban's class, a market
segment that General Motors has owned for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Ford Expedition, introduced two years ago, has offered
some competition to the Suburban, but its size pitted it more
against the Chevy Tahoe/GMC Yukon than the Suburban. Those two
vehicles are just shorter versions of the Suburban, and the only
major difference between the Tahoe/Yukon and the Expedition has
been the availability of a third seat in the Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   But the Excursion is designed as a true Suburban competitor,
appealing to the ``bigger-is-better'' Texas culture that has long
made the Suburban the darling of the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, the Excursion is bigger than the Suburban.
It's a real hoss. Not only are its dimensions larger than the
Suburban, but it's also 2,000 pounds or more heavier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's short enough _ at 226.7 inches or just under 19 feet
_ to fit in a standard residential garage, Ford officials say.
That's the first question most people asked me during my week-long
test drive of the Excursion, right before they asked me about the
gas mileage. Ford says the diesel engine has the best fuel economy
at 15 miles per gallon in the city and 18 on the highway. Expect
about 10 mpg city/13 highway for the optional V-10 gasoline engine,
or 12 city/15 highway for the base V-8.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't actually try to put the Excursion in my garage _
there's too much junk in there. But I parallel-parked it a few
times in downtown Fort Worth, and it did fit in a standard parking
space _ just barely.
</P>
<P>
   It's low enough for downtown parking garages, too. Never did the
roof of the Excursion hit one of those bars that hang down on
chains at parking garage entrances to let you know your vehicle is
too tall.
</P>
<P>
   All during my week's drive, the Excursion drew the crowds,
something I expected here in Texas, where General Motors sells 40
percent of the Suburbans it produces.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban owners were curious but a bit skeptical. After all,
they are a loyal lot. One longtime Suburban owner who went for a
drive with me in the Excursion found a lot to like about this
behemoth, except for the ride. ``It's a lot rougher than my
Suburban,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Excursion also drew hordes of truck fans who wanted to see
this vehicle that is challenging the almost-official car of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At Taco Bell, a group of teen-age boys fell in love with the
Excursion, looking over every inch, opening the doors, sitting in
the front, middle and rear seats, and checking out the cargo
compartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coooooool!!!'' was their collective assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Ford marketing folks aren't naive enough to believe that the
Excursion will knock the Suburban out of first place in the
full-size SUV class. The company plans to build just 60,000 of them
a year. GM sells three times as many Suburbans.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford believes that some sales will come from current or
former Suburban owners, the biggest market for Excursions will be
owners of other Ford sport-utilities who want something bigger and
heavier, especially for towing large trailers. With the largest
engines available in the class _ a 6.8-liter gasoline V-10 and a
7.3-liter diesel V-8 _ the Excursion can pull trailers of up to
10,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   That's not enough to beat the current 2500-size Suburban, which
also can tow up to 10,000 pounds, but it is 2,000 pounds more than
the Expedition can tow. In Texas, horse trailers and campers tend
to be very heavy, and the Excursion should be able to handle them
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the third seat in place, the Excursion has 48 cubic
feet of cargo area. The capacity increases to a 100.7 cubic feet
when the seat is removed. The seat folds up and unhooks from the
floor easily, and is on rollers so it can be readily removed from
the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the third seat and folding the second seat forward
creates a 146.4 cubic-foot cargo area that has a flat floor capable
of holding a standard sheet of plywood (4 by 8 feet) with the back
doors closed.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility to the rear is better than the Suburban with the
double rear cargo doors, thanks to the Excursion's flip-up rear
glass hatch combined with lower Dutch doors. The liftgate can be
raised for simple loading and unloading of groceries. The Dutch
doors, below the liftgate, can be opened for full access to the
cargo area. The doors, an arrangement similar to that of the Chevy
Astro van, are light because they are made of composite plastic,
the only plastic body panels on the Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Getting into and out of the rear seating area is easier in the
Excursion than the Suburban, primarily because the rear doors are
5.5 inches longer than the Suburban's.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine is a 5.4-liter V-8 rated at 255 horsepower and
350 foot-pounds of torque. The V-10 engine raises that to 310
horsepower and 425 foot-pounds of torque, while the turbocharged
Power Stroke diesel ffers 235 horsepower and an unbelievable 500
foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time, shift-on-the-fly four-wheel drive is standard with
the V-10 engine, but optional with the V-8 gas or diesel engines.
All Excursions come with a heavy-duty four-speed automatic
transmission with overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel disc brakes, with a four-wheel antilock system, is
standard on all Excursions. All of them also come with dual front
and rear air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin of the Excursion is quiet, which is a real
accomplishment for what is just a big, enclosed super duty Ford
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the trim level selected, the Excursion's interior
ranges from functional to quite luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   The base two-wheel-drive XLT model, listing for $34,135
(including $675 transportation), comes with cloth interior and a
whole load of standard equipment, including power windows and door
locks and the 5.4-liter V-8. That price is $3,840 more than a
comparably-equipped Expedition, $242 more than the Suburban 1500,
and $1,206 less than the heavier Suburban 2500.
</P>
<P>
   The uplevel model, called the Limited, carries a base price of
$37,775 (two-wheel drive), which is $2,142 more than the comparable
Suburban 1500 LT, but just $694 more than the Suburban 2500 LT.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel-drive Excursions range from $37,450 to $40,880 (base
price). That's $377 less than Suburban for the entry-level model,
or $1,303 higher than Suburban for the fancier Limited version.
</P>
<P>
   Showroom-equipped Excursions _ with the most popular options
tacked on _ range from $36,580 for a two-wheel-drive XLT to $41,915
for a four-wheel-drive Limited.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Excursions is a pleasure. Behind the wheel, they
don't feel as big as they look, and they are rather nimble in turns
for such large trucks _ just about any size driver could handle one
easily. There is ample power even with the base V-8 gasoline
engine, and if fuel-economy is important, the diesel offers the
best numbers while still providing plenty of power.
</P>
<P>
   For safety's sake, the Excursion offers the first system for a
sport-utility vehicle to protect against running over smaller cars
in a rear-end collision. The so-called Blocker Beam, a 50-pound
steel bar running across the vehicle under the front bumper, is
designed to prevent the Excursion from sliding over a car in front.
At the rear, the standard under-bumper trailer hitch is designed to
prevent a car from sliding under the Excursion if it hits the truck
from the rear.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel tank, mounted behind the rear axle, holds 44 gallons,
so even with poor gas mileage, the Excursion has good range.
</P>
<P>
   The official on-sale date is Sept. 30, but the first Excursions
began rolling off Ford assembly lines in late July. As soon as they
begin arriving at dealerships, they will be available for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect discounts anytime soon. Ford officials predict that
the trucks will bring full retail sticker price at least until
dealers are well-stocked, probably late next spring or early
summer.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
