</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-GLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXCURSION: AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At A Glance: 2000 Ford Excursion sport-utility
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Full-size, four-door, five- to eight-passenger,
V-8, V-10 or V-8 diesel-powered, rear- or four-wheel-drive
sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Ford's all-new Excursion is the first sport-utility
designed to compete against the Chevrolet/GMC Suburban. It's 7.2
inches longer and 2,000 pounds or more heavier than the Suburban.
Great engine choices, good roadhandling, quiet and comfortable
interiors, great towing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Much rougher ride than the competition's.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Chevrolet/GMC Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 15 miles per gallon city, 18 highway (diesel);
12 city/15 highway (5.4 liter V-8), 10 city/13 highway (6.8-liter
V-10)
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE RANGE: $33,460 (two-wheel drive, XLT model) to
$40,205 (four-wheel-drive Limited model), plus $675 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWROOM-EQUIPPED PRICE RANGE: $36,580 to $41,915, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
