<SLUG> BC-DASCHLE-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DASCHLE DENIES TRYING TO PROD THE NEWS MEDIA TO INVESTIGATE BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democratic Leader Thomas A. Daschle says he
wasn't trying to prod the news media to investigate Texas Gov.
George W. Bush when he complained that reporters don't press Bush
about whether he has used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement elaborating on comments he made to reporters
Wednesday, Daschle said he was trying to express his view that the
news media have a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's not so acceptable is for the media to arbitrarily hold
one public figure to one standard of disclosure and another public
figure to a far higher or lower standard,'' Daschle's statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Daschle chided reporters for ``respecting far more
(Bush's) privacy and his lack of willingness to discuss his past
than you might have been with others.'' He complained that when
Bush says he has made unspecificed mistakes, ``it appears the media
seem to accept that as a fact and then (are) ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Daschle said, the news media relentlessly
question Hillary Rodham Clinton about her private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time she gets out there, somebody's asking
her private questions,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is campaigning in New York state where she's
expected to announce her candidacy for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wednesday meeting, a reporter asked Daschle whether it
was fair to ask political candidates whether they have used
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle responded: ``Sure, it's a legitimate question. The
second question is, if that person denies it, how many press people
_ investigators _ do you put on his tail to find out whether he is
telling the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Bush has declined to say whether he has used
cocaine, an illegal drug. Typically, Bush puts an end to such
questions by saying he has ``learned from my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement headlined ``Daschle Clarifies Comments'' about
Bush, the senator said it was ``absolutely appropriate and
acceptable for Gov. Bush to refuse to answer questions about his
past personal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said it has become increasingly hard for the media and
for public figures to know where to draw the line between people's
public and personal lives. ``The standards are not clear, and they
frequently are not applied consistently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, campaigning Friday in Rochester, N.Y., was asked
whether there's a double standard on media coverage of Bush's
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the standard is or should be,'' she said.
``Whatever it is, it should be applied, I would expect, evenly.''
</P>
<P>
   And she also lamented a lack of privacy in her own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it serves our nation or our political process
well for people to have every shred of their privacy taken away
from them,'' she said. ``I don't think that's good and I'm speaking
as someone who's been through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
