<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FRIEDAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTIMATE PORTRAIT': RECALLING WHEN BETTY FRIEDAN WAS OPENING
MINDS  
 `MODELS UNCOVERED': THE SEAMIER SIDE OF THE MODELING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of `Intimate Portrait' review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something depressing about having Joan Lunden, in all
her blond morning-television perkiness, introduce the life story of
Betty Friedan, the original, serious ``don't-call-us-girls''-era
feminist.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Lifetime's ``Intimate Portrait'' series, not known
for its depth or stunning insights. Normally the series is not
known for featuring particularly important women either; next week,
for instance, Lifetime viewers will have a chance to see ``Intimate
Portrait: Kelly Preston.'' Ms. Friedan is the subject Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Friedan, says Ms. Lunden, is a ``great American who made it
possible for me and all women to participate in the mainstream of
life.'' Ms. Friedan, now in her late 70s, concludes ``I've used my
life very well'' and says she has learned to ``use even the pain,
the setbacks, the mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   She began life as Betty Naomi Goldstein, a jeweler's daughter in
Peoria, Ill., who was, in her own words, ``often miserable at
home'' and couldn't wait to leave there every day and get to
school. She skipped two grades, went off to Smith College in 1938
and to graduate school at the University of California at Berkeley
four years later. Afterward she worked as a reporter, met and
married Carl Friedan and found herself dismissed from her job in
1952 because she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   That experience alone did not turn her into a feminist. But
later a Smith class reunion did, one at which all those well-bred,
well-educated Seven Sisters alumnae, it seemed, could talk about
nothing but baby formula and diapers. Ms. Friedan's horror at that
turned into a questionnaire, which turned into a magazine article
that nobody wanted to publish, which turned into a 1963 book ``The
Feminine Mystique.'' And nothing for American women _ or men _ has
been quite the same since.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that ``Intimate Portrait: Betty Friedan'' can't
convey that impact more forcefully. The documentary turns into
little more than a list, illustrated with old film clips, of
accomplishments and causes: the founding of the National
Organization for Women, the women's march in 1970, the striking
down of anti-abortion laws in 1973, the losing battle to ratify the
Equal Rights Amendment and the publication of three more books.
Early on, she also got a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The most personal revelations are that Ms. Friedan never liked
her looks (``I wasn't at all pretty'') and that she's an
incorrigible flirt.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INTIMATE PORTRAIT
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan'
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime, Sunday night at 11
</P>
<P>
   Caroline King, writer and producer; Lee Grant, director; Joseph
Feury, executive producer. Narrated by Joan Lunden. A production of
Feury-Grant Entertainment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `MODELS UNCOVERED'
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Channel, Saturday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Things could have been worse for Betty Friedan. She could have
been born dazzlingly beautiful and been forced to endure the
agonies of being a supermodel.
</P>
<P>
   In this documentary, originally done for Channel 4 in London,
Christy Turlington says beauty is ``a gift and a curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crawford acknowledges that the modeling business is ``a
little shady.'' Lauren Hutton declares, ``You're a moron to let a
15-year-old go into the business.'' And Anna Wintour, editor in
chief of Vogue, asked whether she would want her daughter to become
a model, says, ``I would do everything in my power to stop her.''
</P>
<P>
   The dangers seem to be drugs, too much freedom and lechers in
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Management comes off as openly sleazy in this film. It doesn't
help that John Casablancas, of Elite Model Management, is
interviewed while holding a glass of white wine in the back of a
limousine and F. David Mogull, who heads something called Model
Search America, in a hot tub. The only person who comes off worse
is the model Naomi Campbell; ``out of control'' is one of the nicer
descriptions of her.
</P>
<P>
   The show exudes its own sleaze at times (ogling as it condemns
ogling) but is often fascinating in spite of itself. One of its
finest scenes is of a mod, mod 1960s young blond woman solemnly
demonstrating how to get into a sports car in a miniskirt.
Remember?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
