<HEADLINE>
NO GOLDBRICKING FOR GORDON AT BRICKYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CAR-NASCAR-IRWIN) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Jeff Gordon said he was surprised. Why, no one
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Gordon owns Indy. On Thursday, he won the pole for
Saturday's Brickyard 400 with a record speed of 179.612 mph,
bettering Ernie Irvan's time of 179.394 mph run last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gordon's third pole in six races here. He has also
qualified third twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to give a lot of credit to the guys on this race team
because I didn't feel like it was my best lap as a driver,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into one really hard and the front end slid up on me a
little bit. After that, I was a little more prepared for the other
three corners,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Gordon's Chevy were Mark Martin (Ford), 178.941 mph, and
surprising David Green (Chevy), 178.902 mph. Dale Jarrett (Ford),
the current Winston Cup points leader, was fourth at 178.859 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ended up missing most of the afternoon practice when he
and Rusty Wallace collided in the pit area, damaging both cars.
</P>
<P>
   Neither driver had to go to a backup, though.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had this to say about Gordon: ``He's a better driver than
most of us if not all of us and he drives a better car than most of
us if not all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a guy like Mark, that means a lot,'' Gordon said.
``I personally think he's the best out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who the best driver is,'' Gordon said. ``It's
hard to make that evaluation unless you drive their race car. I
think it's whoever has the best combination, a driver who can feed
information back to the team so they can work with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of great drivers feel what the car's doing,'' Gordon
said, ``but they can't relay it back to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gordon's performance didn't surprise anyone, Green's did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we needed this would probably be an understatement,''
Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been headed in the right direction, but we always seem
to hit a roadblock. We've had to regroup as a team, and I'm proud
of my guys for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla, is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
