<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-IRWIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN SHOULD BURN RUBBER, NOT STRETCH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CAR-NASCAR-GORDON) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It is like a rubber band being stretched to the
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Kenny Irwin and his car owner, Robert
Yates, is obviously strained. Irwin's status has been in doubt
almost from the beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make this work, we're trying to stay focused on
making it work,'' Yates said while getting ready for Saturday's
Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still,'' he added, ``at some point, we all know you have to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now, this car is not producing at a level that is
acceptable to Yates.
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that Irwin's Ford is, potentially, the most
attractive ride available for next year. Few think Irwin will be
back, but how seriously Yates has been looking for a replacement is
open to question.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Terry Labonte was linked to Yates. Both denied they
had even talked. Labonte had a contract with Rick Hendrick through
2000, and Chevy and Hendrick moved quickly to extend it.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Indy, the names most mentioned as possible replacements
for Irwin are John Andretti and Ricky Rudd. It is almost certain
Andretti and Rudd have had preliminary conversations with Yates,
although no one will say as much.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti said he and his car owner, Richard Petty, have talked
and that he plans on returning to Petty Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some discussions about next year and I feel like
I'll be back unless they kick me out,'' Andretti, 36, said. ``I've
never left a team on the upswing, and I feel like things are
starting to come together here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go someplace and have to start all over again.
I'm getting too old for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while not confirming that he and Yates had met, Andretti
said, ``I'll talk to anybody. I talk to a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Yates, Robert's son, commented on Andretti's situation,
saying, ``I think he is comfortable where he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who is 42, could be a more viable candidate. He is losing
his sponsor and looking for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm trying to put something together to keep my
team,'' Rudd said. ``We had a sponsor ready to go, but we turned it
down because it wasn't enough money. I'm not going to do something
unless we have the money to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd has set a mid-September deadline to work out a deal. If he
doesn't come up with one, he probably will shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with some owners, and there's a possibility I
could end up driving for somebody else, but that's not my first
choice,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Yates, Rudd said he hadn't talked to Robert Yates. ``But
he does have a son named Doug,'' Rudd added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Irwin, who had his 30th birthday on Thursday, is just
trying to get through it all.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had talked to Robert Yates during tests at Indy.
``Nothing was discussed about what we were going to change, if I
was gonna change or if he wanted to make a change,'' Irwin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that this is what he wanted to do and that he was
gonna keep progressing,'' Irwin said. ``Other than that, I have no
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
