<HEADLINE>
CROSS-STITCHING CAN BENEFIT FROM A LITTLE COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN  
 DRIVING GAME ZOOMS TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Please note that (AT) in tagline represents the symbol.) 
(yn) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For cross-stitchers, patterns are plentiful, but they're not
always what one might want. The collie in the pattern book may not
look exactly like the one at home. The little Hummel-like girl may
not look like the daughter who lives with the collie, either.
Perhaps you'd like to cross-stitch their likeness instead.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so difficult. With a computer, scanner or digital
camera, and a software program from M&AMP;R Technologies, photos can be
converted into patterns for cross-stitch.
</P>
<P>
   PCStitch (Windows; about $50-$60) has been around for 10 years,
long enough to be refined into Version 5, the one recently released
by the Ohio-based company. ``We designed PCStitch to be as simple
and easy-to-use as possible,'' said Mark Miller, M&AMP;R president.
``With each new version, we added more features, but PCStitch is
still one of the easiest craft programs on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can scan pictures into the computer to use in e-mail or
greeting cards, you'll have no problem bringing images into
PCStitch. The program also has a built-in drawing program for users
who want to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the computer, the design can be handled just like a
picture: It can be enlarged, cropped and colors altered. Text can
also be added.
</P>
<P>
   Size is not a problem, either. The program can produce a
cross-stitch pattern up to 999-by-999 stitches. How fine the detail
of the finished product is depends on the number of colors
specified for the final output. For a simple picture, a few colors
may do. For a detailed landscape or portrait, a higher number of
colors may be needed. Up to a maximum of 150 floss colors can be
used.
</P>
<P>
   The program supports images stored in .BMP, .PCX, .JPG, .WMF, or
Kodak Photo CD formats.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 500 floss colors corresponding to floss colors
from Anchor, DMC and J&AMP;P Coats.
</P>
<P>
   The new version gives users the ability to print a design on one
page, complex designs can also be enlarged and printed on several
pages, then glued together, for easier use.
</P>
<P>
   A demo version of the product can downloaded from the company's
Web site (www.pcstitch.com). It can be purchased from the site, or
stores handling software. Hobby and craft stores may also carry it.
</P>
<P>
   For information: 1-800-800-8517.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVING GAME ZOOMS TO THE TOP
</P>
<P>
   Driver, a driving game from GT Interactive Software Corp. for
the Sony Playstation, has sold 1 million copies in the first month
it has been on the shelves, a company spokesman said last week.
It's also at or near the top of titles for rent.
</P>
<P>
   A computer version of the game is scheduled for release in
September.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
