<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOCONA-BOOTFACTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TEXAS TOWN TO LOSE BIGGEST INDUSTRY, JUSTIN BOOT FACTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOCONA, Texas _ ``I was `Given the Boot' at Nocona Boot'' read
little white lapel stickers that brought brief smiles yesterday to
the faces of some of the 160 boot company employees who were told
their jobs are gone.
</P>
<P>
   After hanging on through the booms and busts of a fickle cowboy
boot market, through two layoffs of 40 employees each, and years of
downsizing through attrition, the surviving boot makers of Nocona
are smiling through their tears. But their eyes are moister than
their grins are large.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Industries' decision to close the Nocona Boot Co. and
shift its production to Justin plants in El Paso and Missouri was a
double whammy for 40 of the workers who are employed couples here _
a triple whammy if they factor in a likely drop in home values,
said Liz Buck, 57, a plant supervisor who is herself married to a
co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six are married in my department alone,'' said Buck, who has
30 years under her belt at Nocona. ``It's been family. Now we're
devastated, just devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   She was handed a shoe box stuffed with money. It was to buy
flowers and food for an employee whose husband, a fellow worker,
died of cancer yesterday, the day after she lost her job at the
boot plant.
</P>
<P>
   Each department in the plant is closing as soon at it finishes
work on its current orders, and the whole plant is expected to be
shut down within six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The town is in mourning as if for a universally loved figure who
was always there for the community. Now the residents are not quite
certain how to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Gene Fitzgerald immediately withdrew a draft city budget,
knowing that the town's biggest taxpayer (13.4 percent of the tax
base) won't be easily replaced. The plant's tax appraisal is $8
million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not alone,'' Fitzgerald said. ``The county, the
schools and the hospital district are also going to be hurt
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nocona Boot Co., formed in 1925 after Enid Justin's three
brothers moved the H.J. Justin &AMP; Sons boot company to Fort Worth
for land and tax breaks, is the biggest employer and a landmark in
this North Texas town of 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Its closing is equivalent to Fort Worth's losing 26,000 jobs _
the work forces of Lockheed Martin, Tandy Corp., Bell Helicopter
and Burlington Northern Santa Fe combined.
</P>
<P>
   Nocona's next largest employer is Nocona Athletic Goods, one of
the few remaining domestic makers of baseball gloves, which is
thriving with 100 employees. The third is Nocona Belt Co., which
recently changed hands and employs 85 people. Neither is likely to
absorb many of the laid-off boot makers, said Ricky D. Howard,
president of Nocona Banking Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is not going to dry up and blow away,'' said Howard,
who predicted a gradual recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But the banker doesn't discount the psychological impact of the
boot plant's closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing, apart from the loss of jobs, is that it was
kind of our identity,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing for sure, as Howard and countless others said in
practically identical words, ``Miss Enid is rolling in her grave
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Enid'' Justin was a strong-willed 6-footer who deeply
resented her brothers' closing the Nocona plant their father had
built. She learned the boot making business at his side after being
suspended from seventh grade for dancing at a party and never
returning to school. Though married, she borrowed $5,000 in her own
name, rented machinery and hired back skilled employees. She cooked
meals for oilfield workers and sold coal and washing machines to
help carry the firm through its early years.
</P>
<P>
   In those hardscrabble times, Justin drove a Model T into oil
boom towns, taking orders from roughnecks for boots tough enough to
last. ``I out-sold all my competitors and I wouldn't stop until the
factory had enough orders,'' she said in her 1985 autobiography,
``Miss Enid: The Texas Lady Bootmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees recall a larger-than-life woman who could swear like a
sailor on the shop floor and uncannily collect debts from the
hardest accounts. Yet she was generous and inspired extreme loyalty
from employees. There were parties for their children and Christmas
bonuses. To generations of Nocona residents, she was the ``Cracker
Jack lady'' for the boxed treats she gave out each Halloween from
her large pink house, which matched her trademark pink Cadillacs.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't abide cohabiting by members of the opposite sex
before marriage, recalled Clara Beth ``Yankee'' Speights, 68, a
retired boot maker married to a current employee. ``They had to get
married or they didn't have a job,'' Speights said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Enid Justin agreed to merge her firm with Justin Boots,
then changed her mind, said John Justin, her nephew, who ran the
Fort Worth firm at the time. ``She backed out and there was quite a
rhubarb, but we finally won in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a wheelchair, she continued to visit the Nocona plant
after her retirement in 1982 at age 88. She died in 1990, aged 96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Enid would be totally shocked if she learned this boot
company was closing,'' said Weldon Parr, 61, a 35-year employee who
minds a stockroom of exotic skins ranging from anteater to
stingray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad she's not around to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
