<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORSHIP AT ST. PAUL'S DEFIES DOUBTS ABOUT CHURCH OF ENGLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Religion is not dead, not even dying, in England. At
least it did not appear that way to me on a recent Sunday at St.
Paul's Cathedral in the heart of London.
</P>
<P>
   When the large congregation from around the world began singing
``Angel voices ever singing 'round the throne of light,'' I felt as
if I were being lifted high into the lofty dome of the storied
church.
</P>
<P>
   The magnificence of the surroundings and the swelling sounds of
the pipe organ first installed in 1695 may have contributed to my
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   I was among the first arrivals for the 11 a.m. service. At first
I was a little chagrined that I was an hour early. But that meant
that I would be seated up front almost directly under the richly
decorated dome 366 feet above me. The church is the masterpiece of
Sir Christopher Wren, England's most celebrated architect.
</P>
<P>
   Above me were frescoes showing Adam and Eve being expelled from
paradise and winged angels celebrating the birth of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   I had already been introduced to Wren's artistry. During
nighttime walks by the many ancient buildings of Oxford University,
I often passed the Sheldonian Theatre, another of Wren's
masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Wren was commissioned to rebuild St. Paul's after it was
destroyed by the Great Fire of London in 1666. Directly in front of
where I was seated, Wren's epitaph was inscribed in Latin on the
marble floor. It states: ``Beneath lies buried the founder of this
church and city, Christopher Wren, who lived more than 90 years not
for himself but for the public good. Reader, if you seek his
monument, look around you.''
</P>
<P>
   My arrival at St. Paul's also meant I had time to visit with
some people around me. A woman from Venezuela, Gladys Pinto, kept
looking back over the crowd searching for her husband, Ovideo.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he arrived and she broke into a bright smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a Catholic church but could not find
one,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   They were worshipping in a cathedral of the Church of England,
the mother church of the worldwide Anglican Communion, which
includes the Episcopal Church in the United States. The Church of
England was born in the 1500s, when it separated from the Roman
Catholic Church under Henry VIII.
</P>
<P>
   The Pintos were not disappointed. The pageantry of the service
was enough to satisfy most Roman Catholics. Amid the grandeur of
the cathedral and its music, the clergy, dressed in crimson and
white, were led to the front of the cathedral by the bearer of a
huge golden crucifix.
</P>
<P>
   The Vicars Chorale sang ``''gloria in excelsis'''' and the
Nicene Creed in Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to me was Pat Christie, a Londoner who said she
attends St. Paul's each Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a privilege to worship here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Christian church founded by early Roman Catholic missionaries
has been on the site of St. Paul's since A.D. 604. But despite
England's impressive religious heritage, some clergy are worried
about the future of Christianity in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Right Rev. Richard Harries, bishop of the Diocese of Oxford,
said in a recent address that the church is stagnating. Although
religious practice is increasing in Africa and many other parts of
the world, the reverse is true in England, the bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are faced with a missionary situation in Western Europe as
challenging as any that has faced the Christian church in its
history,'' he said. ``We will need to discover wholly new ways of
trying to connect with people physically, culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   He is encouraging leaders of the Church of England to adopt a
new strategy for evangelism that will be considered in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the crisis may be real, I have every faith that
England, which has faced many crises in its long history, will meet
the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And I believe that the stupendous worship experiences will
continue at St. Paul's Cathedral each Sunday as they've done for
the past 1,396 years.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
