<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVI-DEATH-NYT &LR;      08-06 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMO LEVI'S PLUNGE: A CASE AGAINST SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By DIEGO GAMBETTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime after 10 a.m. on Saturday, April 11, 1987, on the
fourth floor of a late-19th-century building in Turin, the
concierge rang the doorbell of Primo Levi's apartment. Levi, who
was born in that apartment 67 years earlier, opened the door and
collected his mail, just as he did every day. He smiled, thanked
her and closed the door. The concierge descended the spiral
staircase, occupied in the middle by a caged elevator. She had
barely reached her cubicle on the ground floor, she later told the
police, when she heard Levi's body hit the bottom of the stairs by
the elevator. It was 10:20. The autopsy established that he had
died instantaneously of a ``crushed skull.'' No signs of violence
unrelated to the fall were found on his body. At noon I heard the
news on the radio in Rome. There was already mention of suicide, a
conclusion later reached by the police inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shock it caused to his admirers, Levi's manner of
death was explained by most as the ``inescapable'' end of the life
of an Auschwitz survivor. ``Primo Levi died at Auschwitz 40 years
later,'' said Elie Wiesel. And Cynthia Ozick wrote that Levi, like
other writers of distinction before him, suggested ``by a
self-willed death that hell in fact did not end when the chimneys
closed down, but was simply freshening for a second run.''
</P>
<P>
   This explanation of Levi's death also led some people to
interpret it as a delayed victory for Nazism. That such an end
should befall Levi makes the thought doubly disturbing. Philip Roth
describes Levi's ``masterpiece on Auschwitz,'' ``If This Is a
Man,'' as ``his profoundly civilized and spirited response to those
who did all they could to sever his every sustained connection and
tear him and his kind out of history.'' That a figure of Levi's
stature emerged from the fumes of arguably the most savage act of
hatred to scar this century has been a powerful source of hope and
strength. How could he lose that strength and jump to his death?
</P>
<P>
   Italians, it seems, have felt too close to Levi to raise that
unsettling question. In the United States, by contrast, it readily
found a bitter answer. ``The efficacy of all his words had somehow
been canceled by his death _ that his hope, or faith, was no longer
usable by the rest of us,'' an anonymous journalist wrote in The
New Yorker. Leon Wieseltier, in the New Republic, wrote: ``He spoke
for the bet that there is no blow from which the soul may not
recover. When he smashed his body, he smashed his bet.''
</P>
<P>
   But do we have any evidence that Levi's death was a response to
Auschwitz? We know with certainty only that in the period leading
up to his death, Levi was going through a severe episode of
depression. Levi himself denied to friends any link between his
depression and Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstantial evidence that Auschwitz was haunting Levi at the
very end was revealed on the 10th anniversary of his death. At a
commemorative gathering in Rome, Elio Toaff, the chief rabbi of
Rome, disclosed that Levi telephoned him ``10 minutes before'' he
died. He did not say he was about to kill himself, Toaff
recollects, but said: ``I can't go on with this life. My mother is
ill with cancer, and every time I look at her face I remember the
faces of those men stretched on the benches at Auschwitz.''
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing question, however, is not why Levi committed
suicide but whether he committed it at all. Indeed, the possibility
of an accident has never been seriously examined, even though there
is no conclusive proof that Levi killed himself. As his friend, the
Nobel laureate Rita Levi Montalcini, said a few days after the
event, ``Did anyone see him jump over that banister? Did anyone
find a piece of paper announcing his intention to end his life?
Suicide is a far too quick conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite Rabbi Toaff's statement, I find it odd that Levi,
who was not religious, should approach a rabbi to whom, Rabbi Toaff
said, he had never spoken before. It is also puzzling that Rabbi
Toaff would answer the phone on a Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath, on
which observant Jews are not supposed to use any technical
equipment. Rabbi Toaff is out of town for the month of August,
however, and could not be reached to clarify this point.
</P>
<P>
   If Levi wanted to kill himself, it seems that he, a chemical
engineer by profession, would have known better ways than jumping
into a narrow stairwell. Indeed, the stairwell is so narrow that
Levi would have had to aim his fall just right to be successful.
The maximum distance between the stairs and the elevator cage is 5
feet 7 inches; the minimum distance is just over 3 feet 4 inches.
Rather than killing himself, Levi could have hurt himself bouncing
between the elevator cage and the railings of the lower floors. Had
he wished to jump, he could have chosen the street or the
courtyard, both easily accessible. Levi picked not just a hazardous
but a theatrical option, one that exposed his relatives to a
gruesome sight, in sharp contrast to his notoriously restrained
style.
</P>
<P>
   If he died accidentally, something must have prompted him to
open the door again, walk to the banister and lean forward. The
timing suggests that he might have been looking for someone _ his
wife, for instance, who was out shopping and returned minutes after
the event. Or he might have been looking for the concierge,
expecting to find her still in the staircase. The very old nurse
who was looking after Levi's ailing mother, according to his
cousin, Dr. Giorgio Luzzati, said that Levi had gone out to ask the
concierge about a letter he was expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Levi was not tall (5 feet 5 inches). But neither was the
banister (3 feet 2 inches), which reached approximately to his
navel. If he had been looking for someone below, he would naturally
have approached the banister at the 90-degree corner where the
landing meets the stairs and one has a better view of the lower
floors. The banister's height drops by six inches at every step and
offers decreasing protection. So perhaps he positioned himself to
look down by holding, arms wide, the horizontal banister with one
hand and the sloping one with the other. In such a position one's
balance is precarious because it depends on the grip of one's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Levi had had a ``routine'' prostate operation just 20 days
before his fall, and he was still recovering. On the Thursday
before his death he called Luzzati and told him he felt tired and
was having dizzy spells. They agreed to schedule an appointment the
following week. David Mendel, a British doctor who corresponded
with Levi shortly before he died, also suggested that the
antidepressants Levi was taking could have caused dizziness. If he
became dizzy while looking down the stairwell, the weight of the
upper half of his body might have been sufficient to drag him into
the void.
</P>
<P>
   I believe an accidental death is more consistent with what we
know about Primo Levi's last moments than a suicide. It would
explain why he died in such an unlikely way, and why he left no
note. At the very least, it would point to an unpremeditated
suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, were people so prone to believing it was planned
suicide? Devastating past events can set a cognitive trap: if one
survives Auschwitz, everything that happens subsequently tends to
be interpreted in the light of that experience. The Auschwitz hell
may kill survivors decades later, but it may also become a
magnet-explanation. The confidence with which Levi's death was
attributed to suicide perhaps springs more from this understandable
bias than from conclusive evidence.
</P>
<P>
   We shall never know whether Primo Levi committed an
unpremeditated suicide or died accidentally. Doubt is our only
option. One thing is certain, though. Levi's last moments cannot be
construed as an act of delayed resignation before the inhumanity of
Nazism. He never yielded. At most he snapped. On that tragic
Saturday, only his body was smashed.
</P>
<P>
   (Diego Gambetta is a Fellow of All Souls College, Oxford. This
article is based on another that first appeared in the summer issue
of The Boston Review.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
