<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-CULTURE-     08-06 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-CULTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWANESE SIREN BRINGS SEXUAL SUGGESTIVENESS TO CHINA'S MUSIC
SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China is crazy about Ah-Mei. And she rocked Beijing on
Friday night, sending a stadium full of fans into a tizzy of
screeching adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Ah-Mei can sing all right, and her dancing does dazzle, oh yeah.
But it is Ah-Mei's sexy charm and suggestive stage work that seem
to have suddenly catapulted her to the No. 1 slot in rock-and-roll
popularity in China.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: Ah-Mei is from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   It is surely a measure of how increasingly irrelevant China's
political campaigns have become to ordinary people when a rock star
from Taiwan can draw more than 45,000 screaming fans to Beijing's
biggest stadium, at the height of a China-Taiwan political crisis,
and no one gives it a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   To the young people bopping to the rhythms and singing along,
loudly, Ah-Mei's attraction easily overpowered any consideration of
the current battle over who should have sovereignty over Taiwan,
which has badly distracted China's leaders in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the coolest,'' said Li Chen, 28, who would not take her
eyes off the stage, even as she spoke about Ah-Mei, whose real name
is Zhang Hui-mei. ``I don't care where she's from.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan culture has so infused mainland China over the last 15
years that no one here seems to even think about it. The two most
popular television shows in China this year are both from Taiwan,
and Taiwan-style teahouses have become popular hangouts in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China's newspapers may rant each day about the crisis they say
has been provoked by Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui, but the same
newspapers have displayed enormous photographs of Ah-Mei,
accompanied by adoring articles that describe her spunky and
lovable personality.
</P>
<P>
   Ah-Mei, 27, is becoming the Madonna of China. Her voice is fine,
her dancing better, but it is her animated persona and sexual
suggestiveness that really give a kick to her performances, and to
her raging popularity.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of her concert Friday night, Ah-Mei dragged a
long-haired young man up to stage center and lashed his wrists
together with a whip, making him sit still. Cradling a microphone
in her hands, she gyrated slowly up and down before him, as she
sang a slow love song about needing and controlling her man.
</P>
<P>
   Wild applause.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were nearby, posting more than 2,000 armed
police officers on the ground level of the stadium, to make sure
things did not get entirely out of hand. The stadium scoreboard
flashed a reminder, ``Observe discipline, maintain order.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone was watching. There was too much to see on
stage.
</P>
<P>
   In her third costume of the night, a skintight black halter top
and flowing black bell-bottoms, Ah-Mei looked as alluring as her
silky voice sounded when she launched into ``Are You Ready?'' the
number that got the crowd really rocking.
</P>
<P>
   A chant echoed through the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah-MEI! Ah-MEI!''
</P>
<P>
   She followed with a wild series of hoots, something akin to a
moose's mating call. Wild cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's enthusiasm for Ah-Mei, it seems fair to say, has been
overwhelming. Early this week, ticket scalpers were already getting
$250 a ticket, roughly five times the average urban monthly wage
and nearly 10 times the original price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to borrow from my mother,'' said Lei Xiao, 25, who came
with two friends. ``She thinks it's too expensive, but she likes
Ah-Mei, too.''
</P>
<P>
   China's media have given Ah-Mei a welcome to remember this week,
with extensive coverage each day. Friday's Beijing Youth Daily
wrote that it had discovered the secret to Ah-Mei's magic: her
father is a tribal chief in one of Taiwan's minorities of
indigenous mountain people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl we know as Ah-Mei is actually a princess,'' the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Another newspaper, reporting on everything about Ah-Mei from her
blood type (O) to her brothers and sisters (three brothers and five
sisters, two of whom are also singers) added her favorite pastime:
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Ah-Mei is not the first Taiwan pop star to come to China. Though
virtually everything from Taiwan was banned for decades after the
Nationalist government retreated to Taiwan 50 years ago after its
defeat by Communist forces, a gradual loosening of restrictions on
Chinese society that began in 1979 allowed in a few singers who
were deemed acceptable. Teresa Tung and her sickly sweet love songs
were highly popular in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet China has never before seen anything quite like Ah-Mei.
</P>
<P>
   A taste of her distinctive persona lies in the name of her tour,
which will go to Shanghai and Guangzhou next week: ``I Am Me: Mei
Power 99'' _ a play on her name, with a synonym that means
``charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah-Mei did not mention China's dispute with Taiwan, or any other
kind of politics, on stage Friday night. As close as she got was a
public thank-you to the Ministry of Culture for helping her appear.
The crowd booed.
</P>
<P>
   Then she thanked the Beijing Municipal government. The crowd
booed louder.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the music. ``Give Me a Feeling,'' her signature song,
got the crowd going full-blast, singing so loud it almost drowned
her out.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier in the week, Ah-Mei charmed the
local news media, appearing in a skimpy tank top, tan jeans with
red dragons embroidered on the thigh, and monstrously large,
marshmallow-white platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't always control my feelings,'' said Ah-Mei, appearing
pert and vulnerable at the same time. ``Everyone knows I love being
on stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
