<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-NYT &LR;      08-06 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARRED BY U.S. EMBASSY BOMBING, KENYANS STRUGGLE TO RECOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Until Aug. 7, 1998, one year ago Saturday,
Douglas Sidialo was a car salesman who drove around Nairobi for his
job. He tells a dark little joke about why that line of work is
closed off to him now: ``If I drove cars,'' he said, ``I would
knock people over.''
</P>
<P>
   He was blinded completely by glass and debris that exploded
through his windshield that day when terrorists bombed the U.S.
Embassy here. More than 200 people were killed and 5,000 wounded
here and in a simultaneous attack on the U.S. Embassy in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   His story is one of the more inspirational. He started a group
of survivors _ called, with a vein of irony, Visual Seventh August
_ to provide counseling and job training and to watch over how aid
money was spent. He wears a smile and sunglasses, both oversized,
and works hard to set an example for other victims without his
resilience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't reverse the blast,'' Sidialo, 29, said. ``I have to
accept what happened and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still has no job. The other day he went to the local Red
Cross, along with perhaps 100 other victims of the blast, to pick
up free food _ a few bags of corn meal and cooking oil _ to help
him survive.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb may have been aimed at Americans, as many people here
bitterly remind each other. But there is no question that Kenyans
have suffered the most and, a year later, are still coming to terms
with such devastation. It has been hard even for the optimistic
ones, like Sidialo, and simply grim for others.
</P>
<P>
   And so the nation's recovery from the bomb blast has come with
its own set of victories and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kenyans, split by ethnic, religious and class differences,
say the blast gave them a greater sense of unity, just as they
pulled together a year ago hauling the wounded from the rubble or
donating blood en masse. A government fund to compensate victims
apparently did not fall prey to the nation's legendary corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Some outsiders who have helped Kenya recover from the blast _
the United States has donated $42.3 million _ say they have noticed
subtle differences in Kenyan society, some out of bomb-related
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, mental health was seen as a service only
provided to people who were blatantly psychotic,'' said Dr. Lorin
Minless, a Boston psychiatrist who is a consultant for counseling
services for some 2,000 bomb survivors and their families. ``The
idea of getting help outside of the family didn't exist. The bomb
blast helped sensitize people.''
</P>
<P>
   But on some level the unity was short-lived. People have not
even agreed how to commemorate the bombing's anniversary, marked in
a weekend of rallies, concerts and other events: there are four
separate memorial services on Saturday, each claiming to be the
official one.
</P>
<P>
   And the money handed out by the government that was supposed to
make life easier for the victims has backfired in some cases, the
compensation squandered or stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Auma's husband was a shoe salesman killed in the blast.
As she took the body to western Kenya for burial, she said, her
husband's family decided not to recognize the marriage and emptied
their house of everything _ furniture, dishes, even the stove.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly $9,200 the government paid for her husband's
death, his family took $6,500. Now she is nearly broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent everything,'' Ms. Auma, 25, she said as she too
collected the free Red Cross food to feed their two children, ages
6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   There is also still much anger in Kenya over the blast. Some of
it remains directed at the United States, criticized in the early
days for seeming to care more about the 12 Americans killed than
the more than 200 Kenyans. Now, with unemployment sky-high and per
capita income dropping, many people say the United States should do
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Americans gave to the victims was not enough,'' said
Julius Mashalia Isalambo, 37, a grocer in downtown Nairobi. ``It's
like we are fighting their war.''
</P>
<P>
   Isalambo is not a victim of the blast and, interestingly, most
of the victims themselves say they do not blame the United States
(even though some 2,500 of them have joined in huge class-action
lawsuits against the U.S. government).
</P>
<P>
   Francis Gitu Maina, 33, clenched his fists on a recent evening
when he was asked if he was angry at anyone over the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much,'' he said. But he said he blamed ``the ones who came
to bomb,'' suspected to be Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile, who
has denied any role in the bombing, and his suspected associates,
eight of whom have been arrested. ``If they did not bomb, I would
not be in this trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   His trouble is worse than most: Maina was on the No. 126 bus,
stalled in traffic in front of the embassy, when the explosion went
off. He spent four days in a coma, then four months in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his right eye and cannot see well in his left. He can
barely walk because his right leg was broken so badly. When his
wife saw he could not provide anymore, he said, she left him with
their two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the king of ...'' he stared to say, then stopped. ``I'm
the husband. And now I got that trouble. That is why she went.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his life is now divided between the doctor and sitting
alone in his little room with walls and roof made of tin in the
town of Kiserian, about an hour to the southwest of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   A former clothes hawker, he has no clear vision of the future,
except that he would like to buy a little plot of land, build a few
apartments and start selling clothes again. But he does not have
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very bad,'' he said. ``When I think about my
life before, I don't feel good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
