<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOARING JULY JOB GROWTH HELPS TO BOOST WAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unemployment in July held firm at 4.3 percent, but an increase
of 310,000 jobs _ the second-biggest monthly gain this year _ put
more pressure on wages of US workers.
</P>
<P>
   The larger-than-expected job gains, exceeding the average
208,000 new jobs created each month during the first half of this
year, bumped wages up by 3.8 percent compared with wage levels in
July 1998, the US Department of Labor said in its monthly report on
employment. That was the biggest one-month jump in wages since
January.
</P>
<P>
   The news made it virtually certain that Federal Reserve Board
chairman Alan Greenspan will raise interest rates later this month
to limit the threat of inflation. Greenspan and the Federal Open
Market Committee, which sets interest rates, will convene on Aug.
24.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is ``afraid if he doesn't do something about it, it's
going to explode in a burst of wage inflation,'' said William
Cheney, chief economist for John Hancock Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, which boosted interest rates by a quarter percent in
July, to 5 percent, will likely raise rates another quarter point
at the next meeting, economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan fears that rising wages will force manufacturers to
increase prices, setting off a new round of inflation. By raising
interest rates and slowing economic growth, Greenspan hopes to ease
pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the market, fearing a slowdown in the economy, reacted
negatively. The Dow Jones industrial average ended the day down
79.79 points, after being down more than 100 points earlier in the
afternoon. The Dow closed at 10,714.03, down less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year US Treasury bond had its biggest jump in
yields since mid-May. The yield rose from 6.06 to 6.16 percent
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets were unhappy about a 6-cent rise in the
average hourly wages of US workers, to $13.29, from June to July _
the equivalent of a 6 percent annual increase.
</P>
<P>
   The spike in wages was the largest recorded in a single month
since January, when wages rose 4 percent over the prior year.
Despite fears of wage inflation, however, the Bureau of Labor
Statistics data show that wage gains were actually stronger in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the July increase was the latest in a steady drumbeat of
indicators in recent days that point to looming wage inflation,
including a slowdown in productivity growth and a 1.1 percent spike
in salaries and benefits in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Higher wages have not yet shown to be fueling consumer prices,
which are rising at a moderate 2 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Perna, chief economist for Fleet Financial Group Inc.,
said these data ``virtually guarantee'' strength in July personal
spending figures due out soon, continuing to fuel an economic
expansion that has gone on for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer incomes are going to be strong again. Purchasing
power's going to be strong. If you're the Fed and you're looking at
this, you say everything is coming up roses _ maybe too many
roses,'' Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   Even manufacturers, who were hurt last year by a drop in
exports, added 31,000 jobs in July, a trend that contradicts
reports by purchasing manufacturers that showed signs of a slowdown
at the nation's factories. July was only the second month in the
past year in which factory jobs were added.
</P>
<P>
   The service sector, a huge and steady source of jobs during the
expansion, added another 110,000 employees in July, followed by
restaurants, stores, and other retail establishments, which added
91,000, the Labor Department's survey of non-farm businesses
showed.
</P>
<P>
   There were also big gains in demand for workers at temporary
help agencies, which posted their strongest increase in payrolls _
31,000 new temporary workers _ in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sign of any slowdown at this point,'' said William
Ferson, &UR;  &LR; economist in the Boston office of the department's Bureau
of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's job gain of 310,000 was far beyond analysts'
expectations. Analysts had forecast that just over 200,000 jobs
would be added in July, a significantly slower pace than was
recorded in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the miracle of the American job machine,'' Hancock's
Cheney said. ``It's something which we all expected was going to
slow down probably two years ago, and it just keeps on going and
going and going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
