A8548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIEQUES-NAVY-HNS &LR;      08-06 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-NAVY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP PUERTO RICO OFFICIAL CHARGES NAVY WITH `ENVIRONMENTAL RACISM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The attorney general of Puerto Rico charged Friday
that the Navy's use of the island of Vieques for gunnery practice
amounts to ``environmental racism.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the Navy is blasting the island, Jose Fuentes
Agostini told reporters, ``is that we are Puerto Ricans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vieques, a island that is part of Puerto Rico, is home to 9,300
civilians who live next to a 22,000-acre military preserve used by
the Navy and Marines to practice bombing, artillery and ground
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   The military has been shooting at the island for 58 years, and
the Puerto Rican government wants it stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Agostini told a four-member Pentagon panel appointed at
the request of President Clinton to resolve the dispute that ``the
Navy's continued use and abuse of the fragile ecosystem of Vieques
... is a glaring example of institutional environmental racism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No other group has been required to live so close to such
hazardous conditions,'' he said. ``No other group would have had to
put up with this treatment for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Navy's argument that it must use Vieques because
there is no alternative site, Agostini said ``there is no
alternative precisely because no other group of Americans could be
forced to tolerate such abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a report by the Puerto Rican government, Agostini told
the panel that the citizens of Vieques have endured ``significant
physical and mental health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and Marine Corps want to resume training on the
22-mile-long island that was halted in April after a bombing mishap
in which a pilot mistakenly dropped two 500-pound bombs on an
observation post, killing a Puerto Rican civilian employee and
injuring four others.
</P>
<P>
   The accident ignited a political firestorm across Puerto Rico,
prompting the leaders of the island's 3.8 million U.S. citizens to
demand an end to the bombing and the withdrawal of the Navy from
the island.
</P>
<P>
   Agostini said that if the Pentagon panel doesn't recommend
ending the bombing, he will seek a court injunction, citing alleged
Navy violations of environmental laws. He also warned that Puerto
Ricans may start protesting in large numbers at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they may take this into their own hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials argue that the gunnery range must remain open.
Navy Secretary Richard Danzig said that ``from a national security
standpoint this is an important and not a replaceable site.'' The
service examined 18 other sites for comparable training and
concluded that training must continue at the range on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The panel might make a recommendation to Clinton in the next few
weeks about the fate of the island.
</P>
<P>
   The White House decision has potential political repercussions
because First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is exploring a U.S.
Senate race in New York, home to over one million Puerto Rican
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Agostini said that Mrs. Clinton will have to carefully consider
the Vieques issue as she mounts her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue would be of political interest to her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
