<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-GENERATIONS-950     08-06 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-GENERATIONS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA'S 2ND GENERATION OF CORPORATE ELITE CONFRONT SCORN AND DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ To many South Koreans, Chey Jae-won is just
a spoiled rich kid, the kind who plays with empires of corporations
the way others might play with empires of Lego.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary people see members of the new generation of the
corporate elite here as simply spoiled spendthrifts, squandering
their cash on expensive cars and extravagant evenings. That image
does little to ease the transition now as Chey and the scions of
other corporate dynasties are taking over from their fathers in a
major generational transition of Korean industry.
</P>
<P>
   Chey, a dapper engineer with sleek hair and a pen with gold trim
in his pocket, is, like most of the new corporate leaders, devoted
to a tougher, more market-driven model of management. And sometimes
the first casualties of this approach have been Chey's old buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is that it was like a family before,'' said
Chey, the son of the founder of the SK Group, one of South Korea's
biggest conglomerates, and now one of its new bosses. ``I got to
know their families, and they got to know mine. We drink together
and work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to break that tie,'' added Chey, 36. ``It's the most
difficult thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The second generation is moving into power partly because of the
Asian economic crisis, which created demands for new ways of
business management, and the new leaders are already beginning to
turn the economy in new directions. Saddled with the nasty task of
making reform work, they are trying to remold the empires that
their fathers built from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the second generation, Chey and other sons and
daughters of Korea's business leaders are mostly American-educated
and business-minded, with visions in their heads of balance sheets
rather than paternal companies.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of the baton has not been swift, for many of Korea's
giant conglomerates have been run since the beginning by their
founders, who formed these corporations mostly just before the
Korean War in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the elders it is still a struggle to let go of the
reins. At Hyundai Group, the largest of the conglomerates, which
are known as chaebol, 83-year-old founder Chung Ju-yung still
wields influence, though he has paved the way for his son and
grandson. And an ailing Kim Woo-choong at Daewoo Group promised
recently to yield control after the group nearly collapsed when
creditors threatened to pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the second generation _ and in some cases, the third _ is
often said to be the best hope for change in Korea, but the jury is
still out on how they are doing. Economic growth is returning and
dissipating some of the pressure for change at the chaebol, so
there is a good deal of skepticism about how much they will
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This second generation, they don't have the experience and the
know-how to design systems, so it will take time,'' said Jang
Song-hyon, who runs S.H. Jang &AMP; Associates, Inc., an independent
consulting firm. ``They inherited very large businesses without
having the past experience of going through very difficult times.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are indications that some of the scions may be earning
their stripes. For starters, they are moving beyond the
instinct-driven, seat-of-the-pants decision-making used by their
fathers and the cycle of lock-step promotion and lifetime
employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the dinner table, we challenged him, `It shouldn't be this
way!''' said Chey, describing discussions with his father before he
died last August. ``He sees the big picture. He sometimes didn't
see the small changes.''
</P>
<P>
   With a master's degree in materials science from Stanford
University, and an MBA from Harvard, Chey helps shape the group's
strategy and he can chat with any engineer about the nitty gritty
of the company's chemicals, telecommunications and finance
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He and his older brother are in the middle of a battle with
foreign shareholders over management control, and he expects to be
as fierce as his opponents. But he is also tough on his own
employees in a way that would win praise in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the company had 35,000 employees, and all
Chey's friends told him he would ostracized if he cut employees.
Now, after encouraging employees to strike out on their own by
giving them batches of equipment to start their own companies, Chey
has reduced the work force to 21,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet with lots of the second generation and they know where
to go but they struggle so much,'' said Chey. ``They say: `This is
what my father or grandfather did and I have to chop it up and sell
it _ I don't want to do it!'''
</P>
<P>
   But in South Korea such moves only intensify the envy that some
people feel. Of course, the founders themselves, who grabbed the
limelight as South Korea's economy bloomed over the decades, were
also the target of much criticism, but they earned respect for the
companies they cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, members of the younger generation are often scorned
because they have not fashioned success on their own. Some people
fear that they are more likely to continue the mentality of
expansion that their fathers were famous for, when what Korean
companies need now is a dose of healthy slash-and-burn
restructuring. Moreover, unlike their fathers, they have known
little economic hardship, save for the brief collapse of the
economy after the financial crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're trying to change because they've seen what
it's going to be like'' if they don't, said Park Sang-yong,
professor of finance at Yonsei University in Seoul. ``But it would
have been better if they had suffered more. This change in mental
attitude is not something that will take place very easily.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Park Yong-maan, 44, the fifth of seven children in a family that
runs a longtime chaebol, called Doosan Corp., is fighting that
image head on. An energetic man whose American MBA has helped him
embrace the world of market capitalism faster than some of his
peers, he is bracing for the challenges ahead by hiring several
American consulting companies to help him reshape the business.
</P>
<P>
   When Park talks, he likes to have pen and paper in front of him,
and he compulsively jots down notes and strategy formulations to
make his point. As he gets up to stretch, it finally comes out that
he is recovering from back surgery performed two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And who says he did not work hard?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on the floor of a dimly lighted side room by his office
is a clock, a sheet, and a thin mattress, where he takes a rest
when the back pain heats up and he can no longer endure sitting at
his computer. So he bristles at the taunts about him and his
cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the public looks at us _ as spoiled kids,'' said
Park, as he put his hand firmly on the seat by the desk in his
corner windowed office. He said he had worked hard ``to get to this
chair, far more than others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
