<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-BANK-NYT &LR;      08-06 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN AGENCY PROBING FINANCIAL CORRUPTION IS ITSELF UNDER
SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The Indonesian government is investigating
allegations of corruption at the powerful agency entrusted with
unwinding three decades of the same kind of corruption in the
nation's financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a scandal that highlights the paradoxes of a
government's efforts to disinfect itself, Finance Minister Bambang
Subianto said Friday that Indonesia's Supreme Audit Agency would
look into allegations that an official at the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency helped arrange millions of dollars in payments
to a businessman with connections to the country's ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary for IBRA that we clarify the case,'' Bambang
told reporters at a seminar on investment in Indonesia, referring
to the bank restructuring agency's acronym. ``This effort is part
of the government trying to avoid the emergence of other problems
which, in turn, could hamper the bank restructuring process.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank restructuring agency is leading a $35 billion bailout
of Indonesia's banks. Last week, a prominent Indonesian legal
expert accused the agency's deputy chairman, Pande Lubis, of
arranging for Bank Bali _ which has since come under the management
of Standard Chartered PLC _ to pay 550 billion rupiah ($78.3
million) to three businessmen to help it secure the repayment of
904 billion rupiah ($129 million) in delinquent interbank loans
from banks already taken over by the bank restructuring agency.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fees Bank Bali paid purportedly ended up at a local
finance company called Era Giat Prima. The head of that company,
Setya Novanto, is also vice treasurer of Golkar, the political
party of former President Suharto and the current president, B.J.
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie faces a difficult re-election campaign in November
following Golkar's second-place finish in June's national
parliamentary elections. The latest scandal buttresses charges by
opposition politicians that Golkar is using government money to
help finance Habibie's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Pande has issued no statement concerning the charges and was
unavailable for comment Friday. though a bank restructuring agency
official said by telephone from Jakarta that Pande was still
working at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta's financial community is watching the Bank Bali case
closely to see if the bank restructuring agency's reputation for
political independence has been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The bank restructuring agency was created early last year at the
insistence of the International Monetary Fund, which has provided
more than $40 billion in aid to Indonesia to help it recover from
the Asia economic crisis that began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Indonesia's central bank is nominally in charge of the
banking system, the bank restructuring agency has greater control.
It has taken over more than 50 failed banks, lashed together four
state-owned banks into the nation's biggest bank and is helping
raise the money needed to resuscitate nine other banks. Its
takeovers of other banks means the agency has inherited a portfolio
of assets equivalent to at least one-fifth of the entire Indonesian
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank Bali imbroglio is just the latest obstacle the agency
has faced as it tries to rebuild the nation's financial system. The
agency aims to raise 17 trillion rupiah ($2.42 billion) by the
spring via asset sales to help the government offset 34 trillion
rupiah ($4.84 billion) in interest payments on bonds it has issued
to help recapitalize the nation's surviving banks. Doing so means
wresting control of assets from the nation's powerful political
elite, people with close connections to Habibie and Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to aggravating bureaucratic tangles, the agency's
chairman, Glenn Yusuf, has been criticized because he also heads an
investment bank advising the agency. Foreign investors have accused
the agency of stalling on asset sales to prevent them from falling
into foreign hands, while local property owners have accused the
agency of trying to sell the nation out.
</P>
<P>
   The agency moved quickly this week to contain the fallout from
the Bank Bali scandal, with Yusuf acknowledging to journalists that
the agency had discovered the payments when it nationalized Bank
Bali on July 23, and that part of the 550 billion rupiah had indeed
been paid to Era Giat Prima. The agency has vowed to conduct its
own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Adding its voice to the chorus, the Indonesian Democratic Party
of Struggle, which won the most votes in June parliamentary
elections, announced that it would establish a team to conduct its
own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the purported deal remain sketchy, but so far
appear to involve Era Giat Prima's purchase of some of Bank Bali's
bad loans. According to press reports, Bank Bali agreed to sell Era
Giat Prima two of those loans, both from other banks that the bank
restructuring agency had shuttered. In theory, this meant that the
agency guaranteed their obligations and would eventually honor
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
