<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-DRUG-STOCKS-AR     08-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DRUG-STOCKS-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT AMERICAN DRUG-STOCK SELLOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of total returns of 10 companies vs. S&AMP;P drug
index is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember what last year was like for investors in drug stocks?
</P>
<P>
   People who bought Schering-Plough's shares in January 1998 saw
their shares surge 77.8 percent by year-end. Even one of the year's
worst-peforming drug stocks _ Johnson &AMP; Johnson _ soared 27
percent, enough to outperform luminaries like Coca-Cola and Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   But talk about going from riches to rags. Only one of the 10
major American pharmaceutical stocks, a resurgent Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, has delivered a positive return this year, despite a
steady increase in the industry's earnings. The S&AMP;P drug index has
plunged 19.3 percent this year, versus a gain of 5.8 percent for
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors appear to be causing the drug sector's ills. In
the last few months, investors have moved money out of
pharmaceuticals and into rising cyclical stocks, notably energy
companies. And analysts say some investors may be worried that the
economy may overheat or that President Clinton's threat to add drug
benefits to Medicare may lower profits, if it leads to price
controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals of the drug companies are still the same;
they are still as strong as ever,'' said Michael T. Manns, a vice
president at American Express Asset Management. But that isn't
enough, he said. ``You have to have a benign environment for growth
stocks _ stable or lower interest rates. The interest rate fears
are back in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Though drug stocks have been drooping for much of the year, the
pain has become acute in recent weeks. In July, the S&AMP;P 500-stock
index fell 3.2 percent, but the S&AMP;P drug index plunged 7.7 percent,
despite the strong second-quarter earnings reported by most
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts don't see the downward spiral ending anytime soon,
saying drug stocks may decline until the overall market experiences
a correction. Historically, such an event lifts the sector, which
is regarded as relatively sturdy in a declining economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors should look for drug stocks to come back when the
interest rates drop a bit,'' said Ken Corba, chief investment
officer of Pimco Equity Advisors, which owns shares of
Bristol-Myers Squibb and Schering-Plough.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors are already in the stocks' favor. Many
drug-company executives think that President Clinton's plan to make
drug benefits a standard part of Medicare will be derailed, as have
most of his other health care initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the drug companies have continued to be strong
financial performers. Earnings are expected to swell 15 percent
this year, on average, at the largest American drug companies,
thanks to huge revenue gains in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson increased its pharmaceutical sales in the
United States by 37.3 percent in the second quarter, compared with
the same quarter of 1998. Its shares have risen 9.8 percent this
year _ in part because the company is more diversified than most of
its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The bargain-hunting may begin soon. The average
price-to-earnings ratio for large drug stocks has dropped from 39
last November to 32.3, only slightly higher than the 30.8 of the
S&AMP;P 500. Even the industry's earnings champions have become more
affordable. The P/E ratio for Warner-Lambert, for example, has
dropped to 36.7, from 52.2 in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valuations of the drug stocks have definitely fallen in
line,'' said Sergio Traversa, an analyst with Mehta Partners, a
research company in New York. ``You usually see some depression in
drug stock prices during the summer and a pickup in the fall. But
this could be a good buying opportunity for some investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have taken note of the stocks' promise. Eli Lilly's
stock, for example, has dropped 29.5 percent this year, closing on
Friday at $62.6875. But a forecast from Ryan, Beck, Southeast
Research says the stock should reach $85 during the next 18 months,
up 35.6 percent. Warner-Lambert, meanwhile, has tumbled 16.5
percent, to $62.8125; the forecast is for it to reach $83, up 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But when drug stocks start rising, investors may find a new set
of troubles. Analysts worry that in the next few years, the
industry will not match its recent bounty of new high-revenue drugs
_ products like the arthritis drugs Vioxx, from Merck, and
Celebrex, from Monsanto and Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   The next blockbuster drug may not come to market until late next
year, when Bristol-Myers is expected to introduce Vanlev, for
hypertension. Several companies are working on remedies for flu
symptoms, but analysts doubt that they will become huge sellers
because the illness is episodic, not chronic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge is maintaining a blockbuster's boom sales. As
recently as four years ago, a drug would not reach peak sales for
several years. But with the advent of consumer advertising,
prescription drugs are climbing to those peaks much faster, which
could mean revenue gaps between product introductions.
</P>
<P>
   That problem, of course, also has a positive side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the drug companies are not only marketing faster,
they are reaching a larger market than what they did in the past,''
Traversa said. ``We're seeing less me-too drugs, ones that were
like something that already existed, now than in the '80s. They're
coming out with much more innovation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
