<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-RUBELL-$A     08-06 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-RUBELL-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCO HEIRS TURN TO DECO HOTELS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ The Rubell family, whose most famous member
_ Steve Rubell, co-founder of Studio 54 _ proved that hotels could
become as fashionable as discotheques, still speak of their trade
as more art than business.
</P>
<P>
   Since selling his shares in Manhattan hotels like the Royalton,
the Paramount and Morgans after his death in 1989 and shipping
their money, and themselves, south, the Rubells have become leaders
in restoring Art Deco hotels here _ hotels as trendy as those back
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are expanding into other types of hotels and making
plans to work their way back up north.
</P>
<P>
   When Mera Rubell, 55, Steve's sister-in-law, thinks of her
family's business today, she says it calls to mind the sculpture
``Family Romance,'' by the California artist Charles Ray. It
depicts four members of a mannequin family holding hands _ the
parents, a son and a daughter _ all nude, all the same size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the notion that each family member has equal power,''
Mrs. Rubell said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Rubell's equal partners in Rubell Hotels are her husband of
35 years, Dr. Donald Rubell, Steve's older brother, who is 58, and
their two children, Jennifer, 29, and Jason, 30. Three of them
moved to Florida in the early 1990s while Rubell, the former chief
of gynecology at Cabrini Medical Center in Manhattan, commuted on
weekends until last year, when he moved here, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubells, who are major collectors of contemporary art,
opened two renovated Art Deco hotels here in 1995 and 1997 _ the
Greenview, with 45 rooms, and the Albion, with 100. In October,
they will open a bigger, more luxurious hotel in a 1950s building
now under renovation, the 170-room Beach House Bal Harbour on the
shore in Surfside, a few miles north of here.
</P>
<P>
   And the family plans to expand by 2001 into Washington, where
negotiations are under way for the purchase of a 200-room property
near the Capitol. They said they are scouting other locations,
including New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubells also own the 70,000-square-foot Sony Building office
complex on Lincoln Road here and the Rubell Family Collection, a
permanent exhibition of contemporary art in a Miami warehouse.
Where so many other business families have blown apart, sometimes
in failure, they have achieved success by sticking together.
</P>
<P>
   At Rubell Hotels, Jason Rubell, an art history graduate of Duke
University, handles finances. He and his mother, who handles
property acquisitions, are also often at construction sites of new
projects like the Beach House Bal Harbour _ he deals with
architects, she with contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Rubell, a Harvard University graduate who studied fine
arts, determines the hotels' style. She designs everything from
room decor to matchbooks. ``She's vice president in charge of
vibrations,'' her father said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubell's main job is just as quirky: he is the long-term
thinker, the spotter of new projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubells say their family business has worked because the
parents have given up much of their authority, ``the power of our
age,'' as Mrs. Rubell puts it. The children have likewise contained
their own egos, their desires to chart their own paths, ``to prove
yourself and bring back what you've done,'' Jason Rubell said.
</P>
<P>
   The reward, they agreed, is absolute trust in one another's
motivations, and the ability to work as a unit. `'I don't want to
sound mushy, but love is a powerful ingredient,'' Mrs. Rubell said,
a cue for the rest of her family to poke fun at her during a recent
interview at the Albion. ``That went out in the '60s, Mera,''
Rubell said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rubell, Rubell's only brother, gained fame as co-owner of
Studio 54, the 1970s New York City disco. After serving a prison
sentence for tax evasion, Rubell switched to the hotel business in
New York City with his former Studio 54 partner Ian Schrager and
two associates.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rubells, who were close to Steve, sold the hotel
interests they inherited from him to Schrager. At the time, Mrs.
Rubell owned a firm that sold office and retail properties in New
York. Her children were in college, but they had apprenticed with
their uncle and Schrager in the hotel business _ Jennifer full time
as the Royalton's first concierge, Jason overseeing construction of
the Paramount as a summer job.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Jason moved to Florida in 1991 to open an art
gallery in Palm Beach, and later one here, that the other family
members started trickling in. Mrs. Rubell followed in 1993, when
she bought a seven-story office building on Lincoln Road that was
renamed the Sony Building when Sony Music International moved in.
</P>
<P>
   The first hotel purchase evolved from the needs of Sony Building
tenants for an affordable hotel nearby. Today, the Greenview and
the Albion, which includes an office and retail wing, have become
fashion, media and entertainment industry hubs.
</P>
<P>
   The hotels have gained the Rubells considerable recognition.
``They're a good example of what many hoteliers here are doing,''
said David Whitaker, senior vice president of marketing for the
Greater Miami Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``They've created
these spectacular new hotels, honoring the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beach House will cater to families but also provide
idiosyncratic features like a 24-hour food store and an aquarium
with 200 sea horses. The hotel will add 250 employees to the 100
that currently work for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubells are due in New York City, the hotels' largest
market, for a media reception on Wednesday to talk about the Beach
House, which is scheduled to open on Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubells and Schrager, whose high-style 238-room Delano
opened in 1995 only two blocks from the Albion, now compete in the
same market. The Rubells say they have no contact with Schrager; he
had no comment himself.
</P>
<P>
   The family boasts that they emphasize service, aiming for the
intimacy of bed-and-breakfasts while offering the amenities of
bigger hotels. ``He really understood service,'' Ms. Rubell said of
her uncle Steve. ``That's what I learned from him. He gave me a
desire to make people feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   But these Rubells aren't putting up the sort of velvet ropes
that kept legions out of Studio 54. Their hotels, while stylish,
are inspired by the family's idea of their own welcoming home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lived in that environment, what would our house look
like?'' Rubell said. ``That really sums it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
