<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     08-06 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING SOON: THE TAX-CUT WAR OF WORDS  
 BLACK CAUCUS CHAMPIONS LOWERY  
 SOUTH CAROLINA TO HAVE ITS SAY ON JUVENILE JUSTICE  
 AID FOR TOBACCO FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Try this summer blockbuster on for size. Tax Cuts:
Are They a Phantom Fiscal Menace or Help for Runaway Brides and
Grooms?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats plan on taking their dueling tax-cut
themes on the road this month in a concerted congressional-recess
effort to persuade the public of the righteousness of their
respective causes.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of being outflanked by President Clinton in the public
relations war, Republicans are scheduling high-profile events to
share with Americans the good tidings of $792 billion in tax cuts
that ease the burden on married couples, eliminate estate taxes and
cut capital gains and overall rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go across the country in August and we're going
to let the American people know, number one, it's their money, not
Washington's money, and they're going to get to keep more of it to
spend the way they see fit,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, a
chief tax-cut architect.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats plan to counter that effort with a campaign of their
own, emphasizing their view that the Republican plan is
economically risky, would lead to across-the-board spending cuts
and doesn't leave sufficient money to reform Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sell a truly bad idea and that is what they are
trying to do,'' said House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, predicting the GOP push would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats almost uniformly rejected the GOP-crafted tax package,
drawing a clear party distinction on the issue. Even those
Democrats who backed the Senate package first time around thought
the final proposal was ill advised.
</P>
<P>
   One of those moderate Democratic lawmakers, Sen. John Breaux of
Louisiana, attributed the stalemate to the unwillingness of either
party to give ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real losers are the people in the middle and that's where
I believe most Americans are today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sowing Civil Rights
</P>
<P>
   Several Southern lawmakers are pushing for the appointment of a
respected civil rights leader to oversee the dispersal of a
multimillion-dollar discrimination settlement with black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lowery, the retired president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, was recommended for the post of ``monitor''
by members of the Congressional Black Caucus, including chairman
James Clyburn of South Carolina, Earl Hilliard of Alabama and Eva
Clayton of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rev. Lowery has a proven track record and would lend a
tremendous amount of credibility to this office,'' they wrote in a
letter to Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, the federal government reached a settlement with
black farmers who charged that they were subjected to
discriminatory lending practices over the years and suffered losses
as a result. The monitor would help determine how much money
individual farmers would get to settle their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Palmetto Players
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina lawmakers will have a strong voice in the final
stage of crafting a major juvenile justice bill that's become a
flash point for both gun control and religious expression.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Republican Jim DeMint, who led the effort in the House
to protect religious expression in schools, was named to the
House-Senate conference committee that will hammer out differences
between the House and Senate bills. Sen. Strom Thurmond, a
Republican, was also named to that committee.
</P>
<P>
   DeMint vowed to fight efforts to crack down on gun ownership as
a way of combating violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about finding a comprehensive and common-sense
approach to youth violence _ ways to improve school safety, restore
strong neighborhoods and reinforce our shared community values,''
DeMint said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members are expected to meet during the August recess and
lawmakers will get down to business on the juvenile justice bill
once they return in September.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Road
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies are not all that popular on Capitol Hill but
tobacco growers can still find powerful allies.
</P>
<P>
   As it fashioned an emergency $7 billion farm aid measure, the
Senate added $328 million for tobacco farmers at the last-minute
insistence of Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture is in crisis,'' said Edwards, whose state could
get almost half of the tobacco aid. ``It is almost impossible for
North Carolina farmers, including its tobacco farmers, to make ends
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure also included some relief for growers of peanuts and
cotton among other Southern staples.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
