<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BLOCKBUSTER-IPO-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK KID, ON VIDEO: THE BLOCKBUSTER OFFERING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (af)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some investors shaken by the sharp selloff of recently issued
Internet stocks may find comfort in the coming initial public
offering of shares in Blockbuster Inc.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Blockbuster debut is a turnaround story featuring
a bricks-and-mortar company with actual _ rather than virtual _
earnings and a brand name that is synonymous with video rentals.
And some analysts say the offering should be attractive because of
its pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, the No. 1 video retailer, has worked its way back
to profitability, but it has not been able to shake off concerns
that the onslaught of emerging technologies that deliver video on
demand will deal a body blow to the rental business. But company
presentations to investors in the last few days seem to have turned
some heads.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, Blockbuster's parent, Viacom Inc., is
expected to offer a 17.7 percent stake in Blockbuster to the
public, the first of a two-part transaction in which Blockbuster
will become independent. The shares are expected to be priced at
$16 to $18 each, giving the company a stock market value of $2.8
billion to $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The offering is to be followed by a tax-free split-off of the
rest of Blockbuster to Viacom shareholders late this year or in
early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viacom is pricing the shares to sell,'' said Larry Petrella, a
media analyst with Lehman Brothers. He noted that at $17 a share,
the midpoint of the expected price range, Blockbuster would be
valued at six times estimated cash flow of $640 million in 2000,
while media giants like Time Warner and Viacom have multiples in
the mid- to high teens.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Zied, a retail industry specialist with the Maverick
Corp., a Dallas-based hedge fund manager, said Blockbuster's hybrid
status _ part retailer, part entertainment company _ ``makes direct
valuation comparisons problematic.'' But he said that at $17,
Blockbuster would sell at 15.4 times estimated 2000 cash earnings
of $1.10, compared with 27 times for Circuit City, the big
electronics retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, the video rental industry ``looked like it
hit a brick wall,'' said Derek Baine, an analyst with Paul Kagan
Associates, the entertainment industry consultants. After years of
phenomenal growth, rental revenues declined in 1995 and 1997 before
rebounding last year. Baine projects increases of about 8 percent
this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the industry's wounds _ and Blockbusters' _ were
self-inflicted and had little to do with competing technology.
After Viacom acquired Blockbuster in 1994 for almost $5.7 billion,
the 6,500-store video chain struggled with unsuccessful forays into
music retailing and ill-conceived merchandising strategies that had
the stores selling everything from M &AMP; M's to T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Two chief executives and $759 million in write-offs later,
Blockbuster is enjoying a striking turnaround. In 1998,
Blockbuster's current chief, John F. Antioco, signed ``revenue
sharing'' agreements with the major Hollywood movie studios that in
effect pushed them into financial partnerships with the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of paying an average of $65 for new tapes,
Blockbuster pays just $4 apiece on average. In exchange, it turns
over 30 percent to 40 percent of the rental income to the studios.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of revenue sharing was apparent in the second
quarter. Revenues climbed 17 percent from a year earlier, to $1
billion, reflecting a 13 percent gain from stores open in both
periods. Cash flow increased 61 percent, to $105 million.
Blockbuster's share of the home-video rental market reached 31
percent, up from 27 percent a few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   More important, industry analysts say, the studios have no
incentive to tamper with the current 30-to-90-day window that makes
new films available in video stores before they can be shown
through other nontheatrical channels like pay-per-view, basic cable
or network television.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that with revenue sharing, home video now accounts
for 48 percent of domestic film revenues for major studios, more
than double the 22 percent from domestic box office sales. Video
rental income is especially crucial to the profitability of less
popular titles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
