A8597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-AID-0807-COX     08-06 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-AID-0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPECIAL INTERESTS FIND FREE RIDE IN FARM EMERGENCY
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Farmers in the East, suffering from the worst
drought of the century, must wait until fall for federal
assistance. But the disaster has already eased the way for new aid
for tobacco, sugar and peanuts commodities that have hardly been
touched by the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feeding frenzy,'' said John Frydenlund, an agricultural
specialist at Citizens Against Government Waste, a private watchdog
group, of this week's $7.4 billion ``emergency'' farm aid plan,
which the Senate attached to the annual agricultural spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``emergency'' measures are exempted from congressional
budget limits, the amendment was quickly loaded up with programs
that are the darlings of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: $42 million in direct payments to peanut producers
to compensate them for a recent drop in prices and a rise in
production costs, $328 million in direct aid to tobacco farmers,
and $15 million for a fishery.
</P>
<P>
   And these are only the starting point before the lawmakers
return from their August vacation to add relief plans for the
devastated farms in the drought-stricken East.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions that are hitchhiking on the farm aid measure
brought a strong protest from congressional ``pork buster'' Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., who told his colleagues on Tuesday that
``these provisions have no place in a bill to provide emergency
assistance to America's farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, a presidential contender for 2000, found little
support in the Senate when he attempted to end the price support
program for sugar. Nor could he win backing to force the industry
to pay a federal tax that McCain called a ``miniscule assessment''
of 25 cents per 100 pounds of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of McCain's effort was hailed by the American Sugar
Alliance as ``another indication of the solid support the Congress
gives'' to sugar producers, who received the ``emergency'' relief
although they have not been affected by the drought.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Congress forges a final drought relief program,
some experts predict that those who need the aid the most will
benefit only marginally.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, the farm programs help the people who are
well off,'' said Kevin McNew, an agriculture economist at the
University of Maryland. He estimated that 70 percent of farm
payments go to farmers with over $1 million in net worth.
</P>
<P>
   A widespread concern among farmers is that large operators will
use the federal aid to bid up already climbing rents for farmland,
often pricing the smaller farmers out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Big operators won a boost in the Senate bill, which doubles the
current $75,000 cap for federal crop payments to a farmer to
$150,000. On a large multi-farm operation, a couple could qualify
for up to $300,000 in federal payments.
</P>
<P>
   That maximum would represent about 4,000 acres in the Midwest,
estimated Richard Newpher, executive director of the American Farm
Bureau, whose group has long sought an increase in the caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there ought to be payment limits,'' he said,
adding that his group favors the most ``economically viable''
farming.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
