<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAY-TEENS07-COX     08-06 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAY-TEENS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A mother's prayer line reaches out to Ohio youths
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Christina Hurr knows that kids reach a certain
age when there's only so much you can do for them. She has three
kids at that age now: a 16-year-old son and 14-year-old twins.
</P>
<P>
   And, although she knows they are bound to do things she won't
agree with, there's one thing she can always do about it: ``I can
always pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurr has seen prayer at work in her own life and in the lives of
her parents, who she recalls used to kneel by their bedside and
pray every night.
</P>
<P>
   She also believes in the power of intercessory prayer _ prayer
for others.
</P>
<P>
   That's why she has started Pray 4 Teens Ministry, where parents,
friends or the teens themselves can call or e-mail to request
prayer support.
</P>
<P>
   A phone line in her home is dedicated to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churches have prayer chains, but there is nothing marketed to
teens,'' says Hurr, 45, curriculum instruction coordinator for the
Montgomery County Board of Mental Retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Teens may be embarrassed to ask for prayer, and parents of teens
may also feel ashamed if their kids have gone astray. That's why
Pray 4 Teens is answered by machine in the dining room of Hurr's
Centerville home. Callers can leave their initials, or their middle
name. Hurr doesn't offer any form of counseling, and she doesn't
call anyone back.
</P>
<P>
   Since the phone line opened in April, Hurr has prayed for 10
people. Although she is the only one who prays now, she hopes the
ministry grows to include teens who will pray for other teens.
</P>
<P>
   Although she and her husband, Joe, are members of St. Henry's
Catholic Church, she wants the ministry to be nondenominational.
``God doesn't care what church we come from when he listens to our
prayers,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Hurr has prayed all of her life, but the act has become more
meaningful to her as she has grown older. ``Now, I pray all the
time, whether I'm in church or not. I pray in the shower. I pray in
the car. I don't necessarily pray out loud, but I do tune out
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prayer is a discipline, but it is also spirit-led.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone line has been a vehicle for discussion with her own
family, where prayers are said every night at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to tell my kids when there's been an answer to a
prayer,'' she says, to reinforce the belief that prayer works.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger sons aren't always sure they believe in prayer. But
when their mother asks them to help with their prayers, they say
they'll do so.
</P>
<P>
   Their friends know about the prayer line, and ``they think it's
pretty cool,'' John says. He and his twin, Matt, say kids their age
might ask for prayer support for problems such as ``I got in a
fight with my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurr wants her kids to understand that ``the prayer of a good
person has a powerful effect.'' She keeps a small jar of mustard
seed on her windowsill to remind her of the words of Matthew 17:20:
``...if you have faith as a grain of mustard seed, you will say to
this mountain, `Move hence to yonder place,' and it will move; and
nothing will be impossible to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
