<HEADER>
A8614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-IMPACT-$ADV08-COX     08-06 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-IMPACT-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAVINGS UNDER NEW TAX BILL VARY WILDLY
 &HT;    330&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What's in it for me? That's what many Americans
wonder whenever Congress passes a big tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the most accurate answer for the Republican bill just passed
by Congress in the face of a certain veto by President Clinton can
only be an unsatisfactory straddle: It all depends.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP calculated the changes the bill could make
in the tax burdens on 30 different households at income levels
between $20,000 and $1 million. All the bill's major changes will
be in effect from 2005 through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only rule of thumb I can think of is that married couples
who have $50,000 to $60,000 of taxable income are going to see the
biggest effect,'' said Clint Stretch, director of tax policy in the
accounting firm's Washington office. ``But the numbers vary widely,
even for households at the same income level.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the tax burdens on various households with identical
incomes of $50,000 a year before and after the changes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A single man with $48,500 in ordinary income and $1,500 in
long-term capital gains would see his $6,263 tax bill drop to
$5,900.
</P>
<P>
   _ A married couple with the same income from the same sources
would see its $4,725 tax bill drop to $4,405.
</P>
<P>
   _ A family of four with the same income from the same sources
would see its $2,900 tax bill drop to $2,635.
</P>
<P>
   _ A family of four with the same income from the same sources
that also pays college tuition of $3,000 a year would see its
$1,900 tax bill drop to $1,635.
</P>
<P>
   _ A retired couple with $30,000 from Social Security, $16,000 in
ordinary income and $4,000 in capital gains would see its $640 tax
bill drop to $388.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's all before you take advantage of any of the
increased credits that could lower your taxable income,'' Stretch
said. Credits for child care, long-term health care and education
are among those expanded by the bill.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The variations grow out of the interaction of the three major
changes the bill would make in the current income-tax system.
</P>
<P>
   It lowers tax rates. When the changes are fully in effect, rates
drop by 10 percent for capital gains, which are the profits of
selling stocks, bonds or other property for more than they cost,
and by anywhere from 2.5 percent to 6.25 percent for ordinary
income, which includes wages, salaries, dividends and interest
earned.
</P>
<P>
   It also changes married couples' tax brackets in a way that
means the 28 percent marginal tax rate for some couples drops in
half to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it contains new or bigger credits, deductions and other
loopholes that can lower the level of taxable income for any
taxpayer, including corporations.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, how much the new system could affect you depends on
how much you make, which sources it comes from, and how many
credits, deductions and other loopholes you can take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche found that many households aren't affected at
all, because they wouldn't pay any income taxes either before or
after the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of such non-payers:
</P>
<P>
   _ A married couple with two school-age children scraping by on
$20,000 a year. Before or after the change, they would actually get
a $2,228 refund, thanks to a work-subsidy device called the earned
income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   _ A retired couple with $40,000 in income is unlikely to owe any
income taxes under either the current or new system if
three-fourths of its income comes in tax-sheltered Social Security
payments. The remaining one-fourth is offset by standard deductions
and personal exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   But most people do pay federal income taxes. The study showed
that those at different income levels would enjoy widely different
savings from the bill:
</P>
<P>
   _ In dollars, the annual tax savings per household ranges from
$9,861 to $130. The high is for a couple with two children living
on $1 million a year and the low is for a single person earning
$20,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ In percentages, the annual tax savings per household range
from 3.26 percent to 70 percent. The lowest is for that millionaire
couple, whose $302,377 tax burden drops to $272,517. The highest is
for a four-person family living on $35,000 in wages that pays
$3,000 in college tuition costs, and sees its $520 income-tax bill
drop to $156.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
