A8617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FCC-COX07-COX     08-06 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-COX07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relaxed rules likely to instigate `horse trading' of TV
properties
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal government's relaxation of television
ownership rules may promote some ``horse trading'' of stations in
metro Atlanta, according to industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, after lengthy debate,
decided this week to let a media company own two stations in the
country's top 50 markets. Atlanta is among the top 20 markets for
television.
</P>
<P>
   The big four networks and television holding companies have good
incentive to own more than one station in the large markets, a
practice called duopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media choices have exploded,'' Nick Trigony, chairman of Cox
Broadcasting, which owns WSB-TV in Atlanta, has said. ``Cable
channels are TV stations for all practical purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Station owners in town either couldn't be reached for comment
Friday or declined to comment about the change in rules.
</P>
<P>
   But outside experts say the Atlanta market is fertile ground for
some stations selling out and others adding to their local
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect we'll see some consolidation in Atlanta,'' said Paul
Raymond, a industry consultant and media professor at Kennesaw
State University.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Westerfield, a media analyst at PaineWebber, agreed. ``In
select markets, including Atlanta, you're going to see some smart
horse trading,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Westerfield said the relaxation in ownership rules would force
all owners, especially the weak ones, to decide now whether to get
bigger or sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's going to have to rethink their strategy,'' said
Westerfield.
</P>
<P>
   Trigony supported relaxing local ownership rules to let
companies own two stations in any one market _ but only in the 20
largest metro areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duopoly only works if you have six to eight TV signals in a
market,'' says Trigony.
</P>
<P>
   Trigony was out of town Friday and couldn't be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Raymond said that he wouldn't be surprised if Cox
Broadcasting, which owns the market leader in Atlanta, decided to
buy another station here. He also expects another acquirer in the
market might be Fox Television, which owns WAGA-TV, Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Broadcasting is a unit of Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises,
which also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   One media mogul who has already announced his intention to sell
at least some stations nationwide is Lowell W. Paxson, who controls
the PaxTV Network of stations in the 20 biggest cities. His
holdings include WPXA, Channel 14, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going into the duopoly game, we're the prettiest girl
at the duop dance,'' Paxson told The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, according to Westerfield, Paxson holds some ``pretty
attractive properties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
