A8621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-PIRACY07-CO     08-06 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PIRACY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reseller of PCs denies pirating software
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The owner of Microseconds, one of the Atlanta area
companies accused by Microsoft this week of selling pirated
software, said if his company sold counterfeit software it did so
unwittingly.
</P>
<P>
   Steven J. Brandt, who owns the two-site, $2 million-a-year PC
reseller, is accused of selling a pirated copy of Microsoft's
Windows 95 and Office Professional 97 and agreeing to sell a PC
with software for which there was no license.
</P>
<P>
   Microseconds is among the oldest and largest of five Atlanta
area computer dealers that Microsoft sued in federal court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies could face up to $100,000 in damages per license.
A product like Office Pro 97, which is a package of programs, has
eight licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is what we have done is not illegal,'' said
Brandt. ``If we sold a PC with an illegal or pirated copy of
software, we bought it in good faith. And I can show you where we
bought it; there would be invoices.''
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, Microsoft claims Microseconds agreed to sell an
undercover Microsoft representative a PC with a pirated copy of
Windows 95. Microsoft followed that up with a letter asking
Microseconds to stop selling software for which it does not have
licenses. In April and July, a private detective hired by Microsoft
bought what the company claimed were counterfeit copies of both
Windows 95 and Office Professional 97.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt remembers receiving the letter from Microsoft. But he
said he assumed it was a form letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it, did not realize that it pertained to us directly
and never gave it a second thought,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Software programs come with license agreements as a way to
determine whether a copy is legal. A software company gets paid
once for each version of software it sells. With pirated software,
one legal copy of an operating system software program such as
Windows 95 could be installed illegally on several PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft attorney Nick Psyhogeos said companies cannot legally
sell software for which it does not have a license. The company
estimates that one of five software programs being used in Georgia
is a pirated copy.
</P>
<P>
   Microseconds buys computers from consumers and companies selling
old equipment or from stores with excess inventory or ones going
out of business. The PCs it sells on consignment may come with or
without licenses for the software stored on the hard drive, Brandt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the middleman,'' he said. ``We assume they have not
broken the law when they brought it to us. We assume they brought
in a legal copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
