<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAPPINGS-$ADV08-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING BACK: COLOMBIAN CITIZENS REFUSE TO PAY RANSOMS TO
KIDNAPPERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 8) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALI, Colombia _ While their kidnappers roared down the highway
in a convoy of trucks, Norma Beron and her husband, Roy Saykay,
decided that this crime would not pay.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was among about 150 worshippers snatched by leftist
guerrillas May 30 during Mass at La Maria Catholic Church on the
outskirts of Cali. Huddled in the back of one of the trucks, Saykay
whispered to his wife that if she managed to escape, she must not
negotiate a ransom for his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I would rather die than have you pay anything,'''
said Beron, who fled to freedom later that day along with dozens of
other hostages as Colombian army troops chased the rebels into the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Such resolve is catching on.
</P>
<P>
   In a defiant gesture aimed at rolling back Colombia's soaring
rate of kidnappings, a small but growing number of people are
refusing ransom payments.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, relatives of 39 of the 45 remaining captives from
the church kidnapping signed a public document rejecting
guerrillas' demands for cash. The families of other hostages as
well as business leaders, ranchers and other potential kidnapping
victims are considering similar declarations to discourage future
abductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop all of this. It's time to tell these
cretins: No more!'' said Mario Otoya, a photographer, whose brother
and sister-in-law were grabbed at La Maria church and are still in
rebel custody.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe that this citizen-led effort is the first of
its kind in the world. Although it's unclear whether the tactic
will work, people say that something drastic had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia has the highest number of kidnappings in the world.
Last year, there were 2,216 abductions pulled off by guerrillas,
paramilitaries, drug dealers and criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
   During the first seven months of this year, 1,467 Colombians
were taken hostage _ a rate of nearly seven per day. Many were
caught at guerrilla roadblocks, a tactic called ``miracle fishing''
in which the rebels stop dozens of cars in the hopes of snagging
rich motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that huge swaths of countryside are under
guerrilla control, making rescues more difficult. The justice
system is weak, and some convicted criminals continue to order
kidnappings from behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is small because there is a high level of impunity
and police reaction is slow,'' said Juan Francisco Mesa, a lawyer
for the Free Country Foundation, a support group in Bogota for
relatives of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Some hostages escape or are freed by authorities, while a small
number are killed. But cash payments, averaging about $50,000, are
extracted for the freedom of nearly half of all captives, Mesa
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time someone pays a ransom, it provides the money for
kidnappers to carry out their next abduction,'' the National Police
chief, Rosso Jose Serrano, told the Colombian magazine Cambio.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Colombia outlawed such transactions in 1993,
banned the purchase of kidnapping insurance _ which reimburses the
policy-holder for ransom payments _ and gave authorities the power
to freeze the bank accounts of relatives of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Similar laws succeeded in Italy and Ireland and appeared to make
a difference in Colombia. The number of reported abductions dropped
30 percent in 1993. But some analysts believe that Colombians
simply stopped reporting the crime in order to negotiate ransoms
without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcement of the new laws was also lax. One of the few people
jailed was Rene Higuita, the star goalie for Colombia's national
soccer team, who was caught negotiating a ransom payment with
associates of the late drug lord Pablo Escobar.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 months, most of the anti-kidnapping provisions were
struck down by the nation's highest court, which ruled that life is
so precious that Colombians must be allowed to pursue the freedom
of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who have had relatives kidnapped for more than a
year. They feel totally alone in their pain. How can you tell them
to pay or not to pay?'' said Ximena Corzo, whose brother, a
Colombian congressman, was taken hostage in April when guerrillas
hijacked an Avianca domestic flight.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the voluntary no-ransom movement has wide support.
In a recent poll by the magazine Cambio, 95 percent of respondents
supported the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In Cali, leaders of the effort meet every day under a tent next
to the city's bull ring to talk to journalists, promote their
stance and raise each other's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like therapy to a lot of us,'' said Otoya, the
photographer, who is taking care of his kidnapped brother's three
children. ``We are leaning on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the decision to sign the no-ransom pledge was easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not rich. In my case, I don't have the resources to pay
one peso,'' said Gina Camacho, whose husband, Daniel, was grabbed
at La Maria church.
</P>
<P>
   Others muse about whether the hostages would agree with their
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if they are asking: `What the hell are they doing?'''
Otoya said. ``I hope they think that we are doing the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the sensational nature of the church assault
convinced the families that their protest might work.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was carried out by the National Liberation Army, or
ELN, a guerrilla group that wants to open peace talks with the
government. President Andres Pastrana, who was kidnapped by drug
dealers a decade ago, said he will not negotiate with the ELN until
the hostages are released ``without conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, by kidnapping worshippers during a Mass, the rebels
sparked protests around the world and received a rebuke from Pope
John Paul II. Last week, Monsignor Isaias Duarte, the archbishop of
Cali, excommunicated the rebels involved in the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much international attention on this case that
surely nothing will happen to (the hostages). The guerrillas can't
commit the political error of killing them,'' Mesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, relatives of 16 hostages taken during the Avianca
hijacking and 11 sport fishermen snatched by the ELN rebels in June
are debating whether or not to go public with a similar statement.
There are also plans to make a no-ransom document available at
public notaries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risks are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cattle Ranchers Federation approved a no-ransom
policy in 1990, and since then two of its board members have been
kidnapped and killed by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that most kidnappings are driven by profit
rather than politics, minimizing the effect of local and
international political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of kidnappings are individual abductions;
family members lack the group support that often develops among
relatives dealing with group kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   Even the solidarity of the Cali group could fall apart if the
ordeal drags on, said Mike Ackerman, managing director of the
Ackerman Group, a Miami-based security consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guerrillas tend to use time as a weapon. They control
territory, and they'll just keep the hostage until you decide that
you're going to change your mind,'' he said. ``Some fairly big fish
were taken in Cali. As time passes, it wouldn't surprise me if
money did change hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Camacho, wife of one of the church hostages and an advocate of
the no-ransom movement in Cali, disagrees. ``It has to be a
personal philosophy. If you have it in your head that you will not
pay, this whole business will come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
