<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYMENT REPORT DRIVES UP TREASURY YIELDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yields of U.S. government bonds surged Friday to
their highest level in 20 months after the Labor Department's July
employment report added to the mounting concern that the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy-makers raised the target rate for
overnight lending by a quarter-point, to 5 percent, on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength depicted in the July employment report assures an
Aug. 24 Federal Reserve firming,'' said Marilyn Schaja, an
economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dropped 1 20/32 to a price
of 87 19/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
climbed to 6.17 percent, from 6.04 percent Thursday, the highest
since 6.20 percent on Nov. 20, 1997. For investors, the day's loss
amounted to about $16.25 for each $1,000 invested in bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two weeks, three inflation signals have pushed
bond prices lower: Friday's wage data, Thursday's
bigger-than-expected increase in unit labor costs and last week's
jump in the government's employment cost index.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that the economy had added
310,000 jobs in July, while wages rose half of 1 percent and the
unemployment rate remained at 4.3 percent. All pointed to an
increased threat of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ablin, president of Colonial Asset Management Inc. in
Jacksonville, Fla., said the strength of the bond market's decline
had done much to remove uncertainty about the timing of the next
interest rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond market certainly has been betting the Fed will raise
rates, but the question up until now has been the timing of such a
move,'' Ablin said. ``Now market participants are pretty sure and
are positioning themselves for an August Fed move.''
</P>
<P>
   Also weighing on bonds is a heavy schedule of government and
corporate issues, starting with next week's $37 billion government
quarterly refunding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
