<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CIA-$ADV08-1S     08-06 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CIA-$ADV08-1STLDWRITETHR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA IN UNUSUAL ROLE IN ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN CONFLICT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: For release Sunday, Aug. 8. Please note that story was
accidentally sent with wrong keyword and release date.) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ Last February, Palestinian agents foiled
an attempted suicide bombing in Tel Aviv planned by Hamas, an
organization opposed to peace agreements with Israel, members of
the Palestinian security forces say.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, members of the Central Intelligence Agency, hovering
in the background, trekked the grimy streets of Gaza and
whitewashed towns of the West Bank to piece together what exactly
the Palestinians had done to prevent the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unusual role for the CIA, one that has thrust the
organization into the uncomfortable position of judging whether
Palestinians, and by extension, Israelis, are keeping their peace
obligations. Israel 's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, hopes to
change that role.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office July 6, Barak has said he would like to see
the United States revert to its traditional role as ``facilitator''
of peace negotiations, rather than continue as arbiter of
never-ending disputes over which side is failing to live up to its
part of signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. role as arbiter may have been necessary after the Wye
Accords were signed last October, Barak maintains, when relations
between the Palestinians and Israel's out-going prime minister,
Benjamin Netanyahu, were mired in mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike his feisty predecessor, Barak says he is eager to
complete a comprehensive peace deal with Palestinians within 15
months. Since he intends to negotiate in good faith, he says the
United States' role as arbiter is no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the U.S. should be a factor in negotiations,'' said
Zvi Stauber, one of Barak's top political advisers. ``But it should
not be a judge who gets involved in small details.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Americans seem eager to take up Barak's suggestion,
take a step back, and let Israelis and Palestinians solve disputes
without outside intervention. The hope is that Barak's good
intentions will nurture good will and produce breakthroughs in
negotiations without much U.S. prodding.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, however, say they are less keen on seeing the
CIA's unprecedented role diminish. Nor are they enthusiastic about
the prospects that the United States might remove itself as arbiter
of disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Palestinians have asked the United States to step in to
help resolve their latest disagreement with Israel, this one over
the timing of the implementation of the Wye peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erakat on Friday renewed that
call for help, reminding that President Clinton had brokered the
agreement last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian National Authority has officially demanded
that the United States guarantee the honest and faithful
implementation of signed accords, particularly Wye,'' Erakat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them they must intervene to guarantee implementation
of the accords because the United States is responsible for the
peace process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said fully carrying out the Wye agreement now would
isolate and endanger Jewish settlements. On Friday, Barak responded
to doubts about his resolution by reiterating his pledge to
implement Wye as originally designed if the Palestinians do not
agree to delaying the final withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I will implement Wye as it was signed by Netanyahu,
provided the Palestinians do their part,'' he told Israel TV.
</P>
<P>
   Without hands-on CIA involvement, Palestinians say, no one would
be there to verify that they had in fact foiled attacks, such as
the one they prevented last February.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid Abu Shabak, deputy head of the Gaza-based Palestinian
Preventive Security, the organization charged with fighting
terrorism, cites several such instances and say that, more often
than not, the CIA agreed that Palestinians were doing their job _
praise Palestinians say helped them counter Israeli allegations to
the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Abu Shabak says, his men have confiscated dozens of
illegal weapons, arrested opposition leaders and made sure 11
militants wanted by Israel for terrorist activity were behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans had a positive opinion of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the CIA were not available for comment. One U.S.
official said that the Palestinians had been diligent in their
efforts to prevent violence, but less so when it came to seizing
illegal weapons and fulfilling other security obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mohammed Dahlan, head of Preventive Security in Gaza,
said Palestinians welcomed intensive CIA involvement in training
Palestinian police and in overseeing their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are here to say whether we are fulfilling our
obligations or not,'' Dahlan said. ``Their role is to watch ... to
make sure we implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We benefit from it,'' he added. ``We don't agree that the
Americans should leave.''
</P>
<P>
   One windfall the Palestinians may be afraid of losing, say
observers here, is closer ties with the United States than they
have ever had before. While relations between the United States and
Israel strained during Netanyahu's term, ties grew between
Palestinians and Americans to unprecedented warm levels.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak entered office, he pledged to repair those frayed
ties by, among other things, removing the United States from an
awkward role that often pitted it against Israel and put it on the
Palestinians' side.
</P>
<P>
   It still remains unclear how, or indeed whether, the CIA's role
will change in any substantial way. But without a third party
playing judge, Palestinians say they fear Israel will be the only
one to determine whether Palestinian police units are doing their
utmost to stop violence.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Israeli-Palestinian relations are good and peace
negotiations stay on track, leaving Israel to determine Palestinian
compliance might not prove a hindrance to furthering peace.
</P>
<P>
   But renewed talks have already run into trouble over the timing
of the transfer of West Bank land to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the Americans, Palestinians say, gives Barak too much
wiggle room to maneuver out of obligations and then cite
Palestinian noncompliance as a pretext for halting further land
transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to play with the facts without anyone else around,''
Dahlan said. ``We don't want security used as an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
