<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MINDSPRING07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring signs AOL messaging deal
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises and EarthLink Network, two of
the nation's largest Internet service providers, have signed deals
with America Online to distribute its AOL Instant Messenger
software to the 2.5 million combined users of the two services,
beginning in late October.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies say the agreements have nothing to do with
AOL's fierce battle with Microsoft, which introduced its own
instant messaging software, MSN Messenger, two weeks ago, only to
have AOL block access to its network for MSN users.
</P>
<P>
   Erika Jolly, MindSpring's vice president of consumer products,
says the AOL deal was in the works long before there was an MSN
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring will offer a co-branded version of AOL's Instant
Messenger to subscribers in the late fall. MindSpring already
offers its users Excite Pal messaging, which will continue to be
offered, although the AOL product will be the default service.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's deal is nonexclusive, meaning it can offer users
any or all instant messaging products including Microsoft's MSN
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can certainly talk to Microsoft,'' Jolly says. ``But we
don't want to offer confusing product options for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging allows users to ``talk'' to each other online
in real time. AOL pioneered the service.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly says adding AOL's Instant Messenger to its product
offerings is part of the company's ongoing strategy to make the
MindSpring home page a more compelling destination for current and
prospective users. The company has announced a variety of content
alliances over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the largest Internet access provider, with 17.6 million
members. The Virginia-based company is currently engaged in a
bitter war with Microsoft over instant messaging. AOL has blocked
access to MSN Messenger users, claiming that Microsoft is trying to
access AOL's proprietary network without its permission. AOL also
blocks access to instant messaging services from Yahoo! and
Prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the denials, some analysts think AOL seeks to corner the
instant messaging market by lining up big Internet service
providers like MindSpring and EarthLink.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AOL can go around and sign up all the second-level players
out there, there will be less and less of a market to pick off,''
PaineWebber analyst James Preissler told the Dow Jones News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Preissler said MindSpring and EarthLink realized they weren't
large enough to make launching a competing instant messaging
service viable, so they teamed up with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jupiter Communications analyst Lucas Graves disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake to see this as AOL lining up allies in its war
against Microsoft,'' he says. ``Their install base is so incredibly
large, with or without allies, they are the de facto standard. ``
</P>
<P>
   Mindspring shares closed at $28.81 1/4, up $2.81 1/4 on Friday;
AOL was up 81 1/4 cents to $84.75 and Earthlink rose $4.50 to
$41.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
