<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-?-?-BOS &LR;      08-06 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-?-?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Scientific Corp. announced a voluntary recall of one of
its medical products designed to clear clogged arteries, driving
its shares down 18 percent and causing it to reduce its projected
1999 earnings by 8 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company recalled its newest Rotablator systems after
discovering a defect in the products' brake system. The Rotablator
is designed to break up tough artery plaque deposits, and often is
used in preparation for angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific launched what it termed ``an intense
engineering investigation'' of the devices after the company
received six complaints of product malfunction _ one of which
involved a patient who died, though it is not known if the device
is related to the death.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they pulled the product ``within days''
of concluding that the brake on some of the Rotablators may not
adequately secure the guide wire as intended, making such units
unsafe for use.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the product during the first half of the year amounted
to about $60 million. Assuming no sales of the product in the
second half of the year, the company lowered its expected annual
earnings to $1.01 a share from $1.09.
</P>
<P>
   The recall will not impact an earlier version of the product
that is being sold in Japan, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Berman, president of Scimed Life Systems Inc., the unit
of Boston Scientific responsible for the device, said it will be a
matter of months until the Rotalink advancer is back on the US
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closing in on a fix to the problem,'' Berman said,
adding that the company is also considering resuming production of
the original model. ``We are working extraordinarily intensely to
get the technology fixed and back on the market as expeditiously as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rotoblator accounts for about 90 percent of the market,
company officials said, with very few competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific has recalled three other products in the past
year. ``There are more of them than I'd like or more than there
should be,'' said Jim Tobin, Boston Scientific's chief executive
officer. ``The issues that are underlying the events that occcured
are essentially training issues,'' and Tobin said improvements are
already in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The company also restated its 1997 earnings after discovering
accounting problems in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone hoped that there would be no more problems in the
future,'' said Sandra J. Hollenhorst, an analyst with Prudential
Vector Health in Illinois, after Boston Scientific named Tobin CEO
on June 1. ``You can't really attribute this to Jim Tobin's reign
since he has just been in place for three months. But this is
exactly the kind of thing he's trying to rectify.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
