<HEADLINE>
CAPE ELIZABETH RUN FULLY SUBSCRIBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As thousands of recreational runners trickled in behind a
stellar field of elite athletes at last summer's inaugural Peoples
Beach to Beacon 10K, race founder Joan Benoit Samuelson was almost
giddy with relief. After months of planning from, literally, the
ground up, she could finally pronounce her pet project _ a road
race in her hometown of Cape Elizabeth, Maine _ a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible day,'' said Samuelson, reminiscing
recently about the crystalline weather and thrilling
shoulder-to-shoulder finishes in both the men's and women's races.
``I think the spectators enjoyed it as much as the athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the numbers are any indication, a lot of those spectators
appear to have turned into runners. The field, limited to 4,000,
filled up more than two weeks before the race, which steps off
Saturday at 8 a.m. near Crescent Beach before winding its scenic
way, with occasional views of Casco Bay, to the finish line at the
Portland Head lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 3,000 entrants had already made it the state's
largest road race, a fitting tribute to the 42-year-old native
daughter who brought home a gold medal in 1984 from the first
Olympic marathon for women. ``The Maine runners are so excited to
have an event like this in their state,'' said Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year, the event _ offering $50,000 in prize money
_ has drawn some of the world's top athletes. Perhaps the chief
attraction in the men's field is Khalid Khannouchi, a Moroccan who
lives in New York. He hopes to become an American citizen soon, and
owns the eighth-fastest marathon time in history (2 hours 7 minutes
10 seconds) thanks to his win in Chicago in 1997. Also expected are
defending champion Johannes Mabitle of South Africa, who won last
year in 28 minutes 18 seconds; world record-holder (27:20) Joseph
Kimani of Kenya; William Kiptum of Kenya, last year's runner-up in
28:19; and American Todd Williams, a two-time Olympian at 10,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
   Heading up the women's field will be Derartu Tulu, the 1992
Olympic gold medalist at 10,000 meters from Ethiopia, and Hellen
Kimaiyo-Kipkoskei of Kenya, a close third last year in 32:18 behind
countrywoman Catherine Ndereba (32:15) and American Libbie Hickman
(32:17). Gwyn Coogan of Boulder, Colo., is also expected.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of women familiar to Boston fans _ Russia's Olga Markova,
the Boston Marathon winner in 1992 and 1993, and Poland's Wanda
Panfil, the 1991 victor _ also will be making the trip to Maine.
Panfil, who recently turned 40, will be competing in a strong
masters division against Ruth Wysocki, Hopkinton native Jane
Welzel, and last year's masters winner, Kim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Plascencia, who set the US masters record when he won the
division last year in 29:37, will duel with John Tuttle, who broke
the mark this spring with a 29:26 performance.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who crosses the finish line first, Camp Sunshine
will come out a winner. The camp, a retreat on Sebago Lake in
Casco, Maine, for chronically-ill children and their families, is
this year's designated beneficiary of proceeds from the race,
expected to be more than $30,000. Last year, $25,000 was raised for
Big Brothers/Big Sisters of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Samuelson will not run in her own event. Often a
winner in the masters division, Samuelson said she is too busy to
even think about competing, but doesn't really mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough not to run, but this is a sport that has given me
so much,'' she said. ``This is one chance to give back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
