<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS FROM MIDEAST CONNECT IN MASSACHUSETTS CLASSROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ The topic was stress management in the
classroom, but as the professor began his case study about a New
England school coping with the death of a child in a storm, his
students desperately wanted to read aloud from the pages of their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   An English teacher from Morocco politely interrupted to tell
how, as a young boy, he had watched as his school superintendent
was shot to death by a guerrilla who had invaded their classroom.
</P>
<P>
   A high school math teacher from Israel described how his
students were unable to concentrate for weeks after two schoolmates
were blown up by a terrorist bomb.
</P>
<P>
   And another English teacher, an Arab from the Gaza Strip,
recalled how one of his students lay gravely wounded on his
classroom desk, having been shot in the stomach three times by
Israeli soldiers who believed he had pelted them with rocks. After
a two-hour standoff, the teacher said, he slung the boy over his
shoulder and carried him to a nearby hospital, as explosives went
off around him.
</P>
<P>
   For 45 minutes, one teacher after another shared similar
experiences, their various accents blending into one. When it was
over, the professor, Paul M. Kline, a specialist in adolescent
mental health at Boston College, sat motionless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear,'' he said, ``that anything I say will be inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was but one snippet of an improbable dialogue among
19 high school teachers _ including Israelis, Palestinians and
Lebanese _ from seven Middle Eastern nations and territories that
stretched over four weeks, ending Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In coming together for a first-time symposium at Boston College,
their ostensible purpose was to swap methods of instruction and
curriculum. But those who had brought them here had another motive:
to demonstrate that the common bonds between teachers transcend
even the bitterest rivalries between their governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here not knowing what would happen between me and the
Israelis,'' said Zahia Khashab Fakih, 27, who teaches English in
Lebanon. ``I was worried, thinking, `How can I deal with people
whose army is occupying our country?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned in my stay in Boston is that people, between
themselves, can make deep peace,'' she said. ``If the peace process
is given to teachers to deal with _ and maybe to students _ then
they might make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of nurturing that very ideal, the organizers of the
program here have a far grander scheme in mind than just an intense
summer of learning. For three years, they have been working toward
establishing a fully accredited University of the Middle East, with
satellite campuses in every major capital in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Led by an Arab, Hala Taweel, 34, a doctoral candidate at Harvard
who is the sister-in-law of Yasser Arafat, and a Jew, Dr. Ron
Rubin, 28, a lecturer at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
who grew up in Israel and California, the organizers of the
University of the Middle East Project are trying to raise $100
million, with an eye on opening their first campus, in Morocco, in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taweel and Rubin took a first step toward making their dream
real by inviting the high school teachers here this summer. The 19
accepted were among 220 who had applied, their tuition paid almost
entirely by a collection of foundations. The organizers hope that,
upon the university's founding, these will be the first teachers to
recommend it to their students.
</P>
<P>
   To give them a taste of what the university might offer, the
teachers were immersed in the latest concepts of American
education. They were taught to resolve classroom conflicts through
role playing, to minimize lectures in favor of cooperative student
work, and to integrate the school psychologist into their
classrooms _ a prospect that many of the teachers found alien, if
not frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our culture, psychiatrists are associated with craziness,''
said Fatima Kotbi, 35, of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, they likely learned more from one another than
from a roster of professors assembled from Boston College, Harvard
and MIT.
</P>
<P>
   In late-night talks in the hallway of their dormitory, they
realized they shared the same frustrations, whether it was large
class sizes (as big as 60 in Egypt), rigid course requirements
(every English teacher in the Gaza Strip must teach Dickens' ``Hard
Times'' in the 12th grade) or low salaries (from as little as $300
a month in some Palestinian schools to $1,000 a month in Israel.)
</P>
<P>
   And all agreed that their students had been set back in their
learning by conflicts that have never seemed to abate for long.
</P>
<P>
   In relating what it was like to teach on the West Bank during
the period that Arabs refer to as the Intifada, the seven-year
uprising against Israeli occupation that ended in 1993, Frieda
Khayat, 32, said: ``We couldn't get the kids involved in the
teaching because they always thought school would be canceled for
the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke from her desk in a lecture hall on Wednesday, four
Israelis, three of them Jewish, sat just a few feet away. None
raised their voices to argue the relative merits of the various
combatants.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch that day, four teachers _ an Israeli flanked by a
Palestinian on one side and a Lebanese on the other, all sitting
opposite a Jordanian _ briefly debated whether Jerusalem rightly
belonged to the Jews, the Muslims or the Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation never got heated or personal. And the four
agreed that ultimately, they would prefer to set aside their
convictions and to compromise rather than jeopardize the
friendships they had formed over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli teacher, Judith Zilberman, who is Jewish, said she
had found herself empathizing with the diner to her left, Hani El
Akkad, a Muslim from the Gaza Strip, who spoke of being punched in
the stomach by an Israeli soldier when he refused to translate
something from Arabic into Hebrew. El Akkad, 39, said he had told
the soldier he spoke no Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to put myself in Hani's shoes and the Israeli soldier's
shoes,'' said Ms. Zilberman, a teacher for two decades, who was
reticent about revealing her age. ``It doesn't matter. They
shouldn't have hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the table, Mona Barghout, 32, a Jordanian whose family
had been forced to flee Israel at its founding in 1948, told Ms.
Zilberman how hard it would have been, just a month ago, to imagine
herself having lunch with an Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people around me,'' Ms. Barghout said, of her friends and
family in Jordan, ``they wouldn't accept me making contact with the
enemy. Peace, it's only on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet asked the following evening, at a New England clambake that
closed the program, what she would tell those same friends and
relatives upon her return, Ms. Barghout said: ``All people are the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, someone listening to the conversation exclaimed,
``Sah!'' the Arabic word for ``correct.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Moshe Peretz, a Jew, from Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
