<HEADER>
A8674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMM07-COX     08-06 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMM07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill would allow more tech exports
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. Phil Gramm came to Austin on Friday to
unveil legislation that would significantly increase the number of
products that U.S. companies could sell to countries such as China
or Libya while sharply increasing penalties for breaching national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a gathering of technology officials at Motorola
Inc.'s new campus in Northwest Austin, the Republican senator from
Texas said his Export Administration Act of 1999 would slash the
number of items the government reviews for export to unfriendly
countries from 10,000 to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, a free-market advocate and defense-spending hawk, said
his bill would apply a fundamental test to high-tech exports. If
hardware or software is easily available _ for instance, at
retailers such as Radio Shack _ or can be bought over the Internet,
the government cannot prevent U.S. companies from exporting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may like to prevent any potential enemies from getting it,
but the point is it's too late,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as simple as the formula sounds, Gramm said passage of
the bill he is sponsoring with two GOP senators and one Democrat
faces a difficult journey in Congress. The issue of export sales is
fraught with emotion and ideological debate because of concerns
that U.S. companies eager to make a buck are selling sensitive
technology that a potential enemy can turn against the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns were inflamed by the Cox report, released in May.
The study, by a bipartisan House group, concluded China stole the
technology for making nuclear bombs from the United States during
the Clinton and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's bill would not address such spying. But it would stiffen
the fines assessed companies that sell technology the United States
is trying to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm also cited pending investigations of Loral Corp. and
Hughes Electronics, the huge defense contractors that the Cox
report said sold China sensitive missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, such violations bring a penalty of $10,000,
which Gramm called ``throwaway for corporate America.''
</P>
<P>
   His bill would assess companies fines of $10 million or 10 times
the value of the technology sold. Individuals would face fines of
up to $1 million or 10 years in prison or both.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would simplify matters for the electronics industry and
Texas PC companies such as Dell Computer Corp. and Compaq Computer
Corp. They have complained that export restrictions proposed by the
Clinton administration could prevent selling desktop computers in
China, a huge and still-emerging marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Coalition for Responsible Export, which includes
Dell, has been following Gramm's bill, said a Dell spokeswoman. A
spokesman for the coalition was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's bill would renew the Export Administration Act of 1979,
which expired in 1994. Efforts to renew it before now have failed
because Congress and the Clinton administration have disagreed on
provisions. Gramm said the administration helped write provisions
of his bill.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsors include Sens. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., and Michael
Enzi, R-Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
