<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV08-B     08-06 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV08-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH CARPETBAGGER CAN CAST THE FIRST STONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 08, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to Tina Brown, the Trixie Dixie of
magazine publishing.
</P>
<P>
   In a century whose first half front-staged magazine editors such
as H.L. Mencken, the second half closes with the coronation of the
arch-English mistress of buzz, whose mix of slightly naughty,
slightly haughty celebrity gossip wafted her from the New Yorker to
the buzzily titled Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It was to one of Tina's Ikettes that the first lady unburdened
herself of some typically measured and coolly considered opinions
on the origin of the First Randiness. Child abuse, shrugged Hillary
to Talk; issues that still need to be worked on. Talk's exclusive
unrolled. Word then got out, artfully timed to build A-List
attendance at Brown's coming-out magazine party.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pavlovian fashion one now expects, the Clinton-bashers
leapt to keyboard and microphone. Veteran harrumpher George Will
was so upset that his Adam's Apple failed to clear the elastic
string on his bow tie. The New York Times's Maureen Dowd was
similarly scathing. One sure way to get dished, it appears, is to
unburden your soul to a competing scrivener.
</P>
<P>
   This buttinsky Arkansan lady is locked in a supposedly shredded
relationship with the Lil' Abner clone who rules the Free World.
And she has the gall to run for US Senate from New York, of all
places? That drives the journalistic establishment to new lows of
invective. Just who the hell does she think she is, this Senator
Clinton. Hiss-hiss-hiss. The first marriage is talk show fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I concede that Hillary is not everyone's cup of tea. Or
sympathy. I think she could find better things to do over the six
years following the next six months without hanging out in the
Senate cloakroom, watching Strom Thurmond, Jesse Helms and Trent
Lott clear their throats. But that's her decision.
</P>
<P>
   Thrusting herself on the kindness of strangers in New York _
Hah! _ is a brave move, if foolish by my lights. But it's her life.
With New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani playing the troll under the
bridge, she'll need her Billy Goats Gruff accent to cross the
Hudson. New York imposes a tong war on its politicians. But then,
if Hillary were a cupcake, she wouldn't be here today. I would pay
money to see Hillary vs. Rudy in debate. My money's on the woman in
the powder-blue power suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carpetbagger!'' is the epithet hurled most often at Mrs.
Clinton. Most of the hurling comes from tabloid newspapers owned by
gents from other countries. Rupert Murdoch (N.Y. Post) is
Australian by birth, Mortimer Zuckerman (Daily News) Canadian.
Every fourth person who lives in New York City was born outside the
United States. But carpetbagger is the issue, as fiercely
territorial Noo Yawkers who were born far from the Bronx assert
their Noo Yawkiness by trashing Our Lady of Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, moving as a child or even an adult to another state
should be no bar to holding office. And it is not just New Yorkers,
whose state of mind is more provincial than most, who want a
homeboy or homegirl holding up their end in D.C. But I think Mrs.
Clinton is equal to the task of explaining why her experience might
benefit all from Staten Island to Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   So, how many of our 100 US senators were born somewhere else
before lightning struck and they wound up in ``the world's most
exclusive club,'' as nobody actually refers to it anymore?
One-third of our solons, as it turns out: 22 elected as
Republicans, and 11 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Globe librarian Betty Grillo, who plumbed the fine
print of Congressional Quarterly's ``Politics in America 1998: The
105th Congress,'' I herewith present the honor roll. You'll notice
that many of the Sun Belt senators, Western and Southern, were
outlanders who migrated to new homes. They also tended to be
four-square for impeachment; we'll leave that to the grad student
theses to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Senators born outside the states they represent: Alaska's Ted
Stevens (Indianapolis); Frank Murkowski (Seattle); Arizona's John
McCain (Panama Canal Zone) and John Kyl (Oakland, Neb.);
California's Barbara Boxer (Brooklyn); Colorado's Ben Nighthorse
Campbell (Auburn, Ca.); Delaware's William Roth (Great Falls,
Mont.) and Joe Biden (Scranton, Pa.); Florida's Connie Mack
(Philadelphia); Georgia's Paul Coverdell (Des Moines).
</P>
<P>
   Idaho's Dirk Kempthorne (San Diego) and Helen Chenoweth
(Topeka); Indiana's Dan Coats (Jackson, Mich.); Kentucky's Mitch
McConnell and Louisiana's Mary Landrieu, (both born in Arlington,
Va.); Massachusetts' John Kerry (Denver); Minnesota's Paul
Wellstone (Washington, D.C.); Missouri's John Ashcroft (Chicago);
Montana's Conrad Burns (Gallatin, Mo.); Nevada's Richard Bryan
(Washington D.C.); New Hampshire's Bob Smith (Trenton, N.J.); New
Mexico's Jeff Bingaman (El Paso).
</P>
<P>
   The man Hillary wants to replace, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, hails
from Tulsa, Okla. Then there's Oregon's Ron Wyden (Wichita);
Pennsylvania's Arlen Specter (also of Wichita _ what's with
Wichita?) and Rick Santorum (Winchester, Va.); Tennessee's Fred
Thompson (Sheffield, Ala.); Texas's Phil Gramm (Fort Benning, Ga.);
Utah's Orrin Hatch (Pittsburgh); Virginia's John Warner (Washington
D.C.); Washington state's Slade Gorton (Chicago); West Virginia's
Robert Byrd (North Wilkesboro, N.C.); and Wyoming's Michael Enzi
(Bremerton, Wash.). Gasp!
</P>
<P>
   Twice as many Republicans as Democrats were born outside the
states they represent. Five were born inside the hated Beltway that
they all run against. But hectoring Hillary is a parlor game, no
matter where you hail from. If being from New York, or for that
matter being born in the United States, were requirements for being
a cab driver there, Manhattan would be denuded of taxis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
