<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-JOBS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jobs, wages grow beyond projections
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American companies created more jobs than expected in
July and boosted average hourly wages by 6 cents, the biggest
increase in six months, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate stayed near a 30-year low at 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Employers added 310,000 workers to their payrolls last month,
exceeding analysts' expectations by more than 100,000 jobs. It was
fueled in part by the first employment gains in manufacturing in
nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly wages grew 0.5 percent to $13.29 in July, from
June. Wages, however, are up 3.8 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Humphreys, director of Economic Forecasting at the
University of Georgia's Terry College of Business, was not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor markets are very tight. The unemployment rates are
at historically low levels, thus putting upward pressure on
wages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction firms and service companies were among those adding
jobs. Restaurants and bars increased employment twice as much as in
June.
</P>
<P>
   All retail employment grew twice as fast in the first half of
this year as in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While figures for July are not yet available for individual
states, Georgia expects to see a temporary dip in the number of
jobs when its data are released next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's numbers are likely to be off by about 17,000 to
18,000 jobs because of seasonal reductions in employment in the
state's school systems, said Sam Hall, a spokesman for the Georgia
Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the projection, Georgia remains a leader in the creation
of new jobs as more people, especially those who are prime working
age, move here.
</P>
<P>
   As of June, there were about 3.87 million jobs in the state _
about 30,000 more than in May and 120,000 more than in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of this year, the number of jobs grew 3.3
percent from a year ago. By comparison, 2.1 percent more jobs were
added nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta added 33,000 jobs during the first half of the
year, a gain of 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Georgia outperformed the nation,'' said Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   Hall added, ``Our job creation continues to grow at a good,
solid, steady rate but not as rapidly as we experienced in the
mid-'90s, when we really saw a boom in job creation.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality of jobs in Georgia and Atlanta will continue to
attract more people, said Mark Vitner, vice president and economist
at First Union Corp. in Charlotte, N.C. The strongest job creation
was in computer and data processing services, which saw a 19.6
percent increase in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of jobs being added in Atlanta is among the best
in the country,'' Vitner said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the jobs are in the higher-paying fields, such as
technology. By comparison, fewer people in Georgia are seeking jobs
in lower-paying fields, such as retail services. Vitner noted that
stores at the new Mall of Georgia have had trouble finding workers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Humphreys said, employers ``are having to pay more
to either bid workers away from competitors or bring workers to
Georgia from other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
