<SLUG> BC-DELAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeLay: Childhood events help him relate to HispanicsBy Jena
Heath
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressman Tom DeLay told Hispanic business and
political leaders Wednesday that childhood years spent in Venezuela
and waiting while his mother was detained at a Cuban airport have
helped him understand the experience of Hispanic people in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar Land Republican and powerful House majority whip spoke
to a packed dining room at a National Hispanic Assembly breakfast
on Capitol Hill. His talk before the assembly, an arm of the
Republican National Committee, marked another chapter in the
stepped-up Republican effort to woo largely Democratic Hispanic
voters. That effort has drawn increased attention with Gov. George
W. Bush's bid for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who lived in Venezuela because his father worked there as
an oil drilling contractor, told the group that he witnessed three
revolutions in the South American country between the ages of 6 and
14. And he described watching ``these really smelly, ugly
soldiers'' lining an airport tarmac in Cuba as Americans were
emptied from a plane. He said his mother was briefly detained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight for freedom in Cuba is sort of personal for me,''
DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, DeLay lauded Republican congressional
initiatives, bashed President Clinton and exhorted audience members
to encourage Hispanic voters to sign on to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   There are 7.1 million registered Hispanic voters nationwide, and
registration in Texas is expected to reach 2.1 million by next
year's general election, said Lydia Camarillo, executive director
of the Southwest Voter Registration and Education Project in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party still has a firm hold on the minority vote,
including Hispanics, a reality that U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla, a San
Antonio Republican, is trying to change. Bonilla also spoke
Wednesday, urging the audience to ``take a conservative message to
these neighborhoods'' and to support the American Dream political
action committee, which he heads.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC, formed in 1998 and based in Virginia, raised about
$200,000 in the last election cycle to support Hispanic Republican
candidates around the country, including Texas Railroad
Commissioner Tony Garza's successful race against Democrat Joe
Henderson. DeLay said Hispanic voters hold what he described as
Republican values, ``very pro-family, very pro-God, very
hard-working.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would likely describe their values the same way,
Camarillo said. She offered a gentle warning to DeLay and other
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to be important is their platform, their
position, their stand,'' Camarillo said of Republican candidates.
``Latinos can accept the Republican agenda if it stays moderate and
doesn't attack or use wedging issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
