<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sat., Aug. 7. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
GRAND CANYON (Grand Canyon, Ariz.) - Kaibab National Forest makes
its decision about the controversial Canyon Forest Village project
at the gateway to the Grand Canyon. Developers, who have the
backing of environmental groups, want to exchange for 400 acres of
land just outside the park entry-fee station to build hotels,
housing, etc. The other alternative is to keep the community of
Tusayan basically the way it is now and lease about 100 acres of
Forest Service land contiguous to the town to put in vital
services. Cities of Flagstaff and Williams have been very opposed
to Canyon Forest Village because they believe all the tourists will
stay up near the Canyon rather than in their cities. By MARK
SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRIMARY (Phoenix) - What if they gave a debate and nobody came?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question facing Arizona Republicans, along with those
in a handful of other states with early presidential primaries, as
planning for the political sparring matches cranks into gear. Party
officials blame the low interest on candidates who won't commit to
the debates and on an increasingly front-loaded primary calendar
that could cause the debates to pile up on one another. Officials
with the Arizona Republican Party, who want to host a debate on the
weekend prior to the state's Feb. 22 primary, are worried that it
might be overshadowed by a debate in Michigan, which recently moved
its primary up to fall on the same day as the Arizona election. By
KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (Undated) - The 20th anniversary of the great
athlete's death passed Monday, in much the same way as the 19
anniversaries that came before: Unmarked and unfelt, except in a
few scattered hearts. Mine was one of them. The great athlete was
named Thurman Munson, and for the first nine years of the 1970s he
played catcher for the New York Yankees. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ. Story
will move in the ``S'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
