u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCGEN-PARIBAS-NYT &LR;      08-06 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCGEN-PARIBAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANQUE NATIONALE MERGER BID SEEMS ONLY PARTLY SUCCESSFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE  
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Banque Nationale de Paris all but acknowledged Friday
that it was likely to snare only half the prize in its five-month
old struggle for control of two French banking rivals, Societe
Generale and Paribas.
</P>
<P>
   With Banque Nationale's tender offer set to expire at midnight
Friday, Banque Nationale chairman Michel Pebereau, the architect of
the bank's $37 billion hostile bid for its rivals, said he was
certain of obtaining ``indisputable power of control'' over Societe
Generale, the larger of the two target banks.
</P>
<P>
   Pebereau said Banque Nationale had firm commitments through
investors to get more than 50 percent of Paribas shares. But his
statement, in an interview with the French financial daily Les
Echos, fell short of affirming that Banque Nationale would receive
enough voting stock in Societe Generale to assert clear control.
</P>
<P>
   The official results of the tender, the largest ever in France,
will be announced Aug. 17, but bankers said that a fair idea of the
result should be known toward the end of next week, perhaps by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pebereau has asked investors to tender their shares in Societe
Generale and Paribas to Banque Nationale to enable him to create
one of the world's largest banks. Control of Paribas appeared all
but certain, but a hard core of Societe Generale shareholders,
including several major French investors, support the opposition of
Societe Generale chairman Daniel Bouton to the three-way link.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are said to favor the idea of a three-way merger to
form a strong French banking group. But the government is unlikely
to intervene to mandate such an outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
