<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-BOS &LR;      08-06 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRYNESS GRIPS THE EAST; DOMINO EFFECT FEARED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as US-Drought; a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON, Md. _ The dusty face of a natural disaster,
three-year-old Cody Smith scraped manure in his family's dairy barn
as a heat-stricken cow lay on a bed of hay and struggled to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, O.C. Smith, called in the rest of the herd,
his voice booming across dry fields of withered corn and brown
pastures with no grass left to graze.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the boy's grandfather, O. Clayton Smith, padded across
the parched earth to an underground spring that has helped five
generations of Smiths keep their farm from the auction block. The
grandfather kicked the steel top off the spring, and with eyes as
blue as the sky, he peered into an empty hole.
</P>
<P>
   No spring water. No rain. Only dust beneath a searing sun and
clouds of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   In this once-lush valley in the lap of the Blue Ridge Mountains,
the Smiths are like thousands of farmers along the Eastern seaboard
who are hostages of the Drought of 1999, the worst ever to ravage
some states and the most devastating for other areas since the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to hold on,'' said O. Clayton Smith, who is 65.
``But I've never seen anything this bad in my lifetime, and the
stressful part is, I don't know how much worse it's going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   With the crisis escalating, President Clinton Friday warned of a
potentially disastrous domino effect if farms, businesses and
communities continue to sink deeper into economic distress. Citing
federal research, Clinton said the drought is the worst ever for
farmers in Maryland, Delaware, New Jersey and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   For Massachusetts, Connecticut, New York and West Virginia, the
rainfall from April to July was the second lowest since the
government started collecting data in 1894, according to federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout much of this country, we have seen the worst
drought since the Dust Bowl days,'' Clinton said, referring to the
Depression-era drought of 1929. ``Such a natural calamity can have
devastating consequences, not only for farmers, but for small
businesses and communities that depend upon a thriving agricultural
sector, and for the electric power systems so vital to our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   As states throughout the East faced worsening drought conditions
and, in some cases, imposed unprecedented emergency restrictions on
water use, Clinton ordered his Cabinet to form a task force to
coordinate the federal response to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the mid-Altantic region, including Frederick County,
Md., where the Smith farm sprawls through the Middletown Valley,
already has been declared a federal disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do more,'' Clinton said. ``It is our duty as a
national community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths and thousands of other farmers are trying to hold on
until Congress provides emergency relief. Without rapid federal
aid, said O. Clayton Smith, he and many other farmers may join the
ranks of colleagues who have been forced to take drastic measures,
such as auctioning off livestock and land.
</P>
<P>
   Most farmers are also coping with the burden of plummeting
commodity prices. For Smith, that meant selling his wheat crop last
month -- the only good crop he expects to harvest this year -- for
$2.23 a bushel, down from the $4 a bushel he received two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drought couldn't have come at a worse time for farmers,''
said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, ``because they already are
receiving the lowest prices for their commodities in 20 or 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the clamor for help, Congress shut down Friday for its
August recess and delayed action until September on an emergency
aid package. The Senate last week passed a $7.4 billion relief
measure that would provide direct payments to farmers as
compensation for low commodity prices. But the Senate bill does not
address the drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a fix,'' Smith said. ``If we don't get some disaster
money here real quick, we're going to have to start unloading
cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Business is booming at the area's largest auction yard, in
Winchester, Va., where desperate farmers are selling their
livestock at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting hit with the double whammy of the drought and
the rock-bottom commodity prices, and they're saying it's just
impossible to stay in business,'' said Don Vandrey, a spokesman for
the Maryland Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Vandrey said, ``Our fresh farm land is at
greater risk of being sold off and turned into suburban sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Maryland, as much as 80 percent of farm crops have
been lost to the drought, with corn and soybeans the hardest hit.
The meager harvests have produced too little hay and feed to
sustain livestock, and many farmers, like the Smiths, already have
been forced to exhaust their winter supplies to keep their herds
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the pastures dried up, we have to feed the cows like we
would if they were walking around in the snow and couldn't get
anything to eat,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths already have spent more than $50,000 to replace the
winter hay and feed they have exhausted. They blame the heat and
drought for the recent death of a milking cow worth $2,500. And the
milk production from their remaining 100 cows has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the barn, where Smith's corn normally grows 10 feet
tall, the shriveled stalks are knee-high. The field where the
timothy should be six-inches tall is fallow. And the freshly mowed
alfalfa sits in paltry rows on a gentle slope, just a fifth of last
year's yield.
</P>
<P>
   If the Smiths hadn't begun pumping their well water for farm
use, their herd would have no water at all. All three springs on
the farm are dry. So are the creeks and the other waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, state officials said a week of drenching thunderstorms
wouldn't replenish the region, though no substantial rainfall is
expected anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet O. Clayton Smith rises every day at 3:15 a.m. for the first
milking, as he done since he can remember. His farm has weathered
many calamities through the years, and though he has never
confronted a crisis like this drought, he clings to a strand of
hope.
</P>
<P>
   As a recent visitor walked away from the farm, Smith shouted
across the crusted earth: ``I hope you get rich one day and I get
some rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
