</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT ADDS STEEL SECURITY TO TOWER OBSERVATION DECK AS REOPENING
NEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Steven Kraal is cq) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With a cagelike security enclosure almost welded
into place, University of Texas officials said Friday they will
reopen the tower observation deck to the public Sept. 16, almost 25
years after it was closed to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   From nearby streets, the new stainless steel lattice work that
envelops the 28th-floor deck can barely be discerned. Officials
said they strived to make the barrier conform with the tower's
architectural style and are convinced the sturdy lattice will
answer security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The deck, which circles the tower just below its gold-leaf clock
faces, was declared off limits to visitors in 1975 because of a
rash of student suicide leaps and the lingering memory of sniper
Charles Whitman's assault in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The 307-foot-tall tower, which was completed in 1937, used to be
one of Central Texas' biggest tourist attractions, affording views
of the surrounding UT campus; the nearby state Capitol and downtown
Austin; and Hill Country and farmland in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   But the view wasn't all that was lost when the tower deck was
closed. UT officials have described the tower as ``the most
important symbol of academic aspiration and achievement in Texas.''
In recent years, students argued that security issues could be
addressed, prompting a re-evaluation of the closure decision.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, UT officials began exploring the possibilities.
They budgeted about $600,000 _ most of which will be used to make
the deck elevator-accessible for the handicapped and others. Access
has only been available by walking up three flights of stairs from
the 27th floor, where elevators currently stop.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hoped to reopen the deck in time for the spring
commencement, but preparations took longer than expected. But now
that the work is almost complete, officials said the wait will have
been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a vision of Austin that you cannot get from any other
place,'' said UT assistant vice president Steven Kraal, who is
overseeing the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond providing a unique sight-seeing venue, the project is
helping revitalize the university's spirit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university believes it's important that we make this
facility accessible to the public. It's just too valuable not to be
open,'' Kraal said.
</P>
<P>
   For too long, he said, the tower has cast a negative image among
students and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't stop being a negative place until it becomes a
positive place. If people have the opportunity to have half an hour
or 45 minutes up here looking over the city, then I think that's
going to be very positive,'' Kraal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gorgeous view,'' he emphasized to reporters during a
preview tour.
</P>
<P>
   When the deck reopens, escorted tours will be coordinated by the
Texas Union, which will charge $3 for visitors. For now, plans call
for tours _ in groups of about 20 or 25 people _ to be conducted
only on weekday evenings and all day on weekends. Tentative hours
are 6 p.m. to dark on weekdays and midmorning to dark on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging from the interest, we expect every tour to be full
every time,'' Kraal said, adding that ``no one will be left
unattended up here for any length of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors might be more captivated by the view than by the steel
enclosure, which provides an almost unobstructed view of the city.
Architect Lars Stanley of Austin said he designed the metal
structure ``to fit in with the constraints that they had,''
including the historic building's design and its lack of large
elevators to deliver construction materials to the deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of small subtleties'' to the finished product,
Stanley said. For instance, fancy curled ends of the stainless
steel rods mimic the scrolled stoneworks that are part of the
clocks' decorative flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Another constraint was the design ``had to last a long time.
This building is going to be here forever,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   A final concern for designers was attaching the steel bars to
the building without permanently damaging it. The limestone face of
the tower's highest reaches are still marked by the bullets fired
at Whitman during his rampage. On Aug. 1, 1966, Whitman faced no
security screening whatsoever when he carried a locker of guns and
bullets to the deck and fired at people on the campus and streets
below. He killed 16 people and injured 31 others before being slain
by police.
</P>
<P>
   The tower remained open several years before regents sealed the
deck in the wake of nine suicide leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Because security remains a concern, Stanley said he researched
other lofty perches, including the Plexiglas-enclosed deck atop the
Empire State Building in New York City. Though secure, that design
was ruled out in favor of a more open airy concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want it to feel oppressive,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   The stainless steel turned out to be the least noticeable
material for the enclosure. Bars painted to blend with the
limestone tower surprisingly were more obvious than the glistening
steel rods, Kraal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stainless just kind of disappears,'' he said. ``If you're
on the ground looking up, it's very hard to see this. And it has
the added advantage of it's very low maintenance,'' Kraal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lighter it is, the less visible it is from the ground.
That was a primary concern. We didn't want to impair the impression
that the tower makes on the campus.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
