<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON DENOUNCES GOP TAX CUT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Offering a sharp condemnation of the tax-cut
package passed by Congress this week, Hillary Rodham Clinton
finished her fourth so-called listening tour of New York state here
Friday, and refused to immerse herself directly in a discussion
about the politics of next year's race for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a school here, Mrs. Clinton hosted a discussion on
education issues with a group of about 50 invited guests and an
entourage of reporters. She said that the Republican tax cut plan
that Congress passed this week was ``irresponsible'' and that it
would reduce education spending in New York state by $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's meeting took place shortly before Gov. George
Pataki held a news conference at which he expressed support for a
Senate bid by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and suggested
that another Republican, Rep. Rick Lazio, not run for the Senate
seat.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Pataki's remarks, Howard Wolfson, the spokesman
for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory committee, said: ``What the
Republicans do or don't do is up to them. Mrs. Clinton is going to
continue focusing on issues and listening to New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, however, Mrs. Clinton brushed aside a
reporter's questions about how she would draw distinctions between
herself and Giuliani, who is also considering running for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a campaign yet,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``There will
be plenty of time to talk about that. I want to talk about the
issues that people care about,'' she continued, ``and what we can
do to improve education and how to get more jobs and how to provide
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the personal life of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, a Republican candidate for president, had received less
scrutiny than that of President and Mrs. Clinton, the first lady
said she did not want to speculate on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But she quickly added that ``I don't think it serves our nation
or our political process well for people to have every shred of
their privacy taken away from them. I don't think that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton continued, saying: ``I'm speaking as someone whose
been through it so I have some experience in that regard. I don't
think that puts one more job in upstate New York; I don't think
that educates one more child.''
</P>
<P>
   Rochester was the third stop on Mrs. Clinton's listening tour
this week. In addition to Friday's forum, Mrs. Clinton attended a
$500-a-person fund-raising reception in Rochester for Rep. Louise
Slaughter. Two days earlier, she convened a discussion group on
local economic issues at a factory in Jamestown, followed by
another one _ focused on youth violence in schools _ in Buffalo on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the weekend in Washington, Mrs. Clinton is to
travel to the New York City area for two days, beginning with
another discussion in Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
