<SLUG> BC-BLUE-ANGELS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCH-HITTING PILOT PROVES WORTH TO BLUE ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the anonymous world of the Blue Angels pilots, they
call him No. 2, the right wing, who flies 36 inches off his boss's
wingtip at speeds where a tiny mistake could spell disaster.
</P>
<P>
   As the Angels' F/A-18 Hornet fighter jets scream across Lake
Washington this weekend, few spectators will know that No. 2 is a
pinch hitter, a former Blue Angel pilot called back two months ago
to help his old squadron mates out during their busiest time of
year. He replaces a pilot who was reassigned after he violated a
unit rule about relationships within the squadron, according to the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the new guy, Lt. Cmdr. Mike Dunleavy, 6 feet tall with an
inch or so of closely cropped black hair and white teeth, which he
brushes right before beginning a performance, a long-held
superstition of his.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has a face, a name, a call sign, a personality, what
it boils to is that he is No. 2, so long as he flies with the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me six flights before I was able to fly in public,''
Dunleavy said.``I was lucky enough to meet up with the team in
Montana, and we flew twice a day for three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to bang the rust off.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the Navy wants it: The Blue Angels fliers are
interchangeable, part of a precision team that is known for its
awesome aerials and its public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a little bit of growing pain,'' says No. 5, Lt.
Doug Verrisimo. ``But now we are back to where we were.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the six-day-a-week flying schedule for the past month
has contributed to their performance since Dunleavy's return.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers train together, travel together, fly together. In
their winter training, they learn each other's every move,
practicing maneuvers so they know every nuance of their performance
on any given day.
</P>
<P>
   As a pinch hitter, Dunleavy is an all-star, able to fly any
position in the squadron. After two years with the Angels, he was
rotated out in a routine move seven months ago and reassigned to a
fighter-attack squadron, ``The Blue Blasters.'' He was getting
ready to head to sea. Then he got the call, and now he is No. 2,
flying as close to the faultless show as he and the rest of the
team can get.
</P>
<P>
   Their moves, after all, are supposed to be automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' show is 45 minutes of tight turns, steep climbs and
frightening dives that require days of practice and concentration,
including meetings where every movement, every radio call is
rehearsed until each pilot has them memorized. That means few
distractions. It's flying and public relations, and all this stuff
about the removal of the last No. 2, well, the Angels say, let's
just watch the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two months behind us; now we just want to move forward,''
Dunleavy says.
</P>
<P>
   Even by Navy standards, unity in the Blue Angels is rigid _
after landing, the pilots exit their planes at the same time, walk
down the line of planes picking up each pilot before doing a
right-wheel turn, and only then do they break ranks and shake
hands, and even that looks pretty regulation.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe they are interchangeable, for as the men themselves
will say, they are all ``just pilots'' beneath the yellow flight
helmets and blue jumpsuits _ so it really doesn't matter, does it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
