<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABA-HUBBELL07-COX     08-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABA-HUBBELL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hubbell relieved Whitewater case resolved
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They investigated just about every detail of his
professional career. They charged him with federal crimes that
landed him in prison, bringing shame on his family and the Clinton
administration. They even asked him questions about Hillary Rodham
Clinton's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the American Bar Association's annual meeting
here Friday, Webster Hubbell stopped short of criticizing
independent counsel Kenneth Starr over the Whitewater
investigation. But Hubbell, the former Clinton confidante and
high-ranking U.S. Justice Department official, described Starr's
investigators as ``individuals looking for a crime'' rather than
knowing a crime had occurred and then investigating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have any candor left if I didn't say I think part
of the approach was political,'' Hubbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, 51, served an 18-month prison sentence after pleading
guilty in 1994 to federal charges that he stole more than $400,000
from the Rose Law Firm in Little Rock, Ark. This June, he pleaded
guilty to misleading federal regulators about legal work he
performed at the law firm, and to a misdemeanor charge of failing
to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent plea resulted in no prison time or fine, and
ended a nearly six-year independent counsel investigation of him
and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just beginning to sink in that it's over,'' Hubbell said
in a brief interview. ``It was all very painful, very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell's talk at the ABA convention marked his first extended
remarks since the resolution of his case.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell said that after he pleaded guilty and agreed to
cooperate with Starr's investigation, the Independent Counsel's
Office apparently did not want to hear his assertions that he knew
of no wrongdoing by President Clinton or his wife, Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it became my understanding ... they were going to have me
say something about wrongdoing on behalf of the president or first
lady,'' he said. ``Unless I did so I was not cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell said that the Independent Counsel's Office also made it
clear to him that, ``We're going to continue to apply the pressure
on you, your family, on your friends, until you break and tell us
something.''
</P>
<P>
   During one meeting, Hubbell has said, investigators asked him
for details on the first lady's sex life and whether she had an
affair with the late White House counsel Vince Foster, who
committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Hubbell said, adding that he was sure there
had been no affair. ``I thought that had no bearing or relationship
to the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   He still found some humor in his travails, saying, ``I may be
the only person who's flown on both Air Force One and `Con Air',''
referring to the planes that take federal prisoners from one
facility to another.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell recalled being taken from his federal prison camp in
Cumberland, Md., to testify before the grand jury in Arkansas, a
trip that required him and seven other prisoners on the plane to
stay over night in a metro Atlanta jail in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   After Hubbell expressed concern about his safety, federal
marshals allowed him to spend the night alone in the jail's
suicide-watch cell, the walls of which smelled of pepper spray. The
next morning, Hubbell recalled, as he was being chained together
with the seven other inmates, one prisoner, pointing to Hubbell's
cell and indicating how he had received special treatment, looked
at Hubbell and said, ``You must be one bad dude.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hubbell cracked a smile telling this story, it was clear
his re-emergence into the public spotlight did not come easily.
During his talk, his hands trembled and on one occasion he needed
to hold his water glass with both hands in order to take a sip.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell surrendered his law license in 1995 and expressed no
high hope of getting it back. After counseling federal prisoners
for three years, Hubbell said he is now looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in the last three years that I can
actually look for work and know that whoever hires me won't be
subpoenaed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
