<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WALLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE VOWED TO RETURN TO KNICKS, AND NOW HE HAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since John Wallace was unhappily shipped north
of the border in 1997, he vowed to return to New York. Less than
two years later _ and with more than a little help from the Knicks
_ the franchise's former first-round draft choice made good on his
word.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Wallace signed a mid-level exception contract with
the Knicks, a three-year deal believed to be worth $6.62 million.
The Knicks essentially acquired another low-post scorer to bring
off the bench, getting a cut-rate deal on a former Madison Square
Garden employee who never wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be back in New York,'' Wallace said Friday during a
conference call. ``This is where I wanted to be, in my mind, my
heart and soul. The whole time I was watching the finals, I wanted
them to win it. But I also wished I was there at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, 25, was traded to Toronto two seasons ago in a
three-team deal for Chris Dudley, who was then with Portland.
Wallace was the first of three first-round draft picks by the
Knicks in 1996. He was taken 18th over all.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace delighted Garden fans his rookie season, often scoring
in bunches during limited playing time. He averaged 4.8 points in
less than 12 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   He started 36 games his first season in Toronto, averaging 14
points and 28 minutes a game. But he averaged only 8.6 points, 3.6
rebounds and 16.9 minutes in 48 games last season for the Raptors.
The emergence of Tracy McGrady and the Rookie of the Year Vince
Carter hurt Wallace's chances to star. He eventually fell out of
favor with coach Butch Carter over playing time and Raptors
management over a desired contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond depth, the need for Wallace has more to do with the
Knicks' injuries and lack of a low-post scorer other than Patrick
Ewing or Larry Johnson. When Ewing was hurt and Johnson was their
only threat in the paint, the Knicks were hamstrung offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace can be a defensive liability, but his offense often
forces opponents to double-team him. He can be used at both the
small forward and power forward positions, which may lead to
reduced minutes for other players. ``I'm going to come in and work,
and whatever time I earn, I'll get,'' Wallace said. ``I'm not
locked into anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy welcomed Wallace's return by saying:
``Obviously, we've had a lot of injuries the last year, and
there'll be a quality player who won't be in the rotation. The
thing I like about John is, he will find his opportunities. He
doesn't mind competing for minutes; that's one of the reasons I
respect him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Knicks used their annual mid-level exception on
Wallace, the agreement means they are no longer interested in
Charles Oakley, with whom the Knicks met with in July about
possibly rejoining the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had four guys that we had targeted,'' Van Gundy said. ``We
would have been happy with any of the four. John was the most
interested in us. From the Aug. 1 date, we were trying to do
something. Most of the other guys we were considering were up in
their mid- to late 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   Interim general manager Ed Tapscott said that during its
free-agent deliberations, the team has been scouring the league
more for ability than just trying to fill positions. With 11
players under contract, the Knicks still have the $1 million
exception left to acquire another player. As most of the league's
salary-cap room is gobbled up by big-name free agents the next few
weeks, the club hopes to latch onto another bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, one of their first-round draft picks is back in the
fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we traded John, for us it was a necessary evil,'' Van
Gundy said. ``In no way did we want to trade him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
