<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-ELATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING IN A BIG WAY _ CRUISING TO MEXICO ON SUPERLINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFF LARSEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For your first cruise you might think a smaller ship would be
better _ less intimidating, more intimate.
</P>
<P>
   Well, my wife, Trish, and I decided bigger might be better. So
to cruise to the Mexican Riviera to celebrate both our wedding
anniversary and her college graduation, we picked Carnival Cruise
Line's newest and biggest ship, the MS Elation.
</P>
<P>
   The giant ship, based in Los Angeles, first set sail last year
and is the seventh in a series of eight 70,000-ton superliners that
Carnival ordered. It can serve more than 2,000 passengers per trip
and has a crew of more than 900. Big is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   After landing in Los Angeles, we were taken by bus to the ship's
moorage at San Pedro, where we quickly checked in at the terminal
and boarded the ship. Carnival agents assured us our bags would
arrive at our room just before or right after the ship was under
way.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little disconcerting when the ship set sail and one bag
hadn't arrived at our room. I fretted that a huge ship like that
wouldn't be easy to turn around to retrieve our bag, but it
eventually arrived as promised.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the first two days of the weeklong cruise sailing to
Puerta Vallarta. The day after that we sailed back up the coast for
a day in Mazatlan and then on to a five-hour visit to Cabo San
Lucas, a popular resort area on the tip of Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Our upper-deck ocean-view room wasn't as small as we thought it
would be ... sparsely appointed, but comfortable. When we wandered
up on deck, we also discovered that the ship wasn't crowded with
tanned retirees spending their children's inheritance, as many
prospective cruise customers envision.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation is what Carnival Cruise Lines likes to call a ``Fun
Ship.'' That label obviously means fun for kids as well as
grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the usual adult amenities such as bars, clubs, a casino,
workout areas, a jogging track, several Jacuzzis, restaurants and
entertainment centers, the company designed a 2,500-square-foot
``Children's World'' play area into the ship and has actively
solicited the growing family cruise trade.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of port, the first order of business was the mandatory
emergency life-raft drill, where passengers donned their life vests
and _ like a migrating herd _ stepped lively to the ship's muster
stations. Someone made cattle sounds during the drill, but
otherwise all passengers seemed to take it seriously.
(Surprisingly, later in the week the movie ``Titanic'' was shown.)
</P>
<P>
   Then the eating began. The food, no matter which dining area we
chose, was generally good. Pizza, served 24 hours a day, came in
handy between the regular meals.
</P>
<P>
   Trish particularly liked the soft ice cream and frozen yogurt
machines. I thought the juice maker was the most inventive machine
I've seen in a while. Just toss two unpeeled oranges down a funnel
and hold the glass under the spout and out came juice. Hey,
Carnival said it was a ``Fun Ship.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual sociological compatibility maneuver, Carnival
tries to match guests with like interests for the sit-down dinners
in two dining rooms, both with two seating times _ early and late.
</P>
<P>
   There are three sit-down dinner issues to consider:
</P>
<P>
   One: You're not required by laws of the open seas or Carnival to
eat the sit-down dinner every night. You can eat free pizza every
night if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Two: If you decide to attend the sit-down dinner every night,
you can change your seating assignment if you are unfortunate
enough to be seated with Homer Simpson and his family.
</P>
<P>
   And three: Even if you think you have already paid for it, the
sit-down dinner isn't exactly free. (I'll get to that later.)
</P>
<P>
   We lucked out and were seated with four very pleasant couples.
Two of them also were celebrating anniversaries. Be aware ... two
of the seven sit-down dinner nights require formal attire (dark
suit and tie for the men is OK).
</P>
<P>
   Elation passengers are encouraged to set their own onboard
activity schedules, and there is a long list of activities that
tries to cover most of the interests of the age groups represented
on the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the activities such as line-dance instruction and
aerobics are free. The list includes everything from bingo to
talent shows, singles parties, karaoke, disco dance lessons (ouch!)
and even a twist contest.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about hitting one of the singles parties to see if we
still
</P>
<P>
   had it after being married for 32 years, but decided to take a
nap in-
</P>
<P>
   stead.
</P>
<P>
   Mazatlan and Cabo San Lucas were a treat. Puerta Vallarta ...
ho-hum. And like the onboard activity list, we could choose from a
variety of different adventures such as snorkeling, golf and
sightseeing. Or we could just wing it on our own once we left the
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the passengers we talked to agreed the five-hour stop at
Cabo San Lucas on the return leg of the cruise was too short.
</P>
<P>
   Now, why isn't the sit-down dinner free? You paid for it when
you paid for the cruise, right? Well Carnival Cruise Lines suggests
you tip practically anyone even remotely connected to your meal ...
and handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line suggests you tip the table waiter, bus boy,
maitre'd and head waiter ... not just your waiter. For the table
waiter they suggest $3.50 per day per person, $2 per person per day
for the bus boy, and the sky's the limit for the maitre'd and the
head waiter. And cash only please.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised we weren't asked to line up to pay the captain
as we left the ship.
</P>
<P>
   And when you get back to your room after handing out all that
cash at the final sit-down dinner, Carnival wants you to tip your
cabin steward as well _ in our case, someone we never even met _
$24.50 per person for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, we slept well during our final night on board. We
were partly tanned, rested and ready to fly home. I was just glad
to we didn't have to tip the airline pilot, co-pilot and all the
flight attendants. I was out of cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
