<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-GREENLEY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barton `shark's eyes' haunts last person to meet him
 &HT;    By Francis X. Gilpin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ann Greenley hasn't slept well since last week, when
she became the last person that Mark O. Barton spoke to before the
mass murder suspect took his own life at a convenience store north
of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It was Greenley's automobile that Cobb County police say Barton
attempted to hijack at the Town Center Mall in Kennesaw, a few
hours after his Buckhead shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyes were cold,'' Greenley, 25, said. ``Every time I think
about it, it reminds me of shark's eyes. I think that's what let me
know how much danger I was in.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published in the Friday edition of the Marietta
Daily Journal, Greenley said she has been overwhelmed with
interview requests from news media. But she avoided most because
she felt the public should focus on Barton's 12 victims.
</P>
<P>
   Although her moments with Barton were harrowing, Greenley said:
``The people I pray for daily are the ones who got shot and the
ones who died.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenley was leaving the mall about 7:30 p.m. when Barton
approached and spoke to her as she reached into her purse for car
keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Don't scream or I'll shoot you,''' Greenley said.
Barton had his hand in a shoulder bag as he addressed her.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than get in her car with Barton, Greenley decided to try
to make a run back into the mall.
</P>
<P>
   As she sprinted, Greenley said she braced for a bullet in the
back that never came. She said she didn't turn around until she
reached the sidewalk. Barton was walking off, still staring at her,
and still concealing his hand in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Greenley asked a mall store employee to call police. Meanwhile,
at least two other people in the Town Center parking lot also
spotted Barton's green mini-van. A Cobb County police officer
tailed him along Interstate 75 to the Ga. 92 exit, where Barton got
off and headed west. He pulled into a BP station, and was blocked
in by the Cobb police officer and an Acworth officer. He shot
himself once in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The what-ifs are what are most frightening,'' said Greenley,
who is studying criminology at Kennesaw State University and was
considering a career as a victim's advocate even before that night
at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Her fiance, Curtis Brown, said he is grateful Greenley escaped.
They will wed in October. ``She's a hero, in my mind,'' said Brown.
``I couldn't have done it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
