<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8728 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIDENT-SUBS-SPI &LR;      08-06 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIDENT-SUBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIDENT SUBS MAY GET NEW MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS FLORIDA _ Cmdr. Greg Billy stepped around a gang
of sailors working on a piece of machinery and climbed up the
narrow steel ladder to the open hatch of the Florida, a Trident
missile submarine based at Bangor on Hood Canal near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ships are national treasures,'' said Billy, who has
commanded one of two rotating Florida crews since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The eight Trident missile submarines at Bangor are designed for
a single mission _ to wage global nuclear war if the United States
is attacked, or by their very presence to deter such a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida and three other submarines at Bangor may soon by
trading in their nuclear-warhead missiles and taking on a new
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being retired from lurking deep in the Pacific for
the contingency of nuclear war, the oldest four Bangor submarines
could be converted into cruise-missile ships that would be sent to
crisis areas such as the Persian Gulf, Korea or the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than carrying 24 Trident missiles with six nuclear
warheads each, the subs would be armed with up to 154
conventionally armed Tomahawk cruise missiles, under plans being
considered by the Pentagon and Congress. They also would serve as
the ``mother ship'' for up to 66 SEAL commandos using minisubs
carried by the larger vessel for surveillance missions and raids.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Navy Richard Danzig said the cruise missile
submarine proposal is ``an extremely attractive idea'' to Pentagon
planners since the converted Tridents would double the number of
cruise missiles available to a Navy carrier battle group.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise-missile conversion would save the four Trident
submarines from premature retirement, a Bangor official said. The
Pentagon several years ago announced plans to scrap the four
submarines beginning in 2003 as a result of lessening Cold War
tensions and new arms control treaties shrinking the size of the
U.S. and former Soviet strategic nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy report to Congress said it found ``no technical
limitations'' that would prevent the conversions from being
accomplished between 2003-05. Both the House and Senate this month
approved $13 million to continue studying the concept before a
formal Pentagon proposal next year.
</P>
<P>
   Billy and other Navy officials say the four Trident submarines
involved could serve for another 20 years after the proposed
conversion to the cruise missile role.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is even more attractive because the four submarines
are ``built and paid for'' and would fill in for surface warships
otherwise required to patrol in crisis areas, said George Behan, a
senior aide to Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The new cruise-missile configuration has been touted in defense
think tanks and the halls of Congress for several years after a
mid-1990s Pentagon decision to shrink the Trident submarine fleet
from 18 to 14 submarines to conform with arms-reduction treaties.
While the original plan called for retiring the Florida and sister
ships USS Ohio, USS Michigan and USS Georgia in 2003 and 2004,
experts have argued that the Navy should retain the submarines for
non-nuclear missions.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy estimates it can convert the four submarines for $1.57
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to the project involves existing and
planned nuclear arms control treaties between the United States and
the states of the former Soviet Union, the Navy says. Under current
treaty language, the 24 Trident missile launching tubes on the four
submarines would still count against the agreed maximum total of
nuclear warheads allowed on either side, even if the submarines are
being used for non-nuclear missions.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that the other two options include converting
the subs under the Start Treaty requirements by removing their
existing missile tubes and support gear, which would add at least
$1.6 billion to the total cost, or reopening negotiations with the
Russians over the technical counting language in the nuclear
treaties to allow the conversions using the existing missile tubes
without penalizing the U.S. for the ``phantom warheads.''
</P>
<P>
   If recommended by the Pentagon and approved by Congress next
year, the first two sub conversions would begin in 2003 with the
Ohio _ followed by the Florida 15 months later. The Michigan and
Georgia conversions would begin in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Billy is in command as the Florida is in the midst of a
five-week ``refit'' period for repairs after the sub's 50th patrol
in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the standard (repair) package,'' Billy said as he
stepped onto the missile deck and watched as a large dock crane
lifted a large metal container from a forward hatchway and
deposited it on the pier next to a growing stack of material being
removed from the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reloading stores, we're bringing in parts. We'll be
painting a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy said he and his officers are aware of the proposed cruise
missile conversion, but their focus remains on preparing the
Florida for its next nuclear patrol scheduled to begin in late
August. ``We're just starting our refit,'' the captain said. ``And
the clock is ticking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
