<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-GIULIANI-NY     08-06 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT ENTHUSIASM, PATAKI ENDORSES GIULIANI FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-MRSCLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By CLIFFORD LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to avoid a civil war that could poison the
Republicans' chances next year, Gov. George Pataki on Friday put
aside his antipathy toward New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
endorsed him for U.S. Senate and urged the other major contender to
abandon the race.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who had faced pressure from the national party to
end what had appeared to be a furtive campaign to undermine the
mayor, said Giuliani was the best candidate to take on the probable
Democratic nominee, the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he had asked Rep. Rick Lazio, a Long Island
Republican who had been planning to enter the primary with the
governor's tacit backing, to run only if Giuliani did not.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had said in recent months that he would drop out if Pataki
wanted him to, but Lazio's associates said Friday night that he
would not do so immediately. It was clear, though, that without the
support of Pataki, the party leader in New York, Lazio would find
that his prospects would quickly wither.
</P>
<P>
   While Pataki had never formally endorsed Lazio, Pataki's
longstanding reluctance to support Giuliani, and his praise for
Lazio, had signaled his preference. On Friday, though, Pataki said
it was time for Lazio to retreat to the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, we have to unite behind one strong candidate,'' Pataki
said at a news conference at his Manhattan office. ``I believe Rudy
Giuliani has earned the right to be that candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has not formally declared that he is a candidate, but
he has acted like one, harvesting more than $3 million in donations
and familiarizing himself with regions of the state unaccustomed to
visits from New York City mayors. With a Republican primary now
less likely, Giuliani can train his sights on Mrs. Clinton, in a
campaign that is expected to be one of the most expensive,
contentious and well-publicized in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   While Pataki commended Giuliani on Friday, the tone of the
announcement suggested that the endorsement was less than
enthusiastic. The governor called the news conference with almost
no notice and did not appear with the mayor, as is customary at
such events. In contrast, when Pataki threw his support in May to
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in the Republican presidential
primary, Pataki aides tried to orchestrate a lengthy build-up to
the announcement, and Bush spoke by satellite at the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Pataki made the announcement, Giuliani issued a short
statement thanking him, but did not speak to reporters. ``I very
much appreciate Gov. George Pataki's strong words of support,''
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement opens a new chapter in a relationship that has
rarely been warm. It was perhaps irrevocably scarred in 1994, when
the mayor supported the incumbent Democrat, Gov. Mario Cuomo, over
Pataki, then an obscure state senator. While they still tend to
utter niceties in public about one another, both men and their
aides are continually suspicious that the other side is engaging in
some strategy to embarrass or hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki and his associates obviously realize that if Giuliani
becomes senator, he will gain stature and might even be able to
challenge the governor for the leadership of the party in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and his advisers said he had decided to issue the
endorsement Friday because the Legislature had just concluded its
annual session, allowing him to concentrate on politics. Pataki
also wanted to head off Lazio before leaving for a vacation in
Ireland and France on Monday. Lazio had planned to announce his
candidacy on Aug. 16th.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's mentor, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who has also
feuded with the mayor, met with Giuliani this week, and their
discussions may have also helped bring about detente. On Friday
afternoon, D'Amato issued a short statement backing Giuliani in the
race, though its tenor left the impression that he too was giving a
grudging endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important than the maneuvering in New York were the
repercussions of the internecine strife on the national scene.
National party officials are eager to seize the Senate seat, which
is now held by a Democrat, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is
retiring. But they had expressed growing concern that after a
debilitating Republican primary, Mrs. Clinton would coast to
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
