<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There a Jail Term, Here a Wrist Slap &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is the right punishment, 10 years or 10 days?
</P>
<P>
   Glenn O'Hare, a former stockbroker at A.R. Baron, a defunct New
York brokerage firm, was one of 13 Baron brokers and executives
convicted of securities fraud in 1997 in cases brought by Robert M.
Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that O'Hare, who was a broker at Baron for four
and a half years, was part of a criminal enterprise that cost more
than 5,000 investors $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Stearns Securities Corp., while neither admitting nor
denying the allegations, agreed last week to pay $38.5 million to
settle the Securities and Exchange Commission charges that the firm
had contributed to the Baron fraud.
</P>
<P>
   As for O'Hare, Judge Edward McLaughlin sentenced him in March
1998 to three and one-third to 10 years in state prison. McLaughlin
said: ``These were not some trivial violations of some obscure,
pecuniary, overly conservative rule that some bureaucrat created.
The conduct here, to use an Old World expression, was in fact
sinful.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, last month, the National Association of Securities Dealers
disclosed its own disciplinary actions: it fined O'Hare $5,000 and
suspended him for 10 business days.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD said the vast difference in punishments was a result of
its lacking subpoena power and having to rely on customers who
offered their testimony to regulators. Furthermore, the review
period of the case was one year, not the four years of the firm's
operations that the district attorney scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Barry R. Goldsmith, enforcement director at NASD Regulation,
said: ``While these are certainly much less severe sanctions, we
can only bring cases on the evidence we have during the period.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing there are prosecutors like Morgenthau around. Without
his office's efforts, O'Hare might be making cold calls to this
day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Morgenson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New Way to Get the Goods &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two on-line financial services, Edgar Online and its competitor,
Free Edgar, battled it out _ until they announced merger plans in
July _ to provide investors with access to data on publicly traded
companies. Now another company, 10K Wizard, has entered the fray
and offers an even easier way to search the scores of Securities
and Exchange Commission documents and filings.
</P>
<P>
   Its service (www.10Kwizard.com) appears to provide something the
others cannot: free searching with keywords, including executives'
names, across every SEC document ever filed on line. Filings are
detailed, making it easy to find information on any of 68,000
public companies.
</P>
<P>
   The site was developed by Martin Zacarias, a recent graduate of
the Harvard Business School, and Kee Kimbrell, a former game
designer, who were frustrated by the existing online services.
Bypassing venture capitalists for now, they raised $600,000 from
friends and associates and founded the company.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias intends to keep offering 10K Wizard's services free
(like those of Free Edgar), supporting the site by advertising and
licensing deals rather than offering the premium, for-pay services
that Edgar is known for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laurie J. Flynn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Index of Their Own &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When seemingly every television commercial refers to a dot-com
address, it's hard to imagine a Rip Van Winkle who is unaware that
technology and telecommunications stocks are hot. But how hot?
</P>
<P>
   To answer that question _ and a host of others prompted by
changes in the world economy in the last 10 or 15 years _ a new
industry classification system has been drawn up the Financial
Times/Standard &AMP; Poor's-Actuaries world index.
</P>
<P>
   Indexes that track sectors are important to mutual fund
portfolio managers and some individual investors. ``There has been
a recent trend, especially in Europe, toward more `sector-based'
fund management,'' said a statement from Goldman, Sachs, which
helps compile the indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications, for example, used to be included in the
category ``utilities,'' but times have changed since the phone
company was known as Ma Bell. So now, telecommunications companies
have been moved to a sector of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Another addition is the Information Technology Economic Group,
making up 14 percent of the global index, and it, too, has
performed strongly.
</P>
<P>
   In a third change, health care, which has outperformed the old
health and personal care index, and pharmaceuticals, which have
lagged behind, are now in separate sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the indexes classify stocks into 10 economic groups,
39 sectors and 101 subsectors to provide detailed global sector
analyses.
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
