<SLUG> BC-ALA-SHOOT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shooting suspect was `tired of hearing rumors,' lawyer says
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIANA, Ala. _ Alan Eugene Miller, charged with killing
three people at two separate businesses in Shelby County on
Thursday morning, told one victim he didn't like what he was saying
about him before shooting him repeatedly, a prosecutor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During Miller's initial court appearance, District Attorney
Robert E. Owens Jr. told Circuit Court Judge J. Michael Joiner that
after Miller shot two people to death at Ferguson Enterprises, the
heating and air conditioning business in Pelham where he worked,
the 34-year-old trucker drove five miles to Alabaster to confront a
former co-worker at Post Airgas where he used to work.
</P>
<P>
   There, according to Owens, he told Terry Jarvis, 39, ``I'm tired
of hearing rumors about me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thereupon he raised his gun and struck the victim with
numerous shots,'' Owens told the judge, but allowed two witnesses
to flee unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's mother told reporters that her son had been laid off
from Post Airgas earlier this year because of ``economic
downsizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Joiner granted Owens' request that Miller be denied bail. Miller
is charged with one count of capital murder resulting from multiple
murders. Authorities are analyzing a handgun recovered from
Miller's car.
</P>
<P>
   During several interviews outside court, Owens refused to
speculate on what Miller might have thought people were saying
about him or what else might have prompted the three shootings that
came one week after Mark O. Barton shot to death nine people at two
day-trading stock firms in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the motivation is going to be exactly the same for all
of the victims,'' Owens said in interviews. ``What that motivation
is, we still need to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 10:30 a.m. hearing, authorities drove Miller less than a
mile from the county jail to the courthouse in an unmarked, dark
blue Chevy. The car rocked as Miller _ listed by police as
5-foot-11, 350 pounds _ exited the right-rear passenger door. He
didn't answer as reporters asked if he wanted to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Miller wore a prison uniform the color of a navel orange. He had
matching flip-flops. The resident of Billingsley entered the
courtroom shackled in shiny, silver chains secured by a padlock and
handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, Miller spoke only once. Joiner asked the
suspect if he understood an affidavit he was to sign that stated he
had insufficient funds to hire his own attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Miller said. He signed left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Owens told the judge that at least two people Miller encountered
at the businesses pleaded with the suspected gunman to be spared.
Owens said after Lee Holbrooks, 32, and Christopher Yancy, 28, were
killed at Ferguson Enterprises, another person walked through the
front door and saw Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't shoot me. I haven't done anything,'' said the witness,
who then ran, Owens said in court. The prosecutor didn't identify
the witness.
</P>
<P>
   At Post Airgas, where officials say the shootings ended, another
witness encountered Miller and asked not be killed. The suspect,
Owens said in court, told the witness where to seek safety. Miller
is scheduled for a preliminary hearing Sept. 1. After Friday's
proceedings, Mickey Johnson, one of Miller's two court-appointed
attorneys, said he had interviewed Miller's family Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no psychological basis for this, but he seemed
confused to me,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
