<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUT-HNS &LR;      08-06 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS TO PITCH $792 BILLION TAX PLAN TO AMERICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican lawmakers headed home Friday to peddle
their $792 billion tax-cut package to the American people,
beginning a political sales campaign that's sure to get nasty as
the Labor Day start to the 2000 election cycle approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing confidence that their appeal will resonate with
voters, Republican leaders plan to use their tax-cut pitch during
Congress' monthlong summer recess to more clearly define their
values in the face of Democratic criticism. Democrats say the tax
reduction measure is too big and ``reckless'' because it relies on
uncertain budget surplus forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a dramatic difference between Republicans and
Democrats in this capital city, and this is the dividing line,''
House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
declared, setting the stage for a veto showdown with Clinton when
Congress resumes work Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton, expressing a confidence of his own that
the public will reject the plan, said Friday that it ``will not
become law'' as long as he is president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who plans to help Democrats mount their own public
relations campaign against the GOP plan, said he favors giving as
much surplus money back to taxpayers as possible. But he stressed
that tax breaks should be given only after shoring up Social
Security, strengthening Medicare, and investing more in education
and defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a tax cut, but it is wrong to put the cart before
the horse,'' Clinton said, likening the Republican plan to paying
for a vacation ``before we pay the home mortgage and send the kids
to college.''
</P>
<P>
   The $792 billion measure narrowly approved Thursday by the
Republican-controlled House and Senate would amount to the biggest
reduction in income taxes in 18 years. Republicans insist that it
can be done if surplus projections of nearly $2 trillion in Social
Security taxes and about $1 trillion from other withholding taxes
hold and government spending is held in check.
</P>
<P>
   But they too are having a hard time resisting the urge to spend
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House and Senate acknowledge that their 2000
spending plans could be $21 billion to $30 billion over the
spending caps set in the 1997 budget negotiations with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, The New York Times reported that Republican leaders
have a plan to spend all of the $14 billion in anticipated
non-Social Security surpluses next year in hopes of maneuvering
Clinton into raiding the Social Security Trust Fund if he wants
more for his favored programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican strategy could set up another confrontation with
Clinton similar to the one in 1995 that led to two partial
government shutdowns if he vetoes any of next year's spending bills
and demands more funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will negotiate with the president, after he vetoes the
bills, on his knees,'' House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said
in the Times article.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a hard-line advocate of reduced government spending, said
if the negotiations yield an agreement to lift the spending caps,
then that would be OK with Republicans as long as the public
believes ``it's the president who's busting the caps, not us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seized on what he called DeLay's ``secret strategy'' as
evidence that Republicans are willing to play politics with Social
Security just to push their political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of nothing more cynical and irresponsible,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article caused a bit of an uproar on Capitol Hill, and
DeLay issued a statement saying his remarks had been ``clearly
misinterpreted.'' He insisted Republicans would keep spending next
year ``under the (1997) agreement levels'' and ``will never spend a
single cent of the surplus funds in the Social Security system.``
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``the choice'' is Clinton's. ``If he wants to
spend more on his big government programs, he will have to raid
Social Security to pay for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The dust-up over DeLay's comments was just a sample of what's to
come as Republicans and Democrats wage their public relations war
during the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have scheduled 618 ``town hall meetings'' on the
issue and a dozen or so ``tax cut rallies'' to help boost their
cause. They also have planned dozens of radio and talk show
appearances by Republican leaders, and some members, including
House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, plan to go on-line on
the Internet to ``chat'' about what's in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Armey told reporters the lobbying effort is designed to make tax
cuts ``the topic of dinner conversation'' all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are trying to encourage a television and radio
advertising campaign funded by outside groups with a stake in the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference Chairman J.C. Watts of Oklahoma said
the monthlong Republican effort would be divided into four themes,
beginning with explanations of how the package would help seniors
and ensure continued economic growth. The last two weeks of the
campaign, he said, would focus on the benefits that women and
families can expect to receive, including credits for education and
child care, tax rate reductions, and the elimination of the
so-called ``marriage penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very important over the next 30 days that we
drive this message ... and let people know what's in this tax
package,'' Watts told reporters Friday. ``We've go some selling to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts and other GOP leaders have handed out assignments to many
of their colleagues who will travel the country speaking about
provisions that they helped write into the bill. Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, for example, will take the lead in pushing the
benefits that would come from doubling the standard deduction for a
married couple filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, she said elimination of the
marriage penalty is ``our highest priority.'' She called the
current law, which makes married couples pay more than they would
by filing separately, ``a terrible inequity.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Ed Goeas said Republicans can expect to win
over a lot of Americans, even those who now side with Clinton's
approach to handling the projected surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that most Americans believe the surplus
should be used to boost Social Security and Medicare, and invest in
new education programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Goeas said the good news for Republicans is that polling
also indicates that ``in their gut (Americans) think they should
get a tax cut and they think they deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Republicans will have to be careful not to allow their
plan to be painted as a boon for the affluent and big corporations
at the expense of the lower-income earner, an argument that the
Democrats plan to make in their counter offensive.
</P>
<P>
   That argument already has gotten a boost from a few moderate
Republicans, including Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who says the
bill would reward special interests immediately with tax breaks but
would delay most reductions for average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a candidate for the Republican presidential nomination,
trashed the bill during a floor speech last week because he said it
complicates the tax system and would sunset in 2009 because
Republicans really are concerned that anticipated surpluses may not
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   And even Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading contender for
the Republican presidential nomination, favors an approach that his
aides say would be tilted more toward giving lower-income Americans
a larger share of the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Goeas stressed that while Republicans may differ among
themselves about how to cut taxes, it's important that they fight
for their philosophy of returning ``a balanced budget dividend'' to
taxpayers, regardless of their income level, in order to keep their
conservative base happy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans plan to send their tax bill to Clinton to sign
or veto when they return after Labor Day. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., said told reporters as he left town Friday
that he still believes that ``miracles can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in the hands of the American people what happens
with this bill,'' he said. ``It will be up to the people during the
month of August to...express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they will do that,'' he added, ``the president will sign
this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 2023EDT &QL; 
