<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EATON-BO     08-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EATON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL'S NEW TOUGH-GUY APPROACH COULD EARN EATON PRO BOWL BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Chad Eaton is one of the funniest people on
the New England Patriots. At the same time, he is one of the most
serious. He has taken a no-nonsense approach in raising his playing
status from practice squad to starter, and this season he could
take his game to the next level: the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he needs to be pushed if he's going to raise the bar,
so he likes what's happening at training camp, where head coach
Pete Carroll has taken the reins away from the veteran players and
assumed the role of leader himself.
</P>
<P>
   This training camp has been tougher than what Eaton had been
accustomed to. Tougher than under Bill Parcells, and definitely
tougher than under Carroll the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton may be a little biased, because he's always been a Carroll
booster even though it was the Parcells regime that brought him to
New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we were given some leeway, we took things for
granted,'' said Eaton. ``Pete had to toughen up. I love it. Instead
of the 1s going up against the 2s, the 1s get a better look against
the 1s. You don't have that confidence of beating up on the 2s now.
You have to do what you have to do against the 1s. We've had seven
straight days of double days. he's beating on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton has been lined up against No. 1 pick Damien Woody every
day except the first day of camp, when Carroll wanted to let the
center out of Boston College break in gradually, At Saturday's
intrasquad scrimmage at Foxboro Stadium, one of the battles that
Carroll will be focusing on will be Woody vs. Eaton. It'll be a
huge test for the rookie, because Eaton has become one of the best
nose tackles in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beat him up. Beat him up. That's all they say to me,'' said
Eaton about the instructions he's been receiving from the coaching
staff concerning his one-on-ones against Woody.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid has made vast strides. Sometimes I get into my stance
and I say, `What am I gonna do next? He stopped that move, and he
stopped this one; now what? I only have three.' He's definitely one
of the most improved guys in the last seven days. Everyone says we
don't have Dave Wohlabaugh, but I'm telling you, people aren't
going to be saying that because this guy is going to be a good
player for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton thinks it's been the approach of the coaching staff that
has brought Woody along so quickly. Carroll is taking that
1s-vs.-1s approach around the practice field, also lining up
cornerback Ty Law against receiver Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's tough new approach has filtered down to his
assistants. Offensive line coach Dante Scarnecchia has been all
over his charges; Friday, for example, the smoke was coming out of
his ears when Damon Denson showed improper technique on a play.
Scarnecchia has also been all over Woody. And Carroll clearly
approves, knowing that his new line coach needs to light a fire
under an underachieving unit that will have to improve its run
blocking to spring loose a Robert Edwards-less backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Will the tough new approach work? That remains to be seen. Eaton
buys into the New Carroll, and he says all the players he's talked
to about it agree. When Carroll cut one player for being late for
his physical and another for being too overweight, said Eaton, that
sent a clear message to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're puppets,'' said Eaton of the players. ``If there's water
over there and he says you can't drink it, we're not going to drink
it or you'll be out of here. Some guys will, and those guys won't
be here. He can make the change. This is the best I've seen Bruce
Armstrong look under anyone. A lot of guys like the physical, new,
long practices because we need that to knock some sense into us.
We're a talented team, and we need to be on the edge at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton doesn't think the change in Carroll is forced. He thinks
it's a natural process for a coach who hasn't quite gotten it done
in a kinder, gentler way. ``You know why he changed,'' said Eaton.
``Everybody's job is on the line, from head to toe _ the players,
front office, personnel staff. He had to change it. I think it is
natural. He's been around such good teams he knows what it takes to
win. He came to this team, and he thought since they went to a
Super Bowl they must know what they're doing. Apparently we didn't.
So now we have to pull back and take control of these guys because
they don't know how to get it done on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has had a lot of bad luck. When you lose (Willie)
McGinest, Glenn, (Ben) Coates, and (Drew) Bledsoe, I don't think
anyone is gonna feel real good about themselves. Taking this team
to the playoffs even after that terrifying loss to New York and
then Jacksonville proved that you can only listen to team leaders
for so long, but you have to get the leadership from the head
coach. He's the kind of guy who can come back and modify things,
and the guys will listen to him. I think guys have listened to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has tried to stay away from the topic of his change in
approach. Asked about how he's changed, he said, ``I don't know
what it is. Like I told you before, I think as you grow with your
team, and the situations arise where you're not happy with the
results, you'd better adapt and you'd better adjust, and if that's
what it is, then that's what this is. We're coaching very hard.
We're trying to demand, at all times, everything these guys have to
give to this team. I'm just coaching everything I have to coach,
and I'm having a blast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
