<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-PUMP07-COX     08-06 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-PUMP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With outside help, beat goes on for heart patient
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two halves of what amounts to Kenneth Collins's
temporary new heart rest atop his abdomen, making a steady
click-click, click-click as they perform the work his actual heart
no longer can do.
</P>
<P>
   A balloon in his Emory University Hospital room declares: ``When
God closes a door He opens a window.'' In Collins's case, the
window is a biventricular assist device, essentially two external
heart pumps, that for the last 11 days has kept the 57-year-old
Lawrenceville (Ga.) resident alive until he can receive a heart
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is the thought to be first person in Georgian to be
supported by a dual heart pump system since its 1995 approval by
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. Emory only recently acquired
a Thoratec Ventricular Assist Device (VAD) through a $60,000 grant
provided by the Carlos and Marguerite Mason Trust, a private
Georgia foundation that supports organ transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my heart,'' Collins says, putting his hand on the
machinery pulsating beneath his hospital gown. When he lifts the
gown, vistors can see blood pulsing in and out of each fist-sized
device. Crimson, the color of oxygen-rich blood, circulates through
the pump on his left side; dark brown, oxygen-depleted blood fills
the pump chamber on his right.
</P>
<P>
   Even though mechanical devices to assist the failed pumping
chambers of the heart have been around for nearly two decades, it
is still relatively rare for patients to receive two such devices
while awaiting transplant. Most can get by with a single device
that takes over the job of the heart's left ventricle, the main
pumping chamber that pushes oxygen-rich blood to the rest of the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' heart was so heavily damaged, doctors determined, that
he needed a second device to support the heart's right ventricle,
which pushes blood returning from the body to the lungs so that it
can absorb oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Inch-thick tubes carrying compressed air snake out from beneath
his gown and lead to a humming console that powers the pumps doing
the heart's work. The big machine is vaguely reminiscent of a hotel
ice machine, covered in dials and digital displays. The dials
twitch slightly with every mechanical heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   A purple rubber octopus, bought by Collins's physical therapist
at a truck stop, dangles from the console's handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just something to make me smile,'' Collins says. ``We're
talking about adding a Big Gulp cup, maybe a rear view mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   That he can not only smile but talk, laugh, eat and walk is
remarkable. Two weeks ago, Collins suffered a massive heart attack
and went without treatment for at least 36 hours. The resulting
damage from lack of oxygen to the heart muscle was so devastating
it left him with a barely functioning heart.
</P>
<P>
   For a day and a half he refused to believe he was having a heart
attack. He had never had heart trouble and his symptoms didn't fit
the classic description of chest pains; he thought he merely had
indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   His discomfort was severe enough to wake him in the middle of
the night, though, and failed to abate with Tums and aspirin. By
morning he still felt pressure in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have gone at that time to the emergency room,''
Collins says. Instead, he tried to dismiss the sensation and washed
his wife Alice's car.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day at a party, he had to lie down. Other guests,
noticing how pale and drawn he looked, urged him to go to the
hospital, but Collins refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pounding on his chest, saying `I can take care of this.
Besides, I got to go to work in the morning,''' Alice recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Collins did show up for work the following morning at Savin
Corporation's Norcross (Ga.) warehouse, where he prepares equipment
for delivery. But it wasn't long before he checked into Gwinnett
Medical Center in Lawrenceville.
</P>
<P>
   There, doctors affirmed what everyone but Collins had suspected.
Furthermore, they discovered his heart was operating at only 15
percent of normal function. The only option was a heart transplant.
A suitable donor heart wasn't available and without one he would
almost surely die.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 days previously, doctors at Emory University had
completed training in Pittsburgh in the use of the Thoratec VAD.
Heart pump technology isn't new, but Emory purchased a Thoratec
only a few months ago, said Dr. J. David Vega, director of Emory's
heart lung transplant program.
</P>
<P>
   A tube inserted into the patient's atrium, or upper heart
chamber, draws blood into a sac constructed from a special
polyurethane material and encased in the external pump chamber. A
sensor detects when the sac is full of blood, and the blood is
pumped back through the patient's ventricle.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, a VAD can support a patient indefinitely; the record
is 515 days for a patient at a German hospital who eventually
received a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was so ill he didn't realize he had been transferred to
Emory until he awoke two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a dying man going into surgery,'' Alice says. ``When we
saw him afterward, we were all just standing there with our mouths
open and saying, `He looks so good! He looks so good!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has since recovered sufficiently to move from intensive
care to a regular hospital room. He exercises daily, alternating
weight training with treadmill walks, all the while still tethered
to the console that powers the devices. Doctors hope he will be
able to build up his strength for the transplant they hope to
perform soon. Because Collins has virtually no heart function, he
has been moved up to the top of the heart transplant waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The dual VAD means he'll actually be in better condition than
many transplant candidates. In 1997, 131 heart transplants were
performed in Georgia, according to the United Network for Organ
Sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients that are supported by the devices do better with
transplants, because oftentimes you're able to rehabilitate the
patients before surgery,'' Vega says. ``With the devices, his heart
function is `normal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
