<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-RECESS-ART-N     08-06 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RECESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE IS SET FOR AUTUMN SHOWDOWN BETWEEN CONGRESS AND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With passage of a $792-billion tax cut secured,
Congress left for its August recess early Friday and set the stage
for a high-stakes autumn confrontation with President Clinton over
the nation's fiscal priorities in the new era of federal surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over how to divide the expected $3-trillion windfall
among tax cuts, federal programs and debt reduction through the
next decade is the most far reaching of many ideologically charged
policy disputes expected to come to a head in the fall. Others
include debates over gun control, regulation of managed care and an
overhaul of the campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   On one of those issues, managed health care, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert on Friday tried to divide a group of Republican
dissidents by pledging to bring to the House floor a bill that will
include some expansion of the right to sue. His decision marked the
first time Republican leaders have put forward such a provision,
and it created a rival bill to one agreed to Thursday by Republican
rebels and House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, with the razor-thin margin in the House
heightening the partisan competition, the two parties in Congress
have put less focus on legislating than on sharpening their
differences for the 2000 campaign. And Republicans believe their
tax cut will help define their identity next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear whether the president and Congress will be
able to reach some grand compromise on tax cuts, spending, Medicare
and perhaps health care legislation after Clinton makes good on his
promise to veto the Republican tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   In August both parties expect to wage a battle for public
opinion. Republicans said they would hold town meetings across the
nation to showcase different aspects of their tax cut, which would
be largest since 1981, and contains elements designed to appeal to
an array of constituency groups from social conservatives to women
to business.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats planned their own appearances to highlight their call
for some of the surplus to be used to overhaul the Medicare system,
the federal health insurance program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sounded the Democratic rallying cry Friday, by once
again vowing to veto the Republicans' tax cut.``I am disappointed,
though not surprised, that the majority party in Congress has
chosen to pass its massive tax cut, one that plainly would damage
our economic future,'' Clinton said at the White House before
leaving for Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ensure the American people, because this tax cut
will not save and strengthen Medicare, because it will not add a
day to the Social Security trust fund, because it will not pay down
the debt and pay if off for the first time in 150 years, this tax
cut will not become law,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, who see the tax cut as the crown jewel of their
legislative program, predicted that their bill would resonate with
the American people and that public opinion would force Clinton to
embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said that if Clinton vetoes
the bill, ``it will be the strongest indication so far that he is
entering the phase of being a lame duck, because it will say to the
Congress, the American people, `I don't care what you say or do,
I'm going to veto this and I'm not going to work with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a far smaller tax cut of $250 billion, and
prefers to use some of the surplus to expand Medicare and increase
spending on such domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the escalating rhetoric, some Republicans believe that
Clinton, with less than 18 months remaining in his presidency, will
want to burnish his record. That yearning, they say, will lead him
to strike a grand bargain with Congress, where Republicans will get
large tax cuts in exchange for the new Medicare prescription drug
program that he has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got one more year,'' said Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla.,
``He's run his last campaign. He would like to have a good tax cut
and some good reforms. I don't know how to say it without sounding
cliche. He's playing for history.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats counter that Clinton considers the healthy economy his
proudest accomplishment and that he will not strike a compromise
that does not begin to pay down the debt. ``They are misreading
what is motivating the president,'' said House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt of the Republicans. ``What motivates him is that he has
achieved a very good economy and he has made some real strides on
crime and education. And he doesn't want to make a deal that would
compromise or jeopardize those accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another factor this year that provides an incentive for
stalemate. During the days of deficits, an inability to act meant
the deficits grew. But this year if the parties cannot agree on a
tax cut, the surpluses automatically go toward paying down the
nation's $5.6 billion accumulated debt. So both sides say it might
not be so bad if they reach no agreement and take their competing
visions into the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that we've done something if we've done
nothing,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond fiscal issues, the fate of other high profile legislation
is also unclear. Many of the topics on the fall agenda _ campaign
finance overhaul, managed care regulation and gun control _ are
favorite issues of the Democrats. Republicans view these
confrontations as ones they cannot win, but will try to dispense
with them with minimal damage.
</P>
<P>
   So they will hope to do as little as possible while Democrats
will be leery of accepting weak compromises.
</P>
<P>
   A signal of the intensity of the struggle came Friday when
Hastert and other Republican leaders agreed just before 2 a.m. to
allow a managed care proposal, which is being assembled by Reps.
Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and John Shadegg, R-Ariz., to move forward in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision was prompted by Thursday's announcement by
dissident Republicans that they had reached agreement with House
Democrats on comprehensive legislation. They predicted they would
rally a majority of the House around their bill.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, a family physician, and Shadegg were still drafting
their rival measure, which was expected to be similar to the the
bipartisan plan. But Coburn has said that he wants to keep the
right to sue provisions more limited than in the bipartisan
measure. He would require patients to prove they were injured
before they could sue.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the second bill created an even fiercer fight
for perhaps 20 to 30 Republicans who could decide what kind of
managed care bill passes the House. But Democrats were expected to
oppose this version because it would contain a variety of tax
credits meant to help the uninsured get coverage. That would likely
include tax free medical savings accounts, which Democrats oppose,
saying such accounts would draw the healthiest and wealthiest out
of the insurance pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
