<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKEL-DEALS-2TAKES-     08-06 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-DEALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD SUSPECT HOPED EXPANDING HIS EMPIRE WOULD PROTECT HIM FROM
AUTHORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN and KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly seven years, say the authorities, Martin Frankel
quietly ran one of the biggest insurance scams in history, milking
the assets of Southern insurance companies he controlled to pay for
a self-indulgent life style in a Greenwich, Conn., mansion,
complete with a virtual harem of female assistants, corporate jets
and private chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early last year, the reclusive financier went on a global
quest to turn his hundreds of millions into tens of billions. In an
outpouring of ambition, Frankel drew scores of new people into his
dealings, including some legendary characters in the world of
financial fraud, to help him expand his empire.
</P>
<P>
   He boasted to acquaintances that he was exploiting huge, new
business opportunities but confided to intimates that the bold
plans had a more essential purpose: keeping him out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I become big, they won't touch me,'' Oksana Boudanaval, a
20-year-old Russian woman who lived with Frankel in Greenwich,
recalls Frankel telling her as they relaxed in his office one
evening last summer. ``If you have 10 computers and take 5, anyone
can notice,'' she remembers him saying. ``If you have 100 and take
10, no one can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now clear that Frankel's helter-skelter attempt to expand
his empire into a pyramid of interlocking companies and charities
had the opposite effect, kindling regulators' suspicions and
accelerating his demise.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months since he fled overseas with as much as $350
million in insurance company money, the outlines of Frankel's story
_ a financial fraud that lasted for almost a decade, hastily forged
ties to the Vatican, a rush to convert illicit profits into
precious gems to finance life on the lam _ have come into focus.
But as investigators and Federal prosecutors question witnesses and
obtain records, they find themselves examining the roles of a much
larger cast of characters than initially known _ most of whom
appeared on the scene in the final, chaotic months.
</P>
<P>
   For example, associates say that in the last year of his scheme,
Frankel came to rely on Thomas Quinn, a long-time stock-fraud
veteran whose criminal record dates to Frankel's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are also examining how Antonio Greco, a
self-styled detective who has trod the line between law enforcement
and the criminal underworld, may have played a role in Frankel's
dealings in recent months. Long before having become involved with
Frankel, Greco had served time in several countries including
Spain, where he was charged with having ties to international drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   As he struggled to stave off discovery, Frankel sought allies in
Italy, chased insurance assets as far away as Nicaragua and
England, and spent lavishly to woo so many consultants,
deal-makers, bankers, lawyers, accountants, and public-relations
experts that some people who have studied his operation think he
may have had an elaborate plan to confuse people.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, this obsession with growth did him more
harm than good. His painstakingly negotiated link to the Vatican
worried state insurance regulators instead of appeasing them. The
offshore shell companies he set up made his money look dirty, not
clean. And, in his final weeks in the United States, Frankel
complained to Ms. Boudanaval and another of his lovers that some of
his newly recruited business partners had turned against him.
</P>
<P>
   Though Frankel did almost everything on a scale that dwarfs
other insurance frauds, a final binge before being busted is not
unusual. ``It usually happens when they begin to feel a little bit
of pressure _ they start getting grandiose ideas about expanding to
recoup the money they owe,'' said Stuart Allen, a former criminal
investigator for the Securities and Exchange Commission who now
works as a private detective. ``But the bigger it gets, the more
certain it is the bubble will burst.''
</P>
<P>
   To some investigators, the surprising thing is that Frankel's
ventures remained intact for so long. A failed fund manager from
Toledo, Ohio, Frankel was banned for life from stock trading by the
SEC after elderly investors complained that he absconded with their
money. Even as the SEC was concluding that case, he began, in late
1991, to amass a string of small, failing concerns in the South
that specialized in providing burial insurance to people of little
means.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he ran his companies on a shoestring. He had one man,
John Hackney, in charge of the companies' operations, based in
Franklin, Tenn. Frankel claimed to be investing the assets of those
companies. Investigators now suspect he was siphoning off millions
to support an increasingly lavish life in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance regulators in the states where he did business never
fully caught on. But in early 1998, Tennessee officials began
asking some pointed questions about his investing style and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   That's when he decided to get big. Frankel emerged from
seclusion and began working with people he thought could help him
grow quickly. The most important contact Frankel made was Thomas
Corbally, a 78-year-old business consultant who often recruited
clients for Kroll &AMP; Co., a leading private investigation agency,
and has a network of friends on both sides of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The two met around Memorial Day 1998 and became fast friends.
Soon after, Corbally began boasting to potential business partners
of his ties to a ``multi-, multibillionaire'' whose trading prowess
was the envy of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   While living off Frankel's largesse _ his American Express card
bills were paid by Frankel _ Corbally made introductions that
broadened Frankel's universe to include prominent figures in law
and religion, including senior officials at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Frankel assert that Corbally also put him in touch
with several people whose names have surfaced in previous financial
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Quinn, one of the securities industry's
best-known swindlers. Quinn, a disbarred lawyer who rented a home
two blocks from Frankel in the back country of Greenwich until his
lease expired in June, has multiple convictions in securities and
money-laundering cases dating to the 1960s. He has served prison
time in the United States and Europe. He is considered one of the
world's leading experts in running ``boiler rooms,'' or operations
that peddle worthless stocks to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Another was Larry Martin, who friends say is a private
entrepreneur. Martin, who owns a home in Pound Ridge, N.Y., is
registered with the government as a patent lawyer. He has invested
in several well-known real estate projects, according to several
friends who said his business dealings were above board.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has at least indirect links to securities deals that have
come under scrutiny. In the mid-1990s, Martin served as an
intermediary when Osicom Technologies of California purchased a
controlling stake in Builders Warehouse, a failed home-products
retailer in Arkansas, said two people involved in that deal and a
federal investigator.
</P>
<P>
   That transaction was among several that prompted investigations
by the SEC and involved class-action lawsuits by shareholders of
Builders Warehouse who claimed that they were defrauded. Martin has
not been accused of wrongdoing in any of those transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A third recruit was Greco. He is best known for his role in
circulating false and derogatory information about international
banker Edmond Safra in the early 1990s. A former federal
investigator said Greco has extensive underworld contacts in both
Europe and Latin America, where Frankel's operation was seeking to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   Greco and Quinn could not be reached for comment. Martin and his
lawyer declined to return repeated phone calls seeking comment. In
an interview in June, Corbally acknowledged providing help to
Frankel but said he had been duped.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Corbally, who is now living in a London hotel, nor his
lawyer returned recent phone calls seeking comment on whether he
had a role in introducing Frankel to anyone involved previously in
questionable dealings.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1998, Quinn, Martin and Corbally had set up a new
company called American Life Acquisition, of which Martin served as
general manager and Messrs. Quinn and Corbally appeared to act as
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   That company's precise ties to Frankel remain unclear. As they
prospected for business, the company's executives referred from
time to time to their relationship to a trading guru who could coax
sky-high returns from ordinary securities, an apparent reference to
Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Martin recruited two investment bankers, three retired insurance
industry executives, a marketing expert and a chief administrator
to help run the company. Whether dining together at Harry
Cipriani's in midtown Manhattan or flying on Frankel's corporate
jet for business appointments (and sometimes to visit family),
Martin, Quinn and Corbally had all the trappings of an elite
deal-making team.
</P>
<P>
   They made pitches to as many as a dozen insurance companies in
Louisiana, Mississippi, Missouri, Illinois and Virginia. But, as
far as anyone involved knows, they never completed any deals. The
stumbling block: American Life claimed to have at least $150
million to buy insurance companies, but insisted that it could
never reveal where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the impression he was bouncing from state to state,
trying to find out if anyone would allow him to buy insurance
companies under a confidentiality scheme,'' said Craig Gardner,
deputy commission of insurance in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner had a meeting with Martin in November 1998, in which the
two discussed the purchase of United Life &AMP; Annuity Insurance Co.,
a Louisiana-based insurer with $1.4 billion in assets _ a purchase
that would have been larger by far than any Frankel had made.
</P>
<P>
   When Martin told him that he was raising $150 million from
anonymous European investors that would be channeled through a
holding company in the British Virgin Islands, a place prized for
its banking secrecy laws, Gardner said he stopped paying attention.
``I had better things to do,'' he said. ``You just aren't going to
get a deal done under those terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly in search of more pliant authorities, the team made at
least two trips to Managua, Nicaragua. There, according to several
participants, they negotiated with government officials for the
purchase of INISER, the Institute of Insurance and Reinsurance, a
state-owned insurance company the government was considering
selling off. There's no evidence a deal was concluded. Nicaraguan
officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out in the Americas, Corbally introduced Frankel
to British businessmen who claimed they could help Frankel buy
European insurers. After a get-acquainted session in Greenwich,
Frankel gave them some money to get started, two people familiar
with his dealings said. But he grew increasingly frustrated at his
inability to find people who would deliver more insurance companies
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all these people scrambling around without a sense of
direction,'' said a consultant who worked for American Life for six
months. ``It was so desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressures only increased earlier this year. Tennessee officials
demanded that the insurance companies Frankel ran put their assets
in a local bank, a ruling that required Frankel to cough up $60
million of the money he managed.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi regulators at the same time were worried about all
the offshore funding that Corbally, Martin and Quinn were nominally
arranging; talk of ties to the Vatican and to British Virgin
Islands trusts only increased the intensity of their questions. (It
was demands from Mississippi regulators, at the end of April, that
finally prompted Frankel to flee).
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, Martin announced in March that he would no
longer have anything to do with Frankel. He told those he had
recruited to American Life that he had his own doubts about the
sources of money the group claimed it had.
</P>
<P>
   At the Greenwich mansion, Frankel began speaking darkly of
``betrayal'' and ``blackmail'' to Ms. Boudanaval and others who
lived with him. Frankel, who has feared for his own security for at
least a decade and ordered cyberlocks and other high-tech security
systems for his home, tended to blame others for his misfortunes,
people who know him said. In his mind, the slights piled up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business that was supposed to be done wasn't done,'' said Ms.
Boudanaval, speaking of Martin. ``Larry kept telling Marty, `Yeah,
no problem.' But it wasn't done. Marty said he would like to break
his bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was also angry at Fausto Fausti, a retired Italian
aviation official-turned-business consultant. Fausti, who was
introduced to Frankel by Corbally, had helped Frankel make contact
with Catholic charities in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But visiting the Frankel home earlier this year, Fausti brought
along a delegation of Italian businessmen who said they wanted to
start a new microchip manufacturing company. They asked Frankel for
$20 million He rejected them and later complained that the request
amounted to blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of April, it was clear Frankel planned to give up the
fight and flee. Corbally was around the house constantly,
consulting privately with Frankel, people in the home at the time
said.
</P>
<P>
   Documents were being shredded. Frankel had ordered $10 million
in diamonds to take with him and an early shipment _ described by
one person as amounting to $3 million and another as totaling $2
million _ was scattered around his bedroom. Frankel handed out
3-karat diamonds to some staff members. Sitting on his bed, he
openly debated which of his staff he would take with him to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, he boarded a private jet for an airport outside Rome.
Three months later, authorities are still trying to find him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
