<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-850     08-06 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA INVESTIGATING AIR QUALITY PROBLEMS ABOARD INTERNATIONAL SPACE
STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Texas, Russia, Canada) (dw) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the last mission to the new International Space
Station, several astronauts suffered nausea, headaches and other
symptoms that have NASA scrambling for solutions to a suspected
air-quality problem before another crew visits the growing outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the crew of the shuttle Discovery did not report the
difficulties until debriefings two weeks after their landing, a
delay that NASA authorities acknowledge has hampered the search for
possible solutions and caused a review of crew procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-person crew returned from the 10-day supply mission on
June 6.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials say they believe unexpected buildups of carbon
dioxide, fumes from chemicals used in some components and
restricted air circulation may have been the sources of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Culbertson, NASA's space station operations manager at the
Johnson Space Center in Houston, said the problems were not serious
but the agency was taking steps to see that they did not recur on
future missions.
</P>
<P>
   NASA did not disclose the health concerns when it became aware
of them, but appointed what it calls a ``tiger team'' of agency
experts to assess the problem quickly and make recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The agency would not release a preliminary report by the team,
citing the crew's medical privacy. However, NASA Watch, a private
Internet site that follows space issues, posted a copy of a summary
report by the group.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming the specific crew members involved, the report
said ``several'' of them experienced symptoms including headaches,
burning and itching eyes, facial flush, nausea and one incidence of
vomiting while working in the station. Symptoms improved when crew
members retreated to the shuttle or used personal ventilator fans
while working aboard the station.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts, as planned, took air samples as they entered the
station and before closing hatches to leave after six days.
However, mission managers said, if they had been aware of potential
air-quality problems, they would have asked for additional samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew did all the right things and there were no serious
effects,'' Culbertson said. ``Everybody got rid of the symptoms
they had very quickly and there were no major problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson acknowledged that lack of timely reporting of
problems by the crew made it more difficult to diagnose and fix
them. But he said it was the prerogative of each commander and crew
to report problems to mission control as they occurred, depending
upon how they judged the severity of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew felt they understood the problem and handled it
appropriately,'' Culbertson said. ``Every commander is different.
Some are more talkative with the ground than others and we are used
to that. This isn't an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, NASA managers reviewed agency procedures after
the flight and have told crews to take more air samples and inform
ground control if such problems surface again on flights.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's mission was led by Cmdr. Kent V. Rominger of the
Navy, and Lt. Col. Rick D. Husband of the Air Force was the pilot.
The other members of the international crew were NASA astronauts
Daniel T. Barry, Tamara E. Jernigan and Ellen Ochoa; Julie Payette
of Canada, and Col. Valery I. Tokarev of the Russian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Robertson, director of Vanderbilt University's Center
for Space Physiology and Medicine, said that air quality in
spacecraft is important and something that can easily be addressed.
``This doesn't look like something that will be a long-term
problem,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said timely reporting of health problems in space ``is
very desirable and very important'' and that astronauts sometimes
have to be reminded of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astronauts need to keep mission control fully informed of
health events and I think they are doing that pretty well now,'' he
said, ``This was not the case 20 or 30 years ago when some people
tried to suppress problems because they had a test-pilot mentality
and didn't want to disclose something that might be considered a
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Space Station, which eventually is to grow
into a $60 billion complex covering an area the size of a football
field, now consists of two of an expected score of modules and
major components.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-made Zarya work module is attached to the American
Unity connecting hub, forming a unit 77 feet tall and weighing
70,000 pounds. The Discovery flight delivered more than 4,300
pounds of equipment and water for future crews, and allowed
astronauts to repair equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The third component is the Russian Zvezda service module, which
is to provide living quarters and laboratory space during the early
stages of station construction. This module is to be launched in
November, followed by a U.S. shuttle mission in December to perform
more station outfitting.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda contains filters and other air circulation and cleaning
equipment that should eliminate unwanted buildups of carbon dioxide
and fumes in the station, NASA officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The NASA experts investigating the Discovery incident said most
symptoms were reported by crew members working in the Zarya unit
when two or more worked closely for long periods and wall panels to
components were open, possibly blocking the circulation of fresh
air from the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Under conditions of weightlessness when there is no normal air
convection to help carry away gases, experts said, carbon dioxide
breathed out by the astronauts and fumes from solvents and other
construction materials could have built up to unhealthy levels.
</P>
<P>
   For the next shuttle mission to the station, NASA's assessment
team suggested, the crew should carry personal air monitors and do
more sampling. In addition, it said, NASA should re-evaluate the
station's air circulation system design, consider the possibility
of sending up temporary duct work with the shuttle to force more
fresh air through the station, look into installing an extra carbon
dioxide scrubber or filter in the complex and look at the potential
of flushing old air out of station modules as they are activated.
</P>
<P>
   The team noted that there was a potential longer-term impact to
the air-quality question. When the first permanent crew of three
astronauts arrives in a Russian Soyuz space capsule next year, it
said, there will be no American shuttle attached to act as a safe
haven in case something goes wrong with the air supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
