<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL FOR WALL STREET SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street scandals come and go. But the lurid
details in the order that the Bear Stearns Securities Corp. signed
on Thursday to settle Securities and Exchange Commission charges
have staying power.
</P>
<P>
   According to regulators, the fraud that the Bear Stearns unit
helped perpetrate as it processed securities trades for A.R. Baron,
a brokerage in New York that bilked investors of $75 million, is a
tale of personal and corporate greed relentlessly pursued at the
expense of unsuspecting investors.
</P>
<P>
   The firm will pay $38.5 million to settle the charges without
admitting or denying the allegations..
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said the firm ignored hard evidence that Baron
repeatedly defrauded investors: forged trade confirmation slips, a
letter from two Baron brokers admitting unauthorized trades, a
blizzard of customer complaints. Instead, the SEC charged, Richard
Harriton, president of the unit, kept the fraud going by using
funds and securities belonging to Baron's customers to pay for
trades in their accounts that he knew to be unauthorized.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC brought securities fraud charges on Thursday against
Harriton, who resigned from the firm but is fighting the charges.
He is being investigated by the Manhattan district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors and regulators investigated the role of Bear
Stearns in the Baron fraud, many clearing firms feared that one
outcome would be new rules.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC tweaked clearing rules earlier this year. But Richard H.
Walker, the agency's director of enforcement, made clear that the
Bear Stearns case was not about the need for higher clearing
standards, but about a firm that did nothing to stop a fraud and
plenty to perpetuate it.
</P>
<P>
   The case raises many questions about how Bear Stearns is run.
One really nags.
</P>
<P>
   Why was Harriton, the man who brought Baron in as a clearing
customer even as the firm sank deeper into financial and regulatory
distress, defended by Bear Stearns management until the day he was
sued?
</P>
<P>
   Most public firms would have moved quickly to examine the
operations of a department under scrutiny by regulators, if only to
try to maintain shareholders' trust. Judging by the SEC's order, a
glance at the operation would have raised numerous flags.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is no surprise that Bear Stearns shares have
underperformed the returns of the American Stock Exchange
Broker/Dealer Index recently.
</P>
<P>
   Harriton was not only kept on at the firm, but paid very well
and named to its powerful compensation committee. James E. Cayne,
the president of the firm, said he was sorry to see Harriton go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lessons from the Top,'' a forthcoming book about corporate
leadership by Thomas J. Neff and James M. Citrin, includes an
interview with Alan C. Greenberg, the Bear Stearns chairman. In the
book, Greenberg says his proudest accomplishment is that Bear
Stearns has never been hit with an ethical scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, he is quoted as saying: ``Mark Twain said, `Fish
stink from the head,' right? It's people up top who set an example
of how a business should be run.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
