<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-ALEXANDER-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH RAND L. ALEXANDER: HARTFORD STOCK FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Hartford stock fund is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many money managers focus on their stocks and ignore the
economy, but Rand L. Alexander is a big-picture guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at macroeconomic data to see what sectors and
industries in the U.S. will grow fastest over the next 12 to 18
months, given our economic outlook,'' said Alexander, manager of
the $1.02 billion Hartford Stock fund and a partner in the
Wellington Management Co., a money manager in Boston that is also
subadviser for other funds, like Vanguard Wellington and Vanguard
Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   What does he see in the data? ``We think the economic backdrop
looks pretty doggone good,'' he said from his office overlooking
Boston Harbor. He expects the gross domestic product to grow more
than 4 percent this year, with inflation staying comfortably below
2 percent and operating profits for companies in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rising 10 percent to 12 percent. As a result,
Hartford Stock owns more cyclical stocks than it did nine months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's top-down approach has paid off. The fund returned
28.4 percent, annualized, for the three years ended Aug. 5,
according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
That compares with 23.1 percent for its peer group of large blend
funds and 27.7 percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, 48, works with Wellington's 31 analysts to find
quality stocks in their favored sectors among the 300 to 400
American companies with market capitalizations exceeding $6
billion. Those sectors currently include energy, cyclical
technology businesses (like semiconductor companies) and basic
materials (like forest products and chemicals).
</P>
<P>
   He looks for companies with strong brands; the fund's biggest
holdings include household names like General Electric, Exxon and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   He also looks for high return on equity, but frowns on leveraged
balance sheets. The return on equity for the S&AMP;P 500 averages 20
percent, he said, while many of the fund's companies exceed 30
percent or 40 percent. ``Our companies typically have better
financials and stronger balance sheets than the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he often chooses companies that should fit certain themes
for the next three to five years. That, he says, helps stop the
fund from ``getting whipsawed, by fashions in the equity market or
if we're wrong on the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The themes are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ (italics)Global growth.(end italics) The ability to expand
overseas is important, he said, for big companies like McDonald's
and Wal-Mart Stores, two of his biggest holdings.
</P>
<P>
   _ (italics)Balding baby boomers.(end italics) He says the aging
boomers have bigger needs for financial services and health care,
so the fund invests in companies like Franklin Resources, the
mutual fund concern, and the drug makers Warner-Lambert and
American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
   _ (italics)Networking the nation.(end italics) This category,
recognizing the proliferation of technology in everyday life, leads
the fund to buy companies like Intel and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   _ (italics)Survival of the fittest.(end italics) The newest
category, it accounts for companies formed through big mergers,
like Citigroup or MCI Worldcom. ``We want to own the surviving
entity, which will benefit from the synergies of being bigger,'' he
said. ``It's easier to manage big companies now than it was five
years ago, because of improvements in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander uses a variety of valuation measures, depending on the
industry, to choose the 75 to 85 stocks in the fund. For technology
companies, for example, he uses earnings growth rates; for oil
stocks, the ratio of price to cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, he screens his list of big stocks for those with
price moves of 5 percent to 10 percent _ a clue to dig a little
deeper. Over all, though, the fund tends to hold on to its stocks.
Its turnover rate is just 37 percent, less than half the average
for stock funds tracked by Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander added to his five-year-old position in the State
Street Corp., the Boston money manager and one of the leading
global custodians for the mutual fund industry, when its stock
price fell to the mid-$70s in early July, from the mid-$80s.
</P>
<P>
   Besides fitting into his ``balding baby boomer'' theme, he said,
State Street should benefit from the growing demand for equities
worldwide. He estimates annual earnings growth of 15 percent over
the next three years and expects the share price to reach $100 by
the end of 2000. State Street closed on Friday at $67.25.
</P>
<P>
   In May, he bought shares of Micron Technologies, the
semiconductor maker, at prices from the mid- to high $30s. The
price had fallen from about $80 in February because of excess
industry capacity, Alexander said. But Wellington analysts saw
Micron as the lowest-cost producer with the best balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cyclical play on semiconductor prices,'' he said. He
expects the company to become profitable by year-end and to be
earning $5 to $10 a share annually within three years. It closed on
Friday at $65.875; his 12- to 18-month price target is $80 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander recently added to his position in Alcoa, the aluminum
producer, which he started buying last fall at $36. ``We think it's
the best-managed aluminum company in the world,'' he said.
``They've done all the right things to rein in costs, and as
aluminum prices rise, all that will fall to the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects earnings to jump to $3.75 a share in 2000. The stock
closed on Friday at $62.625; his 18-month price target is $80.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
