<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON JARRETT AS NASCAR PREPARES FOR BRICKYARD RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dale Jarrett is speeding down the front
straightaway of the Nascar Winston Cup season. He holds a 254-point
lead over Mark Martin and a 283-point lead over Bobby Labonte
entering Saturday's Brickyard 400, and only a major collapse _ or a
serious run of bad luck _ over the final 15 races of the season
could keep Jarrett from winning his first Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know if we do our job right, we're in pretty good
position,'' said Jarrett, driver of the Ford Quality Care Taurus.
``When you're the second-place guy, like we've been a lot in the
past, you always have to count on someone having a problem. Now,
we're in a reverse role. We are in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, the defending Winston Cup champion, said, ``I don't
see anyone touching Jarrett as long as he keeps doing what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jarrett's team is not looking too far ahead. It has plenty
of challenges, starting with Saturday's race at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway. Jarrett, whose Taurus was fastest among the Fords
during testing here last month, qualified fourth Friday behind
Gordon, a two-time Brickyard champion, Martin and David Green.
Jarrett figures to spend much of the early stages of the race
trying to get around them.
</P>
<P>
   The purse for this year's Brickyard 400 is $6.1 million,
Nascar's second highest after the Daytona 500's $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who won the Brickyard 400 in 1996, always has a strong
car here, but it may not be the strongest this year. That
designation belongs to Gordon, who won the inaugural race in 1994
and won again last year. Gordon, who trails Jarrett by an almost
insurmountable 492 points in the Winston Cup standing, is trying to
win his fifth race of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good starting spot in the same race car we had
here last year,'' said Jarrett, who has three victories, four
second-place finishes and two thirds this season. ``We seem to have
a pretty good package, and it seems to be a really good car. I
think we have a good chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will just be a matter of us doing our job all day long,
staying out of trouble and getting ourselves in a position in the
later stages of the race to win. And obviously, pit strategy will
come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was pit strategy that took Jarrett out of the race last year.
He ran out of gas while leading near the halfway point, the victim
of a terrible miscalculation in fuel mileage that cost him an
apparent victory and a prize exceeding $1.6 million. It was tough
to swallow at the time, but Jarrett laughed about it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened last year, I thought we had that problem
figured out,'' he said. ``But we ran out of gas earlier this year
at Las Vegas. So obviously, we don't have it down pat just yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief, said: ``It took a couple of
days to get over that, for me especially. But it wasn't
life-threatening. We learned not to count on that calculator for
all the answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
