<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-WILLOW-BAY-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLOW BAY HAD THE FAME BUT YEARNED FOR `FORTUNE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Rick Kaplan became president of CNN/USA in late
1997, he wanted to make a splash with three prime-time programs he
was creating in concert with ``Time,'' ``Fortune'' and
``Entertainment Weekly,'' magazine siblings in the Time Warner
corporate family.
</P>
<P>
   Essential to the shows' success would be their anchors, and
Kaplan, formerly an ABC News executive, wanted to woo Willow Bay
from ABC to be a co-anchor for ``CNN &AMP; Entertainment Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch, he made his pitch. Then Ms. Bay surprised him. She
would be glad to do the entertainment program, she said, but what
she really wanted was to be a co-anchor of was ``Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' she asked, only partly teasing, ``why wouldn't
you have thought of me for the `Fortune' show?''
</P>
<P>
   She wound up getting both jobs, and now, after a little more
than a year with them, Ms. Bay has been promoted to CNN's top
business-news spot. On July 19, she and Stuart Varney became
co-anchors of the network's most lucrative show, its 6:30 p.m.
business newscast, ``Moneyline News Hour,'' taking over from Lou
Dobbs, who resigned abruptly in June.
</P>
<P>
   To Wall Street, Varney, a longtime financial journalist, was a
predictable replacement. Ms. Bay was not. Though she has a master's
degree in business administration from New York University, until
her ``Fortune'' anchoring and reporting work, she had primarily
handled softer news.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the fact that she is a former model led many in the
business world to wonder if CNN had gone soft, and would be taking
``Moneyline'' in a more entertainment-oriented direction.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case, according to virtually all of Ms. Bay's
colleagues, from Kaplan on down, who note that it is at best silly
and at worst sexist to assume that an attractive woman is incapable
of solid business reporting.
</P>
<P>
   But at first, even Kaplan was surprised at Ms. Bay's resolve to
move into this realm.
</P>
<P>
   Had he looked at her resume, that business degree from NYU might
have stood out. And he had worked with her on some ABC News special
reports. But most of his familiarity with her came from watching
her work as the anchor of ABC's ``Good Morning America Sunday,'' a
show skewed toward entertainment rather than heavy-duty news, and
as the co-host of a Saturday-morning basketball show for children
on NBC called ``NBA Inside Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing there suggested a potential business journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that lunch, Kaplan said: ``I think she wanted to make
sure I knew how serious she was. After doing the NBA show and all,
she wanted to be involved in something substantive, and she wasn't
sure the `E.W.' show would turn out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three shows performed well in the Nielsen ratings.
Still, Ms. Bay, in Kaplan's estimation, demonstrated that she had
the skill and substance to handle ``Moneyline.''
</P>
<P>
   But at CNN, some people briefly grumbled about a newcomer
usurping a job that could have gone to one of CNN's more
experienced correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   And at CNBC, the business-news cable network based in Ft. Lee,
N.J., rivals sniped that Ms. Bay, who is 35, had gotten the job
because she is young, glamorous and has high-profile connections in
the media business world. Her husband, Robert A. Iger, is the
chairman of Walt Disney Co.'s ABC Group.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of CNBC, which is owned by General Electric Co.'s NBC
subsidiary, immediately laid out a plan to take advantage of the
personnel switch at ``Moneyline.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Dobbs announced his departure _ he left CNN to take
charge of an Internet site devoted to outer space _ CNBC expanded
its roundup show, ``Business Center,'' to an hour, starting the
same time as ``Moneyline.'' ``Business Center'' also changed its
anchors, shifting CNBC's best-known daytime anchors, Sue Herera and
Ron Insana, to replace Maria Bartiromo, who moved to an afternoon
program of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Back at CNN, by naming two anchors for ``Moneyline,'' Kaplan
diffused the burden of replacing Dobbs, who began the program in
1984 when CNN began and, to some, personified business and market
news on television.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Bay and Varney were on the show together for only two
weeks before Ms. Bay went on vacation, no meaningful ratings
comparisons can be made yet. Preliminary figures suggest that
``Moneyline'' has not suffered significantly from the loss of
Dobbs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR;  &LR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bay, whose given name is Kristine but was nicknamed Willow
by her mother, is finally in the kind of job she has long desired.
After getting her MBA in 1991, she wanted to become a business
reporter, she said, but was steered away by her agent, who said
business journalism was too narrow a field.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he urged her to capitalize on her experience as a
model, a career she had begun at the age of 15. For five years in
her early 20s, Ms. Bay was ``the face'' of Estee Lauder cosmetics
advertising worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it was a great, glamorous pedigree,'' Ms. Bay
said of her modeling career. ``In other ways it has been an
impediment,'' encouraging some people to dismiss her as just a
pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   Not that being attractive has ever hurt on television. And with
more people interested in business news, networks are hiring
on-camera talent with a popular, even a glamorous appeal. Several
attractive women _ and more than a few handsome, well-coiffed men,
for that matter _ cover financial news for CNBC and other
television news organizations. Indeed, tabloid newspapers have
nicknamed Ms. Bartiromo at CNBC ``the money honey,'' and sometimes
portray Ms. Bay as a new entrant in the category.
</P>
<P>
   Still, business correspondents must have more than just looks,
broadcast executives say. ``A television audience has traditionally
had a better acceptance of attractive people, in terms of accepting
them into your home,'' said a CNBC executive producer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``But the audience has to believe your
anchors know what they're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Networks are not so much seeking more attractive people as
business-news correspondents and anchors, Kaplan said, as they are
simply getting a wider variety of applicants. ``Business-news
reporting has become big time,'' he said. ``Those jobs are more
sought-after than they were in the past, because they have more
visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if the glamour factor rises, he said, the most
important assets remain knowledge and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bay acknowledges that she has work to do to build up her
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have a wealth of experience in daily financial news
reporting,'' she said in an interview at the midtown Manhattan
headquarters of CNN and CNNfn, its sister
all-financial-news-all-the-time network. ``But I do come to this
job with a background in business reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   From her reporting of longer pieces on the ``CNN &AMP; Fortune''
magazine show, Ms. Bay said, she brings a desire to put business
developments in context, and curiosity about ``the personalities of
the players involved and how that shapes strategy, how that shapes
execution, how that shapes morale and direction at companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, in an interview for ``Moneyline'' last week with
Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of Miramax Films, and Cathleen
Black, president of Hearst Magazines, about their joint venture,
``Talk'' magazine, she put Weinstein on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not known for spending lavishly, and you're also not
known for being a patient man,'' Ms. Bay said to him. ``How
comfortable are you about spending 30, 40 or 50 million dollars to
launch this product?''
</P>
<P>
   Since earlier in the interview, Weinstein and Ms. Black had
declined to give the start-up figures for ``Talk,'' he looked a bit
taken aback. Ms. Bay had gotten the estimate, she later said, from
other magazine industry sources.
</P>
<P>
   She probably could have gotten a pretty good estimate from her
husband, since Miramax, while not under Iger, is a unit of Disney.
``I could have asked him, but I don't do research at home,'' Ms.
Bay said firmly.
</P>
<P>
   She and Iger, who have been married since 1995 and have an
eight-month-old son, Max, do not have ``a formal policy'' about
what they will and won't discuss to avoid potential conflicts of
interest, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just both very respectful of not putting each other in
a precarious position,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions of conflicts of interest also worry her. If
Weinstein reported to Iger, for example, she said she would not
have interviewed him. ``If I feel conflicted or there's a
perception of conflict, I recuse myself, as anyone would,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the first thing people who have worked with Ms.
Bay invariably mentioned was how hard she works _ almost as if they
find that surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not ambitious in the `star' sense,'' said a former
colleague at ABC. ``She's 100 percent devoted to making herself
better. She's absolutely intense about wanting to be prepared, to
learn all she can.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Gerbst, who heads the assignment desk at ABC News, said
that Ms. Bay had ``always done whatever she was asked to do and
more, and always in the most willing and most cooperative way.''
</P>
<P>
   She first applied herself to learning a new field from scratch
when David Stern, the NBA commissioner, and his TV staff hired her
as a co-host of ``NBA Inside Stuff,'' along with Ahmad Rashad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are similarities, especially in learning the special
jargon,'' Ms. Bay said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan sees another analogy to sports. ``Business viewers are
like sports fans in that they come with a whole lot of knowledge,''
he said. ``If I'm an anchor, you have to take my word about what's
in the SALT treaty, but not about who ought to start at center for
the Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN hopes the new anchors can appeal to average investors in
this era of mass ownership of stocks, while not alienating the
high-powered audience that lets ``Moneyline'' earn the highest
advertising rates of any CNN show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always worry about on-air chemistry,'' Kaplan said. ``But
I think it will work because she is what we call a generous anchor,
meaning she's willing to make someone else look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, by the age of 20 she'd had more fame than most people
have in two lifetimes. For Willow, it's all about the work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
