<HEADLINE>
FLEISHER LEADS BY 1, AND TIES COURSE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ On the 17th tee at the Meadow Brook Club on
Friday, a spectator shouted to Bruce Fleisher: he had a chance to
capture the course record in the Lightpath Long Island Classic. The
news went in one ear and out the other, Fleisher said, the sort
that matters more to players who are accustomed to a place in the
record book.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher has four victories and ranks second on the money list
in his first full season on the Senior PGA Tour, after a career on
the PGA Tour that never approached such heights. A bogey on the
18th hole Friday left him with an opening-round 64, tying the
course record set two years ago by Jose Maria Canizares and giving
him a one-stroke lead over Mark Hayes. That was fine with Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone mentioned course record,'' Fleisher said. ``But you're
not thinking course record. I don't think it means anything. I
found out the number in the tent and it wouldn't have made a
difference. I would have liked to play the 18th hole again,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   That is all you will get out of Fleisher in terms of regrets. He
won the United States Amateur at age 19, earning a spot in the 1969
Masters with Arnold Palmer. He shot a 69 that day, four strokes
better than Palmer, setting a high bar of expectation that he never
met on the PGA Tour. He had one victory in 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I've got a very good explanation for that,'' Fleisher
said. ``I really believe there are very few that are chosen, no
matter what we do. There can only be one Jack Nicklaus, one Arnold
Palmer, one Tom Watson. I don't look at my career as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, maybe I never reached my potential. The way I
look at it is, I've lived my life the way I want to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In retrospect, maybe I didn't work hard enough.
There's a lot of sacrifice you have to make. I don't envy any of
them. I look at Tiger Woods today. He has no life. He may in 15-20
years when he walks away.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher's success on the Senior Tour has been startling. After
amassing lifetime earnings on the PGA Tour of $1,695,111, he has
already picked up $1,488,400 this season, second to Hale Irwin, and
there is a $180,000 check awaiting the winner of this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to give Hale a run,'' Fleisher said. ``He may run
away with it still, but it's been a fun year so far.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The race for the money lead has been enough _ along with too
many phone calls disturbing his rest _ to turn what Fleisher
planned as a two- to three-week vacation into just one week. He
watched last week's Novell Utah Showdown from his home in Florida,
but decided to jump back into action this week. It looked like a
good decision Friday, when he carded birdies on six consecutive
holes on the front nine.
</P>
<P>
   Then he birdied the par-5 17th to put himself in position to set
the course record. But on the 167-yard 18th, he opted for an 8-iron
and left his tee shot short, hitting in front of the green and
rolling back approximately 30 yards. He chipped 12 feet past the
hole, and his par putt hung just off the lip, leaving him in a tie
for the record.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, a Monday qualifier, finished with a 65, just one stroke
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddie, Dennis Turning, I lean on him and he made a
mistake,'' Fleisher said, a small smile accompanying the criticism.
``Even though I hit it, I blame him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
