<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCHOLARSHIPS07-CO     08-06 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCHOLARSHIPS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Probe links Atlanta bid to IOC scholarship offers
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Congressional investigators have uncovered evidence
that Atlanta Olympic officials offered college scholarships to
family members of IOC delegates in the city's bid for the 1996
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   A senior staff official involved with a congressional
investigation and who has reviewed the Atlanta Olympic records
cited memorandums and correspondence between bid team leaders and
some IOC members regarding scholarships for their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was solid evidence that only one student actually
attended at least one semester of college, the official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said in their report (to the House Commerce Committee)
that no scholarships were received by IOC members,'' said the
official. ``But they certainly offered them. And there were
certainly lots of letters and memos indicating this person or that
person said they'd take a scholarship. They were certainly using
that as a means to build their friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne has pledged repeatedly that
his team did not offer scholarships as Salt Lake City officials did
in their successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Revelations of exorbitant gifts, scholarships and cash payments
from the Salt Lake bid group launched a global Olympic bribery
scandal that has forced the resignations or expulsions of 10 IOC
members. Congress, in an effort to apply federal bribery laws to
the IOC, is investigating the Salt Lake and Atlanta bids.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional committee is allowing former U.S. Attorney
General Griffin Bell, a top attorney with the King &AMP; Spalding law
firm, to amend a report compiled by the Atlanta bid group after
investigators found evidence of gifts valued at more than $1,000
and favors that were not included in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The senior staff official also cited Friday at least one job
offer to an IOC member for a relative.
</P>
<P>
   Payne declined to comment Friday about the new developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are compiling a supplemental report and while we are doing
that we will withhold comments until after it has been presented to
and reviewed by the commerce committee,'' said Lee Echols,
spokesman for the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, Payne's
organization that was created to bid for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
