<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   1-800-WELLDARNIT! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a former Long Island social worker, James F. McCann sure
knows a lot about marketing. But McCann, whose company,
rechristened 1-800-Flowers.com, went public last week, might need
some homework in the history of initial offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Over 20 years, McCann, his brother, sister, nieces, nephews,
children and scores of others have built 1-800-Flowers into a very
successful private business, claiming over 60 percent of the
nation's flower delivery market.
</P>
<P>
   After courting the company for more than a year, Goldman, Sachs
sold six million shares of the company at $21 each on Tuesday,
raising $126 million. But the shares closed that first day below
the offered price and ended the week at $17.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market could have been kinder,'' McCann said on Friday.
``I would rather have had a nice little pop and built from there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rush from even the gushiest initial public offerings
seldom lasts. Most of the new issues through August last year, for
example, are now trading below their offering prices. ``No
fooling?'' McCann asked. Still, he isn't expecting any sympathy
bouquets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth N. Gilpin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Money-Go-Round &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The analysts who serve as investors' eyes and ears in monitoring
some of the world's biggest companies are changing jobs, with
higher paychecks a usual result.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Lehman Brothers analyst, Joseph S. Phillippi, moved
to the company's investment banking side, so Merrill Lynch's
Nicholas Lobaccaro grabbed his place. John A. Casesa, who was at
Schroder &AMP; Co., took Lobaccaro's spot at Merrill. ``When one
leaves, it causes musical chairs,'' Lobaccaro said.
</P>
<P>
   The music is still playing. Maryann N. Keller, the longtime
thorn in General Motors' side at ING Bering, joined the dot-com
world by becoming president of Priceline.com's auto unit. Credit
Suisse First Boston has lost the auto analyst Nicholas J. Colas to
SAC Capital Management, which he joined as a portfolio manager.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts covering such a cyclical industry as autos said
their colleagues were simply being altruistic; by spending their
raises, they will do their part to keep the economy humming.
``Everybody adds to their salary by making these changes,'' said
David B. Healy, an analyst at Burnham Securities. ``They probably
have in mind adding to gross national product.''
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Meredith &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faces Reflected in Crystal? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What better way to attract beautiful people to a store than by
showing other beautiful people in its ads? But how to get them to
pose? Valerie Lichman, a New York publicist, figured it out for
Lalique, the French crystal company, which is opening a boutique on
Madison Avenue: you help their favorite charity.
</P>
<P>
   So volunteers for Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center will
appear in the Lalique ad campaign, and, in return, Lalique will
make a substantial but unspecified contribution to Memorial
Sloan-Kettering. Last week, the volunteers were photographed
wearing jewelry from Lalique's new collections for ads that will
run this fall in W and Town &AMP; Country.
</P>
<P>
   One ad shows Alexandra Lind, a young fashion designer, and
Jennifer Creel, who says she has her hands full with two preschool
children. They head the associates committee of the Society of
Memorial Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   A second ad shows Joanne de Guardiola, a prominent interior
designer and Society board member, and her stepdaughter Jeanne de
Guardiola, head of the Indian and Southeast Asian department at
Sotheby's and a member of the associates committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the ads have meaning for people who don't do the charity
circuit?'' Ms. Lichman mused. ``Perhaps not, but Lalique doesn't
mind. The new Madison Avenue boutique ad is aimed at those who know
_ or at least know of _ these ladies and look upon them as arbiters
of style.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk About Thank You's. ... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A postscript on the Talk magazine debut party last week: Lavish
as it was, it relied heavily on what could be called television
game show financing, giving plugs and getting goods. ``Thank you
Donna Karan for making this dress and then I had to pull myself
into it,'' said Tina Brown in a speech, referring to her velvet and
silk devore crystal-accented dress from Ms. Karan, a friend of Ms.
Brown's and a prominent Talk advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald A. Galotti, the publisher, thanked Robert Mondavi for the
wine, Evian for the bottled water and Tommy Mottola of Sony for the
music.
</P>
</TEXT>
