<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CHRISTIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT BLAMES INDIVIDUAL IN KILLING OF MISSIONARY AND SONS IN
INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (bl) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The killing of an Australian missionary and
his two young sons by a frenzied mob in January was instigated by
an individual and not by any Hindu right-wing group associated with
the governing Bharatiya Janata Party, according to a summary of a
judicial inquiry issued Friday by the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   The missionary, Graham Staines, 58, and his sons, Philip, 10,
and Timothy, 6, were attacked Jan. 22 as they slept in their jeep
in a remote village in the state of Orissa. According to witnesses,
the vehicle was then set ablaze with the three victims trapped
inside as 50 to 100 people chanted slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Staines, the local director of the Evangelical Missionary
Society, ran a hospital for leprosy patients. His death came during
a string of attacks against Christians and their churches in India.
</P>
<P>
   Police blamed members of the Bajrang Dal, a youth group that is
part of the same family of Hindu nationalist organizations as the
Bharatiya Janata Party, which was then head of India's coalition
government. That coalition has since lost its majority in
Parliament, and the Bharatiya Janata now heads a caretaker
government, with elections due in September.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-page report, written by Judge D.P. Wadhwa, was submitted
six weeks ago. On Thursday, the Home Ministry made a single copy
available to members of Parliament. Only government-written
summaries were given to the press.
</P>
<P>
   According to the summary, a ``fanatic'' Hindu chauvinist and
repeated lawbreaker, Dara Singh, initiated the killings. He egged
on youths in the village of Manoharpur, provoking ``their ire,
saying that Christian missionaries were destroying the Hindu
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He prepared them and then led the attack,'' the summary said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen men have been charged with murder, arson and criminal
conspiracy in the deaths, but Singh is hiding in forests under the
protection of villagers, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Singh's influence in the area grew, the report said, after he
stopped several Muslims from trading in cows. He then voiced his
disapproval of local missionaries. At the time, friction in the
community was already keen. Christians were being accused of wooing
the local Santhal tribesmen to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Staines lived in the town of Baripada, where ``he was a popular
figure,'' the summary said. It added that he was involved in
``spreading the Gospel,'' but that he himself ``was not involved in
conversions.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 23 million Christians in India, but they make up
only 2.3 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The Staines case created a furor here and abroad. The government
was accused of not doing enough to prevent anti-Christian violence.
That Singh was said to have links to a group affiliated with the
Bharatiya Janata Party made the criticisms all the more potent.
</P>
<P>
   If the government's summary accurately reflects the report by
Wadhwa, who serves on the Indian Supreme Court, it would seem to
exonerate the Bharatiya Janata Party.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier press accounts of the report, said to be based on leaks,
maintained that Singh was an activist in the Bajrang Dal and that
even if he was not acting under orders, he was still acting in its
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Parties opposing the Bharatiya Janata Party have already begun
calling the report a whitewash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
