<HEADER>
A8801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-BALLS-ART-NY     08-06 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BALLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS KICKERS GET BRUSH-UP COURSE ON NEW PROCEDURE FOR BALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ He may be the best punter the New York Jets
have had since Curley Johnson more than 30 years ago, but Tom Tupa
is wondering whether the new rules to avoid doctoring the footballs
will affect his average as well as the overall kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   It did not bother him Friday as the Jets devoted the morning to
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   But before practice, their first shipment of sealed footballs
was opened by a National Football League officiating crew, just as
it will be in the regular season for all teams for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen balls, each marked with a ``K'' by the manufacturer,
will be the only ones permitted for use by the place-kickers and
punters. Twenty-four other balls will be used on the other downs.
</P>
<P>
   Only officials can manipulate the ball the kickers will use, and
the officials will have a specially made brush to make each ball
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Kickers tampering with footballs had become so pervasive that
the league's competition committee ruled last year that the
practice would have to stop. No more balls going into washing
machines, being smashed by weights, or being inflated to 16 pounds
before being deflated to the required 13 pounds in order to smooth
out the seams and make them more aerodynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's practice, Bill Lovett of Maryland, a field
judge, demonstrated what would be done to the balls. He scraped the
film and dust off the new ball, and that was it. Then they were
placed in a special kickers bag. No players could get their hands
on a ball before its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to rub them on the turf and wet them to get the new
stuff off,'' said Tupa, who joined the Jets after producing a
44.5-yard average with New England. That number has been bettered
only twice in a season in the history of the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ends of the ball are hard when they come out of the box,''
he said. ``We used to push the ends down hard into the turf. That
softens it up and allows you to get more compression.''
</P>
<P>
   One league official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said some players had put balls in microwave ovens to tenderize
them. And Steve Belichick, a former Navy special teams coach and
the father of the Jets' assistant head coach, Bill Belichick,
recalled one college punter who used the same ball all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the year you couldn't see the grain on the
ball,'' Belichick said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the changes, Tupa suggested, ``There will be a
lot lower averages, especially outdoors and on cold-weather
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Tupa and place-kicker John Hall could prove even
more effective than their rivals. Both have extremely strong legs.
As linebacker Chad Cascadden said, ``They could put a block of
cement on the tee, and John would kick it into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, with shorter kickoffs and fewer punts going into the
end zones, there will be more balls returned. It calls for faster
special-team coverages. The Jets have been working especially on
this area under coach Mike Sweatman, especially after the team
finished last in the punting game last season, allowing 10.3 yards
a return. (The Jets averaged 7.3 yards a return themselves.)
</P>
<P>
   Sweatman will have to throw out the advice he got from Matt
Bahr, who was the heady and reliable place-kicker for Coach Bill
Parcells on the Giants and Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once asked him for the recipe of what he did to the ball,''
Sweatman said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was?
</P>
<P>
   Sweatman smiled but did not respond. Perhaps one day, after all,
the kickers may be allowed to have their way again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Did he really mean it, or was Bill Parcells simply needling his
offense the day before the first major scrimmage of camp? He
described the huddle as the ``superstar-central area.'' This is the
group, he said, ``who think they can dial up a superstar whenever
they want. I'm not pushing any panic buttons, we've got more than a
month, but at the same time we've been here a week and the light
has to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   At various times the first week Parcells asked quarterback Vinny
Testaverde if his arm was all right, complained about the line and
complained about the receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to talk to the offense Thursday afternoon,'' Parcells
said. ``It's just the effort. We're not getting the production out
of some of the players who should be producing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he conceded his biggest worry on offense is not about
first-stringers but the second- and third-team players. Parcells
concluded, ``I'm not being critical,'' then a few sentences later
added, ``If you want to say I'm complaining, you can say that
because I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
