<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WOODSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.H. WOODSON, NEW JERSEY ASSEMBLY CHIEF AND PASTOR, DIES AT 83  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Pa., Ga.)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. S. Howard Woodson Jr., who in 1974 became the first
black speaker of a state legislature, died on Wednesday at a
hospital in Trenton. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, a Democrat, lived in Trenton and led the Shiloh Baptist
Church there for 53 years. He was elected to the Trenton City
Council in 1962 and to the New Jersey Legislature in 1964, serving
six two-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   He served as New Jersey's speaker in 1974 and 1975, becoming the
first black to hold the top post in the lower house of any state
legislature. He was also the minority leader of the Assembly in
1968 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson resigned from the Assembly in 1976, when Gov. Brendan T.
Byrne appointed him president of the state's Civil Service
Commission, which gave him responsibility for many state
affirmative action and equal employment programs. He held the
position until 1982.
</P>
<P>
   A strong supporter of Byrne's introduction of a state income
tax, Woodson acknowledged in 1978 that he did not file state or
federal income tax returns in 1976 and 1977. He said the failure
resulted from an oversight by his second wife, Lola, who had been
ill.
</P>
<P>
   While the matter was being investigated, Byrne ordered Woodson
to take an unpaid leave of absence from his civil service job. The
leave ended after it was learned that he did not owe any taxes and
was due a refund.
</P>
<P>
   S. Howard Woodson was born in Philadelphia on May 8, 1916. He
received a bachelor's degree from Cheyney University in Cheyney,
Pa., and a master's degree in divinity from Morehouse College in
Atlanta. He was ordained in 1944 and moved to Trenton in 1946. He
retired from his church position in March, becoming pastor
emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson also served as president of the State Conference of the
NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Audrey, died in 1969. He is survived by his
second wife, Lola: a son, S. Howard III of Alexandria, Va.; a
daughter, Jean Mitchell of Newtown, Pa.; a stepdaughter, Paulette
George of Hamilton Township, N.J.; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
