<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT SURGES TO THE TOP AT PLEASANT VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ For a week, the talk centered around the big
names who were supposed to be here, but weren't.
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds of the areaWEB.com Challenge at Pleasant
Valley, the talk is of the big names who are here. You can find
them atop the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   The program for this LPGA Tour stop still features Karrie Webb,
the game's best player whose withdrawal touched off a bit of
controversy, but there are a flock of players who are quickly
making that debate history. Lorie Kane, No. 3 on the money list, is
one. Sherri Steinhauer, No. 8, is another.
</P>
<P>
   They each posted 4-under-par 32s on the front, finished 67 and
68, respectively, and share the 36-hole lead at 8-under 136.
</P>
<P>
   But while the breeze picked up to cool things off, there was
little breathing room for the leaders. That's because Rachel
Hetherington posted a 66 to tie Mardi Lunn (71) at 137, and Dottie
Pepper (71_138) headlines a group that includes Michele Redman
(68), Jan Stephenson (70), and Laurie Rinker-Graham (68) at 6
under.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauer began her round with a birdie 2, then rolled in three
more in an outward 32. But she didn't pull away. ``My putter cooled
off a little bit,'' she said. ``I was having trouble with the speed
a bit.'' The reigning British Women's Open champ was seen heading
to the practice green late in the afternoon, most likely because
she knows the women battling her have a knack for winning.
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington has won twice this year, and Pepper's 15th career
victory came earlier this season at the Nabisco Dinah Shore. And
while it's been a while, Stephenson (1987) and Rinker-Graham (1986)
turned back the clock to when they last danced away with a winner's
check.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a player who has never won _ Kane _ who most stands
out.
</P>
<P>
   Her presence at the top is starting to be a given, as each week
she makes a run at it (four straight top-10 finishes), but with
each tournament she is faced with the question: When will you win?
</P>
<P>
   She seemed poised a few weeks ago, but lost in a playoff to
Steinhauer at the JAL Big Apple Classic. Perhaps they can talk
about that Saturday when they walk 18 over Ted Mingolla's plush
playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always enjoy playing with her,'' said Steinhauer. ``I look
forward to it. She's a kind, fun person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunn is very much a part of the good times, though she was five
strokes higher than her opening 66. ``I'm happy,'' she said. One
off the lead ``is a good place to be with 36 holes left.''
</P>
<P>
   A fellow Australian of Lunn, Hetherington, needed a backside
blitz to get in such a mood. She had started the day at 1 under and
though she made two birdies on the front, Hetherington made her
noise coming home. She birdied the par-4 10th, par-5 11th, par-4
15th, and par-5 18th.
</P>
<P>
   And she did it all with her husband, Dean Teske, on the bag.
``He only caddies with me a few weeks out of the year,'' said
Hetherington. ``It's difficult sometimes because he wants to help
me, but sometimes it's a bit more information than I want to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of her colleagues, Hetherington had also heard a lot
of information about the problems this tournament was up against
last week. Marquee names had been promoted, then withdrawn. The
27-year-old Hetherington had planned a schedule that included five
straight weeks of play, then a week off before the Women's British
Open. ``But I thought I would stretch it to six weeks because I
knew they had a short field for this event,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Good for her _ and good for tournament organizers, who had to
smile as the best names in the event moved to the top. Even the
newest star in the LPGA galaxy, Kelli Kuehne (72_141), is lurking
at five back, where she shares space with one of the grandest stars
in the galaxy, Pat Bradley (70_141). And a big name trying to
regain prominence _ Michelle McGann (73_142) _ isn't far away,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are far away, however, will be told of what they
missed at Pleasant Valley when Kane meets up with them next week.
``Of the players who are not here _ Se Ri (Pak), I'm sure (Nancy)
Lopez would be here if she were healthy, and Karrie and Kelly
(Robbins) _ they're all such great strikers of the ball, they could
probably bring this course to its knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But that's a future consideration. For now, those in
attendance are handling things quite nicely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
