<SLUG> BC-FBN-L.A.-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MAY BYPASS LOS ANGELES FOR HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles' bid for the National Football League's 32nd
franchise is approaching its demise and Houston's chances are
looking better every day.
</P>
<P>
   The league said Thursday that it would no longer focus
exclusively on the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum as the site for a
team, following the state of California's refusal to subsidize the
$150 million cost of new parking garages.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the league examines other locations _ in Inglewood
or Carson _ it could not settle on either by Sept. 15, the deadline
set last March for a final financing plan in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Bob McNair, who has a stadium financing plan in
place in Houston, would probably be awarded the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're just working on the things we can control and
looking forward to the Sept. 15 deadline,'' said Steve Patterson,
vice president of McNair's sports holdings. ``The message we've
gotten from the league is that they won't extend the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles plan unraveled earlier this week when the league
refused to sign a deal proposed by California Gov. Gray Davis'
negotiator that the team playing in a renovated Coliseum pay off
$150 million in state-issued bonds with annual rent of $5 million,
a 10 percent ticket tax and all parking revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL wants a pure public subsidy and would never approve a
lease with a rent higher than any other team. The trend in new
stadiums is for teams to pay as little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Davis' negotiator, Bill Chadwick, resigned. Davis
said in a statement, ``The NFL has to appreciate that there are a
number of higher priorities for the use of public funds in
California than attracting an NFL team.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue wrote to Davis, saying that the
league had no option but to pursue other sites. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
