u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-980&AMP;A     08-06 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMATION OF RIVALS' ALLIANCE EXPOSES YELTSIN'S DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In his eight years as Russia's first popularly elected
president, Boris Yeltsin has shown that he can stomach vicious
criticism, manage a virulent Communist opposition and emerge
bloodied but whole from a disastrous civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But what he has never accepted is to have his views discounted,
which is what occurred this week, when two powerful wings of the
political establishment banded together to form an electoral
alliance, against the wishes of the presidential administration in
the Kremlin and despite its best efforts to block the move.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's failure to bring the newly minted center-left party to
heel not only exposed his weakening position as his term enters its
final year, but it has also left the Kremlin empty-handed, without
a party or even a viable candidate, as Russia begins its march into
the post-Yeltsin era.
</P>
<P>
   It is still too early to gauge the strength of the alliance
between the ambitious mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, a potential
presidential contender, and a handful of regional barons, now
united for Parliamentary elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the coalition, an awkward amalgam known
provisionally as ``Fatherland _ All Russia,'' largely depends on
its ability to attract former Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov back
to politics, ultimately as a consensus presidential candidate, and
on whether Luzhkov abandons his Kremlin ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   While the political elite awaited word from the enigmatic
Primakov, one clear fact emerged: The Kremlin is rapidly losing its
influence over the flow of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each passing day, power is slipping from the Kremlin,''
said Vladimir Ryzhkov, a rising star in Our Home Is Russia, a party
created in 1995 under the aegis of the Kremlin and which is openly
weighing an offer to join the Fatherland coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts even compared the situation to the events of 1990
and 1991, when President Mikhail Gorbachev saw his influence being
trampled underfoot as the political establishment rushed to throw
its weight onto a bandwagon for Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the Soviet Union brought that shift to a
historic conclusion, leaving Yeltsin the undisputed leader of a
newly sovereign Russia. This time, the landscape is undergoing
another upheaval, with regional governors, many of whom lord over
parts of this vast country like small-time czars, cast in the role
of kingmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of influence may be the usual fate for lame-duck
presidents elsewhere. But in Russia, where no leader has ever
relinquished power in an orderly constitutional transition,
Yeltsin's ability to handle such a humiliation is being sorely
tested.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers feverishly reviewed the Kremlin's options, among them
a continuation of low-intensity warfare against Luzhkov, an
erstwhile ally of Yeltsin and now an open foe, through the use of
the media, scarce budget resources or `kompromat,' the infamous
Russian word for leaking damaging information.
</P>
<P>
   Some predicted that the Kremlin might cast about for a
scapegoat, with the prime candidates being either Aleksandr
Voloshin, Yeltsin's abrasive chief of staff, who has for weeks led
an ugly war against pro-Luzhkov newspapers and television stations,
or even Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin, who after four months on
the job has proved to be a weak political player, and an
increasingly implausible standard-bearer for Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Other options might be more radical, like an attempt to delay or
call off the Parliamentary elections. Sergei Zverev, a former
Kremlin aide freshly dismissed from his position in another round
of palace intrigue, openly raised that possibility at a news
conference this week, warning that if Yeltsin declared an all-out
war against the new alliance, that could lead to ``disastrous
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts tend to rule out any unconstitutional moves by
Yeltsin, who, they point out, is acutely mindful of his historical
legacy. ``He is capable of such things, but they are unlikely,''
Sergei Markov, director of the Institute of Political Studies,
said. ``Yeltsin wants to go into history textbooks as the one who
established democratic institutions in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kremlin will try to be active but this activity will be
defensive. Yeltsin is no longer leading the country. He is leading
the Kremlin against the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A final alternative would leave Yeltsin to find ways to
accommodate, or maybe infiltrate, the emerging alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Such an alliance leaves open the question of how easily Luzhkov
would abandon his presidential ambitions in favor of Primakov. But
judging from Luzhkov's open-ended offer to the former prime
minister, that is an issue that the mayor is willing to leave
unresolved for now.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Primakov has remained ambiguously silent, except
to welcome the alliance and, in a strong hint of his future role,
to stress that it should not be seen as an ``anti-president'
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The source of Primakov's popularity, reflected in polls that
show him as Russia's most trusted politician, lies as much in his
cautious soothing manner as in his political views, which remain
something of a mystery. In his eight months as prime minister,
Primakov, a former diplomat and wily survivor of the Soviet regime,
delivered on a promise of political stability, won in large part
through the appeasement of Yeltsin's Communist opposition in the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   By discharging Primakov in May and subsequently squashing a
Communist-led impeachment drive, Yeltsin succeeded in weakening his
Communist opponents, depriving them of badly need links to the
central government.
</P>
<P>
   These victories were a reminder of Yeltsin's mastery of Russian
politics and of the power that continues to cling to his office.
But, Markov said, they have proved Pyrrhic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the Roman general Pyrrhus,'' he said, ``they won battle
after battle. But in the end, they have no army.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to newspaper reports, Yeltsin made a series of
attempts to wield his personal influence. He met this week
privately with Mintimir Shaimiyev, a leader of the All Russia group
and all-powerful governor of the oil-rich Tatarstan region, trying
unsuccessfully to dissuade him from an alliance with Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also met former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, head
of the Our Home Is Russia Party, reportedly to try to persuade him
to head an alternative bloc that would include Right Cause and
other right-wing parties made up of liberal reformers. According to
one newspaper report, Chernomyrdin, whom Yeltsin ousted as prime
minister last year, declined, although by late Friday his party did
open consultations with Right Cause, as well as Fatherland _ All
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, in an interview Friday in Izvestia, insisted that the
government had to stay neutral to assure free and fair
Parliamentary elections. Already, he said, ``the fight for power
has heated up so much that it may turn the political arena into a
heap of ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high, Stepashin added. Intervention by the
government ``would mean not only the collapse of the government or
some party or other,'' he said. ``It would be the collapse of
Russia's efforts to become a modern, prosperous country. The
biggest banana republic in the world, and one without bananas at
that _ that is not an enviable fate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
