<HEADLINE>
BURNED BY GOLD? CONSIDER A HEDGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of gold producers is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD A. APPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anglogold Ltd. produces about 10 percent of the world's gold,
but the yellow metal may not be its most valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   While gold prices continue to slide, Anglogold, the giant South
African miner, has posted respectable earnings by hedging, or
agreeing ahead of time to sell production at set prices that are
higher than current ones.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry makers and other gold consumers take the other side of
these contracts to insure a future flow of gold at reasonable
prices _ even if that means passing up cheaper metal today in the
spot market.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of the year, forward contracts enabled
Anglogold to sell its gold at $312 an ounce, 11 percent higher than
average market prices. Another big hedger, Barrick Gold, has sold
three years of future production at $385 an ounce _ enough to
generate hundreds of millions of dollars of added earnings for the
Canadian miner if prices stay close to the current $256.
</P>
<P>
   Hedging has become the most important factor in the relative
success of gold companies in recent years. Those that have hedged
extensively, like Barrick and Anglogold, have seen their stock
prices hold fairly steady. But those that have not, including
Newmont Mining and Homestake Mining, have suffered, as falling spot
prices _ pushed lower, in part, by other companies' hedging _ have
hurt earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 3,000 tons, or slightly more than what is
excavated worldwide in a year, is sold forward through contracts,
put options or other derivatives, analysts say. They predict that
an additional few hundred tons could be sold forward this year.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has become so widespread that it makes proposed
gold sales by central banks look like peanuts. The market-roiling
proposal by the International Monetary Fund to sell gold supplies
to finance debt relief for Third World nations involved about 300
tons; that plan now appears dead.
</P>
<P>
   The summer's other shocker _ the Bank of England's plan to
auction more than half its bullion _ involves 415 metric tons over
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Partially because of hedging, Barrick, the second-biggest North
American producer, now has a stock market value of nearly $7.6
billion. Newmont and Homestake _ Nos. 1 and 4, respectively _ mine
almost two times as much gold but their total market capitalization
is two-thirds that of Barrick.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson here: Investors who bet on a gold rebound
should know exactly what type of producer they are investing in.
</P>
<P>
   Want to roll the dice? An unhedged producer will get the biggest
pop from a rally. When gold surged 10 percent late last fall,
Newmont shares doubled in value in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not so bullish? Hedged producers may fare better. Since the Bank
of England's announcement in early May, which has helped push gold
prices down 13 percent, Newmont's stock has lost almost 27 percent
of its value, far more than Barrick's.
</P>
<P>
   Gold pessimists note that the huge stocks of official reserves _
estimated at 33,000 metric tons _ mean that the spot-market price
will always be subject to rumors of central bank selling. While the
actual sale of gold by Britain is too small to hurt market
liquidity, more serious ``was the signal sent out by the sale,
which was very damaging to the market,'' said Hester le Roux, an
analyst at Gold Fields Mineral Services, a gold industry researcher
in London.
</P>
<P>
   But gold bugs believe that the metal has become seriously
oversold. The Asian economic recovery has spurred demand there,
while the supply of scrap gold that flooded the market last year is
expected to fall by several hundred tons this year.
</P>
<P>
   They also note that Anglogold announced last week that it would
not enter into new forward contracts, citing expectations that
prices have likely bottomed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors of that persuasion may find some gold company stocks
more appealing than bullion anyway. A few years ago, the stocks
traded at several times the earnings multiple of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, but now even a few analysts' favorites
trade at discounts to the index.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Wiskemann, portfolio manager at the Franklin Gold fund,
said gold prices could move higher because of inflation, a crisis,
or other ``events we cannot foresee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will become panicky,'' he said, ``and they will want to
own the yellow metal again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
