<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
WOMAN WINS $23.36 MILLION IN FEN-PHEN LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add byline)  (yn) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the first verdict from among thousands of cases
pending across the country against makers of the diet pills
popularly known as fen-phen, an east Texas jury Friday awarded
$23.36 million to a woman who said she suffered heart damage after
taking the drugs to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Debbie Stone Lovett, 36, a manicurist from Grand
Saline, Tex., had accused Madison, N.J.-based pharmaceutical giant
American Home Products Corp. and its subsidiary Wyeth-Ayerst
Laboratories of failing to warn their customers and doctors that
the diet pills caused heart valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment is the latest setback for American Home Products,
which settled a similar case in Houston in June for a reported $6
million and faces a massive class-action lawsuit over the diet
pills that began jury selection this week in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers said Friday's verdict in Van Zandt County,
about 50 miles southeast of Dallas, is particularly significant
because American Home Products, which had settled several cases out
of court, decided that the facts in the Lovett case favored the
company. ``This is a case that American Home Products chose,'' said
Kip Petroff, a lead lawyer for Ms. Lovett who is also trying more
than 100 similar cases across the nation. ``They were very arrogant
and very confident they were going to win this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts expressed surprise at the verdict
and predicted it would encourage more lawsuits against the company,
particularly since American Home Products appeared to have solid
evidence that Ms. Lovett's heart condition existed before her use
of the diet drugs. She used the drugs on and off for six months
beginning in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schick, a lawyer for American Home Products, said it would
appeal the ruling. ``We feel the evidence presented in this case
demonstrated that the company acted responsibly and lawfully in
marketing and monitoring the safety of the diet drug Pondimin,''
Schick said in a statement released by the company.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, American Home Products removed the two diet
pills, fenfluramine and dexfenfluramine, which were marketed as
Pondimin and Redux, off the shelves at the request of the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, federal health officials advised the estimated
1.2 million to 4.7 million people in the United States who used the
drugs to seek medical checkups after studies linked them to heart
valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Petroff said American Home Products had commissioned studies
that encouraged consumers to take Pondimin and Redux in combination
with phentermine, the other half of fen-phen, to achieve long-term
weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   Phentermine, which is distributed but not manufactured by
American Home Products, has never been associated with the same
health problems when taken alone and remains on the market. Though
the FDA had approved all three drugs for use alone as weight-loss
drugs, many doctors followed the advice of the company and
prescribed them in an unapproved fen-phen combination.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas case, the jury of eight men and four women awarded
Ms. Lovett $3.3 million in compensatory damages and $20 million in
punitive damages. Her lawyers argued that Ms. Lovett developed
leaky heart valves after taking Pondimin in combination with
phentermine for weight loss. But Ms. Lovett's own cardiologist
testified that her heart problems predated her use of fen-phen.
Petroff, however, said that even if she had been sick before taking
the drugs, the company's failure to alert physicians and consumers
to the risks of the pills placed his client in further danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly made a statement that they were mad at
somebody,'' said Patrick J. Spruiell, another lawyer for Ms.
Lovett, speaking of the jury. ``It appeared to me they wanted to
get AHP's attention. They obviously did that with this verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The tide of litigation against the company will apparently keep
growing. Petroff said he will begin another lawsuit two weeks from
now in Ft. Worth, Tex., while the class-action lawsuit brought by
three New Jersey women began this week. Tommy Fibich, a Houston
lawyer involved in 160 cases, estimated that the number of lawsuits
against the company has grown from 3,100 to more than 10,000 in
recent weeks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Texas verdict exacerbates an already trying summer for
American Home Products, the world's seventh-largest drug maker.
Last month, federal officials pulled the company's Rotavirus
vaccine from the market because of health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the company announced that its second quarter earnings
would not meet analysts' expectations, a disastrous performance in
an environment of robust drug sales. Last year, the company was the
subject of two failed megamergers, first with SmithKline Beecham
and later with Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, American Home
Products' stock plunged 11.9 percent, or $6.0625 a share, to
$44.875.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and analysts disagreed about the significance of the
ruling. Fibich described the Lovett case as relatively weak,
particularly since Ms. Lovett had not suffered as greatly as other
users of fen-phen. ``If that case can be won, that tells me almost
any case can be won,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neil Sweig, a pharmaceutical analyst with Ryan, Beck,
Southeast Research in New York, said analysts have begun to warn
investors not to overreact to American Home Products' problems.
When the problems with fen-phen surfaced in 1997, analysts
predicted that the company faced liabilities of as much as $5
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
