<SLUG> BC-GRAND-CANYON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON GATEWAY PLAN WINS FOREST SERVICE APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Ending nearly a decade of studies and
suspense, the U.S. Forest Service on Friday said it will allow a
massive land trade with developers who plan to build a new tourist
gateway community for the next century at Grand Canyon National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Forest Village of Scotts dale will receive 282 acres of
prime National Forest land adjacent to the park's main entrance.
The land is just north of Tusayan, an existing collection of hotels
and restaurants whose developers opposed the land trade in favor of
expanding their own townsite.
</P>
<P>
   For giving up what some have called the most valuable real
estate in northern Arizona, the Forest Service will receive 2,118
acres of private lands controlled by Canyon Forest Village that are
scattered among 12 sites within the adjacent Kaibab National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Towns, Southwest re gional forester for the Forest Serv
ice, said the land trade will eliminate private inholdings - many
of them former frontier ranches - within the forest, while
maximizing the Grand Canyon experience for the park's nearly 5
million annual visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Towns predicted that Canyon Forest Village will ``better serve
the tourists ..., protect the forest's and park's natural
resources, and ... make living more affordable and bearable for the
local workers who stoke this region's economic engine, the Grand
Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are more govern ment hurdles ahead for Canyon
Forest Village, and their opponents promise a fight to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lopez, a Flagstaff city councilman who heads a group
opposed to Canyon Forest Village, said the Forest Service decision
will be appealed within the 45-day window allowed by federal guide
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, the ball has been rolling downhill all the way
from Washington in favor of this,'' Lopez said. ``That hill has
just gotten steeper for us. But we can delay it for a considerable
amount of time and that's what we plan to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt served for a brief time as a
consultant to Canyon Forest Village before his appointment to the
Clin ton administration in 1993. The Interior Secretary has recused
him self from all matters concerning the Canyon Forest Village
decision.
</P>
<P>
   If the Forest Service doesn't reverse its decision, Lopez said,
opponents would file lawsuits against it, challenging how the
decision was made and how the agency came up with its appraisals of
the lands to be exchanged. The Forest Service appraised the 282
acres it plans to give away at $5.4 million, and the 2,118 acres
wants at $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy they got to appraise it came from Texas. He doesn't
know anything about Arizona land val ues,'' Lopez said. ``Anyone
who knows anything about that knows that land just outside the
Canyon is worth more than $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   If appeals and lawsuits don't work, Lopez said, his group is
prepared to bring the matter to vote via a public referendum.
County officials said nearly 1,500 voter signatures would bring the
matter to the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Coconino County Supervisor Paul Babbitt, a brother of the
Interior Secretary, said he expects a grueling battle for approval
before both the county's planning and zoning com mission and Board
of Supervisors, which he estimates will take a year.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Babbitt said he isn't worried about the fears among those
in the hospitality industry in Flagstaff and Williams that more
hotels and businesses near the Grand Canyon will have a devastating
economic impact on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about the continued degradation of the
park, and the lack of facilities and infrastructure there,'' Paul
Babbitt said. ``There's more than enough business for everybody if
they all plow their share of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep. Karan English, co-chairperson of the Coalition
for the Canyon's Future, which favors Canyon Forest Village, said
the county was going to be facing more problems than how to handle
Can yon Forest Village. The 50-mile corridor of Arizona 64 between
Williams and the Grand Canyon is strung with other parcels of devel
opable land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an abundance of private land all up and down the
highway, and this going to spur development all over. The county
has to keep a handle on that,'' English said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Canyon Forest Village plan, 1,220 hotel rooms will be
built on 282 acres of land it swaps for from the Forest Service,
just outside the pay station leading to the Canyon's South Rim.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Forest Service receives 12 private inholdings
total ling 2,118 acres, which the Canyon Forest Village group had
earlier purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Forest Village's Tom De Paolo has pledged that the
project will use state-of-the art energy and water conservation and
materials recycling techniques in the develop ment of hotels,
270,000 square feet of retail space and 1,100 housing units for
local employees only. None of the housing will be available for
purchase on the general commercial market.
</P>
<P>
   The project includes 20,000 square feet of retail space for
Native American merchants, and 29 acres dedicated to Flagstaff's
Museum of Northern Arizona for a visitor-ori entation center about
the history of the Colorado Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Local and national environmental groups backed the Canyon Forest
Village project, except the Sierra Club, which has concerns about
groundwater depletion in the canyon area.
</P>
<P>
   The Havasupai and Hopi tribes have blessed the Canyon Forest
Village project, mainly because it will not harm the canyon's
springs, some of which feed the canyon's largest waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Forest Village will have all its water transported from
the community of Topock on the Colo rado River, except during what
the Forest Service called ``emergency situations'' like wildfires
threatening the Tusayan area. But groundwater will be pumped,
temporarily, during construction of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Hopi Chairman Wayne Taylor Jr. said the concern about water on
the part of the developers earned his tribe's blessing for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that we will have our craftsmen employed in the
retail area,'' Taylor said. ``But the key issue was that our sacred
springs be respected, and we're satisfied that they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Simon of the National Park and Conservation Association,
called Canyon Forest Village the ``green alternative'' for accommo
dating the growing number of Grand Canyon visitors expected in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare environmental suc cess; a victory of long-term
conser vation vision over misinformation (and) jealous economic
self-inter est,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the development is expected to be completed
two years after final approval from the county, and the entire
project should be finished in four years after county approval.
</P>
<P>
   The FaeX plan pushed by Tu sayan business owners called for the
construction of 400 new hotel rooms and 250,000 square feet of
retail space along with an undeter mined number of housing units.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
