<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' STAR PICK OF '96 FINALLY GETS CHANCE TO SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Giants' first pick in the 1996 draft was the
fifth over all, the highest the team had selected in 15 years. They
chose defensive end Cedric Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Jones has had three career starts. While others in
the draft taken above and below him _ Keyshawn Johnson, Terry
Glenn, Simeon Rice, Eddie George, Terry Glenn, John Mobley and
Kevin Hardy _ have fashioned notable careers, Jones has 29 tackles
under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   But barring injury, the semi-anonymous portion of Jones'
National Football League experience is about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 25, has been anointed the Giants' right defensive end,
replacing Chad Bratzke, who left as a free agent to join the
Indianapolis Colts. Since Jones will play opposite the Pro Bowl
left defensive end Michael Strahan, there will be no hiding Jones _
he will see plenty of running plays and screen passes to his side
of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel admits this situation might have made him
nervous two years ago. But last season, Fassel and his coaches
believe, they saw something different in Jones. And as it became
obvious the Giants probably would not be able to afford Bratzke, at
the same time, the Giants became comfortable that Jones would be
his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about that being an exploited position,''
Fassel said Friday of his right defensive end. ``I don't see it as
a weak spot. I wouldn't be as sure if this was Cedric Jones two
years ago, but he's made a turnaround. He's quick and explosive
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround came when Fassel's staff asked Jones to do the
opposite of what the former coach Dan Reeves' staff had been asking
him to do. Jones was told to put on weight when he arrived, which
was late in the 1996 training camp after a lengthy holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose playing weight at Oklahoma University was about 270
pounds, got as high as 285 pounds. The idea was that the added
weight would make Jones more formidable when he went against
310-pound tackles. Instead, it appeared to make him slower. Also,
he had leg injuries in each of his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's coaches saw Jones play at 285 for parts of the 1997
season and decided he might be better, and quicker, at a lower
weight. By last season, Jones was closer to 275, and he had his
best season as a Giant.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded his first NFL sack in the team's fourth game and
three more later. He separated from blocks more effectively and was
more fluid running down ball carriers. His pass rushing forced two
fumbles, including one when he sacked Arizona's Jake Plummer. Jones
recovered the fumble, and the turnover set up the go-ahead
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In Jones' case, smaller does appear to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my doubts about it all along,'' Jones said of the advice
to gain weight in 1996. ``But they're the coaches and you do what
they want. We tried it and it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   He was aware that Fassel's staff did not know what to make of
him when they arrived in 1997. ``I hadn't played much so they had
nothing to watch of me on film,'' he said. ``It was going to take
time to gain their trust and confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He has earned that, something made obvious when the Giants did
not pursue another defensive end when Bratzke departed. Giants
management made up its mind to give the job to Jones last season as
the team watched his impact on games become more significant.
</P>
<P>
   So now, three and a half years after Jones was the fifth player
taken, he is entering a season as a starter for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of it as a landmark accomplishment or
anything,'' Jones said. ``But it is an opportunity I haven't had
before. All I have to do is start making plays and people will
start saying, `I knew he could do that all along.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
