<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In land of Giants, Baker stands tallest
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There would be no batting practice that day. And it
was Dusty Baker's fault. It happened in the early 70s, when Baker
was a kid in a Braves uniform and Hank Aaron's stomach was flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed a cut-off man one day so we spent the whole practice
with cut-offs and relays,'' he said. ``Our team loved to hit so the
rest of practice, everybody's looking at me like I was a commie or
something. It was embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also another lesson Baker filed away. No needless
embarrassment. (Following through, Baker won't even let on what
manager called off BP, though it was Eddie Mathews.) A living
collection of such lessons, Baker had never managed a game in his
life until San Francisco promoted him from batting coach in 1993,
choosing Baker to replace Roger Craig.
</P>
<P>
   What has ensued is an odd metamorphosis, front-office risk
begetting a two-time National League manager of the year. Baker's
wrist bands, the constant toothpick, the casual poses around the
dugout provide a false reading. Through Thursday, the Giants were
running 3 1/2 games behind Arizona in the NL West, running behind
all that high-financing with a banged-up roster. But out by the
Bay, they believe because Dusty has made them.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in his six years, the Giants have been alive for the
postseason on the last day of the season. Last season, after
slumping to four games back in the wild card race with six to play,
Baker's Giants rose from the dead to force a one game-playoff.
While Giants fans have come to expect such competitiveness, perhaps
his players have too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Dusty doesn't have a doghouse,'' said general
manager Brian Sabean. ``He'll give somebody the third, fourth,
fifth try. He has a knack for judging people. And I think that
makes for a comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   This has not been an easy week for Baker. There is a differing
opinion within the organization on whether rookie Joe Nathan should
replace Mark Gardner (3-9, 6.87) in the rotation. During a stop in
Arizona before the Braves series, Baker had a sharp exchange with
Devil Rays manager Buck Showalter, who suggested the Giants were a
bit too proud for hanging on in the race despite injuries to, among
others, Barry Bonds, Jeff Kent, Ellis Burks _ merely the guts of
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of (Showalter) talking, to tell you the truth,''
Baker snapped.
</P>
<P>
   But it's August and the Giants as usual are right in the middle
of it. Deduct the injuries and this team has performed as most of
Baker's clubs: plenty of walks (462, third in the league), high
on-base percentage (.356, third) and plenty of scoring (5.4 runs a
game, fourth) with Bonds and Kent (on the DL) profiting from the
high on-base rate. These items reflect a game philosophy decades in
the making, as Baker solicited opinions from Aaron to Preston
Gomez, from Reggie Smith to Danny Ozark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from Tony La Russa to get your team prepared for
when they go out on the field, which he learned from Earl Weaver,''
Baker said. ``He also taught me to realize when the inning of
decision is, when to take the pitcher out, when to play the game
close, when to try to blow it open, how to get back into the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   To the front office, Baker's personality has helped define the
club's direction. With a restricted budget _ the Giants have yet to
ever spend as much as $50 million on payroll _ the team has been
able to successfully bring in second-tier talent to place around
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Kent arrived to break Rogers Hornsby's RBIs record for Giants
second basemen (128 last year). Marvin Benard, a .273 career
hitter, got off to .322 last year after Baker made him a leadoff
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to hand-pick who you're going to bring in,''
said Sabean. ``Guys do have to really want to play here, which puts
an emphasis on Dusty's relationship with the players. They know his
reputation as a player's manager, which really means he's going to
give everybody on the roster the chance to prove himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he misses the cut-off man.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
