<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brickyard grows in popularity
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For a race only in its sixth year of existence,
the Brickyard 400 has quickly earned a permanent spot on the front
row of NASCAR's racing schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Motor Speedway, the most famous track in the world,
played host to its first Winston Cup race in 1994. Since then, the
Brickyard 400 has elevated to the point where its popularity is
only exceeded by the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, we knew it would be a success,'' said Fred
Nation, IMS vice president of communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The track) is a special place, for motorsports fans of all
varieties. You can see that with the comments from the Winston Cup
drivers, and by the attitudes of the many fans that come here. They
view it as the shrine of motorsports.''
</P>
<P>
   Mystique surrounding the 2.5-mile oval track, which has been the
site of 83 runnings of the Indianapolis 500 and open-wheel racing
since 1909, seems to be the top attraction for the drivers. Dale
Jarrett, the leader in the points standings, paid the utmost
respect when discussing the possibility of winning today's 1 p.m.
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could almost stop racing after that,'' Jarrett said. ``It
doesn't matter what kind of car it's in. To me, what it's all about
is racing and winning at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Obviously,
you want to win a lot of races, but if you could only win one, this
has got to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   An ever-growing purse is another reason for the Brickyard's
rapid popularity. Today's race will pay out around $6.2 million _
including an estimated $700,000 minimum to the winner _ trailing
only the Daytona 500 ($7.3 million) on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pays a lot,'' Mark Martin said. ``I've run third, fourth
and fifth here and when I finished fifth (in '95), I made more
money ($144,850) than I had ever won for winning any of my 30
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Brickyard 400 will result in instant fame, attested
by three-time Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon. The No. 24 Chevy
driver first made a name for himself nationally by taking the
checkered flag at the inaugural race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like your career is complete if you win at the
Brickyard,'' Ricky Rudd said. ``I'm always being introduced as the
'97 Brickyard 400 winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
