<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Judge Lifts Ban on Basque Media
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon authorized the Basque newspaper Egin and
its radio station to reopen, a year after he shut them down while
investigating their potential links to the Basque separatist group
ETA. The rebels have observed a cease-fire since September and the
judge said the two media now pose little threat.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Presidential Hopeful Takes Leave
</P>
<P>
   The leading opposition candidate for president next year,
Vicente Fox Quesada, requested a leave from his post as governor of
the central state of Guanajuato. Fox has been criticized by the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party for increasingly
devoting time to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan: Taliban Forces Fall Back
</P>
<P>
   Retreating Taliban forces were attempting to regroup after an
opposition commander, Ahmad Shah Masood, launched a successful
counterstrike that brought the capital, Kabul, back into shelling
range. The Islamist militants had hoped to mount a ``final
offensive'' this summer to take the 10 percent of Afghanistan that
remains beyond its control.
</P>
<P>
   India: New Missiles on Track
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a military conference, A.P.J. Abdul Kalam, the
nation's top rocket scientist, said two new missile systems will
soon go into production. Defense Minister George Fernandes added
that more money will be dedicated to mountain warfare, resulting
from this summer's conflict with Pakistani-backed infiltrators in
peaks along the Line of Control that separate the Indian and
Pakistani parts of Kashmir.
</P>
</TEXT>
