<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-RIDER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider to Hawks: `I've changed'
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If he is feeling the jet lag from the long flight
east, Isaiah Rider isn't showing it on a sun-splashed Georgia
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   No, he is as cool as the diamond-encrusted watch on his right
wrist, the diamond-encrusted bracelet on his left wrist, the
diamond-encrusted crucifix that rests against the simplicity of his
NBA Players Association T-shirt and the diamond stud in his left
ear lobe. With all that ice, a man would have to be chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Rider is in town to take his physical so the trade that brought
him to Atlanta with Jim Jackson can be stamped official. He passed.
</P>
<P>
   He also is in town to face the media so he can repair the
bad-boy image that followed him from Alameda, Calif., to Las Vegas
to Minneapolis to Portland and now Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that he owned up to his mistakes and he didn't
try to make excuses when we met today,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, 'Hey, you start over with me. It's a clean slate.
You follow the rules here, you've got no problems with me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens also said,''I love his talent.''
</P>
<P>
   No one's walking away from the guy's talent, certainly not
Rider. ``The question's never been about my play, and I'm more
professional now. I demand double teams, and I'll kill you if you
go one on one with me,'' he said, laughing only a little because he
means it.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Conference better watch out, he said: ``A lot of
guys I want to knock off the pedestal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider said he will confine his mistakes to the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 28 and I've learned some lessons,'' Rider said. ``I won't
make the same mistakes at 28 that I made at 23. This is my seventh
year in he NBA. I'm more mature now, more professional.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Rider was arrested twice in June, prompting a trade to
Portland in July, when he called the move his ``opportunity of a
lifetime.'' Then he missed exhibition games and was arrested for
marijuana possession. He also had 12 single-game suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed,'' he said. Events were blown out of proportion
``that made me appear to be an animal or not an intellectual, that
discredited my family,'' he said. ``Bottom line is I made my
mistakes, but I don't want to dwell on the negative. Those things
are behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the news conference, he prompted the media
to ask him some more questions so he could clear the slate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like this team was a little reserved at times, laid
back,'' he said. ``So I'm going to bring that (enthusiasm). I'm
gonna jump up; I'm gonna high-five. I think that's how you get a
relationship. They're gonna be excited about J.R. Rider. I'm gonna
go a little further than they expect, but when they see it enough,
they're gonna say, 'He's not crazy; he's just trying to wake us
up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rider also said he really had been surprised the Blazers traded
him and attributed it to the disappointment of being swept in the
West finals in June. ``The people who didn't like me didn't know
me,'' he said. ``They knew my reputation from before (in
Minnesota), but they never took the time or had the chance to know
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider said he walked away from free agency and accepted the $5.4
million option year on his contract to show the Blazers how sincere
he was about staying in town.
</P>
<P>
   The day the trade broke, he said, he told some cronies that he
would play the year here and then go back to Portland. But he said
he has had time since then to think about his situation. ``But I'm
OK, and I like my team _ Jason Terry, J.J., Chris Crawford, Roshown
(McLeod), LaPhonso (Ellis). We've got some guys who can get out on
the break and put the ball in the basket. We've got the big fellow
(Dikembe Mutombo) to rebound, block shots and take care of
business. I'm not gonna wait 'til training camp to get with them.
I'll be back in September. ``
</P>
<P>
   Hawks president Stan Kasten, acknowledging Rider's reputation
for unreliability, said he already has improved. ``There was a
mix-up at the airport, a ready-made excuse,'' Kasten said, ``but
J.R. took matters into his own hands. He solved the problem, and he
got here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't that say something in his favor?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
