</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-HALL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hall raising play, salary
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ As has become his custom, Travis Hall went
back to his native Alaska for a while before training camp started
and did a little fishing with his wife, Tonya, and family.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons defensive tackle said he is not interested, however,
in fishing for more attention than he's getting as one of the NFL's
least appreciated interior linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Knee, ankle and shoulder injuries reduced his effectiveness at
times last year, when he missed two games and a third start. He
still finished with 73 tackles, 4 1/2 sacks, four fumble
recoveries, eight passes batted down and 30 quarterback pressures.
</P>
<P>
   His 279 tackles in the past three seasons lead all interior
linemen; Arizona's Eric Swann is a distant second, with 226 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   But in one recent ranking of the league's top tackles, Hall was
ranked 10th. And the 6-foot-5, 300-pounder has never been more than
a third Pro Bowl alternate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,'' defensive end Chuck Smith said. ``Swann
ain't as good as Travis. Trav mashes people, man.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem to bother Hall, who grew up in Kenai, Alaska, in
the southwestern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that our team is getting more recognition, I'm getting a
little more recognition. That's fine,'' he said. ``With three
Monday night games, and a Sunday night game ... the exposure will
keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   When healthy, Hall is relentless.
</P>
<P>
   He played just three snaps as a rookie sixth-round choice in
1995. But the former end from Brigham Young got a lot bigger and
totaled 98 tackles and six sacks in 1996, despite missing two games
with a severe ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Hall stood to become a restricted free agent after the '97
season, but one of the first things new coach Dan Reeves and
general manager Harold Richardson did was give Hall a contract that
included a $1 million signing bonus in April that year.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than five times what Hall was to have earned in
salary his third season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even with three years left, one could argue that Hall has
earned another new deal.
</P>
<P>
   He put up big numbers in '97, registering 109 tackles and 10 1/2
sacks while earning a modest $200,000 in base salary. In the
offseason, the market for premier tackles was driving salaries up
to 10 times, and more, what Hall made.
</P>
<P>
   His salary jumped to $750,000 last season, and $1.15 million
this season. Those are nice raises, but the totals are perhaps only
one-third of Hall's market value.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the deal he signed was simple.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons prevented him from becoming a restricted free agent,
and he got a lot more money that year, through the bonus, than he
would have.
</P>
<P>
   But the more that time passes, the more he falls below market
value. Falcon officials have said the deal will be restructured
before running its course.
</P>
<P>
   They have not talked, but Hall seems confident something good
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, if I play out this whole contract, I
would be way underpaid,'' he said. ``But I've just got to keep
producing, and ... hope we can work things out, and make things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall's health is mostly OK, although his right shoulder still
bothers him, after he torqued his arm at an odd angle last season.
</P>
<P>
   He usually plays left tackle, but he and right tackle Shane
Dronett have switched spots occasionally in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to maybe make our defensive line a little more
effective, give a different look,'' Hall said. ``Maybe we can keep
them guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
