<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEWS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trying to find a target
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ When training camp began more than a week
ago, the Falcons faced questions at wide receiver, where they are
trying to replace Tony Martin as a deep threat.
</P>
<P>
   When they hold two joint practices today with the Jacksonville
Jaguars, they will have more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Chris Calloway was expected to replace Martin, at
least as the starting split end if not a deep threat.
</P>
<P>
   But he suffered a high ankle sprain to his left leg Thursday,
and will be out at least a few weeks. After Calloway and starting
flanker Terance Mathis, Atlanta receivers have combined for 12 NFL
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway's replacement, six-year veteran Ronnie Harris, has
eight. Behind him, second-year man Tim Dwight, who had four catches
as a rookie, will augment his work today as a reserve flanker with
time at split end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for Ronnie and Tim to show what they can
do,'' quarterback Chris Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Harris will be Dwight and rookies Eugene Baker and Rondel
Menendez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looks more at your split receiver as your speed guy,
or your deep guy,'' receivers coach Rennie Simmons said. ``With
Terance and Chris, we could interchange them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would play havoc on some defenses, but that's not going
to work out for a while, until we get Chris back.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the four split-end candidates offers the target that the
6-foot-1, 180-pound Martin did. Martin, who is on trial on
money-laundering charges, was waived by the Falcons after he
refused to allow the team to postpone a $400,000 March 1 roster
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Harris (5-11, 185) runs pass routes well, and has a knack for
finding holes in coverage. However, Harris sometimes struggles to
get off the line cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight (5-8,180) has improved as a route runner, but he and
Menendez (5-9, 183) have been inconsistent catching the ball. Baker
(6-0, 167), who missed practice Friday because of a groin pull, has
the best hands, but is the slowest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, behind Mathis at flanker, second-year split end Jammi
German (6-1, 192) will change positions, and Octavus Barnes (6-2,
195) will get some work.
</P>
<P>
   German did not catch a pass as a rookie appearing in six games.
Barnes was on the practice squad last year. Rookie Eric Harris
(6-2, 214) has missed most of camp with a bad back. Corey Allen
(6-1, 200), who was cut last year, had a good practice Friday
morning, but remains a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (flanker) is ... involved more on the strong side,''
Simmons said. ``Since we're a strongside run team, you should have
a pretty good blocker. We do in Terance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jammi continually gets better. He gives us a pretty good range
receiver downfield, even though he may not be blessed with the same
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get familiar with (flanker),'' German said.
``It's more a matter of understanding what the defense is doing.
Watching Terance on film, he's so patient.''
</P>
<P>
   When the team uses a slot receiver, Mathis usually is the man.
Today, though, Simmons said Dwight will get extra repetitions
there. Mathis, Harris and German will work there, too. Coach Dan
Reeves said, ``These guys have to get a rapport with Chris
(Chandler) and convince him they can get open and catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
