<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-MAYORS-NYT &LR;      08-06 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MAYORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL COURT TAKES JUDICIAL ROLE FROM OHIO'S MAYORS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMWOOD PLACE, Ohio _ By court fiat, judicial gavels are being
snatched from the hands of small-town mayors across this state,
striking down an old tradition and leaving Mayor Richard Ellison
ruefully asking what's wrong with local justice proving more
kind-hearted than blind?
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who earns $6,900 a year as a one-stop symbol of law and
order and management in this humble blue-collar village of 2,900
souls, further asks what's so biased about a mayor's cutting
compassionate slack when he sits in judgment of some of the very
people who elected him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I only maxed out one guy in my court in the last six years,''
said the mayor, a nonlawyer who described how he threw the book at
a nasty drunk who had destroyed the tree flourishing outside
Charley's Bar a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three days in jail and $600,'' said Ellison, sounding
judicious to the last as he mourned the end of this state's
``strong mayor'' tradition of having local mayors, most of whom are
not lawyers, hear minor criminal cases ranging from disorderly
conduct to drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a traumatic thing, involving real-life circumstances,''
he declared, grateful to live so close to his neighbors in having
to judge them. ``There's more opportunity for compassion. It gives
you a good feeling to go home and say I think I got the message
across and didn't have to wipe out some family's fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   But a federal appellate decision last month found the system had
more potential for bias than compassion. Since mayors control town
budgets and police forces, the judges said, it could be unfair to
have them judge cases with local police officers as witnesses and
fines that can boost municipal coffers.
</P>
<P>
   A good part of the 400 mayoral courts in the state will be
affected and face the option of hiring trained lawyers as part-time
magistrates, said Augustin F. O'Neil, the lawyer who successfully
challenged the age-old mayors court system before the 6th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of an era?'' said O'Neil, hardly dewy-eyed at the loss
of this vestige of Ohio's small-town life. ``It should be the end
of an era. Frontier justice is what we have here,'' he said, citing
the Magna Carta in his successful argument that for a
revenue-hungry mayor to serve constituents as both police
administrator and judge presents a conflict of authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with power and egos, just as anytime politics is
involved.'' O'Neil declared in an interview. He said some of the
``strong mayors'' _ those who run a municipality without the
insulation of a separate city manager _ are as dictatorial as
big-city machine bosses. ``A lot of these burgs generate big
revenues from mayors courts. Under that robe, a mayor in effect
wears a badge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, a 64-year-old retired truck company manager who has
presided at thousands of cases, sadly dissents, fearing the ruling
is a step toward ``metropolitan'' government of centralized court
systems in which smaller jurisdictions like his will eventually be
eclipsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the criminal factor so much as that personal, that
family, that social and emotional value,'' explained the mayor who
always presided in jacket and tie, never a robe. ``A family I know
might stand before me heartbroken over some dirt-bag son or brother
or cousin. They talk directly to me, hoping for some mitigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor understands the basis of the court ruling, for he
recalls his boyhood days of peddling newspapers in the now-departed
illegal gambling dens of this hamlet, before the interstate highway
was built. ``A mayor could be a dictator in those days, but they
were benevolent dictators,'' said Ellison, honoring the memory of
such predecessors as Art ``Butch'' Wise, a local butcher remembered
for a heart of gold and an iron hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was Otto Hessler, came over from Lichtenstein
as a young man and ran the village for 27 years,'' said Ellison.
``If you needed anything _ a ton of coal in a hard winter _ Otto
was the man who'd get it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayors of Ohio are hardly unanimous in regretting the loss
of their gavels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayors now are facing the possibility of liability _ that's
the crux of their problem,'' said John E. Gotherman, counsel of the
Ohio Municipal League, a nonprofit association of village and city
executives. ``Most mayors are concerned to protect their
municipalities and themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling grew out of a 1994 case in Macedonia in which a
citizen charged his civil rights were violated when the mayor
responded spiritedly to an unpaid traffic ticket with an arrest
warrant plus a contempt of court charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly won't miss the hassle,'' said Mayor Elbert
Tannreuther of Monroe, who has sat in judgment of more than 10,000
cases for the past 13 years in his city of 7,000 residents. ``The
people you see in court today include a lot of repeaters, people
with just absolutely no respect for the system. I wasn't built that
way,'' he said, finding the court a catchbasin for the city's
underlife more than its wayward charm. ``It was depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison agrees it could be depressing _ but also redeeming. ``I
worked closely with Bob Newman, a legitimate liberal, as
prosecutor,'' said the mayor, who describes himself as an
unreconstructed Goldwater man. ``We weren't out to hang anyone,
because that $100 fine might mean a bicycle for some guy's kid. And
the 15 grand we'll pay for a magistrate _ well, that could go for a
new roof for town hall.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil, the lawyer who challenged the mayors courts, says there
must be more to small-town life than nostalgia for the old ways.
``Justice needs to be blind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellison, who has read bits of law in his years as a judge,
cites his own favorite prescription, a maxim from British law, he
said, on how to be a successful judge: ``First of all be a
gentleman. If you know a little law, so much the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
