<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-LAWNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST DRIED-UP LAWNS ARE DORMANT, NOT DEAD, AND LIKELY TO REVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news for lovers of velvety lawns is that much of the
grass underfoot these blistering summer days looks and feels like
Shredded Wheat _ harsh on the eyes and splintery on the bottom of
feet. And if lawns are not crispy now, they will be once the
sprinklers are ordered turned off, as they have been in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that most of the lawns now brown and dusty are
not dead but merely dormant. They will return to green luxuriance
in the fall, experts in turf grass management agree, especially if
they were well cared for before the extreme weather this summer and
not mowed or trampled while in a stressed state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of perennial grasses,'' said James Murphy, a
turf specialist at Rutgers University Cooperative Extension. ``They
will return when the rains return.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics can check for themselves whether the withered thatch in
their backyard is ruined or just resting. ``Get down on your hands
and knees and look at the crown of the plant, just at the soil
line,'' said Tom Smith, a horticulturist at the University of
Cincinnati. Beneath the yellow blades should be a point of green
and below that a healthy root system, protecting itself now and
waiting to rebound later.
</P>
<P>
   That is the rule, but there will be exceptions, the experts say,
depending on the species of grass, the type of soil, the depth of
the root system and the duration of the drought.
</P>
<P>
   Grass that has been watered extensively but infrequently, rather
than drizzled on a daily basis, has the best chance of survival
because it develops a deeper root system. So does grass that has
been mowed to a height of two to three inches, not given a buzz
cut, because the crown stays cooler and the extra leaf matter
promotes photosynthesis.
</P>
<P>
   The duration of the drought and the severity of the heat could
change the outcome. The benchmark number, experts say, is 60 days,
meaning that most grass will survive two months without any water,
even in temperatures of 90 degrees or hotter, regardless of its
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   George Hamilton, a senior lecturer on turf grass science at
Pennsylvania State University, sees no magic in the 60-day limit,
since shade, fertilization and proper cultivation all come into
play. But there is a ``permanent wilting point,'' Hamilton said,
when a dormant plant that has slowed its respiration will stop
breathing entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Ashton Ritchie, an agronomist at Scotts Co. in Marysville, Ohio,
the country's leading supplier of lawn care products, said that
people who live in areas where sprinkling is still permitted can
protect their grass with minimal water. A lawn that is the envy of
the neighborhood takes an inch of water a week, Ritchie said. But a
quarter-inch every two weeks ``is just enough to keep it from
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the grass looks hopelessly dead, experts agree,
homeowners and landscapers can influence its ability to recover.
They suggest that the owners stop mowing and try to keep children
from trampling the dry mat. Also, they say, use no fertilizer or
pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving lawns will not be trouble free, however. Summer weeds,
like crab grass, flourish when it is hot and dry, experts say, and
thus will be more prevalent next year. Also, humidity promotes lawn
disease and pests, which can run rampant in grass that wore itself
out staying alive in trying conditions.
</P>
<P>
   All of these experts say they have stopped watering their own
lawns. William A. Torello, a professor of turf grass management at
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, was one of several
experts who said that the parched grass is easier to tolerate if
one considers it ``blond'' rather than ``brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Torello also urged some revisionist thinking about weeds. ``A
lot of people are perfectly happy with crab grass,'' he said. ``At
least it's green.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
