</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NAIROBI, Kenya -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-2,
08-06 -- Douglas Sidialo, blinded last year in the bombing of the
U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, at a Red Cross food distribution center in
the Kenyan capital. Sidialo, a car salesman who drove around
Nairobi for his job, was blinded by glass and debris that exploded
through his windshield. More than 200 people were killed and 5,000
wounded in Nairobi and in a simultaneous attack on the U.S. Embassy
in Tanzania. (Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NAIROBI, Kenya -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- EMBASSY-BOMBINGS,
08-06 -- Francis Gitu Maina, 33, who was severely injured last year
in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, during a recent
interview. Maina lost his right eye and cannot see well in his
left. He can barely walk, because his right leg was broken so
badly. When his wife saw that he could not provide anymore, he
said, she left him with their two children. (Ian Fisher/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- NY-PATAKI-GIULIANI, 08-06
-- Gov. George Pataki announces his endorsement of New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the U.S. Senate on Friday. Seeking to
avoid a civil war that could poison the Republicans' chances next
year, Pataki on Friday put aside his longstanding antipathy toward
Giuliani and announced the endorsement. (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights -- Aug. 06, 1999 --
GOLAN-HEIGHTS, 08-06 -- Druze children practice their handstands
under Syrian flags in a summer camp called ``Withdrawal'' in the
northern region of the Golan Heights. The name of the camp, where
more than 300 youngsters spend 10 days of patriotic fervor within
sight of Syria and under occasional surveillance by the Israeli
authorities, underscores the cry for an Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan. The strategic plateau was captured from Syria in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war and annexed by Israel in 1981. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) COSTA MESA, Calif. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 8 -- WHITWORTH-PROFILE, 08-06 -- Exemplifying the growing
power of corporate shareholders, Ralph V. Whitworth is now the
chairman of Waste Management. Indeed, Whitworth is the avatar of a
trend: With a style that is surprisingly low-key for a one-time
rabble-rouser, he is helping transform the role of shareholder
activist from outside agitator to inside operator. (Edward
Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) RANCHO BERNARDO, Calif. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., AUG. 8 -- BIZ-MORTGAGE-LOANS, 08-06 -- Ray Rawlins, shootibg
pool in the recreation room of his home in Rancho Bernardo, is
benefiting from a lower rate on an existing mortgage. ``All we had
to do was go down to the escrow company and sign the papers,'' he
says. (Dave Gatley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
8 -- BIZ-EMPLOYEES-PERKS, 08-06 -- At Inc. magazine's meeting of
winning entrepreneurs are, from left, Robert Murphy, president, and
Joel Adams and Samuel Frederick, principals, of Assigned Counsel.
While the group tackled more than a few heady topics during the
three-day event, the most pressing issue for the entrepreneurs -
whose companies, on average, are just eight-years-old - was simple:
keeping good employees and hiring others like them. (Chris
Berkey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MONMOUTH, N.J. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- DROUGHT-MOSQUITOS,
08-06 -- Daniel Markowski, an entomolgist with Monmouth County
Mosquito Extermination Commission, counts mosquitos that collected
from traps earlier this week. As one of the hottest and driest
summers in history plagues farmers throughout the Eastern Seaboard
and Midwest, consider this the up side: mosquitoes are as scarce as
the little puddles and pools their eggs need to hatch. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- FRUITY-DESSERTS-LADN,
08-06 -- Plums, with whipping cream and yogurt, make a colorful
finale to a fine meal. With plums, the color is characteristic of
the variety, so choose by the amount of give. (Los Angeles Daily
News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
DESIGNER-TAILORS-3, 08-06 -- Ned Mateosian fits Frank Perich, an
actor who appears in ``Summer of Sam,'' into a suit at his
Manhattan tailor shop. ``There is clearly an element of remarkably
young, very successful people going to tailors without fail,'' says
Suzanne Kilgore, the executive director of the 300-member Custom
Tailors and Designers Association in Washington. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
DESIGNER-TAILORS-2, 08-06 -- Eva Devecsery fitting a client, Joy
Bogen, who is a cabaret singer, in her Manhattan tailor shop. Until
the advent of designer ready-to-wear in the late 1960s,
dressmakers' salons were mainly the province of fashionable matrons
ordering copies of the Paris haute couture. But that has changed.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
DESIGNER-TAILORS-1, 08-06 -- Felicia Farrar, who apprenticed in the
workrooms of Azzedine Alaia and Herve Leger in Paris, with a
client, Hana Wiczyk, in her shop on Seventh Avenue. Taking a cue
from professional clothes hangers and social swans, many insist
that a $500 custom suit or dress made in the style of a Gucci or a
Dior is just as chic and often more deftly constructed than the
$2,000 original. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
MCDOWELL-ANTIQUES, 08-06 -- Malcolm McDowell, the actor and
collector, at the apartment-showroom of Steven Weiss, an antiques
dealer. ``It's something else to do, away from the damn movies,''
McDowell says during an afternoon spent searching for antique
watches, painted Shaker furniture and 19th-century flywheel toys.
McDowell, 56, collects with the same wild-eyed intensity that makes
him such a distinctive, often disturbing actor. (Miles Ladin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
HUTZ-MENSWEAR, 08-06 -- Eugene Hutz walks the runway at a recent
men's fashion show. Hutz - aka ``Mr. mustache'' - is also a member
of a Ukrainian punk rock band called Gogol Bordello. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
MONEY-CLIPS, 08-06 -- Square shape or pear shape, money clips help
keep bills from losing their shape. The ones shown here are all
sterling silver, from Barneys, ranging from $55 to $200. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) KING OF PRUSSIA, Pa. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 8 -- TEEN-BUSINESS-CAMP, 08-06 -- Michael Rubin, 27, the
chairman of Global Sports Inc., meets with campers at the Julian
Krinsky summer business camp. By age 14, Rubin - who has ``role
model'' written all over him - had opened his first sporting-goods
store. At 22, he was dubbed a mogul by The Wall Street Journal.
Now, his company is shifting focus to the Internet. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- CNN-WILLOW-BAY, 08-06 --
Willow Bay and Stuart Varney, co-anchors of the ``Moneyline News
Hour.'' When Lou Dobbs, the previous anchor resigned in June, it
was no suprise that Stuart Varney, a longtime CNN financial-news
correspondent in the Dobbsian mold, was named co-anchor. But many
on Wall Street were surprised by the choice of Varney's partner:
Willow Bay. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- CONGRESS-RECESS-2, 08-06
-- With Congress in recess, a visitor to the Capitol on Friday
makes use of an umbrella normally shading a U.S. Capitol police
officer. With its tax cut behind it, Congress left for its August
recess setting the stage for a high stakes autumn confrontation
with President Clinton over what should be the nation's fiscal
policies in an era of budget surplusses. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) JERUSALEM -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ISRAEL-VIOLENCE, 08-06 --
An Israeli border police officer keeps watch over a gathering in
Zion Square. Israel has always had a rough edge, always been a
society where aggression and rudeness were accepted as byproducts
of life under siege. But there has been an abrupt shift in this
view in recent months. There has emerged an intense focus on the
issue of internal, domestic violence that has temporarily pushed
aside the historic focus on conflict with the Arabs. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
CAR-SMART-CADILLAC-2, 08-06 -- Cadillac has taken the wraps off its
2000 DeVille, which goes on sale next month. Breaking a 50-year
tradition, the rear bears only the faintest suggestion of the
tailfins that made their debut on 1948 Cadillacs, a year before the
Coupe de Ville was born. The new design is a bridge between the
DeVille's recent corpulence and a sharp-edged, high-tech look yet
to come. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
CAR-SMART-CADILLAC-1-B&AMP;W, 08-06 -- The first Cadillac Coupe de
Ville, of 1949. Cadillac has taken the wraps off its 2000 DeVille,
which goes on sale next month. Breaking a 50-year tradition, the
rear bears only the faintest suggestion of the tailfins that made
their debut on 1948 Cadillacs, a year before the Coupe de Ville was
born. The new design is a bridge between the DeVille's recent
corpulence and a sharp-edged, high-tech look yet to come. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 8 --
ABOUT-CARS-TOYOTA, 08-06 -- Toyota has decided to really compete in
the full-sized pickup truck market. Not only does it have a brand
new truck, the 2000 Tundra (its biggest truck yet), but also a new
$1.2 billion assembly plant in Princeton, Ind. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- CONGRESS-RECESS, 08-06 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, D-Miss., and Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchinson, R-Texas, right, walk to a press conference on Capitol
Hill, Friday. With its tax cut behind it, Congress left for its
August recess setting the stage for a high stakes autumn
confrontation with President Clinton over what should be the
nation's fiscal policies in an era of budget surplusses. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- NJ-DROUGHT, 08-06 --
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, second from right, speaks to
the New Jersey Congressional delegation on Friday which included
Rep. Marge Roukema, left, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, center and Sen.
Robert Torricelli, right. The New Jersey delegation asked for
federal assistance to provide relief for counties suffering damages
from the ongoing drought. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BETHEL, Alaska -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ALASKA-BUSH-PILOTS-2,
08-06 --Daryl Smith, a bush pilot who flies for Yukon Aviation,
looks over weather information as Yukon's co-owner and dispatcher
Cindy Andrecheck looks on. Crisscrossing the vast gray-green tundra
of southwest Alaska, the bush pilots of Yukon Aviation fly
high-school teams to games, shoppers to market, patients to
hospitals, jurors to court, criminals to prison and even dead
people in body bags to the coroner. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEWTOK, Alaska -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- ALASKA-BUSH-PILOTS-1,
08-06 --Daryl Smith, a bush pilot who flies for Yukon Aviation,
based in Bethel, talks to some curious children at a landing strip
in the village. Crisscrossing the vast gray-green tundra of
southwest Alaska, the bush pilots of Yukon Aviation fly high-school
teams to games, shoppers to market, patients to hospitals, jurors
to court, criminals to prison and even dead people in body bags to
the coroner. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SALEM, N.H. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- RAC-JOCKEY-INJURED, 08-06
-- Rudy Baez, the top jockey in New England, in a 1995 photo. Baez
was paralyzed from the waist down when his spinal cord was severed
in a spill, his agent said. Baez was thrown from his mount when the
horse went down in a race Wednesday at Rockingham Park in Salem.
The horse, Gaitor Bait, clipped the heels of the horse in front of
him. The 49-year-old Baez was in serious condition and on a
ventilator on Friday after seven hours of surgery at a Boston
hospital.(Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- BBO-UMPIRES-BOS, 08-06 --
Umpires from left: Rich Garcia, Lazaro Diaz, Mike Reilly and Brian
O'Nora during a game between the Boston Red Sox and the New York
Yankees last Friday. This group, headed by Garcia, represented the
ideological spectrum in the imbroglio that has resulted in the
dismissal of 22 of the 66 major league umpires, effective Sept. 2.
It also has created a gulf of dissension within the union ranks,
turning longtime friends against one another on some issues and in
other cases making enemies of people who invariably describe their
select fraternity as ``like a family.'' (Evan Richman/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- AIR-RAGE-BOS, 08-06 --
Patricia Paiva, trying to get to Florida for some vacation, sits
atop her suitcase as people all around her check to see if their
flights were cancelled or delayed at Logan Airport last Wednesday.
Ever since airlines were deregulated in the late 1970s, the number
of air travelers has skyrocketed, from 275 million in 1978 to 614
million in 1998. The sharp increase in passengers, fueled by
cheaper fares, has meant more flights, more planes, more
overcrowding, more delays, and the phenomenon known as ``air
rage.'' (Justine Ellement/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BURLINGTON, Mass. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- NEWSEDGE-LANG-BOS,
08-06 --Ilene Lang, head of NewsPage.com, serves up a slice of her
on-line news service in her office. Lang, 55, who ran Altavista,
the internet search engine, for Digital Equipment Corp., is once
again trying to build an Internet business under the aegis of a
larger parent company. This time it's NewsEdge Corp., a 400-person
firm that uses computers and humans to serve up electronic news
reports to corporate executives. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
