<P>
   (NYT33) ATLANTA -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- TAIWAN-COX, 08-04 -- Georgia
State students from mainland China have been shaking their heads
over Taiwan's actions. ``It's an old issue,'' says Xiaohui Wang, a
graduate student who was born in Shanghai. ``It's already agreed
that they are part of China. Now all of a sudden they make this
statement that they want to be isolated.'' (Julie Bryant/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. -- Aug. 06, 1999 --
MIDEAST-TEACHERS, 08-06 -- Judith Zilberman of Israel, Hani
el-Akkad of Gaza and Zahia Khashab Fakih of Lebanon, all teachers,
exchanging ideas Thursday as a symposium at Boston College winds
down with a clambake. The exchange was but one snippet of an
improbable dialogue among 19 high school teachers from seven Middle
Eastern nations and territories that stretched over four weeks,
ending Friday. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- FBN-JETS, 08-06 --
An NFL official demonstrates the proper grooming for the balls used
by kickers this season at Jets camp Friday. Only officials will
manipulate the ball the kickers use, and the officials will have a
specially made brush to make each ball smooth. (Vic DeLucia/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NAIROBI, Kenya -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-2,
08-06 -- Douglas Sidialo, blinded last year in the bombing of the
U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, at a Red Cross food distribution center in
the Kenyan capital. Sidialo, a car salesman who drove around
Nairobi for his job, was blinded by glass and debris that exploded
through his windshield. More than 200 people were killed and 5,000
wounded in Nairobi and in a simultaneous attack on the U.S. Embassy
in Tanzania. (Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NAIROBI, Kenya -- Aug. 06, 1999 -- EMBASSY-BOMBINGS,
08-06 -- Francis Gitu Maina, 33, who was severely injured last year
in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, during a recent
interview. Maina lost his right eye and cannot see well in his
left. He can barely walk, because his right leg was broken so
badly. When his wife saw that he could not provide anymore, he
said, she left him with their two children. (Ian Fisher/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
