<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drought spreads to northeast
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern farmers are glancing nervously at the sky
with the return of hot, dry weather, but the region is faring
better than their neighbors to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, Delaware, New Jersey and Rhode Island are suffering
their worst droughts this century.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's corn crop has been hit hard, and farmers now
are worried about cotton crops that had been expected to be the
best in years. In Virginia, some dairy farmers in the Shenandoah
Valley are hauling water to their farms because wells and ponds
have dried up.
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, critically low water supplies have led to a ban
on outdoor water use in several communities.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Friday that the drought in the northeast
threatens to cripple businesses and communities in the hardest hit
farm communities. ``Throughout much of this country, we have seen
the worst drought since the Dust Bowl days,'' Clinton said before
leaving the White House for a weekend trip to Arkansas and
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a natural calamity can have devastating consequences, not
only for farmers, but for small businesses and communities that
depend upon a thriving agricultural sector, and for the electric
power system so vital to our nation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the mid-Atlantic region already has been declared a
federal disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hurting some, but nowhere to the extent of those
states,'' said Allen Tyree, cooperative extension agent in Hamilton
County, an area of northern Florida that produces tobacco, cotton,
peanuts and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, agricultural economist Keith Kightlinger of Tift
County said, ``We are back into a dry situation, but rain in July
helped us a lot. We have not had prolonged dryness.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is faring better this summer than last, but two
dozen municipalities have enacted water restrictions. At this
point, most are voluntary, including in Charlotte and Raleigh. But
Cary, Morrisville and Holly Springs _ in the Raleigh area _ have
mandatory curbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do get some rain, we will see more systems going to
conservation,'' said Tony Young, chairman of the North Carolina
Drought Monitoring Council. ``Things have gotten a little bit more
serious lately.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina farmers ``have gotten rain at critical times when
they needed it. Crops are doing relatively well,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Southeast Regional Climate Center in Columbia,
S.C., the region's dry spots include northern Florida, all of South
Carolina, especially the Pee Dee region, southwestern Georgia and
central Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation as a whole is quite dry,'' said Sam McCown, a
meteorologist with the National Climatic Data Center in Asheville,
N.C. ``There are very few areas that are considered wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has been spared serious drought, but forecasters say a
few more days of dry weather could change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the edge. If we go another week without rain, we
could be in trouble,'' said Gene Danekas, a statistician for the
state and federal agriculture departments in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas of the nation ``are in the grips of a drought of
historic proportions,'' Deputy Commerce Secretary Robert L. Mallett
said. And there was little promise for relief.
</P>
<P>
   Many parts of the East are 8 to 18 inches below normal rainfall,
and while the outlook is for a return to normal rainfall, that will
not make up the deficit, said James Baker, head of the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drought did not happen overnight ... and it will take a
long time to be alleviated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the drought has not
affected commodity and consumer prices because it is not impacting
the large growing regions of the Midwest and California.
</P>
<P>
   By being concentrated in the East, the dry period has been
particularly hard on smaller farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will convene a task force of affected federal
agencies ``to coordinate our efforts and focus our attack on this
problem,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he thinks Congress will come through
with emergency farm money soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a special provision to deal with the drought
crisis, and I hope ... and believe that there will be,'' Clinton
said in response to a reporter's question about criticism of the
administration's efforts so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have done it before the August recess,''
Clinton said, referring to a vacation break in Congress. ``But I
think it will be there in time to aid the farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved $7.4 billion in emergency farm aid on
Wednesday. The House will consider an emergency aid package after
the recess.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
