</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S RULING PARTY SAYS IT WON'T PRESS ON BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The ruling Liberal Democratic Party said Friday that it
would not press the Bank of Japan to buy Japanese government bonds
that are likely to be used to finance further fiscal stimulus
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The issue had become a major point of contention between the
central bank and politicians, who were worried earlier this year
that Japan's rapidly growing debts would force them to raise
interest rates to attract buyers for new government bond issues.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff attracted the interest of economists and
international investors, who viewed it it as a test of Japan's
commitment to free-market principles, one of which is the
maintenance of a central bank free of political interference.
</P>
<P>
   Michio Ochi, chairman of the party's Financial Issues Research
Council, said that the party thought there were other ways to keep
interest rates low now that the economy had shown signs of
stability. ``We are discussing how to develop the bond market so
that it will no longer be necessary to discuss underwriting by the
Bank of Japan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan has campaigned vigorously against the proposal
since politicians floated it in February, saying that forcing it to
buy bonds would cause inflation, undermine confidence in its
independence and possibly lead to a downgrade of Japan's credit
quality by ratings agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the improving economic outlook here provided the
underpinning for the party's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember in January and February, we still had very much of a
sense of crisis here in Japan, and as a result of that, there were
calls for all kinds of policies, radical policies, to be taken,''
said Jesper Koll, chief economist at Merrill Lynch in Tokyo. ``Now,
the economy has stabilized, the sense of crisis has abated and they
can start to be politically correct again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
