<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOB CREATION SURGED IN JULY; JOBLESS RATE UNCHANGED
</P>
<P>
   Employers added an estimated 310,000 nonfarm jobs in July, 50
percent more than analysts had anticipated, suggesting that
economic growth rebounded early in the summer after tailing off in
the spring. Meanwhile, the unemployment rate in July remained
steady at 4.3 percent, the Labor Department said.
</P>
<P>
   The report underscored the mounting pressures in the labor
market and substantially increased the likelihood that the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates at its next meeting, on Aug. 24,
as a hedge against an inflationary spiral in wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON NOMINATES A BANK EXPERT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton nominated Roger Ferguson, a former management
consultant whose monetary views are not widely known, to be vice
chairman of the Federal Reserve. Ferguson, who has served as a Fed
governor for two years, was a banking consultant and a partner at
McKinsey before he joined the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   DOW JONES AVERAGE FALLS 80 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks resumed their slide. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 79.79 points, to 10,714.03, erasing more than half its
119-point gain on Thursday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
was down 13.42 points, to 1,300.29, and the Nasdaq composite index
declined 17.86 points, to 2,547.97.
</P>
<P>
   Yields of Treasury bonds surged to 6.17 percent, from 6.04
percent on Thursday, the highest since 6.2 percent on Nov. 20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   JURY AWARDS $23 MILLION IN DIET SUIT
</P>
<P>
   In the first verdict from among thousands of cases pending
against makers of the diet pills popularly known as fen-phen, an
east Texas jury awarded $23.36 million to a woman who said she
suffered heart damage after taking the drugs to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO AND SCANIA PLANNING TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   In a $7.4 billion deal that will create the world's
second-largest maker of trucks and buses, Sweden's Volvo agreed to
acquire its arch-rival Scania. The agreement comes just 15 months
after the merger of Chrysler and Daimler created the world's
largest truck and bus maker.
</P>
<P>
   GM MOVES TOWARD DAEWOO DEAL
</P>
<P>
   A General Motors executive said the company had signed an
agreement with South Korea's struggling Daewoo Group that could
lead to an alliance between GM and Daewoo Motor, Daewoo's core
holding. A deal between the two companies would help GM increase
its share of car sales in Asia, while for Daewoo it would bring
much-needed capital as well as management expertise.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH BANK'S BID STILL UNCERTAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Banque Nationale de Paris chairman told a French daily he
was certain of obtaining ``indisputable power of control'' over
Societe Generale and that Banque Nationale had firm commitments
through investors to get more than 50 percent of Paribas shares.
But the statements by Michel Pebereau fell short of asserting that
Banque Nationale would receive enough voting stock in Societe
Generale to assert clear control.
</P>
<P>
   STANDOFF OVER BANK OF JAPAN EASES
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Liberal Democratic Party said it would not press the
Bank of Japan to buy government bonds that are likely to be used to
finance further fiscal stimulus programs. Economists had viewed a
standoff over the issue as a test of Japan's commitment to free
market principles, including maintenance of a central bank free of
political interference.
</P>
<P>
   PARTIAL FIX FOR SOFTWARE FLAW
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft released a partial fix for a security flaw in the
company's Office 97 suite of programs. The company acknowledged
that the fix was not satisfactory but said it was still testing a
better solution that it planned to make available to customers
during the week of Aug. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
