<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITWORTH-PROFILE-ART     08-06 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITWORTH-PROFILE-ART-3TAKES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDER? GADFLY? CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, Ore., Nev., Md., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
annotated stock of Apria, performance of Relational Investors fund
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Waste Management Inc. was in trouble as its board
met for dinner four weeks ago at the Four Seasons Hotel near its
headquarters in Houston. Its chairman and chief executive was
sidelined by a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   The company had just announced that earnings would be below
projections, sending its stock plunging 37 percent in one day. To
make matters worse, many executives had sold shares in the weeks
before the bad news was revealed, prompting a bevy of shareholder
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The directors knew they needed to put one of their number in
command. Looking around the room, their eyes fell upon a person
whom most corporate executives and directors would have once kept
as far from the board table as possible _ Ralph V. Whitworth.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Whitworth had been a corporate raider, an aide to
the Texas oilman T. Boone Pickens. In the early 1990s, he was a
corporate gadfly, railing against overpaid executives and
underperforming companies.
</P>
<P>
   On this Monday, however, he was elected Waste Management's
interim chairman. ``It was a good, warm, fuzzy feeling all
around,'' said Steve Miller, a board member and himself a former
chairman of the company.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better measure of the growing power of investors
than the fact that a corporate critic can become a chairman of a
Fortune 500 company. Indeed, Whitworth is the avatar of a trend:
With a style that is surprisingly low-key for a one-time
rabble-rouser, he is helping transform the role of shareholder
activist from outside agitator to inside operator.
</P>
<P>
   Relational Investors LLC, an investment fund he runs with David
H. Batchelder, takes stakes in companies it thinks are
under-performing and need shaking up. Many, in Relational's view,
have dysfunctional boards or executives who disdain shareholder
interests. Relational then uses its leverage as a shareholder to
try to bring about change, gaining board seats if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard of extreme sports,'' said Nell Minow, a principal
of Lens Investment Management, a fund in Washington, D.C., with a
similar strategy. ``This is extreme shareholder activism.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach is not that surprising, given that the biggest
investor in Whitworth's fund is the California Public Employees
Retirement System, or Calpers, the huge and powerful pension fund
that has long been a leader in activist investing.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by $750 million in investor funds _ including $500
million from Calpers _ Whitworth, 43, has become the chairman of
Apria Healthcare Group, a home health care provider in Costa Mesa,
Calif., that he seems to have turned around. And last month he won
a board seat at Tektronix, an Oregon electronics company.
</P>
<P>
   But Waste Management could prove the most daunting test of
whether such shareholders can make good managers. Only two weeks
after Whitworth was named acting chairman, the company lowered its
second-quarter earnings projections for a second time. And
Whitworth got a taste of his own medicine, as angry investors on a
conference call contended that the company was out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no turmoil here,'' he replied, somewhat defensively.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, precedents for what Relational Investors
is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate raiders and leveraged-buyout firms look for situations
ripe for restructuring. But their strategy is to buy the company.
Relational Investors acts more as a catalyst than a conqueror, with
the target company remaining public.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Price, the mutual fund manager, used big shareholdings
to help force the merger of Chase Manhattan and Chemical Bank. But
many institutional investors become involved with companies only if
an investment goes sour.
</P>
<P>
   Relational actively looks for underperforming companies it can
fix, a strategy sometimes called relationship or relational
investing. Similar funds include Greenway Partners, formed by
former aides to Carl Icahn; Trinity I Fund, run by Thomas Taylor, a
fund manager for the Bass brothers of Texas; Active Value, based in
London, and Lawndale Capital in San Francisco. Relational is one of
the biggest and, along with Lens, the best known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly isn't unknown in the past for key investors in
troubled companies to step into leadership roles,'' said Scott
Fenn, executive director of the Investor Responsibility Research
Center in Washington. ``What is a newer phenomenon is to take
positions in companies from a governance perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whitworth says taking a board seat is a last resort. Between
them, Whitworth and Batchelder, 50, are on the boards of only 4 of
the 24 companies they have invested in, though that is a majority
of their seven current holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate success for us is if we can get the companies to
undertake the changes on their own without the need for us to get
intensely involved,'' Whitworth said. ``But we have to be willing
and able to get intensely involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Relational has had an annualized return of 33.8 percent from its
inception in March 1996 through June 30 of this year, according to
Calpers. Its return for the year ending June 30 was 31 percent, and
its three-year return was an annualized 38.2 percent, surpassing
the 22.8 percent and 29.1 percent returns of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 for the same periods.
</P>
<P>
   For the stocks it has already sold out of, Relational reports an
annualized return of 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that performance, relationship investing is a risky
business. Board membership makes an investor a corporate insider,
limiting the freedom to buy and sell shares, and subjects the
investor to shareholder lawsuits. It can raise suspicions among
other shareholders that the one with the board seat will benefit at
their expense.
</P>
<P>
   There are also questions about whether such activists have the
vision to work for the long-term future of the company or just want
to produce a quick uptick in the stock and sell out.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does board membership come with the guarantee of a
turnaround. Taylor, the Bass Brothers' fund manager, was on the
board of Loewen Group, a Canadian funeral home company, when it
sought bankruptcy protection. John A. Bricker Jr. of Sandera
Partners, another activist investor, was on the board of General
Housewares of Terre Haute, Ind., but could not get the company to
follow his advice.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Greenway Partners lost a proxy fight to elect
directors of Venator Group Inc., the company once known as
Woolworth. And Lens has never won a board seat at a company in its
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Relational, as well, typically meets with resistance from
executives. But Whitworth is disarmingly persuasive and personable,
skills he honed during his time as a Washington lobbyist. He has
avoided proxy fights so far, although he has threatened them on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   At Tektronix, where an unprofitable video equipment business was
bleeding the company, the chief executive, Jerome J. Meyer,
initially opposed giving Whitworth a seat on the board when
Relational emerged earlier this year with a nearly 10 percent
stake.
</P>
<P>
   But after checking Relational's track record, Meyer changed his
mind. ``It's quite a different situation from the fast-buck guys,''
Meyer told The Oregonian last month. He declined to be interviewed
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the seat, Relational agreed not to wage a proxy
fight and to limit its stake to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth learned early the value of fixing things. As a
teen-ager in his tiny, remote hometown of Winnemuca, Nev., he loved
to repair appliances. His ability to fix the city's irrigation
system landed him a job as superintendent of parks at the age of
19.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he headed to the University of Nevada at Reno and
then to law school at Georgetown. His father, a mining engineer,
died while he was in college, so Whitworth worked his way through
law school, for Nevada Sen. Paul Laxalt, and sent money home to his
family. He also worked in President Ronald Reagan's 1984
re-election campaign, keeping his student status to himself.
</P>
<P>
   His political work led to his meeting Pickens. Whitworth briefly
dated the oilman's daughter, Liz, but his work relationship with
the father lasted longer. Whitworth joined Mesa Petroleum, where he
participated in efforts to take over companies like Unocal and
Newmont Mining. It was there that he also met Batchelder, Pickens'
right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Pickens set up the United Shareholders Association in
Washington to champion the rights of small shareholders. He put
Whitworth in charge. While the organization was sometimes derided
as merely a front for Pickens' political ambitions, Whitworth
became a shareholder activist to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   United Shareholders published a list of 50 companies each year
that it made the target of negative publicity and a barrage of
shareholder resolutions. Its proxy battle with IBM helped pressure
the board into ousting its president, John Akers.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth also lobbied in 1992 for regulatory changes that,
among other things, made it possible for dissidents to nominate
only one or two directors to a board, rather than an entire slate.
This later became key to Relational's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993, United Shareholders did something extraordinary for
a Washington lobbying group. It declared that it had accomplished
its goals and shut down. Others suspected that Pickens, who had
faded from the limelight, had grown tired of subsidizing the group.
Whitworth worked at the association without pay, supporting himself
as a corporate lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Whitworth had received a telephone call from his
old Mesa colleague, Batchelder, who was running a
mergers-and-acquisition advisory firm in San Diego. Calpers was
looking to invest in an activist fund, Batchelder told him, so the
two teamed up and won out over about seven other contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Calpers concluded that it could not get so actively involved
itself in companies, but figured that it could improve the overall
performance of its portfolio by having Relational stalk a few
underperformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have to bring down a couple of wildebeests to get the
herd moving in the right direction,'' said Sheryl Pressler, chief
investment officer of Calpers. Other investors in Relational
include Hermes, an activist British pension fund, and the pension
funds of Maryland and San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   Batchelder, whose advisory firm is in an adjoining suite,
provides financial acumen to Relational. A third managing member,
Joel L. Reed, who also comes from the Texas oil industry, mainly
works for Batchelder's firm. Whitworth is often Relational's face
to its targets.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and associates describe Whitworth as honest and
thoughtful, cool in a crisis and graceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows everyone on my staff,'' said Sarah Teslik, executive
director of the Council of Institutional Investors, a
Washington-based association of pension funds. ``He knows the
lowest of the low. He knows about their spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he can talk to anyone, she said, she sits him next to
the shyest people at her functions. When Ms. Teslik mentioned to
Whitworth that she had hurt her knee running, a book on runners'
medical problems soon showed up in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth describes himself as a family man who tries to get
home by 5 p.m. He likes to cook, and his designs for columns on the
veranda of his former home on the Potomac River in Washington were
featured in some architecture magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Here in San Diego, the walls and shelves of his office are
festooned with photographs of his two young children and his wife,
Wendy Walker, the executive producer of the ``Larry King Show.''
CNN built a control room in the couple's new home in Rancho Santa
Fe, north of San Diego, so that Ms. Walker could work there almost
as if she were in King's Washington or Los Angeles studios.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth's political instincts have helped in his corporate
battles. Relational picks its fights carefully. In fact, some
corporate executives say the fund merely jumps in the front of
moving parades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what they are about with regard to corporate
governance we were well on the way to accomplishing,'' said Douglas
L. Foshee, chairman and chief executive of Nuevo Energy, a Houston
oil company where Relational has a 9.65 percent stake and
Batchelder holds a board seat.
</P>
<P>
   Tektronix officials say they decided on their own to split into
two companies and sell off a money-losing division, all things that
Whitworth pushed for. Whitworth took a board seat, he said, to make
sure that the company goes through with the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Relational invested in the Storage Technology Corp., a
Colorado company that makes data storage devices, urging a $1
billion stock buyback. Michael Klatman, vice president for
corporate relations, said Storage had already decided by then on a
buyback, though not on its size. Other investors had been urging a
similar course, he said, though Relational set itself apart by
doing its own financial analysis.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months later, Whitworth went public with his
demands. Soon, Storage announced an $800 million buyback, about
twice as large as analysts had been expecting. Whoever deserves the
credit, the stock shot up, and Relational sold out with a profit of
$14.6 million on its investment of $44.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth concedes that Relational's ideas are rarely new. ``We
get more opportunities from the `Ready, aim, aim, aim' syndrome,''
he said. ``The company knows what needs to be done but can't pull
the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Relational has profited from a stock's rise, even
though it hasn't forced the company to do anything. It also has
suffered reverses: a big loss on its investment in Nuevo and
smaller losses in companies like the Moore Corp., an office
supplies maker, and Pennzoil.
</P>
<P>
   Till recently, Whitworth's biggest challenge had been Apria
Healthcare. The company was created in a 1995 merger, and each of
the merging companies placed four members on the new board,
resulting in deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle permeated the whole company,'' Whitworth said.
``It was an absolute disaster, and the business began to
disintegrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Relational invested in 1997, and Whitworth, threatening a proxy
fight, pushed himself onto the board the next January, becoming
chairman that April. Then, at a meeting in May, Whitworth invited
the other board members, one by one, outside the room, Within a few
hours, five directors had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all resigned of their own accord,'' recalled Richard H.
Koppes, the former general counsel of Calpers who was brought onto
the board by Whitworth. ``He just has the kind of skills to operate
within that crisis situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth brought in a new board and a new chief executive. The
staff was cut, nonperforming businesses sold and profits restored.
Apria's stock, which fell below $3 last year, closed on Friday at
$19. Relational now owns 22 percent of the company, at an average
purchase price of $12.59 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why one board seat is so significant,'' Batchelder said.
``As soon as you infused Ralph as the ninth director, the swing
vote, everything changed overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   At Apria's annual meeting last month, the main question from
shareholders was when Relational would sell its stake. Not for a
while, Whitworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Now his crisis skills will be tested at Waste Management, a
company with a history of accounting and management problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth's involvement began when he was recruited to help USA
Waste Services, another trash hauler, acquire Waste Management.
Relational invested $71.2 million in Waste Management before the
acquisition, selling its shares for a profit of $28.6 million and
also earning a fee as an adviser on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He was named to the board of the merged company, which kept the
Waste Management name. Relational now owns 1.2 million shares, a
small stake purchased at a price that Batchelder said was in the
low $40s.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth was appointed acting chairman because he was the head
of the board's governance committee _ and also because he had the
time to get heavily involved. He is working with two other board
members on an executive committee _ Roderick Hills, a former
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, and Jerome
York, who works for Kirk Kerkorian, the financier.
</P>
<P>
   York had recruited Whitworth to help in both Kerkorian's attempt
to take over the Chrysler Corp. in 1995 and USA Waste's effort to
take over Waste Management.
</P>
<P>
   They are scrambling to devise a plan to be put before the board
on Friday for selling underperforming assets and using some of the
proceeds for a stock buyback. The stock is now at $23.875, less
than half the $60 it reached on May 4, its recent peak.
</P>
<P>
   The company must also replenish its management. When the second
earnings revision in a month occurred, Whitworth pushed out the
chief financial officer and accepted the resignation of the general
counsel. He said it was premature to look for a new chief executive
because the current one, John E. Drury, still may recover from his
brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth said the company's troubles stem from poor
projections, not from being a poor business. ``The merged company
won't do everything it was expected to do,'' he said in an
interview. ``But there's no question it's a better company than the
two separate companies.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow shareholders hardly seemed convinced, though some
said they were happy he was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always provides comfort when the insiders are significant
shareholders,'' said Alan Benasuli, a portfolio manager at European
Investors Inc. in New York. But he said a stock buyback, much as he
would like the stock price to go up, would be ``ludicrous,''
because of the company's high debt level.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth disputes any contention that investors like him go
only for short-term fixes, saying that he can only sell a stock at
a profit if the company's long-term prospects are better than when
he bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one change you could make in corporate America, it
would be to put a large shareholder on the board of every
company,'' he said. ``Certainly their incentives are such that you
are going to get better decisions out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at Waste Management, he will get a chance to prove it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
