<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-06 1762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YASTRZEMSKI PRAISES RED SOX TEAM PHYSICIAN PAPPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Yastrzemski says his career with the Red Sox would have
ended a lot sooner, if not for one man _ Dr. Arthur Pappas. ``I
don't understand what all the criticism is about,'' Yastrzemski
said this week, after Pappas took some verbal heat from present Red
Sox players. ``This man is one hell of a doctor. He kept me on the
field for the last five or six years. Without him, I couldn't have
played. I had a real bad back and I never knew when it was going
out on me. He constantly had to help me with my back, getting me
back on the field. I can't tell you how many times I went up to
UMass-Worcester to get treated by him. I remember one time he
wanted to test me swinging before he would let me play again. There
wasn't a bat around, so he had me swing a shovel to prove I could
swing again without re-injuring the back. I think Dr. Pappas has
done a great job for the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mike Foley of St. Elizabeth's Hospital in Boston, who also
works for the Red Sox, is another big supporter of Pappas. ``I've
seen him at work for the past 20 years and he is one of the best
orthopedic doctors you could possibly have,'' Foley said. ``He is
regarded as one of the best in the country. If anything was wrong
with anyone in my family with any kind of orthopedic problem, he
would be the first one I would send them to. He absolutely always
has the best interests of his patients at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas was criticized by shortstop Nomar Garciaparra after the
word came down that closer Tom Gordon could be out for the year
with an elbow problem. Garciaparra also was upset about the
treatment his friend Lou Merloni received from Pappas a year ago,
when Pappas apparently misdiagnosed a stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas, a part-owner of the team, has been with the Sox for 22
years. This reporter has criticized his dual role as owner/doctor
for years and still maintains he should do one or the other, not
both. Pappas is held in high regard in the local medical community,
and it is doubtful that the Sox could get someone of his caliber to
replace him. But if he wants to stay the Sox' top doctor, he should
sell his interest in the team. Then there wouldn't be any question
of his possibly giving an injured player a clean bill of health in
the best interests of the team, and not the player. The present
ownership isn't going to be around here much longer, so now might
be the right time to do make the move.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember all the questions after the All-Star Game, asking why
Yaz didn't wear a Red Sox cap during the pregame introductions of
the all-time all-stars? Here is his explanation: ``The day I
retired at Fenway Park and played my last game, I was running
around the field when it was over saying goodbye to the fans. I
took my hat off and gave it to a little kid in the crowd. Later I
told myself that would be the last time I would ever wear the Sox
hat in Fenway. Before the introductions for the All-Star Game, all
of us were underneath the center-field bleachers waiting to be
introduced. I was talking with Hank Aaron when someone came over
and gave me a Red Sox hat. I thought for a minute that I wouldn't
wear it. But when it came time to be introduced, I was going to
bring it with me and give it to some little kid. When I looked
around, it was gone. Someone took it. It's as simple as that.'' . .
. Yaz on Wade Boggs, Cal Ripken, and Tony Gwynn all pursuing 3,000
hits at the same time. ``Boggs is the best I have ever seen keeping
his head on the ball until it hits the bat. No one has ever done it
better. I always admired Ripken for the kind of competitor he is
and Gwynn for his ability to hit the ball all over the park. I also
like both Ripken and Gwynn because they stayed with the same
organization all the way through their careers. You don't see that
much anymore with guys of their ability.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is generating a lot of interest with its countdown toward
the top athlete of the century. The real question is: How is
``athlete'' defined? If you pick an all-around athlete, then who is
better than Jim Thorpe, who, I believe, was chosen the top athlete
of the first half of the century. Thorpe won the decathlon in the
1912 Olympics, symbolic of the best athlete in the world at that
time. He went on to play major league baseball from 1913 to 1919
and professional football with the Canton Bulldogs; he was a
charter member of the NFL, playing in the league when it was formed
in 1920 until he retired in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Are they going to say that Michael Jordan, the best basketball
player ever, is a better athlete than Thorpe? Jordan couldn't even
excel at minor league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that the final five in the ESPN poll will be 1.
Babe Ruth; 2. Jordan; 3. Muhammad Ali; 4. Jack Nicklaus; and 5. Jim
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   If they are taking an athlete based on just one sport, it should
be Ruth, who was the greatest lefthanded pitcher in the game until
he switched solely to hitting, then changed the face of the sport
with his home run power. He was also an excellent defensive
outfielder and had a tremendous arm.
</P>
<P>
   The best athlete of the second half of the century was Brown. In
this opinion, he is the greatest football player ever. He also is
regarded by experts as the greatest lacrosse player ever, and was
on the Syracuse track and basketball teams as well.
</P>
<P>
   The most overrated athlete is Ali. He certainly was a great
fighter, but when you lose to Kenny Norton, Leon Spinks, and the
ever-popular Trevor Berbick, among others, you are not the
century's greatest athlete. Rocky Marciano didn't lose to anyone,
and they couldn't find a place for him in the top 50?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red Auerbach on the Celtics' latest moves: ``I thought we did
well. (Ron) Mercer didn't want to be here. And he tells Denver he
won't show there either until he gets the contract extension.
(Danny) Fortson will really help us. He's a bull. He plays hard.
He's something like fourth in the league in rebounding. If Kenny
Anderson comes back ready to play, and he's healthy and stays
healthy, then we should be much better than we were last year.''
Personally, I never liked Mercer's game. A terrific jump shooter,
but he couldn't create his own shot and didn't give much effort at
the defensive end . . . Word is that the Patriots' new stadium in
Foxborough will be similar to the Ravens' stadium in Baltimore,
which, in the opinion of this humble scribe, is the best NFL
stadium to date. Patriots owner Bob Kraft, as a member of the NFL
stadium committee, in recent years has had the luxury of looking at
the plans for all the new stadiums in the league. He has taken what
he feels is the best of what he has seen and incorporated it into
the plans for this stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Duval was right when he asserted that not enough money
from the Ryder Cup goes to the players, but the money should go to
charity, not into the players' pockets. If the Ryder Cup players
are in the top 12 in earnings, they don't need another paycheck.
However, with a gross of $65 million coming in for this year's
Ryder Cup at Brookline, and some $25 million-$30 million in
profits, each player's $5,000 stipend is nothing. Why doesn't the
PGA allow each of the 12 players and the captain to designate, say,
$250,000 each toward his favorite charity? That way the players
still would be playing for no pay and keeping in the spirit of the
Ryder Cup, yet at the same time they'd be doing something good for
their community. As it stands, the PGA takes about 75 percent of
the money, with the rest going to the host club.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, when the US team comes to Brookline to practice
Aug. 30, the club will be closed to all except the players and club
members. The practice session is not open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's something about the Patriots getting rid of Willie Clay
that doesn't fit. They have no one left in the secondary that has
ever done what was his most important job on the field _ putting
all the backs around him in the right place and making sure they
know their assignments before the ball is snapped. Lawyer Milloy is
one of the best players in the game, but the task is going to be a
burden on him and could hurt his own play. Between the Detroit
Lions and Patriots, Clay had been around long enough to have seen
just about every offensive formation ever designed. Generally, one
busted assignment in the secondary translates to 7 points in the
NFL. If Clay wasn't doing the job last year, how come he started
every game? And seeing he hasn't played a game since last season,
how did he get worse? The Patriots claim they tried to trade him as
far back as the draft and there was no interest . . . Art Dunphy
went out the right way. The former Boston University publicist
recently retired from the Boston Public Library, and his final
project won best of show in a contest by the Publicity Club of New
England. Dunphy's campaign celebrating the BPL's 150th anniversary
got a ``Super Bell Award,'' coming in first among 240 entries . . .
The Boston schools are going to lose two great coaches when Joe
Mason of Dorchester High and Mike Sheeran of Charlestown High hang
them up at the end of the coming school year. Both started coaching
in Boston in 1961 . . . How is this for loading up? Boston College
will play Penn State at home in 2004; Arizona State here in 2005;
and Tennessee, the reigning national football champion, here in
2007 . . . There are some veterans on the Patriots who feel Pete
Carroll's outburst chewing out the players on the practice field
this week was staged, as part of Pete's new ``get-tough'' image. If
you are going to chew out a team, you do it in the locker room
after practice, or in the meeting room that night, when only the
assistant coaches and players are around. You don't do it with the
fans and media nearby unless you want everyone to know what you are
up to . . . Bob Lobel proves that Major League Baseball juiced up
the balls used at the All-Star Game home run hitting contest in
Fenway Park, and no one seems to care. Next time, we should get
Tiger Woods, give him a driver, and let him hit Titleists into the
Charles River. Because the balls Mark McGwire and company were
hitting were smaller and lighter than regular baseballs, it makes
the whole contest a sham. Yet no one seems to care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
