<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, AUGUST 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ICE-CREAM-AD-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, July 29,
about stagnant sales of ice cream misstated the financial
performance of Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream Inc. The company posted a
profit in the most recent quarter, which ended June 26. It did not
have two consecutive money-losing quarters.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AUTONATION-NYT (moved on Monday, Aug. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Aug. 2,
about the plans of Autonation Inc. to spin off or sell its car
rental businesses misstated the history of the company's Cartemps
U.S.A. division. It was formed through the acquisition of Spirit
Rent-A-Car Inc. and Snappy Car Rental Inc., not Thrifty Inc., which
is a unit of Dollar Thrifty Automotive Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AIRLINES-LEGROOM-NYT (moved on Thursday, Aug. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Aug. 5,
about a plan by United Airlines to offer its best customers more
legroom in the economy sections of domestic flights misstated the
percentage of the airline's annual sales that are contributed by
business travelers. Frequent business travelers make up about 9
percent of United's customers but account for 46 percent of its
sales, not 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-PASSWORDS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Aug. 4,
about problems with computer passwords misstated the name of the
company at which Alessandro Piol is a managing director. It is
Invesco Private Capital, not Investco Private Capital.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BATE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, July 27)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Walter J. Bate, sent by the New York Times News
Service on Tuesday, July 27, misstated the century of John Keats,
about whom Mr. Bate wrote a 1964 Pulitzer Prize-winning biography.
Keats was a poet of the 19th century, not the 18th.
</P>
</TEXT>
