<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS IN LEWIS CIVIL SUIT SET MEETING IN SEPTEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Six weeks after the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice
suit ended in mistrial, attorneys for Donna Harris-Lewis and Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. are gearing up to try the case again _ even as
the judge overseeing the matter encourages both sides to settle out
of court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Harris-Lewis, Lewis's widow, and Mudge, the late
athlete's chief cardiologist, will meet Sept. 10 for a pretrial
``status conference'' at which Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith is
expected to query both parties on settlement possibilities,
according to several people close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sources have confirmed that the insurance carrier for
a fourth doctor, Dr. John D. Rutherford, paid Harris-Lewis $500,000
in a settlement before the case went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement did not require Rutherford to admit guilt or
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the deal called Rutherford's settlement
``short money, considering that the guy saved himself nearly two
months of trial and many, many flights to and from Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bridget Asaro, an attorney for Harris-Lewis, said the amount
was appropriate because she viewed Rutherford as the least culpable
of the four defendants.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, after nearly seven weeks of testimony and six days
of deliberations, a 15-person jury could not agree on whether Mudge
was negligent in his treatment of the Celtics star before his 1993
death. Lewis collapsed and died while shooting baskets at Brandeis
University.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's two co-defendants, Drs. Peter L. Friedman and Mark A.
Creager, were cleared of malpractice charges by the jury.
Harris-Lewis has appealed those verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Fremont-Smith ordered Harris-Lewis to pay nearly
$20,000 in trial costs to attorneys for Friedman and Creager _ an
amount that excludes legal fees _ but stayed the order pending
resolution of the appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fremont-Smith's urgings, there has yet to be any
``summit meeting'' between the two sides to discuss settlement
possibilities, according to a person close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the trial ended, the landscape is different for
everyone,'' the source said. ``Mudge has now seen what an entire
trial will do to him and his family. Donna has seen the gamble of a
trial. Everyone has been educated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
