<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLVO-SCANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLVO BUYS RIVAL, CREATING WORLD'S 2ND LARGEST TRUCK AND BUS
MAKER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Sweden, Japan, Italy, Mich.)   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a $7.4 billion deal that will create the world's second
largest maker of trucks and buses, AB Volvo of Sweden is buying one
of its arch rivals, Swedish truck maker Scania.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced Friday in Sweden, comes just 15 months
after the merger of Chrysler and Daimler created the world's
largest truck and bus maker.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Volvo will buy the 49 percent of
Scania's shares now owned by Investor AB, the holding company that
is the main investment vehicle for Sweden's wealthy Wallenberg
family.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo will pay Investor 315 Swedish kronor per share or about
$38.55 in cash for 60 percent of the shares; the rest of the
payment will be either in cash, or in a swap of six shares of newly
issued Volvo stock for every five Scania shares. Volvo also said
that it will offer a similar deal for all remaining outstanding
shares of Scania.
</P>
<P>
   The deal did not surprise analysts, who had been expecting Volvo
to announce an acquisition ever since it sold its car business to
Ford Motor Co. earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought they were getting out of passenger cars so they
could sit around idly and reap 5 percent on their cash,'' said
James N. Kelleher, an analyst with Argus Research.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have surfaced throughout the year that Volvo was looking
at Deere, Case, Navistar, Cummins Engines and other players in the
truck market. ``This takes a little heat off other companies that
thought they were targets,'' said Robert S. Murley, an investment
banker at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there were early signs that Volvo had its sights set
on Scania. Volvo had been accumulating Scania shares throughout
1999, and already owned 13 percent of its rival when it began
negotiating with Investor to buy its stake.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Volvo's and Scania's shared nationality makes the deal a
bit unusual in the rapidly consolidating truck industry. It has
been far more common for companies in different countries to set up
alliances, if not full mergers, in order to take advantage of each
other's markets.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, for example, has a 49 percent stake in Japan's
Isuzu. The partnership gives GM's truck division an edge in eastern
markets, while the link to GM helps Isuzu in the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, there was speculation that Italy's Fiat would
try to buy Investor's share of Scania.
</P>
<P>
   For most of these companies, more is at stake than added truck
revenue. Many automotive companies view sales of commercial trucks
as a way to establish their brands in emerging economies.
</P>
<P>
   The Scania-Volvo deal will create a truck manufacturer that had
combined sales of $15.8 billion last year, and a work force of
about 76,000. Scania will remain a separate unit in Volvo, with its
own brands and distribution networks, but the sister divisions are
expected to combine purchasing clout, eliminate duplicate overhead,
and otherwise cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   While rival trucking companies expect the merged company to be a
major market force, few seem truly worried. ``Commercial trucks are
a fiercely competitive market segment, and this partnership will
escalate the competitiveness,'' said Dan Flores, a spokesman for GM
Truck Group. ``But it is not going to have any impact on our
long-term strategy or our partnership with Isuzu.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently feel Scania got the best of the deal.
Scania American Depository Receipts rose $7.1875 or 24 percent to
$37.50. Volvo ADRs fell $2.50 or 8.3 percent to $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
