<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-CHRONICLE-HEARST-A     08-06 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-CHRONICLE-HEARST-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST TO BUY SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE, LIKELY TO MERGE IT WITH
EXAMINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hearst Corp., the owner of The San Francisco Examiner, said
Friday that it was buying The San Francisco Chronicle, increasing
the likelihood that San Francisco will join the growing list of
one-newspaper cities.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said that it would try to sell The Examiner, William
Randolph Hearst's first newspaper in his legendary empire, but that
if no buyers emerged it would combine the two papers.
</P>
<P>
   A morning newspaper with a circulation of about 475,000 readers,
The Chronicle is owned by the family descended from the deYoung
brothers, who founded the paper in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner, an afternoon paper, has been owned by the Hearst
family since the 1880s, and for a number of decades it has borne
the slogan ``Monarch of the Dailies.'' But the Examiner's
circulation is just over 114,000.
</P>
<P>
   The sale marks the end of an increasingly unhappy era for both
publications, which have been run under under a joint operating
agreement since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   While neither side would disclose the amount of the transaction,
industry analysts estimated the price at approximately $500
million. The deal also includes SF Gate, the San Francisco Bay
Area's leading Web site.
</P>
<P>
   According to antitrust guidelines established by the Justice
Department, which state that a single corporation can own no more
than one major newspaper per city, Hearst will have to make a
good-faith effort to sell the Examiner. If the newspaper is not
sold, which newspaper-industry analysts predicted would be the most
likely outcome, the staff of the Examiner will be combined with
that of The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In a noontime meeting with staff members at The Chronicle,
Hearst chief executive Frank Bennack and and Chronicle Publishing
Co. president John Sias told employees that their jobs would be
maintained under the deal. Sias told staff members that Nan Tucker
McEvoy, a deYoung descendant who owns a third of the Chronicle
family stock, was ``devastated'' by the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Still up for sale are other assets of Chronicle Publishing. They
include the San Francisco NBC affiliate KRON-TV, two smaller
newspapers, two other television stations and two publishing
companies. KRON-TV is considered a prize property that could
attract the interest of NBC's parent, General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown said, ``Cities are better
served by having more newspapers rather than fewer newspapers. We
would hope that a buyer would be found for the afternoon
Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   But some newspaper analysts are already predicting that in the
end, only one paper will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst is the clear winner here,'' said John Morton, a
newspaper analyst at John Morton &AMP; Associates. ``They are going to
end up publishing the one newspaper in San Francisco. It will be
much more profitable than the agency has ever been because they
will be spared the expense of producing a second newspaper.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the current joint operating agreement, the two papers
share business operations but run separate, competitive newsrooms.
On Sundays, the two newspapers produce a joint newspaper, The San
Francisco Examiner and Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which runs the shared
advertising and production operations of the two newspapers, has
about 3,200 employees, about 1,000 of whom are represented by at
least 10 unions. Despite The Examiner's smaller circulation, the
owners of The Examiner have always taken an aggressive public
stance, declaring that they have no intention of shutting the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of unions representing workers at The Chronicle, The
Examiner and the Agency have been in touch with Justice Department
antitrust experts and specialists in joint operating arrangements,
The Examiner web site reported Friday. They had no immediate
comment but have said that any sales arrangement would require that
contracts existing through 2005 be honored.
</P>
<P>
   While Bennack and Sias were adamant in their assertion that no
jobs would be lost, analysts said that, too, was unlikely. Peter
Appert, an equity analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown, said that
there are no buyers for the Examiner and that the staff would be
folded in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that they will most likely combine the morning
and afternoon newspapers,'' Appert said. ``That's reflective of
what's happening in the newspaper industry as a whole and across
the nation, which is the consolidation of morning and afternoon
newspapers and the continuing evolution to one-newspaper cities. In
terms of jobs, they will keep the strongest folks, and through
attrition, buyouts or reassignment, the staff will be reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton put it in darker language: ``People will wither and fall
off the vine.''
</P>
<P>
   Appert said that Hearst had long been frustrated by the growing
unprofitability of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   William German, the editor of The Chronicle, said that the mood
among the Chronicle staff Friday was ``calm and positive. People
were asking very sound and sensible questions. They didn't seem to
be fingernail-chewing questions. The staff seems happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Bronstein, the editor of the Examiner, was not available
for comment. He was admitted to a hospital Thursday afternoon with
chest pains and underwent surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction means that the struggle between Hearst and
Knight-Ridder will become more pronounced. With the San Jose
Mercury News, Knight-Ridder competes with The Chronicle in the
Silicon Valley area south of San Francisco Bay, and the
Knight-Ridder newspaper in Contra Costa County competes for
suburban readers east of San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder chairman and chief executive P. Anthony Ridder
said he believed that the Examiner would be closed and the two
papers would be combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that will make my job easier, but it certainly
won't make it harder,'' he said. ``We are used to competing on a
daily combined circulation of 600,000,'' he said, referring to the
circulation of both the Examiner and the Chronicle. ``And I don't
know if they combine the papers, all that circulation is
transferable.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest newspaper in Northern California, The San Francisco
Chronicle was founded as the Daily Dramatic Chronicle in San
Francisco in 1865 by two brothers, Charles and Michael deYoung. The
paper has been owned and operated for the last 134 years since then
by the brothers' heirs. The extended family that owns the paper has
had battles for two decades over the newspaper, wrangling publicly
for control of the newspaper and the company's board several times
during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nion McEvoy, the son of Mrs. McEvoy and a board member, said:
``For the Chronicle staff, at least their future is clear. For the
Examiner staff suddenly everything has shifted. I'm just
speculating, but I imagine they will have to retool their
psyches.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Examiner was taken over by William Randolph
Hearst in 1887; the corporation he founded with that move
eventually became Hearst Corp., which has published the Examiner
for the last 112 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sias, the chairman and chief executive officer of the Chronicle
Co. did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
