</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FARWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRON FARWELL, HISTORIAN AND VIRGINIA MAYOR, DIES AT 78  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Iowa, Ill., Ohio, Ariz., Canada, Switzerland,
Britain)   By ESTELA DURAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Byron Farwell, a military biographer and historian and a former
mayor of Hillsboro, Va., died on Tuesday at Loudoun County Hospital
in Virginia after a heart attack. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Manchester, Iowa, he wrote 13 books, including
biographies and studies of military history, specializing in
British warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Among Farwell's works are ``Queen Victoria's Little Wars,''
``Mr. Kipling's Army'' and a biography of the journalist Henry M.
Stanley called ``The Man Who Presumed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was writing his 15th book, about Allied intervention in
Russia after World War I, when he died. His 14th book, the
Encyclopedia of 19th-Century Land Warfare, will be published next
year.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in military history began with his own service in
the Army during the invasion of North Africa in World War II, and
in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a master's degree in English from the University of
Chicago and attended Ohio State University
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Ruth, he traveled around the world. In the 1960s
they lived in Switzerland and then in London.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years he lived in Hillsboro, Va., a town of 125
people in the Blue Ridge hills of Loudoun County, where he fought
the state and federal governments on issues like the census count
and health department regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Farwell was mayor of Hillsboro from 1976 to 1982. He lost the
election for a fourth term after a 17-17 vote. To break the tie, a
name was drawn from a punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Farwell also wrote articles and reviews for many publications,
including The New York Times, The Washington Post and Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the Chrysler Corp. from 1954 to 1971 and was the
director of administration for Chrysler International in Geneva,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Farwell was also a trustee of the Oatlands mansion, operated by
the National Trust for Historic Preservation, near Leesburg, Va.,
and held fellowships from the Royal Society of Literature and the
Royal Geographic Society. He was also a Wallerstein Fellow for the
Institute of government at the University of Virginia from 1978 to
1980.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; three children, Joyce Lewis of Coal
Harbour, B.C.; Byron J. Farwell of Gilbert, Ariz.; and Lesley
Pesnicak of Stafford, Va.; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
