r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-06 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S JUST KISS AND SAY GOODBYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bartender?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, hi, L.A. Surprised to see you before noon.''
</P>
<P>
   Early bird catches the worm, they say. Make it a double tequila.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troubles?''
</P>
<P>
   A woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Please, let me say more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a figure of speech. Go on.''
</P>
<P>
   She walked out on me yesterday. Just when I thought we finally
had something special. She said she thought we should date other
people. I think she meant (begin ital)she(end ital) should date
other people.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you may have met her in here. Goes by the initials
N-F-L. Seems like kind of a tease, but she's just outgoing, that's
all. Don't let the devil tattoo fool you. Real pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys seem to think so.''
</P>
<P>
   What'd you mean by that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry. I know I'm supposed to be the sympathetic ear.''
</P>
<P>
   I also think she has her eye on a certain ``other people''
already. Somebody from out of town. Roses keep showing up at the
house with cards signed, ``Houston.'' Didn't take more than a month
of that before I realized something was up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't slip anything by you.''
</P>
<P>
   I mean, what do I look like, a rube?
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, ready for another drink?''
</P>
<P>
   What frosts me is the sacrifices I made for her. OK, I didn't
exactly (begin ital)make(end ital) sacrifices, but I promised to
make them, and she acted like that was the biggest commitment she'd
ever had from a man. I thought she loved me.
</P>
<P>
   I even told her I was going to patch the crack in the living
room where the termites come in. Only time I saw her cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you go with this, uh, lady once before?''
</P>
<P>
   We were together for a few years, a few years ago. Had a nice
place together in Orange County, then we shared the fixer-upper
near downtown. She moved out, I kept the house.
</P>
<P>
   It ended badly the first time, and I always blamed myself.
Didn't show her enough attention. A woman like that deserved
better. I vowed I'd make it up to her someday. Now it looks like
I've blown that too. Guess I'm not good enough for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, there. Want some advice?''
</P>
<P>
   You're a bartender _ who else would I ask for advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do try to be the voice of experience and common sense,
especially when business is slow, as it tends to be at 9 a.m. Now,
you probably don't want to hear this, because it's obvious you
carry quite a torch for her. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   You know how it is. You never miss somebody till they're gone.
Shoot, I'm starting to sound like Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . What I'm getting at is: This tease you want to hitch
your future to, you're better off without her. Somebody like this,
they'll leave, they'll come back, they'll leave, they'll come back.
The waiting will tear you up inside. And nothing you do when she's
there will ever be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time she shows up on your front porch, that suitcase in
her hand is packed with nothing but heartbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Pithy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had this conversation before.''
</P>
<P>
   One more tequila, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not driving, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   I walked. Can't afford the parking around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I getting through to you? You have a decision to make. Some
guys, they're willing to put up with someone like her. Those guys,
maybe they don't have the confidence to say no to the constant
demands, or they don't have enough else going on in their lives.
Maybe this `Houston' is like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're different. You're smart, strong, worldly, popular,
wealthy. You don't need Miss N-F-L and all her aggravation. It's
time to tell her, `Go ahead, date other people, and don't come
running back to me!' ''
</P>
<P>
   You left out ``good-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cutting you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks. And you know what? You are getting through to me. I've
let her rule my life for too long. She's always known I'd be here,
ready with a warm hug and a cold Budweiser, whenever she knocked on
the door. Well, let's just see what happens if I don't answer the
door the next time!
</P>
<P>
   She and I are through! This guy is moving on!
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be happier in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Damn right! One thing. She still has a key to my place. If you
see her, can you get it from her, and I'll pick it up next time I'm
in?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if she's in the neighborhood, ask her to drop it by
the house. Maybe we could talk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
