<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOREA-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A TEST FOR KOREA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, August 7:
</P>
<P>
   The near-collapse of Daewoo Group, one of the large
conglomerates that dominate the South Korean economy, is presenting
a test for the government of President Kim Dae-jung. Its
performance so far is not reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo came close to bankruptcy last month, a fate that was
averted only when Korean creditors put up more money in exchange
for extensive collateral. At first the government said that those
creditors would be in charge of the restructuring, but then it
seemed to reverse itself and left the company's management in
charge. There are good reasons to doubt that the management is
prepared to take the steps _ of selling off assets and granting
stock to the creditors _ that are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Ominously, there are indications that Daewoo intends to treat
its foreign creditors worse than its local ones as it reorganizes.
Thirteen foreign banks have complained that they are being kept in
the dark regarding what is going on. They are also angry that they
were not offered the opportunity to share in the new collateral.
Daewoo says it will talk to the banks in due course.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo, whose debts total $57 billion, overextended itself by
entering businesses in which it was unable to make money. The banks
that financed that reckless expansion may well lose money, and no
one should shed a tear for them if they do.
</P>
<P>
   But it is important that domestic creditors not be given
preferential treatment, and that creditors as a group be able to
take control of the company if an amicable restructuring agreement
cannot be reached. Any other result would send the message that
Korea's biggest conglomerates continue to have enough political
power to force others to pay for their mistakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
