<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-ONE2ONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM TO BUY BRITISH CELL PHONE COMPANY FOR $11.1
BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Deutsche Telekom AG agreed to buy the British cellular
telephone company One 2 One Ltd. Friday in a deal worth $11.1
billion. The deal is the German phone giant's first big foray
abroad since its attempt to buy Telecom Italia SpA collapsed three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition puts Deutsche Telekom in the middle of a
brutally competitive cellular telephone market in Britain. It also
signals a broader move by the company to become a pan-European
telecommunications brand.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom will pay 6.9 billion pounds, or $11.1 billion,
in cash and will assume 1.5 billion pounds ($2.5 billion) in debt
for One 2 One, which is jointly owned by the London-based Cable and
Wireless PLC and MediaOne Group Inc., the Colorado-based Internet
provider recently acquired by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's cellular telephone business, known as
T-Mobil, and One 2 One will have a combined base of 10 million
customers. Deutsche Telekom said it expected to enhance the service
to all its customers by expanding their capability to roam, or use
their cellular telephones over a wide geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which ended weeks of rumor and speculation
about a possible deal, means that Cable and Wireless and MediaOne
will finally rid themselves of Britain's smallest cellular
telephone company after a four-month search for a buyer. However,
the price is far less than the two companies had originally
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had put One 2 One up for auction, hoping to get as
much as 11 billion pounds ($17 billion). Several companies,
including France Telecom, the German cellular phone network
Mannesmann AG and Telecom Italia Mobile, were said to be bidding
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a steal for Deutsche Telekom, but it is a
pretty good value,'' said Jonathan Adams, a telecommunications
analyst at J.P. Morgan in London.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, the former state-run German monopoly, has
global aspirations but has not expanded much beyond Germany. Even
with the purchase of One 2 One, more than 90 percent of Deutsche
Telekom's business will be derived domestically.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the company's $93.6 billion takeover bid for Telecom
Italia was thwarted by Olivetti SpA, the former typewriter maker,
which is a fraction of Deutsche Telekom's size.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's chief executive, Ron Sommer, has raised $11
billion since then by selling additional shares of the company to
help finance acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Deutsche Telekom said it was in discussions
with a number of other telecommunication companies about possible
takeovers or mergers. Among the moves said to be under discussion
was a purchase of France Telecom's 10 percent stake in Sprint, the
U.S. long-distance and local communications provider. It is unclear
whether Deutsche Telekom, which also owns 10 percent of Sprint, has
made any moves to acquire control of the company, but
telecommunications analysts have not ruled this out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly they want to be a player in the pan-European market,''
said Tim Hirst, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``This deal is
the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said Deutsche Telekom was entering an especially
tough market with its purchase of One 2 One, which lags
considerably behind its three larger competitors: Vodafone Airtouch
PLC, the market leader; BT Cellnet Ltd., which just came under the
complete control of British Telecommunications PLC; and Orange PLC.
In addition, One 2 One has yet to enter the lucrative business
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to say it's a red-hot company,'' Hirst said.
``But the U.K. mobile market is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of One 2 One will help Cable and Wireless shift its
focus from the consumer market to the business market. The deal is
``a further step in repositioning Cable and Wireless,'' said Graham
Wallace, the company's chief executive. Just last week, Cable and
Wireless sold its consumer division to NTL Inc., a New York-based
telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telecom shares fell .15 euro to 37.50 euros. Cable and
Wireless shares rose 4.4 percent to 765 pence ($12.31). MediaOne
fell 12.5 cents to $70.625.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of One 2 One is expected to be completed by the
end of September, pending approval from regulators and
shareholders.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
