<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-DEFECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ISSUES A FIRST REPAIR FOR OFFICE 97 SECURITY FLAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SARA ROBINSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. released a partial corrective Friday for a
dangerous lapse in security. The flaw appears when the company's
Office 97 group of programs is installed with most versions its Web
browser, Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft programmed the browser to trust all files created by
its Office programs, and it is possible that an intruder could
create a malicious program that masqueraded as an Office file _ a
Word, Excel or Powerpoint document _ and plant it on a World Wide
Web site or in an e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   The corrective, released 10 days after Microsoft was alerted to
the problem, does not prevent intruders from exploiting the flaw,
but it installs a trip wire that requires the user to click ``OK''
before an Office file on a Web page or in an e-mail message opens.
It does not warn the user that the document in question could be a
malicious program.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft acknowledged Friday that the change was not a
satisfactory repair but said it was testing a better solution and
planned to make it available to customers during the week of Aug.
16.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the company said, no customers had reported intrusions
related to the flaw. The company posted a security bulletin at a
Web site, www.officeupdate.microsoft.com.
</P>
<P>
   The repair released Friday reconfigures the Internet Explorer so
that an e-mail message containing an embedded Office document
causes a window to pop up. It tells the user that he or she has
chosen to download a file from a Web site and asks if the file
should be opened or saved. The user has the option of clicking
``cancel.''
</P>
<P>
   If the file is saved to the hard drive, however, any malicious
code will still be executed if and when the file is ever opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warning is somewhat confusing,'' said Richard Smith, the
president of Phar Lap Software, in Cambridge, Mass., who has
discovered a number of bugs in Microsoft's Windows software. ``Most
people don't know that a Word document can be dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
