u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-CHRONICLE-REACT-NY     08-06 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-CHRONICLE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SAN FRANCISCO, AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE LOOMS FOR REPORTERS AND
EDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SF-CHRONICLE-HEARST) 
(bl) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO. _ The men and women who pursue the news here
found themselves in the news Friday, and they became the source of
their own journalistic gossip and debate at the M &AMP; M Tavern, the
corner bar where people who work for The San Francisco Examiner and
The San Francisco Chronicle have gathered for decades.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the respective staffs, whose buildings share a block
and whose offices are attached, have heard the rumors that one side
would buy _ and maybe bury _ the other.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent state of uncertainty and expectation left some
feeling relief Friday when the management of each paper gathered
its reporters and editors to announce that Hearst Corp., which owns
the afternoon Examiner, would buy the morning Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement raised new questions. Despite assurances
that employees would keep their jobs ``during the transition,''
many wondered how secure their positions would be over the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   And they are concerned that they will soon be asked to cooperate
in one newsroom, rather than compete. To some long-time reporters
of the scrappier Examiner and the often more institutional
Chronicle, this is like asking the New York Yankees to join forces
with the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either staff is happy about cohabitating with
the other,'' said Larry Hatfield, a 30-year member of The
Examiner's staff who holds the title of chief rewrite man. ``We're
friends and colleagues,'' he said ``but we like to kill each other
competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hall, president of the Northern California Media Workers
Guild, which represents the news and advertising staff of both
papers, said the situation for employees was ``going to be
tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a science reporter at The Chronicle, characterized the
mood at his newspaper as one of disappointment and sadness over the
prospect that the family-owned Chronicle would now be owned by a
``New York-based media giant.''
</P>
<P>
   But reporters and editors at The Chronicle expressed relief that
their jobs look secure for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner's reporters and editors seemed less certain. Many
of them said they hoped their paper would be combined with The
Chronicle rather than sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst would be if we were sold to a nonunion paper,'' said
Christine Delsol, an editor in The Examiner's style section.
</P>
<P>
   At the M &AMP; M Tavern _ where pictures of San Francisco journalism
celebrities hang, sometimes crookedly, on the walls _ Taso
Manitsas, the bar's owner, said the merger would deprive the city
of a welcome competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been an Examiner and a Chronicle city,'' he
said. ``Now there will be only one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
