u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-JUVENILE-PRISON-2T     08-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-JUVENILE-PRISON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA TOWN RIDES TO THE RESCUE OF ITS YOUNG INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALTON, Ga. _ For years, reports of overcrowding, assaults,
self-mutilation and suicide attempts flowed out of the state
juvenile detention center in this conservative northwest Georgia
community.
</P>
<P>
   In many towns, people might have said that the problem was
someone else's business. The children were not theirs, after all,
and the center was a source of jobs. Why should there be much
interest in serving as good hosts to dozens of delinquents?
</P>
<P>
   But not in Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   Upset at the treatment of these young inmates _ boys and girls
both, who typically ranged in age from 9 to 17 _ an unlikely group
including the owner of an asphalt-paving business, a doctor's wife,
a carpet-company owner and a bank president laid out the costs of
bringing a federal civil rights suit against the state, and won a
settlement improving conditions at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Now their unusual role _ it is rare for townspeople to rush to
the aid of local inmates, and rarer still for them to put up more
than $100,000 for the cause _ is drawing national attention. ``I
have never heard of anything like this'' in 20 years of litigating
juvenile justice cases, said Mark Soler, president of the Youth Law
Center, a public interest law firm in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawyers say this rare kind of civic activism demonstrates
the lengths to which people must now go if poor prison conditions
are to be challenged. They blame the 1996 enactment of federal laws
that sharply curtailed the ability to bring lawsuits on behalf of
prisoners, in part by making it more difficult for lawyers to
finance them. The restrictions were passed largely out of anger
over what were seen as frivolous suits, with critics saying one
prisoner had even sued over a lack of chunky peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs here, a loose grouping of a dozen or so,
maintained that children at the Dalton Regional Youth Detention
Center were receiving inadequate education, psychological therapy
and medical care and sometimes slept five to a room designed for
one, often on the floor near open toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Last December a federal judge agreed, pressing the state to
settle and praising the Daltonites who had taken action.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say they had no choice, given what they had
learned about conditions at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never gave it a thought,'' said J.M. Boring, a bank
president, ``other than that it was something that had to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Robinson, deputy counsel in the Georgia attorney general's
office, said the plaintiffs exaggerated the center's problems and
that the state had been moving to correct them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems were not anything near as severe as what the
lawyers alleged,'' Robinson said. ``But were there problems there?
Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, at its annual meeting in Atlanta, the American Bar
Association is to give a juvenile justice award for ``exposing
deplorable conditions'' to the Atlanta lawyers who handled the
case, Robert Cullen and his wife, Martha Miller, and to a
representative of the Dalton citizens' group, Deborah Peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Mlyniec, the ABA's juvenile justice chairman, said the
selection of the award's winners showed how widely known the case
had become among lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty remarkable when the nominations started coming
in,'' Mlyniec said. ``Everybody was talking about Cullen and Miller
and Debby Peppers and a group of people in this town who on their
own got together to make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it happen took some doing. The 1996 laws sharply limited
the legal fees that could be recovered by lawyers bringing suits
for prisoners, and also barred lawyers who get federal money to
represent the poor from handling prison suits at all. Cullen says
that as a result of those restrictions, the few lawyers still
willing to handle such cases no longer have the means to finance
them.
</P>
<P>
   So there would have been no Dalton suit, he says, had it not
been for the $101,103.88 that the group of residents borrowed to
pay for depositions, expert witnesses and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mostly affluent plaintiffs were motivated by what
they had learned as volunteers in the local juvenile court. A few
worked for juvenile agencies. But some were simply interested in
children's issues, just as they were interested in other civic
matters. A few years before the suit was filed in 1996, they had
created Voice of the Children, a group devoted to influencing local
and state child policy.
</P>
<P>
   One member, Connie Maples Blaylock, who was then a lawyer in
juvenile court and is now a judge there, and Mrs. Peppers, then a
county commissioner who volunteered at the court as a child
guardian, began telling the others what the children in the
detention center were saying about the lack of education, therapy
and basic medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were appalled to learn that these kinds of things were
even alleged to be going on in Dalton, Ga.,'' said Judge Blaylock.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say they barely even discussed finances before
filing suit. If they won, they knew, the state would have to pay
them at least some of the money they borrowed. If they lost, they
would split the costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these children didn't have glasses'' to see with,
Deelee Barnwell, one of the group, said by way of explaining the
plaintiffs' lack of concern over money. ``They didn't have
toothbrushes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Under the settlement, the plaintiffs will now be reimbursed by
the state, which will also pay the lawyers' fee, although in both
cases the amount will be determined in arbitration.)
</P>
<P>
   Another plaintiff, Dawn Sanders, an executive in one of the
banks on the main street of this town of 25,000, said Dalton, a
carpet manufacturing center, had always had an entrepreneurial
ethic. That do-it-yourself spirit, she said, was simply applied to
the problem of the conditions at the center.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of testimony last December, the federal judge in
the case, Harold Murphy, sitting in Rome, Ga., made clear from the
bench that it would be in the interest of the Georgia Department of
Juvenile Justice to settle. If there was no settlement, Murphy
said, there would be a court order ``that will be embarrassing to
the department.'' He went on to say of the Daltonites, ``The
plaintiffs in this case are to be commended for calling the
attention of the public to issues in this case that should never
have existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days the state did settle, making broad promises of
improvements. For example, the settlement limits to 45 children the
permissible population of the center, which was designed for 30.
The plaintiffs had contended that as many as 120 children were
sometimes there _ a figure the state denied, although the center's
administrators acknowledged that there had been as many as five in
a one-child room.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also requires improvements in educational,
psychological and other services, and these have apparently been
made. The accord grants the plaintiffs the right to inspect the
center, and Cullen now says, ``It is a different place.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the settlement seemingly brings to an end a living
nightmare for children like a slight 11-year-old boy identified in
the lawsuit only as W.C. He was an emotionally troubled runaway,
once arrested for shoplifting chewing tobacco, who ended up in the
Dalton center.
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition, W.C. maintained for the first time that in
those overcrowded rooms, a 17-year-old had sexually molested him
and a 12-year-old had tried. He was 9 at the time. At the center,
he testified, he tried to kill himself a few times.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, his mother, who agreed to speak if she was
identified only by the initials with which her son was identified
in the suit, said the case had accomplished much. ``It is not going
to undo what was done to my child,'' she said through tears, ``but
maybe some other child won't suffer the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   When W.C. gave his deposition, he was asked why he had tried to
kill himself at the Dalton center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he said, ``I hated it so bad there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
