<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM AND DAEWOO SIGN DEAL THAT MAY LEAD TO ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ General Motors Corp. signed an agreement Friday that
could lead to an alliance with the Daewoo Motor Co., the core of
South Korea's struggling Daewoo Group.
</P>
<P>
   GM, the world's largest automaker, could end up buying assets
from Daewoo or taking a stake in the company, possibly even a
controlling stake, said Alan G. Perriton, president of General
Motors Korea and head of new business ventures and strategic
alliances in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between the two companies would help GM's effort to
double its share of sales in the Asian market to 10 percent in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   For Daewoo, a deal with GM would bring in much-needed capital,
sound financial management and, most important, send a strong
message that the imperiled conglomerate is serious about radically
overhauling and streamlining its sprawling operations.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Friday significantly advances
discussions that the two companies have been holding since February
1998, which had been stalled over issues of price and control.
``We've narrowed down the scope and taken it to a much higher
level,'' Perriton said in a telephone interview from Seoul. ``We'll
be focusing specifically on vehicles excluding commercial trucks
and buses.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreement was not an opportunistic response to the
Daewoo Group's current precarious financial condition, since
negotiations had begun several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Daewoo was rescued from impending default
with debt payment extensions and fresh capital by its creditors.
They were acting at the behest of the Korean government, which was
concerned that the conglomerate's financial crisis was endangering
the country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Daewoo promised a sweeping revamping that would
result in the sale of various assets. The GM agreement seems to be
a step in that direction, but investors have seen so many potential
deals fall apart or fade away that Friday's announcement failed to
incite even cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hesitate to draw any conclusions too quickly,'' said
Richard Samuelson, head of SBC Warburg's office in Seoul, noting
that GM and Daewoo have been in discussions for some time already
without any clear results. ``This almost has a slapstick quality,
with the on-again, off-again nature of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Korean government's last hope for finding a
home for the factory of the insolvent Samsung Motors is Daewoo
Motors. Analysts see little hope the Samsung plant will be sold to
another car company. But because it is in Pusan, an opposition
stronghold, the government wants to avoid a plant shutdown before
parliamentary elections next April. Perriton made it clear the
plant was not part of GM's discussions with Daewoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of this discussion is Daewoo and GM and the assets
that Daewoo has,'' he said. Should GM conclude a deal with Daewoo,
and Perriton said the two companies would work toward that end ``as
quickly as practical,'' the future of the Samsung plant would
almost surely be liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, Kim Woo Choong, the chairman of the
Daewoo Group, said he considered Daewoo Motors the ``crown jewel''
of his group and that he would lavish financial and management
resources on it. Now he is apparently offering to hand over control
of his crown jewel to GM if offered the right price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen various interpretations of the same comment,''
Perriton said. ``It's reasonable to suggest that regardless of how
he views the automotive part of his business, there has always been
a willingness to have that considered in relation to another
international company.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent change of position by the Daewoo chairman could
also be an indication of desperation, although Daewoo's finances
are so murky that any current assessment of them is at best an
educated guess, bankers and analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The group is saddled with total liabilities estimated at $60
billion, a good chunk of it in short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   The only realistic way it can help pay down those debts is to
sell assets, but many of Daewoo's assets are not competitive or in
slumping industries like shipbuilding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
