<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HAMBLETONIAN-ALLENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMBLETONIAN BECOMES AN ALLEN FAMILY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Carl Allen had bypass surgery 18 months
ago and sustained broken ribs two weeks ago, but it seems that
nothing will stop the 69-year-old Allen from driving in the
Hambletonian. Allen has an insatiable desire to be a daredevil, and
he does not want to be outdone by his son, Rod, in harness racing's
most prestigious event.
</P>
<P>
   The Allens will go against each other Saturday afternoon at the
Meadowlands, driving a two-horse entry that is the second choice on
the morning betting line. Carl will drive CR Commando and Rod will
direct CR Renegade as they try to capture the first Hambletonian
title for a family that has been involved in racing for more than
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Allens came to winning a Hambletonian, the $1
million classic for 3-year-old trotters, was in 1990 with Royal
Troubador, but the horse chipped a knee and finished fifth. The
Allens also had a good chance with CR Kay Suzie in the 1995
Hambletonian, but the popular filly broke stride in the first heat
and never qualified for the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two horses of equal quality this time, and both are
going into the race having trained real good,'' Carl Allen said of
Renegade and Commando, who will leave from the first and third
spots, respectively. Renegade is a full brother of CR Kay Suzie.
</P>
<P>
   Renegade and Commando were the early 7-2 choice, behind the
three-horse entry of Angus Hall, Self Possessed and Rafaello
Ambrosio, who were at 3-5 and expected to go even better just
before the race. The Hambletonian will be the 11th race on a card
of 15 races that begins at 11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Commando and Renegade have never raced against one another in an
official event. For Carl, this will be the second time he has
driven against one of his sons. He drove against his son Mike in an
elimination race.
</P>
<P>
   The Allens are not the first father-son confrontation in the
race. Ben White, Stanley Dancer and Billy Haughton raced against
one or more of their sons.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Allen wants to do well against his son. ``The young guys
want to put you out to pasture,'' he said. ``Sometimes it's hard
for the student to beat the teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Allen is a self-taught trainer and driver _ he never
apprenticed with anyone. He got into horse racing by accident in
Detroit while he was working as a bull rider in a rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always liked daring things,'' said Mae Jean, his wife of
49 years. ``I think he needs the stimulation,'' she said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Allen was kinder when speaking of facing his father in the
Ham-bletonian. ``We're too close to have any vice,'' he said, ``but
there is a certain amount of competitiveness there. It goes back to
when these two horses were babies. We've competed in trials and
training, but this whole field is very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best in the field of 10 is Self Possessed, who
captured his Hambletonian elimination last Saturday by six lengths
in 1:53. He will be driven by Mike Lachance and will leave from the
fourth spot, which many drivers and trainers consider the most
desirable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990806.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUKE-CHINA-NYT &LR;      08-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SECURITY ISSUE COULD DELAY NUCLEAR SECRETS INDICTMENT  (mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department has sought a delay in the
government's decision on seeking an indictment against a former Los
Alamos scientist in connection with the mishandling of nuclear
secrets, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More time is needed, the officials added, to decide whether to
release highly classified information for use as evidence. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson has the legal authority to decide what
classified information can be released.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Richardson was waiting for a recommendation from
the department's new security czar, a former Air Force general,
Eugene Habiger. Habiger has to weigh whether the risks of exposing
additional classified nuclear data outweigh the need for the
prosecution of the scientist, Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials are mulling how to handle the case,
and some reportedly believe that the case is too weak to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney for New Mexico, John Kelly, has been
considering indicting Lee on federal charges of mishandling
classified information, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent lack of evidence means that the government is not
expected to charge Lee with espionage. The general allegation is
that China obtained nuclear weapons secrets through Lee, an
allegation that China and Lee have steadfastly denied.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Kelly's office in New Mexico declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Lee has been the chief suspect in an FBI
inquiry into the possible theft of nuclear secrets from the Los
Alamos National Laboratory, including information related to the
most advanced nuclear warhead, the W-88. But he has never been
charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, prosecutors have been considering the lesser charges of
mishandling classified information, because Lee transferred nuclear
weapons data into an unsecured computer network. He has said that
the transfers were routine and that no crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prosecution would be unprecedented, said John Martin,
former chief of the internal security section at the Justice
Department. Martin, who was in charge of the prosecution of
espionage cases until he retired in 1997, said such an indictment
would charge ``gross negligence'' and the mishandling of classified
information under Title 18 of the U.S. Code, Section 793/F. That is
a felony punishable by up to 10 years in prison. But it has never
been used in a federal criminal prosecution, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Lee in Los Angeles, Mark Holscher, did not return
calls for comment. But Lee has previously stated that he has never
betrayed secrets and that he transferred nuclear-weapons computer
codes into an unclassified computer network to protect the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday that in a polygraph examination in
February, Lee provided deceptive answers on whether he had passed
W-88 information to an unauthorized person and whether he had given
computer codes related to nuclear weapons to an unauthorized
person. Polygraph results would not be admissible in court,
however.
</P>
<P>
   An important problem for the government is that prosecutors are
not certain they can keep classified information from being exposed
in a trial. They say they may not be able to use the Classified
Information Procedures Act, which was intended to let the
government prosecute spies without revealing secrets in court.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from Los Alamos in New Mexico have been interviewed
by the government to explain the significance of Lee's transfers of
information. Those scientists, as expert witnesses for the
prosecution, could be cross-examined, and their information could
be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over charging Lee heated up a day after a Senate
report painted a devastating picture of the many errors that have
plagued the case, committed by investigators, lawyers and other
officials at the FBI, the Justice Department, Los Alamos and the
Energy Department. Those errors are part of the reason why the case
against Lee is extremely weak, many people in and out of government
apparently believe.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes may make it impossible for the government to
prosecute anyone. Among the many missteps that the Senate report
detailed was the decision early in the investigation to focus on
Lee without having adequately reviewed other possible suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the chairman and ranking minority member
of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, notes that the FBI
had already investigated Lee two times, once in the early 1980s in
connection with China's reported theft of neutron-bomb data from
the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California, and a
second time in the 1990s, just before the the investigation
concerning the W-88 secrets began.
</P>
<P>
   The first inquiry of Lee started when the FBI found that he had
called the suspect in the neutron-bomb case. In that investigation,
Lee acknowledged having provided unclassified material to China.
Bureau officials have said he passed a polygraph examination, and
the bureau closed its inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate report does not identify the second inquiry, but
states that it was suspended in 1995 as soon as the bureau was
brought into the W-88 investigation. A federal official familiar
with that investigation said the FBI seemed to have prematurely
narrowed its focus on Lee, because he was already under scrutiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
