<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ALBANY WRAP-UP, A WIDE-RANGING PACKAGE EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The package of bills endorsed by Gov. George
Pataki and legislative leaders Thursday night call for far-reaching
changes in a number of areas _ from crime to the environment _
affecting the lives of millions of New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes a plan that allows for the construction of
new power plants in the state for the first time in two decades,
along with several criminal justice measures, like tougher
penalties for stalking and blocking access to abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of high-profile measures were not addressed in the
rush to adjourn the 222nd session of the New York state
Legislature, victims of too little time or too little attention.
The unfinished business includes a proposal to stiffen penalties
for parents who fail to pay child support and a measure that would
have permitted New York to join the multi-state lottery known as
Powerball.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders agreed on legislation to create new criminal
penalties in New York for blocking access to abortion clinics.
Democrats had pushed for the legislation, largely because federal
law-enforcement officers have repeatedly said they lack the
manpower to enforce a similar provision in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The new law mirrors federal legislation in that it makes a crime
of harassing or physically attacking people who work at abortion
clinics or seek services from them. The key difference between the
two is that the state law can be enforced by local law officers.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the federal law, the state law does not allow people
to to seek civil damages in state courts against a person who is
convicted of the crime. Democrats had initially sought that
provision but backed away after Republicans resisted them.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also agreed to create stiff new penalties for
stalking. The Republicans in the Senate had proposed the measure,
with strong support from women's groups who said it would add a
layer of protection for women enduring harassment by former
boyfriends or husbands.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats had opposed the measure, primarily because it
included a provision that they said was so broadly worded that it
could subject people to being charged for something as minor as
begging. Under the Republican proposal, the Democrats noted,
suspects could be charged with stalking if their behavior caused
someone else ``distress,'' even if that was not their intent.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Democrats agreed to enact a new crime for stalking,
but only after the wording was made more precise. In the
compromise, suspects can be charged with stalking only if their
intent is to frighten or harm another person. The crime is a
misdemeanor punishable by up to a year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Nortz, the legislative director for the Coalition for the
Homeless, said the new law provides protections against stalking
while insuring that people aren't charged with a crime they had no
intention of committing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a much more sensible approach'' than the original
proposal, she said. ``On the one hand, it includes conduct that we
all know to be stalking, while at the same time protecting innocent
people from being arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders also agreed on a law to
allow the construction of power plants in the state. The proposal
gained urgency this year because, for the first time in two
decades, energy companies have applied to the state for permission
to build new plants, mostly in the Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But because of an oversight, no state agency had the authority,
under Federal law, to issue the permits. Environmentalists had
hoped to tie the law to new pollution controls on older power
plants, which are exempt from requirements imposed on new plants.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the new law contains environmental provisions that
environmental groups dismissed as a sham. ``They have decided that
the pollution reduction plan for New Yorkers is to hold their
breath,'' said Peter Iwanowicz, director of environmental health
for the American Lung Association of New York State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
