<SLUG> BC-AGENT-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CO-CHAIRMAN OF TALENT AGENCY RESIGNS IN DISAGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Jim Wiatt, co-chairman of International Creative
Management, one of Hollywood's top talent agencies, unexpectedly
resigned Friday after disagreements with his partner, Jeffrey Berg.
Wiatt's departure could lead to defections of some of his movie
star and director clients to rival agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt declined to give a specific reason for his departure,
except to say: ``It seemed the best thing to do was to call it a
day. I'm going to move on and wish everybody well.''
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that Wiatt, 52, a well-liked, highly
personable figure in Hollywood who had been with International
Creative Management for 22 years, was weighing the possibility of a
top job at the William Morris Agency, one of the biggest talent
agencies in town, or Endeavor, a successful new agency that counts
among its clients Adam Sandler, Bette Midler and David Kelley, the
writer-producer of ``Ally McBeal'' and other shows.
</P>
<P>
   There was also speculation that Wiatt was discussing the
possibility of joining Michael Ovitz and his partners at the
Artists Management Group, a talent management firm with clients
that include Leonardo DiCaprio. Wiatt declined to discuss his
plans.
</P>
<P>
   If Wiatt joins another agency, he will probably take some of his
clients with him. These include actors Eddie Murphy, Sylvester
Stallone and Tim Allen, as well as directors like Nora Ephron,
Richard Donner and Penny Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely why Wiatt left was not clear. Berg said in an e-mail
to co-workers: ``It is with great regret that I must inform you
that ICM and Jim Wiatt have been unable to conclude a new
agreement. As a result, Jim will be leaving the agency effective
immediately.'' Berg said in the message that he was saddened by the
departure. ``This was not the result I hoped for,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Wiatt said compensation was a factor behind his
departure. But the associates said other issues were more
significant. Although Wiatt had recently been named co-chairman of
the big talent agency, he still considered himself the No. 2 to
Berg, the longtime chairman. ``He always thought he was in Jeff's
shadow,'' one of Wiatt's associates said. ``He hated being No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the associates said, Wiatt was unhappy with the
realignment of the agency's leadership that was announced last
October. Two top agents, Ed Limato, who represents numerous movie
stars, and Nancy Josephson, a television agent, were named
co-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Wiatt and Berg have failed to get along,
associates said. One talent manager who is a friend of Wiatt's
said: ``Jim has struggled there for quite a while in terms of his
relationship and day-to-day dealings with Jeff. They're very
different. Jim was pretty much the heart and soul of that agency.''
</P>
<P>
   International Creative Management ranks as one of the top talent
agencies in Hollywood _ along with Creative Artists, William Morris
and United Talent. Its clients include stars like Mel Gibson, Julia
Roberts and Dustin Hoffman, as well as directors like James Brooks,
Spike Lee and Francis Ford Coppola.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
