<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BRIGGS-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DOG DAYS, BRIGGS-BOTHA BOUT MAY BE AS GOOD AS ANY FOR SOME
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shannon Briggs and Francois Botha did as much as they could to
hype their heavyweight bout Saturday night at Trump's Taj Mahal in
Atlantic City, N.J. Briggs denigrated Botha's boxing skills, and
Botha questioned Briggs' stamina. Welcome to the dog days of summer
for boxing's heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   On paper this is a fight that no one would really care about,
but Showtime Entertainment Television is hoping that the summer
doldrums will not keep boxing fans away from the pay-per-view. The
two boxers have never really reached their potential (although some
would argue that Botha has) and each was knocked out in the fifth
round of his last fight.
</P>
<P>
   With the rematch for the undisputed heavyweight championship
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis slated for November and
most of the top-rated contenders lining up for a shot at the title,
the match between Briggs (31-2) and Botha (39-2) is as compelling
as the division might get in the next couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer Emanuel Steward said that even before he signed on
to work Briggs' corner he was intrigued by this fight, because he
has a lot of questions about each boxer. Steward said he watched
the Mike Tyson-Botha fight Jan. 16 and walked away wondering
whether Tyson was that bad or whether Botha was that good. He was
working Lennox Lewis' corner when Lewis stopped Briggs last year
and recalls seeing a young boxer with a world of athletic ability
but without a clue how to harness it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is all this potential going to be put together?'' Steward
said. ``I think he's finally decided that he was to be the star
now. I think this is the biggest difference in this fight.''
Douglas Faces a Hurdle
</P>
<P>
   Buster Douglas had to overcome some big odds (42-1) to defeat
Mike Tyson the first time they fought in 1990. And if the two are
to fight again, which it appears will happen Oct. 2 at the MGM
Grand in Las Vegas, then Douglas is going to have to clear a major
medical hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   A few years after defeating Tyson, Douglas ballooned to more
than 400 pounds, went into a diabetic coma and nearly died. He
undertook a weight loss program in 1995 and returned to boxing in
1995. The Nevada State Athletic Commission plans to take a close
medical look at the 39-year-old Douglas before he steps into the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas has not fought in Nevada since he lost the undisputed
heavyweight title to Evander Holyfield on Oct. 25, 1990. Dr. Flip
Homansky, the doctor for the Nevada commission, said he would
review information from the hospital where Douglas recovered from
his diabetic coma; order a battery of cardiology tests; get a
magnetic resonance imaging scan of Douglas' brain; have a diabetic
eye specialist examine his eyes, and have tests done on his
kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do the same type of test if he were fighting a six-round
fight on the undercard,'' Homansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' training habits were always questionable, even when he
defeated Tyson in 1990. But now it appears that Douglas may be a
shell of the fighter he was nine years ago. On June 25, 1998, Lou
Savarese delivered a crushing first-round knockout that exposed
Douglas' fragile chin.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that physical liability proved to be a major asset
for Douglas in landing a lucrative rematch with Tyson. The two
other boxers who were in the sweepstakes were Zeljko Mavrovic, who
gave Lennox Lewis a battle over 12 rounds last year, and Orlin
Norris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
