<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INEVITABLE MOVE FROM PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From any perspective, Gov. George Pataki's
announcement Friday that he would support Rudolph Giuliani in a
likely Senate race next year, instead of Rep. Rick A. Lazio, was a
critical moment both in the Senate race and in the feud between two
New York Republicans with competing national ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Giuliani no longer has to worry about a Pataki-backed
primary challenge that many Republicans had viewed as a serious
threat to the mayor's prospective candidacy. Giuliani no longer has
to worry, as well, about attacks from the leadership of his own
fractured party. He can now presumably turn his full attention to
Hillary Rodham Clinton, and one of the mayor's advisers said there
were cheers at city hall when news of Pataki's decision came over
the news wires.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pataki's announcement was a critical moment in this
emerging Senate contest, it was an inevitable one as well. And it
said more about Pataki's own ambitions than about either the
prospect of Giuliani as a Senate candidate or a potential
reconciliation between two rivals locked in one of the more caustic
feuds that New York politics has seen in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that has drawn extraordinary attention from
Republicans around the nation, Pataki was with each passing day
putting himself at risk of being blamed as a spoiler if Giuliani
ran and lost or skipped the race entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki might have begun his tacit encouragement of a Lazio
primary challenge in hopes of rattling an old rival, but in recent
weeks, as Mrs. Clinton traveled through the state in what seemed
like a precursor to a campaign, his actions have drawn unfavorable
attention from Republicans nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just about Giuliani,'' said Adam Goodman, the
Republican consultant who advises the mayor, in discussing Pataki's
decision. ``It was a question of, is the Republican Party prepared
to do whatever is necessary to put our best forward? Anybody who
doesn't show that publicly, if this race goes against the
Republicans, has to fear that they will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has spent much of this year traveling the nation, giving
speeches and presenting himself as a potential national candidate.
The notion that actions by Pataki could have led to Mrs. Clinton's
sitting in the Senate in 2001 ``would certainly not be the kind of
perception that you would want to create for someone who is a
national figure,'' one of Pataki's aides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's advisers have been coming to terms with what is, for
them, the unsavory reality that the governor would have to embrace
a campaign by Giuliani that seems certain to eclipse Pataki's
national stature. Pataki's advisers said that the governor decided
to act Friday because Lazio had scheduled a mid-August announcement
of his candidacy, and because the governor is leaving on Monday for
a vacation in Ireland and France.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary that could have hurt the nominee, or the probable
nominee, might have become a fait accompli if he didn't act,'' said
Kieran Mahoney, a Republican consultant and adviser to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But there were other, perhaps more compelling reasons for Pataki
to move now. Mrs. Clinton has, with each of her weekly trips to New
York, become more definitive about actually entering the race.
Early polls, which are being closely followed by Republicans in
Washington, suggest how tight this contest could be.
</P>
<P>
   And the risk that Pataki's covert support of Lazio could be
viewed as disloyal became clear this week after an encounter
between the governor and Neal Travis, a New York Post gossip
columnist, at a birthday party for Alfonse M. D'Amato, the former
senator, in Bridgehampton last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When Travis asked about the best candidate to run against Mrs.
Clinton, Pataki laughed and said, ``You mean Rick Lazio, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   His senior political adviser, Zenia Mucha, said Friday that the
governor was being jocular. Still, the remarks stirred new waves of
concern among Republicans inside and outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence of Pataki's having expressed much interest
in Lazio's political fortunes before this year. And while Lazio
could be a formidable opponent to Giuliani in a Republican primary
_ he is more conservative on issues that would count with that
electorate _ most politicians in the state believe that the mayor
would be a far stronger Republican opponent to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the problem for Pataki is that the New York
political stage is only so big. To increase Giuliani's stature,
then, is to diminish Pataki's. And so, when Pataki finally decided
to make his announcement, he did it with as much fanfare as might
accompany a visit by the governor to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki _ who had rented a huge Manhattan ballroom for his
well-advertised endorsement of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for
president earlier this year _ this time read a short, terse
statement from a lectern in his office, on a hot and lazy Friday
afternoon in August, when experienced politicians often release
news that they want to get minimal attention. The governor took a
few questions and then hurried back to his office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
