<HEADLINE>
DOMAIN CONCERN TO RELEASE DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Network Solutions Inc., which has been battling the
federal government over the company's monopoly on registering
Internet addresses, or domains, agreed Thursday to open its
database _ the equivalent of the Internet's telephone directory _
to public use while negotiations over its monopoly continue.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department announced the agreement as it extended
for a third time, until Sept. 10, its target date for introducing
full-scale competition into the domain registration business.
</P>
<P>
   The department and Network Solutions are wrangling over the
terms under which other companies can begin adding Internet
addresses to the master registry of addresses that end in .com,
.net and .org, which the company still administers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the key sticking points has been ownership of the
database. The data had always been considered public, but earlier
this year Network Solutions claimed it as the company's
intellectual property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
