<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINO MARTINEZ'S NUMBERS HAVE NOT ADDED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The roof on the beautiful new Safeco Field began to
close as the New York Yankees took batting practice before Thursday
night's game, the massive retractable sections eventually
spreading, like a tent spread for an evening picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis and other Yankees who hit in the first rounds of
batting practice noticed that with the roof open, fly balls tended
to lose their propulsion quickly. Once the roof closed, and the
field was better shielded from the wind, the ball carried better _
as Tino Martinez discovered once the game began.
</P>
<P>
   After chatting with Joe Torre in the manager's office and
working diligently with the batting coach Chris Chambliss, Martinez
broke out of a slump with a pair of home runs, the 200th and 201st
of his career, as the Yankees dumped the Mariners, 7-4, and moved 6
1/2 games ahead of the Toronto Blue Jays in the American League
East.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the game, Torre summoned Martinez to his
office to talk about what Martinez thinks about when he is hitting.
This is what Torre does with slumping players: he reminds them of
all the good things they have done and will do again. Torre told
Martinez that even when he is not hitting, he is an important
member of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, in turn, reminded Torre that when Martinez was with
the Mariners, he often batted seventh against left-handed starters
and doing so with the Yankees would not bother him. So Martinez
batted seventh, the lowest lineup position he has occupied in his
four seasons with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get him to relax,'' Torre said after the game. ``We
all know he can be very tough on himself. You just have to keep
supporting him, and keep telling him not to force it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had not hit a home run in 79 at-bats and had just 15
runs batted in during his previous 35 games. He has felt as if,
lately, he has been more responsible for his own failures than
opposing pitchers have been; Martinez felt he was lurching at the
ball with his body, and in turn, his swing often was ill-timed, out
in front.
</P>
<P>
   In working with Chambliss before Thursday night's game, Martinez
and the coach tried a new approach _ the same solution that helped
Baltimore's Cal Ripken work through what appeared to be a terminal
slump earlier this year and drive his batting average over .300.
Like Ripken, Martinez is trying to reduce the movement in his body
and trust his hands to do more of the work; keep the body still and
bring the hands through. During Thursday night's game, Martinez
felt that his stroke was more compact, quicker.
</P>
<P>
   He slammed a breaking ball from Seattle's Jamie Moyer to
right-center field in his first at-bat, in the second inning, his
200th home run clearing the wall and the outstretched glove of
right fielder Jay Buhner by inches. Four innings later, Martinez
again homered off Moyer, this ball going deep into the right-field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is like Paul O'Neill in that he berates himself
constantly, but Martinez's anger is contained; he is like a giant
steam engine without release. Afterward, after he felt he had
contributed, Martinez smiled broadly, happily, finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard when it's early in the season and you're trying
to get going,'' Martinez said. ``When it's August, it's more
frustrating, because you know your season is coming to an end and I
feel like I haven't done much and I want to get hot going into the
post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez did not have to go far for his pregame work with
Chambliss, for the visitors' clubhouse is next to a batting cage,
just one of the many reasons why the Yankees offered four-star
reviews of Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Torre believes the park is fair to pitchers, with relatively
deep alleys in left-center and right-center; most new parks, Torre
noted, are built to facilitate offense, but here a ball can be hit
hard to straightaway center and stay in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, who worked seven innings Thursday in improving
his record to 10-4, liked the mound. The clubhouse is beautiful,
the players said, although Joe Girardi stretched for a clothes
hanger and suggested with a smile that the lockers are built for
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Fans surround the bullpens beyond the left-field fence, and one
plunked reliever Ramiro Mendoza on the head with a hot dog. When
warming up in the bullpen, Clemens suggested that he felt as if he
was throwing down a small alley. Curtis said he loved the green
colors, of the grass, of the field. ``Green goes good with
baseball,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   The dugout has the smell of freshly cut wood. Several Yankees
mentioned that even with the roof overhead, there were still
open-air areas all around the perimeter of the park, leaving the
players with the feeling that they were conducting the game
outdoors. They all agreed that Safeco is a vast improvement over
the Kingdome, which was dark and hard in both its artificial
surface and its feeling. ``You're cheating the people in this city
when you make them go inside,'' Torre said. ``The people here are
so hardy and they like to be outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neill, ``All new ballparks are nice, but this is extra
nice, because you're coming from that dome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
