<HEADLINE>
BOND BUYBACK IS ROUTINE BOOKKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The excitement over the Treasury's much ballyhooed plan to buy
back some of its bonds proved once again how little the public
understands when it comes to Washington's fiscal machinations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the administration didn't really commit to
repurchasing the bonds. Rather, it announced a proposed mechanism
for doing so, which makes it something less than a big deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more significant reason it's not a big deal is the way debt
reductions have become routine. Hardly anyone notices, though,
because it's all green-eyeshade stuff. No political hoopla, just
boring bookkeeping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago the Treasury announced it was paying down
$10.7 billion in federal debt this quarter. It was as simple as the
amount of the newly issued debt amounting to $10.7 billion less
than old debt being retired. Nobody made a big deal of it, but
perhaps they should have. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 12 months the total marketable debt outstanding
has declined by $127 billion. This is the portion of the debt held
mostly by individual and institutional investors and foreign
governments. In terms of budgetary surplus, this is the real deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This improvement gets lost in the overall national debt figures,
however, because the total nonmarketable debt increased $206
billion during the same period. The nonmarketable debt, as some
Americans are beginning to understand, is the money borrowed from
trust funds such as Social Security when tax revenues earmarked for
specific purposes outpace the program's expenditures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam spends the extra money and the trust funds get an IOU,
which also pays interest. No real money is involved, however,
because these are only accounting transactions. Nevertheless, the
resulting IOUs show up on the books as part of the national debt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, what we have here is a situation in which Washington is
spending excess tax receipts dedicated to Social Security, highway
construction, airport infrastructure and the like faster than the
Treasury can pay down the publicly held debt, which is real money
owed real people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Treasury this week signaled an inclination to buy back
some of its debt, it was talking about the bond portion, which is
the longest-term and smallest component of the federal debt.
Whatever happens, these transactions won't make much practical
difference in the grand scheme of federal debt management. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, why all the excitement? The Financial Times got it just
about right when it said the intention is ``to cast the Democrats
as the party of sound economic management in the run-up to next
year's presidential election as they battle against Republican
plans for huge tax cuts over the next 10 years.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In reality there is no ``party of sound economic management,''
Democrat or Republican. There are only politicians dedicated to
hornswoggling hard-working taxpayers. This is easily done because
most Americans don't have a clue as to the devious ways Washington
manipulates the nation's finances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The administration says this is like refinancing a mortgage.
Depends on how you look at it. Even if all the national debt's
publicly held bond component were involved, it would amount to only
$10,000 or so worth of a $100,000 mortgage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
