<SLUG> BC-NY-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY MAN IS CHARGED WITH HELPING HIS AILING WIFE COMMIT SUICIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 75-year-old man was charged Friday with helping his
ailing wife commit suicide by fixing a rope to a ceiling beam in
their Queens apartment and tying it into the noose she used to hang
herself early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Peter Florio, stood silently in Queens Criminal Court
Friday as his lawyer entered a plea of not guilty to a single
charge of second-degree manslaughter during a brief arraignment.
Judge Pauline Mullings set bail at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Florio, a trim gray-haired retiree, had told
them that his wife, Ann, had often asked him to help her commit
suicide after learning five months ago that she had Parkinson's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Mrs. Florio, 70, had recently been told that she
was not improving and that, in addition to Parkinson's, a
degenerative neurological disease, she had heart problems. She
bought the rope about one week ago, according to the account her
husband gave to the police, and announced that she wanted his help
in hanging herself.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said Florio told them that late on Wednesday
in their apartment, he drilled a hole in the ceiling beam, threaded
the rope through it and made a noose.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, about 7:30, he left the apartment to do
errands and go to a doctor's appointment, according to the account
he gave to the police. When he returned home about 1 p.m., Florio
told the police, he found his wife hanging from the rope, dead, and
called paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, criminal charges for assisted suicide are rare, in
large part because few of the deaths are dramatic or public enough
to draw the attention of law enforcement authorities. And when
people have been accused of helping an ill family member or friend
die, juries have proved reluctant to punish.
</P>
<P>
   Only last month, a Manhattan grand jury declined to indict Marco
Zancope, a Manhattan veterinarian who said he had acceded to a
dying friend's request to inject her with a fatal dose of drugs.
Like Florio, he had been charged with second-degree manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors described the Florios as a devoted couple who had been
married for more than 45 years, always danced together at their
building's annual courtyard party and loved to feed the stray cats
in the neighborhood. For the last five years or so, they lived on
the fifth floor of a six-story cooperative apartment building in
Jackson Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Florio was said to be an avid reader who regularly walked
the 10 blocks from her apartment to the library to replenish her
stock of books. Lately, people in the building said, she had not
been seen much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen Ann for about a month, so I asked Pete how she
was doing,'' said one neighbor, Margaret Hughes. ``He told me, `Not
too well. She doesn't go out much. She's been having some health
problems.' I didn't think much of it at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Gonzalez, the superintendent of the Queens apartment
building where the Florios used to live, said he had seen the
couple a few days ago when they came to put out food for the
strays. Mrs. Florio, he said, appeared ill and sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me she was very sick and hardly went out anymore,''
Gonzalez said. ``She said she'd waited until late afternoon to come
that day because it wouldn't be as hot. Her husband told me she had
a heart condition and he felt bad for her because she was so
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Halton, the lawyer representing Florio, said it would be
premature to provide information about the family or the
circumstances of Mrs. Florio's death. ``They were a very loving
couple and now the family is dealing with a tragedy of immense
proportion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The manslaughter statute under which Florio is charged
specifically covers those who intentionally cause or aid another
person to commit suicide. It carries a possible prison term of up
to 15 years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
