<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
SEASON OVER FOR SPEEDY RECEIVER MCKNIGHT WITH TORN ACL (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ There was a moment during a spirited photo-op
before coach Chan Gailey's daily news conference yesterday when
Jerry Jones suddenly lost his smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did y'all get the official word on James McKnight?'' the
Cowboys owner] asked inside the interview room before delivering
the worst news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``ACL. Out for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it in a painful nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, whom the Cowboys acquired just six week ago from
Seattle to be a deep threat in Gailey's four-wide receiver package,
was the most serious casualty in a Blue-White scrimmage in which
nine players made the team's official injury list.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, whom the Cowboys traded a third-round pick in 2000 to
get, has been diagnosed with a torn anterior cruciate ligament, and
will undergo surgery within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to lose a guy who had such great potential to come
in and be a positive force on your football team,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I've never been around that many injuries in one
\Rscrimmage\S situation like that before. If I have, I probably
blotted it out of my memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of McKnight creates a highly competitive duel between
much-improved, second-year veteran Jeff Ogden and rookie Wane
McGarity, a fourth-round pick from Texas. Either Ogden or McGarity
will be in the No. 4 wide-receiver position behind Michael Irvin,
Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail and Ernie Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey suggested that the Cowboys are in an ongoing ``evaluating
process'' to see if there is a need to go outside the team to bring
in a quality receiver or if their needs can be met by players
already in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It's too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for management to have a knee-jerk reaction and
bring in a big-time receiver, even if a couple of big-time names
are out there: Carl Pickens, who continues to say he will never
play again for the Cincinnati Bengals, and Michael Jackson, who
isn't with any team after the Baltimore Ravens declined to exercise
the option in his contract in 1999. The Cowboys brought in Jackson
for a workout in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals supposedly have turned down a first-round pick in
exchange for Pickens, and reportedly want first- and third-round
picks. They initially demanded a pair of No. 1 picks. Pickens has
said through his agent, Stephen Zucker, that he would play for the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our receiver situation can hold up as it is right now,''
said Stephen Jones, Cowboys executive VP/player personnel, ``even
with the injury to McKnight, we're confident that our current group
of receivers can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of McKnight also cracked the door open a few more
inches for two of three more young receivers to make the team:
MarTay Jenkins, a sixth-round rookie from Nebraska-Omaha, and a
pair of first-year free agents who played at TCU _ Jason Tucker and
John Washington. The Cowboys most likely will keep six wide
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said 100 times before,'' Gailey said, ``injuries give
someone else an opportunity to come in and make plays.
</P>
<P>
   Cases in point include rookie offensive tackle Solomon Page, a
second-round rookie from West Virginia, and Jeremy Akers, a
free-agent offensive tackle from NFL Europe. Both could be starters
against the new Cleveland Browns on Monday night in the Pro
Football Hall of Fame game in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Akers worked for the first time with the first unit yesterday.
He replaced Flozell Adams at left tackle, which protects Troy
Aikman's blind side. Adams suffered a strained hip flexor Thursday
night in the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Adams, the next most serious injury from the
scrimmage was to cornerback Kevin Mathis, with a lower back
contusion.
</P>
<P>
   But neither was as bad as the news on McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   Because the trade with Seattle occurred in June, ``\RMcKnight\S
hadn't been in any minicamps, any coaching sessions ... we were
just getting to know each other really,'' Gailey said. ``We didn't
have anything especially planned for him, but after two weeks of
practice it was \Rbecoming\S an exciting thought process.''
</P>
<P>
   In McKnight, the Cowboys have lost more than just a wide
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had two big roles he was going to play for us,'' Gailey
said. ``He was going to be a deep threat or speed receiver, and he
was going to get a lot of snaps. Plus, he was an excellent
special-teams player. That's two spots we have to fill now.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility always exists that the Cowboys can decide to
upgrade any area of the team through the waiver wire, but the
better players won't become available for more than two weeks. NFL
teams cut down to 60 players Aug. 31 and to 53 players Sept. 5. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
