<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-06 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE Y2K MEDIA FRANCHISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Y2K bug has never really been just a computer problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bug has scored roles in local and national TV commercials
and become a Hollywood problem child. Books? We quit counting at
50, but Amazon.com lists 300 titles. There's a TV infomercial. Even
songwriter and singer Loudon Wainwright III has jumped on the Y2K
bandwagon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Follow us on the trail of this emerging media icon. &QL; 
Restraint 1, bug 0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports in the Boston Globe, Newsweek and elsewhere, a
Warner Bros. spokesman in Kansas City, Mo., tells us the studio
never had plans for a Year 2000 movie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The script for ``Y2K'' simply didn't hold up, said publicist Tom
Blanck, and is being shopped around to the studio's sister
organizations such as HBO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The film's producers apparently thought they had a deal _ after
all, Warner Bros. has a Web site at www.y2k-themovie.com. The
producers now criticize the studio for not putting faith in
moviegoers to distinguish the difference between Year 2000 fact and
fantasy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they don't even want to talk about Y2K,'' said Bing
Howenstein, president of George Street Pictures, the company behind
the film. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris O'Donnell, the boy wonder of Batman fame, was cast to
portray a computer programmer who discovers a Y2K bug that could
leave New York security systems vulnerable to terrorists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some thought the script was too provocative but movie consultant
Peter de Jager, the Toronto computer guru who is credited with
first sounding the global alarm about Y2K, said the movie script is
``non-volatile.'' &QL; 
Bug 1, Hollywood 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spectrum Films of Mesa, Ariz., whose Web address is just one
character off from the Warner Bros. movie site, is scheduled to
release its direct-to-video thriller, ``Y2K: Year to Kill,'' on
Aug. 31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who prepared for the millennium have become the target
of those who didn't,'' says the movie's Internet trailer, which can
be found at www.y2kthemovie.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Amid the chaos, a gang of young thieves run rampant, taking
what they want and killing whom they please. Everyone is at risk in
a world without technology, where trust and ammunition are the only
currencies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The depths of our anxiety appear to be limitless, said Jonathan
Imber, editor of Society magazine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no coincidence that in the last several years we've had
all these movies about violence and the Earth being destroyed,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference may be that today, people are just capitalizing
on those anxieties rather than believing everything is going to
come to an end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commercial opportunity for everyone in Hollywood.'' And
Arizona. &QL; 
Bankers 1, bug jokes 0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moments before New Year's Eve, a young man stares vacantly at
the ATM screen. His bank account in glowing green figures shows him
to be a pauper. He snaps a picture of the monitor with his new
PopShot camera from Polaroid _ instant Y2K hard copy financial
backup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clock strikes 2000 and bingo _ the Y2K bug adds an extra
string of zeroes to his bank balance. Our pre-2000 pauper is now a
budding Silicon Valley venture capitalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A second photo with the Polaroid PopShot records his newfound
wealth in the parody commercial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the American Bankers Association is not laughing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things you just don't joke about,'' said George
Cleland, a spokesman for the trade association that represents some
6,000 large and small banks. ``On this issue, there are a lot of
people who just don't get the humor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting banks will have problems could create real problems,
he said. ``We simply don't want people to ... take all their money
out of the bank. That is foolish and dangerous.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Banks are heavily regulated by the federal government and are
considered to be well prepared to handle any Y2K glitches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when approached by the bankers, Polaroid, based in Cambridge,
Mass., agreed to pull its ad. But that was not the case in May,
when Kia Motors, based in Irvine, Calif., took on the bankers. &QL; 
Bug jokes 1, bankers 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Kia spots to promote a May sales event were intended to mock
extremist reactions to the year 2000. One ad showed a run on a bank
and another featured a family hunkered in a bunker. The message?
Y2K actually meant ``Yes 2 Kia.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The campaign gave the upstart motor company its second-best
sales month in its history, selling 12,795 cars in May. That
compares with 11,400 sold in March and 13,593 in June, said Geno
Effler, the firm's public relations manager. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign also ticked off bankers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kia received 150 letters from bankers across the country
complaining about the spots. Two letters from banks in
Massachusetts said the lending institutions would not loan money to
those seeking funds to purchase a Kia, Effler said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Effler characterized those letters as a ``threat'' and said he
has since forwarded them to the consumer protection branch of the
Federal Trade Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both sides are standing their ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bankers association says it is prepared to confront any
media spots that it says work to undo the $8.2 billion being spent
by financial institutions to combat Y2K. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kia, for its part, is preparing to challenge a Wisconsin bank to
a Y2K readiness test, Effler said. In a June 18 letter, the bank
took Kia to task for its ads and claimed the bank was more prepared
for the year 2000 than was Kia Motors. &QL; 
Dead bug &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If bankers are angry at Kia, they might love the folks at S.C.
Johnson &AMP; Son in Racine, Wis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The makers of Raid are airing an animated commercial with a can
of the well-known insect killer chasing the Y2K bug. The can, of
course, wins. And the proclamation from S.C. Johnson? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's official. The millennium bug is a dead issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skunks in the machine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Loudon Wainwright III, best known for writing that little
1970s ditty ``Dead Skunk (In the Middle of the Road)'' is getting
in on the Y2K action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright's latest album, released last month, includes a song
called ``Y2K ... a song which celebrates the termination of the
world as we know it promptly on Jan. 1, 2000,'' according to
Hannibal Records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital.)We've been trucking down the information
superhighway &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will be a dirt road come Y2K(end ital.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright also names a Y2K ``villain.'' &QL;
</P>
