<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS CALL UP DURRINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- It figured the Angels would search far and wide to
find a second baseman. But Australia?
</P>
<P>
   The Angels called up 23-year-old second baseman Trent Durrington
Friday and put him in the starting lineup. Durrington, a native of
Sydney, Australia, was playing at double-A Erie this season.
</P>
<P>
   He's been in the Angels' organization since 1994 after playing
for the Australian National Team. He was hitting .288 for Erie this
season with a league-leading 59 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, as one might imagine, was not his primary sport
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played rugby,'' said Durrington, who is 5-foot-10, 172
pounds. ``A buddy was playing baseball and I was looking for a
summer sport. I asked him to take me and I loved it from Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins emphasized that Durrington is here
to stake a claim for the starting job next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not here to audition, just to play,'' Collins said. ``He
can't worry about what he does here, he just needs to play. We want
to look at a young player whose had a good year and worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Durrington said because baseball isn't publicized much in
Australia, he didn't have an opportunity to choose players to
emulate. But ``(Chuck) Knoblauch was a guy I looked up to, and
(Craig) Biggio too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn made his first visit to Edison Field Friday since
Tuesday night. Vaughn, recovering from a staph infection in his
right shin, spent a couple hours getting treatment from trainers
and visited with former Red Sox teammates just outside the Red Sox
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who is taking antibiotics for the infection, is expected
to miss a couple more days before returning to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Angels president Tony Tavares has held his tongue this season, a
calculated decision because of his tendency to let his emotions get
the best of him during interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But he broke his silence for the first time earlier this week in
an interview on the Angels' flagship station KLAC. Following is an
excerpt from the interview:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been the bickering, the blame, the finger pointing.
But, bottom line, and my concern, is that there's not enough
looking in the mirror. It's been the manager's fault, the general
manager's fault, the fans' fault. Next thing I'm going to hear is
that we've changed the names of the bears (mascots) and that's
somehow had an impact. It's ridiculous. People have to take
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher will start tonight against the Red Sox, pushing back
Jack McDowell to Sunday. An interesting matchup will take place
Tuesday when the Angels will throw Chuck Finley against the
Indians' Mark Langston, a former Angel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANGELS VS. RED SOX
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1:05 p.m. at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Channel 11; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Tim Belcher (5-6, 6.53 ERA) returns to the mound after
missing nearly six weeks with a broken pinky finger on his right
hand. Pat Rapp (3-5, 4.61) will start for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
