<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU </SLUG>
 VIOLATIONS-TEX 
SMU SUSPENDS COACH FOR ALLEGED RECRUITING VIOLATIONS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Whit Canning 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ SMU assistant coach Steve Malin has been suspended and
the school has reported alleged recruiting violations to the NCAA
and hired a law firm to investigate the matter, athletic director
Jim Copeland said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the suspected violations appear to be secondary in
nature and isolated to one coach,'' Copeland said. ``We won't know
how many athletes are involved until the investigation is
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City firm of Bond, Shoeneck &AMP; King has been retained
to conduct the investigation and report its findings to the NCAA,
Copeland said.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland said the violations were ``uncovered by our assistants
about two weeks ago through a procedure used to check each class as
it graduates. They appear to cover a period of three to four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Malin, a Dallas native with a master's degree from SMU, joined
Tom Rossley's staff as a graduate assistant in 1994 and was
retained by Mike Cavan when he became the head coach after the 1996
season. Malin coached the defensive line and recruited the Dallas
and Houston areas.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes 10 years after SMU returned from the
NCAA's ``death penalty,'' which caused the school to shut down its
football program for the 1987 season after repeated violations
throughout the early '80s. The school chose to voluntarily shut the
program down for a second year before resuming play in 1989. SMU,
found guilty twice within a five-year period in the mid-80s, is the
only school to receive the death penalty in football.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the earlier situation, Copeland said, ``There is no
evidence at this point of booster involvement, and as yet the NCAA
has given us no indication that it will become involved in the
investigation. If the allegations are proven, it might be
appropriate for us to enact a self-imposed penalty. Beyond that, it
would be in the hands of the NCAA.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland said he does not feel that the school's past will
become a factor in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak to what happened before I came here,'' he said.
``I can tell you that this SMU of today is very concerned, and
takes every violation seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speculate on what the NCAA will do, other than to say
I believe we will be treated fairly. As for my personal feelings,
this certainly is not a highlight of the job.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
