<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-TEX </SLUG>
 
JARRETT HASN'T BACKED DOWN FROM CUP TITLE RACE (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dale Jarrett has a checkered past with the No. 88
Ford he will drive in the Brickyard 400 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good race car,'' said Jarrett, referring to the
red, white and blue No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus
with which he has become synonymous. ``It's the same car as last
year _ except with a bigger fuel cell.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after he ran out of fuel while leading the Brickyard 400
at the halfway point, Jarrett was not above recounting one of the
most expensive gaffes in recent NASCAR Winston Cup history. The
fact that Jarrett has returned to the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
leading the points championship certainly has softened memories of
last August, when he made up a daunting four-lap deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jarrett and crew chief Todd Parrott spent part of
practice here yesterday morning calculating fuel mileage around the
2.5-mile rectangular Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran out of gas at Las Vegas earlier this year, too, so
obviously we haven't gotten it totally down pat,'' said Jarrett, a
serious look crossing his face. ``I think we've worked hard on our
fuel mileage. When you produce a lot of horsepower, that becomes a
problem. We have a lot of horsepower at Robert Yates Racing. I
think what we've done is kind of look at our limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen races into the schedule, the limitations have been few
for the man known as D.J. In a workmanlike manner reminiscent of
his father, Ned, a two-time NASCAR champion in the 1960s, Jarrett
has fashioned a 254-point lead over injured Mark Martin. Three-time
and reigning series champion Jeff Gordon and Jeff Burton each have
won four races, but Jarrett has kept pace with three victories.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, no one has racked up more top-fives than Jarrett's
15, or more top-10s than his 17. He has been saddled with only one
point-sapping Did Not Finish result.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's points system rewards such consistency with checks and
championships, as Gordon fully appreciates.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the championship, I haven't seen anyone touching
Dale Jarrett if he continues doing what he's doing,'' said Gordon,
looking up from a 492-point deficit and sixth place after what
amounted to a perfect season in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to define what a perfect season would be,''
Jarrett said, ``because this is so long, and we've had our
difficulties. It looked for a while that even as good as we were
running and finishing in the top five that it was going to be
difficult for us to win. But since that win in Richmond \Ron May
15\S we've been an extremely good race team and have given
ourselves an opportunity to win other races.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has finished third, second and third in the Cup
standings from 1996-98, a period that has seen him score 14 of his
21 career victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten ourselves in a position to kind of make it where
we're in control of this championship,'' said Jarrett, seeking his
first Cup title at age 42. ``We're in control of our destiny,
instead of having to chase someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably Gordon, who edged Jarrett by 14 points for the 1997
championship. More recently, the two engaged in a blowup worthy of
Jerry Springer after the Jiffy Lube 300 in Loudon, N.H., on July
11. Gordon used a bump-pass to muscle his way around Jarrett for a
third-place finish, dropping Jarrett to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett tracked Gordon down in the pits afterward, got in his
face and told him the next time that happens, his rainbow-hued race
car would end up going over the bleeping fence.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett later apologized _ but only for the color of his
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't proud of his choice of words, and he did come back
and apologize for that,'' Ned Jarrett said of his son. ``I was
proud to see him stand up for what he thought was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ned Jarrett said his son, a former all-conference performer in
football, basketball and golf at Newton-Conover (N.C.) High School,
is a fiercer competitor than he ever was. If D.J. can win this
title, he and his father would join the legendary Pettys _ Lee and
Richard _ as the only father-son championship combination in Cup
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Dale deserves the championship,'' said the elder
Jarrett, a popular NASCAR television commentator. ``He's paid his
dues to the point that if he does win one, he deserves it. And it's
important to win a NASCAR Winston Cup championship for any driver
because that completes his resume. Certainly, \Rcar owner\S Robert
Yates deserves to win a championship because of all he's been
through and the contributions he's made to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've made the statement before and really feel this way:
We're most proud of Dale for the type person he is. The type dad he
is to his kids and the type husband he is to his wife. And the type
person he is in the community. What he does on the racetrack is a
bonus, but he's been giving us some pretty big bonuses lately.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
